<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTROOM DRAMAS TELL WHO WE ARE
</HEADLINE>
   (or use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By early Wednesda morning, the line was thick outside Courtroom
401 in the central building of Maricopa County's Superior Court
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies guarding the door lined po tential spectators against
the dark panel ing of the hallway, then began scribbling numbers on
scraps of paper and handing them out to those who'd have to wait
for a seat to open up in the crowded court room.
</P>
<P>
   A skinny, brown-eyed schoolgirl re ceived No. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you here?'' a deputy asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see my mom,'' the girl answered. ``She's on the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   No one else had a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the courtroom, prosecutor Juan Martinez began his final
argument in the case against Scott Falater, the pale, soft-spoken
man who says he was sleep walking when he stabbed his wife 44
times, then dumped her into the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, in Courtroom 402, prosecu tors and defense attorneys
argued over ev idence in the case of five young men accused of
kidnapping and raping a 15-year-old girl with a mental capacity of
a 6- to 8-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is trying to convince a jury the sex was
consensual. &QL; 
`CENTER OF UNIVERSE'
</P>
<P>
   In the hallway outside the two rooms are lawyers and gawkers and
deputies and family members and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A row of television trucks is parked outside the building,
antennas rising from their roofs like the flower stalks of agave
plants. TV cables snake along the lino leum floor of the hallway,
which is buffed each night and reflects fluorescent lamps in the
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   People lounge on cement benches and vinyl-covered chairs, their
skin waxy in the light.
</P>
<P>
   It's quiet, both inside the courtrooms and out.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Everything we're interested in is right here, in this building,
along this hallway, being performed for us in two long-run ning
plays in adjoining theaters.
</P>
<P>
   There's love and hate, sex, murder, fear, suspicion, race.
</P>
<P>
   There are cops and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   We can watch it in person or we can watch it on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, that's what we like to do. We like to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters from all over the country are here, watching.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth floor of the central building of the Maricopa County
Superior Court complex has become the center of our city, the
center of the nation, the center of our universe. &QL; 
EXCUSES ON TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   A television camera focuses on prose cutor Martinez as he pulls
on surgical gloves, then lifts a plastic bag holding the murder
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   He opens the bag and pulls out the knife and grips it like a
killer, plunging it into the imagined torso of poor Yarmila
Falater, whose photograph is projected on a courtroom television.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the actual murder that interests us, though. Just as
it's not the rape being tried in the courtroom next door.
</P>
<P>
   It's the excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Will a guy who claims he was asleep _ who managed to recognize
his dog but not his wife, then cut her to pieces _ get away with
it? Will five punks taking ad vantage of a girl with the mind of
sec ond-grader convince a jury the sex was consensual?
</P>
<P>
   Martinez asked jurors not to fall for a fairy tale. He spoke of
the novel Don Quixote by Miguel de Cervantes. He said Quixote's
companion, Sancho Panza, at first recognized the old man was
jousting at windmills. Over time, however, and with constant
exposure to Quixote's rant ings, Panza came to believe in the fan
tasy. Is that how it is in court?
</P>
<P>
   Can buggy fantasy absolve brutal real ity? And, if it can work
for an accused murderer or accused rapists, can it work for us?
</P>
<P>
   Cervantes was never in the county courthouse here, but he
managed to put a line in Don Quixote for everyone on the fourth
floor and everyone at home, watching. It goes, ``Tell me what com
pany thou keepest, and I'll tell thee what thou art.'' &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978, or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
