A7600 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LA     06-24 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON YOUR MARKS, GET SET, SHOOT!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unbelievable as it sounds, the United States Golf Association
almost staged a perfect U.S. Open. That would be akin to the winner
shooting a record score all four days and the rest of the field
wearing smiles bigger than their corporate logos.
</P>
<P>
   The players actually liked way the USGA prepared the course
since they didn't have to use a weed whacker to advance balls from
the secondary rough. Even par 4's played with a driver, 2- or
3-woods, a wedge and a putter, and had the participants talking
about thinking rather than thinking about cussing.
</P>
<P>
   OK, John Daly did have a meltdown on Sunday after taking 11
strokes on one hole and a subsequent swipe at the USGA. By
Wednesday he had apologized.
</P>
<P>
   But after all, this is the USGA, which year after year seems set
on embarrassing the world's best golfers rather than identifying
them. So on Sunday afternoon, as Payne Stewart, Phil Mickelson and
Tiger Woods struggled with figuring out the treacherous slopes of
Pinehurst No. 2 in an Open finish for the ages, the USGA realized
it had one shot left at controversy,
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievable as it sounds, the USGA took it.
</P>
<P>
   It clocked the final two groups, which raises the possibility of
a penalty stoke for slow play. This means that the players had a
certain amount of time to hit the ball, depending on the
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   With THE major of all majors on the line, the USGA expects the
contenders to pick up the pace? On a course made as difficult as
possible?
</P>
<P>
   Who or what was being held up anyway besides NBC's Sunday-night
lineup? What did the rules guys think they were watching, the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   The NBC broadcast crew did not make a big deal about this. I
slipped away from the television several times during the lengthy
telecast but was there at the end and heard a lot of blathering
about courage, destiny, missed opportunities and a baby on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Don't recall much about slowpokes, though.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I was stunned when I tuned into the postmatch press
conference televised live by The Golf Channel and heard Woods, who
tied for third with Vijay Singh, raise the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Had Woods not blown a couple of short putts, no more than six
feet worth, he might have been in a playoff on Monday. He seemed
more miffed, and rightly so, about the time-clock issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree being on the clock when you're in the last few
groups of a major championship,'' said Woods. ``With the greens as
severe as they are . . . it takes time to figure out the slopes. I
understand the pace-of-play rule, but there are exceptions to it.
And by looking at these greens, I think that's a pretty good
exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods and his playing partner weren't guilty of holding up
Stewart and Michelson. And those two were being followed only by
thousands of fans and, unfortunately, Tom Meeks, the director of
rules and competition for the USGA, or as he's also known, the
ultimate clock watcher.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks whipped out the stopwatch at almost the same point in last
year's tournament at San Francisco's Olympic Club: the 11th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had noticed the play was slow for several holes,'' Meeks
told the Associated Press. Seems Stewart and Michelson were
dallying a little to much for Meeks taste. Hey,I always thought
golf was a sport you clocked with a sundial.
</P>
<P>
   Not Mr. Meeks. He informed Trey Holland, the USGA's vice
president, that Stewart and Michelson were on the clock. What was
the rush? An Open course demands long rounds. Holland approached
Stewart, who was on the way to the 12th tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell me you're putting us on the clock,'' said Stewart,
and then walked away after Holland gave them the news. Mickelson
took it in stride. He'd gotten the same message all four days.
Besides, if his baby beeper went off, he was out of there anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart makes a good point.
</P>
<P>
   When you are concentrating on winning a major championship, it's
hard to keep tabs on the group in front of you or how many minutes
it takes to figure your way out of trouble, which Open courses have
in abundance. Stewart suggested the USGA try to pick up the pace
during the first two days of competition.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, golfers are rarely given a penalty stroke, but just
knowing they are on the clock can be disruptive. In a major it can
be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   USGA officials could not be reached this week for comment on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   They might have already heard from Stewart, even though he liked
the way the entire contest was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell Tom Meeks, `I thought this was a golf
tournament and not a track meet,' '' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
