<HEADER>
A7602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-N     06-24 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDED BY LINEUP SHIFT, YANKS ROUT DEVIL RAYS, 12-4 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The New York Yankees wipe away the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays like lint, so it's hard to accept everything they
accomplish at face value. But there is no question the lineup
changes made last week are helping Bernie Williams and, in turn,
the entire Yankee offense.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, shifted from cleanup to No. 2 last Friday, had four
more hits Wednesday night in a 12-4 rout of the Devil Rays, and the
Yankees (41-28) moved to 13 games over .500 for the first time this
season. Tino Martinez had two home runs among the Yankees'
season-high 19 hits. ``It's nice to come here and get it going,''
said Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   In a seeming mismatch that pitted five-time Cy Young Award
winner Roger Clemens against a journeyman with six career victories
_ Tampa Bay's Dave Eiland _ Clemens barely hung on for the 240th
victory of his career, pitching poorly over five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has 13 hits in 22 at-bats in his five games in the
second spot in the batting order, for a .591 average, with 10 runs
scored, four doubles, three home runs and five RBI, and with just a
little bit of luck, he could have had even more Wednesday night.
Williams pushed center fielder Randy Winn against the wall with a
ferocious flyout in the third inning, and in the seventh, Winn
intercepted Williams' line drive while moving toward left-center
field.
</P>
<P>
   When manager Joe Torre juggled the lineup _ shifting Derek Jeter
to the third slot, Paul O'Neill from third to fifth and Martinez
from fifth to fourth _ he said he did so because Williams had
success while hitting second. But Torre probably was just being
gracious; the real reason, in all likelihood, was that he wanted to
force opponents to throw better pitches to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   While batting cleanup, Williams was surrounded by O'Neill and
Martinez, both of whom were struggling. Pitchers could work
carefully to Williams, to the fringes of the strike zone, knowing
that even if he walked, they could escape trouble by pitching to
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such luxury now: With Williams batting second,
pitchers know that if they work around him, they then have to cope
with Jeter, who is to the Yankees' lineup what Bill Gates is to the
computer industry. Consequently, Williams is getting more fastballs
to hit _ and he's been devastating, including two straight four-hit
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take the credit, sure,'' Torre said, joking. ``But I
don't think changing spots means a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The results speak for themselves. The combination of Williams
and Jeter hitting back-to-back _ they've already reached base in
the same inning seven times in the last five games _ appears to be
having a ripple effect. The Yankees are getting more runners on
base, and as they proved so often last year, more runners mean that
pitchers are liable to make more mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Eiland, who made his major-league debut on Aug. 3, 1988 while
pitching for the Yankees, survived for awhile Wednesday night, but
even after the Devil Rays took a 3-0 lead after three innings, his
demise seemed inevitable. Martinez banged his 11th home run to open
the fourth inning, and in the fifth inning, a reliever began
warming up as soon as Williams singled with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter singled and Martinez walked and the bases were loaded for
O'Neill. Devil Rays Manager Larry Rothschild called on the
left-hander Scott Aldred.
</P>
<P>
   Bearing a .140 average against left-handed pitchers, O'Neill
laced Aldred's first pitch down the right field line, and all the
runners were on the move, Williams scoring, and then Jeter and
Martinez. It was a crucial hit for O'Neill, who had 7 hits in his
last 55 at-bats (.127) with runners in scoring position, since May
1, and needs to produce to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge base hit for us,'' said Torre. ``I just sense
he's seeing the ball better.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens required all the run support he could get, on a night
when the physical action of throwing strikes appeared foreign to
him. Clemens threw a ball on the first pitch to 13 of the 27
batters he faced, constantly fell behind in the count, and labored
_ he threw 38 pitches in the second inning, 29 pitches in the
third. But he prevailed, and this was a night for the Yankees'
hitters, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had his first game of three or more hits since May 18,
O'Neill drove in four runs _ or just one fewer than he had driven
in over his 12 previous games _ and Chuck Knoblauch reached base
four times. Close your eyes and, for one night, you could imagine
it was 1998 all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys are seeing the ball well, and it's great to see
them get their confidence going,'' said Clemens. ``We've got a lot
of guys who are tough on themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
