<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI NOT IN PARTY MOOD OVER QUESTIONS ON MRS. CLINTON AND NAVY
YARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Facing persistent questions from reporters Wednesday
about why his administration had killed plans for a glittery
magazine party at the city-owned Brooklyn Navy Yard, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani tried several tactics.
</P>
<P>
   He said ask someone else. He tried to change the subject. He
dismissed the issue as frivolous _ even injected a little humor.
Finally, he just left.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for his discomfort was obvious. On Tuesday, a top
aide conceded that the city had blocked the party in part because
of reports that the new magazine, called Talk, planned to put
Hillary Rodham Clinton, the mayor's likely opponent in next year's
U.S. Senate race, on the cover of its inaugural issue.
</P>
<P>
   Also obvious was the intense media interest. Talk magazine is
co-owned by Miramax Films and Hearst Magazines; a Miramax
co-chairman, Harvey Weinstein, and the magazine's editor, Tina
Brown, were to be hosts of the Navy Yard soiree.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's news conference Wednesday had been scheduled to
follow a meeting with San Antonio Mayor Howard Peak, who was in
town for the basketball championship between the Knicks and the
Spurs. Giuliani is often sharp and unforgiving with the local
press, though he has cultivated a far friendlier image nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Peak and his wife stood off to the side as a reporter asked the
first of what would be eight successive questions about the Talk
magazine party. ``Talk to the Navy Yard,'' Giuliani retorted.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy Yard is city-owned property, operated by the Brooklyn
Navy Yard Development Corp., whose three directors are appointed by
the mayor and include Rudy Washington, the deputy mayor for
business services. When reporters pushed the point, Giuliani said
the decision had little to do with the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Navy Yard would have treated me the same way, even
though I am from Brooklyn, was born in Brooklyn and my father
worked at the Navy Yard,'' he said, adding pointedly: ``I don't
think this is an issue of discrimination against somebody from
Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he was pressed to explain who had made the decision to
block the party: Navy Yard officials or Randy Levine, the deputy
mayor for economic operations, who had already acknowledged in
interviews that he made the decision. ``I am sure it was their
joint decision,'' the mayor said. But he said he himself had
nothing to do with it. ``I don't care one way or the other,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, Brooklyn Navy Yard Development Corp. president
Marc Rosenbaum issued a statement supporting the mayor's
explanation. He said the Navy Yard's roof deck, recently renovated
as a party space, could accommodate only 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed scope of the event became larger and increasingly
unwieldy, involving over 1500 people,'' the statement said, though
it added that Mrs. Clinton was also a factor. ``We felt that the
party was beginning to take on a political cast and was no longer
simply for the launch of a new magazine, a situation which could
easily violate our policy against holding political events.''
</P>
<P>
   After the eighth question at his news conference, the mayor
sought to change the subject. ``I think you have got to have
another question,'' he said. ``I can't believe this is the only
thing.'' After yet another party question, he said: ``I imagine
there must be something else going on in the life of this city that
you'd like to ask about. Or we have gotten to the point of ultimate
frivolity?''
</P>
<P>
   His exasperation was rewarded by a question about City Hall
lobbying. But a moment later, it was back to Talk. Giuliani had had
enough. ``No no no,'' he said. ``No no. We have exhausted the
subject. If there are no more questions about another subject, then
I can go back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   An obliging television reporter switched topics, to plans by
Hadassah, the Jewish charity organization, to give Mrs. Clinton an
award. ``Are they going to have that ceremony at the Navy Yard?''
the mayor asked, trying a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Told it would be in Washington, he replied, ``Oh, OK, well, as
long as it's not at the Navy Yard, I'll have no comment on it.''
Then he muttered ``thank you'' and walked out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
