u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATAKI-ECON-NYT &LR;      06-24 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI AVOIDS BUDGET ISSUE IN SPEECH ABOUT POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mich.)   (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki went to Detroit on Wednesday to
promote his economic policies as a model for the nation, detailing
his record of cutting taxes and reducing the size of government but
skirting mention of the standoff back home over the state budget,
now nearly three months overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the Detroit Economic Club, Pataki called for
reducing federal income taxes an average of 13 percent over seven
years, eliminating the capital gains tax and changing Social
Security to allow people to invest some of the money they now
contribute. He proposed a Constitutional amendment that would
require a two-thirds vote in Congress to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He said he favored increasing federal spending on defense and
education, while scaling back the bureaucracy by abolishing the
departments of Commerce and Energy, repealing burdensome
regulations and selling some government assets.
</P>
<P>
   He said his proposals would save hundreds of billions of
dollars. ``But in a broader sense, this plan isn't about numbers,''
he said. ``It's about freedom. It's about people. It's about
restoring certain inalienable rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech before the club, a traditional stop for politicians
eager to proclaim the success of their stewardship, marked the
latest effort by Pataki to seize the national spotlight. It comes,
though, at an awkward time for him. After flirting for several
months with a long-shot bid for the presidency, Pataki took himself
out of the running in May when he endorsed Texas Gov. George W.
Bush for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   So at best, the speech was an attempt to help his standing as a
potential vice presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about those aspirations before the speech Wednesday,
Pataki said, ``I don't think that you think about the vice
presidency or cabinet positions. You have to first get the
nomination and win the election. That's where we are going to be
focused, doing that for Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, the state government remains paralyzed by the dispute
over the state budget. Perhaps unsurprisingly, Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver, a Manhattan Democrat, made a pointed reference
Wednesday to the governor's trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever he chooses to be, that's his priority and I think the
people of the state will eventually respond to each and every one
of our priorities,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Silver, Pataki and Republican state Senate Majority
Leader Joseph Bruno continued budget negotiations Wednesday, but
without substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
   While the sides are relatively close to a compromise, the
deadlock remains over Silver's insistence that Pataki agree not to
veto spending items proposed by Assembly Democrats. The governor
has refused to provide such a promise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
