<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITS-NYT &LR;      06-24 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBITUARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patricia Kerr Ross, 60, SUNY Arts Director &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Kerr Ross, former director of the State University of
New York's Programs in the Arts, died June 22 at a hospital in
Albany, N.Y. She was 60 and lived in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was ovarian cancer, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   As director of the university-wide arts programs from 1971 to
1991, Ms. Ross was instrumental in producing statewide arts
festivals, workshops and exhibitions. Over the years, her office
provided creative assistance and support to artists and arts
administrators throughout the State University system.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ross helped bring dance to SUNY campuses by producing such
festivals as the Early Years of Modern Dance (1981) and Merce
Cunningham and the New Dance (1987). Dance Black America (1984) was
produced with the Brooklyn Academy of Music and filmed for public
television.
</P>
<P>
   From 1979 to 1987 she was executive producer of a series of
public television specials, ``SUNY in the Arts on Television.'' She
also organized faculty and student visits to artists, actors,
directors and producers, as well as the SUNY Writer's Festival of
readings, discussions and workshops. In 1985 she was co-producer of
``The Educated Eye,'' an exhibition at the New York State Museum of
400 artworks from 25 SUNY campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ross, who taught arts policy at Empire State College, was
also director of the Thayer Fellowship, which supported outstanding
SUNY arts graduates in their first year of professional activity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 she founded and directed what became an annual ``Come
Sunday'' celebration of music and dance in Albany's historic Center
Square neighborhood. The festival presented such performers as
Dizzy Gillespie, Branford Marsalis and Garth Fagan as well as
emerging local artists. She retired from the university in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ross is survived by a daughter, Linda Proctor of Concord,
N.H.; her companion, George Hofmann, an artist and professor at
Hunter College, and two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Pagliaro, 99, Concrete Contractor &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frank J. Pagliaro, a concrete contractor whose projects included
the Chrysler Building and the New York Athletic Club in Manhattan,
died June 20 at his home in Mount Kisco, N.Y. He was 99.
</P>
<P>
   Pagliaro provided concrete for the United Nations, Shea Stadium,
the New York Coliseum, the Huntington Hartford Gallery in Columbus
Circle and numerous public housing projects in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1960s, Pagliaro expanded his business, Knickerbocker
Construction, and became a general contractor, helping to build
Lincoln Towers in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   He constructed buildings in many cities like the Federal Court
Building in San Francisco. His projects in the Washington area
include the Senate Office Building, the CIA Building and Robert F.
Kennedy Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Pagliaro was born on March 4, 1900, in Manhattan. After
graduating from Cornell University in 1925, he joined his father's
company, Knickerbocker Fireproofing, which encased steel beams with
concrete.
</P>
<P>
   The firm later branched out into reinforced concrete, the basic
material of modern high-rise buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Pagliaro is survived by his wife, Anita; a sister, Mary Petrillo
of Bronxville, N.Y.; two sons, Frank Pagliaro Jr. of Burlingame,
Calif., and Leonard Pagliaro of Seattle; four daughters, Anita
Pagliaro and Carla Pagliaro, both of Livingston, Mont., and Alix
Barthelmes and Lisa Selz, both of Manhattan; six grandchildren; and
a great-granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce MacIver, 95, Novelist and Playwright
</P>
<P>
   Georgette Scott, a novelist and playwright who wrote under the
name Joyce MacIver, died June 15 at her home in New York. She was
95.
</P>
<P>
   She was best known for her 1961 novel, ``The Frog Pond,'' which
was inspired by her own experience with psychoanalysis and became a
best seller. Miss Scott was also the author of ``The Exquisite
Thing'' (1968), ``Mercy'' (1977) and ``The Glimpse'' (1984). She
was co-author of a play, ``American Royalty,'' with Richard Haase.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Baltimore, Miss Scott attended the Johns Hopkins School
of Journalism and began her writing career at The Baltimore Sun.
After moving to New York, she wrote for the International News
Service and contributed articles to magazines including Esquire and
The Saturday Evening Post.
</P>
<P>
   No immediate family members survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
