<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS24-CO     06-24 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs roll at finish, near title
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now only one victory separates San Antonio from a
title. One victory and the Spurs become the first of the old ABA
teams to win an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   They have their chance because they held on, 96-89, against a
swarming New York team that could completely dig out of a hole it
dug for itself early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson and Tim Duncan had plenty of help this time, the
entire lineup in double figures, Robinson scoring 14 with 17
rebounds, Duncan 28 with 17 as the Spurs took a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks scrambled, gambling with traps and running wildly
after falling into a 13-point hole to start the second half and
when they cut the lead to a point with 5:24 left, feeding off
Latrell Sprewell, who scored 16 of his 26 points from 6:49 of the
third to 6:16 of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring or dishing, he brought his team back and then Allan
Houston sank a baseline jumper that cut it to 81-79 with 5:40 left,
the Spurs 3-for-13 in the period to that point. Charlie Ward could
have tied it seconds later but made only one at the line. After
Duncan and Robinson scored inside, Ward threw a jump pass that
Mario Elie intercepted. The lead was six. Marcus Camby's
three-point play halved it. Larry Johnson, enduring a terrible
night, made one from the line at 3:40. The Spurs began to take
control from there.
</P>
<P>
   After their 12-game playoff winning streak ended Monday _ they
had last lost May 11 to Minnesota _ the Spurs had plenty to think
about.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the matter of shot selection. Duncan, their
leading scorer, took only 16 shots in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the ball-handling lapses that cost them 18
points from 20 turnovers. ``We don't make 20 turnovers in two
games, let alone one,'' Avery Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was the ineffective play of forward Sean Elliott
and Elie. Elliott had only two points after three quarters and
seven for the game in 38 minutes. Elie was in early foul trouble
and scored only six points.
</P>
<P>
   That also meant they did not apply pressure on Sprewell and
Houston to work on defense, and the Knicks tandem combined for 58
points.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, they gave Elliott early shots. Duncan worked
into the flow quickly. The Spurs controlled tempo until Avery
Johnson had to leave with blood on his elbow. In his absence, the
much-maligned Ward took control against slower Steve Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks needed more help than usual from Ward because Chris
Childs was limited with a sprained knee. And Ward stepped up,
scoring 10 in the first as the Knicks grabbed a 29-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott came through. He had eight points by the five-minute
mark of the second quarter when he sank his second triple of the
game. The Spurs led 42-40 when Houston's string of converted free
throws in the Finals ended at 19, the Knicks hanging on with Ward
watching virtually the entire quarter. When he came back in the
final minutes, the Knicks had more energy, but they trailed 50-46
at the break, unable to stop Duncan, who had 14 points, seven
rebounds by intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly, the Spurs broke to their biggest lead _ 59-46 _ as
Larry Johnson was overmatched trying to score against Duncan and
Robinson. Duncan scored six in a 9-0 start while the Knicks missed
five with two turnovers in 2:46 of the second half. The Knicks
tried to rally as Houston worked a three-point play, Sprewell put
down a jumper and Camby forced a Robinson turnover, then dunked on
Duncan for 61-53.
</P>
<P>
   Trapping and gambling on defense, the Knicks excited a crowd
wearing so much home team orange it could have been Knoxville or
Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   But he Knicks could not get closer than eight despite a flurry
of 10 points by Sprewell. They trailed 72-63 going to the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
