<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7616 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-NYT &LR;      06-24 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBATTLED KNICKS FALL TO SPURS, WHO NOW LEAD SERIES 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Undermanned and physically drained, the New York
Knicks opened every resource they had and received an energized
effort from Latrell Sprewell, but they straggled out of Madison
Square Garden on Wednesday night crestfallen and on the brink of
elimination in the National Basketball Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, down by 13 in the third quarter and by seven with
eight minutes left in the game, pulled within 81-80 with 5 minutes
24 seconds remaining. But the Spurs, fresher, bigger and uncommonly
calm under the frenzy of the Garden crowd, held the Knicks off to
win Game 4, 96-89, and take a three-games-to-one lead in the
best-of-7 series.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were led by Sprewell's 26 points on 9-for-22 shooting
and 20 points from Allan Houston. The Spurs leaned on their big men
as Tim Duncan scored 28 points and had 17 rebounds on a pained
Larry Johnson (five points) and David Robinson came up with 14
points and 17 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will try to keep their finals dreams alive with Game
5 at the Garden on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy had his fears about this game. The
three key players he had left standing _ Houston, Sprewell and
Larry Johnson _ had all played 43-plus minutes in an emotionally
and physically draining Game 3 on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win, we're going to have to be highly energetic,'' Van
Gundy said Wednesday afternoon at the team's shoot-around. ``And I
just sensed Tuesday that _ well, it was a draining game, and we've
got to get ourselves back energy-wise to come ready tonight. It's
not about a letdown. It's just that playing at a high level of
energy when you're down people is more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks needed to give Houston, Johnson and Sprewell a break.
In the first half, they found reinforcement from one usual suspect
and from one who was not so typical. Camby, the impact player from
the Indiana series, and Ward, the invisible point guard for most of
the playoffs, both came on to keep the Knicks close to the Spurs;
New York trailed by 50-46 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks shot 47.4 percent in the first half, which was a
major bump up from the 35 percent they had been averaging in the
finals. The Spurs, who have the league's best defense, were clearly
upset at how loose they had been.
</P>
<P>
   They came out in the third quarter a different team, and did not
allow the Knicks to score in the opening four minutes of the second
half. The Spurs held the Knicks to 0-for-5 shooting and were
contesting everything inside. They were also double-teaming Houston
and Sprewell and forcing turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Before they knew it, the Knicks were behind by 59-46 with 8:14
left in the third period. Van Gundy called a time out, and the
Knicks regrouped. Houston began a 7-0 run with a 3-point play when
he was fouled by Duncan on a jumper. The Knicks pulled within 61-53
with 6:13 left in the quarter on a dunk by Camby.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' defense stopped the momentum with a couple of stands
that led to Mario Elie either driving inside for a 3-point play or
popping a shot from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, ahead by 68-57 with 3:34 left in the third, were
trying to maintain their edge despite the lively play of Camby and
Ward, who both stripped the Spurs' big men from behind to force
turnovers and give the Knicks a chance to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   They had their chance, trailing by just 72-63 after a frantic
third quarter in which they were led by the 10 points of Sprewell,
who put up a shot every time the ball was in his hands, and Camby
and Ward continued to make their presences felt.
</P>
<P>
   After having failed to duplicate the impact he had against
Indiana in the conference finals, Camby made a concerted effort to
keep himself on the court and avoid the foul trouble that had
plagued him against Robinson. He succeeded with 19 minutes of
foul-free effort in the first half, finishing with a lively 10
points and seven rebounds. He was one of four Knick starters with
10 points at halftime, along with Houston, Sprewell and Ward.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Ward looked as if he were going to be a liability
for the Knicks. In the opening minutes of the game, he played
pedestrian defense as Avery Johnson drove by him, shot over him and
went to the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   That must have irritated Ward. With his pride challenged, he
came right back at his counterpart. Ward saved the Knicks, who were
down by 23-17 midway through the first quarter. He burst into view
with a flurry of steals and two 3-pointers to lead his team on a
9-2 run. Ward gave his team a 26-25 lead with 1:32 left in the
first quarter when he darted in front of a pass at the top of the
3-point arc and dashed the other way for a layin.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first period, the Knicks were up by 29-27 and
Ward's 10 points were the reason. In one quarter, Ward had scored
more points than he had in any Knicks playoff game but one, the 12
points he had in Game 4 against Miami in the first round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   When Ward walked off the floor for a rest early in the second
quarter, the Garden crowd stood in applause of the oft-maligned
point guard. By coincidence, the Nets' Stephon Marbury, who once
said the Knicks could not win a title with Ward and Chris Childs at
point guard, was sitting in the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Childs, playing on a sprained knee, took over. And Avery Johnson
went back to work. He drove to the basket twice for scores, and
then Jerome Kersey popped open for a long jumper to give his team a
33-31 lead with 8:20 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks tied the score several times, but the Spurs never
fell behind, countering every score by the Knicks with a steady
stream of passes to Duncan in the paint. He had 14 points in the
first half over a rubbery-legged Larry Johnson, who had played him
so admirably on his sprained knee in Game 3. In the first half, the
Knicks' power forward was 1 for 5 with two points.
</P>
<P>
   With only one day of rest, the Knicks could not lean on Johnson
for 43 minutes again. That was where Camby's ability to stay free
of fouls helped the Knicks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
