<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-24 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE SPURS MAKE THEIR POINT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas)  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They won it the way Red Holzman's old Knicks used to.
The San Antonio Spurs claimed the game they needed at Madison
Square Garden, sending thousands into the street thinking the
miracle run is over. They did it without a celebrity show, without
a Jordan or a Miller standing up and planting a flag in the middle
of the court. The Spurs won with interior defense as imposing as
the New York skyline.
</P>
<P>
   The first five minutes of the third quarter Wednesday night
defined the Spurs, put them on the doorstep of their first title.
The race to get even for the New York Knicks ended in the forest of
arms, the long arms of David Robinson and Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson rejecting Larry Johnson low. Robinson stuffing Allan
Houston on the break. Marcus Camby, standing in the shadows of the
twin towers, blowing a layup. The second half starting with nine
straight San Antonio points. The Knicks pushed hard in the fourth
quarter, all the way back to within one point, but they never quite
made it all the way up the mountain. They lost Game 4, 96-89, and
face the end Thursday night. The Spurs made their point to all the
big stars in the house.
</P>
<P>
   A special treat. A rare experience. That's what the Spurs
originally thought playing the finals at Madison Square Garden
would be like. Festive. Star-studded. Billy Crystal, Woody, Spike,
and we get to perform for them.
</P>
<P>
   This was, Will Perdue said, a subject of much discussion on the
flight in from San Antonio last Saturday night. Baldwins and
Broadway, here we come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was saying how nice it would be to play here because
of the crowd and the celebrities,'' Perdue said.
</P>
<P>
   They returned to Madison Square Garden Wednesday night for Game
4, needing one victory, just one for the road. The Spurs came here
with what amounted to three break points on the Knicks' serve. Win
one, and they'd be on the threshold of a title. Lose all three, and
they'd be looking like every other Knicks' playoff victim.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-series consensus was that this should not have been such
an ordeal for a bunch that had already closed out playoff series in
Minneapolis, Los Angeles and Portland. Yet, after Monday night,
after the Knicks informed the Spurs they were not quitters like the
Lakers and Blazers, the Spurs may have understood the difference
between there and here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that Billy Crystal is going to defend us that
well or intimidate us,'' Steve Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what about Evander Holyfield, glaring hard at them
Wednesday night from the honorary first seat alongside Celebrity
Row?
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs claimed they had learned their lesson in Game 3.
They had to play ahead at the Garden. Their own little point guard
did some serious penetrating of his own. Duncan got untracked and
began lofting soft jumpers over Larry Johnson. By halftime, the
Spurs were ahead, 50-46, their defense warming up for the big
second-half start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked getting up on this team here because the fans here
are liable to turn on their team at the drop of a dime,'' Perdue
said before Wednesday night's game. ``We didn't do that. We wound
up giving them less to doubt. So the fans cursed behind our bench
at us for 47 minutes and when they realized in the 48th minute they
were going to win, they said, `Nothing personal. See you
Wednesday.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's more than the stars coming out that made this a challenge,
to avoid letting the Knicks send them home to face elimination.
It's driving through midtown on the way to the Garden, feeling the
energy in shadowed streets. It is the acoustics of the Garden, the
closeness and ferocity of the crowd. The Alamodome was loud with
nearly 40,000. It still was not Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Perdue, the former Bull, recalled how Michael Jordan's eyes
would sparkle as soon as the team bus rolled into town. Jordan had
the advantage of walking into the building with the idea that he
was bigger than any courtside fan, bigger than the Garden itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But who else could control a game like Michael?'' Perdue said.
</P>
<P>
   Before he shrank in the presence of Allan Houston this spring,
Reggie Miller stole a few spring showdowns by summoning Spike into
his theater and playing the classic villain for the reluctant
director. Tim Hardaway was hurt all the way back in the first
round, but in past years, he certainly had enough chip on his
shoulder to shoot the Garden stone quiet.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to know from Tim Duncan's face what he's feeling.
He is just 23. The idea that David Robinson was soft was always a
stretch, but his strongest supporters never called him arrogant.
That's what he and Duncan were Wednesday night in the lane, in the
the game the Spurs had to have. Broadway demanded no less.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
