<HEADLINE>
REALLY QUIET FIELD FOR CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Real Quiet, with jockey Jerry Bailey,
emerged as the new Hollywood Gold Cup favorite against only three
opponents after the withdrawal of ailing ailing Old Trieste from
Sunday's $1 million race.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park morning-line maker Russell Hudak said Real Quiet,
a winner once in five races since his 1998 Kentucky Derby and
Preakness victories, will be 7-5 or 8-5 in the odds to be announced
after entries and post positions are set this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Hudak expects the betting to be close among Donn Handicap winner
Puerto Madero (Kent Desormeaux), 1998 Santa Anita Handicap winner
Malek (Alex Solis) and likely pacesetter Budroyale (Garrett Gomez).
The long shot could be no more than 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park apparently will have to settle for the smallest
field in the Gold Cup's 60 runnings. The 1\-mile race has drawn
five starters three times, most recently in 1994 when Slew of
Damascus and Gary Stevens led from gate to wire.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the loss of a would-be favorite like Old Trieste, who
was declared out of the race Tuesday after developing a fever,
would draw a last-minute entry or two from owners looking to
collect the $20,000 fifth-place check.
</P>
<P>
   But other local candidates are either unnominated or injured.
And top-ranked older horse Behrens is staying in the East for now,
because trainer Jim Bond didn't want to ship him to California for
both the Gold Cup and Del Mar's Pacific Classic, the Aug.29 final
race in the NTRA Champions on Fox series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
