</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A THIN LINE BETWEEN FOULING AND PLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the National Basketball Association controlled
track and field, the league would have devised a system by now to
make sure the favorite runners win and the popular jumpers triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Lesser known sprinters would be forced to race on uneven
surfaces that twisted and turned while their marquee opponents ran
straight away _ and five yards fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Elite hurdlers would only have to clear low hurdles while the
underdogs would have to clear high ones. A high jumper on the verge
of upsetting the favorite would suddenly see the bar elevated just
as he was about to clear it.
</P>
<P>
   Farfetched? Maybe. But this is essentially what the NBA, for
want of entertainment and maintenance of a star system, has done to
competition. With each new season, Dr. Naismith's game is moving
closer to professional wrestling. The NBA has an entire vocabulary
of calls, from veteran calls to makeup calls and calls that make a
point.
</P>
<P>
   This is not about pro-Knicks or anti-Spurs; this is about a
continuing evolution that turns games into vaudeville acts starring
overpaid coaches and officials who come dangerously close to
crossing the line between keeping order and manipulating results.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the referees bailed out the home team with foul
calls time after time, including, with about five minutes left in
the game, a 3-second violation on Tim Duncan that kept the Knicks
close. But alas, they couldn't keep them close enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks-Spurs championship series, which took a dramatic tilt
toward San Antonio with the Spurs' 96-89 victory Wednesday night,
is simply another example of how the NBA is evolving away from
competition and toward the embrace of marketing and entertainment.
About an hour before Game 3 on Monday night, a longtime television
basketball analyst, who also covered the NBA as a beat reporter for
several years, glanced at a list for the officiating crew and
casually predicted that the Knicks would go to the line
substantially more than they had in the first two games. Presto!
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks lived at the line on Monday as the bewildered Spurs,
who had been allowed to knock the Knicks around like pinballs in
San Antonio, protested. In the first two games in San Antonio, the
Knicks attempted only 31 foul shots to San Antonio's 66. On Monday,
the Knicks had 30 free throws to 22 for the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Why is a foul in Texas not a foul in New York? In San Antonio,
the Knicks attacked the Twin Towers and their shots were swatted
around the Alamodome like flies. In New York, the Knicks attacked
and went to the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' Mario Elie said he guarded Allan Houston in Game 3
the same way he had guarded him in Games 1 and 2: he mauled him,
used his bulk and toughness to offset Houston's quickness and
range. On Monday the officials apparently decided that what was
cool in San Antonio was not cool in New York. Elie was hit with two
quick fouls and then with a technical for protesting. Wednesday
night, Elie had clutch basket after clutch basket en route to 18
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, two ticky-tack fouls,'' the New York-born Elie said of
Monday night's game. ``Fans want to see key players playing, not on
the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   What Elie doesn't understand is that, in this Broadway drama,
Allan Houston, not Elie, is the key player. But Wednesday night,
Elie got the better of the matchup. At a time when the league is
wringing its hands over low scoring, the suddenly explosive Houston
_ with the all-America good looks, blossoming into a star before
the nation's eyes _ is the perfect antidote. The law has spoken,
without actually speaking: Elie will not be allowed to manhandle
Houston in Games 3 through 6. NBA law is extremely fluid.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1992 playoffs, Chicago Bulls head coach Phil Jackson
incurred a fine when he said the NBA would probably be delighted to
have a seventh game involving two of the nation's three largest
markets. Asked if he thought the results were being orchestrated,
Jackson said: ``I don't like orchestration, it sounds a little too
fishy. But they control who they send as referees.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a peculiar symmetry between NBA rules and the law,
between NBA officials and the police. Each has a mandate to keep
the peace, though more specifically their primary job is to
maintain law and order. Depending on your perspective _ and
standing _ the ultimate responsibility of each cop and official is
to protect the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The police might stop suspicious characters in nice
neighborhoods, or follow shady characters around the mall.
Officials protect the NBA elite, making sure they have enough elbow
room to maneuver without being manhandled by the likes of Elie.
</P>
<P>
   Under the NBA system, referees mark some players for fouls.
Marcus Camby has not yet earned the right to guard David Robinson
aggressively without drawing fouls. Wednesday night, Camby seemed
to finally unlock the secret of playing Robinson. Using finesse
rather than power, Camby didn't pickup his first foul until 8
minutes 36 seconds remained in the final quarter. He finished with
20 points.
</P>
<P>
   Jaren Jackson, a journeyman player who has spent nine years
bouncing around the NBA, understands both the scene and the play.
``You got to understand how games are being called, how officials
are calling against certain players on the floor,'' Jackson said.
``You may sacrifice getting a few jump shots in your face and guys
scoring, but that's the way it goes. You might get mad, but that's
the nature of the beast.''
</P>
<P>
   The beast, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   And the more I watch the NBA, the better I like track and
field. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-HEIGHT-NYT &LR;      06-24 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-HEIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HEIGHT BEATS HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Originally skedded as BKN-KNICKS-JOHNSON) (mk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was early in the fourth quarter Wednesday night,
and Latrell Sprewell received a basic entry pass from Allan Houston
in the low post. Maybe eight feet from the basket, he turned
another bland possession into a Broadway show.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning away from Jaren Jackson, he suddenly looked like a
tailback who fought through a scrum to the open field. With his
team crawling back into Game 4 at Madison Square Garden, Sprewell
had nothing but the rim in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   He never saw the long arm of Tim Duncan from behind, the
elongated reach of a 7-footer recovering defensively in time to
block the shot and keep the New York Knicks out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over that scene was repeated, a San Antonio Spurs
7-footer rejecting a New York swingman's shot. These National
Basketball Association finals are no longer about the Spurs and
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   It's height versus heart, and even the Knicks' corpuscles cannot
completely compensate for all those inches and pounds they give
away. In easily the most difficult loss of the postseason, New York
crept to within one point in the final minutes before begrudgingly
going down to the Spurs, 96-89.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether the Knicks can actually pull this off
was answered Wednesday night, when they fell behind by three games
to one. Whether they will be finished off by a team clearly more
talented and multidimensional in Game 5 or Game 6 is merely the
difference of waiting two days between games.
</P>
<P>
   But there they were, climbing uphill all evening, waiting for
the right moment to strike. You may remember Charlie Ward's errant
cross-court pass intercepted by Mario Elie with less than five
minutes left, a crucial turnover at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as anyone, Ward symbolized what this Knicks season
is about. Playing poorly for most of the series, he was asked to
play more and better because Chris Childs was physically unable to
perform after sustaining an injury in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   He made himself an offensive option in Childs' absence, scoring
10 points in the first quarter while darting all over the floor on
defense. At one point, he came around Duncan's backside as the
Spurs' center was about to corral a rebound. Snatching it away, he
motored upcourt before being knocked down and fouled.
</P>
<P>
   Maligned often and the subject of more trade rumors than Scottie
Pippen, Ward played as well at times Wednesday night as he has all
season.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before the Knicks took the floor, Kenny Anderson and
Stephon Marbury were literally holding court on opposite ends of
the floor. Two New York schoolboy legends, wearing immaculately
tailored suits, waiting to watch Ward direct his team in Game 4 of
the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about envy.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, stubborn as ever, would not take back comments he made
regarding Ward and Childs earlier this season, something like:
``They will never win a title with them. Never, never, never.''
</P>
<P>
   They may not, but on a night Ward's team needed a huge
performance from him, he delivered.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Larry Johnson, who did not look fluid on his
sprained knee moving up and down the court.
</P>
<P>
   In this wild postseason the Knicks have created for themselves,
he has been the lightning rod in so many instances. Whether it be
his immaculate 4-point play against Indiana, the way he shut down
Tim Duncan in the fourth quarter of Game 3 on Monday night or his
profane tirade at a practice, Johnson seems to sell papers and keep
the ratings from bottoming out.
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, he embodies the Knicks' dilemma: On the whole,
they're not a terribly likable cast. Yet they're accomplishing
something that's impossible not to like. Small, undermanned and
unrelenting, they're taking it to a physically superior team.
</P>
<P>
   The dichotomy is so hard to reconcile: Each time Johnson bends
his knees and looks into Duncan's eyes, he is much more than the
underdog; he is the antagonist in a basketball morality play _ the
reviled L.J. and his hooligans in gym shorts versus Saint Tim and
the San Antonio choirboys.
</P>
<P>
   The whole idea is provincial, really, as if we truly know that
Duncan and David Robinson are much better people than, say,
Houston. But we see what we want to see, and draw on the facts that
support our arguments.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, you have to give it up to San Antonio. In the
crucible of this wild series, when Duncan, Robinson and their
allegedly soft Western Conference friends could have folded up the
tent, they found a resolve befitting, well, the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle of height versus heart, the tall guys had
something in them, too, that told them not to quit.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did not execute down the stretch, and missed some
important shots that could have turned this game and series around.
For that, they can be faulted. Their season 48 minutes from over,
they gave you a nice run that no one expected.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, heart gets you only so far in the finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
