<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-COURT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REINSTATING SYMINGTON CONVICTION UNLIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The odds will be heavily stacked against prosecutors if they ask
a group of federal Appeals Court judges to consider reinstating
former Gov. Fife Symington's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals gets 600 to 800 requests a
year for such ``en banc'' reviews of its decisions. Only 13 were
granted last year, and eight the year before, according to court
records.
</P>
<P>
   An en banc review is one of several options facing prosecutors
from the U.S. Attorney's Office in Los Angeles as they decide how
to respond to Tuesday's appel late reversal. The court threw out Sy
mington's 1997 conviction on six counts of bank and wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1 split, the court panel found that U.S. District Judge
Roger Strand erred by dismissing an elderly juror from Syming ton's
jury during deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Fallout from the reversal began Wednesday. A group of union pen
sion funds suing Symington in U.S. Bankruptcy Court asked to delay
the former governor's upcoming bank ruptcy trial, saying more time
was needed to prepare in the wake of the federal ruling.
Symington's lawyers oppose the delay.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in the criminal case could respond to the appellate
reversal in several ways: seek the en banc review, appeal to the
U.S. Supreme Court, retry the case, craft a plea bargain or simply
drop the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we can persuade them not to proceed (with a new
trial),'' said Terence Lynam, a member of Symington's defense team.
</P>
<P>
   But lead prosecutor David Schin dler said Wednesday, ``We have
no present intention of just letting Symington walk.''
</P>
<P>
   A plea bargain is possible but appears somewhat unlikely in
light of statements by both sides Tuesday and Wednesday. Defense
attorneys said they do not want to make a deal that requires time
behind bars or admissions of felony conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they are willing to consider only a plea to
more than one felony, a factor that under normal circumstances
would bring prison time.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles prosecutor's office, one of the largest in the
nation, requests only two to four en banc hearings a year, said
Miriam Krinsky, chief of the criminal appel late division.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Levenson, a former prose cutor and law school professor
at Loyola University Law School, said it would be tough to win an
en banc hearing because the appellate deci sion in Symington's case
boils down to differing interpretations of the facts of the case,
not a dispute over the reading of the law.
</P>
<P>
   En banc hearings generally are granted only if extremely
important constitutional issues are at stake or if a decision seems
to directly conflict with another case on which the court has
ruled, appellate court spokesman Mark Mendenhall said.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court, meanwhile, would be heard
only if a new issue of constitutional law was at stake, Levenson
said.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by prosecutors on any appeal is probably a month
away, Krinsky said. Justice Department officials in Washington,
D.C., in cluding the U.S. solicitor general, must make the final
call on any appeal.
</P>
<P>
   If prosecutors opt simply to retry Symington, they could do so
imme diately on the six counts that were reversed. However, if they
wanted to include 11 counts on which Sy mington's jury was hung,
they would have to seek a new indict ment on those charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd have to reconvene a grand jury . . . just as if they
were starting over,'' Lynam said. ``That's a little more of a
hurdle they'd have to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Schindler said cost is not an issue. Decisions are made ``based
on the merits, and whether it's in the interest of justice to
pursue a case.'' The cost of the five-year prosecu tion has never
been revealed, though Lynam estimated it ``in the millions.''
</P>
<P>
   A retrial would cost less than the first trial because the
thousands of documents and exhibits in the case are ready for use
in court, Schindler said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution team, however, may not be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Attorney Nora Ma nella, who presided over the Sy
mington investigation for five years, is now a federal judge in Los
Angeles. Her successor, Alejandro N. Mayorkas, spent four years
specializing in prosecution of secu rities and bank fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Drooyan, who headed the criminal division that
prosecuted Symington, has since left the office for private
practice. His successor as division chief was Schindler's litiga
tion partner, George Cardona, who helped try the case against
Syming ton in 1997. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
