<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-JOBS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-OCTANE ECONOMY A BOON FOR TEENS SEEKING SUMMER JOBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE   AND GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- School's out, summer is here and for many San
Fernando Valley students, that means grabbing a slice of financial
freedom with that dreaded, but oh-so-necessary, summer job.
</P>
<P>
   As Reseda High School senior John McCrary graduates Thursday, he
already has scored a $9-an-hour job at Northridge Hospital Medical
Center, delivering supplies to operating rooms, nursing stations
and specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that hard to get,'' said McCrary, 19. ``You just
have to look and go for something you enjoy. It helps to look at
places other kids might not think to apply.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrary is right, according to economists.
</P>
<P>
   These days any teen-ager looking for a summer job should find
one because of the supercharged economy, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to say the summer job opportunities are going to be
pretty rich. Almost every business is looking for somebody,'' said
Jack Kyser, chief economist at the Los Angeles County Economic
Development Corp., a nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser said this is the best job market for teen-agers he's ever
seen since he began tracking the Los Angeles economy in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy roaring, unemployment last month hit
5.5 &UR;  &LR; percent, its lowest level since July 1990, when the state
entered a dark economic period that lasted until 1995, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser and other economists have noticed an increased number of
help wanted signs in store windows _ an unsophisticated yet
accurate gauge of the market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question for teens is what do they bring to the table
in terms of skills,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The more skills teens have, the better. Clerical,
communication, computer and machine shop skills are good ones to
hone.
</P>
<P>
   Like McCrary did &UR;  &LR; -- He took a work experience class at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   And like Reseda High School junior Denise Morataya, who is
putting her clerical skills to work as a secretary at Allstate
insurance for the summer. The 15-year-old aspiring psychologist is
making $148 a week, plenty for her needs now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was referred by my sister, but knowing how to do the job --
like how to be a secretary -- helps a lot,'' she said. ``It can be
hard without that _ going out there cold with no skills.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey released by the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics at the
end of April found that this generation of teens likes to earn a
wage during time off from school, especially in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-four percent of 15-year-olds work at jobs in places like
stores and restaurants, said the National Longitudinal Survey of
Youth taken in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At Reseda High School, many students said they would go ``just
about anywhere'' to find a job, but a few said the key to
summertime employment bliss -- or as close as you can get to that
-- means finding a job that suits you.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fallbrook Mall's Sport Chalet, five high school students
found jobs in departments that handle their favorite sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been biking for a long time, and I got lucky when they
hired me here,'' said Craig Svanberg, 16, who works in Sport
Chalet's bicycle department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm good at repairing and tuning bikes. This job is a little
about the money, but more about having fun because I love what I
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Whale, 16, sells sports clothing at the store while her
friends go to the movies or the beach. But she enjoys the financial
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you're more responsible, and it gets you used to
the working world,'' Whale said. ``I like having the money so I can
buy my own stuff without having to ask anyone for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Smith, deputy chief economist for the California
Department of Finance, said service jobs, like fast-food
restaurants, are common summer stops for teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder to hire people now. If I were a high school
student, I would think that this is a very good summer to work,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics survey found that 28 percent of
15-year-olds worked during both the summer and the school year.
Eight percent reported working only during the school year, and 6
percent said they worked only during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed that academically gifted and academically
challenged students were equally likely to work.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are always those cases that draw frustration. These
days, 17-year-old Zachory Kemp is feeling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've applied at movie theaters and video stores, and no one is
calling back. I'm going to have to go fast food,'' said Kemp, a
Reseda High School sophomore. ``I've been looking for a job for a
year, and it's just getting harder. I might try some
supermarkets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
