<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS USE HEFT, BUT IT'S USELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kurt Thomas would not be caught bragging about the
Knicks' defense on San Antonio's David Robinson and Tim Duncan, not
with the two of them scoring a combined 45 points in Game 3, not
with the power duo so clearly in control of the Spurs' two
victories to start the finals.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a new confidence to the Knicks for Game 4, if their
ability to control the Spurs' big men had suddenly turned this
series on its ear, then the swagger would have to remain in the
walk. They had used their bodies to push Duncan away from the
basket, but the Knicks would be careful not to use their mouths to
push his buttons, too.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Thomas _ and later Chris Dudley _ were asked if they
could possibly hope to shrink Duncan's numbers further from his
20-point, fourth-quarter-shutout effort in Game 3, they deferred to
the dominance of Duncan and Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as much as you can do because they get so many
touches,'' Thomas said. ``If they get 80 to 90 plays, 60 of the
plays go to those two guys. It's going to be difficult to stop
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did not stop Duncan on Wednesday night. Although they
rode the bulky body of Larry Johnson to successfully nudge Duncan a
few inches away from his preferred spot in the low post, and forced
him to rely on his turnaround jumper from the middle of the paint,
or on a shot from the perimeter or around the foul line, Duncan got
28 points on 9 of 19 shooting. Robinson had 14 points. Only once in
the half did Duncan get a completely uncontested layup when, with
the lean Dudley barely able to move Duncan an inch on the baseline,
Duncan took a pass along the baseline from Jaren Jackon and laid it
in to give San Antonio a 44-40 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to meet them as early as possible and try to move him
out just an extra step,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said of the strategy
before Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   But Duncan adjusted to the pressure in a way he did not do in
Game 3. With the Knicks also putting pressure on Robinson to take
away the high-low game with which the Spurs drilled the Knicks in
the first two games, Duncan simply moved his all-round game away
from the basket. Although he got deep post position several times,
it was usually a few feet from the basket, where he set up for his
jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the first half, Duncan took a pass from Avery
Johnson at the foul line. Johnson _ 5 inches shorter _ stood in
front of him, but when the 7-foot Duncan lofted a 14-foot jumper
over his hands, Johnson was powerless to alter the shot. And when
Johnson found Duncan on the right wing, Marcus Camby was playing
well off Duncan when he put up his midrange bank shot that made the
score 59-46 early in the third quarter. Then, two times in a row,
the mismatch with Johnson was exploited. The Knicks had managed to
alter Duncan's game _ his shots were not the high-percentage ones
he got in the first two games and he was flustered enough to commit
three inexplicable turnovers late in the game _ but the alterations
were not drastic enough to change the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go to Duncan so often, you're not going to stop him,''
Dudley said. ``He's going to score and score a lot but you try to
limit his effective and the percentages. You keep a body on him and
take away the easy shots.''
</P>
<P>
   After letting Duncan run amok against one-on-one defense in the
first half of Game 1, the Knicks have used a variety of double
teams to shadow him. He finished Game 1 with 33 points and had 25
in Game 2. But Monday _ and again in Game 4 _ the Knicks hoped to
tweak their help on defense just a bit. Johnson will never be able
to stop Duncan's flawless turnaround jumper, but in Game 3, he had
successfully invaded and shrunk Duncan's comfort zone and had
pushed Duncan closer to a second defender who comes over to help.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the constant attention paid to Duncan with
the help defense opens up everyone else. In Game 1, when the double
team finally came, the Spurs kicked the ball out to the perimeter,
where Jackson awaited with a flurry of 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   The long-distance shots did not fall in Game 3, but Wednesday
night, the double team on Duncan cleared the way for the outside
shooters. In the third quarter, Duncan was double teamed, with
Johnson again blocking the easy way to the basket. So Duncan swung
the ball over to Johnson, who swished a 19-footer. Sean Elliott,
Mario Elie and Johnson combined for 46 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
