<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7635 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR &LR;      06-24 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY DELIBERATIONS BEGIN IN SLEEPWALKING TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Phoenix jury must now decide whether to accept a man's claim
that he is not responsible for killing his wife because he was
sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   After a month of testimony in a case that has drawn
international attention, the jury began deliberating Scott
Falater's fate Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Juan Martinez's urged the panel to take a lesson from
the story of Don Quixote. He said they should reject the defense
that Falater's attorneys presented with the help of two nationally
known sleepwalking experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fanciful sort of world, just like Don Quixote's,''
Martinez said. ``Are you willing to follow him there?''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said that Falater, who acknowledges stabbing his wife
and dragging her body into a swimming pool at their Phoenix home,
``is just plainly and simply a killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``His actions clearly indicate it was premeditated,'' Martinez
said. He said Falater stabbed his wife Yarmila 44 times in the back
yard, stashed his bloody clothes, put on pajamas and bandaged a
cut, returned to find that she was still breathing, and dragged her
into the swimming pool to finish her off.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing argument, defense attorney Michael Kimerer fired
back at Martinez, accusing the combative prosecutor of distorting
evidence in an effort to win a first-degree murder conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who is the man from La Mancha creating the fantasy
world is the prosecution in this case,'' Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer was particularly critical of Martinez's claim Wednesday
that a psychologist's cryptic notes about an ``unforgivable sin''
showed that Falater had a motive for murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There simply is no basis or motive or reason why Scott Falater
would kill his wife,'' said Kimerer, who during the trial called
more than a dozen character witnesses. They testified that Falater,
43, was a devoted family man and a respected engineer known for his
calm demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sadness and the horror in this case is that because you're
in a sleepwalking state and have no voluntary control over your
actions, you have ended up killing the most important thing in your
life,'' Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   As the burly defense attorney spoke to the jury, Falater sat
behind him, expressionless, hands clasped in his lap.
</P>
<P>
   Crews from ``Court TV,'' ABC's ``20/20'' and from MSNBC recorded
the session. Their presence, along with squadrons of local press,
reflect the national fascination about the unusual defense on
behalf of a man whose frenzied 1997 outburst shattered the apparent
calm of his home life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a person who has never been in any trouble, this is a
man who had a wonderful marriage, and this is a man who had two of
the finest children you ever could have,'' Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's bloody attack ``was a total aberration from everything
in his life,'' Kimerer said. And that supports the defense claim
that Falater was acting involuntarily and therefore is not legally
responsible, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer offered his own literary allusion. He said the Falater
case reminded him of Franz Kafka's story ``The Metamorphosis,''
about a man who awoke one morning to find that he had been
transformed into a giant insect.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tragically transformed man is Scott Falater, Kimerer
said. He said Falater awoke from his bloody sleepwalking episode
with no memory of what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finds out that the life he had . . . is gone, the wife that
he loves is gone, his children are gone,'' Kimerer said. ``He's in
jail and he doesn't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer reminded the jury of Rosalind Cartwright, the Chicago
sleepwalking expert who said she believed so strongly in Falater
that she was testifying for free. Cartwright had also said she
feels obligated to educate the public about sleepwalking violence,
Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a sham,'' Kimerer said of the sleepwalking defense.
``Sleepwalking homicide or violence is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez offered his own interpretation of the handwritten notes
of a psychologist who evaluated Falater after the killing. It was
unclear whether the notes were a series of unconnected observations
or a disjointed narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unforgivable sin _ not continuing to grow _ getting stuck in
life,'' the notes read. Dad did it, so did SF (Falater). Dad told
him not to grow past his wife like he felt he did _ Scott did it
too.''
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Falater said his comment about ``unforgivable
sin'' was a reference to his concerns about a Mormon doctrine that
says those who kill will find no forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez offered a new interpretation of Falater's comment.
He told the jury that it explained his motive for killing Yarmila.
``We know by his own statement that she committed an unforgivable
sin,'' he said, drawing a conclusion that did not appear justified
by the trial's discussion of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez offered a series of speculations on the meaning of
``unforgivable sin,'' all of which suggested that Falater had
voluntarily admitted having a motive for killing his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps, she didn't want to attend temple,'' he said. Perhaps
it was her refusal to have more children, as Scott wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Then Martinez, who has claimed throughout the trial that the
Falater marriage was unraveling at the time of Yarmila's death,
commented sarcastically about the defense's version of the
Falater's home life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sure sounds like there's grounds to say this is the
happiest marriage around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer attacked Martinez's interpretation of the notes. ``This
concept of unforgiven sin is simply not supported by the
evidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both attorneys framed the case as a battle of the experts, in
which the jury must decide who offered the more convincing
interpretation of Falater's killing of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez claimed that the defense experts had defied common
sense, performing sloppy analysis of Falater's actions because they
were eager to add his case to the catalogue of sleepwalking
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so quick to want to make this a cause celbre,'' said
Martinez. ``They want to be a part of this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez ridiculed the extensive resumes of Cartwright and Dr.
Roger Broughton, the Canadian sleep disorder researcher who said
sleepwalking was ``by far the most probable'' explanation of
Falater's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I submit to you that these (resumes) are nothing but steps to
their shrines of self-indulgence,'' he said. Martinez attacked
Broughton's explanation of why Falater stashed his bloody clothes
in the wheel well of his Volvo stationwagon, which was parked in
the garage.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton said Falater was sleepwalking as he removed the
clothes and put them in a Tupperware container, which he then
placed in a plastic bag that police found in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian researcher, explaining that sleepwalkers often
carry out habitual tasks, said Falater had been accustomed to
storing the clothes there and using them for yard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is opposed to what the defendant says,'' Martinez noted.
He pointed out that Falater had testified that the clothes were
stashed in the car for use in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Walking over to the defense table, Martinez extended both arms
and pointed directly at Falater, ``You couldn't get your story
straight,'' he said to Falater, who looked back without expression.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer countered by describing Broughton and Cartwright as
``two of the finest, best experts in the world on parasomnias,'' a
subset of sleep disorders that includes sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's experts knew a lot about people who have
trouble breathing in their sleep, Kimerer said, but they had little
experience dealing with sleepwalkers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
