<HEADER>
A7638 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-LADN     06-24 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MOVIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY INDICATORS POINT TO SIZZLING SEASON AT THE THE CINEMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hollywood's box office is lightsaber hot.
</P>
<P>
   Industry trackers interviewed Wednesday say the summer of 1999
will demolish last year's $2.58 billion U.S. record _ a daring
prediction since less than one-third of the 15-week summer period
has gone by.
</P>
<P>
   So far, domestic grosses have jumped an astounding 27 percent
over last summer's and are on pace to hit $3.2 billion _ revenue
from 665 million tickets _ when Labor Day rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty confident we'll set a new record,'' said Paul
Dergarabedian, president of the Exhibitor Relations Co. tracking
service. ``We've had terrific numbers so far, and there are a lot
of big films still to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer is the industry's most critical period, accounting for 40
percent of all ticket sales. In a change from previous years, when
the top movies were released by late June, movie fans this season
still can look forward to three movies considered sure-fire hits
and a dozen other films with solid prospects in the next 2{ months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely no question that this summer will do better
than last,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source
forecasting service. ``There's a lot of diversity in the schedule,
with films for every audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The dominant player has been 20th Century Fox's ``Star Wars:
Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace,'' which topped $333 million Tuesday
after five weeks. But four other movies have had strong results.
Universal's ``Notting Hill,'' Disney's ``Tarzan,'' New Line's
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' and Paramount's ``The
General's Daughter'' opened strong.
</P>
<P>
   All but ``Notting Hill'' beat ``Phantom Menace'' last weekend
even though the George Lucas prequel grossed nearly $19 million. In
a stunning show of drawing power, the latest Friday-Sunday period
set the record as the biggest nonholiday weekend ever. It was also
the first time three films ever topped $20 million on a nonholiday
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of performance underscores the success of megaplexes.
About 5,000 new screens have been added across the country in the
past four years, most of them in massive megaplex theaters that can
show a hit movie in as many as six different auditoriums at once,
Dergarabedian noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might think that there are too many major titles out
normally, but the audience has expanded,'' he said. ``The megaplex
strategy can work when there's a lot of good product out there.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, theater owners are no longer complaining, as they
used to, that studios are bunching most of their key titles at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have the shelf space to accommodate major titles as
they come out,'' said AMC marketing chief Richard Fay. ``When you
have three films do as well as those did last weekend, it shows
that megaplexes have expanded the grossing potential of movies. I
look for that to continue to happen this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Positive buzz has escalated recently for three upcoming
comedies: Sony's ``Big Daddy'' starring Adam Sandler, which will
open Friday; Warner Bros.' Will Smith vehicle, ``Wild Wild West,''
which will open Wednesday; and Paramount's ``Runaway Bride,'' which
reunites ``Pretty Woman'' stars Julia Roberts and Richard Gere and
is scheduled to open July 30. Each could take in at least $150
million.
</P>
<P>
   The second tier contains a wide variety of July and August
titles with breakout potential, led by Universal's teen comedy
``American Pie,'' due July 9; Warner's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' with Tom
Cruise and Nicole Kidman in Stanley Kubrick's last film, to be out
July 16; and Disney's ``Inspector Gadget,'' which will open July
23.
</P>
<P>
   Positive word also has emerged on Fox's ``Lake Placid,''
Paramount's ``The Wood,'' DreamWorks' ``The Haunting,'' Warner's
``Deep Blue Sea,'' Universal's ``Bowfinger,'' Warner's ``Iron
Giant,'' MGM's remake of ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' Miramax's
``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' and Universal's ``Dudley Do-Right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer is different from previous years where you'd see
most of the top movies by the middle of June and then wind down,''
said Bucksbaum, who rates ``American Pie,'' ``Inspector Gadget''
and ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' as the potential sleepers.
</P>
<P>
   Fay said Universal's ``The Mummy,'' which opened May 7, played a
key role in jump-starting moviegoing a dozen days before ``Phantom
Menace'' opened. ``People got excited about going to the movies,''
he said. ``So now if they can't get in to see `Tarzan' or `The
General's Daughter,' they find another movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The first four months of 1999 suffered by comparison with 1998,
mostly because of the record-setting performance of ``Titanic''
last year. It took until last week for revenues to catch up with
1998's, when the industry set a $6.95 billion record for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like a banner summer,'' said Fox distribution chief
Tom Sherak. ``The bottom line is it looks like we'll put a dent in
the bad first quarter exhibitors had.''
</P>
<P>
   The strength already likely in July and August has prompted more
shuffling of release dates than usual. Release of Universal's Steve
Martin-Eddie Murphy comedy ``Bowfinger'' was moved twice and is now
set for Aug. 13. Other prominent films such as Fox's action-drama
``The Fight Club,'' Sony's Martin Lawrence comedy ``Blue Streak''
and Universal's baseball drama ``For Love of the Game'' have been
moved back to the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a spectacular screening of `Blue Streak' and we felt it
matched up better in the fall lineup, which had been much more
adult and comedy-free,'' said Sony distribution chief Jeff Blake.
``So we chose to be the first big event film of the fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
