<HEADER>
A7644 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-BOMBING-WARNI     06-24 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-BOMBING-WARNING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIA ANALYST QUESTIONED TARGET BEFORE CHINESE EMBASSY BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to clarify `Thursday's issue' of Washington Post in 3rd graf.
CHANGES `superiors' to `co-workers' in 12th graf. INSERTS date
Chinese EMBASSY moved in 15th graf. Changes `embassy' to `arms
headquarters' in 19th graf.)  (mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A midlevel analyst in the CIA raised doubts about
whether military planners were zeroing in on the right building
shortly before American bombs struck the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, the night of May 7, government officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials spoke on the same day that the administration
began to brief Congress about an internal investigation of the
bombing that included an account of the analyst's warning. The
administration provided a similar reconstruction to the Chinese
last week in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The officials gave slightly conflicting accounts of the timing
and specificity of the warnings, first reported in Thursday's issue
of The Washington Post. But for whatever reason, according to the
administration, the doubts either came too late or were lost in the
bureaucratic thicket before the strike that killed three Chinese
and wounded at least 20 others.
</P>
<P>
   The accident, at the height of NATO's air campaign meant to
deter Yugoslav forces from atrocities against Albanians in Kosovo,
was a stinging embarrassment to the United States and a serious
setback to relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   In an analysis immediately after the satellite-guided bombs from
an American B-2 struck the embassy, military officials explained
that the intended target had been the headquarters of a Yugoslav
arms agency that is actually a few blocks from the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put an X on the map, but we put the X in the wrong place,''
a senior American official said at the time. The arms agency and
the embassy are about 200 yards apart.
</P>
<P>
   According to the officials familiar with the investigation, the
midlevel analyst did not know where the embassy was situated. But
based on his familiarity with downtown Belgrade, he did know _ or
thought he knew _ where the arms-agency headquarters was.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the building being targeted might not be the
headquarters, though he left open the possibility that it was a
related office, according to one official.
</P>
<P>
   One official said the analyst had raised his concerns many days
in advance of the bombing mission. Two other officials, however,
said Wednesday that the warnings were raised closer to the May 7
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there had been a few more days, it could have been
prevented,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior government official said Wednesday night that a
classified report from the inspector general's office of the CIA
has concluded that the analyst's cautions indeed went unheeded _ in
large measure because he departed for two days of training and
returned to discover, to his horror, that the bombers were already
on their way.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Wednesday night, and might not be for some
time, how furious an alarm the analyst had tried to raise before
his departure, and whether his co-workers had simply dismissed the
warnings or given them serious consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was saying, `Gee, I don't think that's the right
building,''' one official recalled Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after the bombing mission, CIA officials and
senior officers at the U.S. military's European Command learned to
their dismay that American bombs had struck the Chinese Embassy.
Pictures of grief-stricken survivors amid the rubble were a deep
embarrassment to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When the target was initially checked against electronic mapping
data in U.S. and NATO computers to guard against civilian
casualties, no alarms were sounded because a half-dozen government
databases had the location of the old Chinese Embassy before it
moved in 1996, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav arms agency headquarters were picked because
intelligence experts have long suspected that it helped America's
rivals to develop advanced weapons, and that it sold weapons to
help finance the Yugoslav military, American officials explained
immediately after the warning.
</P>
<P>
   In their briefing to Congress Wednesday, the administration
officials said that a cascading series of errors contributed to the
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The first involved the use of three outdated maps, two
commercial maps made in Yugoslavia and a 1997 map prepared by the
National Intelligence Mapping Agency. That map was based on
information in a series of intelligence agency databases that were
outdated. But when the databases were checked against each other,
no mistake was detected _ because they were all based on the same
sources. ``There was some circularity to the databases,'' one
official said, meaning that they were based on the same erroneous
information.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the address of the arms headquarters, and thus its
coordinates, was extrapolated based on an examination of numbers on
nearby streets. ``It was a pretty rough estimate,'' one official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation of how the mistakes were made was given to the
Chinese last week by Thomas Pickering, the undersecretary of state,
in a mission to Beijing that also included representatives of the
Pentagon, the CIA, the Defense Intelligence Agency and the National
Security Council. To the surprise of the American delegation, their
Chinese counterparts were matter-of-fact about the incident. ``They
raised no allegations or alternative scenarios,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese officials had demanded earlier to know the names of
those responsible, and to get an account of whether they were being
held responsible. But Pickering's delegation deflected those
questions, identifying no individuals and simply assuring the
Chinese that ``there would be no attempt to whitewash the
incident,'' one administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   But a week after the explanation, relations with Beijing still
seem frozen in place. Chinese officials have not restarted talks on
China's effort to join the World Trade Organization, a negotiation
that was reaching its final stages when the bombing occurred and
resulted in an outpouring of government-orchestrated anti-American
protests on the streets of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It now looks like this is going to take a long time to get
back to normal,'' one trade official said Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
