<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7651 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK     06-24 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINER CASTOFF OLIVARES EARNING HALO WITH ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He leads Anaheim pitchers in victories, has the
Angels' lowest earned run average, even claims his club's lone
complete game.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like someone the pitching-poor Mariners could use.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Olivares, however, is quite happy where he is. Besides,
Seattle had its chance, employing him for 13 games in 1997, and
didn't quite know what to do with the right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just been pitching good,'' said Olivares, who won't face
the Mariners on this trip but is scheduled to catch them in Anaheim
next week. ``I'm more consistent and I'm able to hit spots with all
of my pitches. When you're able to do that, it helps you out.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares, 6-5 with a 3.45 ERA this season, was successful before
he joined the Mariners, playing for St. Louis and Detroit. He
obviously has distinguished himself since leaving Seattle as a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   As a Mariner, he was 1-4 with a 5.49 ERA in 13 outings, mainly
as the fifth starter. He didn't make the club's playoff roster. He
was gone by the winter.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Mariner manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares says he wasn't used properly to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, I didn't pitch every five days, for whatever reason,''
Olivares said. ``I got caught in between. It didn't help me. Every
sinker-ball pitcher needs to pitch regularly to stay effective. I'd
be rested and get too strong.''
</P>
<P>
   BUZZ STUFF: Buhner Buzz Night, the annual shorning of a few
thousand fans, will take place before Thursday's game, even though
the principal figure involved remains hobbled.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners right fielder Jay Buhner, who has been on the disabled
list since May 19 with a strained left hamstring, had hoped to be
back for this homestand, but aggravated the muscle while running
the bases to show he was healthy again. His return now is
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be 72 hours until I know anything,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner says the Kingdome, with its AstroTurf playing field, is
largely responsible for many of the injuries he has incurred in
recent seasons, the hard surface putting an extra strain on joints
and muscles. He said the place was the cause of serious injuries to
Edgar Martinez and Alex Rodriguez as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ballpark has shortened my career, no doubt about it,''
Buhner said. ``Anybody will tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner won't play in the Kingdome again, a place he says will
leave him with more good memories than bad. He won division titles
there, played in a couple of no-hitters, hit for the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   He also won't forget standing atop the building watching the
Blue Angels fly just 50 feet over head, using the Kingdome flagpole
as a guide point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's home,'' he said. ``I made a name for myself here.''
</P>
<P>
   FOUL POLE: One guy who didn't flourish under the cement top was
Dick Pole, a former Mariner pitcher now working as Anaheim's
pitching coach. He had an undistinguished two-year tour with
Seattle during the first two seasons of the franchise in 1977 and
1978.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for memories, Pole said, ``I don't have any. They were all
bad ones. That's why I'm a good coach, because I know how not to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pole said he's not sad to see the Kingdome go.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can get rid of this place as far as I'm concerned. It
wasn't a good place to pitch. I tell (Angels pitchers) not to walk
anybody. This place can be like arena baseball. You come into a
place like this, you tell your pitchers to keep it to five runs or
less, and you have a good chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL CHART: Mariner pitcher Jeff Fassero will start
Thursday's game against Anaheim, even after appearing in relief
Monday and Tuesday. First baseman David Segui won't be in the
lineup, still hobbled by a knee strain.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero faced two batters in the series opener against the
Angels, four the night before in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella called in his struggling left-hander Wednesday for an
office chat and is confident the player will be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him and he told me he was fine,'' the manager
said.
</P>
<P>
   Segui's knee remains sore after he injured it while taking a
swing and catching his spikes Monday in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think it would be a few more days,'' Piniella said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
