<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY RETURN FOR SABERHAGEN, RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ORIOLES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ As much as his Red Sox teammates appreciate his
ability to throw a party, Bret Saberhagen meant much more to them
throwing on the mound in Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's 5-0 win over the
Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   And it was clear, from the heavy emotion Saberhagen invested in
the pumped fist he threw after striking out Baltimore's Mike
Bordick with two on and two out in the fifth inning, that he
prefers to be more than team toastmaster, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I feel like part of the team?'' said Saberhagen, who hadn't
pitched since stepping on a piece of broken glass at a team party
he hosted in New York a couple of weeks ago. ``It hasn't been two
years since my last win, but it sure feels like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, who came into the game with as many wins (two) as
stints on the disabled list, shut out the Orioles on seven hits and
a walk in 5 1/3 innings for his first win since April 13. This was
only his eighth start, one in which John Valentin, on a night he
said he couldn't see the ball, broke a scoreless tie with a two-run
home run in the fifth off Juan Guzman and Reggie Jefferson hit a
solo homer in the Sox' three-run ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a frustrating year,'' Saberhagen said. ``But it's a
matter of getting out there the rest of the year and taking my turn
when it comes up. It doesn't feel like I've been a big part of it,
but there's still time.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, who is always in the middle of all
things Red Sox and earlier extended his hitting streak to 11 games
with a seventh-inning single, left after his triple into the
right-field corner in the ninth. Manager Jimy Williams said
Garciaparra, who is 13 for 18 with two walks and a hit by pitch in
his last five games, hurt his upper left leg rounding first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to say day to day,'' Williams said when asked
about Garciaparra's availability in Thursday night's rubber game
against the Orioles, who had won four in a row and 11 of 12 before
falling Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's wait and see until tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Merloni, who started at second base in place of Jose
Offerman after playing third base for Valentin Tuesday night,
finished the game at short and made the relay on a game-ending
double play with Tim Wakefield on the mound. Merloni would start at
short Thursday night if Garciaparra can't go, which would seem
likely given Williams's penchant for prudence when it comes to leg
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we have a team,'' Williams said. ``Certainly, we
don't make up lineups ahead of time, but Merloni can play four
spots. Maybe that's the way we have to be, the way we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen benefited from 2 2/3 innings of splendid relief by
Derek Lowe and another block of home plate by catcher Jason
Varitek, who prevented Cal Ripken from scoring on Charles Johnson's
single in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken, who had opened the inning with a line single to center,
took second on a sacrifice and tried to beat a throw home from left
fielder Damon Buford. Varitek, however, planted his right shinguard
between Ripken's toe and the plate and applied the tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I got away with it,'' Buford said of his throw. ``It
wasn't the strongest throw. I threw it off my back foot. Tek
(Varitek) did a good job of blocking the plate. Really, it was all
Tek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what, he's good. If the throw's close enough,
he's going to block the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Buford, who struck out with the bases loaded in the first,
singled twice and made a terrific running catch of B.J. Surhoff's
foul fly at the left-field railing in the seventh. He was playing
left in one of those head-scratching lineup moves made by Williams,
who gave Troy O'Leary the night off even though he'd homered in
each of the previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   So, what else is new? Darren Lewis hit leadoff instead of
Offerman for only the second time this season and tripled and was
grazed by a pitch from Guzman just before Valentin went deep.
Jefferson, serving as the designated hitter and batting third
despite having just one hit in 13 at-bats this month, hit his
fourth home run in the ninth off Ricky Bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like each other in here,'' Williams said when asked why
this team recovers so nicely from tough losses, like the one
Tuesday night, in which the Sox took a 3-1 lead into the eighth and
lost, 5-3. ``It's easy to say, you know, but it has to be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I think. I hear them pull for each other, things
like that. It's a compliment to them. We just try to make it simple
and play hard out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen departed with a 2-0 lead courtesy of the home run by
Valentin, who interrupted a stream of strikeouts by Orioles starter
Juan Guzman _ nine whiffs in 5 2/3 innings, which included striking
out the side in both the first and third innings _ with his seventh
homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That more than compensated for his three whiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see the ball, I couldn't pick up the rotation,''
Valentin said. ``It might have been because of the day off. That's
why I looked as bad as I did. It was scary out there. I was shaking
my head.''
</P>
<P>
   And Saberhagen was pumping his fist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just picked up where he left off,'' Buford said. ``A great
pitcher. A good night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
