<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A GAME WORTH WATCHING 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Let's get the basics out of the way first.
</P>
<P>
   No team has ever come back from a 3-1 deficit to win the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   If the New York Knicks are going to do it, they'll have to win
two games on the road against a team that has lost two playoff
games, period.
</P>
<P>
   That said, let us salute the return of an old friend. After
three messy games that typified what the NBA has become in the late
'90s, an honest-to-God NBA basketball game broke out
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. This is not going to be any consolation to the
disappointed Knicks fans, but Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's 96-89 San Antonio
victory in Game 4 of the championship series was something that
wouldn't have been out of place 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There was movement. There was some decent shooting. There was a
sense of give-and-take, of just plain flow. We saw some superb
individual play, most notably the 28-point, 18-rebound performance
by mortal lock Finals MVP Tim Duncan, and we saw some collective
brilliance by a Spurs team that is now just one victory away from
winning the first championship in its combined 26-year ABA-NBA
history.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks made them sweat, but when there was a game to be won
the Spurs made all the requisite plays. Charlie Ward walked to the
free throw line with a chance to tie the game at 81 with 5:25
remaining. He made the first, but missed the second. New York never
did tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had one opportunity to get within 1 when Larry
Johnson, at the tail end of a miserable game at both ends of the
floor, had two shots with his team trailing, 86-83. He made the
first, whereupon San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich tried the old
let's-call-time-out-and-ice-him ploy. By golly, it worked. Johnson
missed the second one, and that's as close as New York would come,
primarily because when the Knicks needed a basket they missed six
outside shots in succession.
</P>
<P>
   But shooting wasn't what bothered Knicks mentor Jeff Van Gundy.
``Offense was not the problem tonight,'' he pointed out. ``We got
killed on the boards and we didn't guard as well as we needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The stats didn't lie. San Antonio outrebounded the Knicks by 15
(49-34), and that doesn't begin to outline the inside dominance of
Duncan and David Robinson, who combined for 35 rebounds and whose
altitudinous presence eliminated any hope New York might have had
of submitting an inside game to augment the sniping of Latrell
Sprewell (26) and Allan Houston (a controlled 20).
</P>
<P>
   Duncan blocked five shots, sometimes in tandem with Robinson.
And when Duncan blocks shots, he doesn't just block them. He
ingests them. He even comes up with some two-handers. The Knicks
had no chance.
</P>
<P>
   This has actually been a textbook NBA seven-game series. The
favored team won Games 1 and 2 despite not playing anywhere near
its capabilities for the simple reason that Games 1 and 2 were at
home. The other team came home and played a classic Game 3,
displaying far more energy and desire. The Knicks thoroughly
deserved to win that game.
</P>
<P>
   If form were to prevail, the Spurs should have come out with a
renewed sense of purpose for Game 4 Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. They should
have analyzed the goings-on in Game 3 and realized just how little
true energy they had. They should have made a vow to become the
aggressor. They should have made a pact to become a true team, and
not merely an aggregation featuring two big stars and 10 guys just
happy to be drawing a paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly what happened. San Antonio led at the half,
picked up some nice breathing room by scoring the first 7 points of
the third quarter, then acted professionally when threatened in
what Magic Johnson used to call ``Winnin' Time.''
</P>
<P>
   And let's talk balance. You've already heard about Duncan and
Robinson. The Spurs also got the precise contributions they needed
from their other three starters.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Elliott, heretofore very quiet, had a solid 14. Mario Elie,
completely buried by Houston in Game 3, had a vintage Mario Elie
game, mixing up an occasional outside shot with some hard slashes
to the hoop, all of it adding up to a valuable 18-point game.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the Spurs got a first-class game from the
oft-forgotten point guard, Avery Johnson. AJ had a 14-point,
10-assist game that featured three first-half running hooks and
great floor leadership during a vital 44-minute stint. ``AJ is so
important to us,'' saluted Popovich. ``He keeps us in our sets.
Without him, we look a whole lot different. He gives us coordinated
possessions. He is The Man for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have every right to feel proud of what they did
Wednesday night, but the job is not yet done. The Knicks have
revealed themselves to be an ornery bunch. They don't quit in games
and they don't quit in series. But they really have next to no
hope. They have gone a long way but there are two very tall
obstacles in their path now.
</P>
<P>
   New York will fight, but the quest is now officially quixotic.
They might win Friday night, but three straight against this team?
Not remotely possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
