<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ In a little-remarked but crucial
shift, the technocrats' 18-year domination of Mexican politics,
during which government policies have modernized the economy but
impoverished the country's working class majority, appears to be
ending. Unlike President Ernesto Zedillo (Yale Ph.D.'78) and his
two predecessors, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, (Harvard Ph.D.'78) and
Miguel de la Madrid, (Harvard M.A.'65) none of the four candidates
currently seeking the presidential nomination of the governing
party, the PRI, which has won 11 straight presidential elections
here, are technocrats. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   TIBET-DIVISIONS (Dharmsala, India) _ Sitting in a shady
courtyard near the Dalai Lama's residence, two young Tibetans, both
of them born in India, argued about what strategy would lead most
quickly to their return to the homes they have never seen. Their
perspectives represented the division of opinion that appears to be
growing here. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-NUDE-BEACH (LaJolla, Calif.) _ Blacks Beach, one of the
oldest and most famous of California's nude beaches, may be history
as town clamps down. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   S.C.-POLITICS (Columbia, S.C.) _ South Carolina's primary is
going to be more crucial than ever this campaign season to
Republicans, who are showing up earlier and more often than in
years past. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-LAWSUITS (Undated) _ As a sign of the impact on gun
companies of lawsuits being filed around the country, a major
manufacturer of so-called Saturday Night specials announces it has
filed for bankruptcy. In addition, representatives of other major
manufacturers say they are willing to talk about how to better
police themselves. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
