<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOTHAM NATIVE SHOWS KNICKS THE EXIT DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All of Gotham went to bed in a bad mood Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   All except some folks who hail from West 97th Street, where
Mario Elie grew up, the place where he learned what kind of
toughness it takes to be a winner.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 friends and family who were guests of Elie for the
disastrous Spurs outcome in Game 3 _ when Elie was whistled for two
quick fouls and never could become a factor _ were the only city
dwellers who left Madison Square Garden smiling.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are dead. The team Elie grew up watching has been
shown the door. Friday, the Spurs might escort the Knicks out. All
of San Antonio understands that the imported New Yorker is part of
the reason why.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, when the Knicks were making another run at the
Spurs late in the fourth quarter, it was Elie who launched a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Kiss of death ... that's what they called the shot Elie hit to
put the Spurs up 81-73. And just moments later, when the Knicks
still refused to die, Elie took another shot.
</P>
<P>
   With the Spurs' lead down to 86-84, Elie missed, but it turned
out to be just as well. Elie snatched the long rebound, and the
Spurs whittled precious time off the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The ball in his hands, his feet on the Garden floor, his heart
steeped in New York basketball lore, Elie was at that particular
moment holding the key to San Antonio's win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what New York City is all about. Going to the basket
hard. Trash talking. I grew up five minutes from here, and it's
always great to come back here and play,'' Elie said.
</P>
<P>
   To make it extra special, Elie even jawed with Knicks fan
extraordinaire Spike Lee throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   Elie is no stranger to these sorts of moments. He won two titles
in Houston, which, in part, is why he is now with the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   But to sign him, the Spurs understood that Elie is the kind of
hard-nosed, up-from-the-trenches scrapper who likes to tell the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, every natural-born New Yorker has his own version of
the truth, but Elie doesn't do too bad.
</P>
<P>
   This past February, for instance, when the Spurs started off 6-8
and all of San Antonio was calling for coach Gregg Popovich's head
and for the trade of David Robinson, it was Elie who decided he
better go ahead and open his big truth-telling trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `As you go, we go, and you are not playing up to your
capability,'''' Elie said in his early-season state of the Spurs
address to Twins Towers Robinson and Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``And from then on, we went 43-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had lost, I would have taken a lot of flak, but we
didn't lose. I said what I said because it was the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   On that subject, let's call what happened Wednesday another
moment of Mario Elie truth.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more to the point, 48 minutes of truth, because the Spurs
rule, which accounts for Wednesday's 96-89 victory and their 3-1
lead in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone out there still interested in this series that is
leaking dangerously close to the month of July, this is without a
doubt the Twin Towers NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Robinson and Duncan combined for 35 rebounds
and 42 points. Despite the relentless will of the Knicks to stick
close, the Towers were too tall to topple.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it could be Duncan and Robinson who put an end to these
Finals, maybe as soon as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever natural-born size and talent Duncan and Robinson
possess, it took an early season kick in the pants from Elie to
shake them into action.
</P>
<P>
   If the Spurs are on the brink of a championship frontier, it is
because Elie brought his street swagger and heart to a franchise
desperate to shake its too-soft image.
</P>
<P>
   Elie brought that to Game 3, and it cost him when the refs
whistled fouls so quick that Elie was sure he was the victim of
Knick-friendly calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just let me play,'' Elie said, begging the refs to let him do
his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of questionable calls. There were a lot of
fast whistles. Two of our guards had four fouls with eight minutes
to go in the first quarter. I mean, this the NBA Finals. Let the
players decide the game,'' Elie said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, it was a different story. No ticky-tack fouls kept
Elie on the bench, out of action. In the cauldron of the Garden _
the place he dreamed of playing basketball _ Elie knew better than
anyone it was time to sieze the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they let me play tonight. Being home, getting 25
tickets, I was excited about being home. But I was a little more
relaxed tonight, and I put my head down and took my shots,'' Elie
said.
</P>
<P>
   The native New Yorker who now hails from San Antonio already
likes winning on the Garden floor, much to the Knicks' dismay.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
