<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7661 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-KNICSK-BOS &LR;      06-24 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-KNICSK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS ONE STEP CLOSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everywhere they turn this morning, the Knicks will be
surrounded by an annoying stat. It is the same one all teams in the
NBA Finals see when they are on the verge of elimination: No team
has ever come back from a 3-1 deficit to win the championship
series.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks can tell you about the 7-foot humanity behind
that stat. They can tell you that the NBA has never seen a center
combination similar to Tim Duncan and David Robinson. Forget about
deep analysis. You want to know why the Knicks lost Game 4 at
Madison Square Garden, 96-89? Duncan and Robinson; Robinson and
Duncan; Tim and David; David and Tim . . . you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan finished with 28 points, 18 rebounds, and 3 blocked
shots. Robinson contributed 14 points, 17 rebounds (including 9
offensive boards), and 4 blocked shots. In other words, they
outrebounded the entire Knicks team between them. Not only that,
they made any driving Knick a paranoid Knick around the basket.
They were constantly looking for the 7-footers. Each of those New
York drives had three options: a good basket, a block, or, most
often, a San Antonio rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was just a monster,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said
when it was over. ``People counted him out for some reason I'm
still not sure about.'' As for Duncan, ``Tim, just has a knack for
the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment has a double meaning. Not only can Duncan rebound,
he uses the backboard better than any player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got two 7-footers back there to help us out,'' said
Mario Elie, who had 18 points, 6 rebounds, and 4 assists. They help
so much that it is almost impossible for the Spurs to have a
complete defensive lapse. Even though New York got 26 points from
Latrell Sprewell and 20 apiece from Marcus Camby and Allan Houston,
they had to work for everything they got. They shot 41 percent from
the field and needed 40 shots from Sprewell and Houston to get
their 46 points.
</P>
<P>
   It probably doesn't mean much to the Knicks, but
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's game was one of the more entertaining ones of
the playoffs. The league has formed a special committee to help
bring flair back to the game for next season. But when you watched
the first half, a half the Spurs won, 50-46, you found yourself
wondering, ``Who needs changes?'' For the first time in the series,
a team actually managed to crack 90 points.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those aesthetics, both teams will have plenty to discuss
at this morning's film sessions. The Spurs should expect to hear
some choice words from Popovich, considering that the coach knows
the end of the game shouldn't have been as interesting as it was.
The Spurs had an 81-73 lead with just more than seven minutes to
play. Elie had just dunked, following a Larry Johnson airball. All
the Spurs had to do was maintain and close. They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they had to listen as the Garden reached its loudest
levels of the night in the next two minutes. Houston, the star of
Game 3, posted up Avery Johnson and hit a turnaround jumper to make
it 81-79. After that postup, Duncan turned the ball over and,
eventually, Charlie Ward was fouled. But the Knicks couldn't tie it
as Ward made only 1 of 2 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   That began a frustrating trend for the Knicks. They quickly fell
behind by 5, closed to 2 again, then fell back again by 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our chances,'' Houston said. He added, ``We still have
to play better defense. We have to play better defense to stay in
the series.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, the same man who said the Spurs are not superior to the
Knicks, still wouldn't say the Knicks are in trouble. Like most
Knick fans here, he mentioned a seventh game a few times Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking forward to the challenge,'' Houston said. ``It's
something that, if we win it, people will look at it and say they
can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks are beyond that point now. All the celebrities in
their house _ from John F. Kennedy Jr., to Adam Sandler, to Evander
Holyfield _ know that they are in more trouble now than they have
ever been in the postseason. They haven't been down two games
before. They are now.
</P>
<P>
   They have to figure out a way to control point guard Johnson (14
points, 10 assists). They also have to figure out how to do the
impossible. They have to stop Duncan and Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Late in Jeff Van Gundy's postgame press conference, someone
asked the coach if he had considered using ancient center Herb
Williams to help with Duncan-Robinson. Williams played in six games
all year. Van Gundy said he won't use him ``unless we have extreme
foul trouble.'' That's another way of saying Williams's playing
days are over. And after Friday night, the rest of the Knicks might
be done playing for the summer, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
