<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO ADMITS HE'S NOT BEEN A LEADER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Many of the Anaheim Angels said it Tuesday: ``We've
got our leader back. We haven't had a leader all year.''
</P>
<P>
   They were speaking of shortstop Gary DiSarcina, and it stung Mo
Vaughn. After all, the Angels shelled out $80 million for Vaughn in
large part for his leadership abilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn is the first to admit he hasn't really been much of a
leader this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been a leader since. &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; .,'' he said, his voice
trailing off. He was referring to his fall into the visiting dugout
at Edison Field in the first inning on opening night.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting sprained left ankle has limited Vaughn to just 12
starts at first base this season. He started his 44th game at DH
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a leader, you have to be on the field, he said. ``When
you're DH-ing you don't feel a part of what's going on. There's no
way you can. When I get on the field and play both sides of the
ball, I'm going to lead. When you're not on both sides of the ball,
you can't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game flows when you're on the field,'' he said. ``I'm
struggling right now because I'm really frustrated, but I don't
want these guys (teammates) to know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who went into Wednesday's game hitting .271 with a
team-leading 14 homers and 41 RBI, will return to first base Friday
against Oakland at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time, he said. ``If I have to stay in the dugout one more
week, I'm going to break something up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Mariners complete their three-game series tonight
at 7:05. Chuck Finley (4-7, 4.18 ERA) will start for Anaheim
against Seattle's Jeff Fassero (3-7, 7.19).
</P>
</TEXT>
