<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STADIUM-COSTS-SPI &LR;      06-24 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-COSTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINER'S ANNOUNCEMENT WAS `LIKE RUINING SOMEONE'S WEDDING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN SNEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The timing looked fishy to Tom Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Mariners fans were in a sentimental mood Monday, with
the ballclub starting the Kingdome's last homestand. And the hype
for a new stadium christening in three weeks was in full gear.
</P>
<P>
   To Phillips, co-founder of DeLaunay/Phillips, a Seattle public
relations firm, the twin events were a harmonic convergence that
prompted Mariners brass to throw a high, hard one at King County
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners owners say $60 million from ballpark tax surpluses
should be used to help offset the $100 million cost overrun of
building the new ballpark, Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mariners seem to be very adept
</P>
<P>
   at picking the time with which they basically put a gun to the
public's head,'' Phillips said when asked to rate the M's public
relations acumen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is sentimental about the last few days of the
Kingdome and the fervor of the new stadium is building and now
we're hearing about their plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Mariners' announcement on Tuesday reopened emotional
wounds left from the volatile political year of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   That's when King County voters narrowly rejected a ballpark
sales tax, only to see
</P>
<P>
   state legislators patch together a financing scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's understandable. There's a tendency
</P>
<P>
   to low-ball the cost estimates and grossly overstate the
benefits, and in the end, there isn't a tooth fairy or an Easter
Bunny,'' said Allen Sanderson, a University of Chicago economist
who studies sports facility financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state did a sugarcoated end run to finance the package,
and now the chickens are coming home to roost,'' Sanderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for taxpayers in those situations. `I told you
so' is small consolation when it's your own money.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Wednesday Seattle-area residents vented at the prospect of
forking over more public dollars for North America's most expensive
sports venue.
</P>
<P>
   And many noted the Mariners' pitch taints the excitement of the
days leading to the ballfield's July 15 debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be a big, joyous occasion for baseball fans
_ and the Mariners just ruined it,'' said state Rep. Steve Van
Luven, R-Bellevue, who sponsored the ballpark legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they ruined somebody's wedding. This will go down in
history as one of public relations' biggest blunders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mariners will lose in the court of public opinion and the
court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a spokeswoman for the Public Facilities District, which
owns the $517 million, 45,000-seat ballpark, acknowledged the
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very caught up in the excitement and the race to finish,
but the timing was unfortunate,'' district spokeswoman Kathy
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   A common strategy for teams that are offering unpopular
solutions to politically volatile issues is to time the
announcement during the best possible environment, said Dean
Bonham, a Denver-based sports business consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to capitalize on the opening of the stadium by
telling fans to hold your nose and try to get over the smell of the
money to cover the stadium construction overruns,'' Bonham said.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners board member Howard Lincoln maintained the timing was
not a political maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   The team went public for the first time in months only after it
exhausted behind-the-scenes efforts with PFD members that started
in February, and it learned from the team's lawyers that the
Mariners had a case to ask for the tax surplus, Lincoln said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lincoln said the Mariners did want to announce its mediation
request before the stadium-opening so that fans would not get
attached to the venue, then get the unpopular news.
</P>
<P>
   M's fan Scotty Dagman of Grays Harbor didn't like Lincoln's
stance that the county should issue more bonds to help cover cost
overruns.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't surprised the club would try to make a play for
more public money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know all the angles, all the tricks,'' Dagman said at the
Kingdome before Wednesday's Mariners-Angels game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year from now if the chaos is done and they put a winning
team on the field, it will be tamed. It's the torment you have to
go through.''
</P>
<P>
   But King County Councilman Pete von Reichbauer, R-Federal Way,
said this week's frustration among fans and taxpayers is different
than the emotions expressed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate has changed. You have season ticket-holders
expressing outrage,'' said von Reichbauer, who voted against the
county's ballpark bond package.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said `enough is enough'
</P>
<P>
   and now they're very angry ... The irony is these were the same
people who three years ago were threatening to vote against me for
``losing baseball.'''
</P>
<P>
   The PFD, which is building the venue and will own the building
on behalf of the public, has kept a low profile in the contract
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our board is paranoid and I'm afraid I'll be in the doghouse
for speaking to you,'' stadium board member Bob Wallace quipped
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said he hasn't detected any public outrage, noting the
core issue is whether the PFD is obliged to ask the county to issue
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wallace said fans will be able to separate the legal
dispute from the game on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as a political issue. I see it as public
relations issue for everyone connected with baseball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of a new sports venue is a time for euphoria, said
Craig Tartasky, a Maryland-based sports marketing consultant and
chairman of the annual International Sport Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Once fans start enjoying the venue's amenities _ and the team
plays winning and entertaining baseball _ this week's political
anger will start to dissipate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always the feeling among fans that, `I want to be the
person who gets to the stadium.' It's not surprising there's a
reaction to not wanting to pay more for a stadium,'' Tartasky said.
``But in three years, will anyone remember that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
