<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-1STL     06-24 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBATTLED KNICKS FALL TO SPURS, WHO NOW LEAD SERIES 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: CHANGES throughout . ) (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A rigid, misplaced jumper by the Knicks' Allan Houston licked
off the rim and bounded up in the air late into a tense night, and
the two 7-foot stars for the San Antonio Spurs popped up like two
cymbals flashing and glinting in the air.
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson clamped down on the rebound and embraced the
chance to turn the Knicks' desperate attempt at a fourth-quarter
comeback into an act of futility. By the end, Robinson and Tim
Duncan combined for 35 rebounds to erode the body and spirit of the
Knicks by winning Game 4 of the National Basketball Association
finals, 96-89, Wednesday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks left their home floor crestfallen and on the brink of
elimination as the Spurs took a 3-1 lead in the best-of-7 series.
No team has ever come back to win a championship from such a
deficit. The Knicks, a team that has thumbed its nose at bleak
situations all year, will have to win Game 5 Friday night at the
Garden to keep their run toward destiny alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' Houston said. ``This is the ultimate challenge.
Your back can't get any further against the wall at this point,
down, 3-1, in the finals. But you know something? This is something
that you always welcome as a competitor, as an athlete. We're not
hanging our heads down. We're looking forward to the challenge. All
you can do is stay positive and say, `If we win this thing, people
won't believe it.' But they didn't believe we'd be where we are
right now when we were 21-21, either.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would have thought they would be so close Wednesday night
after trailing by 13 points in the third quarter. Somehow, the
Knicks dug deep and scrambled to come within a point with 5 minutes
24 seconds left, and they were down by just 86-84 with 3:40
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   That was all they could do. Standing on wobbly legs, the Knicks
missed their next seven shots while the Spurs remained uncommonly
cool beneath the frenzy of the Garden and took a 94-84 lead with 37
seconds left on the strength of good free-throw shooting by
Robinson and Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   It was over. The core players who had pulled off Game 3 on
Tuesday _ Houston, Latrell Sprewell and Larry Johnson _ had no
impact in the last 3:40. Harassed by double-teams much of the
night, Houston did not have the same feathery touch and finished
with a tough 20 points. Sprewell scored 26 points, but was often
too frantic under pressure and hit just 9 of 22 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't execute well down the stretch,'' Sprewell said. ``We
were stuck on 84 points for what seemed like the longest time.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could help, especially not Johnson. He had worn the
springs in his remaining good knee to the nub and had nothing left
in his body to give. With just five points, Johnson fouled out with
1:14 left and fell into his seat dejected over the Knicks' turn of
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, Duncan was relentless. He had 28 points to go
with 18 rebounds, while Robinson scored 14 points and had 17
rebounds around an active Marcus Camby, who finished with 20 points
and 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   After having failed to duplicate the impact he had against
Indiana in the conference finals, Camby made a concerted effort to
keep himself on the court and avoid the foul trouble that had
plagued him against David Robinson. He succeeded with 19 minutes of
foul-free effort in the first half, finishing with a lively 10
points and seven rebounds. He was one of four Knick starters with
10 points at halftime, along with Houston, Sprewell and Ward.
</P>
<P>
   But the spindly Camby was no match for the massive and looming
presence of the Twin Towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Size does matter in this league,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said.
``And their size beat our speed and quickness because not only did
they affect us on the boards and in the post, but they affected
everything else. Every penetration was a difficult, difficult
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven blocked shots Robinson and Duncan combined to make was
a testament to that fact. But as tall as they were, the Spurs'
greatest jolt came from its smallest player, point guard Avery
Johnson. The two point guards who had been the most maligned,
Johnson and the Knicks' Charlie Ward, were the two impact players
in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Invisible for most of the playoffs, both came on to lead their
teams. Ward scored 11 points, his most in 14 games, while Johnson
drove right back at him for 14 points and had 10 assists. They were
responsible for a close first half, which the Spurs led 50-46. The
Spurs leaned on their defense to start the third quarter and forced
the Knicks to miss their first five shots as they took a 13-point
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just came out of the half and wanted it more,'' Camby
said of the Spurs' third-quarter start. ``We left guys open and
they went on a 9-0 run. From that point, we were playing from
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Spurs were too much to overcome. Houston wasn't there to
save them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed shots,'' Houston said. ``I wasn't frustrated. I
wasn't tired. I had some good looks. I just missed shots.''
</P>
<P>
   They Knicks just missed a chance. They were within reach, just a
clawing moment away from turning the whole tone of this series
around. Now, they must try to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes it more fun,'' Camby said. ``No one gave us a shot
of making the playoffs. We're all about making history. People
doubted us before, and they're going to doubt us now. We're
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   But they understand what they are up against. Robinson and
Duncan are right there in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have to come in very focused,'' Duncan said. ``We
don't want to give them an opportunity for life. We want to get
this next game and concentrate and be focused and not have to worry
about going back to San Antonio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
