<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7694 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIPELINE-SPI &LR;      06-24 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPELINE WORKERS INVOKE FIFTH AMENDMENT IN INQUIRY INTO DEADLY
FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELLIS E. CONKLIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLINGHAM, Wash. _ Five Olympic Pipe Line Co. employees have
invoked the Fifth Amendment, refusing to answer federal
investigators' questions about the deadly explosion that rocked
this city two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators also revealed on Wednesday that a valve on the
pipeline closed without warning minutes before the rupture, causing
a massive pressure surge on the line. The reason for the closure is
unknown, since system operators did not order it.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the investigators said they have learned that tests on the
pipeline conducted by Olympic more than three years ago revealed
three potential trouble spots in the line, close to the rupture.
</P>
<P>
   The same results were found in testing a year later,
investigators said, but Olympic did not excavate the pipe to check
the spots.
</P>
<P>
   The employees' refusal to assist the National Transportation
Safety Board has stalled progress in determining what caused the
fuel-pipeline rupture, NTSB lead investigator Allan Beshore said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never personally experienced before people exercising
their Fifth Amendment rights,'' Beshore said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the employees, whom Beshore declined to identify, worked
in Olympic's headquarters in Renton. Two of them were pipeline
controllers, another a person who supervised the two controllers.
He did not disclose the duties of the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Pipe Line officials could not be reached for comment
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Between 13 and 25 minutes before the fiery inferno killed two
10-year-old boys and an 18-year-old fly-fisherman, a valve about 20
miles south from the break closed unexpectedly, investigators said
Wednesday. It is the second valve on the pipeline that apparently
did not function correctly. Last week investigators said a check
valve just one-tenth of a mile from the break ``either
malfunctioned or was not closed in a timely fashion'' after the
rupture, increasing the spill by up to 130,200 gallons.
Investigators now estimate the spill at 277,200 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   Beshore said Wednesday that a March 1996 test administered by
Olympic Pipe Line revealed the three potential trouble points,
including a .4-inch ``defect'' that is thought to be within a few
feet of the rupture, but that won't be known for certain until the
damaged pipe is at last unearthed - perhaps as early as Friday or
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of that defect, which investigators believe may have
been a gouge or dent, was to thin the pipeline wall by 23 percent.
Apparently, Beshore said, Olympic Pipe Line officials took no
action because the gouge was so small.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're currently looking into that,'' Beshore said, declining
to elaborate further.
</P>
<P>
   With the use of an internal detection device called a smart pig,
the pipeline company also found two other ``anomalies'' in the line
near the eventual rupture. One was termed a ``wrinkle,'' which
means the line may have been bent or buckled. the other was a
``mash,'' or a dent possibly caused by something pushing down on
it.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the discovery of the irregularities in the
pipeline, Norm Stanley, an Olympic spokesman said, ``We have no
idea whether to be concerned with this yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Beshore said the NTSB will want to `` look at the accuracy of
that inspection device.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the 23 percent reduction in the pipeline wall was
alarming, Beshore said, ``That would weaken a spot in the pipe.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Pipe Line also inspected the same section of line in
1997 and found the same problems.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Batten, a former NTSB pipeline accident investigator for
23 years, expressed concern over the Olympic Pipe Line inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen, I would have to ask why the pipe wasn't
excavated for inspection,'' Batten said. ``They said it was too
small (the .4-inch gouge), but one needs to ask what their criteria
they used to make this decision (not to dig up the damaged line).''
</P>
<P>
   Beshore said the Olympic employees were subpoenaed after
rebuffing NTSB's demands for an interview. Two of the employees
quickly invoked the Fifth Amendment to protect themselves from
self-incrimination, while the other three had their lawyers do it
for them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he has asked the U.S. Attorney's Office to
intervene, Beshore said after a long pause, ``I'd rather not get
into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without the assistance of the employees in question,
Beshore said NTSB investigator will eventually be able to recreate
what happened on the system. But he added, the investigation is a
long way from completion. It may take six to nine months. In the
interim, ``this is not a criminal investigation,'' Beshore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline continued to seep Wednesday from a small spot on the
hillside into Whatcom Creek, near the water treatment plant. The
gasoline is being contained using absorbent pads, booms and
skimmers. The city of Bellingham asked again Wednesday that people
stay away from Whatcom Falls Park for safety reasons. Officials
estimated Wednesday that cleanup expenses have exceeded $2.4
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
