<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ST. LOUIS _ Entering Wednesday night, the Astros were trying to
avoid their first series sweep at Busch Stadium in nearly three
years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Worse, they could feel the Cincinnati Reds breathing down their
necks.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros defeated the St. Louis Cardinals 8-4 before a
rain-soaked crowd of 36,402 at Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, only 13-13 against National League Central teams,
begin an important four-game series today at the Astrodome with the
second-place Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett and Bill Spiers each drove in two runs for the
Astros, who haven't been swept at Busch since Sept. 2-4, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get swept on the road, especially in your
division,'' Everett said. ``We're only .500 against our division.
We need to salvage all the games we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiers, Derek Bell, Craig Biggio and Tony Eusebio had two hits
each for the Astros, who are 5-5 in manager Larry Dierker's
absence.
</P>
<P>
   After a 1-hour, 52-minute rain delay, the Astros wasted no time
against Cardinals starter Juan Acevedo, scoring two runs in the
first inning and two in the third. With two outs in the first, Jeff
Bagwell walked, Bell singled and Everett drilled a two-run double
into the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio led off the third with a single, advanced to second on a
grounder by Spiers and took third on a wild pitch. Bagwell singled
up the middle to put the Astros up 3-0, and Richard Hidalgo added
an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the Astros' eight runs came with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our situational hitting was a lot better,'' interim
manager Matt Galante said. ``We're a free-swinging team that is
going to strike out a bunch. That's the kind of players we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have good days, we're able to score a bunch of runs.
When we have a bad day, we leave men stranded.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had 12 hits Wednesday after combining for 16 in the
first two games of the series. They batted .243 in the series and
struck out 29 times. The Astros lead the majors with 528
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds cruised through five innings before allowing two
home runs that brought the Cardinals to within 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Powell pitched two scoreless innings of relief and Trever
Miller closed it out, ending the game with two strikeouts. Galante
said it was important for Reynolds to pitch deep into the game
after the entire bullpen worked in Tuesday's 14-inning loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing was we were able to get through with thin
pitching,'' Galante said. ``Last night took a lot of pitching out
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis fell one game below .500 and 7{ games behind Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire went 3-for-5 with an RBI for the Cardinals, and Joe
McEwing extended his hitting streak to 15 games with a one-out
single in the third inning. On the play, Everett slipped on the wet
grass and appeared to jerk his neck. He was attended to on the
field and remained in the game until the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who delivered the game-winning hit Tuesday, singled
past Spiers at third base to make the score 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis caught a lucky bounce in the fourth. After a leadoff
single by Willie McGee, Edgar Renteria bunted to the right side and
Eusebio's throw ricochetted off Renteria's hand and struck
first-base umpire Gerry Davis above the left eye. Davis left the
game but later returned.
</P>
<P>
   Placido Polanco sliced the lead to two runs with an RBI ground
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds escaped potential disaster in the fifth. After a
leadoff single by McEwing, Reynolds struck out Darren Bragg and got
McGwire to fly out to right field. Ray Lankford singled to put
runners at the corners, but Reynolds struck out McGee.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros pushed lead back to four, 6-2, in the sixth courtesy
of three walks and two singles, and Spiers singled in a pair in the
eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
