<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7697 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-24 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ Their last time out, the Twin Towers of David Robinson
and Tim Duncan were just a couple of nondescript big buildings on
the famous New York skyline.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, they stood taller than the skyscrapers of the
World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   The last time they hit the floor at Madison Square Garden, the
supporting cast of the Spurs was like that old saying about there
being a broken heart for every light bulb on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, the likes of Mario Elie, Avery Johnson and Sean
Elliott played like their names belonged in neon on the marquee.
</P>
<P>
   These were once again the Spurs who had devoured the shortened
NBA season like a plateful of hors d'oeuvres.
</P>
<P>
   They were alive. They were aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Now, following Wednesday night's 96-89 victory over the Knicks,
they are back in control of the NBA Finals and one win away from
capturing their first championship.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anybody have expected anything different from a team
that has treated defeat like a trampoline all year long and always
bounced back bigger and stronger than ever?
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone think that these Spurs, who have not lost
back-to-back games in nearly four months, would suddenly come
unwound after just one emotional effort by the home team in Madison
Square Garden?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since we got ourselves together at the end of February
and went on a roll, we have always made a point of responding
strong to a loss,'' Robinson said. ``When we've lost games, we've
gotten together, we've talked, we've refocused and we've taken care
of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody did more business in Game 4 than the two-headed monster
of Duncan and Robinson. Duncan used his fundamentally sound
footwork and a quick drop step to hit a steady diet of bankers to
finish with 28 points and 18 rebounds. Robinson did most of his
offensive damage simply by making himself available around the hoop
and cleaning up all of the Garden, collecting 14 points to go with
his 17 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   That's 35 rebounds between them, one more than the entire roster
of the Knicks, who this time couldn't quite match the emotion and
the fever pitch and the magic that carried them in the previous
game.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson, the talkative little point guard, wasn't darting
into the lane for driving shots or setting up teammates with his 10
assists, the combo of Duncan and Robinson was always around to
cover up San Antonio mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   When Elie wasn't responding from a personal failure in Game 3
right here in his hometown with one of his classic Junkyard Dog
efforts, pouring in half of his 18 points in the third quarter
alone as the Spurs took control, then the two big men were around
to keep balls and their team alive.
</P>
<P>
   When Elliott, who had been so quiet, so rarely heard from in the
first three games, wasn't hitting big fourth-quarter shots, it was
Robinson and Duncan always there to bail the Spurs out.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and Robinson. Or Robinson and Duncan. The billing doesn't
really matter when they are clubbing you over the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``When those two guys have got it going like that, they are
virtually unstoppable,'' said Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``When
they outrebound us by themselves, when we get beat on the boards
like we did (49-34), well, you're not going to win a Finals game.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet New York had its chance with just over five minutes left in
the game and Charlie Ward at the line for two free throws. He made
just one, and the Knicks, who had a chance to tie, stayed behind
81-80 and never could climb over the hump.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson came back with a hook in the lane. Duncan went down
onto the blocks on the right side of the hoop and connected on
another one of his bankers. When the Knicks missed seven straight
shots, it seemed that either Duncan or Robinson was there to
rebound every one.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have had an unlikely and often messy run through the
playoffs and into the Finals, filled with soap-opera elements of
coaching intrigue, management backstabbing and player unrest. It
has also given rise, maybe, to the next great scorer in the league
in Allan Houston. But after carrying the day with 34 points Monday
night, Houston was limited to 20 and shot only 7-for-18.
</P>
<P>
   Open shots were harder to come by. The Spurs' Twin Towers were
always lurking, blocking seven shots between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels so good to have responded like this again after a
game the last time that didn't make any of us happy,'' Robinson
said. ``This is the way we wanted to play then, and this is how we
have to play on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the stage that Robinson has wanted to play on for 10
years in the NBA. Now the curtain rises on his big night in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim was just Tim,'' said Spurs coach Gregg Popovich. ``He has
been so dependable, so strong all year. But I'm so glad for David.
He's a guy who has had to respond to all of the criticism through
the years and performed so well this year when a lot of people said
he couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and Robinson. Or Robinson and Duncan. Two big standouts
in the Manhattan skyline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
