<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7698 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-HNS &LR;      06-24 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFINALS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ The Knicks had it all going again. They might have been
outclassed and outmanned by a bigger, better, healthier team. But
there they were, in great shape for a stretch run. They made
highlight plays on desire. The Madison Square Garden crowd screamed
its throats raw. The faith in magic expressed on nearly 20,000 ``I
Still Believe'' T-shirts seemed real.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Spurs, however, had no use for magic and other such romantic
nonsense. Instead, they believed in free throws and rebounding, in
size and defense.
</P>
<P>
   If that might be dull, as it has been labeled, then the NBA can
have more committee meetings. The Spurs might just settle for the
league championship after a 96-89 victory in Game 4 of the NBA
Finals on Wednesday put them one win away from their first title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we did anything amazing on the offensive end,''
Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said. ``But we did make free throws, and
we made stops.''
</P>
<P>
   After trailing by 13, the Knicks at one point got within one.
And with four minutes left, after a Marcus Camby slam for a
three-point play, they were within three.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs simply stepped up their defense, refused to allow
the Knicks more than one long, tough jumper per trip downcourt and
made enough simple, dull free throws to take a 3-1 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   And for all the magic the Knicks seem to have whenever needed,
no team has ever come back from a 3-1 hole in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to come in very focused the next game and get it out
of the way,'' said Spurs forward Tim Duncan, who turned in game
highs of 28 points and 18 rebounds. ``We don't want to give them
any opportunity for life. We just want to knock them out.''
</P>
<P>
   They might have knocked most of the remaining life from the
Knicks by physically outmanning them inside.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, however, will not concede anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win this thing, people won't believe it,'' New York
guard Allan Houston said. ``But they wouldn't believe it when we
were 21-21 that we would be where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, they might be running out of reasons to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs outrebounded the Knicks with a 31-16 second-half
blitz. By themselves, Duncan and David Robinson outrebounded the
Knicks 35-34, with Robinson getting nearly as many offensive
rebounds, nine, as the entire Knicks team (10) and blocking twice
as many shots, four, as the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to say David and Tim were outstanding and really took
it to heart as far as rebounding the basketball,'' Popovich said.
``David was just a monster. I'm so happy for him. He showed people
what he could do when a lot of people counted him out for reasons
I'm still trying to figure out. And Tim really has a knack for the
boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan finished as strongly Wednesday as he had played poorly
down the stretch in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be more effective in the fourth quarter,'' Duncan
said. ``I knew I didn't play well in the fourth quarter (on
Monday). Even if it wasn't scoring, I wanted to throw out of the
double teams and make them pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a very good team down the stretch. We developed
that through experience. We make plays down the stretch. That was
the big thing in Game 3 we knew we didn't do. We really
concentrated on that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Camby dunk on, the Knicks missed their next seven
shots, never getting close to the lane. The Spurs didn't need to
shoot. They made eight of 10 free throws in the final minutes to
put the game away easily.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Elie dropped in the final two free throws to give him a
series-best 18 points, thoroughly reversing his homecoming disaster
in Game 3 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell had 26 points for the Knicks. Houston added 20
but made just seven of 18 shots. As a team, the Knicks were
15-of-42 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Knicks managed, as they have throughout their
postseason run, to do just enough to stay in range, and 2{ minutes
into the fourth quarter they were within five.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and Robinson each scored off offensive rebounds, and Elie
got loose for a fast break. But the Knicks stayed on the Spurs'
heels, pulling out the precise formula that had lifted them to the
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell made a flying tip-in of a Charlie Ward miss, then broke
loose for a fast break, forcing Duncan to foul and give up two
points. And when Houston swished a fadeaway, the Knicks had a 6-0
run, pulling them within 81-79 with 5:39 left. They even moved
within one on a Ward free throw.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Garden crowd rocking again and the Knicks waving
their arms and running the floor as they had not since the Eastern
Conference finals, the Spurs suddenly found themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson hit a jump hook with 5:09 left, his first field goal of
the second half, to stop the Knicks' run. Duncan hit another, his
first field goal since shortly after halftime, and Robinson added a
layup. And the Spurs choked the life from the Knicks' offense,
never allowing them another chance to shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was just great down the stretch,'' Elie said.
``When we had to make stops, we made them. Our big guys did a great
job eating the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Knicks could not defeat that with blind faith and a few
miracle, off-balance shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Size does matter in this league,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy
said. ``It does, particularly in the playoffs. Their size beat our
speed and quickness. Not only did they (Duncan and Robinson) affect
us on the boards and post scoring, every penetration was a
difficult, difficult shot. Those guys are great, great players.''
</P>
<P>
   Too great to beat, it would seem. No matter what the Knicks tell
themselves they believe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 0225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
