</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALAMA ENDS M'S SKID; UNIT TRADE LOOKING BETTER AND BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While the Mariners conduct their Kingdome countdown
this week _ just four days left inside on plastic grass _ the
Anaheim Angels have been running their own tally.
</P>
<P>
   Lost starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they're 2-for-2. On Tuesday, the Angels' Steve Sparks
went out after three innings with a badly swollen right ring
finger. Wednesday night, Anaheim's Ken Hill was lifted after two
frames, experiencing tightness in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, it's unclear which will disappear first, the Angel
pitching staff or the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Taking full advantage of this hardship, the Mariners made their
four-game losing skid evaporate, beating their shorthanded visitors
8-3 before a crowd of 25,087.
</P>
<P>
   The home club has had no such problem filling the mound this
series. One leg of the Randy Johnson deal has followed another in
impressive fashion, making that 11-month-old trade look better each
week.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, rookie Freddy Garcia tossed seven shutout innings
before losing his touch in a 4-2 defeat to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, fellow rook John Halama (6-2) turned in six solid
innings. Though hit around at times, the 24-year-old lefty from
Brooklyn continued to show remarkable poise, keeping the damage to
a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, Halama and Garcia are 14-6, while the Big Unit is
off to a 9-3 start in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the point,'' Mariner manager Lou Piniella said of
the record comparison. ``The point is the organization went out and
made a trade a lot of people frowned on. To their credit, these two
young guys have held up to their end of the bargain real well.''
</P>
<P>
   In his sixth Mariners start, Halama got out of serious trouble
in the fourth and fifth innings, leaving runners on second and
third each time. He was pulled after 96 pitches, his legs tired and
holding a comfortable 6-2 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up six hits, walked two and struck out six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt comfortable all year,'' Halama said. ``Now it's just
a matter of doing it every five days instead of coming out of the
bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing up, Frankie Rodriguez, just back from a rotation
stint, went the final three innings, allowing one run on four hits.
He earned a save and Piniella plaudits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked the way Rodriguez threw out of the bullpen,''
said Piniella, who has been desperate for another setup man. ``His
arm bounces back real well.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rodriguez, ``It was a good lift for me and the team. We've
been taking some shots lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Wilson backed the Mariners' offensive effort with three
hits, Brian Hunter had three RBIs and the club went its third game
without a home run, a season high.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, Anaheim was left wondering how long starter
Chuck Finley will last Thursday. His rotation mates, Sparks and
Hill, faced just 11 Mariners batters each in the previous two
evenings, forcing heavy bullpen use for Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Hill had no trouble in the first inning. He retired the Mariners
1-2-3, not permitting a ball to leave the infield. He had a 1-0
lead, thanks to teammate Darin Erstad's leadoff home run on the
fifth pitch of the game. He used 13 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Anaheim's veteran right-hander started to wobble,
his inning extended by a defensive lapse. Hill gave up a single to
Edgar Martinez, walked Butch Huskey and, after a flyout, walked
David Bell to load the bases. Wilson singled sharply to left,
bringing home Martinez to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Davis grounded one to third, where Angels rookie Troy Glaus
cleanly gloved the ball and _ nothing happened. Glaus glanced to
second and to first. Each time, he held the ball. Glaus was charged
with an error, Davis was safe at first, even after stumbling as he
left the plate, and a run scored, putting the Mariners ahead 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   To rub salt in it, the next batter, Hunter, hit a high chopper
to Glaus, who again caught the ball but had no chance to make a
throw. Another run scored.
</P>
<P>
   Hill got a double-play grounder from Alex Rodriguez to end the
mess, but that would be his last pitch. The right-hander, who has
had arm surgery in the past, flies home to California Thursday to
receive more extensive medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny's arm tightened up on him, and I wanted to get him out
of there,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``There are going to
be days it doesn't feel good, and tonight was one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Make that two of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
