<SLUG> BC-KHRUSCHEV-CITIZENSHIP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHRUSCHEV'S SON SAID HE FELT OBLIGATED TO BECOME U.S. CITIZEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ARTHUR C. GORLICK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sergei Khrushchev, whose father ruled the Soviet Union
and its Communist Party during the height of the Cold War with the
United States, on Wednesday passed the examination to become a U.S.
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev and his wife, Valentina Golenko, successfully
completed the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
examination in Providence, R.I., said Dan Danilov, their
Seattle-based immigration attorney, who was with them for the
20-question test.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will take the oath to become naturalized citizens July
12,'' Danilov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It marks a remarkable turn of events, especially considering
that it was his father who told the United States, `We will bury
you,' and had the economic and military power to make that a
credible threat at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev's father, Nikita Khrushchev, ruled the Soviet Union
from 1953 until he was deposed in 1964, two years after he and
President John F. Kennedy squared off in the Cuban Missile Crisis
that brought the world to the brink of nuclear conflict. Nikita
Khrushchev died Sept. 11, 1971, in virtual isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Khrushchev, 63, a senior research scholar and lecturer at
Brown University's Center for Foreign Policy Development in
Providence, is a rocket engineer and computer scientist who once
headed the Soviet Missile Design Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   He has published his father's memoirs and other books, including
several about how leaders of powerful nations make dangerous
mistakes because of misperceptions of their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Valentina Golenko, 50, who is also a scientist, got 100 percent
of the INS citizenship questions correct and Sergei Khrushchev got
95 percent correct, Danilov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed one question on what form of government is the United
States,'' Khrushchev said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He responded, `executive,' meaning `Legislative, executive and
judiciary,' but the answer they wanted was `democracy,''' Danilov
said. ``He had enough correct answers to pass anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife said she has been studying a 10-volume history of the
United States to prepare for the test.
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev said he felt obligated to become a citizen after
living here for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be good citizens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kane at the INS press office in Washington, D.C., said
the agency is barred from commenting on the tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
