r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONTRACT-GOP-SFCHRON     06-24 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONTRACT-GOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP REVEALS HIGH-TECH MANIFESTO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans unveiled their ``e-Contract with
High Tech'' Wednesday, declaring that they, not Vice President Al
Gore and his fellow Democrats, are the true friends of Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Republican majority will keep the Internet free _ count
on it,'' promised Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La. ``With this e-Contract,
we are telling this nation that we will stand at the door to the
Internet in front of all those in this administration who think
they can put their greedy, grubby hands on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-Contract is the GOP's most overt pitch yet to the
high-tech community and perhaps the strongest proof yet of the
industry's growing clout in Washington. It essentially compiles
existing GOP bills _ many of which have Democratic support _ into
one top-priority package.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled on the Republicans' Contract with America, the 10-point
tax-and-welfare-cutting agenda that ushered in their House majority
in 1994, the e-Contract promises to ``ensure that high-tech America
has the freedom it needs to innovate, grow, expand and imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insisted that they will clear the way for the
industry to ``create wealth'' and accused Democrats of stifling the
growth of the New Economy through taxes, regulations, subsidies and
antitrust suits.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats derided the effort as a craven appeal for campaign
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money and sticking their hands into the pockets
of high tech,'' said House Democratic leader Richard Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican leaders proved Wednesday that they intend to play
hardball, provoking a direct showdown with the White House over
legislation to limit lawsuits related to the Y2K computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP leadership announced that the House will move to a quick
vote on the Senate version of the bill and send it directly to the
White House, skipping a House-Senate conference at which the
administration had hoped to negotiate further compromises.
</P>
<P>
   Gore urged President Clinton to veto the bill unless Republicans
make concessions, and even though the White House Wednesday
reiterated its veto threat, Republicans were undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to overcome (Gore's) objections, we want to beat
his objections,'' said Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas. ``The Y2K bill
represents a dichotomy between two major political parties. We're
saying we're on the side of the engineers who create wealth, and
the vice president has put himself on the side of the lawyers who
want to redistribute it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K bill is a top priority for Silicon Valley manufacturers
who fear getting hit by a wave of lawsuits stemming from computers
that are not properly programmed to deal with the year 2000 date.
Gore's office has said the legislation is ``overreaching and not
protecting American consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   By refusing further compromises on Y2K, which has support from a
dozen Senate Democrats, including California's Dianne Feinstein,
Republicans are hoping to drive a wedge between Democrats and
Silicon Valley just as the presidential race is heating up.
</P>
<P>
   The new e-Contract reflects just how seriously Republicans are
taking Democratic inroads into what they consider their natural,
pro-business constituency.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda, outlined on Armey's Web site at www.freedom.gov,
includes virtually all Silicon Valley's legislative priorities,
from looser computer export and encryption controls to a permanent
research and development tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda also calls for more vague efforts such as
``modernizing the education system,'' ``reining in excessive
regulation from federal agencies,'' ``allowing high-speed Internet
access to flourish'' and protecting intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said Republicans will push the legislation with the same
intensity that drove their original Contract with America, much of
which was passed into law, including a  &LR; major welfare reform and
restrictions on securities litigation, another high-tech priority
that remains the only Clinton veto that Congress overrode.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also touted their high-tech record so far _ much
of which passed with broad Democratic support _ including a
three-year moratorium on Internet taxes, an increase in immigration
visas for skilled workers and a bill that partially deregulated
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Their enthusiasm toward a laissez-faire approach to high-tech
has so far been confined to commerce, however, as Republicans have
been much more aggressive in attempting to regulate online content.
Republicans have backed legislation that, for instance, would
impose criminal penalties on commercial Web sites that allow anyone
17 or under to access pornographic material deemed ``harmful to
minors,'' and require Internet service providers to provide
information on filtering software to block salacious content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our measures were designed to let the high-tech industry
continue to thrive without the three biggest drags on innovation:
big government, trial lawyers and big labor,'' Armey said in policy
memo.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech industry associations, which have tried to avoid
entanglement in Washington's partisan wars, warmly welcomed the
e-Contract, but they were careful to note that they hoped for a
``bipartisan'' effort and pledged to ``work closely with both sides
of the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry lobbyists also warned Republicans that the showdown
with the White House on the Y2K bill would doom the legislation and
be a disaster to Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 Coalition, which includes the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, the National Association of Manufacturers and a host of
high-tech trade groups, wrote in a letter to the GOP, ``We are
convinced that if such a bill were vetoed, the momentum to
legislate on this important matter would be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups wrote that a veto ``would be viewed as a complete
failure and would pose substantial risk to the American economy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 0310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
