<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GORE SWEEPS INTO CALIFORNIA AS A CONTENDER  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On his first swing through California as a
declared presidential contender, Vice President Al Gore received an
enthusiastic standing ovation Wednesday night at the San Francisco
Hilton from about 600 supporters who had paid $1,000 each to hear
him stress improving schools, the economy and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began his 57th trip to California _ which was expected to
raise nearly $1 million in a state crucial to his fortunes _ in the
exclusive San Diego community of La Jolla with a campaign lunch
Wednesday that raised $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   At last night's dinner in San Francisco, California Gov. Gray
Davis introduced Gore, saying, ``The vice president cares about
California, and he has come through time and time again for this
state. It is time for California to come through for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Bill Lockyer, San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown,
mayoral candidate Clint Reilly, former White House Chief of Staff
Leon Panetta and developer Walter Shorenstein were among local
dignitaries who attended the dinner of grilled chicken, mashed
potatoes and white chocolate mousse.
</P>
<P>
   In both La Jolla and San Francisco, Gore stressed improving
California schools, building a strong economy and protecting the
environment. But he hit particularly hard on gun control. ``We have
to make sure the agenda for America's future is set by the American
people and not the NRA,'' he told the San Francisco audience to
enthusiastic applause.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing to distance himself from President Clinton, Gore said
in San Francisco: ``It is time for a clean start in a fresh
century. ... I want to keep the prosperity going and make some
dramatic and indeed revolutionary changes.'' In a theme he had
repeated throughout the day, Gore also stressed ``my own values of
faith and family.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles Thursday, Gore is expected to attend three
fund-raising events before heading to Iowa Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day fund-raising push is expected to swell his
campaign's bottom line in time for the June 30 filing deadline for
campaign fund raising in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In La Jolla, Gore spoke to warmly enthusiastic groups of
supporters, seeking to underscore his experience as a Vietnam
veteran, a former divinity student, a husband of 29 years and a
future grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   But he was greeted as well by anti- &LR; abortion protesters at a
lunch at the home of Patrick Kruer, a Southern California real
estate magnate and an alternate on the state Coastal Commission.
</P>
<P>
   There, the vice president stressed his experience and his family
history in an effort to underscore the differences between himself
and the pack of GOP presidential candidates _ notably George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in San Diego, in a county that Gore noted has the largest
population of veterans in the United States, he mentioned his own
status as a Vietnam veteran _ something Bush cannot claim.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting a contrast with the family values agenda of GOP
candidates like Dan Quayle, who used the Murphy Brown television
character in a famed critique of single motherhood, Gore said he
wants to lead an America that respects and serves ``all kinds of
families.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did in his official campaign kickoff last week in
Tennessee, Gore called again for ``revolutionary improvements in
public education _ not gradual, incremental change.'' He said that
would include making ``high quality preschool'' available to all
American children.
</P>
<P>
   That Gore enjoys advantages in the campaign as a sitting vice
president was evident as he toured the state in Air Force II, where
even the seats carry the vice presidential seal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was met by dignitaries at both the San Diego and San
Francisco airports, and then whisked through the streets, stopping
traffic with an official motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's visit, with its official veneer, included few chances
to rub elbows with voters, in contrast to other presidential
candidates. In recent visits, Democratic rival Bill Bradley rode
the Sausalito ferry, and Republican John McCain visited a Silicon
Valley computer firm.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sought to remind audiences Wednesday that it is his
experience in office _ on the environment, education and foreign
affairs _ that separates him from the rest of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   He also underscored his agenda, which has been dubbed
``practical idealism,'' and argued for policies that will ``build
an America that's not just better off, but better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
