 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2552 -- June 24, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2552 -- June 24, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. THE SEX PATROL IS MONITORING THE HALLS Everyone thinks of the
famous North Carolina story about the 6-year-old who was suspended
from school three years ago for kissing a classmate on the cheek.
That's because it is a lot easier to contemplate than the actual
fact of many of the ``student-to-student'' sex harassment cases
that are now coming before the U.S. courts. By Cynthia Gorney. From
The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (7,500 words) + edited
article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
FROM HERE TO ETERNITY Two Keck telescopes, which stretch a massive
10 meters across, have been operating on Mauna Kea since 1990 and
1996. Japan's wafer-thin 8.3-metre Subaru telescope collected its
first images from space in January. And in the same neighbourhood
the Gemini North, an 8.1-metre telescope built by a seven-nation
consortium, is scheduled to begin scanning the heavens any day.
These are three of an elite new generation of optics that promise
to lead mankind beyond the solar system into unexplored regions of
space. By Michael D. Lemonick. From Discover magazine. 1,000 words
+ photos.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
STOP EXPORTING WEAPONS Oscar Arias, the former president of Costa
Rica who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1987, argues that Americans,
who show great concern about the reported loss of classified
nuclear secrets to China, should be just as outraged at U.S. sales
of advanced weaponry throughout the world. New York Times Op-Ed.
800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
RUSSIANS DON'T BELIEVE THE U.S. MEANS WELL It sounded like
kiss-and-make-up time again when President Clinton and President
Boris Yeltsin met at the Cologne summit. If Mr. Clinton felt he
kept having to repeat how eager he is to see Russia flourish, it
reflects the intensity of disbelief that has built up in recent
months. It is reported that 80 per cent of the Russian public
consider the U.S. to be the enemy. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
TRACKING MUTATIONS IN AIDS VIRUSES MAY HELP GUIDE
</P>
<P>
   DRUG CHOICE There are now a number of drugs that can effectively
suppress the AIDS virus HIV-1 and improve the health of many
HIV-infected patients. HIV-1, however, mutates rapidly and can
quickly acquire genetic mutations that make it able to resist
particular drugs. This is one of the major reasons anti-HIV
treatments fail. In this week's Lancet, researchers report that
they were able to improve the treatment of HIV-1 infected patients
by periodically checking them for viruses with drug-resistance
mutations and then, if mutations were found, switching the patients
to more effective drug combinations. By Michael McCarthy. From The
Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
DIRECTIONLESS? SCIENTISTS OFFER SOME CLUES Scientists have taken a
keen interest in how humans and other species navigate - or fail
to. The study of what they call spatial cognition, or way-finding,
is attracting growing numbers of researchers from all sectors of
the academic map, including psychology, neuroscience, computer
science, zoology, anthropology, linguistics and geography. By
Natalie Angier. New York Times Science Times. 2,000 words +
graphic. 7. FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   A. GUM DISEASE LINKED TO STROKES
</P>
<P>
   Brushing your teeth regularly may pay off in an unexpected way -
by
</P>
<P>
   lowering your risk for stroke. By 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. ANGLED KEYBOARDS EASE PAIN OF COMPUTERS
</P>
<P>
   Prolonged computer use has long been associated with aches and
pains as
</P>
<P>
   well as carpal tunnel syndrome, a condition affecting the median
nerve in
</P>
<P>
   the wrist that can be disabling. But now a study by ergonomic
researchers
</P>
<P>
   has identified one commercial keyboard that may ease the
discomfort of
</P>
<P>
   workers who spend extensive periods at the computer. 450 words.
</P>
<P>
   C. HIGH RESISTANCE TO PENICILLIN FOUND IN ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Several types of bacterial infection in Asian countries are
becoming more
</P>
<P>
   difficult to treat because of developing resistance. 450 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
THE ENGINE OF CREATION It's the smallest train in the world, but
it's no toy. The nano express could take us closer to the dream of
incredibly tiny robots that build themselves. By Jonathan Knight.
2,500 words. (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand)
