<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS BADLY NEED TOM GOODWIN AT TOP OF LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Tom Goodwin taking batting practice is a
little like watching your toddler play one of those tiny toy
pianos.
</P>
<P>
   Plink, plunk, plink, plonk.
</P>
<P>
   Flare to left. Dribbler to short. Flare to left. Pop fly to
center.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a toe-tapping tune, is it?
</P>
<P>
   That said, the news that Goodwin should be back at the top of
the batting order Sunday in Seattle is music to the Rangers' ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you don't know how much a guy means to you,'' Rusty
Greer wisely observed last night at The Ballpark in Arlington,
``until he's not there any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing to say about a guy with but a single homer and a
measly dozen RBI, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to a curious hypothesis: The Rangers may just be
a better team _ at this point in time _ with Goodwin in the lineup
than with super rookie Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Before you get a rope and form a lynch mob or petition the
Baseball Writers Association to revoke my baseball writing
privileges, hear me out.
</P>
<P>
   First, it's a moot point at the moment anyway, since Mateo went
on the disabled list with a badly strained groin after last night's
game with the A's. It's not as if he has to be sent back to
Oklahoma to make room for Goodwin to return to the active roster,
now that the center fielder's injured left hip has just about
healed.
</P>
<P>
   But have you taken a look at the Rangers' offense over the last
three weeks?
</P>
<P>
   Here, put this clothes pin on your nose and get a little closer
to these numbers:
</P>
<P>
   .156 and .063.
</P>
<P>
   The first represents what Rangers leadoff batters had hit in the
first 11 games after Goodwin was injured (not including last
night's game). The second is what they've hit in the last nine
games, going a scintillating 2-for-32.
</P>
<P>
   Not so coincidentally, the Rangers, until last night's breakout
game against Oakland, had been struggling to score runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the last 23 games,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
suggested. ``He's missed 12. In 19 of those 23 we've scored four or
fewer runs. I can't answer the question how much, but we do miss
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His on-base percentage is not what we'd like, but he was
leading the league in scoring percentage \R54 percent\S when he did
get on.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin had hit .297 in the 17 games before pulling up lame with
a slight tear in his left hip flexor, lifting his average to .240
for the season. He still leads the American League with 27 steals.
</P>
<P>
   There's no dispute that inserting the multiple-talented Mateo
into the lineup adds firepower. But without someone to ignite the
offense, the Rangers have sputtered badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When \RGoodwin\S is on base, he changes the pitches that guys
behind him get,'' Oates pointed out. ``It just makes the whole
lineup better.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates has tried three different players in the leadoff spot
since Goodwin was injured, including Greer and Luis Alicea for a
game each, but the burden has fallen primarily on second baseman
Mark McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mac is suited much better as a No. 2 hitter,'' Oates said.
``We've experimented a little. We've tried Mac, we've tried Rusty.
We tried Luis \RTuesday\S night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mac can do it. He's been in one of those streaks where he's
not hitting very well, but he can hit leadoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, McLemore was showing signs of doing exactly that last
night, reaching base safely with a pair of walks and a hit through
the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   But the point has been effectively made: Inserting Mateo into
the lineup and forgetting about Goodwin isn't the answer, at least
not right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tom does make a difference in our lineup,'' Greer
said. ``It's hard to explain. When he's in there, you don't really
think about it, but when he's not there for a couple of weeks, it
really starts to show.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's at the top of the lineup and getting on base, he's
putting pressure on the defense. And he was swinging the bat much
better before he got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, meanwhile, has shown flashes of brilliance but was
hitting just .182. His only home run came in his first game almost
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   What he doesn't need to do, however, is sit on anybody's bench.
If he's not starting here, he needs to be playing in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Mateo's groin injury _ the Rangers summoned
Scarborough Green from Oklahoma to hold the fort until Goodwin
returns Sunday _ allows Oates to delay his decision about what to
do when both are available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have either of them right now,'' Oates said, ``so I
don't have to answer that question today.''
</P>
<P>
   No, not today, but somewhere down the road, it's coming.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, starting Sunday in Seattle, Goodwin starts
plinking away again.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see if the rest of the Rangers'
orchestra chimes in.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
