<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7833 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-GOMEZ-COM     06-24 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-GOMEZ-COMENT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE WANTS TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the beginning, Mark McGwire genuinely did not understand
the public's fascination with him.
</P>
<P>
   After smacking five home runs during a three-game series in
Detroit as a rookie with the Oakland Athletics, several reporters
requested a few minutes with McGwire, who was on his way to hitting
a rookie-record 49 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if naive is the right word, but there was a golly
gee-whiz mentality about him in those days,'' former A's public
relations director Jay Alves said. ``He had not been exposed to
that type of scene. He was protected and sheltered, even at USC
(his college). He asked, `Why do they want to talk to me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   As he lumbers into Bank One Ballpark today with the Cardinals
for a four-game series, the country still wants to talk to McGwire
about last season's exploits and his 70 home runs. But McGwire
tires whenever the subject turns to 1998. Since none of us knows
exactly what it was like from the inside out, maybe he knows
something we don't.
</P>
<P>
   But what McGwire knows now is that St. Louis might not be
capable of contending for the playoffs this season. Injuries to
Cardinals pitchers have again ravaged their staff. And McGwire
badly wants to be on a playoff club.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, McGwire admitted how difficult the Cardinals'
chances appear in a discussion with St. Louis-area reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play too perfect,'' McGwire said to St. Louis-area
reporters. ``We can't afford to make mistakes. It's not just one
player. If it was two or three players coming into the mix and
jelling, I think that might make a difference, yeah. But one player
is not going to make a huge difference.''
</P>
<P>
   It's always been about winning for McGwire. Even back when
McGwire was puzzled over the interest in him, the one aspect of the
game that really grabbed his attention was the winning. Playing in
Oakland in those days meant there was plenty of it going on.
</P>
<P>
   Over a three-year span from 1988 to 1990, the A's averaged more
than 100 victories a season, won the American League pennant each
year and won the 1989 World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   It may very well have been the best time in McGwire's career,
and he was barely old enough or mature enough to recognize it and
appreciate how rare an experience it was.
</P>
<P>
   He had just turned 26 when he won his first and only World
Series. McGwire readily admits he didn't fully grasp what was going
on.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire seemed to be rotting away in Oakland during his final
seasons with the A's. The club was going nowhere in the American
League West, and McGwire, with the help of a psychotherapist he
still consults, had matured by leaps and bounds.
</P>
<P>
   The personal turmoil in his life had finally come to an end, and
he wanted to appreciate the game and what it meant to him. But the
constant losing and playing in front of almost non-existent crowds
wore on him. It was evident to everyone within the organization and
those of us who covered the A's during those years.
</P>
<P>
   All through it, though, McGwire never demanded out of Oakland.
That simply is not his style and would make it seem impossible for
him to ask out of St. Louis in the future, especially since he
loves playing for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   He was vocal in wanting the A's to make the necessary moves to
return to contention. McGwire was willing to do his share by not
asking for the moon when his contract was set to expire after the
1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   But all that changed on July 31, 1997, when the A's traded
McGwire to St. Louis for three pitchers. McGwire, who thought his
career would start and finish in Oakland, was not only traded, he
was now in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   While the Busch Stadium crowds have rejuvenated McGwire, it
appears the Cardinals are incapable of making a serious run in the
National League Central at any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he remains in top physical shape, the years are
starting to click by. McGwire will turn 36 on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, McGwire continues to do what he does best,
blasting home runs wherever he is.
</P>
<P>
   The home run hitter has always enjoyed a special place in
society and the game. During those early seasons in Oakland,
McGwire admitted he did not know the history of the game, but
simply knew how to play.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe it was understandable back then that he was unaware of
the adulation showered upon the long-ball hitters.
</P>
<P>
   If he didn't, or couldn't, understand the public's intrigue and
attraction with him in the early years, he surely does now. McGwire
reached the zenith of his career on a muggy September evening in
St. Louis late last summer when he became the game's single-season
home run record holder.
</P>
<P>
   He finished the season by demolishing Roger Maris' 1961 mark of
61, winding up with 70 home runs, a record that may stand the test
of time over another 37 years. The public's love affair with him
grew all summer, hitting a crescendo the night of Sept. 8, when an
entire nation was fixated on his every move.
</P>
<P>
   By now, there's little that hasn't been written or spoken about
McGwire, who stands atop the game as the greatest home run hitter
of the current era, on the verge of entering the hallowed ground of
the greatest home run hitters ever.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the adulation and fanfare, McGwire could not
escape controversy during his march toward immortality last season.
He was forced to defend himself after it was discovered he used the
dietary supplement androstenedione, which some researchers believe
to be harmful to the human body.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire needs 21 more home runs to become just the 16th player
ever to reach 500 in a career. Given that he still has not reached
his 36th birthday and has hit at least 50 home runs three
consecutive seasons, McGwire would seem to have a very good shot at
joining Hank Aaron, Babe Ruth and Willie Mays as the only players
ever to hit 600 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all of the home runs and statistics can be found in
any baseball record book, where McGwire has placed his name in
several categories. That's the easy stuff to know about McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   But given his lack of interest in rehashing his glorious summer
of '98, it's clear that individual records are not what matter at
this stage of his career.
</P>
<P>
   What McGwire is searching for is a return to the postseason. The
question looming over his head is whether it will happen. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
