<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BATTING-PRACTICE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS GOING TO BAT FOR CHANCE AT BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Mark McGwire's bat appears to be getting hot just in
time for the St. Louis Cardinals' four-game visit to Bank One
Ballpark this week.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, with three homers in his past four games, is tied for
second in the league with 22. And that spells danger for
Diamondbacks pitchers and excitement for batting-practice fans.
</P>
<P>
   Who can forget last year's onslaught, when McGwire walked into
BOB for the first time on June 12 and blasted a batting-practice
home run through one of the open panels in left field and onto
Jefferson Street?
</P>
<P>
   By now, 50,000 fans probably claim they were there for batting
practice on that Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   If the panels aren't open today through Sunday, there could be
an advertiser with a dented sign and a golden marketing
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   How about the Sunday batting practice of last season's June
series, when the bleachers, picnic areas, pool, outfield
concourses, TGI Friday's restaurant, the outfield mezzanine and
even the corners of the upper deck were jammed with thousands and
thousands of fans for batting practice?
</P>
<P>
   McGwire ripped shot after shot, some off the scoreboard wall,
some into the seats, one into Friday's and one into the upper-deck
beer garden in left field.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals took two out of three in the series, played before
more than 144,000 fans, and McGwire was on his was way into the
baseball history books.
</P>
<P>
   He hit one home run in that series, a 450-foot grand slam off
Andy Benes in Friday's opener, won by the Cardinals, 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   But it was batting practice that wowed the fans.
</P>
<P>
   The batting-practice scene begins early, long before fans can
even get into the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers take their cracks first, beginning about 3:40 p.m. for
a typical 7:05 p.m. start. Often, Diamondbacks reserves will take
extra batting practice even earlier in the day, sometimes joined by
starters.
</P>
<P>
   By about 4:30 p.m., as ushers are cleaning the suites and box
seats, the Diamondbacks begin regular batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter holds his daily chat with the media by
the dugout. It appears to be a relaxed, informal scene as players
come and go, coaches tend to their duties and monitor the players,
and some players' kids frolic on the field. But in reality it's a
scheduled, orderly process everyone goes through day after day.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, diehards are lining up or huddling in shady spots
around the ballpark, waiting for the magical 5 o'clock hour when
the gates open.
</P>
<P>
   Boom! Matt Williams smacks one into the left-field seats as the
first fans take up their positions. It bounces out of the stands,
missed by the initial wave of souvenir hunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' Albert Luna of Phoenix said before a recent
Chicago Cubs-Diamondbacks game as hundreds of fans poured into the
stadium when the gates opened. ``You have a chance of getting a
ball from somebody you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Luna attends a few games each year and always arrives early for
batting practice, glove in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Early birds also have a chance to stumble upon that rare find, a
ball from early batting practice that wasn't picked up by ushers.
</P>
<P>
   From 5 to 5:35, fans can see the Diamondbacks in batting
practice. From 5:35 to 6:15, the visitors get their swings. After a
five-minute break to remove the cages, each team has 10 minutes of
infield practice before turning the field over to the grounds crew.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller children, those who aren't playing on the center-field
jungle gym or testing their youthful skills at the Cox Clubhouse
games area, try to get into the front row of the bleachers for
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   There, chances of getting a ball are better if a friendly player
tosses one up than trying to catch one amid the aggressive
grown-ups with their gloves in the rows above.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the big guys dive, jump, run and knock over anyone in
their way in pursuit of the balls. That angers some fans, but most
don't seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Expert ball retrievers will tell you to stand about halfway up
in the bleachers and play for the rebounds of missed balls if
you're serious about the souvenir hunt.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Tim Hollman of Sedona and his son, Tyler, were
hanging out, hoping to snag a Sammy Sosa shot.
</P>
<P>
   They did the same thing last year, when Sosa and McGwire were
neck and neck in the home run race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just fun to get here early,'' Hollman said. ``And I was a
Cubs fan last year, but this year it's different.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to experience a leisurely batting practice and have
a chance to shag balls, go on a weeknight against a weak team, such
as the Florida Marlins. If it's spectacle you want, get there early
for the Cardinals series beginning tonight.
</P>
<P>
   While the left-field bleachers are the main hangout, right field
isn't bad. A number of balls soar into the outfield concourse or
picnic overhang on both sides. And it's fun just to watch sluggers
like Mike Piazza tattoo the center-field scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Key spots for autograph hounds are right next to the field down
the lines _ the third-base side for Diamondbacks, right field for
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   And fans who just want to relax and take in the proceedings
without getting trampled can sit in their box or grandstand seats
in solitude for a while _ before the late-arriving, early leaving
crowd shows up.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wilhelm of Glendale did just that on Friday when the Atlanta
Braves were in town. He came straight from work, waited outside
about 10 minutes, and then was the only fan in his section,
relaxing in the pre-game fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's cooler in here than it is out there,'' he said.
``And this is an exciting team.''
</P>
<P>
   Others stroll around the concourse, checking out the baseball
exhibits, shopping for souvenirs or loading up on food and drink
before it gets crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals fan Jake Robinson of Mesa says ``bandwagon'' fans have
taken some of the fun out of batting practice by jamming the stands
to see the stars.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers going to batting practice as a child in St. Louis,
when only a few dozen people would show up early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still fun, though,'' he said last week, waiting for the
gates to open for an Atlanta Braves game. ``It's a cheap way to get
balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson brought along a friend, Rene Schafler, to attend his
first batting practice ever at BOB.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't wait,'' the Los Angeles Dodgers-turned-Diamondbacks fan
said with a grin, flexing his glove.
</P>
<P>
   Neither got a souvenir that night, but you know they'll be
back. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
