<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Seeing the sites has its price
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, June 27, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a wall running the length of my family room, 38 identically
framed photos present a tiered montage-like remembrance of places
visited _ there's my wife standing on the Great Wall of China, me
atop one of Giza's huge stones, my grandson and me at Stonehenge,
my wife in front of the Sydney Opera House...
</P>
<P>
   It has been my passion to see the world, but I didn't want to
have to join the Navy to do it. Preferably, I've seen it with my
wife.
</P>
<P>
   We hardly are alone in this quest. Worldwide, tourist sites are
beginning to become inundated with people like me. I must confess
it's not a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   America's national parks have had to set limits for visits
because of the overcrowding and subsequent damage to the
environment. No longer can I mount the Giza pyramid stone I
straddled 30 years ago; Egyptian authorities properly have cracked
down. The constant throngs trying to see Michelangelo's ``David''
at the Academy Gallery in Florence now are governed by admission
rules that set 15-minute limits to the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Lines are serpentine to board the ferries for the Statue of
Liberty and Ellis Island; so are they to enter the great mosques of
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   Gravity and masses of people now make it impossible for tourists
to wend their way to the top of the very Leaning Tower of Pisa, and
the lines of those waiting to get up the Eiffel Tower or to enter
the Washington Monument often are too long to endure.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is this an era when a weekend trip to Grandma's house
was the travel adventure of the year. We now are cross-country,
more and more becoming world travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, adventurers and/or explorers _ choose your definition
_ are finding more for us to visit some day. Cleopatra's ancient
Alexandria has been discovered just off the coast of Egypt,
everyone now knows every nook and cranny of the Titanic, and just
this past week it was revealed that Titanic's discoverer, Robert
Ballard, found two ancient cargo ships (circa 750 B.C.) in 1,000
feet of water near Tyre in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Where will it lead? I read somewhere not long ago that there
were plans to bring tourists to the site of the Titanic (at a very
heavy price) and there's still the likelihood that the generation
being born now will some day be able to buy a ticket for a ride in
space.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, however, there are other plans nearer actuality. In
Peru, the government is considering a plan to build cable-car
access to the ancient Inca capital of Machu Picchu, nearly 8,000
feet above sea level. Presently, the ruins can be reached by bus,
foot or helicopter, but the trip is arduous for most and thus the
numbers trying it are not unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Open it up with a cable car and it will be like trying to jam
into the elevators on the Eiffel Tower on a lovely June day.
</P>
<P>
   As the world population increases, the discovery of ancient
sites (i.e., tourist photo opportunities) do not increase
proportionately. The once easily accessible locations are not so
accessible anymore because we came to them in huge numbers _ and
did not treat them well.
</P>
<P>
   The world is a remarkable place to see and I do not regret my
travels. But I sense the need for better controls, keener
environmental protections and higher admission costs to cover those
necessities if these sites are to endure us _ for, if not, that
39th picture on my wall might be of a road sign advising me of a
great cultural site just ahead but to proceed no further.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
