<HEADER>
A7839 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN27-COX     06-24 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Exhuming McCarthy
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine a much tougher mission in rehabilitation
than trying to buff the image of Sen. Joseph McCarthy, the
grandstanding Red-baiter of the 1950s whose excesses are enshrined
in his namesake -ism, to this day a synonym for bully demagoguery.
</P>
<P>
   But the historians and other wordsmiths of the cultural right
have lately taken up the task like manic elves. Scholarly
re-evaluations have been published, to the effect that McCarthy was
a misunderstood hero of the resistance to communism and the Soviet
Union, fatally maligned for a wee misstep here or there by foolish
and knavish liberals either indifferent to the horrors of Stalinism
or contemptuous of their own country. Or both.
</P>
<P>
   Now the redoubtable and relentless William F. Buckley Jr. has
joined in, with a novel in which the senator is, by reviewers'
accounts, treated more or less as a great and noble, if sometimes
floundering, beast brought down by nasty terriers.
</P>
<P>
   Revisionism, Lord knows, is not a conservative proprietary. A
testy cell of liberals has spent years, for instance, trying to pin
the Cold War on the United States. At the left fringes, there are
some who figure the Ayatollah Khomeini, if for the wrong reasons,
had it basically right with his Great Satan stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But reinflating the Joe McCarthy doll takes some especially
heavy huffing and puffing. First, his opponents must be recast as
either naive if principled dupes or duplicitous fellow travelers,
and Soviet subversion has to be made the fundamental menace to
American survival that it never had any hope of being.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the ranks of Soviet-leaning liberals, never vast, were
first decimated in the '30s by disillusion wrought of the Moscow
purge trials, and the survivors of that decimation were decimated
again by the shocking Hitler-Stalin pact.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, labor unions, often at heroic effort, were
ridding themselves of Comintern cadres. The Soviet-front
conveniences of wartime's expedient alliance were flopping. The
radical presidential candidacy of Henry Wallace fizzled. Liberals
were gearing up to press for social reform at home while contesting
imperial communism abroad, a parlay that would take formal shape
with the creation of Americans for Democratic Action. Few doubted
Soviet spying.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy was a naked political opportunist, sloppy with the
facts, wanton in accusation, disdainful of civil liberties. The Red
scare he incited surfaced a few communist small fry, most of them
more dabblers than threats, but it savaged innocents equally and
created a hysteria that, among other damage, drove seasoned
diplomats from the State Department, degrading our ability to fight
the Cold War ably.
</P>
<P>
   It is well to revisit and newly understand history. But history
is not there just to be up-ended to serve ideological conceits. The
Soviet historians, who were the masters of that craft, would look
on the cultural warriors who are trying to outfit McCarthy with a
new, exculpatory narrative as mere amateurs _ but not without
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
