<HEADER>
A7840 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPT-GAMBLING-BICKLEY-     06-24 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-GAMBLING-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S THE OUTRAGE? GAMBLING MA JOR THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once, you could stand under the Gateway Arch in St. Louis,
follow the Mississippi River, imagine Huckleberry Finn and darn
near taste America's heritage floating by.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you can stand in the same place and find a casino boat
anchored to shore, sending waves of cheap neon into the night.
</P>
<P>
   It is a terrible sight, the perfect metaphor for a country
infatuated with gambling and sports. And if ever the twains shall
meet . . .
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Isaac Burton was sentenced to prison for his role
in the ASU point-shaving scandal of 1994. On his way out of the
courtroom, he apologized to Bill Frieder, a poignant moment and the
first time someone said sorry to the coach.
</P>
<P>
   But no one gives a chip. Frieder is not an exiled cockroach, as
he may have been in another era. He is just a sloppy and friendly
uncle, doing commercials, running Jason Kidd's basketball camp,
dining alone in the press room of Bank One Ballpark, living a life.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, John Daly admitted to the golfing world that he
gambled away $9 million in recent years. That's not the total
amount bet _ which is closer to $93 million _ just the money he
lost.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Albert Belle admitted he lost more than $40,000
gambling on sports other than baseball, and baseball shrugged its
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, a large sports gambling ring was found operating
inside a Columbia University fraternity house.
</P>
<P>
   Hello? Doesn't anybody care anymore? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the NCAA concluded a two-year study on gambling and
announced the following: It will support legislation introduced by
Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., who is seeking a ban on Internet gambling.
The Senate Judiciary Committee adopted the legislation last week,
but many legal issues remain on how to police borderless
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA also supports a recommendation to restrict legal
gambling to those over age 21, and to ban legal betting on college
and amateur events.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bold and wonderful move, but the hurdles are enormous.
Gambling is so big that professional leagues tread lightly,
painfully aware of their consumer base. Gambling is so hot that Las
Vegas is spawning hotels like tadpoles. Gambling has grown up a lot
over the past few years _ and is looking very much like T. Rex.
</P>
<P>
   And in other news, the National Association of Directors of
Athletics recently held a convention in Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' Arizona State Athletic Director Kevin White said.
``It's inexcusable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC; 
Somewhere along the line, gambling went from dark secret to
national pastime. And many experts think the proliferation of
legalized gambling has set the recent tone of acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   State lotteries sell a government-sponsored dream to those who
can least afford to play games of chance. But proponents claim they
are just channeling a nation's taste for gambling into a productive
end, and by 1995, 37 states were sponsoring lotteries, reaping in
more than $34 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have an insatiable interest in gaming,'' White said.
``It's at a fever pitch and growing. Go to every major community in
this country, and if they aren't in the gaming business, they're
contemplating it very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   This sudden tolerance has led to a rage of riverboat gambling
and on-land casinos, and over the past decade, 21 states have
legalized commercial casinos.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, here was the menu of legalized gambling in Arizona:
horse and dog racing, off-track betting facilities all over the
state, two weekly Power Ball drawings, two weekly Lotto drawings,
four weekly Fantasy Five drawings, more than 20 scratch-off games
and 14 casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Now, one local casino tempts you with a new radio catch phrase:
With two locations, you can gamble 48 hours a day!
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become part of the American fabric,'' White said. ``And
in my view, it's a contradiction to sports.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If the numbers don't grab you, the apathy should.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, a research firm in New York estimated illegal sports
wagering at $8 billion a year. By 1995, it had risen to $84
billion, or $35 billion more than the illegal drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the NCAA cited these figures: $2.4 billion a year is
spent on sports wagering in Las Vegas. Nevada is the only state
with legalized sports betting. The illegal sports wagering
industry, however, could be generating as much as $380 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, the brush fires: Point shaving scandals at
ASU and Northwestern. A Cal State-Fullerton athlete who was offered
money to shave points. Betting on college sporting events by
Maryland players. A fiasco at Boston College, where players bet
against their own team.
</P>
<P>
   Once, in 1951, City College of New York's basketball team landed
in a point-shaving scandal and a nation screamed in outrage. Once,
Pete Rose was banned from baseball and his conqueror, Bart
Giamatti, was a hero. Now, it's too commonplace to get worked up
about.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bill Saum, the NCAA director of agent and gambling
activities, admits there isn't a college in the country where you
can't find a campus bookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear is it's much like that proverbial iceberg,'' Arizona
Athletic Director Jim Livengood said. ``As bad as things seem on
the surface, I get the feeling it's going to get a lot worse.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Titanic Casino _ take what you will from the name _ is just one
of an estimated 250 online casinos. They are the breeding termites
that could tear down the foundation of college sports.
</P>
<P>
   The anonymity of Internet gambling is beyond frightening. A
basketball player at any major college can open an account under a
friend's name. Among a myriad of options, he can bet on the range
of points he will score in an upcoming basketball game. He can fix
the event in a most subtle fashion, even without throwing the
contest.
</P>
<P>
   But the implications are devastating. What if half the players
on the court have placed side bets?
</P>
<P>
   With a click of the mouse goes the integrity of sports.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard enough tackling the problem of point-shaving and
illegal gambling through human channels. But this is something
entirely different.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA knows its students gamble. An infamous and random NCAA
survey of 2,000 male student-athletes in Division I basketball and
football found that more than 25 percent reported gambling on
college events. Four percent claimed to have wagered on games in
which they played.
</P>
<P>
   New York economist Sebastian Sinclair says Internet wagering
generated an estimated $651 million in 1998. But to date, none of
the recent rash of scandals has pierced the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   It is the next Black Hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about more gambling scandals, it's a matter of
when, not if,'' Livengood said. ``It could be the ruination of
college athletics. It's that serious.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Titanic Casino's Web site sends you to a sports book
that adds 10 percent to the initial account of new customers.
</P>
<P>
   Need any other evidence that this is a sucker's proposition? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Addiction:
</P>
<P>
   My father was a heavy smoker.
</P>
<P>
   On his deathbed, days before dying of lung cancer, he asked for
a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   My wife's grandfather was a riverboat fanatic.
</P>
<P>
   On his deathbed, just days before dying in early February, he
sat in his hospital bed, nearly unconscious, holding an imaginary
conversation with a dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Hit me, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hit me, too. Once again. Like a ton of chips. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
