<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7842 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-TWO-GUARDS-     06-24 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-TWO-GUARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP FOR SHOOTING WOES IS NOT ON THE WAY IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the league that can't shoot straight, a hunt for accuracy is
under way. But it promises to be a lot like the NBA this season.
More miss than hit.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be little help in the draft at the very
position that has the name but little else.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting guards? How about missing guards?
</P>
<P>
   In basketball's current parlance, they are called ``the twos.''
The terrible twos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much,'' Suns scout Al Bianchi said of the chance
to land a reliable, accurate backcourt shooter in the draft on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that the Suns need one. A sure sign at the lack
of prospects in this class is the Suns' interest in Penny Hardaway,
who has talked about leaving Orlando and moving exclusively from
playmaker to shooting guard. The Suns have the No. 9 pick, but it's
not likely to land them the shooter they need immediately. Hence,
the Hardaway talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The twos are terrible this year,'' said Dick Percudani,
another Suns scout.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, they are a collection of players who have
been at other positions. College forwards are being measured for
their potential to play shooting guard in the pros.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the bunch are too small for the spot in the NBA,
although one might be an exception. Some scouts say 6-foot-3 Steve
Francis could succeed at the two spot, his position at the
University of Maryland. But for now, Francis, the potential No. 1
pick, is projected to be a point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is the versatile Lamar Odom of Rhode Island.
Bianchi said the 6-9 Odom has the physical ability to play at least
three spots: the point, small forward and shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   But there are questions about his maturity. Odom, an
underclassman, failed to report for a couple of physicals and has
expressed doubts about whether he should go pro. Odom was thought
to be the No. 1 pick by some scouts several weeks ago, but he might
be in a free fall.
</P>
<P>
   So what's left?
</P>
<P>
   One of the intriguing possibilities is Wally Szczerbiak, a 6-8
senior forward last season at Miami of Ohio. Statistics say he can
shoot. He averaged 23.6 points on 52.1 percent shooting last
season. But there are predictable questions about his quickness
along the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a small forward who people would eventually like to see
at the two,'' Percudani said. ``But can he create his own shots?''
</P>
<P>
   The marketing department has very few doubts about Szczerbiak,
who apparently has off-the-floor qualities that create interest and
ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks fluent Spanish, a language he learned as a kid when
his dad played in Spain. His father was in an early Suns training
camp three decades ago. Szczerbiak also has matinee-idol looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be the Ricky Martin of NBA basketball,'' Percudani
said, referring to the bilingual singer and soap opera star.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is Richard Hamilton, a 6-6 junior swingman
who averaged 21.0 points last year at Connecticut, the NCAA
champion. At 195 pounds, Hamilton probably has to make it as a
shooting guard in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Of the prospects under serious consideration, Trajan Langdon is
the one player who was a shooting guard in college. He averaged
17.1 points last season as Duke senior.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting statistic about Langdon is his three-point
accuracy: 42.8 percent. In a recent workout with the Los Angeles
Clippers, Langdon shot 22 for 25 from the NBA's longer three-point
distance.
</P>
<P>
   But there are questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big enough, quick enough?'' Percudani asked.
</P>
<P>
   At only 6-3, some question whether Langdon has the size to shoot
over bigger defenders. He was effective in shooting over zone
defenses in college. But against man-to-man coverage? Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Two other names in a very uncertain class:
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Levett, Cincinnati. He can be an explosive athlete. He
also is an explosive personality. The second factor scares scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Carter of Mississippi. See Levett. The scouting report on
Carter is the same in a short book with too few twos. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
