<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7857 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-GOODLING-$A     06-24 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-GOODLING-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TOP LAWMAKER SAYS HIS WASTE OF FEDERAL FUNDS EDUCATED HIM
 &HT;    700&AMP;add. For release Sunday, June 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The battle in Congress over how to improve federal
aid to schools is heavily influenced by Rep. William F. Goodling's
memories of his own abuse of federal grants during his days as an
educator more than a quarter century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasted a lot of federal dollars early on,'' the 71-year-old
Pennsylvania Republican admitted in an interview. He vowed to
reshape the controls over federal education funds before he retires
next year from Congress, at the end of his six-year term as
chairman of the House Committee on Education and the Workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Before his election in 1974 to succeed his father as the
representative of a bucolic, three-county area near the Gettysburg
battlefield, Goodling worked for two decades in small public school
districts around Seven Valleys, Pa. He was first a teacher,
counselor and coach of football, basketball and baseball teams, and
later a high school principal, superintendent and school board
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the early days, when this money from the federal
government for equipment would arrive in October or November and
nothing was planned. My superintendent would come in and say,
'Order, order, order,' `` Goodling recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ordered all sorts of things that nobody even knew how to
use, if that's what the money was earmarked for,'' Goodling said.
``For all I know, that district still has some of our overhead
projectors piled up in a closet somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that experience left him suspicious of narrow grant
programs that are audited only to make sure that the paperwork
shows that funds were spent exactly how the federal government
specified.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Miller of California, who would become chairman of
the education panel if the Democrats retake Congress, ``always
wants to know what the taxpayers are getting for their money,''
Goodling said. ``I want to know what the children are getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodling was the chief drafter of the ``Straight A's Act,'' more
formally known as the Academic Achievement for All Act, which he
and House GOP leaders introduced last Tuesday (June 22).
</P>
<P>
   That bill would give states the option of blending funds from
their biggest federal grants, instead of using each only for the
purpose specified under federal law. If a state decided not to take
that option, any of its districts could do so on its own. Only
states or districts that failed to prove that their students were
improving in academics would have to follow federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   One typical rule dedicates about $8 billion of the $15 billion
in federal education grants distributed each year to help children
from schools with lots of poor students. Another rule earmarks just
over $1 billion for President Clinton's plan to reduce class sizes
by hiring 100,000 more teachers for the early grades.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking the Straight A's Act, Secretary of Education Richard
Riley charged, ``In their zeal for quick fixes and silver-bullet
solutions, Republicans are proposing another experiment in revenue
sharing (that) fails to ensure that federal resources are spent
effectively on practices that work.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley's attack, and the fact that Rep. Ralph Hall of Texas was
the only Democrat to join52 Republicans in cosponsoring the bill,
bodes ill for the proposal. Goodling might have a hard time
rounding up the kind of bipartisan support that is needed to avoid
a stalemate between the Democratic president and the
Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodling shrugged that off, pointing out that Clinton
overcame his early skepticism and signed a modified version of the
Educational Flexibility Act this spring. In some ways similar to
the Straight A's Act, although it affects fewer programs, the
flexibility act also allows mingling of funds. It was adopted
nationwide only after it had been pilot-tested in 12 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, after we've built a big enough coalition, the
president will see how good the Straight A's Act is, and he'll find
a way to take credit for it,'' Goodling predicted. ``If it'll help,
we're willing to change the name to the William Jefferson Clinton
Reform Act.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   Goodling said his belief that at least some federal aid can be
justified grows out of his experiences between 1967 and 1974, when
he was superintendent of the Spring Grow (cq) Area District near
his 20-acre horse farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the start, we were just wasting federal dollars trying to
make readers out of illiterate senior high school students,''
Goodling said. ``They didn't want to admit they couldn't read in
the first place, and we didn't know how to motivate them or how to
teach high school students to read.''
</P>
<P>
   So he convinced his school board to let him use federal funds
for the disadvantaged to support a completely different
anti-dropout plan designed by an early-childhood specialist on his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   The plan offered in-home tutoring for pre-schoolers who would be
described by today's educators as ``at risk'' _ children with a
parent, older brother or older sister who had dropped out of
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``By doing it at home, the parent or older sister was also
learning some things _ things like what it is you can do to help a
child become reading-ready,'' Goodling said. ``After several
months, they would move to a program at a church, because we didn't
think 3- and 4-year-olds should be brought into a formal school
setting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefits over the years of working on the whole family's
literacy were so obvious, and not just for the kids,'' he said.
``You saw parents participating in PTA meetings who, before, would
never have come anywhere near a school.''
</P>
<P>
   When he left that job to go to Congress, Goodling warned the
incoming superintendent, ``Remember, board members' children can't
participate in this program (because their parents weren't
dropouts), so you're going to have to fight for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years the program was abandoned. ``He didn't do a
very good job of fighting for it,'' Goodling lamented.
</P>
<P>
   But as a member of the Republican minority on the education
committee in the 1980s, Goodling convinced the members to transform
the idea into a small but widely admired federal program for family
literacy. Called Even Start, it helped inspire similar requirements
for parental involvement in Head Start.
</P>
<P>
   Goodling didn't include either Even Start or Head Start on the
list of programs that states or districts could lump together under
his Straight A's Act.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
