<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials hope osprey population will take off in Ohio
 &HT;    By Rachel Kipp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ On Wednesday morning eight osprey chicks woke up
in their nests in the Maryland wild.
</P>
<P>
   Now the chicks are living in nesting boxes 25 feet off the
ground in the Spring Valley Wildlife Area as part of an effort to
bring the bird species back to the state of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, Spring Valley has been one of five sites in Ohio
to receive osprey chicks from the East Coast as part of an Ohio
Division of Wildlife project to have 20 breeding pairs of ospreys
in Ohio by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Ospreys, also called fishhawks, are a species of bird who feed
almost entirely on live fish, said Gary Imwalle, wildlife area
supervisor for Spring Valley. According to The Raptor Center at the
University of Minnesota, ospreys have special adaptations that make
them expert fishermen, such as a `spicules' on the bottom of their
feet for grasping slippery objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to a combination of pesticides which cause reproductive
failure, a loss of habitat, decreased water quality, and nest site
disturbances, ospreys left the Ohio area,'' Imwalle said.
</P>
<P>
   The last recorded wild osprey nest in Ohio was seen in 1913.
Imwalle said. Spring Valley was chosen as a site for the 10-year
study because it met certain criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted sites in all the corners of the state,'' he said.
``Sites had to be close to a wildlife work unit, to have a good
fish prey base, and be in a place that wasn't occupied by bald
eagle territory, who tend not to tolerate ospreys.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicks, who are about six weeks old when they arrive in Ohio,
come from Maryland, New York, and Virginia. Only one chick is
removed from each nest. A chick is only taken from the nest if
their are at least two others left for the parents to raise, said
Imwalle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
