<HEADER>
A7870 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-CUTS25-COX     06-24 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CUTS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medicare cuts mean less help for elderly, critics say
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Last year, when the Rev. Clifton Freudenberg was
released from the San Antonio hospital that installed his
pacemaker, he still felt unsteady from an inner ear condition that
was causing him vertigo.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than go home, he entered the skilled nursing unit at
Guadalupe Valley Hospital in his hometown of Seguin.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-year-old wing was the kind of modern health care facility
that rural people don't often see in their communities. In fact, it
had been named the best in Texas by the agency that runs Medicare,
the federal health insurance program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Just months later, however, the unit had to close when the
federal government reduced the amount Medicare pays for patients
like Freudenberg. In Austin, the same cuts forced the St. David's
HealthCare Partnership to close all three of its skilled nursing
facilities this year and lay off 250 people. The last is set to
close June 30.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year and a half, cuts in what Medicare pays have
squeezed health care providers across the state and across the
country, causing hospitals to scale back services for the elderly,
such as skilled nursing, and forcing home health agencies to close
altogether. Statewide, more than 300 home health agencies that
relied on Medicare payments _ or one in five _ have closed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, hospitals are saying Congress went too far in making the
cuts and pleading with lawmakers to soften the blow. They estimate
that Medicare reductions will cost them $18 billion more than
Congress projected in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saving more money than I think they meant to save,''
said Ron Anderson, president of Parkland Memorial Hospital in
Dallas and chairman of the Texas Hospital Association, which held
its annual meeting in Austin last week. ``If we undermine the
infrastructure too much, sure, we save some money, but we hurt
people on the other end.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, doctors and patients say, the cuts are
putting the hurt on facilities that are better at treating elderly
people recovering from strokes, infections or broken bones than
acute-care hospitals or nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks, Freudenberg received physical therapy and
supportive care that got him back on his feet. He participated in
group activities meant to ease his re-entry into his normal routine
as a preacher at Cross United Church of Christ in Seguin. Twice, a
volunteer stopped by to play the accordion music Freudenberg loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the hospital has the time to do for patients
what these people did,'' said Freudenberg, 76. ``Without that unit,
I don't know where I would be in ability or how I would have been
restored had I not had all the features of the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal budget passed in 1997, Congress ordered hundreds
of changes in Medicare aimed at reducing overuse of and overpayment
for certain services.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the biggest targets were skilled nursing _ facilities
that treat elderly patients who are well enough to leave the
hospital but too sick to go home _ and home health care, which
brings treatment to the home during recovery and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents in Congress said there was too much variation in what
Medicare was charged for the services and too much opportunity for
waste and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
