r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN25-COX     06-24 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life in the land of white beaches and blue drinks
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANCUN, Mex. _ The new growth industry in this city of 400,000 _
built 28 years ago solely for the purpose of enticing tourists into
trading dollars and Deutschmarks for tequila and fajitas _ is hair
braiding.
</P>
<P>
   There are more people braiding hair in Cancun per linear foot
than anywhere in the world, I believe: tight braids with pieces of
silver foil on the ends, like the ones Bo Derek wore in the movie
``10'' some 15 years ago, or such as Whoopi Goldberg still wears on
occasion. As you wander through the innumerable shops selling
everything from Tommy Hilfiger knock-offs to Mayan art, merchants
beckon, showing off samples of hair braids perched spookily on
Styrofoam skulls. ``K-Mart blue-light special, today only, pretty
lady,'' they chant.
</P>
<P>
   Business is good, judging from the number of women and even a
few brave males I saw wearing braids. Even my better half fell for
the pitch and tried it, though it was only a day before she spent
hours unraveling braids out of her hair and cursing her moment of
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   This is my second trip to Cancun, which sits near the tip of the
Yucatan Peninsula, surrounded by ocean water so blue-green and sand
so white it almost looks fake, especially after getting used to
upper Texas Gulf Coast beaches. Cancun was founded in 1971 and on
my first visit 12 years ago it had already caught on as a tourist
destination, but nothing like now. It appears to be the preferred
destination point for high-school senior trips, at least judging by
what I saw last week while on vacation there.
</P>
<P>
   A parent has two choices to make if his child says he wants to
go to Cancun for a senior trip. Either say ``No way, Jose. Over my
dead body,'' or expect that the child:
</P>
<P>
   _ Will drink massive amounts of cheap alcohol at clubs that
could care less if the kid is 15, let alone 18 or 21. The legal
drinking age in Mexico is 18. The accepted age in Cancun appears to
be about 12, at least for visitors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Is likely to come home with a tattoo or pierced body part,
possibly both. I overheard more than one high-school student, whose
party was about to end with the trip back to the real world, say,
``Oh, man, my mom is going to kill me when she sees this tattoo.''
Or pierced eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   _ Will have a difficult time adjusting to normal-world hours,
having just spent a week sleeping until 3 p.m., drinking beer for
breakfast, then partying until the sun rises.
</P>
<P>
   My approach, which likely will draw criticism, is that ignorance
is bliss. I don't want to know what happened when my daughters went
to Cozumel, Cancun's older sister in tourism, for the youngest's
senior trip a few weeks ago. Now that I've seen it for myself, I
really don't want to know how my daughters spent their time. Those
are your two choices as a parent: Refuse permission and deal with a
surly, whining teen-ager. Say OK and hope it all turns out. Take
your pick. I figure they're about grown by high-school graduation
anyway, and they'll do what they'll do.
</P>
<P>
   Cancun has exploded in growth, and it now has the inevitable
array of hip eating places _ Hard Rock Cafe, Planet Hollywood,
Rainforest Cafe, Carlos and Charlies. The food is cheap, about
two-thirds of what you'd pay at the American franchises. The
service is impeccable everywhere you go, from the condos to the
beach-side beverage service, to the hundreds of shops both quaint
and chic, cheap and expensive. You can buy a Rolex watch here,
though why anyone would pay $3,500 for a used watch is beyond me,
or you can get a piece of Mayan ceramic for 30 pesos _ about three
bucks. I went for the latter.
</P>
<P>
   If you go, take a trip to Isla Mujeres, a tiny island five miles
off the coast and accessible by ferry for $14. It feels more like
real Mexico, with none of the franchise frenzy of Cancun, though it
too has grown tremendously in the past decade. At Isla Mujeres, you
can find a pleasant open-air cantina, such as Sombrero de Gordos,
and eat fajitas, sip Dos Equis and walk away having spent less than
$20 for three people. Then you can rent a golf cart or moped and
putter around the cobblestone streets, making your way through
narrow alleyways until you come across the whitewashed adobes and
dirt yards of the people who actually live here. It will remind you
this isn't Disney World, when you see where the people making five
pesos an hour live.
</P>
<P>
   Snorkeling is wonderful at Isla Mujeres, though the rainy
weather and cold weather precluded doing that on this trip. This is
the rainy season in the Caribbean, with a late-afternoon shower
almost a sure bet.
</P>
<P>
   The rain didn't bother me, since I'm not one to lie prostrate in
the sun baking myself for no reason. I endure enough sun working in
the yard. I prefer sitting under a thatched cabana on the beach,
reading a trashy novel, watching the rain and celebrating the fact
it had driven all the whooping high-school students inside to the
bar. The contingent from a Georgia high school was starting to
annoy me with their rebel yells as they downed shots of some
mysterious blue liquid I wouldn't drink on a bet. It looked like
windshield washer fluid.
</P>
<P>
   I noticed most the clubs don't open until 10 p.m., which is yet
another reason I never darkened the door of one during our visit.
That's bedtime when you're middle-aged.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, to be young again, although I think I would still pass on
the tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
