<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7873 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-AGENCIES25-COX     06-24 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-AGENCIES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Accountablility key for Texas agencies
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ The Texas governor who would be president of
the United States needs a better explanation of why he does not
favor public accountability by groups that spend taxpayer money.
Gov. George W. Bush's rationale for vetoing House Bill 2557 just
doesn't add up.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the background: There are 55 community action agencies in
Texas that spend tax dollars on programs designed to help children,
the poor, the disabled and the elderly. These agencies are exempt
from the Texas Open Meetings Act and the Texas Open Records Act,
yet they spend millions of tax dollars funneled to them by state
and federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The East Texas Human Development Corp., headquartered in
Marshall, is one of those agencies. Since 1991, the Longview
News-Journal has been reporting about HUDCO's wasteful spending,
questionable management and inefficient delivery of services. In
addition to receiving state funds for programs that provide energy
and housing assistance and meals to children, the elderly and
disabled, HUDCO received some $3 million in Head Start education
funds annually.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1996, we reported the story of a $900,000 spending
spree with Head Start education funds. That included a $17,000
parent-staff banquet, of which some $12,500 was spent on gifts for
board and staff members. The other money was squandered on snow
cone and popcorn machines, cameras, sewing machines, microcassette
recorders and other items of questionable use. At the same time,
less than one-fourth of Longview's
</P>
<P>
   eligible children are being served by Head Start. That's where
we were 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, HUDCO was finally forced to voluntarily give up
its Head Start contract. But for more than eight years, precious
funds to help children were wasted and misused.
</P>
<P>
   HUDCO also has operated other programs providing housing,
weatherization, energy assistance and emergency services. The Texas
Department of Housing and Community Affairs and federal auditors
have criticized HUDCO for a ``pervasive misapplication of grant
funds,'' financial and management problems, failure to follow state
and federal regulations in spending grant funds, substandard or
nonexistent record keeping, violating federal contract terms,
failure to seek competitive bids and improperly shifting funds from
one program to another.
</P>
<P>
   This is what led state Rep. Bob Glaze (D-Gilmer) to introduce
legislation to require Texas' 55 community action agencies to open
their records to the public and hold public meetings when they
decide how they will use tax dollars. The bill passed without a
single dissenting vote. How often does that happen?
</P>
<P>
   The idea that it could subject ``faith-based organizations in
Texas to unnecessary government intrusion'' if they get state or
federal grants just doesn't wash. The proposed law wouldn't have
applied to faith-based groups unless they received a federal
contract to operate as a community action agency _ and then the
groups would be accountable only for the tax dollars received.
Shouldn't any organization that receives state or federal funds be
accountable?
</P>
<P>
   The second objection _ that any future problems such as those
with HUDCO would be dealt with promptly by the TDHCA _ is a
patently bad assumption. TDHCA and federal officials say they are
unable to hold tight reins over problem agencies such as HUDCO.
</P>
<P>
   That's why vetoing this bill is neither conservative,
compassionate, nor wise. Surely, a conservative would want to
ensure accountability of tax money. It's not compassionate because
a large number of Texas children from disadvantaged homes are
missing the educational, social, health and nutritional benefits of
Head Start. Texas' children, its poor, elderly and disabled are
being deprived of nutrition, housing, energy assistance and other
services.
</P>
<P>
   Public accountability and open government are concepts that
should apply to any agency that spends taxpayers' money. Without
adequate public oversight to ensure that these human services are
being delivered effectively and efficiently, it is harmful to
children, the poor, the disabled and the elderly of Texas. It
allows taxpayer money to be wasted and hurts all Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
