<HEADER>
A7875 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-COLUMN25-COX     06-24 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Invisible on the streets of Southeast Austin
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's Note: I recently spent a couple Friday nights seeing
Austin as APD Officer Wayne Vincent and Dr. Ed Racht, EMS medical
director, see it. This is the first of two reports. The other will
run next week.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After 14 years on the street, Wayne Vincent
knows what it's like to be invisible. It's about 1 a.m. and we're
watching this guy walk through a parking lot, pointedly avoiding
looking at the white Chevy with the Austin Police Department decals
all over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you like being invisible?'' I asked Vincent as the guy
walks by the car without so much as a sideways glance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to it,'' he replied, adding that the passerby must
have either steel nerves or a clear conscience. ``He's not turning
around to see if we're looking at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Wayne's World.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Frank Sector, Southeast Austin. Everything from the
river south was his to watch from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m. I rode with him
on a slow night, but there was more than enough to do.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first calls is about a missing person. A 14-year-old
hasn't come home. Her parents are worried. Vincent arrives, asks
the parents some questions. It doesn't take Sherlock Holmes to
figure out this is most likely a runaway, but fortunately for this
family, it's a slow night and Wayne Vincent can pursue it.
</P>
<P>
   He asks about the teen-ager's friends and leverages bits and
pieces of information slowly, patiently by calling one friend, then
another, then another. In about an hour, he's got a pretty good
idea of who the girl is with and where they are.
</P>
<P>
   When we get there, we've just missed the teen, but she's on her
way home, so we go there for the reunion. Before leaving the house
to allow the girl and her parents to continue a rather painful
discussion about what's bothering her, Vincent talks to her.
</P>
<P>
   The officer delivers a forceful, but gentle, lecture on the
potential consequences of running away and says that he doesn't
want to see her again. It's a story with a happy ending and a cop
will take one of those whenever one presents itself.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent joined the Austin Police Department in April 1985. I
rode with him as he was winding up the patrol cop phase of his
career. He was top scorer on the detective's examination, so he was
just waiting for a slot.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that he is popular with his colleagues. On a ramp
outside the jail, a fellow officer asks, ``How do you say `No.
1?'''
</P>
<P>
   Flashing a wide grin, Vincent replies: ``Wayne Vincent.''
</P>
<P>
   He's an easy guy to talk to and like most officers, has a
definite point of view. ``I was doing community policing before
they had a name for it. I knew the people in Montopolis and all the
store owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Before community policing was the thing, getting to know the
community he policed got Vincent in periodic jams. ``I got chewed
out for not writing enough tickets,'' he said, explaining that
given the choice between writing tickets or getting to know people,
he went with getting to know people.
</P>
<P>
   For all that you see on television about cops or what you think
you know about Southeast Austin, police work can be awfully dull.
It can change in an instant, of course, but even the crowd at the
gang banger hangout is quiet. They give looks that are both dirty
and defiant, but dirty, defiant looks don't violate the penal code.
</P>
<P>
   There's a complaint about a noisy party. And there's a DWI
arrest where we wait for what seems like forever for a wrecker.
</P>
<P>
   It's 3:25 a.m. and Vincent is in the APD station, finishing up
the paper work on the DWI arrest. He and I are the two oldest
people in the room. The people who watch your streets at night
remind me of the people who stand guard at military posts all over
the world _ they are mighty young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the department has grown fast, that's why there's so
many young people,'' Vincent said.
</P>
<P>
   When we leave the police station, I look up at the interstate
and see a rare sight: no traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That window is getting smaller and smaller,'' Vincent says
about the lull. ``What you really hate is to catch a wreck at 6.
We've got the beginning of rush hour. Get one of those, and you
know you're not getting home before 10 or 11.''
</P>
<P>
   We get lucky. The rest of the night consists of a disturbance
call that amounts to very little and we call it a night.
</P>
<P>
   Before we part, I ask if Vincent has been assigned to a
detective detail yet. No, he says, he still has to get through the
school (since completed). But he does have a wish.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to work Southeast Austin. That's what he knows. That's
what he likes.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at 445-3667 or
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
