<HEADER>
A7876 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN25-COX     06-24 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You've been served, Gov. Bush, everything's fair game
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush in The New York Times isn't
new. But a New York Times column about Gov. W.'s contemplated veto
of a measure and the tone it sets for his possible presidency is.
</P>
<P>
   It underlines how people and groups will be using W.'s actions
in Texas, in light of his presidential candidacy, to leverage
issues they hold dear.
</P>
<P>
   The column, which the Austin American-Statesman shared with its
readers, was by regular Times columnist Bob Herbert. It said
indications were the governor was about to veto a bill to allow new
methods of appointing lawyers for poor people accused of crimes.
Judges make the appointments now.
</P>
<P>
   The piece was obvious jawboning to try to keep the governor from
vetoing the bill or at least to make him pay a political price if
he did.
</P>
<P>
   Bush vetoed it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But the column served notice to W., if it was needed: Just about
anything that's happened in Texas government during the 4 1/2 years
you've been governor, and particularly in the recent 140 days of
the regular legislative session, is going to be fair game.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to pay complete attention to everything happening during
the session is like trying to fly a kite in a hurricane. There is
too much going on _ more than 5,000 bills and resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the storm has passed, the nation's news media _
including the American-Statesman _ will be analyzing in greater
detail what happened. And didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   And increasingly, Bush is going to get credit or blame in news
media all across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the lawyer-appointment bill.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 247, by Sen. Rodney Ellis (D-Houston), passed the
Texas Senate and House without dissent. It would have let county
commissioners courts set up a council to select attorneys, contract
with an outside association to appoint them or leave the power with
the judges.
</P>
<P>
   But judges, particularly in Houston, complained to the governor
that it stripped them of power.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert, noting that the bill would have required attorneys to
be appointed for poor defendants who request them within 20 days,
said, ``Most jurisdictions in the United States provide a lawyer
within 72 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But for some folks in Texas the idea of providing even minimal
constitutional protections for poor defendants is a step too far,''
Herbert wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one of those folks appears to be that beacon of
compassionate conservatism _ you've heard of him _ George W.
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the argument over need for the bill. Bush called it a
``drastic'' removal of power from judges and said ordering release
of defendants not assigned a lawyer within 20 days ``poses a danger
to public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis County District Judge Bob Perkins, a Democrat, said
judges know lawyers best and appoint them in Austin within 48
hours.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Sharlot, dean of the University of Texas Law School,
called the proposed change desirable because it would ``give both
rich and poor defendants full access to the system.''
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't be alone if you suspected it was Ellis who
contacted Herbert. But though his office helped provide information
to Herbert, the push for the column came from civil rights
attorneys in Atlanta and Houston, said Ellis' top aide, Deece
Eckstein.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen B. Bright, with the Southern Center for Human Rights in
Atlanta, confirmed he had sent to Herbert copies of articles he has
written about Texas' justice process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judges (in Texas) have been so much a part of the problem
instead of part of the solution that I said to Bob Herbert and
others, `This is something you might want to keep an eye on,'''
Bright said. ``If anyone cared anything at all about fairness, they
would certainly care about this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas is No. 1 in executions, Bright noted, ``and the fact that
the governor's a part of all that is certain to become an issue at
some point. What Texas is doing would certainly be unthinkable in a
lot of other states.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis has been in South Africa for a week, Eckstein said. But
Bush turning thumbs down on the bill that passed the Legislature
without dissent makes him culpable, Eckstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until Bush vetoed the bill, it wasn't his system,'' Eckstein
said. ``He's no longer the governor of a state that had a bad
system. Now it's his system.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
