<HEADER>
A7879 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX     06-24 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    River of dirty air mucks up one of Texas' most grand vistas
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEND NATIONAL PARK, Texas _ The Window View Trail pamphlet
hedges its claim, and for good reason. It says that at this spot,
where a vulcanian basin in the Chisos range opens up in a V, one
can drink in 35 miles of desert vista ``on a clear day.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not clear days.
</P>
<P>
   These are milky days, days in which Big Bend's grand Window is
fogged. Even on good days visibility is limited. On the worst days,
say the locals, visibility is cut to 20 miles in and around the
park.
</P>
<P>
   Which is mystifying, since no one is around, seemingly, to dirty
up the air. Unlike national parks saturated with gas-guzzling rigs,
Big Bend's 801,163 acres swallow up its many visitors. It has a
sense of asylum many national parks lack anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Towering century plants _ the agave and lechuguilla _ reach high
from parched earth, seemingly to spare their blossoms from wild
passers by. On days like this it seems they're just trying to catch
a breath.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, responding to what might have been dismissed as
rants of a few environmentalists, the Texas Natural Resources
Conservation Commission held a hearing in nearby Alpine about air
pollution. One hundred and fifty people showed up, ranging from
aging hippies to ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't satisfied with the state's response to the problem,
particularly its dismissing Big Bend's veil as ``regional haze''
and its casual pointing of a finger across the border.
</P>
<P>
   True, Mexico may be Big Bend's biggest air problem. Two
coal-fired electric plants in northern Mexico, ominously monikered
Carbon I and Carbon II, belch out uncontrolled tons of sulfur
dioxide. The plants have controls for some pollutants like grimy
particulates and nitrous oxides. But sulfur dioxide doesn't become
a problem until it's somebody else's problem. It leaves the
smokestack barely visible, only becoming a real nuisance downwind
when chemical reactions turn it to sulfate.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Bend Regional Sierra Club has mounted a postcard
campaign to urge Mexicans to get their government to respond to
this issue. It also plans a ``Hands Across the Border'' conference
to talk up mutual concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But the last thing Big Bend's neighbors want to do is focus all
their attention on Mexico. Texas has much attending to do.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 preliminary field study involving the Environmental
Protection Agency and the U.S. Parks Service raised concerns that
pollution from North Texas, particularly what's called the
``lignite belt'' of coal-burning electric plants, was contributing
to the problem, too.
</P>
<P>
   A more definitive study to trace the sources of the haze is soon
to commence. Mexico initially was ready to commit itself
wholeheartedly to the effort, but reportedly has backed out.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, focusing too heavily on Mexico can blind us to our
own responsibilities. For too long we stood by while the panoramas
of the Grand Canyon were carved away by pollution attributed
largely to two electric plants to its west and its east. After a
successful lawsuit by environmentalists, a crackdown resulted in a
90 percent reduction in sulfur dioxide at the Navajo Generating
Station near Page, Ariz. Recently the Mojave generator in Nevada
agreed to similar controls.
</P>
<P>
   Days ago I saw with my own eyes, which expected the worst, that
visibility in the Grand Canyon seems stabilized. Parks service
experts agree, but aren't satisfied. We all deserve better.
</P>
<P>
   We can do something about the soiling of our air. We need to
lean heavily on Mexico. Texas needs to follow through on
initiatives from this legislative session to clean up electric
plants and other industrial polluters.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing pollution where there's no one to pollute brings home one
truth: It's everyone's air.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
