<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7881 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMMAKER-BLANK25-COX     06-24 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMMAKER-BLANK25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blank uses documentaries as his voice By Alison Maco
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Although not all of Les Blank's documentaries
are about musicians, many writers call him an ethnomusicologist
because of the intimate manner in which he captures performers like
Dizzy Gillespie and Mance Lipscomb _ playing music and living life,
seemingly unaware of the camera's presence.
</P>
<P>
   But Blank doesn't consider himself an ethnomusicologist. ``I'm
not that orderly in the way I gather information,'' he said during
a recent phone interview from the offices of Flower Films, his San
Francisco Bay area-based production company.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there was very little order in the way he made one of
his earliest works, ``The Blues Accordin' to Lightnin' Hopkins''
(1969), which the award-winning filmmaker screened Wednesday at the
Alamo Drafthouse Cinema as part of this month's Texas Documentary
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Blank came to Austin was during the 1995 South by
Southwest Film Festival, and he told AustinAmerican-Statesman
writer Don McLeese the following story about working with Hopkins
in the late 1960s. After a long first day of shooting, during which
the mercurial Texas bluesman had played about 10 songs for the
camera, Hopkins kicked out Blank and his producer Skip Gerson,
saying he never recorded more than 10 songs for an album and he
wouldn't do it for a film.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling dejected and desperate to finish his film, Blank noticed
that Hopkins was playing cards with his friends. He engaged Hopkins
in a conversation about the game, called Pity Pair (``It's a pity
if you don't get a pair,'' said Blank). Hopkins invited him to
play. Blank promptly lost his last $60.
</P>
<P>
   ``He found this very amusing,'' said the filmmaker recently,
``and invited me to come back and try my luck the following day.''
</P>
<P>
   Blank borrowed some money and returned the next day, only to
lose again to Hopkins. However, the bluesman agreed to finish
shooting the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought we weren't so bad after all,'' Blank said with a
chuckle as he recalled the incident 30 years later.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Florida, Blank began making documentaries in the
1960s after graduating from Tulane University with an undergraduate
degree in English literature and a master's degree in theater.
Between 1967 and 1972, Blank started his production company and
worked on industrial films to make ends meet. After 1972, Blank
devoted himself full-time to independent documentary filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   One of his best-known documentaries is ``Burden of Dreams''
(1982), which chronicles the making of German filmmaker Werner
Herzog's doomed epic ``Fitzcarraldo.'' ``Burden of Dreams'' won
numerous awards for its unflinching behind-the-scenes portrait in
which Herzog reveals a passion for filmmaking that teeters on the
brink of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after ``Burden of Dreams,'' Blank made ``Gap-Toothed
Women,'' which also screened Wednesday at the Alamo. The
documentary is a lively meditation on, among other things, the myth
that gap-toothed beauties are sexier than the average woman. Blank
interviewed about 30 gap-toothed women, including '70s supermodel
Lauren Hutton. One woman, after biting into a piece of food,
describes the gap as her ``signature.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his own signature, Blank was hesitant to
categorize himself. ``I've been told I have a style. I've been told
that if someone saw one of my films, they could say who made it.''
</P>
<P>
   A respect for his subjects and a genuine appreciation for who
they are come through in Blank's documentaries. The absence of
voice-over in his films is another characteristic of his style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also reflects my lack of articulateness to be able to
define what the whole thing's about,'' Blank said of this
technique, and his explanation echoes Hopkins' definition of the
blues. Instead of explaining with words, Hopkins tells us early on
in the documentary that he lets his songs do the talking for him.
</P>
<P>
   Blank uses his own talent in a similar fashion. ``There are
certain things I can't say in words, and that's why I make movies.
I feel I've said something without having to use words to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
