<P>
   MOVIE REVIEWS FROM ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-DADDY _ Movie review of ``Big Daddy.'' It's Adam
Sandler's latest surefire moneymaker. The movie nimbly ties
together elements from his successful date movie ``The Wedding
Singer'' (boyish innocence and charm to woo the women in the
audience) and his even more successful yukfest ``The Waterboy''
(scatalogical scatting just for the boys). Throw in an itty-bitty
kid for Sandler to pal around with and you've got the makings of a
mack-daddy movie. Grade: B. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BIGDADDY _ A review of ``Big Daddy.'' Adam Sandler plays
an incorrigible slacker who must prove to his ex-girlfriend he's
mature dating material. So he adopts a 5-year-old kid. With Joey
Lauren Adams and Jon Stewart. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-HUSBAND _ Movie review of ``An Ideal Husband'' with
Rupert Everett. Grade: C+. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
15.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-VIOLIN _ Movie review of ``The Red Violin,'' unrated film
about violin that changes hands over the years. Grade: B. (Ringel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   KUBRICK-RETRO _ SXSW kept us from paying our proper respects to
Stanley Kubrick when he died March 7. We remedy that today, with an
appreciation and retrospective a few days before the release of
special editions of Kubrick's films on video and, for the first
time, on DVD, and three weeks before his last film, ``Eyes Wide
Shut,'' opens. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman). 30.
</P>
