<SLUG> BC-GAY-BAR-HONORED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GOVERNMENT HONORS HISTORIC GAY SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time, the federal government has
given landmark status to a gay and lesbian site, putting New York's
Stonewall Inn on the National Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   The bar on Christopher Street in New York's Greenwich Village
was the scene of several nights of strident protests and fighting
after police raided it in the early hours of June 28, 1969 _ nearly
30 years ago. After the arrest of patrons and employees, protesters
assembled in the street and, by throwing pennies, beer cans and
other objects, forced police to retreat back into the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Widely viewed as the birthplace of the gay civil rights
movement, the Stonewall over the years has become a focal point for
homosexual activists. New York's annual Pride Parade for gays and
lesbians routinely passes in front of the Stonewall.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Interior Department Assistant Secretary John Berry
unveiled the plaque at the bar. He compared the Stonewall uprising
with other American historical events such as the Boston Tea Party,
the battle of Gettysburg and the signing of the Declaratino of
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the heat of a summer's night here at Stonewall that led
to the creation of a new civil rights movement for America,'' Berry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, President Clinton cited the Stonewall in a
proclamation declaring June to be Gay and Lesbian Pride Month. He
called the original Stonewall protesters ``a courageous group of
citizens (who) resisted harassment and mistreatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The rioting set ``in motion a chain of events'' that led to
``the birth of the modern gay and lesbian civil rights movement,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Department spokesman Tim Ahern said that of the 68,000
listings on the national register, no others were for gay and
lesbian sites. ``The Stonewall is the first and most significant,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the Stonewall, police harassment of gay bars was
routine not only in New York but in other cities as well, according
to David Smith, communications director of the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest gay and lesbian civil rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Police often raided such establishments on the pretext of
enforcing liquor licensing or morals laws, he said. ``Establishing
the Stonewall as an historic landmark is a very important symbolic
gesture for our movement,'' he said. ``The Stonewall has enormous
cultural significance for our community.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
