<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7952 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BIGDADDY-TEX     06-24 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BIGDADDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S BAAAACK! THIS TIME, ADAM SANDLER DOES FATHERHOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not since Bill Murray has a ``Saturday Night Live'' player
claimed stardom on his own terms like Adam Sandler. In fact,
Sandler has made a career for himself by following in Murray's
footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Waterboy,'' he played a slurring crackpot who talked in
a side-of-his-mouth patter like Murray's groundskeeper in
``Caddyshack.'' But Sandler doesn't exhibit Murray's streak of
psychosis. In ``Happy Gilmore,'' Sandler displayed a hilariously
uncontrollable rage, but more often, Sandler plays a spoiled lug
whose charm comes from his saying whatever's on his mind and
following his slob impulses, as he does in ``Big Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is a lot like ``Stripes,'' in which Murray was a
smart-aleck loser who tried to use the Army as a dodge and walked
out of the service a better human being. (And the movie lost its
comic purpose once that happened.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead of joining the Army, Sandler ends up caring for
5-year-old Julian (played by twins Cole and Dylan Sprouse), who is
dropped on the doorstep of his best friend (Jon Stewart). It occurs
to Sandler, who plays the not-so-ironically named Sonny, that
having a kid around would be just the way to get his old girlfriend
(Kristy Swanson) back. Not only does that not happen, but it turns
out that having a kid around can really cramp one's style.
</P>
<P>
   Except that Julian doesn't exactly make Sonny a better guy. It's
more like Sonny makes Julian in his own image, indulging the boy's
tendency to make a meal of ketchup and training the kid to urinate
on walls in Manhattan. (It's as if he helps Julian find his inner
child.)
</P>
<P>
   One of ``Big Daddy's'' odd side effects is that the movie casts
a cold light on how intolerant the world can be of parents and kids
_ Sonny and Julian end up using the wall for a bathroom only after
some attitude-radiating jerk of a waiter won't let them use the
restaurant's facility.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Big Daddy'' deepens Sandler's streak of one-of-the-boys
tolerance; this time around, his crew includes a pair of gay
friends and a well-intentioned, accented idiot of a delivery boy
(Rob Schneider). And the biggest plea for tolerance comes from
Sonny's love of the original power balladeers: Styx. (He also gets
in a not-too-subtle shot at critics along the way.)
</P>
<P>
   He shares his love for Styx with Layla (Joey Lauren Adams), the
sister of his best buddy's girlfriend Corinne (Leslie Mann), who
looks down her nose at the underachieving Sandler. (He constantly
ridicules Mann, who put herself through medical school by working
at Hooters _ like I said, it's a one-of-the-boys comedy.)
</P>
<P>
   Adams takes a shine to both Sandler and his sorta-son, who share
as much chemistry as Sandler had with Drew Barrymore in ``The
Wedding Singer.'' It helps that Julian has the face of a tulip _
his doe-eyed look of misery will elicit the kind of ``awww'' that
will make ``Big Daddy'' a perfect date movie.
</P>
<P>
   This movie doesn't have the wild streak of my favorite Sandler
movie, ``Happy Gilmore,'' which was directed by ``Big Daddy''
director Dennis Dugan. ``Gilmore,'' Sandler's tribute to
``Caddyshack,'' features a moment that will go down in pop-culture
history, when Sandler's bad-tempered hockey hack-turned-golf pro
gets into a fistfight with Bob Barker. ``Big Daddy'' has nothing
quite that spectacular. It's like a collection of greatest hits
with one new tune thrown in _ a crowd-pleaser that's guaranteed to
be a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Sandler tones down his brazenness even more than he did for
``The Wedding Singer.'' He shows a kind of ... well, I'm not sure
maturity is the word I'm looking for, but there is an evolution
here. This movie will make a kind of history all the same _ the
moment when the title ``Big Daddy'' came to suit Adam Sandler's
status in the entertainment world.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Big Daddy''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Dennis Dugan
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Adam Sandler, Joey Lauren Adams
</P>
<P>
   Length: 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ adult language and situations and toilet humor
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
