<SLUG> BC-GORE-CALIFORNIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BACK IN CALIFORNIA, STRIKING GOLD FOR CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Vice President Al Gore is borrowing at least one
political lesson from his boss, President Clinton: If you need
quick campaign cash, head to California.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president swooped into San Francisco Wednesday night
and, after a short stump speech and a little pressing of the flesh,
pocketed more than $600,000 for his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, San Francisco was the second stop on a two-day
campaign and fund-raising swing through the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, this must be the umpteenth time that we've been
favored with a visit by the vice president to our state,'' Mayor
Willie Brown noted, with some sarcasm, in an introduction at a
$1,000-per-plate dinner at the San Francisco Hilton Hotel. ``It's
as if he's adopted this state as a part of his individual
constituency.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, it is Gore's 57th trip to California as vice
president. And of his five scheduled events, only one is not a
fund-raiser: a visit to the Los Angeles Gay and Lesbian Center.
</P>
<P>
   Past trips have largely revolved around fund-raising as well,
often for the Democratic National Committee. But Gore takes and he
gives. He also has handed out millions in federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   The largess Gore has helped secure for the state was even touted
by his aides in a 3-page memo entitled ``Working for California,''
which was distributed to reporters before Wednesday night's
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president cares about California, and he has come
through time and time again for this state,'' Gov. Gray Davis, a
fellow Democrat, said at the event.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began his speech by reminding the audience of the recession
that afflicted California before he and Clinton entered the White
House in 1993, contrasting it with the state's now flourishing
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot going on here in California that wasn't going on
seven years ago,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The response from the 600 Democratic contributors at the event
was warm. Alec Lambie, 56, of San Francisco, said he was encouraged
by Gore's talk of increased funding for education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds good,'' Lambie said. ``He'll have to get specific
about which particular programs and how he'll put them across. ...
By next fall, we should be able to see the meat of the matter and
what he's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gore is trying to add to his campaign fund
before June 30, the deadline for presidential candidates to file a
report with the Federal Elections Commission on contributions in
the previous three months. Politicians view the report as a
critical barometer for the financial health of each candidate's
campaign, even though the party nominating conventions are more
than a year away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, at the end of the filing period, you make a
final push,'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   That main fund-raising race is between Gore and the early
Republican front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush. Although Gore
was expected to raise $1.1 million Wednesday and Thursday in
California, Bush raised $2 million at a single event in Washington,
D.C., on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PACINO-STAGE-LADN     06-24 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACINO-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACINO REKINDLES HIS LOVE OF THEATER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Given his druthers, you suspect that Al Pacino
might've spent his entire career hunkered down in some overworked,
underpaying off-Broadway theater deconstructing Shakespeare and
honing his avant-garde muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's had to settle for being one of the planet's
biggest movie stars.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the entertainment gods can be cruel.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's not unusual for successful Hollywood actors of a
certain age to speak wistfully of the theater as their ``first
love,'' just as some burned-out journalists prefer to think of
themselves as frustrated novelists.
</P>
<P>
   But in Pacino's case, the years of dedicated theatrical
craftsmanship speak louder than the cliches. So do his two Tony
Awards, the first of which he earned in 1969 for his performance as
a drug addict in ``Does a Tiger Wear a Necktie?'' the second for
playing a nondescript nobody caught up in the turmoil of the
Vietnam War in a 1977 revival of ``The Basic Training of Pavlo
Hummel.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, when he wasn't making movies, Pacino has
returned to live theater, tackling everything from the title role
in ``Richard III'' (which he also filmed) to Oscar Wilde's
``Salome'' and a rave-inducing 1982 revival of David Mamet's
``American Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   Those occasions have allowed the Oscar-winning actor to
reconnect with the challenges of stepping out in front of a live
audience, minus the safety net that movies provide in the form of
skillful cinematographers and sympathetic editors.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino will walk the tightrope again this summer at the Mark
Taper Forum, where he'll be directing and starring in Eugene
O'Neill's ``Hughie,'' a brief, little-known two-character drama by
the author of ``Long Day's Journey Into Night'' and ``The Iceman
Cometh.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Pacino, 59, spoke of the occupational
hazards of stage acting with evident satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the feeling of the journey, going out there and you
can't turn back,'' he said. ``Generally, you really are, in movies,
just trying to get by, trying to live within the wires.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the millions who've seen his films, only a relative
handful of people have witnessed Pacino's stage work. By all
accounts, the Method-trained actor brings the same compacted
intensity to a 1,200-seat house that he does to his big-screen
portrayals of manic low lifes (``Dog Day Afternoon''), calculating
Cosa Nostra dons (``The Godfather'' series) and iconoclastic cops
(``Serpico,'' ``Heat'').
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hughie,'' Pacino plays Erie Smith, a Times Sqaure hustler,
gambler and horseplayer who, in the wee morning hours, bends the
ear of a night clerk (Paul Benedict) at the run-down Manhattan
hotel where Erie lives. Erie has just come off a five-day alcohol
binge occasioned by the funeral of Hughie, the previous night
clerk, who for years had been a willing co-conspirator in Erie's
chronic self-delusions.
</P>
<P>
   For Pacino, ``Hughie'' is practically an extended monologue,
during which the bored night clerk's thoughts wander hither and
yon, according to stage notes supplied by O'Neill that are never
spoken aloud.
</P>
<P>
   Do O'Neill's italicized prompts actually help, or are they
distracting?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know, you try not to read those things,'' Pacino
says. ``Usually you'll get them later as you get into rehearsal.
But it gives you a general idea of a sense of what was going on
with O'Neill at the time and what he was thinking about. That's
what intrigued me, really, how to communicate that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mentioned before (that) this is the same author who wrote
`The Hairy Ape' and wrote `Strange Interlude.' (`Hughie') is this
kind of expressionism, which made me think it's possible to
actually voice the hotel clerk's ruminations. And it has to balance
the play, too. Where there is the touch of irony or humor, I think
it comes through a little more, in that juxtaposition.''
</P>
<P>
   To communicate the night clerk's subliminal ruminations, Pacino
briefly thought of adding another person on stage to read O'Neill's
editorial asides. Then, after trying out different approaches, he
came up with another idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to set it up in such a way that there's a different
tone in his voice when he's speaking (his thoughts),'' Pacino
explains. ``We spent a lot of time trying to find the right kinds
of sounds and present something that would give us the sense that
he's (thinking out loud).''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has been down this road before _ he first did
``Hughie'' in 1996 at the Long Wharf Theatre in New Haven, Conn. _
Pacino speaks of the L.A. revival as if he were wrestling with a
freshly minted drama instead of returning to an obscure,
70-year-old piece that O'Neill himself never intended to be
produced.
</P>
<P>
   In conversation, Pacino gives you the idea that his background
as a New York actor, trained by the venerable Lee Strasberg, is
never far from his mind when he sets about constructing a
character. ``I just read a Chekhov story the other day ...'' he'll
begin an anecdote, then digress into a point-by-point reminiscence
of a show he saw at a downtown New York theater 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Later, responding to a question about stage-acting methodology,
he launches into a quietly impassioned soliloquy about ``finding a
way to discover this play'' and the ``whole sense of adventure''
that comes from making dramatic sense of a difficult text.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always taken me a little longer to come to something,''
he says, ``and I'm happy that it does. And with Shakespeare, I'm
not ready to start until the run's over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, that's what I was saying in `Richard III' (his 1996
`Looking for Richard,' a documentary-style film about his staging
of the Shakespeare play). You're not going to get the play, you're
going to get pieces of it. But as you learn it, you're forced to
digest it, and it's with you in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   That aforementioned ``sense of adventure'' is why Pacino prefers
what he calls the ``fluidity'' of live performance vs. the
``fragmentation'' of film. When Hollywood came knocking 30 years
ago, ``It was suddenly a life that I wasn't prepared for,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to feel that in order to do a movie, one has to
have an appetite, because there's so much that goes into it. For
me, (film acting) is an exhausting experience _ not just the acting
itself (but) the being uprooted from where you are and sitting
seven or eight hours in a camper. As Orson Welles said, that's
really what you are paid for.''
</P>
<P>
   While the movies have made his fortune, Pacino still harkens
back to a memory of seeing a performance of Anton Chekhov's ``The
Seagull'' that he says changed his life. At the time he was ``just
a kid from the South Bronx,'' and that experience ``was the moment
that changed me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the line `People don't do things like this' at the
end of the play,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never heard anything like that. It was a whole (new)
world, like my whole life I was walking around and I had never
looked up at the sky _ and looking at that was like looking at the
sky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There I was, this kid sitting up in the third balcony. It's
like this ticket fell out of heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   And while great acting parts rarely drop from the sky _ either
in film or in theater _ Pacino seems content, for now, to let the
career chips fall where they may.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, I'm sort of trying to go with the flow. And I'm
happy in the sense that I don't know what the next thing is I'm
going to do. So maybe I can listen to these passions that are
there. 'Cause you don't _ for the most part.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FACTBOX &UR;  &QL; 
What: &LR;  ``Hughie.'' &UR;  &QL; 
Where: &LR;  Mark Taper Forum, Music Center of Los Angeles County, 135
N. Grand Ave. &UR;  &QL; 
When: &LR;  Opens Sunday. Performances 8 p.m. Tuesdays through Fridays.
2:30 and 7:30 p.m. Saturdays, 2:30 and 7:30 p.m. Sundays; through
July 25. &UR;  &QL; 
Tickets: &LR;  $25 to $40. Call (213) 628-2772. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
