<HEADLINE>
FILM GETS LOST IN SEARCH FOR SEXUALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably no one makes more of those ``What does he think he's
doing?'' movies than writer/director Mike Figgis. He's out to
exhibit the mysteries of sex in a style that's one part film noir,
one part Calvin Klein commercial and one part Enya video. In his
newest film, the convoluted and pretentious puzzle ``The Loss of
Sexual Innocence,'' those who don't get up and walk out may be too
hypnotized by the imagery. And you can tell that all this tony,
film-school philosophizing means something to Figgis _ he's not
just showing off.
</P>
<P>
   This journey of self-discovery by lead character Nic (Julian
Sands) screams art film. Nic is trying to make sense of sex
throughout his entire life. As a teen, he's played by Jonathan
Rhys-Meyers, whose sculpted nose and mouth bear no resemblance to
Sands _ it's almost as if he's imagining himself as a
different-looking person when he was younger. But so much of this
adult fairy tale is annoying that stopping to nitpick over any one
point feels like a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Figgis can generate excitement. The movie jumps back and
forth between Nic's determination to get back to Africa, where he's
from, to an Adam-and-Eve story in which Adam is black and Eve is
white. (His ``first couple'' are so beautiful it's like Adam and
Eve themselves have answered some cosmic casting call.) Figgis'
reflex to change people's perceptions is touching, as is one of
Figgis' subplots, about twins separated at birth. It has so much
resonance that it may make you think about how horrible ``The
Parent Trap'' would be if twins were ``really'' separated at birth.
This section alone demands that the movie be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual Innocence'' is more like Figgis collected ideas that
wouldn't stand up as a movie on their own and pressed them into a
kind of film scrapbook. It could have used a lot more thought,
because his instincts veer more toward the hollow panache of a
Levi's ad when he doesn't shape them into a coherent story. But
there are bits, and bits of bits, that you won't soon forget _ if
you don't find the rest of the movie too insufferable.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Mike Figgis
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Julian Sands, Saffron Burroughs
</P>
<P>
   Length: 101 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rating: R _ nudity, adult language and sexuality
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
