<SLUG> BC-FILM-IDEALHUSBAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HUSBAND' IS IDEAL TREATMENT OF A WILDE IDEA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there a performer around who looks like he loves himself more
than Rupert Everett? Craig Kilborn comes close, but Everett's
slim-lipped hauteur makes him look as if he's blowing kisses to
himself. (That's what was so much fun about watching him in ``My
Best Friend's Wedding'' _ when he launches into ``I Say a Little
Prayer,'' it's like he's serenading himself.)
</P>
<P>
   And his slam-bang affair with, well, Rupert, gives a welcome
sizzle to ``An Ideal Husband,'' which has a glorious undercurrent
of intrigue. And right in the middle of it, there's Everett as Lord
Goring, shaving years off his age and loving every second of his
unabashed hedonism. Even in a waistcoat, his verve breaks through.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Ideal Husband'' is a handsomely mounted adaptation of
playwright Oscar Wilde's look at the intrigues of longing. Instead
of looking like a big-screen antique catalog, where you'd love
buying the rooms but you can't imagine anybody living in them,
``Husband'' is stocked with people you can relate to. Especially
Julianne Moore's roguish Mrs. Cheveley: As she prowls the rooms,
her smirk is initially entrancing, until it's evident just how
lowdown she can be.
</P>
<P>
   It's a marvel of a performance _ her opportunism is simply an
accessory to her, like pearls for the evening. Her tony cool is so
well-practiced that she makes Minnie Driver (who plays Mabel) come
off as a jumpy suburbanite in a school play.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cheveley inflicts her deviousness on the hapless Sir
Robert, played by Jeremy Northam. Northam shows restrained pain
beautifully; his despair is glimpsed through his thin veneer of
ice. His reserve comes from a fear of being found out. He's being
blackmailed by Mrs. Cheveley, and his past threatens his marriage
to Lady Chiltern (Cate Blanchett), whose idealism is nevertheless a
little tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   In this production, knowingness is key, and Goring and Cheveley
seem to have been hatched in the same bird's-eye-view nest, proudly
sidling up to each other in a corner and slicing up magnificent
dish about every loser in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Goring is capable of decency _ his feelings about
his friend Sir Robert make him dangerously close to human. As
Goring works to rouse himself from the paradise of his self-regard
and pursuit of women long enough to help his friend, ``Husband''
drizzles a glaze of warmth over its intricate, cold machinery. But
not too much to diminish its wicked, intelligent fun.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``An Ideal Husband''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Oliver Parker
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Rupert Everett, Julianne Moore, Jeremy Northam
</P>
<P>
   Length: 96 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ adult language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
