<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE MOVIES OUT OF REACH _ FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is there any way to buy the airline version of a film, which
has the profanity and sex edited out?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.M., Richland Hills, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: At present, none of the major film studios is selling
``airline'' or ``family edited'' versions of its films for video
release.
</P>
<P>
   The Dove Foundation and the Video Software Retailers Association
have called on studios to release the versions of R-rated films
that are shown on airlines, which are often edited to remove
profanity, violence or sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Dove recommends films by awarding ``family approved'' and
``family edited'' seals that can be displayed by video retailers.
So far, no ``edited'' seals have been issued because studios aren't
selling these versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is not giving the public what they want,'' said Dave
Lukens, Dove's development director. ``We think Hollywood would be
surprised by the choices the public would make if tamer versions
were also available.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write to Dove Foundation, 4521 S.E.
Broadmoor, Grand Rapids, MI 49512, or visit the Web site
www.dove.org.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Jimmy, the blond-headed guy in ``Sons of Thunder,'' the
son of Chuck Norris?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.R., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Norris has two sons in their 30s, Eric and Mike Norris, but
neither plays Trent on ``Sons of Thunder'' or ``Walker, Texas
Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Wlcek, 35, portrays the character and is no relation to
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   Eric and Mike Norris have worked with their father on ``Walker,
Texas Ranger.'' Eric has directed an episode, and Mike has appeared
in small roles. Both brothers perform as actors and stuntmen.
</P>
<P>
   You can write to any cast member of ``Walker'' or ``Thunder'' in
care of CBS Entertainment, 13801 Diplomat Drive, Farmers Branch
75234.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Dick Cavett?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.N., Granbury, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Cavett in care of the William Morris Agency, 1325
Avenue of the Americas, New York, NY 10019.
</P>
<P>
   Cavett, 62, will be the main host for a new cable channel
premiering this year. Fanfare: The Classical Music Channel was
created by Washington PBS station WETA and is scheduled to launch
on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
