<HEADLINE>
INKSTER, KUEHNE ARRIVE AT CHAMPIONSHIP FROM DIFFERENT ROUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ They are nearly a generation apart and at
different points in their playing careers, but US Women's Open
champion Juli Inkster and Kelli Kuehne understand each other quite
well as they begin the LPGA Championship at Dupont CC.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, who has two daughters, tries to balance her time
between golf and family, and frequently has older daughter Hayley
with her on tour while golf pro husband Brian is at home to watch
over younger daughter Cori. Keuhne, who is a two-time US Women's
Amateur champion and struggled through her first season on the
tour, is engaged to be married next year and admires the way
Inkster handles her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is not the only thing I want in life,'' said Kuehne,
whose breakthrough victory came last month in the LPGA Corning
Classic in Corning, N.Y. ``I want to have my cake and eat it too. I
want to one day be the best golfer in the world and be a wife and
mother. (Inkster) has two girls that are crazy about her, and she
is a great mother too. She does a great job with balancing other
things with golf, because golf is such a difficult game.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kuehne finished third in the US Women's Open at Old
Waverly GC in West Point, Miss., Inkster went up to her to offer
encouragement. ``I think she will be a very good player out here,''
said Inkster. She works hard at her game. She wants to be good. She
wants to be one of the best players out here. She has a lot of
spunk and you can't teach that. You just have to have it. You have
to have the determination to want to play well, and she has that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though she wasn't exempt, she was out there practicing,
practicing, practicing even when she wasn't in a tournanment. It's
a big jump from college golf to professional golf. She can't
overpower the golf courses and get away with it. She has to have
all of her aspects of her game working, and she has improved on all
aspects. Everybody is on their own page, and I just think it took
her a little longer. Now she knows she can win out here, I think
she will kind of springboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, who has won three times this year and 20 times in a
career that began in 1983, is still on an emotional high after
winning the Open. ``It's been great,'' she said. ``It's been a lot
of fun. It's just a huge tournament and to win the Open is just
kind of like the icing on the cake as far as my career. I'm still
walking around with butterflies in my stomach. I still came back
last week and finished third without practice the week before.''
</P>
<P>
   The family comes first, but winning the Grand Slam would be a
sizable bonus. ``I'm going to have to have another great week to do
it,'' she said. ``It's been a little hectic in my lifestyle and I
just have to focus on my golf game. I think I can do it. I think I
have as good a chance as anybody else out there right now. It's
just the pressure you put on yourself, the pressure that the media
puts on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne, who attended the University of Texas and saw brother
Hank win the US Amateur to become the first brother/sister
combination to win the women's and the men's amateur championships,
said winning should breed winning. ``I wouldn't say it was a
relief,'' she said. I would just say it happened a lot sooner than
I thought it would.''
</P>
<P>
   She told her caddie in the US Open qualifier just before Corning
that she thought she was on the verge of winning. ``I played
well,'' she said. ``It was a confidence booster, and I played well.
It was kind of weird. I just wasn't thinking mechanically about my
golf swing. I was just out there doing it and it was all going
great for me. As I said, it happened a lot sooner than I thought it
would.''
</P>
<P>
   The expectations were too high a year ago, and she lost her
exempt status. ``Last year was one of the hardest things for me,''
she said. ``I expected to win right off the bat. I expected to have
a year like Se Ri Pak had (when she won two majors) and that comes
along every 20 years. It was a lot harder because I put a lot of
pressure on myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most frustrating time of my life. It just seemed
like everything was going against me. I'd hit down the fairway and
it would catch a branch and go out of bounds. Right now if I hit a
ball down the middle of the fairway the tree would make it go 2
yards farther. The tides have turned and things are going well.
Everything that could have gone wrong went wrong last year. It was
just a very difficult year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
