<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-24 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENDERING UNTO CAESAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that we're all properly enthralled with cut-rate shopping on
the Internet, along comes a chorus of bureaucrats and scholars to
bring us the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those Internet bargains are made possible by the absence
of old-fashioned sales taxes. But this week in Virginia, a band of
bigwigs from government and Internet industries began trying to
work out ways to close this lovely loophole before it grows to the
diameter of the Lincoln Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Advisory Commission on Internet Commerce was set up by
Congress eight months ago, but there's nothing new about
governments railing against out-of-state merchants who don't pay
local taxes. Ever hear of mail-order? The exact same issue arises.
How does a state or city levy sales tax on a retailer doing
business in another state or city?
</P>
<P>
   In general they don't, thanks to a 1992 Supreme Court ruling
that had nothing to do with the Internet. The court held that a
business must have a physical presence in a state before it can be
taxed there. In law, the concept is called ``nexus.'' Whether you
order by mail, phone or the Internet, if the retailer is outside of
Massachusetts and doesn't have a branch office here, he's beyond
the taxman's grip.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, buyers are the ones who really pay sales taxes. If
you order a product from out of state, you're supposed to pay your
state's sales tax. But the only enforcement mechanism is a guilty
conscience. Judging by how few of us pay, none of us is losing any
sleep.)
</P>
<P>
   So it's nexus, not networks, the panel will argue about. Ralph
Tabor, associate legislative director for the National Association
of Counties, hopes Congress will pass a law that sets aside the
Supreme Court's view of the matter. He wants Congress to declare
that a nexus exists whenever a transaction occurs. Sellers would
have to collect the sales tax that applies in the buyer's state,
county or city. Tabor says there's not much chance of such a law
passing anytime soon. But something like it will have to happen
before Internet sales can be taxed in an orderly way.
</P>
<P>
   Say you waved a magic wand and installed a reasonable Internet
sales tax system. How much money would it raise for local
governments? Less than you might think. A fascinating new report
from the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young says that if every sales tax
loophole had been closed last year, the Internet would have
generated a measly $170 million in extra state and local revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Measly? It is when you divide it up among the 6,000 government
bodies that charge such taxes _ or compare it to the $155 billion
these agencies managed to collect last year.
</P>
<P>
   In a forthcoming paper, Jonathan Zittrain, lecturer at Harvard
Law School's Berkman Center for Internet and Society, and
University of Chicago economist Austan Goolsbee, figure lost taxes
at $430 million tops, and probably closer to $210 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly at the moment, it's chicken feed,'' says Zittrain.
But he notes that states are really worried about what will happen
in five or 10 years if a substantial amount of the nation's
retailing goes virtual. The National Association of Counties says
local governments could lose up to $50 billion in tax revenues by
2005. Zittrain isn't looking out that far, but he reckons on $3.5
billion in vanishing taxes by 2003, still a relatively small chunk
of change, but real money at last.
</P>
<P>
   That's why government bodies are determined to bring taxation to
Internet commerce, to the consternation and horror of Internet
mavens who have long argued that the Web is a new universe of
commerce, unfettered by the traditional constraints of
``meatspace.''
</P>
<P>
   Dream on. Internet commerce will be far easier to tax than any
other kind. All transactions are going through computers, remember?
They're rather good at keeping track of who owes what to Caesar.
Once federal, state and local regulators get their acts together,
they'll learn to love Internet commerce, and the needed nexus
reforms will also force phone and mail-order firms to start
collecting taxes. Far from liberating us from taxation, the
Internet will likely make it harder to evade taxes than ever
before, even for those who've never plugged in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
