<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whales, calving glaciers just the tip of Alaska cruise iceberg
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 27.
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESURRECTION BAY, Alaska _ At one point the boat seemed
surrounded by killer whales, and we all ran from side to side to
see their tall, black dorsal fins piercing the surface.
</P>
<P>
   We were on an Alaska day cruise through green bays ringed by
sharply cut brown mountains. And I was wanting whales.
</P>
<P>
   When the orcas came, they arrived gloriously in a group of four,
first seen in the distance, then cresting right by the boat. We
could see their shiny, leathery backs wheeling across the top of
the water. No matter how often they're on TV, seeing killer whales
firsthand will start the heart thumping.
</P>
<P>
   If you do only one thing in Alaska, a Kenai Fjords Tours cruise
of the Resurrection Bay area will fill your memory with mental
snapshots of glaciers, sea otters, bald eagles, mountain goats and
possibly even a giant humpback whale.
</P>
<P>
   As we pulled out of the harbor in the small port city of Seward,
sea otters were performing their morning grooming, floating on
their backs, keeping their heads and webbed feet above the icy
water.
</P>
<P>
   We were on the Alaskan Explorer, a 95-foot ship with outdoor as
well as indoor seating. The captain provided color commentary as a
Ranger Rick-type fellow, clad completely in forest green, brought
around items such as animal skins.
</P>
<P>
   At times, things happened so quickly. Four porpoises leaped from
the sea in formation and were gone in a flash. I fumbled trying to
hit the camera shutter, missing the moment completely.
</P>
<P>
   But stunning landscapes always enveloped us. We passed a steeply
sloped island, pristine and uninhabited. The tall, craggy walls
held countless seabirds _ eagles, puffins, cormorants _ all
crisscrossing in flight, bringing to mind the chaos of bats in a
belfry.
</P>
<P>
   On another mountain, a white mountain goat sat alone on an
outcropping so narrow the animal could hardly turn around. He
worked a chaw of grass with such nonchalance, you expected he would
soon spit out a line of juice. Or blow a bubble.
</P>
<P>
   Moving on, we saw huge Steller sea lions hauling themselves out
of the water onto rocks, where they clustered together. They seemed
to either rest quietly or bark madly at each other. A large male
can weigh a ton. When one male approached a female, they yelped at
each other like Ralph and Alice Kramden on ``The Honeymooners.''
You couldn't tell if they were fighting or flirting.
</P>
<P>
   It is a gifted tour guide who, while leading a captive audience
across a scene of natural beauty, knows when to be silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just stop here and listen to the glacier,'' said the
captain, pulling up to the Holegate Glacier. The mammoth hunk of
ice hung off the land, rising more than 300 feet above sea level.
It held mysterious blue highlights.
</P>
<P>
   The glacier loomed in the amphitheater-shaped bay that it has
created over time, presenting an awesome display of nature's power.
Our boat sat quietly as sheets of ice ``calved'' off the face of
the glacier into the water, sounding like thunder and gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   We stopped for lunch at Fox Island, and were greeted by whale
bones on the shore. Over a meal of grilled salmon the passengers
came to know one other. Some walked along the slate rocks of the
shoreline, trying to find heart-shaped stones and beat the
stone-skipping record of nine water jumps.
</P>
<P>
   This part of Alaska, by the Aialik Peninsula in the southern
part of the state, offers abundant natural wonders. Homeowners can
have a 3,000-foot mountain in their back yard. Bald eagles perch
atop telephone poles. The mountains, so huge and so near, climb
into the clouds and are veined with snow. They loom beside the main
highway winding south to the bay. Here, nature is the big
developer. And a visit, even for a day, allows you to experience
Alaska's deep bond with the natural world.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling stays long after.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Kenai Fjords Tours offers six cruise options,
from the three-hour Resurrection Bay Wildlife Cruise ($54 adults,
$27 children under 12) to a 9 1/2-hour Northwestern Fjord Cruise
($139 adults, $69 children under 12). The 7 1/2-hour package, which
includes the grilled salmon lunch on Fox Island, is $115 adults,
$57 children. It affords a better chance of seeing whales than some
of the shorter cruises. The $10 binocular rental is worth it. In
general, tours run from from March to November. But weather can be
a factor in the longer rides, which launch later in the year. And
from Oct. 1 through Nov. 3, a four-hour tour of the bay is offered,
including a trip to the Alaska Sea Life Center. Call
1-800-478-8068.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Schneider writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
