<HEADER>
A7985 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MAPS1STTAKE27-     06-24 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAPS1STTAKE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unfolding America: From paper to computers, a century of maps
has gotten us there
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 27.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before she wrote her famous etiquette book, Emily Post
was a bit of an adventurer. In 1916, she decided to brave the
Lincoln Highway, the first auto road that stretched from coast to
coast. Stopping at a Manhattan book store for some maps, she ran
into an acquaintance who had made the journey. Her advice: Don't
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get beyond the Mississippi, the roads are trails of
mud and sand,'' she warned. The Lincoln Highway might look neat and
navigable on paper, but the map was an illusion, the road an
imaginary line like the Equator.
</P>
<P>
   Today that line is Interstate 80 _ a 70-mph asphalt fact. You
can take it from the Hudson River to San Francisco Bay without so
much as peeking at Rand McNally.
</P>
<P>
   As millions of Americans hit the highways this summer, the last
of the automobile century, it's hard to appreciate how exciting
road maps once must have seemed. We take them for granted these
days, as we take for granted that highways will be paved, gas pumps
plentiful and rest stops mercifully located. But there was a time
when the humble map wasn't so routine, when that ink-webbed paper
unfolded with a tingle of romance and possibility, when the open
road really was, as William Least Heat Moon put it in ``Blue
Highways,'' ``a beckoning, a strangeness, a place where a man can
lose himself.''
</P>
<P>
   You could lose yourself, all right.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of this century, thousands of people had local
bicycle maps but no one had automobile road maps as we know them.
With only 8,000 cars registered in the entire United States, who
needed such a thing?
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't use maps the way we do. If they had to go any
distance, they took trains,'' says Jim Akerman, a cartographic
historian at the Newberry Library in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Akerman, 42, has been studying maps since he was a kid
navigating from the back seat on family vacations. (He loved Rock
City. ```See seven states' _ that's a very cartographic
attraction.'') While he lost his boyhood stash of maps when his
parents tossed them during a move to Atlanta, he more than
compensated by earning a Ph.D. and becoming director of the
Newberry's Hermon Dunlap Smith Center for the History of
Cartography, a repository of 70,000 rare maps. They're stored in a
separate building, in dark, chilly stacks where you half expect to
see a tagged toe sticking out. It's the Fort Knox of road maps.
</P>
<P>
   The first ones didn't look a thing like the ones you stuff in
the glove compartment now. Instead of displaying the highway
network, early road maps followed strip itineraries, with
directions keyed to odometer readings and pictures of landmarks.
The information was provided by ``pathfinders,'' camera-toting
motor enthusiasts hired by mapmakers and highway promoters to do
reconnaissance. Akerman finds an example of their work in the
stacks, the Automobile Blue Book of 1920 _ it looks more like a
hymnal than a map.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it took an element of faith to drive American roads
before the '20s. Surfaces were unpaved, and cars were so frail that
``automobilists,'' as they were called, were often advised to strap
chains on their tires to climb hills. One Georgia map warned
ominously that the road north of Dahlonega was ``not passable after
rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Government spent little money on highway construction in the
early years, so private road associations organized to improve
driving conditions and promote particular routes in the interest of
business. Soon the nation was crisscrossed with named highways like
the Lincoln and the Dixie, the first Great Lakes-to-Florida route.
You can still find outcroppings of the era; Atlanta's Bankhead
Highway, for instance, was part of a national road that ran from
Washington to San Diego. But most of the old names are as extinct
as a Stutz Bearcat. Few Georgians would remember the Woodpecker
Route that burrowed through the pine lands from Augusta to
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Named highways could be confusing. In some cities, so many road
logos were tacked to the same post that it looked like a telephone
poll on election day. A Rand McNally draftsman came up with the
idea of numbering the routes, and the federal government adopted
the system in 1926. Thus the Dixie Highway became U.S. 41 and the
Lincoln Highway became U.S. 60. Perhaps the only highway that grew
more renowned as a number was the Old National Trails Road, which
became part of Route 66.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, for an exhibition, Akerman was able to borrow
the map that Bobby Troup used in 1946 when he wrote ``Get Your
Kicks on Route 66'' during a drive from Chicago to Los Angeles.
Troup circled the jaunty succession of towns he ticked off in the
lyrics: ``Now you go through St. Looey, Joplin, Missouri, Oklahoma
City looks mighty pretty ... '' For a scholar who loves the
American road, artifacts don't get any sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   There's another class of map buffs who don't care so much about
cartographic history. They're in it for the pretty pictures.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, road map collecting has emerged as a small
but vigorous hobby, with its own association, national convention,
and newsletters and chat rooms. The maps that collectors prize
above all are the lavishly illustrated folding maps that oil
companies handed out by the millions, starting around 1913.
</P>
<P>
   Oil company maps present an idyllic world of colorized scenery,
speeding roadsters and crisply uniformed attendants checking under
the hood as they pump 29-cents-a-gallon Kant-Nock gasoline. The
motorists, who never sweat despite the lack of air conditioning,
look like Arrow shirt models out for a spin. It's potent nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this is time travel,'' says Ronnie Futch, a
48-year-old librarian at Georgia State University, as he shows off
his collection of 300 vintage maps. Futch has been crazy about
petroliana since he was a youngster pumping gas at Exxon. He's
always looking for maps put out by obscure regional companies like
Reed Oil, an Atlanta firm of the '20s that marketed a gasoline
called Blue Streak, so named because it was tinted blue.
</P>
<P>
   When Futch started collecting almost 20 years ago, people asked
him why he was spending good money on trash. Back then, he paid
trash prices, buying maps for as little as 50 cents apiece. Now he
pays $10 or more for a single Pennzoil or Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing. Peter Sidlow, a retired real estate developer in
Las Vegas, recently got $400 for a 1924 Shell that was part of his
5,000-map collection. He'll pay up to $250 _ but not for anything
from the last quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new maps are disposable,'' he says. ``Wrapping paper.''
</P>
<P>
   The free map era that collectors cherish ended abruptly. In
1972, petroleum companies distributed a record 250 million maps.
After the Arab oil embargo rear-ended the industry in 1973, they
stopped giving them away.
</P>
<P>
   Yet mapmakers believe more of their handiwork is in circulation
today than ever. State tourism bureaus hand out maps by the bushel.
The American Automobile Association publishes record millions every
year. Specialty publishers like DeLorme, a Maine company that
produces topographical road atlases, have flourished. And recent
times have brought the new technology of computer software mapping
and vehicle navigation systems.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
