</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAPS2NDTAKE27-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: vehicle navigation systems.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, one company has remained the largest commercial
map publisher in the world: Rand McNally.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1856 as a printer of railroad tickets, Rand McNally
has been intimately involved in auto mapping since 1904. (Very
intimately; in 1909, Andrew McNally II devoted his honeymoon to
pathfinding for a Chicago-to-Milwaukee guide.) This year, the
company is celebrating the 75th anniversary of its first U.S. road
atlas. With more than 15 million copies sold a year, the annually
updated atlas easily ranks as the nation's most popular
cartographic product.
</P>
<P>
   Rand McNally's headquarters looks exactly like it ought to.
Located in the leafy Chicago suburb of Skokie, the company occupies
a two-story brick-and-limestone complex that resembles an
Eisenhower-era high school, down to the globes visible through the
windows. Inside, a maze of hallways is marked with street signs so
new employees can find their way around. At the end of North
Avenue, just past Central, you'll find Michael W. Dobson, chief
cartographer.
</P>
<P>
   Dobson, a white-bearded former professor of 53, is Rand
McNally's resident geographical philosopher. He's as likely to
mention Lewis Carroll as the highway department when he discusses
the art of rendering ``spatial diversity'' on paper.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, mapmaking has changed radically. Artists used to
sit at tables etching with styluses, a laborious engraving process
called scribing that would require 60 to 100 films for a solitary
map. The task got easier in 1992 when the process went digital. Now
most Rand McNally maps are produced from a master database, with
graphic artists guiding mouses in front of computer screens. The
highway matrix may not be altering as drastically as it did in
Emily Post's day, but there's always a new bypass or bridge to add
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think long and hard about what we put on a map,'' Dobson
says. ``We convene committees and hold focus groups _ we've even
been known to interview travelers at rest stops. Because whenever
we put something on a map, it means that something else will be
left off. It's relative. If you're a small town in Montana, you'll
probably make it. If you're a small town in Pennsylvania, you might
not.''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugs. ``Geography isn't fair.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one thing that Rand McNally would never put on a map:
something that isn't there. Mapmakers have been known to invent
places so they can prove the originality of their work in copyright
infringement cases. Dobson once met a cartographer in Florida who
admitted that he had been working on a city map while he was
watching ``The Sound of Music'' on TV. Bingo, Clearwater had a new
thoroughfare _ Von Trapp Street.
</P>
<P>
   As if getting lost wasn't easy enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Road Map Collectors of America, P.O. Box 22624,
Oklahoma City, OK 73123. The club's Web site (www.roadmaps.org)
offers history, pricing info and links to other sites celebrating
roadside Americana.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
<P>
   ``WHENEVER WE PUT SOMETHING ON A MAP, IT MEANS THAT SOMETHING
ELSE WILL BE LEFT OFF. IT'S RELATIVE. IF YOU'RE A SMALL TOWN IN
MONTANA, YOU'LL PROBABLY MAKE IT. IF YOU'RE A SMALL TOWN IN
PENNSYLVANIA, YOU MIGHT NOT. GEOGRAPHY ISN'T FAIR.'' Michael w.
Dobson, Chief Cartographer, Rand McNally
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
