<SLUG> BC-FIGHTING-IRISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IRISH TIES ARE COLLIDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Talk about the fighting Irish. Or at least, the
squabbling.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the University of Massachusetts announced it would
help fertilize the seeds of peace with a conference on economic
development in Northern Ireland, to be held in Derry.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College, which prides itself on being the uber-Irish of
Boston institutions, quickly began planning its own conference on
the same topic the very same week, in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as two delegations of Massachusetts officials and
university types descend on Northern Ireland, the close quarters
are producing some sniping and suspicion. BC officials are grousing
that UMass is trying to upstage them in their role as chief link
between Ireland and the largest Irish community outside the Emerald
Isle. And UMass, with South Boston's own William M. Bulger at the
helm, is flaunting enough Irish political connections to suggest
that the once-backwater State U just might prove a fair rival.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this being Boston, it's not quite as clear as two
sides. Many of the UMass delegation are BC grads _ Bulger, a Triple
Eagle, no less _ BC High, BC, BC Law. His spokesman and the
spokesman for BC President William P. Leahy are cousins. All this
only adds more grudge to the match.
</P>
<P>
   Both are trying to establish their Irish bonafides, trotting out
press releases with the names of political celebrities who will
appear at their conferences, the details of events, and affiliation
agreements signed with various Irish entities. Observers back home,
meanwhile, are bewildered that a people once so ashamed of their
heritage would now be competing to show it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly being Irish in Boston has become the in thing; it's
suddenly fashionable,'' said Thomas O'Connor, a professor of
history at BC. ``Fifteen or 20 years ago, if some university said
we want to hire someone in Irish studies, people would have looked
at you twice. The Irish people were loath to be characterized as
Irish _ there was something second-class citizen about it. The
connection with Ireland is now something that enhances your
reputation. `No Irish need apply' is no longer relevant. Now it's
`Only Irish need apply.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Both conferences hold out the same goal: to facilitate economic
growth and job creation in Ireland and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Both conferences feature Governor Paul Cellucci (BC, BC Law), in
Europe on a trade mission, as well as Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern. House Speaker Thomas Finneran (BC Law) was also expected to
drop by both events.
</P>
<P>
   But UMass also scored visits from Protestant Leader David
Trimble and Ireland's Secretary of State Mo Mowlam, as well as
Social Democratic party leader John Hume, who has been a close
friend of Bulger's since the two met 11 years ago at the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta, when another Massachusetts
politician who doesn't happen to be Irish was nominated as his
party's candidate for president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The current US president, too, sent a delegate to Bulger's
conference. And UMass drummed up enough attention that British
Prime Minister Tony Blair was said to be ``50-50'' on attending
until just a few weeks ago, when he, too, decided to send a
representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Bulger's political connections, it's hard for us to
compete,'' said Jack Dunn, a cousin of Bulger spokesman Robert
Connolly, and a close friend of Bulger's youngest son from their
days at BC High. ``They could really move in on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps only Bulger, the former State Senate president, could
make BC insecure in its Irishness, which is, after all, fairly well
established. BC's Irish Institute has long run seminars for Irish
entrepreneurs and political leaders at the Chestnut Hill campus;
its academic program in Irish studies is recognized as the best in
the nation. This winter, BC purchased a house in St. Stephen's
Square in Dublin, and some professors say they worry the university
has gone a little overboard in emphasizing its Irish Jesuit roots.
</P>
<P>
   But there is apparently no fear of overemphasis this week, as BC
publicizes its flurry of events in Belfast and Dublin. There was
the reunion for Irish alumni at the National Gallery, which, BC
officials note, lent the college a Caravaggio. There was the
signing of a memo of understanding between Linen Hall Library and
the BC Library, which allowed the two to boast of being the largest
repository of Irish publications in the world. Father Leahy was
invited to a luncheon at the Parliament building in Stormont, seat
of the British government in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said BC knew about the UMass conference, but that it was
merely a coincidence that the two were planned for the same week.
</P>
<P>
   From the Irish perspective, the timing adds to the amusement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always amazing to the native Irish that Ireland can be so
significant in people's consciousness outside of Ireland,'' said
Thomas Groome, a professor of theology and education at BC who
arrived here from Ireland 30 years ago. ``The native Irish have a
bit of a wink and a nod and a wink to it all. They welcome them, as
they always do, of course. But for the Americans, there's a bit of
self-interest, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Both universities want to encourage development in Ireland. But
for BC, enhancing the connections between the two lands has also
enhanced the university's own reputation. BC's extensive outreach
to Ireland, BC officials hope, means the Irish will consider BC
first when looking for a place to send their students or for help
in their economic or political affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The worry is that UMass has figured out the same equation.
``With Bulger,'' one professor noted dryly, ``things like
coincidences don't come easy.''
</P>
<P>
   UMass officials, though, insist they are not competing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a presence, an impact, but we don't see it as
one school looking over its shoulder,'' said Connolly, Bulger's
spokesman. ``BC is distinguished when it comes to this stuff;
they're a good role model. But there is enough work here for at
least two universities.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger, of course, is that all the jockeying for position
might backfire for both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch,'' Dunn said, joking. ``We'll be so obnoxious, the Irish
will all go to Notre Dame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
