<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TECHMAPS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-tech options: trumping the compass?
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 27.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The latest thing in personal navigation seems a lot
like the oldest thing: asking directions.
</P>
<P>
   OnStar, the General Motors program that links your car with a
navigator looking at a computerized map somewhere in Michigan, is
like having a gas station attendant available for questioning 24
hours a day. During a recent test drive, my wife and I enjoyed the
novelty of being guided through North Georgia by a disembodied
voice named Angie. But would we pay the regular price of $1,000 for
the hardware plus $22.50 a month for the subscription fee?
</P>
<P>
   There are cheaper options, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular paperless road maps are software programs like
DeLorme's Map'n'Go and Rand McNally's TripMaker. They combine roads
with guidebook listings, letting you plot personalized routes and
check restaurants and accommodations along the way. For full techie
portability, you can buy a GPS (Global Positioning System) receiver
_ no bigger than a mouse _ that tracks your vehicle by satellite
and allows you to follow your progress on a laptop. Rand McNally
sells software and receiver for $99.95.
</P>
<P>
   We tried Microsoft's Expedia Streets &AMP; Trips 2000, mapping a
drive from Atlanta to my mother's home near Sandersville (Ga.). The
program chose a 130-mile route through Milledgeville, with times
and odometer readings for each turn (right). The military precision
of it all reminded me of my father's Durham-by-lunch vacation
timetables. I didn't care for the routing; I can get there faster
through Sparta. But I enjoyed the travel tips. Microsoft told me
about a restaurant I had never noticed in all my treks to the old
sod _ Mary's Kountry Kitchen. Unfortunately, it also showed the
demolished Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium. Streets &AMP; Trips '96?
</P>
<P>
   The logical next step in navigational technology is integrating
map and vehicle. GM pioneered the field with its OnStar program.
</P>
<P>
   A computer chip in the car tells a satellite where you are,
while a cell phone built into the roof keeps you in touch with
``advisers'' sitting hundreds of miles away at computer screens.
There's a microphone in the roof and three buttons above the
rearview mirror _ two to start and end calls, another to summon
emergency road help.
</P>
<P>
   We climbed into a blue '99 Envoy SUV and pushed the start
button. After a startling electronic flourish, we were connected to
the pleasantly helpful Angie. We wanted to drive from Atlanta to
New Echota, the state historic site marking the capital of the
Cherokee nation. She asked me to spell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the New Echota Grocery,'' she said, ``but I'm having
trouble finding the historic site. Can I give you a call back?''
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later the roof rang. Angie had directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if we take a wrong turn?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't watching you the whole time. I mean, we don't care
if you stop for breakfast at Bob Evans.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it was up to us to determine whether we were
lost. As any wife knows, that's easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting New Echota, we called back and asked another
OnStar adviser how to get to Howard Finster's place near
Summerville. She clearly had no idea who the folk artist is, but
once we mentioned that his environment is called Paradise Garden,
she found it on her database and laid out the best route.
</P>
<P>
   I know it's the best route because I had a $15 road atlas in my
lap.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constituion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
