<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENZYME TRACKING STOCKS ARE OFF TRACK ON RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do you do with a promising business division that isn't
really in the same line of work as its much bigger corporate
parent?
</P>
<P>
   In growing numbers, large companies are creating ``tracking''
stocks that trade in public markets even though the business
continues to be attached to its parent in many important ways.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme Corp., the Cambridge, Mass. biotech company, was
creating tracking stocks long before it came into vogue. It will
launch its fourth, Genzyme Surgical Products, on Monday. An implied
$400 million value for the new stock is more than twice the actual
market value of Genzyme's three other tracking stocks combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (a tracking stock) is fundamentally different from the
subsidiary approach, spinning off 10 or 15 percent,'' said Genzyme
Corp. chief executive Henri Termeer. ``These companies are still
very much connected; they're still very much part of Genzyme. They
are visions, where shareholders have a specific interest.''
</P>
<P>
   But as pure investments, Genzyme's existing tracking stocks have
left a lot to be desired. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   --Genzyme Molecular Oncology, which finished its first day of
public trading at 7 3/4 in November, has not been able to match
that price since. The stock slumped almost immediately and finished
Wednesday at 3 1/32.
</P>
<P>
   --Genzyme Tissue Repair lost two-thirds of its value in the last
year. The stock, which peaked at 25 1/8 in 1996, never finished
above 6 5/8 in the last year. It was valued at 2 3/32 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   --Genzyme Transgenics Corp., the elder tracking stock in the
Genzyme family, is down 40 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stocks usually follow the financial ups and downs of
its business operations, but the parent company continues to own
its underlying assets. That makes expenses lower, particularly when
it comes to borrowing money.
</P>
<P>
   The tracking stock is spun off to shareholders of the parent
company, who can keep it or sell it at any time once it goes
public.
</P>
<P>
   Large, mature companies sometimes create tracking stocks to
unlock market value for a small unit in a relatively glitzy field,
like the Internet. The stock market may accord the business no
value as a financial footnote to its giant parent, but reward it
handsomely if broken out into a stock that can trade on its own.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors created the earliest and perhaps best known
tracking stocks for two hot businesses that had nothing to do with
automobiles: Electronic Data Systems and Hughes Electronics Corp.
Even Microsoft Corp. has more recently considered rolling out a
tracking stock for its Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Genzyme's tracking stocks have not captured any waves
of investor euphoria. But, said Termeer, that was not the driving
point anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He sings the praises of tracking stocks as vehicles to create an
entrepreneurial environment (most importantly, stock options
targeted to the specific business units), a following among
investors focused on their particular business, and corporate
support from a larger parent all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   As for the performance of Genzyme's other tracking stocks,
Termeer described that as a reflection of the poor equity market
for small and speculative technology stocks that are not
Internet-related. Some others agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put that in the context of how small caps in the
biotechnology sector have done,'' said analyst Meg Malloy of
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. ``By and large, those kinds of stocks have been
out of favor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Genzyme tracking companies are nothing if not small and
speculative. Genzyme Molecular Oncology develops gene-based
diagnotics and therapies for cancer. Genzyme Tissue Repair develops
biological products for severe burns and other serious skin
problems as well as other disorders.
</P>
<P>
   But size is a serious issue for tracking stocks. How many
investors or analysts, no matter how specialized, are going to
bother following a stock with a stock market value of less than
$100 million? How much better off will shareholders be if they own
a new tracking stock that no one cares to buy?
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme Surgical Products is two businesses in one: a surgical
instruments venture it bought from Deknatel Snowden Pencer Inc. of
Taunton in 1996 for $250 million and its own Seprafilm product, a
thin film surgeons apply to organs to reduce adhesions after
surgery. The instruments business is established and generating
cash flow but Seprafilm is still developing, according to Termeer.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme is cashing out fraction shares of Surgical Products at a
rate of $25 per share, creating an implied value of $400 million
for the entire company. That value is based on the price paid for
Deknatel Snowden Pencer and $150 million Genzyme has promised to
pump into the new tracking company.
</P>
<P>
   Termeer may be a big fan of tracking stocks, but don't look for
Genzyme to spin off many more new units soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should do many more,'' said Termeer. ``We
have a very effective, overseeable situation right now where
investors understand what we're doing. For the time being, this
feels very good.''
</P>
<P>
   It would feel better if Genzyme's other tracking stocks would
gain back some ground.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   --Marsh &AMP; McClennan Cos., parent firm of Putnam Investments, is
slogging through the application process to create an Internet bank
based in Natick, Mass. MarshMac applied for a thrift charter with
the US Office of Thrift Supervision in the spring. It would be the
first Internet banking institution headquartered in the state. A
review is expected to be completed late this year.
</P>
<P>
   --Two top executives who recently resigned at PanAgora Asset
Management in Boston to start their own firm have taken on a unit
of Putnam, Lovell, de Guardiola &AMP; Thornton, as a minority investor.
Highcrest Capital Partners is investing an undisclosed sum in
Arrowstreet Capital, newly created by former PanAgora chief
executive Bruce Clarke, chief investment officer Peter Rathjens,
and Harvard University professor John Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
