<SLUG> BC-BIG-DADDY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDLER PLAYS FATHER FIGURE TO THE HILT IN `BIG DADDY'  
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Adam Sandler's latest flush of the pop-culture
plumbing, ``Big Daddy,'' is actually a sweet little rip-off of
Charlie Chaplin's ``The Kid'' and its 800 or so imitators.
</P>
<P>
   Sandler is back in the lovable loser mode of ``The Wedding
Singer,'' which is always a welcome change from his other
Neanderthal screen persona. The boy, played by 6-year-old identical
twins Cole and Dylan Sprouse, is suitably sad-eyed and adorable _
and good at substituting w's for r's (``wock n' woll'') in the way
that makes women go ``aw.'' Even the inevitable upchuck is
attractively candy-colored.
</P>
<P>
   But since originality and sophistication never figured into the
equation here, the only way to judge the success of this thing is
by how long it allows Sandler's no-account slacker, Sonny Koufax,
to set bad examples for the orphaned urchin in his charge. Happily
enough, most of this mercifully brief slob comedy's running time is
devoted to spitting instruction, Hooters references and
bladder-relief jokes. Sentimentality and responsible attitudes
don't reach egregious levels until the inevitable, climactic
courtroom scene.
</P>
<P>
   Koufax is an apparently brilliant law school graduate (the
film's smartest joke, considering who plays him) who's opted for a
one-day-per-week job as a New York toll booth attendant. He doesn't
even need that work, since he's apparently invested the $200,000
settlement from a taxi accident lawsuit well.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than appreciate his layabout logic, Sonny's girlfriend
Vanessa (Kristy Swanson) frets about his lack of ambition. Shortly
after his roommate Kevin (Jon Stewart) takes off for a long
business trip to China, the illegitimate child Kevin didn't know he
had appears at the bachelors' apartment. Naturally, Sonny figures
pretending to adopt the kid will show Vanessa he's matured. Things
don't work out as planned, but bonding ensues regardless.
</P>
<P>
   Sandler and his regular writing partner Tim Herlihy worked
consistently amusing behavioral humor into Steve Franks'
screenplay. The clueless surrogate dad's solution to all spills,
whether of container or bodily origin, is to cover them with
newspaper; when the kid gets upset, Sonny makes him laugh by
inflicting grievous bodily harm upon himself; uncertain what the
rules are these days, he makes Julian wear swim trunks at bath time
just to be on the safe side, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout all of this, Sandler works his doofus charm to the
limit, then punctuates the proceedings with judicious explosions of
his signature, psycho-comic anger. There's enough of both schticks
here to satisfy fans of each gender. Indeed, Sonny's patient but
persistent courting of a likable environmental lawyer (played by
the always winsome Joey Lauren Adams) is almost romantic enough to
raise the film a notch or two above pure infantilism.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprouse twins strike a similarly nice balance between cuddly
cute and obnoxious. And director Dennis Dugan improves here on both
of his previous brat comedies, ``Problem Child'' and the
Sandler-starring ``Happy Gilmore,'' letting more than an inkling of
wit inform his obsessional interest in bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Consistently chucklesome if hardly great comedy, ``Big Daddy''
suggests _ in its superficial, overcalculated way _ that Adam
Sandler could even be funny once toilet trained.
</P>
<P>
   Someday. When he grows up. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
