<SLUG> BC-SOX-WWC-NIGERIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVED NIGERIA SEEKS A FOOTHOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Americans already tried the hair-dyeing thing.
``We did blue,'' says Brandi Chastain, ``but it didn't take.'' So
how do the Nigerians do it? Blue is Crayola-basic for them.
Marvelous Mercy Akide has green and silver ringlets. Florence
Omagbemi, the captain, tints her locks burnt orange, like the Texas
school colors. Ann Chiejine, the keeper who runs a hair salon back
home, wraps her white hair in a neon-orange bandanna.
</P>
<P>
   The US women's soccer players see Nigeria play on TV and they
shake their sun-streaked ponytailed heads in amusement and wonder.
``They're fun,'' says Michelle Akers. ``I've been reading about
them and watching them. They're definitely a colorful team with a
lot of energy and a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, inside sold-out Soldier Field, the flamboyant
Super Falcons will be standing between the Americans and the World
Cup quarterfinals. ``Very big game,'' says US coach Tony DiCicco,
whose squad shut out Denmark in its opener last weekend. ``Big game
for Nigeria, too. The winner gets 3 points, gets into the second
round, and goes to the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   The form sheet says that the Americans, who've already been
places the Nigerians can only dream about, should win. They're
11-1-1 lifetime in Cup play and they've won 58 of their last 59
matches at home. But they've never played the Nigerians (or any
African side) before and they've seen enough of them to know
they're dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look very good, better than I'd hoped they would,'' says
DiCicco, who had his assistants scout Nigeria's 2-1 victory over
North Korea in the Rose Bowl Sunday. ``They're very athletic, they
play physical, and they've got a lot of speed all over the place.
So we've got our work cut out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, do the Super Falcons, who rarely face rivals who have
the experience, depth, and tactical sophistication that the US
does. Though they've dominated Africa for years, they've finished
10th and 11th in the previous two Cups and hadn't managed a victory
until they edged the Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Nigerians are decidedly on the rise. They beat the
Chinese (who've handled the US twice this year) in a recent tuneup
and profess to be uncowed by their hosts' international resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they are one of the favorites to win the championship,
but we are still in the race,'' says coach Ismaila Mabo. ``I will
not be intimidated by their record. It is going to be a fight to
the finish. Nigeria will play its game. Nigeria will play to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerians, both for better and worse, play the same way
against everybody. ``We believe in attacking football and we will
always play that way,'' says Mabo. ``We don't care who we play. If
we play the Brazilian male team, if we play the American male team,
we would play exactly the same. We don't believe in negative
football. We will be taking risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The subtext is that the Super Falcons don't believe much in
defending, either, which is why the Americans believe they will
prevail over 90 minutes. ``They'll be coming at us, coming at us,
coming at us,'' says keeper Briana Scurry. ``But if they don't
succeed on a corner kick, we'll be right back at them. It could be
a field day for our forwards. The Nigerians won't be able to hold
Mia (Hamm) and the rest of them all game. There's no way.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Americans must do is absorb the shock of the Nigerian
attack, keep their shape, and not fret if they give up a goal in
the first five minutes. ``That'd be a nightmare,'' nods Tiffeny
Milbrett. ``But it would slap us in the face and get us in gear a
lot faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it may take Milbrett and her teammates a while to get to
cruise control, they figure they'll have another three points by
night's end. But they've already conceded the style competition.
Red and blue fingernails can't match the day-glo rainbow the
Nigerians have in their every-day paintbox. ``We're plain Janes,''
shrugs Scurry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With defender Kate Sobrero doubtful for Thursday's match after
spraining an ankle in Wednesday's practice, Natick-born Sara Whalen
could start. DiCicco said that Whalen, Christie Pearce, Lorrie
Fair, and Tiffany Roberts were all options, depending on which
formation he uses. But if he wants speed against the fleet
Nigerians, Whalen's the one. ``She could be our fastest player,''
DiCicco says. ``She's one of the fastest I've ever seen coming up
the field with a soccer ball. And she's been playing with a lot of
bite recently.'' Whalen, a 23-year-old University of Connecticut
grad, has played in 10 of the squad's 19 matches this year and
started three.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sellout of 65,000-plus at Soldier Field will make it the
third-largest paid crowd in women's soccer history, behind last
Saturday's US-Denmark opener at Giants Stadium (78,972) and the
1996 Olympic final between the US and China (76,489).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
