<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-TALLAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLAS'S HORIZONS MAY SOON BE EXPANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He wasn't surprised. Not even a little. The issue had
been talked about, discussed, and dissected long before it became
official.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Tallas had plenty of warning that the Bruins were going to
protect goalie Byron Dafoe and expose him in Friday's expansion
draft that is being used to stock the National Hockey League's most
recent entry, the Atlanta Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   So when the news finally came with the league's announcement
Tuesday afternoon, the ever-upbeat Tallas gave it the proverbial
shoulder shrug and said he'll deal with whatever life brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to happen,'' said the 26-year-old Tallas.
``There are a lot of goalies out there who are unprotected this
year. It's a tough situation (the Bruins are in). To protect me
means they couldn't protect one extra forward or one extra
defenseman. That's big this year. I'd heard rumors since the last
month of the season about them not protecting me, so it came as no
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas has been one of the better Cinderella stories in the
Bruins' organization. He first came to training camp in 1994,
arriving as a tryout. No one had ever heard of him, and he turned
out to be the player everyone was talking about in the end.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a contract with Charlotte of the East Coast League and
worked his way up through the ranks before playing 24 games with
the Bruins in the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back and I'm very thankful, and there's not a day that
goes by that I've stopped thinking about how I did get here,'' said
Tallas. ``But it's one of those times in life, again, that whatever
happens, it happens for the best. If I do stay here, then great.
This is my team, this is my home, they know exactly what I can do.
They know how me and Byron get along.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do go, I'll miss my relationship with Byron. There aren't
too many times when you have two goalies who get along as well as
we do. Sometimes it's a competition between the two goalies, but
with us, it's not like that. We get along great. I think that will
be the biggest thing. But it might be time for me to play. Now that
I've got confidence in this league and know that I can play at this
level, I'd like to try it as the No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that there will be 28 teams in the NHL next
season, that chance is actually more difficult to come by. Perhaps
because of the big salaries starting netminders command, teams have
begun playing their top guys more often, meaning less work for the
backups. Tallas was odd man out down the stretch with Dafoe playing
virtually every game. The Bruins were in a sprint for a playoff
spot, and Burns felt he had to use Dafoe just to make it to the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's being a backup goalie,'' said Tallas. ``I remember
talking to Byron right at the end of the season about how being a
backup in some ways is tougher than being the No. 1 guy. When you
have a bad game, as the No. 1, you know you're going to play the
next night and redeem yourself and continue. When you're a backup,
if you play once a week or once every two weeks or you sit out 20
straight games, there's a lot that goes through your mind. Practice
becomes frustrating. You see the team having success and you don't
feel quite a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas played in 17 games last season, compiling a 7-7-2 record
with a 2.61 goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   Tallas said he has seen plenty of his fellow backups go through
the difficulty of sitting and waiting for their turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Rick Tabaracci, and he told me to hang in there,''
said Tallas, referring to the much-traveled Washington netminder.
``He said, `Hey, I did 22 games straight (without playing). But
they want to expose me so now they won't stop playing me.' It has
happened to others. Same with Chris Terreri. He's played the least
amount of games and here's a guy who's been around longer than
anyone else. That's just part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas is set to become a restricted free agent July 1, so if he
is picked by Atlanta, he'll negotiate with the Thrashers. If he
remains in Boston, he'll try to work out a contract with the
Bruins. As was the case last year, Tallas has arbitration rights
and said he would file. Last summer, it wasn't a fight over money,
it was over a one-way contract. Tallas felt he earned the right to
be paid NHL money for the entire year. The Bruins wanted to give
him a two-way contract meaning he'd be paid less if he wound up in
the minors. Tallas got what he wanted and earned $625,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to be here forever,'' said Tallas. ``I know
(coach) Pat Burns likes me. I know Byron is going to play 65 games
again next year. That's what they expect of him. Hopefully, I can
get more games in. We'll see what kind of contract they give me. If
it's a two-year deal, make the best of it. If it's another one-year
contract, I've got to also look that next year, there are two more
teams coming into the league. There is another year where they're
going to expose me. But I do want the challenge of being a No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   As frustrating as it was last season for Tallas, he said it
would never make sense for him to be satisfied being No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only practice so much,'' he said. ``You want to be out
there and in a game and a part of it. If I wasn't frustrated, I
wouldn't be a competitive guy. I wouldn't have that edge. If you
were satisfied with being a backup, that's not good enough. Not at
this level.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he realizes even Dafoe had to pay his dues,
which he did in Los Angeles and Washington prior to being traded to
Boston. Tallas paid his dues here and is hoping that will lead to
an opportunity whether it be here, in Atlanta or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to be a good goalie in this league and to last a long
time, (Philly netminder) John Vanbiesbrouck said it best,'' Tallas
said. ``You're always a student of the game. Every year is
different. You can never be relaxed. You're always learning. I feel
I've come along comfortably. I've come through some hard times and
some great times.''
</P>
<P>
   And now it's an uncertain time. But not for much longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
