 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans _ The Coca-Cola Essence Music Festival, Friday
through Sunday at the Louisiana Superdome, will feature headliners
Lauryn Hill, R. Kelly, Erykah Badu, Brian McKnight, Monica, Deborah
Cox, Dru Hill, Will Downing and Gerald Albright, the Temptations,
Patti Labelle and Maze featuring Frankie Beverly. Tickets:
1-800-488-5252. Travel packages: 1-800-762-9523.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Smithville, Tenn. _ The Official State and National
Championship Smithville Fiddlers' Jamboree and Crafts Festival,
Friday and Saturday, han 200 booths. 615-597-8500.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Young Harris _ The 11th season of the state's official
historical drama, ``The Reach of Song,'' continues through Aug. 22.
The musical features local musicians and cast members in a
celebration of the Appalachian spirit and tribute to mountain poet
Byron Herbert Reece. 1-800-262-7664.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Highlands, N.C. _ The Highlands Playhouse presents the musical
``Grease,'' through Sunday. Upcoming: the farce ``Cash on
Delivery'' July 7-18; the musical ``Crazy for You'' July 21-Aug. 8;
and the comedy ``Take This Man'' Aug. 11-22. 828-526-2695.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cherokee, N.C. _ The annual outdoor drama ``Unto These Hills''
tells the story of the Cherokee people from 1540 through the 1800s.
Through Aug. 21. 828-497-2111 or www.dnet.net/(tilde)cheratt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boone, N.C. _ The Appalachian Summer Festival, Monday through
July 31, features nearly 30 music, dance and theater performances
at Appalachian State University. An outdoor concert with fireworks
July 17 will feature Mary Chapin Carpenter. Tickets: 1-800-841-2787
or online at appsummer.appstate.edu.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tuscumbia, Ala. _ Playwright William Gibson's ``The Miracle
Worker'' is performed on the grounds of Ivy Green, Helen Keller's
birthplace, through July 4. 256-383-4066 or
www.bham.net/keller/home.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Williamsburg, Va. _ The Yorktown Victory Center presents an
exhibition, ``The Washingtons of Colonial Virginia,'' in observance
of George Washington's death 200 years ago. The exhibition focuses
on the first president's ancestors in Virginia and their role in
the history of the colony. Through February. 1-888-593-4682.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
