<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JET: BLACK AND READ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a recent documentary on the history of America's
black press, one veteran journalist eloquently explained its
function. Blacks ``were truly invisible'' in the media, he said.
``But in the black press, we did get married.''
</P>
<P>
   The film concluded that the 140-year-old black newspaper
business essentially died in the 1960s when the mainstream press
began hiring away black reporters. But John Johnson, the feisty
81-year-old multimillionaire magnate who publishes Jet and Ebony
magazines, offers another theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black newspaper thrived on protest, they thrived on
getting rights for black people,'' he says. When those rights were
officially won, ``the black newspapers failed to make that
transition.'' But ``we didn't forget that people had to lead normal
lives. They had to get married.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why 48 years after Jet's founding, one of the magazine's
enduring features is ``Society World,'' a photo collage of nuptials
and anniversaries. A black person has to be ``real hoity-toity to
be in the wedding section of white publications,'' says Johnson
with a smile. But not in Jet magazine.
</P>
<P>
   An Arkansas native and robust octogenarian (regular exercise, no
tobacco or alcohol), Johnson did not become one of the most
powerful black businessmen in America by misjudging his market. The
holder of 30 honorary degrees and 1996 recipient of the
Presidential Medal of Freedom, he runs a company _ which includes
the magazines and a major cosmetics operation _ that is the
nation's second-largest black business, with nearly $372 million in
annual sales, according to the latest issue of Black Enterprise
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Started with a $500 loan Johnson took against his mother's
furniture, the 57-year-old Chicago-based Johnson Publishing Co. is
a private family enterprise. Its boss has a simple theory for the
success of Jet, a no-frills, apolitical, pocket-size, retro-looking
weekly digest of news: ``It's just having a sensitivity about what
black people want to know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the magazine's reputation for being chock-full of
short and tidy tidbits of information, longtime reader Vicki Jones
says, ``USA Today is white people's version of Jet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a saying,'' adds senior editor Sylvia Flanagan. ``If
it wasn't in Jet, it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   While the standard-size, glossier, more feature-oriented Ebony
has the larger circulation _ 1.75 million to Jet's 927,000 _ there
is one stunning figure that best illustrates the fanatic loyalty
Jet seems to inspire. There is a stratospheric pass-along rate of
9.7 readers per copy, meaning that each issue is seen by about 9
million people. Flanagan attributes the pass-along phenomenon to
Jet's compact size, and thus easy portability and readability,
noting ``we're like a family member.'' (Interestingly, Jet's
penetration of Boston's black population is the second-lowest of
any of the nation's top 100 black-census cities.)
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's editorial content starts with the staff's regular
perusal of about 50 newspapers, Associated Press stories and the
offerings of dozens of photo agencies. Some pieces are rewrites of
news stories, others entail more thorough follow-ups. The stories
are short, basic, and mostly without bylines. The common thread is
that it is news for and about black people.
</P>
<P>
   That style hasn't changed dramatically since the inaugural Nov.
1, 1951 issue featured Edna Robinson _ wife of boxing great Sugar
Ray Robinson _ on the cover. Today's cover subjects include Aretha
Franklin, Samuel L. Jackson, and Deion Sanders. Inside are popular
items like ``This Week in Black History,'' ``Society World,'' and
``People'' as well as features on music, movies, and television.
Another traditional element, and one that is printed in color in an
otherwise predominantly black-and-white magazine, is the
pinup-style ``Beauty of the Week'' photo.
</P>
<P>
   All of which leads to questions about Jet's editorial
philosophy, which seems to lie somewhere between Sgt. Friday's
``just the facts, ma'am,'' approach and a Dale Carnegie dose of
feel-good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to be positive,'' notes managing editor Malcolm
West, a goal manifest in much of the upbeat information about black
movers and shakers. But Johnson also contends that ``we report the
news,'' and Jet does run its share of stories featuring the kind of
violence, mayhem, and racial strife you'd find on Page 1 of any
American newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But ``deep down, at the end of the day, we're trying to give
people hope,'' Johnson explains.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the temptation is to view Johnson and his upbeat
magazine that chooses not to rock the boat as throwbacks to the bad
old days in America's racial history. (With a chuckle, he explains
how southern blacks knew which white candidate to vote for when
both used the N-word on the campaign trail: The one who said it
more quietly.)
</P>
<P>
   But then, with vivid clarity, he recounts a 40-year-old story
about being denied a reservation in a tony Washington hotel and a
different philosophy emerges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have ever known discrimination and humiliation, it
never goes away,'' Johnson says. ``Everything I do is a response to
discrimination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
