<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC DECEPTION ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1968, the average American voter was a white Midwestern male
who worked in manufacturing. He was married to a woman who worked
part time or stayed home with her two, three or four children. He
went to church on Sunday and believed in the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   He was liberal on economic issues, conservative on social
issues, and supportive of Cold War national security policies. He
was unwaveringly anticommunist. And he believed that, in the main,
American elites acted in the best interests of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the average American voter is a white Sun Belt woman who
works in the service industry. She is just as likely to be divorced
as married. She works full time and does not stay home with her one
or two children. She goes to church on Sunday and she worries that
her kids will be left behind in the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   She is conservative on economic issues (she works hard for the
money), tolerant on social issues and deeply skeptical of
interventionist US national security policies. She is, above all,
worried about her parent's health (Who's going to pay for it?), her
own health, her children's education, and a culture run amok. She
believes that American elites are, in the main, self-interested.
</P>
<P>
   This woman will decide the outcome of the year 2000 presidential
and congressional elections. One can predict how virtually every
other demographic group will vote just by scanning their previous
vote patterns. But this baby-boom woman (who has been trending
Democratic in the last two elections) is not so predictable and
much more open to political dialogue and debate.
</P>
<P>
   She voted for Clinton in 1996, but actually agreed with Dole on
most issues. Lose her and you lose the election. She holds the
balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats believe they can win her allegiance in 2000 by
exciting her fears. Her deepest fear is that something will happen
to her children while she is at work. Littleton, Colo., was
emblematic of that fear. She could imagine herself on the other end
of that phone call from police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   This fear is what the political issue of ``gun control'' is all
about. It has nothing to do with gun control, per se. There are 200
million guns in circulation in America and over 220,000 laws
regulating their use. These laws range from the very strict
(they're basically illegal in New York City) to the very lax (There
aren't any state laws to speak of in Montana regulating gun
ownership).
</P>
<P>
   The notion that background checks at gun shows will somehow
prevent future Littletons is ludicrous on its face. In the age of
the Internet, the notion that those background checks can't be done
in one hour is equally ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   Preventing future Littletons, however, is the last thing
Democratic congressional leaders care about. Their interest is
self-interest. They want to regain their majority status in the US
House of Representatives. They think ``gun control'' may be their
leverage back in.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Democratic members chanted ``six seats, six seats''
during last week's ``gun control'' vote, as it went down to defeat.
Six is the number of seats they need to win back to control the
House.
</P>
<P>
   This why House minority leader Richard Gephardt, Democrat of
Missouri, said to his colleague John Dingell, Democrat of Michigan,
whose amendment doomed the proposed gun-control legislation,
``thank you.'' Had Gephardt truly cared about the issue, he would
have been livid at Dingell's parliamentary maneuvering. But in the
inside-out world of issue management, what Dingell had done was
hand his Democratic colleagues in suburban districts a a ``hot
button issue'' with enormous appeal to the new average Amercian
voter.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Bill Clinton has used the gun-control issue
repeatedly throughout his presidency and three presidential
campaigns (two of his own and the nascent Gore effort). Clinton was
governor of Arkansas for 12 years. During that time, he did exactly
nothing to strengthen gun laws because statewide polling showed it
would cost him votes. Only when he moved to the national stage did
he adopt the issue. He did so because focus groups told him it
scored well with average American voters.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly enough, ``gun control'' may well improve the
Democratic Party's fortunes in 2000. This is largely due to the
inability of the Republican congressional leadership to formulate
and articulate a serious agenda that appeals to the new average
American voter.
</P>
<P>
   Absent a serious GOP agenda, the president and his Democratic
allies drive the national debate. The fact that the issues raised
by the president and his Democratic colleagues are almost entirely
synthetic matters less than the fact that the GOP congressional
leadership has nothing to say.
</P>
<P>
   The old adage that ``you can't beat something with nothing''
applies. Even when that something is as cynical as Democratic
posturing on ``gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
