<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORN-PRIVACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORN CASES RAISE ISSUES OF WORKER PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- To the outside world, Erik Butler appeared at the top
of his game. The homeless shelter he ran had just been the subject
of glowing features in newspapers from Washington, D.C., to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Tuesday, Butler resigned abruptly from his position as
the Pine Street Inn's executive director amid allegations that he
had stored pornography on his office computer last year. The
allegations, coming on the heels of the November resignation of the
dean of Harvard Divinity School under similar circumstances,
reignites a debate about whether peeping at porn at the office
should be a firing offense.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who say that privacy is sacrosanct, and that
what is done on a productive employee's office computer should be
of no concern to the boss. But employers who are having to grapple
with the issue more frequently say what is done on office equipment
reflects the integrity of the company or institution.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, companies have had to develop strict policies about
Internet usage at work. Some have even begun monitoring where their
employees surf during business hours.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, though, continues to ensnare employees as the
tolerance for such behavior declines.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight employees were disciplined last month at St.
Louis-based Edward Jones &AMP; Co., a brokerage house, for sending
e-mail that contained pornography or offensive jokes. Another 19
were dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the chief executive officer of Florsheim Group Inc.
was forced to resign amid allegations of lewd behavior that
reportedly included viewing pornography in his Chicago office.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republican Senator James Inhofe, of Oklahoma, was
embarrassed this month when two of his aides had to be disciplined
after they downloaded so much pornography onto their office
computers that the entire office network crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the presence of the Internet in the workplace raises a
host of questions: Are computer technicians being put in the
awkward position of becoming workplace cyber-police? Where is the
line drawn between one employee's right to privacy and another
employee's right to work in a harassment-free workplace?
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been muddied by the murkiness of the
circumstances surrounding the resignations of Butler and the
Harvard Divinity dean, Ronald Thiemann. Neither Thiemann, who lost
his deanship but remains on Harvard's faculty, nor Butler will
comment on the allegations made against him. Their employers,
Harvard University and the Pine Street Inn, aren't talking either.
</P>
<P>
   According to people familiar with the cases, the pornography
allegedly on Butler's computer was discovered by a coworker last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Sources at Harvard say the pornography on Thiemann's computer
was discovered in October after he asked an information technology
specialist to transfer files from his hard drive, which was filled
with thousands of pornographic images, to a new hard drive. Harvard
Divinity School policy states that use of ``inappropriate, obscene,
bigoted or abusive material is prohibited.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Thiemann in recent weeks has been portrayed by
civil libertarians as a victim of nosey information technology
workers who should not have reported his alleged pornography use to
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the biggest issue in the Harvard case is why the
technicians were not disciplined for disclosing the content of the
computer files,'' said Alan Dershowitz, a law professor at Harvard.
``The computer technicians didn't have to look at the content of
the files they were transferring. These were snoops. These were
Peeping Toms.''
</P>
<P>
   While declining to discuss the details of the case publicly, a
Harvard spokesman rejected Dershowitz's assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We emphatically reject the idea that there was an invasion of
privacy,'' said spokesman Joe Wrinn. ``The information staff acted
entirely appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   Another question raised was whether Thiemann's position as dean
of the Divinity School should weigh into the equation. Robert Ellis
Smith, the publisher of the Privacy Journal, a Providence
publication, who is usually a staunch defender of privacy rights,
said he believes it should. He cited the example of a Massachusetts
bus driver who was fired after he drove the school bus during off
hours to an adult bookstore, emerging with a brown paper bag _ a
termination that Smith said was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's reasonable for the employer to act to protect the
reputation of the organization or the integrity of the job,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another question raised is whether there is something about
Internet pornography that makes employers especially uneasy. Are
they, for instance, more likely to punish an employee for use of
cyber-porn than they would be if a Playboy magazine were found in
an office desk?
</P>
<P>
   Eric Krause, a spokesman for Gillette Co., said the company
considers the display of any sexually suggestive material in the
workplace as a possible form of harassment _ be it on the computer,
in a magazine, or in a calendar on the office wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``What may have been appropriate once in the manufacturing
environment is definitely not appropriate now,'' Krause said.
``Those tool calendars may have been up years ago, but if it
creates a threatening work environment, it's inappropriate and
unacceptable now.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in office mores is being driven by several factors,
experts say, such as the larger numbers of women in the work force
and the fact that most women no longer accept that harrassment must
be endured.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony of Anita Hill against Supreme Court nominee
Clarence Thomas in the early 1990s prompted many companies to
develop sexual harassment policies. And the rapid proliferation of
computer and Internet technology has forced companies to scramble
to develop clear rules regarding Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Greenberg of the American Management Association said
employees should assume that anything on their computer could be
viewed by their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own personal advice is, don't be stupid,'' Greenberg said.
``If you're going to call a bookie, don't do it from your office.
If you're going to surf for porn don't use your office
connection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
