<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDLCARE-COLUMN-BOS     06-24 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDLCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING VACATION WORK AFTER DIVORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Second of two parts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If you're a parent getting ready to send your kids to visit
their father or mother for part of the summer, especially for the
first time since your separation or divorce, give yourself a break.
Just because you know this is important and special for your
children doesn't make it any easier for you. On the other hand, you
don't want to make it any harder for them.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tough transition for children of any age. Leaving
behind the parent they live with most of the year to visit a parent
they see only occasionally is anxiety-producing. A 5- to 7-year-old
wonders, ``What will Daddy be like? Will he still like me? Will I
still like him?'' An older child is more likely to focus on what
they'll do together: ``Will we do things that I like? Will Daddy be
fun to be with?''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do you need to help a child with his concerns, but you
also need to deal with your own.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sheehy, whose 14-year-old son, John, typically spends five
or six weeks each summer with his father in Seattle, remembers that
when he first started to make the trip, she would grow anxious as
the time approached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel myself getting more and more tense,'' she says.
``I was conscious of having to hold my feelings in.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing that she could.
</P>
<P>
   Children who have a sense that this visit is a threat to the
custodial parent are more anxious. ``They don't feel free to look
forward to it or to have a good time,'' says family therapist
Suzanne Midori Hanna of the University of Louisville in Kentucky, a
specialist in custodial issues.
</P>
<P>
   She tells parents to give children figurative and literal
permission to enjoy the time with their other parent. If parents
are in contact all year long sharing information, symbolic
permission is implied. The less collaboration and the more
hostility there is, the more children feel they are betraying the
primary parent by visiting the other one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They anticipate being caught in the middle, having to tell one
parent about the other. Kids hate that,'' says psychologist Carol
Philpot, dean of the School of Psychology at the Florida Institute
of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   While it's OK for a parent to ask questions about the child's
life, she tells both parents to stay away from questions about each
other, even if they are only an attempt to get factual information:
Is your mother dating? Did your father cook or do takeout every
night?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Setting the stage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the time for the visit approaches, whether your child is
forthright in saying he doesn't want to go, whether you just sense
ambivalence, or even if he's expressing excitement, Hanna urges
getting the topic out in the open, preferably by asking questions.
To a child under 8: ``What do you think it's going to be like when
you get to your dad's?'' or ``Do you remember when you visited last
year?'' To an older child: ``What was good and bad about last time?
What would you like to see happen while you are there this time?''
</P>
<P>
   Even a 6-year-old has a vision of what she wants to happen, says
Hanna. The young child not only will have very concrete ideas _ ``I
want to go to the amusement park'' _ but will likely remember a
detail that surprises you: ``I didn't like the cereal Daddy had.''
The older child may be more abstract: ``Mom treats me like a baby.
She makes me go to bed too early.'' With either kind of response,
says Hanna, a good reply acknowledges a child's need and fosters
adaptability: ``The amusement park would be fun. I don't know if
your dad has that planned, but you could certainly tell him you
want to do that''; ``When you feel as if you're being treated like
a baby, it's not a good feeling, is it? Have you ever told your mom
that?''
</P>
<P>
   A preteen is the child least likely to want to talk to the other
parent about an issue that involves that parent, especially if he
feels the issue shows him to be babyish _ he wants a light left on
at night _ or needy: He wants more time alone with Dad without
Dad's girlfriend around.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna tells parents not to leave a child of any age alone on a
limb by saying something like, ``That's the way your dad is; you
just have to get used to it.'' Instead, we should act as a broker.
Preteens, for instance, may not want to make their dependency needs
known but they're happy to have your help as long as it's done in a
face-saving way: ``I could tell your dad that I'm worried about
this . . .'' Then say to the other parent, ``It'll embarrass Tim if
he knew you knew he was worried about this . . .''
</P>
<P>
   For the 9- to 13-year-old, ambivalence about going may have to
do with feeling inconvenienced or angry at being separated from
friends. As selfish as this may seem, it's a normal developmental
response, says psychotherapist and author Isolini Ricci, who heads
the office of family court services for the Family Court System of
California. Her book, a classic in divorce literature, is ``Mom's
House, Dad's House (Revised Edition)'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster).
</P>
<P>
   Rather than come down on a child for her feelings, Ricci
suggests acknowledging them and sympathizing: ``It's too bad we
live in different cities. It's too bad you can't see your friends
and your dad during the summer. Is there anything you'd like to see
happen to make this go a little easier?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding trust
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ricci says PPV _ phone, pictures, and videos _ can ease the
transition between homes. Before the trip, conversations about the
vacation by phone or e-mail can help a child feel in control. But
she cautions parents: ``Be sure to only offer choices you can live
with.'' It also helps a 5- to 10-year-old to see a video of Dad's
new apartment or of the new lamp Dad put in the child's room. If
nothing is new or different, what about a video of the office, or
of the new puppy at the neighbor's?
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost anything serves as a connection, a reminder, a
refamiliarization,'' says Ricci. ``It rebuilds a sense of trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, it helps if the child takes videos or pictures with
him of classmates, teachers, and teammates. (It helps even more if
the parent requests these.) Says Ricci, ``It creates a connection
while the child gathers these materials because of the anticipation
of sharing them, and then it becomes a bonding activity once she's
there.''
</P>
<P>
   When a child is sad just before leaving the parent who's the
primary caregiver, try to find out why. Is it anxiety about being
there or worry at leaving you?
</P>
<P>
   For the former, a good response might be, ``Is there anything
you can take that will help cheer you up if you feel sad?'' Give
her something with good-luck charm quality: ``If you feel sad, this
will remind you of how much I love you.'' That sends a message of
reassurance as well as confidence in her ability to handle this.
</P>
<P>
   If she's worried about you, she's likely picking up on your
anxiety. Avoid saying things like, ``I hate to see you go, too,''
or ``The house will be so empty without you!'' This is the time to
give literal permission, says Hanna: ``I'll be hoping every day
that something fun is happening for you''; ``This is a time for
both of us to do some things we enjoy. You're going camping, and
I'm going to go to the movies every night! We'll have lots to tell
each other about!''
</P>
<P>
   The parent left behind
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may also have to bite your tongue when your child calls from
the other parent's. Sue Sheehy remembers years when she practically
slept at her office rather than come home to an empty house, and
she counted the days until John returned, but she never let any of
that out over the phone. Now that John is 14, they are both
accustomed to the separation, but it helps that they got a dog a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me something to come home to,'' Sheehy says.
</P>
<P>
   With so much angst and preparation involved, a custodial parent
may well wonder if the visit is worth it. Hanna and Philpot are
quick with reassurances that it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for children to have both genders represented
in their life and to see the role model of both parents,'' says
Philpot.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna says all children have natural questions about their
parents. ``Whenever a child has the opportunity to answer them for
him or herself rather than to have to rely on someone else's
stories or opinions, it gives them peace of mind and a sense of
their own identity,'' she says. ``You're giving your child a
gift.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Encourage the other parent to provide details of what the
vacation will be like in advance. If she isn't forthcoming and you
know where they are going, get a book from the library: ``Since
you're going to the Grand Canyon, let's check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   --Encourage your child to bring souvenirs back to you. It's a
way for her to connect the two worlds.
</P>
<P>
   --While it's good for there to be some consistency between
households, especially around values and bedtimes, it's also OK for
there to be differences: ``In your father's house you go to bed at
10. In this house, bedtime is 9.''
</P>
<P>
   --The less you bad-mouth the other parent all year round, the
easier the transition to vacation will be for your children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended reading for babies and toddlers:
``baby! talk!'' by Penny Gentieu (Random House).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barbara F. Meltz's first book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is now
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments and can
be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
