<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAW-FAMILY-ART-BOS &LR;      06-24 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAW-FAMILY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW AND THE DISORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Andy Epstein, a Harvard Law School graduate who joined a
prestigious New York firm before practicing at a big firm in
Boston, had an awful realization one afternoon: He hated his work.
It felt like an endless grind, and he worried that he was not
devoting nearly enough time to his two young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd made a terrible mistake in becoming a lawyer,''
Epstein said.
</P>
<P>
   He quit big firm life and took a job as an in-house attorney for
Lotus Development Corp. in Cambridge, Mass. Now he works out of his
house as a solo practioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed my life,'' he said. ``Being out of the firm,
suddenly I enjoyed being a lawyer. It was like a revelation. You
realize your life doesn't have to be your work and your work
doesn't have to be your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, so many young attorneys are leaving Boston firms in
search of fulfillment and a better family life that the legal
profession must consider ``revolutionary'' changes in the way it
operates, a Boston Bar Association panel said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-month study by the bar association's Task Force on
Professional Values and Family Needs found that 43 percent of new
associates quit within three years, largely because they felt they
had to choose between a career and a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were all surprised to see a number that big,'' said
Nancer Ballard, who chaired the panel and is a partner at Goodwin
Procter &AMP; Hoar.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing new about lawyers working long hours. But the
study said that firms have become so demanding that for many
lawyers ``private practice is incompatible with daily involvement
in family life.'' Such sentiments are shared by both partners and
associates _ the junior lawyers who typically join firms
immediately after finishing law school and work for seven or eight
years before they become eligible for partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in danger of seeing law firms evolve into institutions
where only those who have no family responsibilities can thrive,''
said Lauren Stiller Rikleen, the bar association's president.
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on a survey of 30 large and midsized Boston
firms and interviews with about 100 lawyers. Even though many firms
have adopted ``family friendly'' policies for those who want to
devote more time to domestic life, few lawyers take advantage of
them, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture at law firms is such that you are marginalized,''
Ballard said. ``Virtually no men opt for those packages and the
women who do are outcasts. They're perceived as not being real
lawyers anymore. What we hope will happen is that every single law
firm will read this report and take a good, hard look at itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The study comes at a time when attorneys are increasingly
questioning their profession. An earlier Boston Bar Association
study, released in 1997, found that attorneys at virtually every
sector of the legal community felt underappreciated, underpaid,
overworked, isolated, and sometimes blocked from advancement by
racial and gender biases.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the National Association of Law Placement
found two-thirds of all new associates quit their firms within six
years and that one-third quit in less than three.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent Boston survey is among the first to pinpoint
family issues as a major cause of attorney unhappiness, the study's
authors said. And it may come as a surprise to local firms, many of
which have earned a reputation for treating associates better than
law firms in other big cities.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, according to the study, is that discontented
lawyers rarely communicate problems they are having with senior
members of the firms. ``Change will only come if people on the
inside are willing to be vocal,'' said Stiller Rikleen.
</P>
<P>
   The study's authors said firms should change not only because
lawyers are discontented but because the defections may be
expensive. According to an analysis of law firm costs in Boston
conducted as part of the study, firms lose money when young lawyers
leave, mainly because they must gain several years experience
before they begin making money for the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first anybody has looked at the economics like
this,'' Ballard said. ``We're trying to tell these firms that they
have an economic model that doesn't work as well as they think it
does. We're trying to say that this isn't just a touchy-feely
issue. It's a matter of money for the firms.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, many firms reward attorneys who bring in
the most business without considering how much the work cost the
firm to perform, the study said. That means part-time lawyers who
generate profits but bring a relatively small amount of work to a
firm go unrecognized.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein has no regrets about leaving big-firm practice, and he
thinks that many firms are at least attempting to change their
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of firms are trying to get a lot better about
some of these issues,'' Epstein said. ``But in the meantime they're
losing some really good people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
