<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-24 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEE DEE AT THE HEIGHT OF HER POWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dee Dee, our all-purpose advice columnist, hesitates to take on
the word ``shag.'' However her hotline has been ringing day and
night, with calls from anxious citizens confused by the title of
Mike Myers's new Austin Powers movie, ``The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
Who else but Dee Dee can answer their questions and calm their
mounting hysteria?
</P>
<P>
   Here in America the word ``shag'' refers to a haircut, a dance,
a bird, and a carpet, among other things. However, in Britain,
``shag'' is a no-no, a nasty euphemism for what Dee Dee prefers to
think of as The Act of Love. Over there, its appearance in the
movie's title has caused something of a stir. An English friend of
Dee Dee's explains, ``It's not quite the F-word, but it's very
rude. For instance, you'd never say it to your mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he might never say it to his mother. Dee Dee's mother has
heard it all, and then some. But now to today's questions.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   I went to see ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' because I thought it
had something to do with baseball. I thought maybe it was about Moe
Berg, the World War I spy who later played for the Red Sox and
several other major league teams. But there was nothing in the
movie about baseball, or about anything, really. What gives? _ Left
Out, Ragtag, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shagging of baseballs in the new Austin Powers
adventure. Actually, there's none of that other kind of shagging,
either, just a lot of suggestive talk about it, because the
producers wanted a PG-13 rating. Dee Dee saw the movie in a theater
full of 12-year-olds, all of them laughing in the right places,
too. Dee Dee thinks they should be grounded indefinitely, and the
same goes for the movie's producers.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   Our rural idyll here in coastal Canada has been shattered by the
release of ``The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' Our tiny community has
become the subject of endless callow joking, even though its name
has nothing to do with the sort of shag associated with the movie.
As far as we know, anyway. What can we do? _ Seething in Shag
Harbour, N.S.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee understands your distress. She once passed through Shag
Harbour and a less shag-a-delic spot would be difficult to imagine.
She advises you to ignore the taunts and capitalize on the
connection. Invite tourists to stop and savor the atmosphere of
``The Town That Put the Word Shag on the Map.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   At this point I may be more sag-tastic than shag-tastic, but I
have enough long-term memory to recall the horror that followed the
release of the first Austin Powers film, when I was forced to
endure so many idiots repeating catch-phrases like
``Shag-alicious!'' and ``Behave!'' It's happening all over again.
What can I do? _ Plainspoken, Ridgeback, MA
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee suggests you practice saying the same phrases in the
most obnoxious manner possible, repeat them over and over again and
hope your tormentors take the hint.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   I purchased a talking Austin Powers doll for my 8-year-old
daughter and the first words out of its snaggle-toothed little
mouth were, ``Shag me, baby!'' I understand this is a smutty remark
of some sort, so I am thinking of suing the doll's manufacturer,
the producers of the movie, and everybody involved in project right
down to the gaffer, whatever that is. Do you know a good lawyer? _
Hopeful, Red Tide, ME
</P>
<P>
   What did you expect an Austin Powers doll to say? ``Honor thy
father and thy mother''? Dee Dee suggests that you have the doll
re-programmed to recite excerpts from ``The Book of Virtues for
Young People.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
