<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-LYME-BOS &LR;      06-24 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LYME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEER TICK   THREAT   IS SERIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When summer comes, so do the bugs that bite. Some, such as deer
ticks, carry serious diseases, one of which is Lyme disease.
</P>
<P>
   The East Coast, Wisconsin, and Minnesota account for 90 percent
of reported cases, although Lyme disease has occurred in 43 states.
Where it is endemic, such as on the Massachusetts shore and
islands, many residents carry antibodies even though they may not
be aware of having been infected.
</P>
<P>
   Bambi and her deer kin are the ticks' favorite hosts, but when
looking for a blood meal, they will latch onto any warm-blooded
mammal, even us as we walk in tall grass, brush, and woods, on golf
courses, and along rustic paths.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of Lyme disease infections occurs between June and
August, when the adult ticks are looking for blood before laying
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 12 percent of human cases occur from March through
May. However, not all ticks are infected all the time. The woods
and fields are relatively safe for about two weeks in August before
the eggs hatch and during winter when the ground is frozen.
</P>
<P>
   A deer tick, which is the size of a period on this page, has to
be attached for 24 to 48 hours to transmit the disease. The ticks
crawl to protected areas under cuffs, collars, and waist bands, and
they will hide in hair. They should be removed with tweezers, after
being stunned with alcohol to get them to let go. Don't crush them
or leave the head attached. Check pets, too.
</P>
<P>
   If flu-like symptoms develop in 2 to 20 days, or if a red ring
develops around a bite, see a doctor. When diagnosed early, Lyme
disease can be treated with antibiotics, so get treatment because
Lyme disease can affect victims long-term and can be debilitating.
</P>
<P>
   Precautions are worthwhile! Apply repellants containing DEET to
either skin or outside clothing. (Works for mosquitoes and black
flies, too.) Wear long pants tucked into socks, and each day, check
the family for ticks, especially children.
</P>
<P>
   DEET is absorbed through the skin, and a concentration of 10
percent to 35 percent is enough for adults. A concentration of 12
percent should last about four hours, 7 percent about 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Older children should have concentrations under 10 percent,
specialists say, and small children less. DEET should not be used
on babies, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Polymer extended-release products are absorbed less. Skedaddle
(6.5 percent and 10 percent) was formulated for children but can be
used by adults. HourGuard's 25 percent spray (which is supposed to
last eight hours) and the 35 percent cream (12 hours) was developed
by the Army for adults (available from Amway, 800-544-7167).
Skin-So-Soft does not deter ticks.
</P>
<P>
   Higher concentrations of DEET make it last longer, not work
better. It has been used for 40 years with some rare incidents of
sensitivity usually associated with overuse and sweating. So
carefully follow the directions on the label.
</P>
<P>
   One can also spray tents and clothing (but not people) with
permethrin, a synthetic pyrethrum, which will last for several
weeks, even through a few washings.
</P>
<P>
   Lawns can be sprayed with it, too, and that will last a few
weeks. Be aware, though, that a dog will carry whatever chemical
you put on your lawn into the house on its fur, not just the less
toxic pyrethrins but the more toxic grub and crabgrass pesticides
as well.
</P>
<P>
   A new Lyme disease vaccine is being advertised directly to the
public through television and magazines. However, serious
reservations remain in the medical profession.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that even after the necessary three doses of
vaccine (given over the course of a year), it gives only about
70-80 percent protection, according to the state Department of
Health. The first two doses, taken a month apart, provide
protection only 49 percent of the time, the department says.
</P>
<P>
   Length of protection is unknown at this time, but booster shots
may be needed. The vaccine is expensive ($180) and is only approved
for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Another worry, according to the Medical Letter on Drugs and
Therapeutics, a nonprofit review of drugs published for doctors, is
that though the few minor side effects are well tolerated, its
long-term safety is unknown. Of most concern are development of
antibiotic resistance if one is later infected and its effect on
rheumatoid arthritis and some other neurological conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Department of Public Health says it is
concerned because the vaccine does not protect against other
tick-borne diseases, and is not 100 percent effective against Lyme
disease but may give people a false sense of security so they do
not take preventive measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Partners Healthcare Newsletter suggests that, at this time,
the vaccine be given only to people in endemic areas who have
intense, long-term exposure such as landscapers, gardeners,
forestry workers, serious hikers, and campers.
</P>
<P>
   Partners says people who vacation for less than one to three
months have a less than 1 percent chance of getting Lyme disease,
and prompt treatment with antibiotics cures more than 90 percent of
patients with early stages of the disease, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
