<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8021 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-NOVELIST-JACKIE-     06-24 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-NOVELIST-JACKIE-COLLINS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKIE COLLINS' HOLLYWOOD LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of novelist Jackie
Collins. 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    With 200 million copies of 21 books sold in more than 40
countries, Jackie Collins is the McDonalds of the best-seller
lists.
 &HT;    The 50-something, British-born author, younger sister of actress
Joan Collins, has been a star in her own right since she published
her first novel, ``The World is Full of Married Men,'' in l968.
 &HT;    Its success spelled the end of her fledgling acting career, and
led to ``The Stud'' (l969) and ``The World is Full of Divorced
Women'' (l975). All three were turned into British films,
controversial for their steamy sex scenes and perfectly geared to a
celebrity-obsessed public.
 &HT;    By the 1980s Collins had settled in Hollywood and begun making
novelistic hay from her show-business connections. Such provocative
tales as ``Hollywood Wives'' (1983) give her readers the delicious
illusion of getting the inside dope on Tinseltown's dirty little
secrets and the big, bad and beautiful people who keep them.
 &HT;    Widowed in l992 after a 23-year marriage that produced three
now-grown daughters, Collins lives in a 16,000-square-foot mansion
in Beverly Hills _ white with leopard-skin accessories _ where she
continues to churn out her racy, thinly veiled romans-a-clef,
drawing on her insider's knowledge of the goings-on in Hollywood.
Several of these have in turn become hit television miniseries _
``Chances'' (l981), ``Hollywood Wives'' and ``Lucky'' (l985).
 &HT;    ``Dangerous Kiss,'' published this month by Simon and Schuster,
returns to the glitzy life of Lucky Santangelo, a woman who has it
all _ children, a great marriage and a lucrative career as a
Hollywood studio chief.
 &HT;    The other day I dropped by for a chat with Collins. Clad in
black pants, Robert Clergerie shoes and a black Armani jacket with
a lipstick-red collar, the author _ who is recently engaged to
real-estate pro Frank Calcagnini _ sat down amid her walls of David
Hockneys, tabletops crowded with her signature leopards and shelves
laden with translations of her books in a dozen different languages
to offer some no-holds-barred insight into her world. 
 -0- 
 &HT;    IVOR DAVIS: How did you get into writing?
 &HT;    JACKIE COLLINS: I grew up intrigued by the novels of Harold
Robbins and Mickey Spillane. Their books seemed very exciting, but
women were always stuck in the bedroom or kitchen and didn't seem
to do much at all.
 &HT;    So I decided I'd put my women out there doing everything men can
do _ only better.
 &HT;    Q: Are your characters based on real people?
 &HT;    COLLINS: Real life is much stranger than fiction, so although I
write about Hollywood I have to tone my characters down. How could
I match the stories of O.J. Simpson, the Menendez brothers or Heidi
Fleiss?
 &HT;    Some of my characters are quite recognizable, although they are
composites of actual people, not one person in particular.
 &HT;    Q: Let's get personal. Is marriage in your future?
 &HT;    COLLINS: I like being engaged. As an engaged couple they still
sit us together at Hollywood dinner parties. If we were married
they'd seat us apart. We don't like to be separated.
 &HT;    But we both feel marriage is just a piece of paper. If we're in
a romantic place and feel like it, we'll get married. To me being
married is having kids _ and I've got my family.
 &HT;    Q: So whose house is home?
 &HT;    COLLINS: We're perfectly happy the way we are. He has his house,
I have mine. We live together in whichever house is convenient for
that particular night.
 &HT;    Q: Who was the first person to break your heart?
 &HT;    COLLINS: When I was about 13 I looked about 18, and I made a
date with this American guy in London whose name was Cliff. He
looked exactly like Rock Hudson, and was supposed to meet me at
Baker Street underground station. I turned up but he didn't _ I
think he found out I was only 13.
 &HT;    Q: When was the last time you cried?
 &HT;    COLLINS: Last week I threw my shoulder out lifting weights. I
was in tears, absolute tears from the pain.
 &HT;    Q: What's in your handbag?
 &HT;    COLLINS: A camera. A phone. Makeup. A notebook, three or four
felt pens. Peppermints and Angel perfume.
 &HT;    I always snap a lot of photos at Hollywood parties, because I
worry that something might happen and I won't be able to photograph
it. I've got some great stuff. Maybe I'll do a picture book called
``Hollywood Snaps.'' It could be fun.
 &HT;    Q: What's your most shameless indulgence?
 &HT;    COLLINS: Chocolate and traveling first class. Not just any
chocolate _ it has to be those great orange-peel sticks covered
with milk chocolate.
 &HT;    Q: What would you do if you ruled the world?
 &HT;    COLLINS: I'd make sure that everybody had enough food _ and
chocolate _ and that things were fair for people.
 &HT;    Q: What turns you on?
 &HT;    COLLINS: A man in a suit with his tie slightly loosened. I go
for a slightly rumpled look in a perfect man. I prefer older men.
 &HT;    Q: What's your biggest fear?
 &HT;    COLLINS: Spiders. I hate them. If I find one, I drop a
wastepaper basket over the spider until I can find somebody who
will take it out and throw it away.
 &HT;    In these parts there are black widows that have a deadly bite _
but I don't examine them closely enough to check their identities.
 &HT;    Q: If you could meet one person on earth, who would that be?
 &HT;    COLLINS: Probably Bill Clinton, and I'd like to say to him,
``Why?''
 &HT;    Q: What's the most surprising thing about you?
 &HT;    COLLINS: When people meet me, they have my image confused with
the characters that I write. So they expect me to be more of a
bitch.
 &HT;    I don't think I am. I'm quite down to earth. People don't expect
me to be nice.
 &HT;    Q: What do you do for kicks?
 &HT;    COLLINS: Travel. I'm taking a trip on a private yacht with
friends this summer. We leave from Antibes to ports like Portofino
and Capri. Maybe I'll also be taking notes.
 &HT;    Q: Where do you go to shop?
 &HT;    COLLINS: The Serpette flea market in Paris. I don't shop for
clothes _ I've picked up an Art Deco desk and a fabulous
leopard-skin couch and chairs from the '20s. I get paintings and
beautiful old furniture.
 &HT;    Q: What do you despise and love about Hollywood?
 &HT;    COLLINS: I despise the phoniness of some people in Hollywood,
and I love the fact that it's really a little village.
 &HT;    Q: What are you plotting next on the book front?
 &HT;    COLLINS: A ``Hollywood Wives'' for the new millennium. It has
changed completely since my first ``Wives'' book in l983.
 &HT;    Then the women were behind their husbands, pushing and doing
what they could to help them. Today the Hollywood wives are the
Kate Capshaws and the Rita Wilsons. They have seven or eight kids,
maybe one nanny. They are looking after the house, looking after
the kids and have a career as well.
 &HT;    They are very equal with their husbands and do everything
together. It's a whole different dynamic.
 &HT;    Or they are Roseanne, paying their husbands the alimony.
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Jackie Collins, consult the
Simon &AMP; Schuster Website at www.simonsays.com/collins. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
