<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8027 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      06-24 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUBBORN CASEMENT MAY NEED NEW ARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETEER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My Andersen casement windows are very hard to operate, and
they are only 12 years old. I sprayed WD-40 and other dry lubes on
the tracks and operating arms, which helped some, but they are
still hard to move. What else can I do?
</P>
<P>
   GLENN MILLEY, Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Call the manufacturer or the dealer. Andersen, like most
manufacturers of building components, is very sensitive to any
malfunctions or complaints, and might be able to do something.
</P>
<P>
   What has probably happened is that the operating arms are bent,
possibly by trying to force-crank the windows closed, particularly
if the windows are tight in their frames. This would account for
the dry lube helping some, but not a lot. You can buy replacement
arms at virtually any dealer or building supply house. The handyman
had just that problem with one of his casements, so he undid the
arm and took it to a store where he found a replacement. Worked
like a charm. The arms are relatively easy to remove and install.
If the handyman can do it without messing things up, anyone can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My patio roof, of corrugated fiberglass, is outside my
bedroom window, and when nuts from an overhanging tree start
falling, it's like it's hailing baseballs; a real sleep disturber.
What can I put on the roof to muffle those cannonball impacts?
</P>
<P>
   JIM FITZPATRICK, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Hmm. You could put Astroturf or indoor-outdoor carpeting on
the roof. Either will provide good padding to deaden the sound of
the falling nuts. Both are breathable; that is, when they get wet,
they will dry out quickly. And, since the nut storm is seasonal,
you can take off the covering for most of the year. Or, suspend a
tarp over the roof, raising it a few inches. Or, put plywood on top
of the roof, then cover it with roll roofing. It all depends on the
size of the roof.
</P>
<P>
   The ony problem with the above is that anything you cover the
roof with will cut out a lot of light coming through the
translucent fiberglass panels. I don't advocate cutting down the
tree but you could cut some of the overhanging branches, which
would be a good idea anyway if they are that close to the house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My pull-down attic stairs have some cheesy braces; in fact
the whole thing is cheesy, from a chain lumber store. Where can I
get quality folding stairs?
</P>
<P>
   DOUG BAIRD, Charlestown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Brockway-Smith, a large distributor of windows, doors,
staircases, and a million other manufactured house items, offers
three grades of folding stairs, which might be called good, better,
and best. You can order one from any local (not chain) lumber
store. The chains sometimes offer a middle-grade product.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I live in a 1750 house with soft pine floorboards. How can I
preserve them? Should they be sanded?
</P>
<P>
   PATSY REYNOLDS, Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Floors were often never finished in Colonial days, or were
painted. If yours were never finished, they are pretty dirty, and
there is no way you can clean them, or get them back ``new''
looking without sanding. But you can sand softwoods such as pine,
hard pine, fir, and cedar. Some people say you can't sand
softwoods; yes you can, but you want to be a little careful that
you don't get carried away.
</P>
<P>
   So, you can sand, and apply several coats of oil-based
polyurethane varnish. Or, if the floor is relatively smooth and
only dirty, you can clean it with paint thinner, then apply a floor
paint.
</P>
<P>
   I have never liked painted floors, mainly because paint does not
stand up well under wear and tear, and it peels more readily than
properly applied varnish. I have sanded my 1768 wide pine floors,
some with a belt sander (never again!) and some with a floor
sander, and they came out wonderfully.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I notice you recommend putting up cedar clapboards rough side
out. Why?
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN WACHMAN, Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Three reasons: 1. They do not look different from
smooth-side-out clapboards. 2. The rough side holds stain, primer,
and paint better (stain is better than primer and paint). 3. It is
difficult for anything to stick to the smooth, planed surface,
partly because the planers at the factory sometimes heat the wood,
melting resin to form an impenetrable surface glaze.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Several weeks ago I heard squirrels scampering in the attic.
I can see the hole where they entered. I tried repellents, which
made them scamper even more, but not out. I tried an ultrasound
machine without success. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   VICTOR JONES, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Wait. Check the attic in the daytime; squirrels usually go
back to their nests (in this case, your attic) at night. When you
know they are all out, plug the hole and cover with galvanized
steel plates. If the wood around the hole is soft and punky,
replace it. Squirrels may leave sound, well-painted or stained wood
alone, but once they get have gotten into the attic, they might try
again, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   Making sure all the squirrels are out of the attic is critical.
If they have babies, they're not going to leave for a while, so you
have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in a hurry, call a pest control specialist who will
remove the rodents. You can find such persons in the Yellow Pages
under ``Exterminators.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
