<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8031 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-24 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTED RITUAL FILLS A NEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ours is a culture with few rituals.
</P>
<P>
   We move around so much that it's considered perfectly natural
for people to come and go without any ceremony at all. In order to
make life's transitions meaningful, people often have to invent
their own rituals, imagining the details as they go along. That's
what my friend Kaiya did when her older daughter, Shannon, was
about to move from Marblehead, where she and her husband had lived
all their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying to my younger daughter,'' Kaiya tells me, ``that
in other cultures they might pass the hat as a way of saying, `We
give you our blessings.' I wanted to give Shannon and Mark some
kind of send-off, and Ali said that at Esalen, a personal growth
center in California where she lived for a while, that when someone
left, they had an auction to raise money for them. That's what
started us off.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiya and Ali put their heads together, and this is what they
came up with: a potluck supper at a local church, along with a
silent auction, a storyteller to entertain the kids, an altarlike
table with candles, flowers, and photographs, including a collage
of all the families in Shannon's mother's group, a book in which
people could write down memories for Mark and Shannon to take with
them, and a ceremony during which guests could reminisce about
their relationship with the departing couple.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon's dad made up a sheet of paper for each item offered in
the silent auction, and since guests could write down their bid at
any time during the evening, they were put under no pressure. The
auction featured items like an afternoon sailboat ride, a car
cleaning, a night at a bed and breakfast owned by a guest, and a
massage; objects that people had but no longer enjoyed, like a step
machine and antique prints; and creative endeavors, such as
notecards made out of photographs. One of the offerings, a flight
in a small plane, which was purchased for $85 at a previous
auction, was sold for $55 to someone who plans to resell it at an
upcoming church auction.
</P>
<P>
   You might call this item a flight of the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised enough money to pay moving expenses,'' Kaiya says,
``and everyone ended up with something they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a group that eats organic, that dotes on vegetarian
dishes, that expresses its love through food. The food was
delicious. As his gift, Tony Toledo, a local storyteller, kept the
kids entranced with his tales.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the evening was a sharing ceremony, using an
American Indian talking stick. The stick itself was 7 feet tall _
Erica, who'd volunteered to make it, had misunderstood the
directions and thought she was making a ``walking'' stick _ and it
was decorated with bittersweet vines, pods, sticks, flowers,
feathers, and even bits of plastic trash collected at Mark and
Shannon's favorite conservation spot. The person holding it spoke
without interruption as the group stood in a circle for more than
an hour, listening to tributes from folks who had shared with the
two of them the work of raising children, preserving the
environment, creating an organic food co-op and a nature camp, and
raising public consciousness about the value of the natural world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how proud you are of your kids,'' says Pete,
Shannon's dad. ``Well, it's different when you stand back and
listen to other people speak about your child as an adult. It was
very exciting to hear what other people had to say, and now I feel
as if my children are my peers.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a little more difficult for Mark. ``It's very unusual to
be in the position of receiving, and receiving without giving
anything back. During the sharing, I felt a bit uncomfortable at
first, but it was such a touching experience to have people gather
together to honor who you really are. It was really moving for us.
No pun intended,'' Mark says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   This is what it means to be embedded in a supportive community
working together on cooperative endeavors, and why it is so
enriching to ground yourself in a larger reality than just your
nuclear family and your work. This is what it means to have made a
difference. When there are so many caring people in your life, it
takes a minimum of effort for each of them to provide something to
eat, something to auction, something to think about, and something
of sustaining value to take with you when you leave a fruitful
phase of your life behind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
