<HEADER>
A8033 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EPILEPSY-TREATMENT-BO     06-24 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPILEPSY-TREATMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP SEEN FOR EPILEPSY PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maureen Horrigan, 17, has suffered epileptic seizures since she
was 4 1/2 years old. For years, she woke up every morning with a
seizure and often got them when she was tired, losing
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   After years of trying different medications, she and her parents
opted for surgery at Children's Hospital in Boston in 1998. Doctors
shaved off her long, brown hair and implanted 148 monitoring
electrodes for two weeks in order to locate where in her brain the
seizures originated. Once surgeons located suspect areas, they
removed them.
</P>
<P>
   But the monitoring period offered an opportunity to Brandeis
University neuroscientists. While they would never subject even a
volunteer to such invasive testing, they asked the Windham, N.H.,
teenager if she would play a computer maze game during the
presurgical monitoring period. During the video game, they observed
the electrical activity in her brain to test a hypothesis that
certain brain waves are associated with navigational and spatial
learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have anything better to do. I could give up Jerry
Springer to help them out,'' said Horrigan.
</P>
<P>
   While Horrigan and other presurgical epileptic teenagers
maneuvered around the virtual mazes, Michael Kahana, an assistant
professor of psychology and neuroscience at Brandeis, found
episodes of a slow brain wave activity, called theta oscillations.
</P>
<P>
   Normal brain waves occur at different frequencies that are
linked to various brain functions. One rhythm of about 10 cycles
per second, the alpha wave, is associated with relaxation. The
theta wave is about four to seven cycles per second.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say that although there have been many animal studies
linking these brain waves to spatial learning and navigation, there
have not been studies showing the link in humans.
</P>
<P>
   The study, the first to establish this link in humans, is
published in this week's Nature magazine.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kahana, the theta oscillation brain waves may be
the key to learning and remembering how to find our way from one
place to another.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gyorgy Buzsaki, a professor of neuroscience at Rutgers
University who has done many studies on theta oscillations in
animals, said that proof of theta activity in humans is
significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If theta waves were absent in humans, then these theories and
studies done on animals would not apply to the human brain,''
Buzsaki said.
</P>
<P>
   In the video game, the researchers first led players through the
mazes with arrows placed at junctions. In a second round of trials,
they removed the arrows, leaving the teenagers to rely on their
memory to find their own way through the complex set of twist and
turns.
</P>
<P>
   Watching electrical signals, Kahana and his colleagues found
that various parts of the brain, including some not related to
seizure activity, produced the theta oscillations during both sets
of trials.
</P>
<P>
   During the experiment, theta oscillations occurred more
frequently and were more pronounced in mazes of greater complexity,
and they were more frequent during the recall trials than the
learning trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't simply show that there were theta oscillations, but
also the degree to which you see them,'' Kahana said. ``By
manipulating the task demands and complexity, you can modulate the
oscillations, which makes the evidence much stronger that
oscillations have something to do with our learning tasks.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Joseph Madsen, a neurosurgeon at Children's
Hospital and one of the study authors, the findings could help
neurosurgeons operating on epileptic patients do a better job of
removing parts of the brain without disturbing healthy parts
important for memory and other critical brain functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't really come up with a definitive test of where
memory is,'' said Madsen.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are also noninvasive methods for detecting
functional areas of the brain, such as functional magnetic
resonance imaging, which shows where the brain is activated in an
anatomic fashion, said Dr. Steven Schachter, an epilepsy specialist
at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The new study ``is an important finding in its own right,''
Schachter said. ``I don't see it necessarily helps doctors now, but
perhaps, maybe there is a long-term spinoff for epileptic
patients.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
