</P>
<P>
   INTEREST-RATES (Washington) _ Is it 1994 all over again, the
beginning of a prolonged series of interest rate increases intended
to wring inflationary pressures out of an economy that is
threatening to overheat? Or is it 1997, when the Federal Reserve
bumped interest rates up once just to let everyone know it was on
the case, and then let the economy go on its rip-roaring way? By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   COCA-COLA-EUROPE (Bornem, Belgium) _ ``I'll never drink Coke
again,'' one Belgian youth said Thursday after getting sick from
drinking a Coca-Cola 10 days ago. That is exactly the sentiment
that the Coca Cola Company fears most in Belgium and many other
parts of Europe after the biggest recall in its 113-year history.
By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   GANNETT (Undated) _ The Gannett Co., the publisher of USA Today
and dozens of other newspapers, offers $1.5 billion for the British
regional newspaper chain Newsquest, which describes the offer as
``serious and fair,'' but stops short of urging shareholders to
accept it. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co.
becomes the latest Wall Street firm to report
stronger-than-expected earnings thanks to a surge in trading. By
Sholnn Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
