<HEADER>
A8062 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-WHITE27-COX     06-24 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WHITE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    blanc expressions
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 27.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pope wears it religiously. So does ``A Man in Full'' author
Tom Wolfe. Tennis fanatics court it faithfully. Brides and
debutantes also slip into it on their big day.
</P>
<P>
   It's the color white, the hottest shade for warm-weather
dressing and the perfect antidote to endless seasons of black.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's called a color, white technically is not. It's
simply a shade caused by the reflection of all the sun's rays that
do produce color.
</P>
<P>
   Every fashion look this season _cargo trousers, pretty peasant
petticoats and blouses, a simple T-shirt _ is represented in white,
in such fabrics as ribbed cottons and nubby linens, as well as
high-tech synthetics and open-weave silks. Designer Donna Morgan
did a series of white dresses for summer, ranging from a sleek
sleeveless sheath to a laced-back sundress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple styles make white as easy to wear as black,'' said the
designer. ``And on a hot day, white just feels fresh and clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Hinson, Nordstrom's East Coast fashion director, thinks
white makes the most modern statement when worn head to toe. ``But
women will also find it easy to combine the many shades of white,''
she said, ``such as bright white, ecru, ivory and cement, for
maximum versatility.''
</P>
<P>
   These shades of white complement each other and work well with
darker colors. They also give a woman options when choosing the
most flattering white for her skin tone. According to Hinson,
brunettes with olive skin look best in bright white, while those
with fair skin and light hair look best in creamier shades.
</P>
<P>
   New York color forecaster Carole D'Arconte of Color Portfolio
Inc. refers to white as ``the silent color'' and ``the flavor of
the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fashion,'' she said, `` we've gone through the baby colors
of blue and pink. Now, we are starting all over with white. It's
virginal. It's pure. And white will take us into the year 2000 and
beyond, along with silver.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep your whites bright
</P>
<P>
   White clothing can get downright dirty in a hurry. If your
whites are cottons and cotton blends, simply throw them into the
washer. If they are cut from silk, rayon or linen, have them
dry-cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Allsbrooks of the International Fabricare Institute in
Maryland suggests the following ways to keep clothes bright and
white:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  White clothing should not be stored or hung in direct
sunlight. Most whites contain brightening agents that are broken
down by exposure to light. This contributes to yellow streaks or
discoloration. Unfortunately, once an item has been discolored due
to loss of brightener, there's no way to return it to its original
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't overuse chlorine bleach. It can break down the
brighteners in white garments. And never pour bleach directly onto
fabrics. Always dilute in wash water or a spray water bottle before
using.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If possible, remove stains when ``fresh'' by using home stain
removal products followed by washing. The longer a stain remains in
a fabric, the greater the chance that it will become permanently
``set.'' Incidentally, seltzer water makes a good stain remover.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure you don't overload your washing machine. If you cram
too much in, there may not be enough water flow for soil removal.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
