<HEADLINE>
BANKS UNITE IN ON-LINE BILLING VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In another leap forward for electronic commerce,
three of the nation's largest banks have formed a new venture to
deliver bills electronically to on-line consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The system, known as the Exchange, will serve as a hub to route
electronic bills to 60 million potential bank customers and 59,000
businesses that mail mountains of bills each year.
</P>
<P>
   The executives of Wells Fargo &AMP; Co., Chase Manhattan Corp. and
First Union Corp. hope the venture will help them establish a
stronghold in the young and untested market for on-line bill
delivery, known in the industry as bill presentment.
</P>
<P>
   On-line banking has grown slowly because of consumer fears about
technology, security and privacy. Bank executives argue that banks,
as trusted financial institutions with longstanding ties to
customers, are the best business creatures to usher in the on-line
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Bank executives said the Exchange would be a great convenience
for consumers who want to view and pay all of their bills in one
simple format by using their personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The system also will save billions of dollars for corporations,
such as telephone, utility and cable companies, which spend $1.50
to $2.70 to deliver each bill statement in paper form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the very beginning of a very important, emerging
business,'' said Sharon Osberg, head of Wells Fargo Online
Financial Services. ``We believe we're filling a gap in the
marketplace, and the Exchange is the missing link.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Braco, a Chase Manhattan executive, added: ``Easy access
to a critical mass of billers and consumers is fundamental to the
wide-scale growth of electronic bill presentment and payment.''
</P>
<P>
   The banks teamed up on the venture in January. They will test
the new system in the next few days, then roll it out nationwide in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Bank executives declined to say how much the venture is costing,
but they said each bank is investing an equal amount and will share
any profits in the venture.
</P>
<P>
   New York City-based Chase Manhattan is the nation's second
largest bank, with $368 billion in assets. First Union, based in
Charlotte, N.C., is the sixth largest, with $223 billion in assets.
San Francisco-based Wells Fargo is the seventh biggest bank, with
$201 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   The Exchange will use software and other technology from Sun
Microsystems Inc. and Visa USA Inc. The technology will be
developed by Sun, while Visa will supply several software
components and support to the system.
</P>
<P>
   The Exchange will compete for customers with other similar
ventures, such as Integrion Financial Network, partly owned by
BankAmerica Corp., and TransPoint, formed two years ago by the
Microsoft Corp., First Data Corp. and Citigroup Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
