<SLUG> BC-UAL-SHANGHAI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED TO START DIRECT FLIGHTS TO SHANGHAI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ United Airlines plans to begin nonstop service
from San Francisco to Shanghai next spring. It would be the first
nonstop service for an American carrier to the Chinese city since
United suspended summertime-only flights three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Department of Transportation awarded five
``frequencies,'' or scheduled flights, to United for use between
the United States and China, according to United spokesman Matthew
Triaca. United has elected to use all five to serve the
Shanghai-San Francisco route, which means it will fly between the
two cities nonstop five days a week, year-round. The exact launch
date and days of service are to be decided, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is regarded as the industrial and financial center of
China, and Silicon Valley and the Bay Area are key business
centers,'' Triaca said. ``There is also a large Chinese community
in the Bay Area. We're going to link these two complementary
business centers.''
</P>
<P>
   United is the biggest carrier at San Francisco International
Airport, with half of all flights and passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Air China, China's flag carrier, flies twice a week nonstop
between San Francisco and Beijing and Shanghai. Other major
carriers, such as Northwest, fly to Shanghai via Tokyo or Beijing,
with a change of planes required.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco airport's director of international
development, Greg Moix, said the airport vigorously lobbied the
Department of Transportation for the new service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business travelers will be a large portion of the
passengers,'' Moix predicted. Business travelers require frequent
flights, pay high fares and often fly on short notice, making them
lucrative customers for airlines that can offer frequency and
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Chicago-based airline, which is owned by the
UAL Corp., said: ``More than 30 business and community
organizations _ including a number of high-tech companies based in
Silicon Valley _ sent letters in support of the new service to the
Clinton administration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
