<SLUG> BC-HOME-PRICES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIAN HOME PRICE SURGES IN SAN FRANCISCO AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The median price for a home in the San Francisco
Bay Area has passed the $300,000 milestone.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, homes resold in the nine-county region in
May edged past that figure to reach a median of $301,000, according
to Acxiom/DataQuick, a real estate information service.
</P>
<P>
   No other region in the state comes close to the Bay Area
figures, Acxiom/DataQuick analyst John Karevoll said. The next
closest area was Orange County, where the median price of a home
was $262,000. Overall, the median price for a home in California
was $181,000 last month.
</P>
<P>
   The rising prices in the Bay Area are caused by a robust economy
and a dearth of homes. Yet Karevoll said it could be _ and has been
_ worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are high and it does give you sticker shock. But
when you take into account the mortgage rates that are prevailing
now, you still pay less money each month than you were 10 years
ago,'' he said. ``Homes seem horrendously expensive and an
increasing number of people are being priced out of the market, but
it is still much better than the frenzy of '88, '89 and '90.''
</P>
<P>
   The median price for a Bay Area home in May increased 3.1
percent from the $292,000 reported in April. The May figure was up
7.5 percent from $280,000 in the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
   The highest median home price by county were:
</P>
<P>
   _ $450,000 in Marin, up 20 percent from May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ $420,000 in San Mateo, up 14.4 percent from the year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   _ $372,000 in San Francisco, up 8.5 percent from May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the number of resale homes sold in the Bay Area in
May dipped to 7,331 from 7,849 in April, a 6.6 percent drop.
Karevoll said this was a normal fluctuation in the market, which
saw a 5.3 percent increase in the number of homes resold a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest increase in sales is happening in Solano County as
well as some of the cities on the outskirts of Alameda and Contra
Costa counties, Karevoll said. Solano County experienced the
greatest percentage increase in homes sold _ a 28 percent jump from
last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing now is that the entry-level market is coming
back on line with the rest of the markets,'' Karevoll said,
explaining the more affluent sectors responded more quickly to the
economy's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The real estate service expects sales counts to stay at current
levels through the rest of the summer and into fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
