<SLUG> BC-NEWS-RACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES IN NEWSPAPERS' FAVOR ON NEWS RACK LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judge has temporarily blocked the city
of San Francisco from launching a program to banish thousands of
old-style news racks and replace them with new vending devices in
designated places.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Saundra Brown Armstrong of Oakland issued a
preliminary injunction on Wednesday against the city's new ``Fixed
Pedestal Newsracks'' ordinance, saying the plan intended to tidy up
crowded street corners posed a threat of censorship.
</P>
<P>
   In a 47-page ruling, Armstrong concluded that the Department of
Public Works had the right to ban individual news racks from parts
of San Francisco, and to require publishers to apply for permits to
distribute newspapers from news pedestals for a $30 annual fee.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said a group of publishers who challenged the
ordinance had raised ``a serious question concerning the adequacy
of procedural safeguards'' that were necessary to ensure that the
city could not indefinitely delay decisions on granting permits.
</P>
<P>
   On that basis she prohibited the plan from proceeding, pending
further hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ordinance fails to prescribe adequate time limits by which
cubicle permit decisions are to be made, and also fails to provide
for adequate judicial review of permit decisions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This potential for delay is one of the dangers of prior
restraints,'' she said, noting that the ordinance specifies no time
limits for city officials to respond to appeals from publishers
denied access to the pedestal vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   Under an ordinance approved a year ago by the Board of
Supervisors, the city plans to replace 12,000 free-standing news
racks with 1,000 ``fixed pedestal'' news racks containing cubicles
offering multiple publications.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Works director would designate pedestal-only zones in
``highly congested areas, or areas with particular public safety,
aesthetic, historical or economic concerns,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers became concerned that too few, or poorly located,
cubicles would cut into revenue and the free flow of information.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed in January by the San Francisco Newspaper
Agency, the business arm of he San Francisco Examiner and the San
Francisco Chronicle; SF Weekly; the San Francisco Bay Guardian; the
New York Times; the Los Angeles Times; and the San Jose Mercury
News.
</P>
<P>
   The publishers agree that the city has a legitimate interest in
promoting urban aesthetics and safe sidewalks, and that the
profusion of news racks can be a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   But their suit contends _ and the city denies _ that the
ordinance is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers hailed the ruling and said they hoped to work with
city officials to revise the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted that a federal judge has recognized the
constitutional problem that we saw with this ordinance,'' said
Steven Falk, president and chief executive officer of the San
Francisco Newspaper Agency.
</P>
<P>
   James Rizzi, publisher of the SF Weekly, said: ``We feel like we
have very deliberately been kept out of the process. Hopefully,
we'll be a little bit more involved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
