<HEADER>
A8080 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN     06-24 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THIN RED LINE': A MEDITATION ON MEN AND WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A lot of critics praised Terrence Malick's ``The
Thin Red Line'' last year, with the film picking up seven Oscar
nominations. A number of others, though, felt the film was a bore
and that writer/director Malick was just diddling around with
endless nature shots. (Malick never met a leaf he didn't like,
remarked one wag.)
</P>
<P>
   But those nature shots _ though overdone at times _ were
integral to the film's themes, and ``The Thin Red Line, which comes
out on video Tuesday, possesses a flawed but worthy artistic
vision.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins with two soldiers who have gone AWOL and are
living contentedly with a tribe on a Pacific island. The two are
then captured and returned to their Army company for the assault on
what is being called a strategically important hill on Guadalcanal
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the world a man himself is nothing and there is no world
but this one,'' Sgt. Welsh (Sean Penn) tells one of the AWOL
soldiers, Pvt. Witt (Jim Caviezel) before the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're wrong,'' Witt replies. ``I've seen another world.
Sometimes I think it was my imagination,'' he says, referring to
the island idyll where he lived within nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you've seen things I never will,'' says Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing and not seeing is at the heart of the film. Unlike last
year's other war film, ``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``Line'' isn't
directly about heroism and sacrifice _ though both occur. In fact,
when a few of the characters are cited for bravery, they want to
shun the honor. But, ironically, when another is cited so that his
commander can get rid of him for caring too much about his men, he
accepts gladly, which is contrary to what you would expect in a
typical war film.
</P>
<P>
   Malick, for the most part, is trying to create a transcendental
experience as he did in his last film, 1978's ``Days of Heaven.''
Despite a stellar cast _ Nick Nolte, Sean Penn, Woody Harrelson,
John Cusack _ the characters are not fully formed. We get to know
bits about them through their internal monologues, though at times
it is unclear whose thoughts are being voiced. At other times, they
all seem interchangeable with names like Fife, Gaff, Bell, Tall,
Witt.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the thoughts are philosophical, but mostly they are
bits of memories, fears, rationalizations, justifications and the
fragility of life. Not for a moment do you believe that what you're
hearing would be the real voices of the men _ the thoughts are too
sculpted, too poetic to be those of anyone in a combat zone. Malick
has meant them to be _ as in a novel _ a distillation of the
characters' frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Around them as they try to take a grassy hill from a hidden
enemy, nature remains indifferent. It goes on whether man looks up
from his endeavors _ in this case, battle _ long enough to think
about his place in it or not. That's what those nature shots are
about. They are in contrast to characters like Nolte's Col. Tall, a
career soldier who sees the battle as his one chance for glory
after having studied war for so long, including reading Homer in
Greek while at West Point.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte gives one of the film's few full-blooded performances.
``You are not gonna take your men around in the jungle to avoid a
goddamn fight,'' he snarls at a subordinate after his troops have
been bloodied badly.
</P>
<P>
   What Malick captures is the confusion _ the chaos _ of battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be the best friend you've ever had,'' Welsh tells Witt
during a respite in the fighting, ``and you don't know it.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this is overly profound. At times, Malick doesn't seem
to have a handle on what he's trying to do. And ``Line'' is a bit
too arty for its own good.
</P>
<P>
   But what Malick has done is give us a film that creates a
cinematic sense of the mind-set of war. It may not be totally
successful, but with so many literal and simple-minded films out
there these days, Malick should be commended. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
