<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8081 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POTATO-SALAD-HNS &LR;      06-24 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTATO-SALAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT DOESN'T TAKE AN ARMY TO MAKE, OR EAT, POTATO SALAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Who says making potato salad means peeling
potatoes? And who decreed you have to make enough for an army? And
what law requires potato salad to contain mayonnaise? Thanks to the
grab-and-go nature of products in the supermarkets, making recipes
that were once labor-intensive, like potato salad, are now fast,
easy and flavorful.
</P>
<P>
   In the produce department, start by buying little plastic net
bags of baby potatoes. Available in red, white and Yukon gold
varieties, the bags save the time you'd spend in the store
selecting potatoes. And since there are only 28 ounces of spuds in
a bag, each one makes enough salad for eight people, not 80.
</P>
<P>
   Baby potatoes have thin skins so you don't need to peel them
before, or after, cooking them. And since the bags usually contain
potatoes of similar size, they'll all cook in roughly the same
amount of time (about 30 minutes on a simmer), so you needn't spend
time cutting the big ones.
</P>
<P>
   To buy other salad ingredients, take a stroll down the salad
bar. Celery, carrots, pickles, hard-cooked eggs, olives ... they're
all there, washed and ready to be cut and tossed into the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Want bacon in your salad? Run to the packaged meat section and
pick up a box of heat-and-eat bacon. These precooked products make
adding bacon to potato salad, baked beans or BLTs much easier by
letting you leave the frying pan in the cabinet. Just cut the bacon
into bite-size pieces and add them in. If you want your bacon warm,
you can heat it in the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Once all your ingredients are chopped, dress your potato salad
with something to hold it together. At one time mayonnaise mixed
with salt, pepper and a splash of cider vinegar was the preferred
dressing. Then came the practice of adding mustard to the
mayonnaise to make a tangy binder. But don't be shy about adding
other ingredients to suit your taste. A teaspoon of sugar can go in
if you prefer a sweeter dressing. Use sour cream for a more tart
dressing, or a spoonful of fresh snipped chives or dill for an
herbal flavor.
</P>
<P>
   For a Mediterranean flavor, dress them with oil, vinegar and a
tablespoon or two of toasted mustard seeds such as in the following
recipe. If you want to convert your side dish potato salad into
cool entree, toss is a can of tuna, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIGHT POTATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 6 to 8 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1 (28-ounce) bag baby red or baby Yukon gold potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup white-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh snipped dill
</P>
<P>
   1 (6.5-ounce) can tuna, drained and flaked (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Place potatoes in a 3 1/2-quart saucepan and add water to cover.
Bring to a boil over medium-high heat, then reduce to a simmer. Let
potatoes cook for about 30 minutes or until a meat fork will poke
through a potato easily. Drain and run under cold water to stop the
cooking process. Cut potatoes into bite-size pieces. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place mustard seeds in a skillet and heat over medium heat,
shaking pan occasionally, until seeds begin to lightly brown and
release their aroma.
</P>
<P>
   Combine vinegar, oil, dill and mustard seeds in a large bowl and
whisk to combine. Add potato chunks, and tuna if using, and toss to
combine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
