<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S PLUNGE INTO PERVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hats off to the San Francisco Chamber of
Commerce for stating loudly, clearly and officially that the
Definition of Marriage initiative is a nasty piece of work that is
no good for California.
</P>
<P>
   A March 2000 election might seem a long way off, but in
political time it is dead ahead. Fair-minded folks all over the
state need to get off their complacent duffs and start working to
defeat this gratuitous, wasteful and reactionary ballot measure.
</P>
<P>
   As Rhea Serpan, president and chief executive of the chamber,
said: ``The Knight initiative is a mean-spirited attack that is
meant to be divisive, not to help California come together to grow
and prosper and celebrate its diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The creation of state Sen. Pete Knight, a Republican from
Palmdale, the marriage initiative is the sort of law they just love
to pass in progressive states like Oklahoma, Mississippi and
Indiana. It is based on a faulty premise _ heterosexual marriage is
in danger of losing its long-dominant standing in society _ and
blames gays and lesbians for the non-attack.
</P>
<P>
   Like the many ``family values'' members of Congress who felt
compelled to pass the Defense of Marriage Act in 1996, Knight and
his supporters want to legislate as though marriage is such a
fragile institution, it cannot survive woman-woman or man-man
versions.
</P>
<P>
   When they are talking about marriage between heterosexuals, of
course, the institution is the ``backbone'' of society and a
powerful stabilizing force for the future.
</P>
<P>
   But, in their view, when a woman pledges to take a woman as her
lifelong partner or a man promises himself to a man until death do
they part, marriage is a threat to the very fabric of America.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's initiative, which twice failed in the state
Legislature, seems to some a simple and harmless declaration of the
status quo. Since 1977, the state's Family Code has defined
marriage as ``a personal relation ... between a man and a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   But anti-gay rights folks like Knight are worried that some
other state _ Hawaii, Vermont or Alaska _ might do the unthinkable
and include homosexual unions under the definition of marriage.
Then gay people could move to California and their marriages would
be recognized as valid _ just as the state recognizes marriages
between cousins from states where that combination is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Knight's March ballot measure asks voters to affirm or
reject this: ``Only marriage between a man and a woman is valid or
recognized in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining gay and lesbian activists and a shipload of straight
sympathizers, the San Francisco Chamber of Commerce sees the
marriage initiative as anything but harmless. Serpan terms it
``discrimination,'' which the chamber ``has a proud history of
opposing ... in any form.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight's missionaries collected 650,000 signatures to
over-qualify the measure for the ballot, and every poll taken shows
it passing. Lesbian and gay activists figure they'll need at least
$10 million to fight the thing.
</P>
<P>
   That is a ridiculous waste of resources.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where underfunded public schools are a sad
contradiction to a booming economy, where a nonviolent prison
population is about to burst the seams of a system operating at 192
percent capacity, where hundreds of thousands of residents have no
health care coverage _ that waste is perverse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
