<HEADER>
A8097 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPOSED-BELIEFS-NYTSF     06-24 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPOSED-BELIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T CONFUSE CIVIC VALUES WITH RELIGIOUS VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By JIM CASTELLI  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Whenever a catastrophe like the Littleton massacre occurs, there
is a predictable call for a return to religion as a solution.
 &HT;    Most Americans associate religion with morality. But the two do
not necessarily go together.
 &HT;    American history is full of people who believe in God but
consistently act immorally; the use of the cross as a symbol by the
Ku Klux Klan is the most vivid example.
 &HT;    American history is also full of people like Thomas Paine, who
practiced no religion but acted morally.
 &HT;    Many calls for a ``return to religion'' are actually thinly
disguised efforts to impose a narrow religious view on the rest of
society. As American history has shown from day one, religion often
brings intolerance and conflict, not peace.
 &HT;    In addition, Americans rightly view religion as something which,
though it has public implications, is an intensely private matter.
The idea of forcing religious belief on someone, whether belief in
God or denial of God, is repugnant to Americans, who also
instinctively understand that no imposed belief can be genuine.
 &HT;    Seeing a simplistic return to religion as a solution to social
ills is actually a diversion from efforts to reduce violence and
rebuild community. If you want to get from Point A to Point C, then
Point B should be a step along the way, not a detour. If Point A is
America in 1999 and Point C is an America with less violence, then
making religion Point B is a dangerous detour.
 &HT;    That's because, while there are rational elements to religion,
religion is ultimately irrational -- it depends on faith, a belief
in something that cannot be proven. It's difficult enough to
convince people of anything with logic; it's far more difficult to
get them to make a leap of faith before they change their behavior.
 &HT;    Most people who believe in God admit they cannot prove God's
existence; they say they do not need rational proof. This is fine
for individuals, but a society does not have the luxury of relying
on irrational beliefs to sustain law, order, and justice.
 &HT;    Society does not exempt people from crucial laws because of
their beliefs. America does not let murderers go free because they
don't believe in God. The average criminal probably believes in
God, just not in society's right to tell him or her what to do.
 &HT;    Social peace does require shared values, but they must be civic,
not religious, in nature. Civic values are the beliefs members of a
society share across religious, racial, ethnic, gender, class, and
other divisions. There is some overlap between religious and civic
values, but there is a crucial distinction -- civic values don't
claim that they will get you into heaven, only that they will make
you a good citizen.
 &HT;    It's easy enough to identify basic American values -- freedom,
equality, justice, compassion, fairness, diversity. We find them in
America's core documents -- the Declaration of Independence, the
Constitution, and the Bill of Rights. These values go beyond the
United States. They are also reflected in principles accepted by
virtually every nation on earth.
 &HT;    You don't have to be a historian or political scientist to
understand civic values, you only have to be able to understand
``Everything I Needed to Know I Learned in Kindergarten'' --
``Don't take things that aren't yours. Put things back where you
found them.... Clean up your own mess.... Play fair. Don't hit
people. Say you're sorry when you hurt somebody.''
 &HT;    Virtually every religion and every ethical belief system hold
that it's intrinsically wrong to lie, cheat, steal, and hurt
people. But it's also wrong because, if everyone did it, society
would not be protecting its members and could not survive. It
doesn't matter if you believe that there's nothing wrong with
stealing; society says that it's not legal.
 &HT;    People learn by example; the best way to teach morality is to
act morally. Young people in particular seem to have an innate
ability to know when their elders aren't being honest with them.
 &HT;    So when America claims to be looking for solutions to violence,
but our lawmakers are reluctant to require background checks for
people who buy guns at gun shows, the message is clear: Other
things -- ideology, NRA campaign contributions, the risk of
offending gun-toting voters -- are really more important than
saving lives.
 &HT;    It teaches Americans far more about moral values than a month's
worth of talk-show and editorial calls for a return to religion.
It's not a pretty lesson.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    Jim Castelli is the author of ``A Plea for Common Sense:
Resolving the Clash Between Religion and Politics'' (Harper &AMP; Row).
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Jim Castelli
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
