<HEADER>
A8108 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREK-RAY-PARK-IN-STAR     06-24 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-RAY-PARK-IN-STAR-WARS-ART-ADV05-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV05 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 RAY PARK: YOU'VE GOT MAUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., JULY 5, 1999) 
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Ray Park as
Darth Maul in ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Darth Maul idolized Han Solo.
 &HT;    ``Han Solo always got the girl and he was very cool,'' says Ray
Park, the soft-spoken Scottish actor who portrays Darth Maul in
``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace.'' ``I wanted to be Han Solo, but
with Jedi powers and a lightsaber.
 &HT;    ``It's a bit ironic that I'm playing Darth Maul,'' he adds. ``I
never, ever thought I'd be in a `Star Wars' movie. I mean, who
would think that?
 &HT;    ``It's hard to take in sometimes. It's unbelievable.''
 &HT;    Believe it, Ray. And believe this, too: Darth Maul _ no, George,
not Jar Jar Binks _ is the film's breakout character, the Sith Lord
audiences love to hate. After all, he sports that sinister
crimson-and-black makeup, wields that nifty double-bladed
lightsaber, grits those grungy teeth and takes obvious pleasure in
skewering Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam Neeson).
 &HT;    ``I knew `The Phantom Menace' would be big, but I didn't think
Darth Maul would be so big,'' Park says by transatlantic telephone
from Twentieth Century Fox's offices in London. ``All I knew was
that he was a cool character and I wanted to play him.
 &HT;    ``It was my first role as an actor,'' he says, ``and what better
movie than a `Star Wars' movie to start off with? I was just happy
to get the gig, and I never realized the kind of reaction the
character would get.''
 &HT;    Only 24 years old, Park holds a second-degree black belt and is
a veteran of numerous martial-arts competitions. Hoping to pursue
his lifelong dream of acting, he accepted a job as a stunt
performer in the 1997 fantasy/action film ``Mortal Kombat:
Annihilation,'' which led directly to ``The Phantom Menace.''
 &HT;    It took a lot of people to make Darth Maul a reality, of course.
After George Lucas wrote the script, Nick Gillard choreographed the
lightsaber duels. Makeup wizards Nick Dudman and Paul Engelen gave
Maul his sinister visage, while Peter Serafinowicz provided Maul's
voice.
 &HT;    What did that leave for Park to do?
 &HT;    ``There's a little bit of me in there, too, because of the
martial arts, the look and the attitude,'' he says. ``I'm like
that, very serious and disciplined, when I'm competing, and I could
take that a little farther with Darth Maul.
 &HT;    ``You don't growl in competition,'' Park says, ``but you have to
have piercing eyes and strong body language to show your
confidence. The makeup, the horns and the double-edged sword just
gave me more confidence, and I hope that comes across in the
performance.
 &HT;    ``The character is not about talking and being aggressive. He's
more about presence.''
 &HT;    Actually, at this point he's more about absence. A vengeful
Obi-Wan Kenobi (Ewan McGregor) strikes him down in the film's
rousing final faceoff between good and evil. Unless fan rumors
about a clone are borne out, don't expect to see him in the
upcoming second or third episodes.
 &HT;    ``Darth Maul becomes a bit overconfident, in an arrogant way,''
Park says. ``He becomes cocky, and that's what does him in.
 &HT;    ``I'm not bothered that I can't come back, though,'' he adds.
``I knew going into the movie that he was going to die.''
 &HT;    Upon wrapping ``The Phantom Menace,'' Park accepted a job as a
stunt man on Tim Burton's upcoming film, ``Sleepy Hollow,'' which
co-stars Park's ``Phantom Menace'' master, Ian McDiarmid, as well
as Johnny Depp and Christina Ricci. He's also hobnobbing with
``Star Wars'' devotees on the convention circuit and supporting the
British release of ``The Phantom Menace'' with a flurry of
interviews and public appearances.
 &HT;    When the stardust settles, Park's acting career awaits. And
he'll pursue it with Sithlike tenacity, he promises.
 &HT;    ``Performing is what I want to do,'' the actor says. ``I'm
making the rounds and trying to get work as me. I think `The
Phantom Menace' is starting to open doors.
 &HT;    ``People are wanting to meet me and talk to me, at least,'' he
concludes. ``So we'll soon find out just how wide the door has
opened.''
 &HT;    And as anyone who's seen ``The Phantom Menace'' can attest,
anyone who opens a door to find Darth Maul on the other side ...
well, they'd better be ready for some action.
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Star Wars: The Phantom
Menace,'' consult the official Website at www.starwars.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
