<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-FIELD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON, GREENE ADD SEX APPEAL TO TRACK AND FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Although the USA Track &AMP; Field Championships
involve 39 men's and women's events contested over four days, the
meet can be condensed to a single 20-second flash of pure sex
appeal: Michael Johnson vs. Maurice Greene in the 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give people here a great show,'' Greene said.
``It's going to be a lot of fun. I'm just here to run a phenomenal
200. It's going to be an exciting race.''
</P>
<P>
   The 200 is the penultimate race on Sunday at Hayward Field and
wraps up a whole hour of live programming by CBS. After that, the
concluding women's 5,000, featuring Regina Jacobs of Oakland,
Calif., will be a tree falling in the proverbial forest: no one
watching or listening.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson vs. Greene is the kind of head-to-head match-up track
and field desperately needs to promote itself in a non-Olympic
year. It came about because each man already has a free pass in
other events to this August's World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The International Amateur Athletics Federation, governing body
for the sport, decreed that defending champions can compete in the
following World Championships without having to qualify in their
country's trials. Thus, Johnson, the 1997 World Champion at 400
meters, and Greene, the '97 champion at 100, will not run those
events in the USATF meet, which began Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones will not run the 100 here, either, based on her
world championship at the distance in '97. Instead, she will
concentrate on the 200 and long jump Friday through Sunday. Her 200
final directly precedes the Johnson- Greene furlong fandango.
</P>
<P>
   The men's 200 is compelling stuff because Johnson, at 31, is
trying to hold onto his domain as the world's greatest long
sprinter while Greene, 25 next month, is stepping up in distance.
</P>
<P>
   Each man is a world record-holder. Johnson ran his astonishing
19.32 seconds at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. Greene a week ago
claimed the 100 record with an overpowering time of 9.79 in Athens,
site of the 2004 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael gets a lot of respect from us,'' said John Smith,
Greene's coach. ``For Maurice it's stepping into a new area where
he's challenged. Michael's a challenge. Ato's (Boldon, of Trinidad)
a challenge. He loves a challenge; loves to compete. Michael didn't
come here to run second, and we appreciate that, but neither do
we.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene's best in the 200 is 19.86, more than half a second
slower than Johnson's world record. However, Greene scored a win
over Johnson in 1998 in the Prefontaine Classic on this same fast
track.
</P>
<P>
   Greene loves running in Eugene and said he's had second thoughts
about not entering the 100 in these national championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special place for me,'' Greene said. ``You have to have
a game plan and my plan is to come here and run a fast 200.
Michael's the world record-holder in the 200. He's one of the
biggest names in track and field. I just broke the 100 world
record. That should draw some people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
