<HEADER>
A8127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-CARIBBEAN-062     06-24 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-CARIBBEAN-0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: STARS FLOCK TO THE CARIBBEAN TO SEE AND BE SEEN
 &HT;    575&AMP;ADDS.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For nearly three years I've bopped around the Caribbean
as a foreign correspondent. I've chased decent stories, but one
goal has always eluded me -- rubbing elbows with a star.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Aspen. Forget St. Tropez. It's the islands that have long
been the real havens for actors, musicians, and other celebrities
who covet the discreet retreat. But I've never seen any. And this
matters to someone -- yes, I admit it -- who gravitates towards
Parade magazine's column on personalities before reading any other
part of the Sunday paper.
</P>
<P>
   But at least I know the stars are out there -- somewhere --
enjoying all the trappings of wealth on my turf.
</P>
<P>
   Those like actor Tim Robbins and actress wife Susan Sarandon --
who vacation in a secluded bungalow in the Bahamas -- seek to avoid
attention, while those like supermodel Elle Macpherson(CQ) -- who
reportedly sunbathes topless on beaches in St. Bart's within plain
view of tourists -- actually seem to seek it out.
</P>
<P>
   A nomadic breed, stars migrate to certain parts of the world for
one main reason: to get away from the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Like herds of cattle, they've been flocking to the Caribbean
since before the 1940s, when Errol Flynn used to hold torchlit
rafting parties down the Rio Grande in Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   Today, supermodel Naomi Campbell fancies New Providence Island,
a green splash in the midst of the Bahamas archipelago, while
talk-show maven Oprah Winfrey so likes Jumby Bay, a 300-acre isle
off Antigua, she once rented the whole island for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Eddie Murphy stays at the Half Moon Golf, Tennis and Beach
Club in Jamaica, where Georgian-style villas come complete with a
live-in chambermaid and rent for $10,500 a week in high season.
</P>
<P>
   I think I'll save that one for when I win the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, magician David Copperfield rented Little St. James
Island so that he and supermodel girlfriend Claudia Schiffer could
be alone when he proposed. But despite a $5 million ring, their
engagement appears to be as endless as the Caribbean's translucent
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Bill Clinton and the first lady enjoy these
parts, having been photographed frolicking and slow-dancing (or was
it mock-slow-dancing?) on a beach in St. Thomas in the U.S. Virgin
Islands during a brief respite there in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Besides luxuriating with their own kind, stars also go to the
Caribbean to get married, to conduct business, and to be, well,
unabashedly wicked.
</P>
<P>
   Ageless rocker Mick Jagger, 55, recently had a thing on the
secluded island of Mustique with a voluptuous 27-year-old
Venezuelan heiress even as the musician's marriage to leggy Texas
beauty Jerry Hall was on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Crawford honeymooned on Paradise Island in the Bahamas
last year after wedding nightclub entrepreneur Rande Gerber in a
tranquil, barefoot wedding ceremony on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Also last year, singer Michael Jackson persuaded St. Croix
during a three-day visit to let him build a multimillion-dollar
casino and theme park there after the weirdest nose in pop was
supposedly spurned by Brazil and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, St. Croix hasn't heard from him since.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, Eric Clapton turned over dozens of his guitars
to a charity auction to benefit his Crossroads Center in Antigua,
the residential treatment center Clapton, a one-time drug abuser,
opened in 1998 on the West Indies island to help combat alcohol and
drug dependency.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trims.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no where else in the world are celebrities more of a
fixture than they are on Mustique, an emerald speck in the
Grenadines due south of St. Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   This one-time patch of scrubland has been an outpost of wealth
ever since a shrewd developer named Colin Tennant gave England's
Princess Margaret a parcel of land there in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustique Co., controlled by private investors, eventually
bought the island and now owns or oversees almost everything,
including a security force whose job it is to keep the paparazzi --
as well as tourists -- at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-by-1.5-mile island has become so synonymous with privilege
that the company's public relations firm readily provides a long
list of more than 75 famous visitors to Mustique -- everyone from
Brad Pitt to Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Rubbernecking is about all there is to do here, but you can rent
one of 50 or so scrumptious-sounding villas for $4,000 to $17,000 a
week which, leasing agents assure me, includes the use of a car.
(Gee, that makes me feel better about the price).
</P>
<P>
   Jagger owns one, a Japanese-style abode that sleeps 10, and he
rents it out for about $9,000 a week, depending on the month.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion mogul Tommy Hilfiger owns one too, but he doesn't rent
his out. (I wonder if it's decorated in red, white and blue).
</P>
<P>
   He's having to tear down his spacious villa anyway (he
apparently considers it too small) to make room for a palace-like
dwelling with nine bedrooms more to his liking. Poor baby.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Another tiny, lah-di-dah island is St. Bart's in the French West
Indies.
</P>
<P>
   This is the place where Arista Records chief Clive Davis parties
with rapper Sean ``Puff Daddy'' Combs. (Clive has a yacht, Puffy
has a yacht).
</P>
<P>
   This past New Year's, those said to be attending various
shindigs there included rocker Jon Bon Jovi, director Penny
Marshall and home-making maven Martha Stewart. Tommy Mottola,
ex-Mr. Mariah Carey, also visited. Good thing he didn't show up in
April, when Carey was there with Luis Miguel. Unfortunately, Carey
and Miguel did bump into Miguel's ex-flame, Daisy Fuentes.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of action for an island of nine square miles.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for those of you who'd like your own shot at a star
encounter, here are a few spots to check out after you've robbed
that bank.
</P>
<P>
   Harbour Island in the Bahamas is a mixture of pastel-colored
cottages and white picket fences where all sorts of celebs,
including Jimmy Buffett, Sydney Poitier, Keith Richards, and Robert
De Niro, either have homes or are frequent visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The best place to stay there is the Pink Sands, a resort that
offers ``cottages'' bigger than most people's homes sprawling
across 18 acres of lush foliage.
</P>
<P>
   On St. Bart's, the Isle de France hotel is a favorite with the
jet-set, with its marble-floored guest rooms furnished with
mahogany antiques.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms at the Isle de France cost up to $880 a night in peak
winter months. Some rooms at the Pink Sands go for a cool $1,750 a
night.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of money for the chance at a little bit of
hobnobbing. But, hey, breakfast is included.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
