<HEADER>
A8135 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-LIFE25-COX     06-24 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monumental healing power of mullein
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga, _ Mullein has never been shy. Or choosy. It
takes up just about anyplace, growing all along roadsides, in
fields _ and gardens, especially new ones up here in the mountains.
A lover of sun and sand, mullein grows well on the coast, I'm told,
though I've seen no mullein by the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced to the herb as a child when I drank tea made from its
leaves to fight coughs and colds, I remain a mullein man. I
actually planted it here, though it clearly needed no help finding
my space and getting a roothold.
</P>
<P>
   And did it ever.
</P>
<P>
   I know mullein. But the mullein I'm seeing out the cabin door is
like no mullein I've seen. One flower stalk at last measurement had
reached 7 feet, several feet taller than any I'd grown before. I'm
sure mullein grows flower stalks this high elsewhere. But along the
road or in a huge open space, a 7-foot stalk with little yellow
blooms at the top doesn't seem nearly as imposing as it does in a
new garden filled with mostly tiny plants made even tinier by
grazing deer. Talk about vertical accents.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprising, all who see this monster mullein can't resist
comparisons to Jack's fabled beanstalk, alien plants from sci-fi
flicks and assorted sordid creations of astonished minds.
</P>
<P>
   It all started innocently enough. In a spring like any spring.
Here and there, a few fuzzy little gray-green leaves pushed through
the rocky earth, cutely. With time and a little moisture, the
leaves grew larger. And larger, eventually becoming longer than a
foot. This stage made me pay attention but mostly to note the fine
ornamental value of leaves such as this. Lambs' ear never was so
impressive; wouldn't children love this? Rubbing the leaves feels
sensational. And that incredible stalk _ whoa!
</P>
<P>
   Those leaves historically have had purpose far beyond the
ornamental. I knew about the tea, but Thomas Broken Bear Squier of
Aberdeen, N.C., who learned plant medicine from his Cherokee
ancestors, calls mullein ``a unique medicinal plant in that the
dried leaves used to treat asthma and bronchitis are smoked either
in a pipe or in cigarette form.''
</P>
<P>
   I could make cigarettes for the state, I said to myself as I
watched countless big leaves flop around the ground, appearing
overnight in places I hadn't dreamed of planting them. Including
over at the Japanesque garden, where two mulleins stand just
outside a foot-high bamboo fence, staring menacingly at the
Japanese maples.
</P>
<P>
   By May, I had pulled mullein plants up by the dozens, realizing
again the fine line between an ornamental and a weed. The few I
left let their leaves lie around for a few weeks. Then, the stalks
began. First, a little nub popped up from the center of the leaf
clump. It sat there for a few days, then took off in a race for the
sky. Each time I walked by during a day, I swear it had inched up.
</P>
<P>
   Mullein at this stage may not equal the growing pace of bamboo
or kudzu, but it's a very speedy creature.
</P>
<P>
   As daughter Leslie put it when she walked warily past the two
tallest: ``I can hear them growing.''
</P>
<P>
   For Leslie, who just tops 5 feet, two giant mullein plants take
on monumental proportions _ and provide opportunity for big fun.
One friend visiting the cabin the other day looked at the mullein
stalks and asked, curling her lips, ``What do you do with that top
part?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You run like hell and hope it doesn't chase you,'' answered
Leslie. Everybody laughed. With only slight nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay
</P>
<P>
   (at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
