NYT-06-24-99 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8136 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILDFLOWERS25-COX     06-24 1583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDFLOWERS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book fresh off the press, athens couple continues mission to
ensure wildflowers grow on
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ On a shelf of biology and gardening texts, the
periwinkle cover of their new wildflower guidebook stands out
against the dull green background like a pink lady-slipper among
rocks _ just the way botanists Wilbur and Marion Duncan planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inviting to have color, isn't it?'' says Wilbur, rising
from his chair. He returns a few seconds later holding two books.
``Which of these are you going to be drawn to? Why, the one with
color on the spine, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   The Duncans hope that plant lovers, hikers and gardeners across
the country will reach for ``Wildflowers of the Eastern United
States,'' an identification book published this month by the
University of Georgia Press. Its 380 pages contain a glossary,
plant descriptions and 1,100 wildflower pictures, almost all of
them taken by Wilbur. Printed overseas and not available until
July, the book also includes information about vegetative, floral
and fruiting structures, blooming season, where flowers are found
and their habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose in creating this wildflower book was to get more
people interested in plants,'' says Marion, who collaborates with
Wilbur on the research and writing. During World War II, the couple
lived briefly in Charleston, where Wilbur was eradicating
mosquitoes near military operations for the U.S. Public Health
Service. When they visited the South Carolina coast more than 20
years later, they were stunned at the number of plant species that
had been wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked ourselves, `how can we stop it?''' she says. ``With
more interest in plants of a particular area comes more
conservation. If people are aware of what's there, they are more
likely to value and protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, with their youngest child in college, the Duncans
undertook a book project on seaside plants, a particular interest
of Wilbur's. They obtained maps of coastal counties, aerial
photographs and Intracoastal Waterway maps.
</P>
<P>
   They studied, planned and then hit the road, armed with
notebooks and cameras. When the book was finished, they continued
to find, document and photograph plants. Over the past 24 years,
they've driven 80,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   For their wildflower book, the Duncans began traversing the
interior of the country, following the same procedure used for the
seaside book. They took pictures and notes on everything they
found, and they took a specimen of every species, which they
brought back to the UGA Herbarium for identification. Those they
couldn't identify were sent to specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some idea of where plants should be, but sometimes we
had to rely on local people to direct us,'' says Wilbur. ``Once in
Nova Scotia, someone told us to open a gate, drive through a
pasture, through another gate, and then get out and walk down to
the bay. We did, and it was so lovely that whenever we were near
there, we always visited that site.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding something new
</P>
<P>
   The couple's living room _ in the house they've lived in for
more than 40 years _ is a simple, elegant room with a few pieces of
furniture. The walls are paneled in walnut cut from trees on the
Indiana farm where Wilbur grew up. Marion has made a coffee table
from some of the same walnut.
</P>
<P>
   On the end tables are plants, live and dried _ pipsissewa,
foxtail, a leek and garlic bulbs. Two watercolors, of Hairy
Rattlebox and an Oglethorpe oak, both of which Wilbur found and
named, hang on the walls. The artwork is a reminder of some of
Wilbur's accomplishments _ finding new plants isn't an everyday
occurrence for botanists.
</P>
<P>
   His 1939 discovery of an oak tree species in Oglethorpe County
was the first new oak found east of the Mississippi in 90 years, an
event so newsworthy that Time magazine did a feature article about
it. With typical modesty, Wilbur deflects attention from himself
and onto the tree, which others had identified as a shingle oak,
saying ``there was a kind of quiet pleasure in finding a new
species.''
</P>
<P>
   He found the Hairy Rattlebox in Brantley County, south of Jesup,
where he and Marion were visiting her family in 1942. As usual,
Wilbur was driving in the country and stopping periodically to
search for plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I see swamps, ravines, bluffs or other habitat, I want to
know what's growing there, so I drive along and stop,'' Wilbur
said. ``When I saw this plant, I knew immediately it was different,
because I'd been working with Baptisia and was armed with
information. It was very hairy _ really hairy. I had to check out
the literature to be sure I was right, and I was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My father got so where he wouldn't ride with Wilbur,'' says
Marion with a laugh. ``He said that Wilbur would drive three miles
and back up two.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, Wilbur was instrumental in having Hairy
Rattlebox placed on the Federal Endangered Species list. The plant
was adapted to open pine lands. A paper company had bought the
Brantley County land and planted pines, changing the habitat and
threatening the plant. Letters to federal officials in Washington
helped assure the plant's protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we were crusaders,'' Marion says. ``It seems
like we were always poking our noses into something.''
</P>
<P>
   Always something to see
</P>
<P>
   The living room window offers the best views of the hilly land.
Almost every morning, Wilbur gazes at the trees and flowers as he
dozes off for a brief nap, but there's plenty to look at inside as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``See these flowers?'' Wilbur points to the foxtail. ``Not a day
goes by that Marion doesn't find something blooming for us to look
at.'' He smiles at her. ``This foxtail, when the light hits it,
it's something. Every time I look at it, I get a funny feeling,
it's so beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur, 88, hasn't lost his passion for plants or for sharing
his knowledge with others. With the completion of the wildflower
book, the Duncans are already working on a book about shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discovery is an exciting thing and preparation of books for
others to use and learn about plants is very satisfying,'' he says.
``It's basic to all science _ to gather knowledge and to try and
understand the relationships of plants to each other and to the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   But plants weren't Wilbur's first love, birds were _ until he
was an undergraduate at Indiana University and found that his best
teacher was a botanist.
</P>
<P>
   After earning a Ph.D. at Duke in 1938 with forest ecologist C.F.
Korstian, former director of Yale's prestigious School of Forestry,
Wilbur took the advice of colleagues and headed to Athens,
convinced it was an ideal setting for his taxonomic research. He
joined the biology department and focused on the proper
classification of specimens and the naming of plants.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few years away during World War II, Wilbur spent
his career doing research, running the UGA Herbarium and teaching.
When he retired in 1978, the Herbarium had grown from 16,000 to
135,000 specimens.
</P>
<P>
   The biology department is also where he met Marion, who is eight
years younger. She had come to UGA after completing a premed
program at Georgia State College for Women at Milledgeville,
reasoning that graduate school was more affordable than medical
school. She earned a master's degree in botany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilbur had to break a date to get married,'' Marion says with
a laugh. ``He was dating Miss Pandora, a campus beauty queen. He
asked me to marry him and we got married two weeks later. Neither
of us feels that once you make up your mind, you should put things
off.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiles at her husband and then looks out the living room
window. In view are mountain laurel, Carolina rhododendrons and
stewartia, as well as the rocky banks of one of three creeks on
their property.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 33 acres of woods and water bear witness to the
Duncans' crusade to save plants from destruction. They have
transplanted more than 150 species of wildflowers to their property
and have planted thousands of pines as well, primarily to stop
erosion on the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the plants have come from land later submerged by
reservoirs, including lakes Allatoona, Russell, Sinclair and
Hartwell. Wilbur brought 300 pale yellow trillium from the Savannah
River drainage system before Lake Russell was created. Another,
dwarf sumac, came from land near a Covington water tower.
</P>
<P>
   They can measure their lives by the size of the trees, shrubs
and flowers on their property, remembering how large the Georgia
Oak was when their three children were growing up. They can point
out places where their children and their children's friends, and
now their grandchildren, had picnics, built forts and held
sleepovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we bought this land, we hoped to live here forever,''
says Wilbur. Adds Marion, ``Our daughter Lucia wants to strew our
ashes on the property after we die. I think we'd like to be on the
hill, overlooking the creek.''
</P>
<P>
   A T A G L A N C E
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Name: Wilbur and Marion Duncan
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Occupation: retired botanists
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Book: ``Wildflowers of the Eastern United States,'' by Wilbur
and Marion Duncan, University of Georgia Press. 380 pages.
``Wildflowers of the Eastern United States'' is number 20 in the
UGA Press's Wormsloe Foundation Publications. $29.95. The books
will be available in July.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
