<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8144 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-SAFETY-LADN     06-24 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-SAFETY-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK _ Women who vacation alone or in groups
of two or so are confronted with a choice: Acknowledge
vulnerability or stay home.
</P>
<P>
   The latter isn't a particularly attractive option, so the best
way to try to prevent a time of fun from suddenly becoming one of
terror is to maintain caution in the midst of enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instinct and awareness always play the biggest role, and
paranoia almost none,'' writes Sheila Swan, author of ``Safety and
Security for Women Who Travel'' (Travelers' Tales Guides; $12.95).
``To be careful and open is a delicate balance. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Risks can be reduced with attention, preparation and
awareness. Knowing dangers and devices for protecting yourself
enables you to screen risks when you can, and reduce or survive
them when you can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is particularly germane in the wake of the murders of
three women who had visited Yosemite National Park in February.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Sund, 42, her teen-age daughter and a teen-age female
friend of the family disappeared shortly after exiting the park to
the west on Highway 140. All three bodies were found later in
remote foothill locations, Sund and the family friend in the trunk
of their burned-out rental car, the daughter near a reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Although the crimes are presumed to have occurred outside the
park's borders, they nonetheless shattered Yosemite's longstanding
sense of tranquillity _ and exemption from urban horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it, they were traveling in (a group of) three _ exactly
what you're supposed to do,'' said Susan Arthur, a spokeswoman for
one of the park's administrative operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of women travelers headed to Yosemite this summer,
park ranger Scott Gediman said, ``I think our advice is to use as
much common sense as possible and not change the way we behave.
When we come to a national park, we may not be as much on guard as
we are in a city. ... It's important to be aware of our
surroundings.''
</P>
<P>
   To maximize safety, it might be wise to consider the following
tips:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Try to head off a vulnerable situation. If you intend to
drive your own car on a trip, have it checked out thoroughly before
you depart, averting, if possible, a breakdown in a remote area.
And don't wait for the needle to be in the red to fill up on gas.
You have half a tank, and you're in a brightly lit, busy community
as night begins to fall? Stop and fill up; there's no telling when
the next opportunity will come.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Invest in a cell phone. If you do experience car trouble, or
even if you sense a driver is stalking you, you don't want to have
to search for a pay phone or call box for help. This can also serve
as a safety device on a hike or in remote lodgings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; As sad as it is to admit, maintain a healthy suspicion of
someone in distress _ a motorist broken down by the side of the
road, for example. It might be best to keep your doors locked and
your windows cracked, and offer to make a phone call _ on your
newly acquired cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Swan, in her book, suggests carrying pepper spray and/or a
whistle around your neck. Some foreign countries prohibit
possession of pepper spray, however; if that is a factor in your
thinking, it's best to check in advance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Swan further advises that the proper attitude is important.
``Walk and act with a sense of confidence and purpose,'' she
writes, adding that few things attract undesirables faster than
``an obvious tourist standing around looking at a loss for what to
do next.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Gediman urges women to stay in groups and, if walking at
night, to carry a flashlight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8146 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-GOBOX-LADN     06-24 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-GOBOX-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: &UR;  &LR;  From the Los Angeles area, Yosemite National
Park is best reached by following I-5 and I-99 north to Fresno,
then proceeding north on state route 41 to the park. The Automobile
Club of Southern California lists the drive from L.A. to Yosemite
Village (heart of the valley) at 314 miles and advises allowing
more than six hours to complete it (traffic on route 41 can be
numbingly slow, particularly in summer). Another option is to fly
to Fresno. This still leaves you a three-hour drive to Yosemite
Valley in a rental car, however.
</P>
<P>
   COSTS: &UR;  &LR;  Yosemite National Park is open 24 hours a day,
year-round. The entrance fee, good for seven days, is $20 per
vehicle, $10 for visitors who arrive by bus, on foot, by bicycle,
by motorcycle or on horseback. The Yosemite Pass costs $40 per
person and is valid for one year. The Golden Eagle Pass costs $50
and is valid for all national parks for one year.
</P>
<P>
   LODGING: &UR;  &LR;  Yosemite Concession Services handles reservations for
all lodging in Yosemite Valley, including the Ahwahnee and Yosemite
Lodge. Reservations phone number: (559) 252-4848. Web:
 &UR;  &LR; www.yosemitepark.com &UR;  &LR; . Reservations cannot be made any further
in advance than one year and one day from first date of stay. Early
this month, there was availability at the Ahwahnee and the Yosemite
Lodge no earlier than November, but there is a three-day
cancellation policy, so if you're flexible in your plans, sometimes
a room can pop free on short notice. The Ahwahnee ($292) is upscale
and worthy of its sterling reputation. Lodging units at Yosemite
Lodge ($101-$126) are nicely appointed, but the walls are thin _
hair dryers and conversations in the adjacent rooms are often
audible. Cabins with bath at Curry Village run $83; tent cabins
$44. Outside the valley, a room with bath at the Wawona is $132.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPING: &UR;  &LR;  Three campgrounds in Yosemite Valley (Upper Pines,
Lower Pines, North Pines) are available on a reservations basis but
currently are booked solid well into September. Cancellations
sometimes result in last-minute availability. Reservations may be
made up to five months in advance, on the 15th of the month, by
calling (800) 436-7275, or online at  &UR;  &LR; reservations.nps.gov &UR;  &LR; .
Sites at most campgrounds cost $15 a night. There are nine National
Park campgrounds outside Yosemite Valley.
</P>
<P>
   DINING: &UR;  &LR;  Dinner beneath the towering ceilings of the Ahwahnee's
dining room is a memorable experience. Also elegant _ men are urged
to wear coat and tie. Dinner will push $40 per person excluding
wine and dessert. At Yosemite Lodge, tasty main courses are served
up for under $20 at the Mountain View Restaurant, and some tables
offer views of Yosemite Falls. Hikers and picnickers can find
excellent, made-fresh deli sandwiches at Degnan's in Yosemite
Village. For breakfast, skip the Yosemite Lodge cafeteria (it's
college-dorm quality) and spring for the $20 or so it will cost you
at the Ahwahnee; you won't be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: &UR;  &LR;  Recorded park information and road conditions are
available at (209) 372-0200. For a live operator, call (900)
454-9673, but be advised it is a toll call. Web:
 &UR;  &LR; www.nps.gov/yose &UR;  &LR; . Publications about the park may be ordered by
calling (209) 379-2648; Web:  &UR;  &LR; www.yosemite.org. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
