<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8170 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XIU-XIU-REVIEW-LADN     06-24 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XIU-XIU-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEN EVOKES   THEME OF ALIENATION IN FINE DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Our rating: 3 stars  
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ ``Xiu Xiu: The Sent Down Girl'' has been trading
heavily on the fact that its director, Joan Chen, has been barred
indefinitely from working in China. Print advertisements for the
film bear the brand: BANNED in China for sexual and political
content. Apparently, in a crowded summer marketplace, you have to
make your movie stand out in whatever way you can.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion is a bit misleading, however, since the
subversiveness at the heart of ``Xiu Xiu'' is quiet and much more
poetic than provocative. That doesn't make the film any less
withering as an indictment of the social engineering conducted in
China from 1966 to 1976. During this time, nearly 8 million young
Chinese were ``sent down'' from cities to the country's remote
regions like Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind this had more to do with indoctrination than
genuine education. China's Communist leaders wanted to eliminate
class distinctions and ``re-educate'' its young people in the ways
of manual labor and the lifestyles of its rural villagers. The
movement was not only anti-intellectual at its core, it was also
emotionally devastating for the millions of families it tore apart.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age Xiu Xiu (pronounced ``show show''), the film's
title character, comes from one such family. We meet her through
the recollections of a young male admirer, whom Xiu Xiu leaves
behind in her home city of Chengdu. From there, Xiu Xiu is assigned
to an isolated grassland in Tibet to learn horse ranching. Her
teacher, Lao Jin (Tibetan actor Lopsang), is a former cavalry man
who was castrated and now seems more comfortable with horses than
he does with people.
</P>
<P>
   Xiu Xiu (played with impressive confidence by 17-year-old Lu Lu)
is told her stay will last six months, after which she'll return to
lead an all-girls cavalry unit. Six months pass, then a year, and
there's no sign of the Chinese authorities. In fact, there's no
sign of anyone in this lonely wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a handsome peddler comes upon Lao Jin's
weather-beaten tent and tells Xiu Xiu that the girl's cavalry unit
has been disbanded and that if she wants to return home, she had
best be prepared to trade on her physical beauty. Soon, a host of
soldiers and local bureaucrats are taking advantage of Xiu Xiu's
plight as the film fatefully builds toward its tragic conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The Shanghai-born Chen, who also co-adapted the screenplay with
author Yan Geling, filmed ``Xiu Xiu'' on the fly along the
China-Tibet border, bypassing the Chinese film board along the way.
Smart move. The subsequent uproar with the final product has
everything to do with the way the movie shows the pervasiveness of
corruption and favoritism in China's cultural experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Chen displays a nice eye for composition and pacing, although
she relies a bit much on visual symbolism at the expense of
emotional impact. Still, it's an assured filmmaking debut from a
woman who came of age in China during those years of cultural
upheaval and clearly learned a thing or two in the process. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1531EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
