<HEADER>
A8192 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-X-GAMES-HAWK-HNS &LR;      06-24 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-GAMES-HAWK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X GAMES STAR DEFIES STEREOTYPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK FAINARU-WADA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The face of the X Games is not some
prepubescent, trash-mouthed hellion with a pierced tongue, hair
down to his waist, shorts down to his shins and a Black Sabbath
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only face of the X Games _ the only truly
recognizable athlete _ is the guy in the Lexus bombing down
Interstate 5, somewhere between San Diego and Los Angeles, chatting
on his cell phone on the way to an audition for a television show.
</P>
<P>
   He's the 30-year-old man (not dude) who employs the William
Morris Agency and a New York publicist, who has done commercials
for milk, Campbell's Soup and Levi's, who would fit right into the
pages of GQ and who is married with two children.
</P>
<P>
   While the tone and image of ESPN's made-for-TV event, which
begins Friday in San Francisco, are all about extremes, Tony Hawk
is most notable for being extremely un-extreme.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous skateboarder in the world _ the guy whom
publicists and journalists love to refer to as ``The Michael Jordan
of skateboarding'' _ hauls in a six-figure annual income and has
fans all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as close to transcending the X world as we have,'' said
an ESPN spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Jordan, Hawk's fame and notoriety have left him hated
by some of the more stereotypical bad boys within the skateboarding
community.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, just as it has become popular to loathe NASCAR's Jeff
Gordon because of his California roots and his corporate presence,
it's now ``in'' to hate Hawk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely sort of the surging opinion in the hardcore
skate world, where I'm the guy people love to hate,'' Hawk said as
he cruised down I-5 on his way to an audition for the HBO show
``Arli$$.'' ``Maybe they don't even know why, it's just the cool
thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not me, it'll be someone else that they're gonna
decide embodies what they don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like? Hawk's resume includes: ad work for the GAP
clothing company, Gatorade, AT&AMP;T and Coca-Cola; a thriving business
called Birdhouse Projects Inc., which manufactures and distributes
skateboards, shirts and stickers; on-air host appearances for MTV;
production of a skateboard video; a Web site (http://tonyhawk.com)
that includes, among other things, a link to Disney's promotion for
its latest animated epic, ``Tarzan''; and, coming soon, a video
game called, ``Tony Hawk's Pro Skate.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hawk admitted in a recent issue of ESPN The Magazine, ``Oh
yeah, I'm Mr. Commercial now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years ago, Hawk was the son of the Little League
president in the San Diego area. That, though, was not enough to
keep him from dumping baseball and turning his entire focus to
skateboarding. By 1983, at the age of 14, Hawk had become the
youngest-ever professional skateboarder.
</P>
<P>
   And he was dominant from the start. In fact, from 1981-93, he
finished first in the National Skateboarding Association series, a
run that earned him the title ``Skater of the Decade'' by Thrasher
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Within his sport, Hawk is most beloved for creating the 720 _ a
midair, 360-degree somersault done twice _ as well as for such
tricks as the Stale Fish, the Madonna and the Varial 540. His cache
of moves and his icon status will be on display beginning Saturday
with the start of the skateboarding competition, which will take
place at Piers 30 and 32 and will run through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the faction of children who are hawkish about Hawk, he
surely will have a huge following at these X Games. His recognition
factor isn't to the point where he is accosted merely by walking
the streets, but, within the world of skateboarding, his can be a
hectic like.
</P>
<P>
   During the last two X Games, which were held practically in his
back yard in San Diego, just moving Hawk from place to place was a
chore for event organizers. Last week, as he and Andy MacDonald
went to a skatepark to practice for the doubles competition, local
kids skidded to a halt and started shouting out trick requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always really friendly and not so intrusive that
you can't relax,'' said Hawk, who said that once he told the kids
that he and Andy MacDonald were there to practice, they returned to
their own skateboarding.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Hawk has become the poster boy for his sport,
which has meant speaking out not only in his own defense but making
the effort to distance skateboarding from the very stereotype some
of its hard-core followers most embrace.
</P>
<P>
   He's not defensive about his popularity and exposure, but rather
logical in making the case that those critical of the corporate
nature of both him and the X Games are missing the point.
</P>
<P>
   Where skateboarding clearly was a fad as it drifted through the
1970s and '80s, it seems to have taken a firmer hold in the '90s _
if for no other reason than the legitimacy afforded it by
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize that in all of this promotion that
skateboarding is involved in,'' Hawk said, ``it's really bringing
the popularity to a level that it never reached and providing more
opportunities than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who love to bash don't realize that (the exposure) is
why they have a new skatepark in their hometown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1552EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
