<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMBUKTU-BOOK-REVIEW-     06-24 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMBUKTU-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIMBUKTU': MY LIFE AS A DOG: A DOG FEELS LIFE'S VAGARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In book after book, from his acclaimed ``New York Trilogy''
through ``Moon Palace,'' ``The Music of Chance'' and ``Leviathan,''
Paul Auster has examined the same themes: the role that randomness
and coincidence play in determining people's lives, the elusiveness
of truth and identity and the limits of language and free will.
</P>
<P>
   In his charming if slight new novel, ``Timbuktu,'' he has found
the perfect subject and narrative strategy for re-examining these
issues: he has told the story of a dog and his master from the
dog's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   It is a perspective that by its very nature suggests a world
processed with partial understanding, a seemingly arbitrary world
in which one's fate, and even identity, is determined by large,
mysterious and controlling creatures known as human beings.
</P>
<P>
   The dog in this case is a mongrel named Bones, a pooch adopted
from the North Shore Animal Shelter by a would-be poet and
full-time lush named Willy Gurevitch. Bones will play Sancho Panza
to Willy's Don Quixote, Jim to Willy's Huck.
</P>
<P>
   He will accompany Willy on his shuffling peregrinations around
America, and he will be there, too, for Willy's last journey _ to
Baltimore to search for his high school English teacher, Bea
Swanson, who inspired him to become a writer so many decades ago.
Though Willy hasn't spoken to Bea in years, she remains his last,
best hope: now that he is dying (worn down by age and illness and
life on the streets), he hopes to give her his poems and persuade
her to find a new home for Bones.
</P>
<P>
   Willy, who grew up in Brooklyn, the son of Holocaust survivors,
was a malcontent in college, a rebel with ``a noisy, fractious
disdain for Everything-That-Was.'' He was ``a loudmouthed crank, a
nihilist, a besotted clown'' who believed ``the more wretched your
life was'' the closer you were ``to the gritty nub of existence.''
</P>
<P>
   That all began to change, however, after Willy had a breakdown
and reinvented himself as Willy G. Christmas, a disciple of Santa
Claus devoted to making the world a better place. Willy gives away
his meager inheritance to the needy and importunate. He fantasizes
about building a transparent toaster that would ``be a thing of
beauty.'' And he pens dozens of poems with titles like
``Thirty-Three Rules to Live By.''
</P>
<P>
   This much about his master Bones has pieced together by
listening to Willy's tireless soliloquies and by listening to
Willy's mother and friends. The do's ``grasp of Ingloosh was as
good as any other immigrant who had spent seven years on American
soil,'' and while he wonders sometimes about the truth of some of
his fanciful master's stories, he has ``a sense of the drift'' of
Willy's world, ``a feeling for what its shape both was and
wasn't,'' which is more than can be said for many of Auster's
earlier characters, who tended to ricochet from one episode in
their life to the next without ever piecing together a coherent
picture of the whole.
</P>
<P>
   Bones has been with Willy since his earliest days as a puppy,
and it is hard for him ``to imagine a world that did not have his
master in it''; for him, ``every thought, every memory, every
particle of the earth and air was saturated with Willy's
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Willy is dying, Bones experiences what can only be
called ``pure ontological terror'': ``subtract Willy from the
world,'' he thinks, ``and the odds were that the world itself would
cease to exist.'' He not only feels grief and terror at the
prospect of his master's death, but he also fears for his own
future.
</P>
<P>
   As a dog on his own, he knows, he will be subject to dogcatchers
and police officers; he will have to forage for food and depend on
the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   He dreams of joining his master in Timbuktu, that great
hereafter in the sky, where ``you were at one with the universe, a
speck of antimatter lodged in the brain of God.'' Bones just hopes
it's not one of those places with fancy carpets and expensive
antiques, one of those places where pets are banned.
</P>
<P>
   In limning the story of Bones, his life both with Willy and
after Willy, Auster does a nimble job of showing what the world
might feel like from a dog's perspective: a world in which devotion
to one's master is paramount, smells matter more than sights and
the perplexities of human life are a constant source of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   When Willy stops to rest in front of a house where Edgar Allan
Poe once lived, Bones confuses ``Poe-land'' with Poland, the home
of Willy's ancestors. He cannot understand why two types of birds,
the Orioles and the Blue Jays, play a game called baseball, and
he's amazed that humans spend their vacations traveling hundreds of
miles to visit a mouse named Mickey.
</P>
<P>
   Auster, unfortunately, does not make as much of these sorts of
misunderstandings and incongruities as he might. Too often, he has
Bones thinking more like a vaguely dimwitted human being than a
bright, curious dog, and too often he settles for tired jokes about
the difficulty of teaching old dogs new tricks and the problem of
dogs' not being able to read signs that say ``No Dogs Allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if ``Timbuktu'' does not entirely deliver its promising
premise, it nonetheless emerges as Auster's most touching, most
emotionally accessible book. In writing this slender fairy tale,
Auster seems to have realized that putting his philosophical theses
across does not require deliberately elliptical narratives or
fancy, post-modern pyrotechnics, that he can tell an old-fashioned
story, replete with sentiment and even flourishes of
sentimentality, without losing his voice.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, it seems, he needed to turn from the highfalutin
world of human affairs to the earthier realm of doggy travails. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   TIMBUKTU
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Auster
</P>
<P>
   181 pages. Henry Holt and Co. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
