<SLUG> BC-LOVE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHEN LOVE COMES': CHURNING IN A SELF-PITY BATH SURE CAN WHIP UP
THE SUDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With her sullen, downturned mouth, hollow, haunted eyes and air
of tattered glamour, the New Zealand actress Rena Owen suggests a
Down Under descendant of the '40s Bette Davis via the late-'60s
Jeanne Moreau.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Owen's majestic, wrecked beauty lent an extra poignancy to
her portrayal of a battered wife in Lee Tamahori's harsh domestic
drama ``Once Were Warriors.'' And it adds a tinge of divalike
grandeur to her portrayal of Katie Keen, a fading international pop
star, in Garth Maxwell's ramshackle sudsfest ``When Love Comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in this emotionally overwrought film Ms. Owen delivers a
distraught monologue while standing on the beach, silhouetted by a
raging bonfire, in which she tearfully explains why she returned to
New Zealand after many years in the United States. Hint: It wasn't
just because her career was on the skids. Katie, unfortunately,
isn't the film's only character who likes to wallow in strident
self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   Easily the worst offender in that department is Mark (Dean
O'Gorman), an angry young songwriter prone to getting drunk and
stoned and throwing tantrums in the presence of his older lover
Stephen (Simon Prast), who happens to be Katie's best friend from
way, way back. &UR;  &LR;  Mark's lyrics exalt things like kissing the boot
that kicks you and other masochistic delights. His songs are
performed with snarling abandon in a local rock club by a frisky
lesbian duo, Fig (Nancy Brunning) and Sally (Sophia Hawthorne).
These two young women, who are wildly in love with each other,
serve as the movie's cheeky Greek chorus, introducing the story and
commenting on the action.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the film, who should arrive in New Zealand but Katie's
American manager and married ex-lover, Eddie (Simon Westaway). It
turns out that Eddie still cares about Katie and ... But it would
be unfair to give away the gist of Eddie's preposterous confession,
which sets up the movie's icky, lovey-dovey ending.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, not even Ms. Owen's screen presense and the actors'
intensely earnest performances can pull together the strands of
this meandering, indulgent film. The title, ``When Love Comes''
says it all. Thud.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   WHEN LOVE COMES
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Garth Maxwell; written by Maxwell, Rex Pilgrim and
Peter Wells; director of photography, Darryl Ward; edited by Cushla
Dillon; music by Chris Anderton; production designer, Grace Mok;
produced by Michele Fantl and Jonathan Dowling; released by Jour de
Fete Films. Running time: 94 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Rena Owen (Katie), Dean O'Gorman (Mark), Simon Prast
(Stephen), Nancy Brunning (Fig), Sophia Hawthorne (Sally) and Simon
Westaway (Eddie). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1601EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
