<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEACHES25-COX     06-24 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACHES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEDERAL POLICIES HARM BEACHES, ENVIRONMENTALISTS CLAIM
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's seashores are in trouble as oceans
rise and beaches erode, a trio of environmentalists warned
Thursday. Development is accelerating the damage, they said, and
federal policies are making the situation worse, not better.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the dire messages delivered by Cornelia Dean, author
of the recently released book, ``Against the Tide: The Battle for
America's Beaches''; Jackie Savitz, executive director of the Coast
Alliance, and Donald Boesch, president of the University of
Maryland Center for Environmental Science.
</P>
<P>
   Boesch even suggested that vacationers should regard ``Against
the Tide'' (Columbia University Press, $26.95) as this summer's
version of ``Jaws'' _ a fascinating, scary book to read at the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   Dean, science editor of The New York Times, said beaches are
almost like living creatures in their ability to move and replenish
themselves to ensure their survival.
</P>
<P>
   When politicians talk about preserving beaches, they are really
talking about preserving buildings along the shoreline, she said.
``Left alone, a natural beach will preserve itself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the barrier islands along the nation's coastline, beaches
have existed for centuries by continually shifting sands between
dunes and beach and offshore sand bars and back around again. But
the natural replenishment is disrupted when homes are built on the
dunes and sandbars are dredged to deepen channels. Building
seawalls eventually causes eroding beaches to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beaches are dynamic landscapes,'' said Dean. ``But development
pins them down, freezing them in place. They can't protect
themselves when storms or erosion strike.''
</P>
<P>
   With oceans rising around the world, there is no way to stop
some beach erosion, Boesch said. And it is unlikely that existing
homes and hotels and other buildings with an ocean view will be
razed to save nearby beaches.
</P>
<P>
   But it is reasonable to consider a ban on development along the
beaches, said Savitz. ``Why are we talking about where we can still
build?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists said beaches have been endangered more by
the National Flood Insurance Program than by hurricanes.
Established in 1968, the program enables owners of oceanfront
property to buy federally subsidized insurance at bargain rates,
explained Dean.
</P>
<P>
   Before the system was created by Congress, it was practically
impossible to buy flood insurance for buildings located on the
shore. Consequently, most beach houses were modest structures.
</P>
<P>
   With the federally backed insurance, however, bankers were
willing to give bigger mortgages to property owners along the beach
and development exploded. Now taxpayers subsidize the insurance for
some of the most expensive property on the planet, Dean pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
   Abolishing the program, or scaling it back, would discourage
development and protect the beaches, Savitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Dean was skeptical of projects to renourish beaches by bringing
in new sand. A recent proposal is to import sand from the Bahamas
to build up Florida beaches, she said. But the replenished sand
eventually is lost because the basic problem of over-development
has not been solved, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, taxpayers are footing the bill, the
environmentalists said. A current project to replenish 33 miles of
New Jersey beaches will cost nearly $3 billion, with 65 percent of
the funding coming from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists spoke a press conference sponsored by the
Environmental Media Services, a non-partisan group devoted to
increasing news coverage of ecological and medical issues.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
