<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      06-24 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROGUE TRADER': FOR THE LOVE OF MONEY AND THE RISKS OF MAKING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ewan McGregor was sexy as an unusually cheerful Scottish heroin
addict in ``Trainspotting.'' Ewan McGregor was sexy as a Jane
Austen country gentleman singing duets at the pianoforte with
Gwyneth Paltrow in ``Emma.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewan McGregor is even a little sexy as the young Obi Wan Kenobi,
grossly overshadowed by Liam Neeson's character, in ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.'' But Ewan McGregor is not even
remotely sexy as a panicked futures trader in ``Rogue Trader,'' a
new Cinemax movie about a very young man who singlehandedly,
accidentally brings down the oldest merchant bank in the world.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just the dreadful black-and-yellow-striped jackets
that McGregor's character and his financial team wear to work.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, international futures trading isn't a naturally sexy
subject, except for viewers who spend their days with margin
payments and straddles and derivatives, whatever they are.
</P>
<P>
   James Dearden, the writer and director (who is best known for
having written ``Fatal Attraction''), has taken a straightforward
approach to the story and the results are inoffensive and mildly
interesting, but there's no life to this, even though the story is
based on remarkable, recent real-life events.
</P>
<P>
   McGregor plays Nicholas Leeson, a British plasterer's son who
goes to work for Barings, the esteemed British bank, and makes
good. Still in his 20s and a newlywed, he is put in charge of
trading in Singapore, where things quickly go bad. One of his
young, inexperienced trading-team members makes a mistake and loses
$20,000; rather than dismissing her, he takes some chances and
tries to make it good.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he keeps losing more and more. Things get dicey.
``There's not enough in the client account to cover margin
payments,'' an employee tells him at one point. But his luck
changes, the Nikkei hits 19,000, and he makes back all his losses,
which had added up to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad, because it just encourages him to take chances
again, and this time he gets in even deeper. Meanwhile he is
getting six-figure annual bonuses, being hailed by the London
office as ``a turbo arbitrager.''
</P>
<P>
   He is asked to give speeches to share his secrets of success (if
only they knew) but is in such turmoil over a situation he knows is
out of control that he throws up backstage. When an audit finds a
discrepancy of 7.78 billion yen (about $64 million), he begins
forging memos and other paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he's caught and Barings goes under. In fact, Britain
very nearly goes under. Leeson is arrested at the Frankfurt airport
and extradited.
</P>
<P>
   The real Leeson is expected to be released from prison in
Singapore next weekend and to return to England after having served
roughly three years of a six-and-a-half-year sentence. He is now
32, divorced and suffering from colon cancer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ROGUE TRADER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cinemax, Friday night at 8 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written by James Dearden and based on the book by Nicholas
Leeson with Edward Whitley; Dearden, director; Jean-Francois Robin,
director of photography; music by Richard Hartley; Paul Raphael,
Janette Day and Dearden, producers; William Tyrer and Chris Ball,
co-executive producers; Sir David Frost, Pippa Cross and Claire
Chapman, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Ewan McGregor (Nick Leeson), Anna Friel (Lisa Leeson); Tom
Wu (George Seow), Daniel York (Henry Tan), Nigel Lindsay (Ron
Baker), Irene Ng (Bonnie Lee) and Lee Ross (Danny Argyropoulos). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
