<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIANT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-24 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNGODLY GOINGS-ON IN A FORSAKEN TOWN'S CHURCH
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
(nk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its rapid pretitle images of a young couple in bed in the
morning light, of soberly dressed men and women filing into a
church, of a woman fleeing from a house into woods, of a young man
donning the garb of a clergyman and delivering a sermon from the
Book of Job before bluntly dismissing his disgruntled congregation,
``The Broken Giant'' cloaks itself in an immediate air of
theological profundity and secular mystery.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time this film, written and directed by Estep Nagy,
has run its attenuated course, it proves to be a monotonous drama
that generates tensions and avoids resolution by withholding
essential information about its pivotal characters for as long as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Broken Giant,'' opening Friday at Anthology Film
Archives, moody visual talent outbalances literary skill; character
is not so much revealed as arbitrarily obscured.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a little town that seems depopulated rather than
underpopulated, this low-budget film tells the story of a troubled
young minister, Ezra Caton (Will Arnett). He is descended from a
line of preachers, including his namesake grandfather who perished
in a way known to all the townspeople but withheld from the
audience until late in the film.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, Ezra types notes to his grandfather and sets
them afire. Ezra is having an affair with Rosemary (Brooke Smith),
the daughter of the town's mayor, Thomas Smith (George Dickerson).
Rosemary, who tends the counter at the local coffee shop, worries
that the distant Ezra might be moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Life grows more complicated when Clio Hale (Missy Yager), the
runaway seen in the film's opening moments, arrives at Ezra's Free
Will Church seeking sanctuary from her father, the sinister Bennett
Hale (John Glover).
</P>
<P>
   Although details of the relationship between Bennett and Clio
are never specified, it has clearly been unhealthy. But with an
assist from Tom Smith, who is not happy for various reasons about
the young woman sharing the church premises with his daughter's
beau and the town's not-so-popular minister, Bennett tracks down
Clio and appeals for her return.
</P>
<P>
   So, with Bennett threatened by the intervention of Ezra, with
Rosemary threatened by the appearance of the attractive Clio, with
Ezra and Clio threatened by the devious Bennett, the disapproving
Tom and their individual psychological demons, ``The Broken Giant''
at last provides the victimized Clio and the passive Ezra with an
opportunity to share confidences and take action.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE BROKEN GIANT
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Estep Nagy; director of photography,
Garrett Fisher; edited by David Leonard; music by Will Oldham;
production designer, Michael Krantz; produced by Jeffrey Clifford
and Jonathan Cohen; released by Blue Guitar Films. At Anthology
Film Archives, 32 Second Avenue, at Second Street, East Village.
Running time: 83 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Brooke Smith (Rosemary Smith), John Glover (Bennett Hale),
George Dickerson (Thomas Smith), Missy Yager (Clio Hale), Will
Arnett (Ezra Caton) and Chris Noth (Jack Frey).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
