A8253 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-NESS-PROFILE-HN     06-24 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-NESS-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIKE NESS HANGS TOUGH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mike Ness has tattoos covering much of his body. Two
of the least ornate, yet most provocative, are on his hands. Across
the knuckles of his left hand you'll find the letters ``L-O-V-E.''
On the other hand you'll find ``P-A-I-N.''
</P>
<P>
   Ness has known his share of both emotions in a music career that
began 20 years ago, when the 17-year-old high school dropout formed
a punk-rock band called Social Distortion in Orange County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   While all but a few bands from punk's formative years have long
since gone the way of all flesh, Social D has hung tough. The
band's masterpiece, ``Somewhere Between Heaven and Hell,'' was
released in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But following the release of a live album in 1998, Ness found
himself feeling restless. He wanted to write and sing some songs
that just didn't fit in Social D's louder, faster punk aesthetic.
Like, say, a love song.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Cheating at Solitaire,'' Ness' first solo album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved American roots music _ folk music, blues,
country, rockabilly,'' Ness said. ``With Social Distortion, I tried
to bring American roots to punk. With the solo thing, I'm trying to
bring punk to roots, to put back some of that darkness and angst
that's been lost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheating at Solitaire'' admirably fulfills this ambition, as
Ness combines covers of Bob Dylan's ``Don't Think Twice,'' Hank
Williams' ``You Win Again,'' Lefty Frizzell's ``Long Black Veil''
and Al Ferrier's ``Send Her Back'' with his own gritty originals.
He's joined on the album by a few high-profile friends, including
Bruce Springsteen, Brian Setzer and Billy Zoom.
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen, whom Ness approached after he read in Rolling Stone
magazine that Bruce was a Social Distortion fan, plays a mean
guitar and shares the snarling lead vocals on ``Misery Loves
Company.''
</P>
<P>
   Setzer adds his distinctive lead guitar to the bluesy ``Crime
Don't Pay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes a Gretsch guitar squeal like a pig,'' Ness said with
admiration. ``We have the same tattoo artist, so I guess it was
inevitable that we would share the same dark, sleazy, rockabilly
vibe.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoom, an original member of the seminal Los Angeles punk band X,
plays guitar on ``Dope Fiend Blues,'' which recalls Ness' lost
years as a heroin addict in the mid-'80s. He's been clean for more
than a decade, but he still feels drawn to the darkness on the edge
of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that ever really leaves you,'' Ness said. ``I've
also come to realize that I'm chronically irritable and discontent.
I have to be. That helps me write.''
</P>
<P>
   Ness, 37, grew up in Fullerton, Calif. As a kid, he was consumed
by a rage and frustration that found an outlet in the hard-core
punk-rock that was spreading to the Southern California suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Social Distortion's first album, ``Mommy's Little Monster,'' was
released in 1983, shortly before Ness began his descent into
junkiedom. One story from those days has him pawning the band's
equipment shortly before a gig to buy drugs, then borrowing another
band's equipment and pawning that gear, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ness announced his return to the living with Social Distortion's
1988 album ``Prison Bound.'' ``Somewhere Between Heaven and Hell''
included a flat-out rock cover of the Louvin Brothers country
classic ``Making Believe.'' The band's last studio album was called
``White Light, White Heat, White Trash.''
</P>
<P>
   Ness figures he'll eventually get back together with Social
Distortion. He plans to maintain separate band and solo careers,
like Neil Young with Crazy Horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I've learned about punk/alternative shows in the
last 15 years. A lot of people come who really have no idea why
they are there, or they're there for the wrong reasons. They come
to get drunk, and to fight, or to get in the front and crowd-surf.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff gets old after 20 years. I'm not sure how long I
can keep doing it. But I am sure I can keep doing this (his solo
career) from here on in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The older he gets, Ness said, the more he realizes that the
battle between the love and the pain is really taking place inside
him. He has a 7-year-old son, Julian, whom he describes as ``the
light of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am constantly having to rebond with him, because I'm gone
all the time,'' Ness said.
</P>
<P>
   But lest anyone accuse him of going wimpy or soft, Ness says
fans can expect a high-energy rock band.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still the same Mike Ness you know from Social Distortion.
It's a more intimate setting, but it's definitely not a quiet
show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
