<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHRISROCK-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIS ROCK: TOO BIG AND TOO FUNNY TO IGNORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ His raw, relevant and Emmy-winning HBO stand-up show,
``Bring the Pain,'' established Chris Rock as a talent bigger and
better than any of his peers, a voice too strong, too funny for his
fame to be limited to his race, his generation.
</P>
<P>
   Now here comes ``Chris Rock: Bigger &AMP; Blacker,'' a new stand-up
show that will play on HBO next month. Rock says he selected the
title as ``a knockoff on LL Cool J's second album, ``Bigger &AMP;
Deffer.'' It's a title that puts pressure on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   As if he needed an excuse. Just 33, he's been crowned ``the
funniest man in America'' by Vanity Fair and ``probably the
funniest and smartest comedian working today'' by The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   That billing comes hard-earned _ smart, hilarious performances
on TV, in movies, on CD, in commercials, in print. The trick is
holding on to it: staying visible without overexposing himself;
maintaining his Everyman appeal while producing extraordinary work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The maintenance is the hard thing,'' Rock says. ``You know,
people win the lottery, they're doing fine. It's just the
maintenance. They buy the big house, but it's keeping it up (that's
difficult).''
</P>
<P>
   He feels that pressure to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I like where I'm at, and I'd like to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   And maintaining does not mean standing still.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm the same guy (I always was),'' Rock says. ``I live
at the same place I lived before the HBO special (a three-story
carriage house in Brooklyn that he shares with his wife, Malaak
Compton-Rock). I don't know _ I may be a little more demanding, a
little more confident. That's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits his work habits have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work harder,'' he says. ``I've got more to lose. A lot more
to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why he's playing Sunday in Houston and 27 other cities
in anticipation of his first stand-up appearance on TV since 1996's
``Bring the Pain.'' The majority of what audiences see will show up
on the special, which Rock taped in mid-June at the Apollo Theater
in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   What can we expect?
</P>
<P>
   ``You start with the Columbine thing, get into a little gun
control, the media, Clinton. You get into a lot of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   How does television come out in this?
</P>
<P>
   ``TV's fine,'' says the TV star, who also is an executive
producer of the ABC-TV sitcom ``The Hughleys.'' ``You can't blame
the media for this ... .No one takes into account, if you went to
medical school right now, what do you listen to? Marilyn Manson,
Snoop Doggy Dogg. What do lawyers listen to? What do engineers
listen to? They're listening to that same (stuff).
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't think a 35-year-old physician saw `Scarface'? So
does he not count? Is his degree not good? (It's said that) no one
listens to gangsta rap and actually does something with his life.
`Au contraire.'''
</P>
<P>
   There's your evidence that Rock approaches issues from a
different place than most. Combine that with impeccable delivery in
a modulating, often high-pitched voice that can only be described
as ``funny,'' and you have what The Washington Post calls ``a
brilliant comic, a charming presence.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that praise comes a bigger, brighter spotlight.
Appearance, scrutinized. Every word, scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   His few detractors point to his penchant for obscenities and his
use of the ``n'' word. His monologues have been scribbled down and
reprinted, cussed and discussed with the frequency and attention
afforded a network anchor, a politician or the president.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, amid all that noise, he maintains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, until I do something that (reeks),'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So he kept a low profile for most of the year _ ``since
November, the only time people have seen me on TV is at a Knicks
game'' _ and now is touring furiously. The ``Bigger &AMP; Blacker''
stand-up tour ends July 8. The TV special, July 10 on HBO, will
beget a CD, July 13 from DreamWorks Records. Then he'll turn around
and begin a new season of ``The Chris Rock Show.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is the secret to his success:
</P>
<P>
   ``The act always needs to be better,'' he says. ``Everything
needs to be better. Until I wake up and I'm Richard Pryor, I'm
always going to have to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means the funniest man in America believes someone else is
the funniest man in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a tenth as funny as Richard Pryor. I'm not (one of the
giants). I can barely ...''
</P>
<P>
   His voice trails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they'll let me sit at a little table next to the big
table.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
