<SLUG> BC-KILLER-KIDS-EXPERTS-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY YOUTHS' ATTITUDES ABOUT VIOLENCE SHOCK SOME EXPERTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, June 27) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Houston last year, juveniles committed 6.7 percent of all
reported homicides.
</P>
<P>
   And while that number is small _ 17 were recorded _ it doesn't
reflect the number of more common crimes in which potentially
deadly force was used. Statewide in January, 126 juveniles were
held in Texas Youth Commission facilities for killings. The figure
did not include those minors certified to stand trial as adults.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Godwin, a 25-year prosecutor who now heads the Harris
County District Attorney's juvenile division, is among those
flabbergasted by the pervasiveness of youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1974, we almost never saw a case involving a gun,'' she
said. ``Now it's completely off the map. ... Often kids don't have
a real idea of morally what's right or wrong, but they are
streetwise about what's legal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, authorities noted, homicide is the second leading
cause of death for minors. That many of those crimes were committed
by the victims' age peers is a given.
</P>
<P>
   Violence, said Texas Youth Commission official Linda Reyes,
often begets violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find that most (violent youths) have been in seriously
abusive families,'' said Reyes, who is the agency's assistant
deputy executive director for rehabilitative services. ``They
witness violence between parents, violence between siblings,
violence on the street. By the time they're 4, 5 or 6 years old,
they've actually witnessed several killings on the streets of their
own neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Those messages are reinforced by the media, ever eager to find
more novel, violent ways to entertain. While video games and rap
lyrics might not, in themselves, lead teens to kill, Reyes said,
they help desensitize youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time they're 14 or 15, they've been immersed in a
violent socialization and the idea of killing someone _ or seeing
that as an option _ comes easily to them. ... They see that power
is in the hands of the victimizer and say, `I'm not going to be the
victim anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   Family abuse doesn't even have to be violent to wreak
devastation on young psyches, added Peter Sheras, University of
Virginia professor and associate director of the Virginia Youth
Violence Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it doesn't even have to be abuse,'' he said.
``Sometimes it's neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask the parents, `Where's little Joey?''' said veteran
Houston homicide Sgt. Waymon Allen, ``and they'll tell you he's
visiting Pete. But if you ask them who Pete's parents are, or what
his phone number and address are, they can't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Too often, gangs provide the missing family support.
</P>
<P>
   Sheras noted that youth gangs bind their members with ``fierce
loyalty, a strong emotional connection.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They see other people as the enemy,'' he said. ``Or as an
annoyance.''
</P>
<P>
   And often a reckless fatalism is encouraged. ``They don't
imagine living long and fruitful lives,'' Sheras said. ``What they
see is the short term. They'd rather die in a blaze of glory rather
than struggle to make a life for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said children from the most violent backgrounds
sometimes exhibit symptoms of the ``post-traumatic stress
syndrome'' found among battlefield veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They develop an armor against feelings,'' said Sheras.
</P>
<P>
   Such antisocial teens _ a group that includes 60 percent of
violent youth _ seem to have no feelings of guilt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They act in manipulative ways to gain money, position or
dominance,'' he said. ``They act in ways that seem cold-blooded.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
