<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILLER-KIDS-ART-$ADV2     06-24 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-KIDS-ART-$ADV27-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
HOUSTON :come to the games. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some aspects, the Littleton killings paralleled his own case,
Carson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kids,'' he said, ``were so neglected.''
</P>
<P>
   By his early teens, Carson was in free-fall.
</P>
<P>
   Urged on by bad companions, unsavory neighborhood youths Carson
described as ``knuckleheads,'' he drank two to three quarts of beer
each day, acquired guns and assumed the role of neighborhood tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started drinking at family barbecues,'' Carson said.
``Parents just assume that if they let you drink in the home under
their supervision, you're not going to do it in the streets.
They're wrong. My mother, a cook at the hospital, would be at work
when I'd come home at night. In the morning, there would be the old
remedy _ I'd start drinking again. When I'd get home from school,
she wouldn't know. She'd be there asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   On the chance occasion Carson's mother found her son
intoxicated, she simply admonished him ``to never put a syringe in
my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to have guns for self protection,'' he added. ``You'd
go to parties and there would be fights. On several occasions, I'd
step in to help a friend who was being beaten up and end up having
a pistol shoved to my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Such episodes of near violence might have served as an impetus
for Carson to find new friends. But, Carson added, ``In a situation
like that, you just don't want to get out. ... I wish to God I
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson's downward course accelerated on the evening of May 8,
1981, when the 16-year-old youth and four friends ran out of
gasoline while cruising a Houston neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   As Carson recalled the incident, he and his friends were walking
home when they were accosted by a group of men who shouted racial
slurs and began chasing them. Authorities suggested the men
surprised Carson's group as they burglarized an auto.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Carson fired two shots at the men, killing one and
injuring a second. ``We turned and ran,'' Carson recalled. Within
days, he and one of his friends, Toren Michael Milburn, 18, were
arrested and charged with murder. In October, weeks before the pair
were to be tried, Carson heard that Milburn wanted to talk with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Carson said said he found Milburn in a rage. ``He said his
lawyers told him I was going to testify against him,'' Carson said.
``He pulled out a knife. He started a fight and ended up
deceased.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Carson killed Milburn to keep him from turning
state's witness, then hastily buried him in a shallow grave.
</P>
<P>
   So hardened was Carson that even veteran prosecutors found him
unnerving.
</P>
<P>
   During his trial he threatened a prosecutor, then sat glowering
at witnesses from the defense table. ``He was scary,'' allowed
Assistant District Attorney Kris Moore, who worked to have him
certified to stand trial as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Carson was sentenced to two concurrent 40-year terms for the
murders.
</P>
<P>
   His grandmother, Ardilia Washington, was a frequent visitor to
the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had heard a lot of stories about what I had done,'' he
said, ``And the first time she came, she just said, `Chris, did you
kill those men?' I told her that I had. She was quiet for a minute,
and then said, `OK, now I'm at peace.' She just had to know for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   During his 14 years in prison, Carson said he matured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does someone have to get hurt for people to find
themselves?'' Carson said. ``Why did people die for me to get my
head right?''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Carson has been free on parole. He lives in a small
East Texas community, where he has married. He and his wife have an
infant daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Still his crimes haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry for killing these people,'' he said. ``I think about
them and their families. I'd like to write to tell them I'm sorry.
But how do I do that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see their anger. Their frustration. They may view me as
a little old (expletive). How do I know how they'll react? Maybe
they'll let the Lord handle it. Or maybe they'll say the law made
me pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or maybe they'll say, `You haven't paid enough. You're going
to pay for it our way.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`I TOOK LIFE, AND LIFE IS SO PRECIOUS' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a gangster, that was my goal in life,'' said Robert,
whose real name is being withheld at his request. ``That was my
life. It was real painful. If I gave out pain, I didn't feel
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 19, Robert doesn't know how many people he's killed.
Although he told Houston police and state psychologists that he
believed he had killed at least two people, he did not mention
those cases when interviewed recently at an Austin halfway house,
where he is enrolled in a capital offender program.
</P>
<P>
   What's clear is that he meant to kill. On the night that he
participated in the murder of a rival gang chief at a Houston
multigang peace conference _ the crime for which he was sentenced _
he also twice tried to shoot an enemy in the head with a shotgun.
On both occasions, the weapon failed to fire.
</P>
<P>
   Robert's early life with an abusive father, passive mother and
wayward siblings was a harbinger of worse things to come during his
adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   The youth's father, who ran an auto body shop, beat his children
three or four times a week, he said. On one occasion, Robert was
battered black and blue. That episode resulted in a phone call to
authorities. But when investigators arrived, Robert claimed the
bruises had resulted from a fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved my father,'' said Robert. ``... I came to see that
being a man was to be powerful, violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert first smoked marijuana at age 8.
</P>
<P>
   At 10, he joined one of the city's burgeoning Hispanic gangs as
a ``pee-wee member,'' serving an apprenticeship in stealing guns
and committing robberies.
</P>
<P>
   At 11, he joined in stealing cars, and at 12 he was a practiced
robber, ready to do anything it took to get the goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about their families,'' he said. ``If they had
something, I'd take it. If I had to shoot them, I'd do it. If I had
to hit them in the mouth, I'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the victims were gay residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd get $300 or $500 in each case,'' he said. ``We'd get
leather jackets and jewels. They'd come out of the beer joints
drunk. Once, my friend hit him and he fell and we stomped on him.
We got $500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of them tried to fight, but what can you do when
you've got five people on you? I didn't give a damn. I always felt
justified. It was pretty much a thrill. I was young, and youth has
to show strength. There was this power thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As Robert proved himself to his gang _ he ultimately pulled as
many as 100 robberies _ he was entrusted with greater
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owned crack houses,'' he said. ``I sold drugs. I had sex
with prostitutes. I figured only those who were unlucky got AIDS
and I was lucky. ... I smoked, drank beer, got into fights and got
involved with drive-bys.''
</P>
<P>
   On one occasion, Robert's heavily armed gang went in search of
the rival who had stabbed a member. They found a house they thought
_ but weren't certain _ was the offender's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fired a warning shot,'' Robert recalled. ``A lady, a
mother, came out. One of my gang had a 12-gauge. He shot at her and
she fell down. I had a .410. We shot up the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert didn't bother to find out if they had targeted the right
house or if their victim survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never watched the TV news,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Robert lived literally and figuratively on the edge of
a larger world _ sometimes he'd sit on his rooftop at night and
stare at the glimmering lights of downtown Houston _ he was so
involved in his gang that he saw few alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to school,'' he said. ``But to go to college, to be a
doctor, that wasn't in my future. The image taught to me was to be
bad, violent. That was my `doctor' _ to be bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no self-esteem. I didn't know who I was. I recognize now
how many people I've hurt, the pain I've caused. I took life, and
life is so precious.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a participant in the Texas Youth Commission's intensive
capital offender program, Robert has completed his high school
education and works part time as an auto mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Within six months, he will be released to a closely monitored
independent living program in Houston or Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think working was stupid,'' he said. ``We had all
the money we needed. But now I work hard for a living _ I'm a
mechanic. I work hard and it feels good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go to Dallas. It's a new place. I want to make
something good out of it. After all, everyone in the world is
looking for happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
