<HEADER>
A8274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     06-24 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `AFTER LIFE,' starring Arata, Taketoshi Naito and Erika Oda.
Directed by Hirokazu Kore-eda (not rated, 118 minutes). Much of
this transcendently compassionate, gently humorous Japanese film is
set in a drab office building where courteous caseworkers welcome
the week's new clients. The place turns out not to be a social
service agency but a metaphysical way station where the newcomers
are people of all ages and types who have just died and have three
days to select one memory to take with them into eternity. Before
they depart, those memories will be filmed. As they tell their
stories and make their choices (those who can't choose remain at
the processing center as caseworkers), the movie becomes a profound
meditation on life's meaning and value and the relationship of
movies, memories and dreams (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `AUSTIN POWERS: THE SPY WHO SHAGGED ME,' starring Mike Myers,
Heather Graham and Elizabeth Hurley. Directed by Jay Roach (PG-13,
95 minutes). There may come a time when even Austin Powers tires of
the words ``Oh, behave!,'' but it isn't here yet. Although the
sequel with the fab title is several love beads short of its
predecessor and more than a few scenes play like outtakes, this is
still a crafty, intermittently hilarious comedy. Myers' neo-Sellers
multiple-personality act is fine even when the material is less so,
and this sequel makes the most of Dr. Evil, his most inspired
creation. A scatological Scotsman, the film's walking id and
bathroom joke, is more of an acquired taste. Costumes and pop
references are still a hoot, as is the adorably benighted Austin.
Ms. Graham makes terrific eye candy, but doesn't share Ms. Hurley's
quick-witted air of being in on the joke (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ELECTION,' starring Matthew Broderick and Reese Witherspoon.
Directed by Alexander Payne (R, 105 minutes). From the acerbically
funny director of ``Citizen Ruth'' comes this caustic satire of the
American electoral process in a high school setting. Its leading
candidate, Tracy Flick, played tartly by Ms. Witherspoon, has a
mother who sought tactical advice for Tracy from Connie Chung and
Elizabeth Dole. Broderick plays the hapless good-guy teacher who
thinks this wicked little front-runner needs to be stopped. And the
hunky newcomer Chris Klein plays Tracy's reluctant opponent in a
style best described as early Keanu. With a lovely ear for
hypocritical conversation, the screenplay specializes in keeping
all the characters a few beats off what they actually mean
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ENTRAPMENT,' starring Sean Connery and Catherine Zeta-Jones.
Directed by Jon Amiel (PG-13, 105 minutes). This glossy caper
summons the days when being a thief was the profession of choice
among debonair movie heroes. And heroines: As the great-looking
insurance investigator who is supposedly investigating Connery's
glamorous super-burglar, Ms. Zeta-Jones makes a smashing gymnast
and heist expert in her own right. No need to believe the
outlandish details of the story; there's enough verve and charisma
to the stars to make the escapade easy on the eyes. The action
sequence, in which the stars hang off the side of the world's
largest skyscraper, is a vertiginous show stopper. And here's a
nice bonus: nobody gets killed (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE GENERAL'S DAUGHTER,' starring John Travolta, Madeleine
Stowe and James Woods. Directed by Simon West (R, 118 minutes).
Murder on a military base was once enough of a pretext for a
detective thriller, but nowadays it takes more. The prevailing
sleaze quotient calls for kinks, and this galling adaptation of a
Nelson DeMille best seller is happy to oblige. So the title
character, a pretty young officer whom the film thinks has no place
in the military, is the victim of a lurid crime. Travolta and Ms.
Stowe affably investigate whodunit, though the unraveling of the
crime is laughably arbitrary. The real point of their ponderous
investigation is that the victim asked for what she got (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `AN IDEAL HUSBAND,' starring Cate Blanchett, Minnie Driver,
Rupert Everett, Julianne Moore and Jeremy Northam. Written and
directed by Oliver Parker (PG-13, 97 minutes). The best thing about
Parker's likable but diluted screen adaptation of Oscar Wilde's
1895 comedy of politics and Victorian morality is Everett's
portrayal of Wilde's elegantly epigrammatic alter ego Lord Arthur
Goring. In underplaying this seemingly incorrigible (but actually
wise, witty and caring) rake, Everett makes him all the more
charming. Northam and Ms. Blanchett are well cast as a politician
and his priggish wife, but Ms. Moore and Ms. Driver miss hitting
the right notes in a screenplay that streamlines Wilde into a
quasi-contemporary style, keeping some but not all of the
playwright's scintillating bons mots. The settings are so lavish
they're almost edible (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `LIMBO,' starring Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio and David
Strathairn. Directed by John Sayles (R, 126 minutes). Part
survivalist drama, part satirical portrait of contemporary Alaska,
Sayles' powerful new film is almost as vast as the great outdoors
it contemplates. Ms. Mastrantonio, as a well-traveled folk-rock
singer working Alaskan lounges, and Strathairn, as the brooding
local fisherman with whom she becomes involved, make one of the
most compelling adult couples to be seen in an American film in
quite some time. When they find themselves castaways along with her
teen-age daughter on a remote Alaskan island, the movie becomes
both a suspense thriller and a sorrowful meditation on survivalism,
civilization and the ties that bind. Though marred by an abrupt
ending and glaring literary devices, ``Limbo'' is eminently
worthwhile (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE MATRIX,' starring Keanu Reeves and Laurence Fishburne.
Directed by Andy and Larry Wachowski (R, 120 minutes). The
time-traveling story steeped in virtual reality will be all but
incomprehensible to anyone but techno freaks. And the film borrows
unapologetically from other sci-fi extravaganzas, with a big debt
to ``The X-Files.'' But the storytelling is intricately bizarre and
the special effects are indeed special, notably when it comes to
midair martial arts with a gravity-defying gusto. And Reeves shows
that you can look like a Prada model while behaving like an action
hero. One of the main stars here is Bill Pope, an inventive
cinematographer. He and the Wachowskis provide a couch-potato
epiphany; while the characters seem to be performing marvelous
feats, they're often lying stock-still in the grip of virtual
reality (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE MUMMY,' starring Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz, Arnold
Vosloo and John Hannah. Directed by Stephen Sommers (PG-13, 134
minutes). More like a video game than a movie, this incoherent
spoof (very loosely based on the 1932 Boris Karloff horror
classic), overloaded with cheesy special effects, suggests an
unwieldy hybrid of ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' and ``Abbott and
Costello Meet the Mummy'' via ``Night of the Living Dead.'' The
intrepid adventurers who disturb an ancient Egyptian crypt that
carries a fearful curse are Fraser (playing a swashbuckling
American in the Foreign Legion), Ms. Weisz (as a plucky, wide-eyed
English librarian) and Hannah (as her twitty older brother). It's
all played for laughs. The only scary moments involve swarming
scarabs that burrow under the skin and do awful ``Alien''-like
things (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `NOTTING HILL,' starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant. Directed
by Roger Michell (PG-13, 105 minutes). The most romantic notion
here may be that a Hollywood star as famous as Ms. Roberts might be
out, unassisted, browsing for a book. But it's enough to bring her
together with Grant's bashful bookseller and let two
extraordinarily charming actors play out an intelligent flirtation.
As written by Richard Curtis with frequent wit and welcome echoes
of his ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' this is a bright, winsome
romantic comedy that's as teasing as the characters themselves,
inviting the audience to ponder the movie star's burdens of being
world famous and desperately attractive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE RED VIOLIN,' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Jason Flemying,
Greta Scacchi and Don McKellar. Directed by Francois Girard (not
rated, 130 minutes). ``The Red Violin'' follows the colorful
300-plus-year journey of a priceless violin from its construction
in an Italian workshop in 1681 to a contemporary auction in
Montreal. As it makes its way from Vienna to England to Communist
China, the instrument becomes the inspiration for some richly
photographed historical tableaux. If the movie's narrative energy
is undermined by a plodding screenplay and wooden acting, the
music, composed by John Corigliano and played by Joshua Bell and
the London Philharmonia Orchestra, is sublime (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE,' starring Liam
Neeson. Directed by George Lucas (PG-13, 132 minutes). Stripped of
hype and breathless expectations, Lucas' first installment offers a
happy surprise: It's up to snuff. It sustains the gee-whiz spirit
of the series and offers a swashbuckling extra-galactic getaway,
creating illusions that are even more plausible than the
kitchen-raiding raptors of ``Jurassic Park.'' While the human stars
here are indeed reduced to playing action figures, they are
upstaged by amazing backdrops and hordes of crazily lifelike space
beings as the Lewis Carroll in Lucas is given free rein. The ``Star
Wars'' franchise was funnier and scrappier when it was new. But it
simply wasn't capable of this (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TARZAN,' with the voices of Tony Goldwyn, Minnie Driver and
Nigel Hawthorne. Directed by Kevin Lima and Chris Buck (G, 88
minutes). No need to wonder how this animated Tarzan movie could
improve on the 47 others that preceded it. Disney animation turns
the hero into a supple, long-haired hunk, lets the apes talk to
him, and whooshes through lush jungle settings with exultant
agility. This ``Tarzan'' is sprightly and likable in ways that are
hard to resist, with lively vocal performances, excitingly kinetic
animation and Phil Collins singing tunefully in the background.
Parents will stay awake, and children will be charmed (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TEA WITH MUSSOLINI,' starring Cher, Dame Judi Dench, Joan
Plowright, Dame Maggie Smith and Lily Tomlin. Directed by Franco
Zeffirelli (PG, 117 minutes). The screen divas (especially Dame
Maggie) who give ``Tea With Mussolini'' a patina of class obviously
relish chewing the scenery in this sudsy historical drama (adapted
from a chapter of Zeffirelli's autobiography) about a circle of
English expatriate women living in Florence on the eve of World War
II. Dame Maggie, a quintessential British snob, is the leader of
the pack, nicknamed the Scorpioni, whose comfortable lives are
shattered when the Fascists rise to power and they find themselves
carted off to a Tuscan hill town, where they are held under house
arrest. Cher is her usual likable self as a free-spending,
free-loving wealthy American heiress and art collector who
befriends the group (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WINSLOW BOY,' starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca Pidgeon and
Jeremy Northam. Directed by David Mamet (G, 110 minutes). Terence
Rattigan's play about the 1910 schoolboy's trial that created a
furor in England has been artfully pared down to its essentials in
this adaptation. Played with unusually effective restraint by a
fine cast, it works as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in
which the family of a cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered
by the consequences of that accusation. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly
arch acting style sets the film's tone and gives her suffragist
character a sharp edge (Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
