<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8277 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILLER-KIDS-ART-$ADV2     06-24 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-KIDS-ART-$ADV27-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRONG CHOICES: TV? THE STREETS? UPBRINGING? WHAT CAUSES KIDS TO
KILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, June 27) 
 
(Eds.: Photos available on NYT database) 
(Also see: Killer-kids-experts) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Robert didn't care whom he killed. He was a robber,
drive-by shooter, Houston bad man extraordinaire, and all life,
except his own, was cheap. That's the way he felt when he took a
hard, 35-year fall for murder five years ago. He was only 14.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Carson always looked out for number one. First he
killed a man; then he killed an accomplice who planned to testify
against him. He was 16 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Beaver loved his mom. No one was more surprised than he
when he beat her to death with a baseball bat at their Fort Bend
County home near Houston. He was 15.
</P>
<P>
   These are the stories of kids who kill.
</P>
<P>
   Such crimes invariably galvanize politicians to word-whip the
entertainment industry for glamorizing violence, to demand an end
of easy juvenile access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   They perpetually startle complacent Americans whose attention
turns to youth violence only after headline-grabbing tragedies like
this year's Littleton, Colo., school shootings in which 15 people
died.
</P>
<P>
   What causes kids to kill? The answers are myriad _ and
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts hypothesize that violence spreads like an insidious
virus from generation to generation. A preponderance of violent
teens, they note, have felt the lash of parental abuse or, more
subtle but no less destructive, the hush of parental indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Violence in the home, violence in the streets, violence on the
movie or television screen _ it's easy to see, they say, why some
kids come to believe murder is an acceptable solution to some of
life's problems.
</P>
<P>
   But while prosecutors, police and psychologists can offer
valuable insights, no one understands the nuances of pain _ for the
victim and the victimizer _ better than the teen-agers who have
grown to maturity behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I hope,'' said one interviewed for this article, ``is that
someone, maybe a high school counselor, can take my story and use
it. To tell some kid, `Here's someone who made the wrong choices.
Don't be like him.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`WHAT'S GOING ON WITH THESE KIDS?' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The inmates at Texas' grimy red-brick Walls Unit in downtown
Huntsville have seen it all. But when word of the April 20
slaughter of students at Columbine High School in the Denver suburb
of Littleton filtered through the cell blocks, even the most
hardened prisoners shook their heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such an extreme,'' said Walls inmate Beaver. ``People
in here generally were shocked. They were saying, `Man, what's
going on with these kids?'''
</P>
<P>
   Similar sentiments were voiced in suburban Fort Bend County in
the late summer of 1988 when Beaver, then 15 and a member of a
loose-knit adolescent gang called the Wolverines, was arrested for
bashing his mother's head with a baseball bat.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Macha, 39, was beaten at least a dozen times with the
bat, a portion of which lodged in her skull.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a little baseball with my mother,'' Beaver told other
youths after his arrest. ``I made a boo-boo.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believed members of the group, about 10 suburban
high school kids, some of whom were suspected Satan worshippers,
planned to kill their parents, then flee to Mexico. Two other
parents of gang members suffered nonlethal attacks on the same day.
Beaver, however, who now is serving a 15-year sentence for his
crime, insisted that his mother's death simply grew out of a
daylong quarrel about his previous day's attempt to run away from
home.
</P>
<P>
   Beaver said he was driven to the Wolverines _ ``a bunch of kids
trying to appear tough'' _ by violent disagreements with his
stepfather, a heavy equipment operator who occasionally beat his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a distant type of person,'' Beaver said. ``He was
emotional, and his main emotion was anger. He disapproved of me and
my two sisters. He didn't want us to talk at the dinner table. He
wanted to discipline me; he'd talk about how I needed to be
disciplined. I'd be standing there, and he'd talk as if I was
furniture. He just made me feel worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, Beaver said, his stepfather grabbed his shirt in an
apparent effort to assault him. ``I didn't wait,'' Beaver said. ``I
came out swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of a `floater,''' he said. ``I had friends in
different groups, but I didn't belong to any of them. I liked
athletics _ soccer, basketball, football _ but I wasn't a jock. I
liked heavy metal, but I wasn't a metalhead. I had a lot of
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   It was through a friend that Beaver was introduced to the gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't walk around with gang signs. There weren't certain
clothes we'd wear. You were just a Wolverine. There was no
organization, just a bunch of kids. If you'd see a girl and she was
involved, that was one way to get the girl. You'd join up to beat
your chest for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his arrest, one of Beaver's classmates said that
Beaver often fantasized about becoming a ``vampire.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the gang, Beaver said, often got drunk and used
drugs. Never an outstanding student, Beaver began to fail his
classes. ``Me and a couple of guys broke into a store,'' he said.
``One said he knew where the money was, but we just got a bunch of
cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   As his school performance deteriorated, Beaver came to the
attention of school counselors. But their efforts made matters
worse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a problem with my mother,'' he said. ``She stood
between the kids and our stepfather. ... She liked to have a good
time, go out drinking with her friends. She wanted to help her kids
do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to leave,'' he said. ``I had tried to run away but
they arrested me. The day before I had been drunk and high. We got
into an argument. I was thinking with the mindset of a Wolverine. I
was prepared mentally for gang banging. When our fight began, I was
already preset. I grabbed what was nearby _ a bat. I only remember
the beginning and the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, I was numb. I had no feelings. I was walking down the
street, thinking, `What's wrong?' There was no anger, no sadness.
Just completely numb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, I was just tired. Then scared. A few days later, I
started feeling sadness and remorse. At first, I was just charged
with aggravated assault. I thought maybe it wasn't that bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how bad it was. You've got a protecting
mechanism for things you don't want to know. When it was explained
to me that my mother had died, then the realization set in. Grief.
Fear.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Beaver _ certified to stand trial as an adult _ was
convicted of murder and sentenced to the penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, Beaver said he has repeatedly relived the events
leading to the murder. He's gleaned bits of truth about himself and
teen-agers in general. If he could convey a message to his dead
mother, he said, it simply would be: ``I'm sorry. I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers, Beaver said he now recognizes, live purely in the
present, with little appreciation for the consequences of their
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids don't realize they can be put in jail,'' he said. ``It
really sucks. Day for day, I've lived (nearly) half my life in
prison.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`I'M SORRY FOR KILLING THESE PEOPLE' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gang life held little allure for Carson. He excelled in sports,
did relatively well in school and seemed destined for a future of
some promise.
</P>
<P>
   Though his home life on Houston's north side sometimes was
tumultuous, his visits to his grandparents' East Texas farm were a
touchstone of stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have stayed up on the farm,'' the two-time killer
mused during a recent interview. ``I got into it more. I loved my
grandparents. I worked with the hogs and cows. I loved hauling hay.
I knew right from wrong. All I needed was a little push in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   In the city, though, Carson felt anchorless. His parents,
preoccupied with making ends meet, offered little support, he said.
Though Carson played school football, he was perpetually
disappointed when his family failed to come to the games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
