<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FTC-INTERNET (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission unveils
a consumer education campaign designed to steer people away from
misleading health information on the Internet. The agency also
cites four companies for deceptive online marketing of products
like magnets and shark cartilage. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-GLORY (Washington) _ For the third time, the House votes
overwhelmingly to approve a constitutional amendment aimed at
outlawing desecration of Old Glory. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CRIMINAL-ASSETS (Washington) _ The House votes on a bill to make
it harder for the federal government to seize private property
without filing criminal charges. The bill's supporters, led by Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., say it is needed to remedy what they see as a
license for federal officials to abuse the rights of innocent
people. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ENDS (Washington) _ A look at the big picture as the
Supreme Court concludes its term, including where the court has
ventured and what its actions might mean for the country. By STEVE
LASH.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-BAR-HONORED (Washington) _ For the first time, the federal
government has given landmark status to a gay and lesbian site,
putting New York's Stonewall Inn on the National Register of
Historic Places. The scene of rioting 30 years ago after police
raided the bar, it was recognized by President Clinton earlier this
month as the birthplace of the gay civil rights movement. By DAN
FREEDMAN. (Will update)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-DISCRIMINATION (Washington) _ A bill to ban job
discrimination against gays and lesbians is reintroduced in both
chambers of Congress but faces many hurdles, especially in the
House. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL-JUDGE (Washington) _ Keith Ellison, a Houston lawyer,
clears the Senate Judiciary Committee on his way to Senate
confirmation as a federal judge. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Austin, Texas) _ Republican presidential candidate
Steve Forbes attacks Gov. George W. Bush's claims that he is a
tax-cutter, noting accurately that Bush in 1997 endorsed and
lobbied for 75 tax increases. Bush, meanwhile, stumps in Detroit
before heading off to Florida to campaign with brother, Gov. Jeb
Bush. By CLAY ROBISON and R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER-MEXICO (Mexico City) _ The FBI knows him as Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez, but in his Mexico hometown of Rodeo, Durango,
townsfolk know the suspected killer as Angel Maturino Recendez.
Initial accounts show him to be a child of landowner. His
stepfather was a soldier, and his mother works in a health clinic.
A police officer who went to question the family says they appear
to have skipped town. By ANDREW DOWNIE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER-FUGITIVE (Houston) _ Sightings of accused serial
killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez in El Paso, and interviews with his
family in the same area, bring law enforcement officers closer to
finding the fugitive, but not yet close enough. By S.K. BARDWELL.
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER-FBI (Houston) _ Authorities in the FBI Command
Office have fielded nearly 1,000 tips regarding alleged serial
killer Rafael Resendz-Ramirez. We look at how authorities filter
the good tips from the bad, how the tips are categorized, and other
developments. By JANETTE RODRIGUES.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELOU-FLAP (Houston) _ A Houston group that honored Maya
Angelou last year with its ``Order of Kilimanjaro'' has sued the
famed writer/poet for not showing up at a December ceremony to pick
up the award. The group, African Overseas Union, says Angelou
breached a contract by not attending. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR-APPOINT (New York) _ Katherine (Kate) Betts, former
fashion news director of Vogue magazine, has been appointed
editor-in-chief of Harper's BAZAAR magazine. Betts, who succeeds
the late Elizabeth (Liz) Tilberis at the helm of the Hearst
publication, will join the company immediately. By The Hearst
Newspapers. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton is doing well
in the polls in New York, but Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr is
still after her. Will calling her to testify again and trashing her
in his final report backfire? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-FINALS (New York) _ Advance on Game 5 of the NBA Finals,
where the San Antonio Spurs can wrap up their first title. By
JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Astros return home for the first game
of a series with the second-place Cincinnati Reds. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
