<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush bids on large ranch near Waco
 &HT;    By Brad Reagan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Is McGregor the next Kennebunkport? And is Gov.
George W. Bush taking steps toward creating the next Texas White
House?
</P>
<P>
   That's the talk in Central Texas as sources confirm that Bush is
looking to buy a ranch west of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he has a bid in on it,'' said state Sen. David Sibley
of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman in Bush's office confirmed recently that Bush was
looking at land in the area, but said a deal had not been
completed. At a campaign stop in South Carolina, Bush declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley said the ranch is ``several hundred acres'' in western
McLennan County near the town of McGregor, about 20 miles from
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner in Austin last week, Sibley said, Bush extolled the
beauty of the land, which includes a creek running through the
property and several canyons. Bush's wife, Laura, then asked for
recommendations of home builders in the area, Sibley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes have reportedly been looking at land in the area for
several months.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Citrano, owner of the Coffee Shop in Gatesville, said the
couple stopped in the restaurant last month and told him they were
looking to buy a ranch nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Before closing the deal, Bush is waiting on an engineer's report
regarding whether the land will hold water, Sibley said. The report
would indicate whether Bush, an avid fisherman, would be able to
build a stock tank on the property.
</P>
<P>
   As for the possibility that Bush could make McLennan County the
millennium's equivalent of LBJ's Texas White House in Blanco County
near Johnson City, Sibley said, ``It's an exciting prospect.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
