<HEADER>
A8302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARGE-MUSIC-ART-3TAKE     06-24 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARGE-MUSIC-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBER MUSIC AS IT WAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chamber music, as its name implies, is music meant to
be performed in chamber-size rooms. Historically, such performances
were informal. When Mozart and some friends got together to play
string quartets, they were taking part essentially in sight-reading
sessions for the musicians involved, with sometimes an extra
listener or two. And they were usually playing in someone's living
room. Even when the idea of chamber music concerts took hold, these
still tended to be private affairs in smaller spaces, at most a
wealthy musical amateur's elegant salon with chandeliers, satin
sofas and floor space for additional chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The concert halls where chamber music is typically performed
today are too large. Alice Tully Hall, which was built for chamber
music, is much too large at 1,096 seats. Merkin Concert Hall, which
seats about 450, is better. The rotunda at the Frick Collection,
which can accommodate about 175, is better still, though the sound
of the room is rather bright.
</P>
<P>
   But is there any place where music lovers can experience the
intimacy of chamber music as it was in the days of Mozart and
Mendelssohn and as it should still be today?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. On a 102-foot solid steel barge docked on the East River in
Fulton Ferry Landing in Brooklyn, just south of the Brooklyn
Bridge, practically underneath it.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1977, this has been the home of Bargemusic, which may be
the most prolific chamber music series in the world, since it
offers at least two concerts a week _ on Thursday evenings and
Sunday afternoons, and during certain periods one more on Friday
nights _ all year round.
</P>
<P>
   The founder and director of Bargemusic is the 80-year-old Olga
Bloom, a wizened, soft-spoken yet indomitable amateur violinist who
is also something of a local character among her maritime
neighbors. She owns the barge, which she bought in the 1970s for
$10,000, and until about 15 years ago she lived on it as well. ``I
was a peculiar apparition around here,'' she said on Sunday after
an all-Schubert concert on the barge. ``I was happy living here.
But the city was getting so many inquiries from other harbor people
who wanted to live on the river that they kicked me off.'' She
bought a Civil War-era home in the Red Hook section of Brooklyn for
$6,000 and lives there still.
</P>
<P>
   She might as well be living on the barge for all the time she
spends there. It's nothing fancy, just your basic barge, with a
10-foot high ceiling and a narrow metal gangplank. But inside, the
walls are paneled with lovely cherry wood, which Ms. Bloom carted
over in her car from Staten Island and installed herself with help
from family and friends. There are the requisite amenities (a
restroom and such), and a pantry to prepare snacks and drinks for
sale. Using folding chairs, the space can accommodate about 130
comfortably, though the Fire Department has given clearance for
179.
</P>
<P>
   The barge may be spare, but the view it affords of lower
Manhattan across the river is spectacular, and it can be enjoyed
not just from the rooftop deck, where the audience wanders during
intermission, but from inside during the concerts: The musicians
play on a slightly raised platform against a rear wall of windows
that overlooks the river.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the room's acoustical properties that make it so ideal
for chamber music. Actually, the space has some acoustical quirks.
The piano, a lovely Steinway, sounds imposing up close, yet
somewhat under-powered on the far side of the room. But it doesn't
matter. The intimate space draws you into the midst of a
performance. On Sunday, when a group of fine musicians played
Schubert's ``Trout'' Quintet, the resonance of the bass seemed to
travel right through the floorboards, and the brilliant piano
writing in the high register of the keyboard jangled in the ears.
It was positively symphonic. And that's the point. Heard up close,
chamber works become enormous musical statements.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of chamber music on a barge may seem peculiar, but Ms.
Bloom points to a precedent. When King George I of England asked
Handel to write music for a royal water party, legend has it that
the musicians played for the revelers on a barge floating up the
Thames. ``If it was good enough for a king, it is good enough for
us,'' Ms. Bloom says.
</P>
<P>
   But her inspiration was as much spiritual as musical. ``We are
strangling in plastic,'' she says. ``It has been my sad fate to
watch electronic developments increase the profitability of music
in certain areas and diminish the sensitivity of human response in
general.'' She wanted to create at least one small place where
people can come together, audiences and musicians, and realize that
they have shared values.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, for gala events, Ms. Bloom will participate in a
performance. Mostly she plays chamber music in the traditional way:
with friends at home in the darkness of the night, she says.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloom was born in Boston to immigrant parents. Her Russian
father, an ardent communist, ``played the violin atrociously,'' she
says. Her mother, of Slavic descent, sang beautifully. Their
relationship survived the turbulent 1920s by their shared love of
nature and music. Ms. Bloom's violin teacher, Jacques Hoffmann, was
the associate concert master of the Boston Symphony Orchestra at
the time. When the Depression came, he kept teaching her free of
charge. When Ms. Bloom realized that a professional career as a
violinist was not in her future, she still felt a need to give
something back to music.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Bargemusic going was a formidable undertaking. She owned
two barges before settling on the current one. The first was a
``glorious thing,'' Ms. Bloom says, with massive beams. But the
4-inch-thick flooring just soaked up the sound. Moreover, a wooden
barge was uninsurable, she learned. So public concerts would have
been prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   The second barge was solid steel, but the particular type of
steel was spongy and brittle. ``If you poked your finger in the
hull, it started to give way,'' she explains. Over the years Ms.
Bloom has put some $100,000 into renovating the current barge,
which has proved reliable and inviting.
</P>
<P>
   A large circle of excellent and loyal musicians have been
involved with Bargemusic. The remarkable cellist Ronald Thomas, who
is based in New York but is also the artistic director of the
Boston Chamber Music Society, participated in Sunday's program and
serves on the seven-member Resident Artists Committee, which picks
the programs. ``So many of us have played with each other over the
years, not just here but in other places, that it feels like we are
regular partners,'' he said after the concert. ``Yet there is a
comradeship, a spirit of informality that allows us to take musical
risks that we might not in some Manhattan hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the musicians must deal with the shifting of the
barge, which rocks gently up and down every time a ferry, tugboat
or cargo ship passes by. ``You can count on having a slip, or two
or three, in every piece,'' Thomas said. ``But it doesn't matter.''
Ms. Bloom thinks that a little sense of danger makes the atmosphere
more romantic and helps the audience pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians take risks not just in interpretations but in
programming, which is adventurous. A concert Friday night, part of
a special Friday series sponsored by the Nakamichi Foundation,
offers a piano trio composed in 1984-85 by the Argentine-born
composer Maurizio Kagel and the Brahms Piano Quartet in G minor. A
program on Sunday afternoon at 4 will present the fine Hungarian
pianist Peter Nagy in a recital of works by Messiaen, Bartok and
Schubert.
</P>
<P>
   Programs frequently mix the old and the new in enticing ways.
But even standard repertory programs, like Sunday's all-Schubert
concert, are freshly thought out. The ``Trout'' Quintet was
preceded by an Adagio and Rondo for the same group of unusual
instruments (violin, viola, cello, bass, piano), a little-known
work that sounds like a sketch for a mini piano concerto. Nagy also
gave an eloquent account of one of Schubert's least-heard piano
works, the five-movement Sonata, D. 459.
</P>
<P>
   New musicians keep getting drawn into the Bargemusic circle. In
February the pianist Peter Serkin played there for the first time
with a group of exemplary performers including two members of the
Artists Committee: the violist Paul Neubauer and the cellist Fred
Sherry. The program offered recent works by Oliver Knussen and Toru
Takemitsu and a pair of Haydn piano trios in big-gestured
performances that, heard up close, seemed a rebuke to the notion
that Classical-era chamber music should be refined.
</P>
<P>
   Change is coming to the Bargemusic schedule in January. Ms.
Bloom's board has just given her the go-ahead to offer regular
concerts on Saturday evenings. The idea would be to have one
program played on Thursday nights and Sunday afternoons, and
another on Friday and Saturday nights. This means that the rental
of the barge for catered events on Saturdays, which in the past has
provided one-third of the organization's income, will cease. ``The
hell with it,'' Ms. Bloom says. ``Everything in life is a risk.
Let's go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloom must be the only presenter of chamber music around who
has to worry about the dredging of New York Harbor. Plans for this
environmentally essential work are under heated discussion between
the Coast Guard, the Army Corps of Engineers, the Port Authority of
New York and the Department of Economic Development, she explained.
It will be a huge project, and no agreement has yet been reached
about how to proceed. Silt and sediment have accumulated in the
riverbed to the point that during low tides the barge sometimes
rests on rock, which is terrible for its hull.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Bloom remains irrepressible and committed to her barge
as a site for chamber music. She is even feeling more hopeful about
the economic future of struggling musicians, something that pained
her for decades. ``Finally, there seems to be a growing awareness
that we in this society are being blunted spiritually and
personally beyond redemption,'' she says. ``The arts can heal us,
and I think there is a new awareness of this. I think there is a
change in the tide.''
</P>
<P>
   She may be right. Ms. Bloom is an authority on the tide.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Bargeschedule
</P>
<P>
   Bargemusic is at the Fulton Ferry Landing, Old Fulton Street, at
the foot of the Brooklyn Bridge. Tickets are $23 ($20 for the
elderly, $15 for students). Information: (718) 624-2083 or (718)
624-4061. Here is a schedule of programs through August:
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: Kagel's Piano Trio and Brahms' Piano Quartet in G minor,
7:30 p.m. Performers are Jennifer Frautschi, violinist; Toby
Hoffman, violist; Felix Fan, cellist, and Paige Hoffman, pianist.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: Bartok's Dance Suite; Messiaen's ``Baiser de L'Enfant
Jesus'' from the ``Vingt Regards sur L'Enfant Jesus''; Schubert's
Sonata in B-flat, 4 p.m. Peter Nagy, pianist.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 1: Beethoven's String Quartet No. 5 in A; Dvorak's String
Quartet in F; Gershwin's ``Lullaby,'' 7:30 p.m. Also July 4 at 4
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 2: Griffes' Sonata for Solo Piano; Rorem's ``Night Music'';
Copland's Waltz and Celebration from ``Billy the Kid''; Fass'
``Capriccio''; Schonfeld's ``Cafe Music'' for Piano Trio;
Gershwin's ``Preludes,'' 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 8: Rossini's Duet for Cello and Bass; Mozart's
Divertimentos for Strings in F and D; Dvorak's Bass Quintet, 7:30
p.m. Also July 11 at 2 p.m.; the July 11 performance will be
broadcast live on WNYC-FM (93.9) and WNYC-AM (820).
</P>
<P>
   JULY 9: Telemann's Trio Sonata for Two Violins, Harpsichord and
Basso Continuo; Couperin's Duet for Bass and Harpsichord; Three by
Bach: Sonata for Violin in G minor, Gamba Sonata in G and the Trio
Sonata in C for Two Violins, Harpsichord and Basso Continuo; two by
Handel: the Ciaccona for Harpsichord in G and Air and Variazoni in
E, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 15: Mozart's Piano Trio in B flat; Mendelssohn's Piano Trio
in C minor; Pinnington/Peskanov's ``Circle II'' for Voice, Violin
and Cello, 7:30 p.m. Also July 18 at 2 p.m.; the July 18
performance will be broadcast live on WNYC-FM (93.9) and WNYC-AM
(820).
</P>
<P>
   JULY 16: Vivaldi's Violin Concerto ``L'a Tempesta di Mare'' in E
flat; Schubert's Rondo for Violin with String Quartet in A, and
Chausson's Concerto for Piano and Violin with String Quartet, 7:30
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 22: Beethoven Sonatas for Violin and Piano: in D (Op. 12,
No. 1); in A (Op. 12, No. 2); in E flat (Op. 12, No. 3) and in A
minor (Op. 23), 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 23: Beethoven Sonatas for Violin and Piano: in F (Op. 24);
in A (Op. 30, No. 1); in C minor (Op. 30, No. 2), 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 25: Beethoven Sonatas for Violin and Piano: in G (Op. 30,
No. 3); in A (Op. 47) and in G (Op. 96), 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 29: Beethoven's Piano Trio in D major; Chopin's Sonata in B
minor; Shostakovich's Piano Trio in E minor, 7:30 p.m. Also Aug. 1
at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 30: Stravinsky's Suite Italienne; Wuorinen's ``Fast
Fantasy'' and ``An Oracle of Jasp'' and short works by Debussy,
Stravinsky, Cui and Bach, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AUG. 5: Francaix's String Trio in C; Chopin's Sonata in G minor;
Brahms' Piano Quartet in C minor, 7:30 p.m. Also Aug. 8 at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AUG. 6: The Great American Song Book: Spirituals, love songs,
American songs and Bauer's ``Four Piano Pieces,'' 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AUG. 12: Beethoven's String Trio in C minor; Arensky's Quartet
for Strings in A minor; Schubert's String Quartet in C, 7:30 p.m.
Also Aug. 15 at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AUG. 13: To be announced.
</P>
<P>
   AUG. 19: Beethoven's Trio for Clarinet, Cello and Piano in B
flat; Elgar's Sonata for Violin and Piano; Mendelssohn's Trio in C
minor, 7:30 p.m. Also Aug. 22 at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AUG. 20: Debussy's Sonata for Cello and Piano; Beethoven's
Sonata for Piano and Cello in C; Schumann's Five Pieces in Folk
Style for Cello and Piano''; R. Strauss' Sonata for Cello and Piano
in F, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AUG. 26: Mozart's Flute Quartet in D; Villa-Lobos' ``Jet
Whistle'' for Flute and Cello; Durufle's Prelude, Recitative and
Variations for Flute, Viola and Piano; Brahms' Piano Quartet in A,
7:30 p.m. Also Aug. 29 at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AUG. 27: Bach/Reger's Brandenburg Concerto No. 6 in B flat;
Schubert's ``Lebensstuerme''; Debussy's ``Six Epigraphes
Antiques''; Gershwin's ``Rhapsody in Blue,'' 7:30 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
