<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8310 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEADLEY-QA25-COX     06-24 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADLEY-QA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Catching up with Headley: Concert, album, rehearsals for
retooled `Aida' among performer's projects
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's Atlanta's favorite diva up to these days?
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Heather Headley, the once and future star of
Disney's ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida,'' is languishing in
her Manhattan apartment, sifting through sheets of music, trying to
decide what to sing when she returns to the city this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After stealing the hearts of Atlanta theatergoers last fall, the
24-year-old Broadway performer _ known for her gazelle-like grace,
dramatically swooping eyebrows and, most importantly, that
murderously gorgeous voice _ is back for a solo, one-night-only
show Saturday at the 14th Street Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed up until 3 or 4 last night. I've got all my music
laid out on the bed,'' Headley (which is pronounced ``HAD-lee'')
says in a telephone interview, in an accent that has traces of
everything from Brooklyn to her native Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   For the concert she promises a bit of Broadway (including
numbers from her ``Ragtime'' and ``Lion King'' repertories), some
jazz (``Lush Life'') and plenty of gospel (her father was a
minister, so she grew up singing in the church). And, of course,
her signature song, ``Elaborate Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, these people will be able to leave the theater by
11 o'clock,'' she jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Headley's own clock is ticking. She's counting the
minutes until Aug. 1, when she wraps up her engagement as Nala in
Broadway's ``The Lion King,'' and Sept. 20, when she begins
rehearsals for a new version of ``Elaborate Lives,'' retitled
simply as ``Aida.'' The heavily overhauled production of the
musical begins Nov. 5 at Chicago's Palace Theatre; the show is
expected to open on Broadway in March.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, she'll be cutting her first album, which will
feature original music written by herself and others. But Headley
says she's taking her time on the project, which some believe could
be a major breakthrough. ``It's Whitney Houston meets Lauryn Hill,
who has lunch with Celine Dion while talking to Regina Belle,'' she
says, teasing about her big-throated style.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Headley talks nothing like a diva, sprinkling an
hourlong conversation with infectious laughter and self-deprecating
humor. Here's what she had to say about:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Her dream date: ``I'm so easy to please. `Pick up Kentucky
Fried Chicken, and we'll go to the beach.' I'm not a big restaurant
person. I don't like going to places where you feel you must
behave, where you have to sit and use the right fork and the right
knife. That's not me. If it's a dream date, it's that sense of
completeness and just being accepted (that I'm looking for). I
would be so comfortable with this person that I would eat chicken
wings in front of them.'' She says there's no significant other in
her life at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Her voice: ``I think I have the gift of air. I think God gives
you gifts, and he says, `Your gift of air is going to last for 80
years.' I feel that if I don't make the payments, it will be taken
from me. I have to make sure I give back in some way. I think
everybody has a loan (from God). All you have to do is figure it
out. Some people have a talent for listening, or being a friend.
Some people cannot be a good friend. Your talent does not mean you
have to be in front of people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Her early career: ``Mummy says I started singing at 2, that I
was on a radio program at 2. I remember coming home from school,
dropping my books and charging into the church and singing. It
would be a daily ritual, and I would sing until I was sweaty. I
would imagine that there were people in the pews. I would have a
little concert every day. I was just praying nobody would see me!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Her first record: ``I want to do timeless music, music that
you can go back and listen to years later _ like the Supremes and
Ella Fitzgerald. It sounds like it was just done yesterday. That's
why we are still talking Shakespeare and singing Verdi.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have the gift of air. I think God gives you gifts,
and he says, `Your gift of air is going to last for 80 years.' I
feel that if I don't make the payments, it will be taken from me. I
have to make sure I give back in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   HEATHER HEADLEY
</P>
<P>
   Entertainer
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
<P>
   Heather Headley in Concert
</P>
<P>
   7:30 p.m. Saturday. $35. 14th Street Playhouse, 173 14th St.
N.E. 404-733-5000 or www
</P>
<P>
   .woodruffcenter.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
