<HEADER>
A8312 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-DADDY25-COX     06-24 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-DADDY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comedian Adam Sandler pitches yet another winning goofball
character
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two ways to look at Adam Sandler. He's either the poor
man's Cary Grant or the white-collar crowd's long-lost fourth
Stooge.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of stokes his box office potency, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Here you have ``Big Daddy,'' Sandler's latest sure-fire
money-maker. It nimbly ties together elements from his successful
date movie ``The Wedding Singer'' (boyish innocence and charm to
woo the women in the audience) and his even more successful yukfest
``The Waterboy'' (scatological scatting just for the boys). Throw
in an itty-bitty kid for Sandler to pal around with and you have
the makings of a mack-daddy movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Daddy'' does work much of the time. It's light on its feet
and full of jokes that often hit their marks (especially if you
don't set the bar too high). Best of all is Sandler himself. He's
one smooth talker, whether he's connecting with his pint-size
co-star (played by 6-year-old identical twins) or cozying up to his
latest love interest (``Chasing Amy's'' Joey Lauren Adams).
</P>
<P>
   Sandler plays Sonny Koufax, a law school grad who's chosen to
spend his life watching cartoons and drooling milk while snarfing
down cereal. Oh, and he works part time at a New York toll booth.
</P>
<P>
   It's all the sweet sloth of life until his girlfriend bolts and
little Julian (played by Cole and Dylan Sprouse) shows up at his
door.
</P>
<P>
   Julian's story is a tremendously sad tale, and one that ``Big
Daddy'' pretty much lets slide right by. Suffice it to say that
Sandler's character ends up as the tyke's caretaker _ and the
comedy kicks into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   When a scared Julian wets the bed, Sonny's answer is to lay a
few newspapers over the sheets. When the kid can't sleep without a
night light, Sonny hooks one up: a neon sign that reads ``Live
Nudes.''
</P>
<P>
   He teaches Julian how to properly fold a pizza slice before
devouring it, how to master wrestling's sleeper hold, how to
urinate in public.
</P>
<P>
   It would be criminal if it wasn't all put together so darned
cutely.
</P>
<P>
   Stoking the shenanigans are numerous gay jokes, too many barbs
about Hooters restaurants, and respectable support from a talented
cast that includes Rob Schneider, Jon Stewart and Steve Buscemi.
Counterbalancing it all is Sandler's artistry in depicting Sonny's
sweet-guy attempts to win Layla (Adams) as his new girlfriend. Face
it, he's a pro.
</P>
<P>
   As Julian says in baby talk, reciting word for word Sonny's
tutelage in attracting women: ``Initiating the conversation is half
the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Daddy''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Adam Sandler and Joey Lauren Adams. Directed by Dennis
Dugan. Rated PG-13 for language. At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: He's all fun and
</P>
<P>
   games.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
