<HEADER>
A8313 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-HUSBAND25-COX     06-24 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-HUSBAND25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not at all ideal: Wilde with too little wit
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``An Ideal Husband'' is not an ideal introduction to Oscar
Wilde, playwright. Which probably explains why his ``The Importance
of Being Earnest'' or ``Lady Windermere's Fan'' are more frequently
revived. However, it was a long-running and unexpectedly successful
revival of ``Husband'' _ staged by Peter Brook in the mid-1990s _
that reportedly inspired director Oliver Parker to tackle the piece
on film.
</P>
<P>
   Wilde purists will note a few alterations. Everyone else will
probably wonder why Parker bothered.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Ideal Husband'' is a tale of politics, marriage and
morality in 1895 London. Rising political star Sir Robert Chiltern
(Jeremy Northam) and his high-minded activist wife, Gertrude (Cate
Blanchett), are routinely described by the press as ``what is best
in English public life.'' But a snake has entered their
late-Victorian paradise. She's Mrs. Laura Cheveley (Julianne
Moore), a visitor from Vienna. She wants Sir Robert to do her a
little favor. Namely, support a shady Argentine canal scheme in
which she is heavily invested. Should he refuse, Mrs. Cheveley has
a certain incriminating letter exposing a youthful indiscretion
that helped Sir Robert amass his wealth and reputation.
</P>
<P>
   One incriminating note leads to another. Thus, the complications
and misunderstandings mushroom as we ponder the following:
</P>
<P>
   (A) Will Sir Robert yield to Lady Cheveley's blackmail?
</P>
<P>
   (B) What will Gertrude, his no-less-ideal wife, think of him
should his sullied past be revealed?
</P>
<P>
   (C) Which Wildean witticism will their good friend and
self-appointed social gadfly Arthur Goring (Rupert Everett) drop
next? (Sample: ``To love oneself is the beginning of a lifelong
romance.'')
</P>
<P>
   What's onscreen is a well-acted, very well-appointed period
piece that becomes more stifling and less engaging as it goes
along. That's not to say you won't enjoy hearing Arthur tell his
fusty, patrician father (John Wood) that he talks about serious
things only on the first Tuesday of every month. Or that drama
lovers won't appreciate the not-so-subtle theatrical in-jokes (at
one point, everyone attends the London premiere of ``Earnest'' and
hears the playwright's celebrated curtain speech).
</P>
<P>
   But in a world where our own chief executive can carry on with
an intern in the inner sanctums of the White House, ``An Ideal
Husband'' can't help but seem a bit dated. Idealistic, perhaps, and
even admirable in its staunch support of public and private
responsibility. But dated nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even that might be less of a problem if Parker had
employed an aura of arch theatricality. Instead, he opts for a
humanistic realism that stymies even such good actors as Blanchett
(``Elizabeth'') and Northam (``The Winslow Boy''). And poor Minnie
Driver, who plays Sir Robert's younger sister, is a disaster. She's
supposed to be saucy and provocative but comes off as mannered and
unappealing.
</P>
<P>
   Everett is luckier. He has the most screen time (he may, in
fact, be the ideal connubial partner of the title _ a juicy irony
because he poses as a confirmed bachelor) and gets the good lines.
He strikes exactly the sort of playful, raised-eyebrow tone the
rest of the production lacks. And Moore is simply wonderful.
Punctuating her every dastardly deed with a friendly twinkle, she's
the most Machiavellian screen female this side of Bette Davis in
``The Little Foxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An Ideal Husband''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Rupert Everett, Cate Blanchett, Jeremy Northam and
Julianne Moore. Rated PG-13 for brief nudity and sexuality. At
Garden Hills and Mansell Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Less than ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
