<SLUG> BC-FTC-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC WARNS CONSUMERS ABOUT MISLEADING INTERNET HEALTH PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission unveiled a consumer
education campaign Thursday designed to warn the public about
misleading health information and unproven cures touted on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also cited four companies for deceptively marketing
products like magnets and shark cartilage capsules over the
Internet as effective treatments for cancer and other serious
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet offers a powerful tool for finding health
information,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of the FTC's Bureau
of Consumer Protection. ``Our survey of web sites found that too
many make deceptive, unproven and fraudulent claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year more than 22 million Americans sought health and
medical information on the Internet, making health and medical
information one of the most popular targets of online searchers.
</P>
<P>
   While the FTC continually monitors the Internet for bogus health
claims, Bernstein said the agency cannot keep up with the hundreds
of web sites that promote fraudulent products.
</P>
<P>
   One such site touted shark cartilage capsules as a ``tumor
inhibitor'' and offered the product for $14.50. The company
marketing the product, Body Systems Technology, Inc., said that
studies proved ``that shark cartilage is an effective cancer
treatment.'' The firm cited a 1992 study by a Texas doctor claiming
that tumors in eight breast cancer patients significantly shrank in
size because the patients consumed shark cartilage. The FTC later
found that claim and other studies cited by Body Systems as lacking
``credible scientific evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein recommended that people use government Internet web
sites that provide a so-called gateway with links to reputable
health and medical web sites operated by universities, medical
clinics and organizations like the American Heart Association.
Operators of gateway web sites, such as the FTC, decide which links
to allow on their web site and thus can control the type of
information people can access.
</P>
<P>
   ``Separating what's good on the Internet from the bad or the
ugly isn't easy,'' said Mary Jo Deering, director of health
communication at the Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   The Health and Human Services Department operates a gateway web
site with links to more than 5,000 reliable sites containing health
and medical information, according to Deering.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet address of the HHS site is www.healthfinder.gov.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC says consumers can also access reliable health
information through the FTC's Internet web site (www.ftc.gov). That
address will link consumers to such web sites as those operated by
the American Cancer Society, the Mayo Clinic and the National
Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the FTC surveyed 800 Internet web sites that contained
questionable promotions for products or services purporting to help
cure, treat or prevent cancer, heart disease, AIDS, diabetes,
arthritis and multiple sclerosis. The agency then e-mailed each web
site operator warning them that their claims must be backed up by
scientific information and that disseminating false or
unsubstantiated claims would violate federal law.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the web sites have either been taken down or
the site operators have removed the unproven claims.
</P>
<P>
   The four companies charged by the FTC are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Arthritis Pain Care Center of Arlington, Texas, for claiming
that a product called CMO, which contains a fatty acid, was
effective in treating arthritis. CMO was also advertised as a
treatment for cancer, multiple sclerosis and high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Body Systems Technology, Inc. of Casselberry, Fla., for
promoting shark cartilage capsules and other products as effective
treatments for cancer, HIV, AIDS and arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Magnetic Therapeutic Technologies, Inc. of Irving, Texas, for
marketing magnetic devices as an effective treatment for a variety
of medical problems and diseases including cancer and high blood
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pain Stops Here! of Baiting Hallow, N.Y., for also marketing
magnetic devices as an effective treatment for various medical
conditions including liver disease and arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   In all four cases the companies agreed to stop promoting
products using the unproven health claims. Body Systems Technology
was required to make refunds to customers who previously purchased
the shark cartilage capsules.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
