<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL WOULD LET SOME VETERANS GET MEDICARE TREATMENT AT VA
CENTERS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Senate panel agreed Thursday to allow veterans to
receive Medicare coverage at eight Department of Veterans Affairs
facilities beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, which passed the Senate Finance Committee with
one dissenting vote, about 4 million veterans nationwide would be
eligible for Medicare coverage in VA facilities in selected
demonstration areas. They are those who are eligible for Medicare,
but who don't receive VA care now because they do not have a
service-connected disability or have incomes above certain limits.
</P>
<P>
   The secretaries of the Departments of Veterans Affairs and
Health and Human Services would select the demonstration sites.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining access to quality health care for our veterans is of
tremendous importance,'' said Sen. William Roth, R-Del., the
committee chairman. ``This (bill) substantially improves veterans'
access to the VA health system.''
</P>
<P>
   The only dissent came from Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., who said he
agreed with the intent of the bill, but opposed the mechanism for
paying for the services.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would reduce Medicare's coverage of hospitals' bad
debts for care of Medicare patients from 55 percent to 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt by Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., to alter the financing
mechanism was defeated on a 9-11 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said he hoped to vote for the bill on final Senate passage
if a different way could be found to pay for the $50 million-a-year
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also contained a provision to extend for one year,
until 2001, the law that allows military retirees _ those who did
not serve in combat but retired from the armed services _ to obtain
Medicare coverage in VA facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
