<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-24 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAISSANCE FOR A QUIRKY DESIGNER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jean Royere has never been a household name, until
now. This French decorator, furniture and lighting designer, who
lived from 1902 to 1981, was a great success in his day. But he was
nearly forgotten after death.
</P>
<P>
   A profoundly modest man, he never sought fame, and he never
thought his designs were immortal. ``Why would you want to
resuscitate works that belong to the past?'' he once asked an
interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   But that is exactly what is happening. His whimsical furniture
and lighting designs from the 1940s and 50s _ roly-poly Polar Bear
sofa, goat-fur-covered chairs and coffee tables with spider legs _
are suddenly in great demand.
</P>
<P>
   Royere is back. On May 11 at Christie's in London, a pair of
upholstered arm chairs that he designed in the early 50s went for
$137,000.
</P>
<P>
   Through July 30 Galerie de Beyrie in SoHo, is presenting a show
of several works from an apartment interior Royere designed in 1950
on the French Riviera. ``To find a whole apartment is a dream,''
said Stephane de Beyrie. The furniture includes beds with
wave-shaped, white-lacquered headboards; a tufted pink couch
nicknamed the Bordello sofa, and a nine-foot-long mahogany
sideboard with white brass birdlike decorations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A piece like this sideboard is really serious, but the brasses
aren't,'' said his wife, Catherine de Beyrie. ``They make you
laugh.'`
</P>
<P>
   A strikingly modern metal sofa commissioned for the apartment's
veranda predates by years a similar-looking chair by Eero Saarinen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of fashion, Royere came after Jean Prouve and
Charlotte Perriand,'' Mrs. de Beyrie said. ``Now he is just as
popular, and not just in New York, also in Beverly Hills and Palm
Beach. The movie industry loves Royere.''
</P>
<P>
   Joann DeLorenzo of the DeLorenzo gallery concurred. ``Our
clients are Royere crazy,'' she said. ``Royere is becoming the new
Prouve. But he was much more sophisticated than Prouve.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris the Galerie Jacques Lacoste recently sold two-thirds of
its current Royere show the day it opened (it is on view through
July 2), even though prices ranged from a $15,000 Egg armchair of
1951 to a $100,000 Polar Bear couch and chair set in bright purple
from 1946. Lacoste said most of his buyers at the show have been
French.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French were late, but they are finally getting it,'' he
said. ``What makes Royere different is that he never applied
decoration. The materials are the decoration.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 7 the Museum of Decorative Arts in Paris is mounting a
Royere exhibition. ``There is so much interest in French 1940s
design now,'' said Bruce Newman of Newel Art Galleries in
Manhattan. ``I've been buying Royere for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean Royere came from a distinguished French family and became a
banker after studying the classics at Cambridge. In 1931, at age
29, he quit banking to become an interior designer. ``I always had
a flair for decorating,'' he recalled in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   He apprenticed with Pierre Gouffe, a furniture maker in Paris,
and soon became the artistic designer for Gouffe's contemporary
line. In 1934 Royere won a contest to design a brasserie for the
Hotel Carlton on the Champs-Elysees, and in 1939 he showed his work
at the prestigious Salon de la Societe des Artistes-Decorateurs in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was greatly influenced by Le Corbusier and Charlotte
Perriand,'' Lacoste said. ``But he always chose his own personal
path, somewhere between modernism and traditionalism.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also brave. During World War II he was able to use his
metier to hide some Jews and a few English aviators who had been
shot down in France.
</P>
<P>
   He opened his own company in 1944. After the war, he moved to a
large space on Rue du Faubourg Saint-Honore. ``In this period it's
totally couture furniture,'' said Alan Moss, who has a gallery just
east of SoHo. It is difficult to mix Royere with other furniture
designs, Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   But Christine Grajales of Gallery 1950 in Manhattan disagrees:
``I think it's easy to mix Royere with contemporary art as well as
18th-century furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   Royere loved to travel. He set up an office in Cairo in 1947,
and one of his first commissions was a private apartment for King
Farouk. He opened bureaus in Beirut, Tehran, and Sao Paulo. ( Moss
is selling for $65,000 a red brocade sofa that Royere designed in
Beruit. He also has a pair of Royere chairs covered in fake fur.)
</P>
<P>
   He worked for King Hussein of Jordan, the shah of Iran and the
shah's family. He designed the Senate building in Tehran, the Hotel
Semiramis in Cairo, the Bristol in Beirut, and the Philadelphia
Club in Amman. In 1953 he redesigned the Paris restaurant Fouquet's
on the Champs-Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   At the very end of his life he moved to the United States, where
he died in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Royere was full of opinions that did not endear him to his
competitors. In 1963, for example, he wrote: ``I'm against
furniture. I think we should eliminate it as much as possible.''
The man who set up design companies all over the world declared,
``I am against decoration because everything that is strictly
decorative goes out of fashion too quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was he the member of any camp. ``I'll never be attached to
one school or one theory,'' he said. ``The words `functional,'
`style,' `contemporary,' have no meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-taught, Royere said all he was trying to do was create a
``harmonious spectacle to enchant the eye, rejoice the heart and
elevate the spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
