<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8343 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-$ADV     06-24 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BODIES DISAPPEAR FROM MASS GRAVES, HAMPERING KOSOVO WAR CRIMES
PROSECUTIONS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With WARCRIMES-BOX-$ADV27.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IZBICA, Yugoslavia _ Churned earth has replaced the neat rows of
mounds that told the world a mass grave was here.
</P>
<P>
   A few detached body parts may remain in the clods of dirt, along
with the errant shoe or muddy blanket once used to wrap a body. But
gone are the corpses, the most compelling evidence of a heinous
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were removed to destroy the evidence, to destroy the
facts,'' said Sadik Gjemajli (pronounced, ``Jie-MY-lee), the local
commander of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the Izbica (pronounced, Is-BEE-tsa) massacre, in
which more than 140 people are said to have been executed, is one
of seven in the four-count indictment against Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and four cohorts for war crimes in Kosovo, a
province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Gjemajli and other eyewitnesses said Serb soldiers returned here
three days before the Yugoslav army agreed on June 10 to withdraw
troops and spent two days digging up the graves, removing the
corpses, and then setting afire a wagon load of grave markers and
blankets that had wrapped the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The grave robbers were trying to rob the world of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Kosovo, a province of Serbia, that justice will be
terribly difficult to attain even where there has not been
intentional evidence tampering. There is ample opportunity for
evidence to be ruined simply by the passage of time and intrusion
of innocent people to crime scenes that have no guard, no fences or
even any markings.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, confusing conditions of continued danger, bad
communications and hard travel contribute to delays in
investigations by The Hague tribunal on war crimes in the former
Yugoslavia, the body that indicted Milosevic and four of his
leading cohorts.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic teams began probing through alleged sites in Kosovo
last week, including from Britain's Scotland Yard, America's FBI
and Canada's Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
</P>
<P>
   But they are the second stage of the investigative process,
according to Paul Risley, spokesman for The Hague tribunal, while
thus far the crucial first stage hasn't even been carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each of these cases, we have soldiers secure the sites,''
Risley said, speaking of NATO troops in the KFOR, or Kosovo Force,
taking over the seven sites of alleged atrocities listed in the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a limited window of opportunity for (collecting) the
surface evidence -- tire marks, footprints, bloodstains,'' he said,
emphasizing the need for quick forensic assessments at protected
sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern Kosovo town of Djakovica, the crumbling house
where an estimated 20 women, children and elderly people were
burned alive still sat open last week to the elements and to
intruders. The attack on this modest home on the night of April 1
also is listed in the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor poked through the charred remains of the house,
picking up pieces of human bone with a pair of pliers, just out of
curiosity. One piece was potentially important as evidence that
might help identify a victim -- a piece of jawbone with a tooth
still attached. Other visitors urged him not to disturb the site,
and certainly not to take away any of the gruesome mementos he
inexplicably was hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Less grisly artifacts are popular souvenirs, such as spent
bullet casings that also could be useful to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Nor at mid-week was there any sign of KFOR protecting anything
within miles of Izbica, a village in the central Kosovo region that
was a KLA stronghold and was thoroughly routed by Serb troops. It
is a place reached after winding down rocky dirt roads, where cows
may as easily wander through the remnants of mass graves as through
adjacent grasslands.
</P>
<P>
   With the bodies of dead villagers missing, any evidence left
gains in importance.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the victims clearly have been moving through the
site, if only to replace grave markers bowled over by Serb backhoes
-- despite the fact that the bodies are gone. Tire marks by now
have been largely mixed with the treads of tractors and mushed
under heavy pelts of rain.
</P>
<P>
   The corpses would be the best evidence, holding bullets that
might be identified as Yugoslav military issue and other signs
indicating the manner of death. And of course, the identification
-- and even the numbers -- of the victims now is a matter of
hearsay, based on lists the KLA and villagers compiled before they
buried their friends and loved ones. There also is a video-tape of
some stages of the burials.
</P>
<P>
   The graves first appeared in NATO spy satellite photographs in
early April, and were publicized as evidence of Serb atrocities.
That alone might have been sufficient to provoke efforts to erase
proof of the crime, but then additional publicity drew more
attention to it.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-April Cox Newspapers interviewed villagers who said they
buried the bodies after a Serb massacre, and the video-tape
surfaced later and was shown on CNN news broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Izbica is not the only place Serb forces are reported to have
dug up and removed corpses. Risley said the tribunal has received a
number of such reports, about Yugoslav authorities saying their
forces discovered the mass graves and identified the corpses as
``victims of terrorist attacks'' which the Serb troops then removed
and humanely gave a decent burial in individual, marked graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see this as a kind of very sophisticated effort to
hide the evidence,'' he said. ``That in itself would be a specific
kind of war crime committed by the military units.''
</P>
<P>
   Additional indictments against other aggressors and possibly
more charges against Milosevic are expected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
