<HEADER>
A8358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     06-24 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.) 
 `AMY'S VIEW' WITHOUT ITS STAR 
MAKING THE SHOE FIT 
NOT TYPE-CASTING
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Texas, London) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) (nk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dame Judi Dench, who won a Tony for her leading performance in
``Amy's View,'' returned to England Thursday to tend to the health
of her husband, who was ill.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Boneau, a spokesman for the play, said that Dame Judi
would miss performances at least through the weekend and that the
date of her return was uncertain. Her understudy, Jennifer Harmon,
will perform in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Dame Judi said: ``I am devastated to disappoint
anyone who came to see me in the play, but I must be with my family
at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Boneau said that Dame Judi was told late Wednesday afternoon
that the medical condition of her husband, Michael Williams, had
worsened. Williams, an actor, has been hospitalized with pleurisy,
an inflammation of the lining of the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Judi missed Wednesday evening's performance to board a
flight for London.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 250 of nearly 1,100 ticketholders remained to see the
play on Wednesday night after they were told that Dame Judi would
not appear. One ticketholder said the scene in the lobby of the
Barrymore Theater was chaotic after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Boneau said ticketholders for future performances who want
refunds should either return the tickets to the Barrymore box
office or send them to P.O. Box 998, Times Square Station, New
York, N.Y. 10108.
</P>
<P>
   Making the Shoe Fit
</P>
<P>
   Think you've seen ``Closer''? Think again.
</P>
<P>
   The play, at the Music Box Theater, has had some tweaking in
recent weeks with the departure of the English actress Natasha
Richardson and the arrival of the American actress Polly Draper.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Ms. Draper took over the role of Anna, a beautiful
photographer caught in a savage sexual food chain in modern-day
London. But now Anna is no longer a Brit with a troubled past but
an expatriate American. (The troubled past remains.)
</P>
<P>
   The playwright and director, Patrick Marber, said the identity
shift was made in part to help American audiences identify with the
play, which was one of a flood of British imports in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the play to be accessible to an American audience, as
much about their society as about our society,'' Marber said from
London. The changes, he said, may make the play ``feel a little
less foreign perhaps.''
</P>
<P>
   The nationality switch was made with the addition of a handful
of lines in the play's second scene and the deletion of several
British colloquialisms later in the script. For example, where the
old Anna had said ``Romantic tosh,'' to dismiss a lover's
statement, the new Anna says, ``You're just romanticizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Also altered is the play's ending, which has reverted to the one
seen in an earlier production in London's West End. Previously in
New York, the play ended with Anna alone onstage. Now another
character is left, providing what Marber called a ``more
bittersweet'' ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's correct for the tone of the play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It may also answer some critics who have said the West End
version was more impressive than its New York incarnation.
``Closer'' received mixed reviews, but has returned about 80
percent of its original investment, its producers say. Sales have
slowed since the summer doldrums took hold.
</P>
<P>
   While rewrites are de rigueur in rehearsals and previews,
opening night usually marks the end of substantial work on a play's
text. But Marber said the changes were one of the benefits of being
both playwright and director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I perceive the play as a living text,'' he said. ``And if I'm
the director, I'm at liberty to do whatever I want with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Type-Casting
</P>
<P>
   Forget the fact that Linda Hart has black hair and Bunny
Weinberger is, in the words of her creator, Albert Innaurato, a
``hepatitis blonde.'' Ignore, too, that while Ms. Hart is a petite
120 pounds, Bunny is a good 160.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference between Ms. Hart (the actress) and Ms.
Weinberger (her character) is that while Bunny has a mouth like a
sailor, Ms. Hart says she hasn't said a dirty word in as long as
she can remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my entire life, I have not cursed as much as I do in one
night at Second Stage,'' Ms. Hart said with a laugh. ``My friends
are amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   They aren't the only ones. For the last month, Ms. Hart has been
donning a fat suit and astounding audiences with her portrayal of
the coarsely hysterical Bunny in Second Stage's revival of
Innaurato's ``Gemini.'' The play's producers, who have posted an
official closing for this Sunday, are mulling an extension.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas native, Ms. Hart is the daughter of two evangelical
ministers and has nine other relatives who are preachers. Her first
seven years were spent on the road in a tent revival, and her
family's firm no drink, no smoke, no curse ethos remains part of
her life.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had to think twice before taking on Bunny's bad
self, but that it was a lesson from the pulpit that keyed her into
the character. ``You don't go up there without knowing you're going
to go for it,'' she said. ``It's a real leap of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Fiona Shaw, Tony Randall and Isabella Rosellini are confirmed
as readers in the world premiere of ``The Days Before'' by Robert
Wilson, playing July 7-10 at Lincoln Center Festival '99. The piece
is based on an Umberto Eco novel about a sailor, a shipwreck and
some subsequent surrealism.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marian Seldes, a recent Tony nominee, will appear in the Irish
Repertory's production of ``Dear Liar,'' a comedy based on the love
letters of George Bernard Shaw. It opens July 22.
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Buckley is heading the cast of a September production of
``Camino Real'' at Hartford Stage. Michael Wilson directs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Valarie Pettiford, nominated for a Tony for her performance in
``Fosse,'' will leave that show in mid-July to play opposite Chita
Rivera in the London production of ``Chicago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
