<HEADER>
A8365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-24 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compliments Of a Friend &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At his death on Feb. 1 at 91, the philanthropist Paul Mellon
left the National Gallery of Art in Washington the largest gift in
its history: $75 million in cash plus more than 100 pictures, many
of them masterpieces by artists like van Gogh, Manet, Cezanne,
Monet and Renoir.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not all Mellon intended to leave the museum. This
week it announced that it was receiving 73 additional works from
Mellon, which were not listed in his will because they were not
part of his estate. These were left to the gallery through a trust.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the latest gift is Degas' ``Scene From Steeplechase:
The Fallen Jockey'' (1866), which was shown at the National Gallery
in 1998 as part of its exhibition ``Degas at the Races.'' It joins
18 others by Degas in the gallery's collection, of which 5 were
given by Mellon. The gift also includes 37 Degas sculptures: 29 in
wax, 4 in plaster or mixed materials and 4 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Degas holdings are now extraordinary,'' said Earl A.
Powell III, director of the gallery. ``With this latest gift we
have 49 Degas waxes.'' The gallery plans to exhibit them together
in a Degas room in the West Building, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other works in this latest bequest is a Stubbs
painting, ``White Poodle in a Punt,'' (circa 1780), which had been
promised to the gallery at the time of its 50th anniversary in
1991. There are also five oils on board or panel by John Frederick
Peto, the late-19th-century American artist.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mellon was a longtime trustee of the gallery; his father,
the financier Andrew W. Mellon, helped found the institution. Paul
Mellon had previously left the gallery more than 900 works,
including many Impressionist and Post-Impressionist paintings.
</P>
<P>
   His father paid for the Gallery's West Building; Paul Mellon and
his sister, Ailsa Mellon Bruce, gave nearly two-thirds of the funds
to build the museum's East Building, which was designed by I.M. Pei
and completed in 1978 for about $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mellon had told the gallery about most of the works he
planned to donate, but the final transfer of property occurred only
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no real surprises,'' Powell said. ``But this is
confirmation of a remarkable gift by a remarkable collector and
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The gallery is planning a Mellon memorial exhibition in the
fall. ``It will include a selection of things, highlights,'' Powell
said. ``We can't show everything. If we did, we'd strip the
gallery.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Rush for Rauschenberg &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The competition is getting stiffer among leading museums in the
United States for great works by the country's leading artists _
names like Ellsworth Kelly, Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns _
as both the Museum of Modern Art in Manhattan and the San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art make serious efforts to strengthen their
permanent collections.
</P>
<P>
   Take the work of Rauschenberg. This week the Modern in New York
announced that it had acquired four important works by him, three
from the 1950s and one from 1998. A year ago the San Francisco
museum bought a group of 14 works from his own collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``While these acquisitions may crisscross, they are not
related,'' said Glenn D. Lowry, director of the New York museum.
``I'm one who believes competition is healthy. It's good for the
artists, the public and for museums.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowry said this recent acquisition represented ``the pendulum
swinging from the early art of the century to the late part.'' He
added, ``We want to concentrate on post-1950, giving the collection
the same depth coming out of this century as going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now Rauschenberg's work was not so well represented in the
Modern's collections. But the addition of ``Factum II'' (1957) is
considered a coup for the museum. Although not as sculptural as
many of his combine series, the work is composed of found images,
scraps of writing and other paper or cloth elements, all on a
canvas that he has also painted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Factum II'' belonged to Hubert Neumann, an investor whose
20th-century art collection was begun by his father, Morton G.
Neumann, who made his fortune in the mail-order business.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Neumann has been selling portions of his collection
recently; in November Sotheby's sold a group of works that included
a 1909 Picasso. For years auction houses, collectors and museums
have been trying to buy ``Factum II,'' considered one of the stars
of the Neumann collection. While the Modern declined to discuss the
price it paid, experts estimated it in the region of $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Factum II'' was conceived as a direct companion to ``Factum
I,'' which belongs to the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles
but is being lent to the Modern from Thursday through Oct. 5. The
two will be displayed together for the first time in decades, when
the Modern hangs its new '50s Rauschenbergs in its third-floor
painting and sculpture galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The other two '50s Rauschenbergs acquired by the Modern are
``Untitled (Asheville Citizen)'' from 1952, a two-panel painting
bought directly from the artist, and ``Untitled'' (1953), a
sculpture sold to the museum by Pace Wildenstein. ``Asheville
Citizen'' is one of the most austere Rauschenberg works, dominated
by a black matte surface.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture, one of a series, is a cubic box, seven and
one-eighth inches on each side, fashioned from thick used boards,
which contains a slightly smaller cube of transparent silk,
stretched on a frame.
</P>
<P>
   The more recent Rauschenberg is ``Bookworms Harvest'' (1998), a
promised gift from Jerry I. Speyer, a trustee of the Modern. It
incorporates computer-manipulated photographs on paper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fragment of the Renaissance &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There has been a very last-minute addition to ``The Treasury of
St. Francis of Assisi,'' an exhibition of Italian Renaissance art
at the Metropolitan Museum of Art that opened on March 16 and runs
through Sunday: the fragment of a small angel's head by Giotto.
</P>
<P>
   The fragment was one of the largest of the 50,000 recovered
after the 1997 earthquake collapsed two sections of vaulting in the
upper church of the Basilica of San Francesco in Assisi. It was
also one of the few to show a recognizable figure.
</P>
<P>
   But it took months of negotiating to get it to New York,
officials at the Met said, because the Italian cultural ministry
was reluctant to send a fragment so frail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smallness of the fragment highlights the complexity of the
restoration, given that it is one of the largest pieces,'' said Pia
Palladino, a research associate in the Met's Robert Lehman
Collection. ``The colors are remarkably fresh and brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   The fragment will be displayed next to the Franciscan tree, the
tapestry commissioned by Pope Sixtus IV. It will travel to the
Palace of the Legion of Honor in San Francisco for the show's
opening there on July 15.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
