<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     06-24 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIRECTOR WHO LEFT HIS HEART IS ON MADISON AVENUE 
MAKING A CRITIC PAY 
WITH OFFENSE FOR ALL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Vt. )   (nk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's Hollywood's version of a man-bites-dog story: Kinka
Usher, a highly successful television commercial director, has just
finished his first feature film, ``Mystery Men,'' which Universal
will release on July 30, but he doesn't really want to direct
movies.
</P>
<P>
   How's that?
</P>
<P>
   The world of commercials and music videos is Hollywood's farm
system for movie directors. People ranging from Ridley Scott
(``Blade Runner'' and ``Thelma and Louise'') to Michael Bay
(``Armageddon'') earned their spurs making commercials, and the
studios regularly comb the ranks of commercial directors looking
for the next Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   For the studios it is a source of relatively cheap talent with a
presumably fresh perspective, while some critics have complained
that it has filled theaters with movies that are fast-paced,
visually arresting and hollow. But for the aspiring directors, the
offers are like professional catnip. Everyone, it seems, wants to
be in motion pictures, and the directors are generally happy to
dump their running-shoe and soft-drink sponsors for a shot at
Hollywood glamour.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone except Usher, who is, by his own admission, a devotee
of the television commercial process. ``I'm an adman,'' he said.
``I like the freedom and the autonomy.''
</P>
<P>
   His clients have included Pepsi, Nike and Miller Lite, and last
year he won the Directors Guild's commercial director of the year
award. He said he believes that many ad people who have succumbed
to the lure of films are ruining Hollywood with movies that are
often soulless amusements.
</P>
<P>
   Given his visibility in the industry, he said, he has been
approached several times over the years about directing movies but
always said no. And he was unenthusiastic when he was first sent
the script for ``Mystery Men,'' a superhero sendup, roughly in the
same genre as ``Men in Black,'' based on a comic book series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was boring,'' Usher said. ``However, the premise
was great. It was about a bunch of lousy superheroes who believe
they are just a break away from being real superheroes.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked out a deal with Universal and assembled a striking
ensemble cast, including Ben Stiller, Janeane Garofalo, William H.
Macy, Geoffrey Rush, Greg Kinnear, Paul Reubens (a k a Pee-wee
Herman) and Hank Azaria. The well-meaning but daffy heroes, who
strive to save Champion City, use weapons like a bowling ball,
forks and a shovel. One of the heroes can make himself invisible,
but only when no one is looking.
</P>
<P>
   Usher said he played it straight, emphasizing the sincere desire
of these misfits to do good, to give them some depth. ``Most of the
movies made by commercial directors are heavy on visuals and thin
on content,'' Usher said. ``I don't want to be part of that. I was
very cognizant of showing that I know how to work with character.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience, Usher said, was a delight, and he is finishing
the sound dubbing on the movie. And yet, he said, it has only made
him eager to return to his core business. He added that he was not
looking for another film, but conceded that he might be tempted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Usher said, ``the more you say no in this town,
the more people want to work with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Making a Critic Pay
</P>
<P>
   Call it an actor's ultimate revenge: William H. Macy, the actor
and sometime writer, has helped write a script about a movie critic
who turns out to be a philandering, larcenous murderer and, best of
all, gets caught and suffers for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, revenge was not my aim,'' Macy, vacationing in Vermont,
said of the film, ``A Travesty.'' He wrote the script with Steven
Schachter for the TNT cable network. But he was quick to add,
``It's a morality tale about paying up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Travesty,'' whose title may be changed later, is based on a
Donald Westlake novel, and it is scheduled to be shown in
September. The movie is sort of a post-modern thriller with a wry,
ironic movie critic, Terry Thorpe, played by Macy, sinking ever
deeper into a chain of crimes from which he cannot extricate
himself. For the character, it is all just an interplay of scenes
from movies. He sees life through the lens of scripts and considers
his actions in terms of famous films. The whole idea of reality
gets fuzzy in this nervous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let him Hitchcock me and I'll Spielberg him one right back,''
Macy said, quoting one of Thorpe's lines as he is being pursued by
the police.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is dark, filled with black humor and violence. But,
Macy insisted, it is not the sort of violence, often seen in
movies, in which characters get hit on the back of the head with a
shovel and then go about their lives as if nothing had happened.
Macy said he was a critic of gratuitous violence in film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The violence we show has consequences,'' Macy said. ``I
believe you tell the story you want, and it can have violence in
it. But tell the truth about violence, let there be a day of
reckoning.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie also stars Adam Arkin, James Cromwell and Felicity
Huffman (Macy's real-life wife).
</P>
<P>
   The film is indirectly about the way art has insinuated itself
into reality, about how people model their behavior on what they
have seen in movies. Thorpe, in addition to referring constantly to
movie action, also turns to the camera from time to time and speaks
right to the audience as he explains how he sees his increasingly
hopeless situation.
</P>
<P>
   That technique, Macy added, helps make Thorpe a likable rogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bad and he's gotta pay, but he's a classic antihero,''
Macy said. ``I just think the hero of the '90s will be the
antihero, despicable people but we kind of dig them. There's
something in the Zeitgeist that makes that kind of character our
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With Offense for All
</P>
<P>
   Lona Williams has given everyone something to hate in her movie
``Drop Dead Gorgeous,'' which, she said, makes her happy.
</P>
<P>
   In this black sendup, she ruthlessly skewers, not necessarily in
this order, small towns, beauty pageants, anorexia, shopping malls,
trailer parks, Lutherans, Asian-Americans, gun clubs. Well, you get
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   While humor in movies is in general getting blacker, ``Drop Dead
Gorgeous,'' which New Line Cinema will release on July 23, may be
among the darkest comedies of the season. The movie, on which Ms.
Williams was the writer as well as the executive producer, is in
the form of a fake documentary, a so-called mockumentary, about a
beauty pageant in a small Minnesota town in which everything gets
out of hand. It is about murder, mayhem and taut, insincere smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Told that it offers a bleak vision, Ms. Williams responded with
a hearty ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that it makes people uncomfortable,'' said Ms.
Williams, a former writer on ``The Drew Carey Show,'' making her
first feature film. ``I use humor to deal with these subjects. I
didn't set out to do something black. I just thought it was
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Williams, the movie was a matter of writing what she
knows. The movie takes place in the fictitious town of Mount Rose,
a none too subtle reference to her hometown, Rosemount, in rural
Minnesota. And she was a contestant in the Miss Teen Princess
America Pageant, the contest that is the source of the bedlam
depicted in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won in the town, which was odd, and I competed in the state
pageant, which was even more odd,'' Ms. Williams said. ``I went to
the nationals in Mobile, Ala., and it was one of the freakiest
experiences of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Kirstie Ally and Ellen Barkin play mirror opposites
caught up in an unusual interaction. Both have daughters competing
for the beauty title, a major event in the town.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ally, a former pageant winner herself, is wealthy and
domineering and will not even entertain the idea that her daughter,
played by Denise Richards, might not win. Ms. Barkin styles hair
from her mobile home in a trailer park and pushes her daughter,
played by Kirsten Dunst, to compete. She hopes a victory will help
her daughter escape the town where she does the makeup on corpses
in a funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ally plots to blow up Ms. Barkin in her trailer but succeeds
only in giving her serious burns and fusing her ever-present beer
can to her hand. Another character meets an untimely end atop a
papier-mache swan in the local parade.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a note of grace, it is the relationship Ms. Dunst
has with her screen mother, which is open and supportive. ``After
all, what would a black pit be without a bottom,'' Ms. Williams
said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
