<HEADER>
A8377 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-SPONSOR-NY     06-24 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-SPONSOR-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN BEHIND SPONSORSHIP HAS OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LOWELL COHN   
 Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ This is the story of NASCAR'S phenomenal
success, and the potential losses that are a byproduct of that
success.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Sunday's Save Mart/Kragen 350. The owner of
Save Mart Supermarkets is Bob Piccinini. He's the guy from Modesto
who's heading up an investment group that hopes to buy the Oakland
A's.
</P>
<P>
   Piccinini is devoted to the annual race at Sears Point Raceway
and this is the eighth year the race bears his company's name. But
Piccinini also wonders how long he can go on sponsoring it. He's
currently in the second year of a three-year contract with Sears
Point and is debating with himself whether to continue his
association with the event.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, if you can call it a problem, is the immense
popularity of the race, which has become the most-attended
single-day event in California. When Save Mart first sponsored the
event in 1992, it cost Piccinini $200,000. Sure, 200 grand may seem
like a chunk of change, but it was well within the supermarket's
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. Total sponsorship this year is more than $1.2
million. (It's $1.5 million at the Daytona 500.) A grocery man,
even a smart one like Piccinini, would have to sell a lot of
broccoli, toilet paper and Hostess Cupcakes to make up the
difference. To help him out, Sears Point brought in Kragen last
year to split the bill. Even with Kragen sharing the burden, Save
Mart's cost on Sunday will be $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Piccinini is not in the business of losing money or squandering
money or throwing away money. It occurs to him that Winston Cup
gives Save Mart an incredible amount of publicity, of marquee
value, all over the country. He likes that. He notices that the
employees at his stores, most of them situated in California's
Central Valley, are excited about the association with NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks before the event, he promotes the race at Save
Marts. He understands that a grocery clerk in, say, Coalinga, not
always the most high-profile job, could get turned on by the
connection with something big and nationwide and glamorous, could
go weak in the knees when a Winston Cup driver shows up at the
store, which happens from time to time. In Piccinini's words,
``This is good for esprits de corps.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also studied the demographics, and understands that every
year the percentage of fans from the Central Valley who attend the
race has grown. This is good for business, and Piccinini is a good
businessman. But he understands something else. Someone watching
Sunday's race on ESPN in a bar in Utica, N.Y., might get excited by
the idea of Save Mart. This theoretical race lover might run out of
the bar with the firm desire to purchase nonfat yogurt at the
nearest Save Mart.
</P>
<P>
   But this theoretical Utica race lover couldn't get his yogurt at
a Save Mart because Save Mart is strictly a Northern California
business. Piccinini wonders about the effectiveness of paying
constantly rising sponsorship fees to reach folks who can't buy his
hot peppers, onions and barbecue sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Kragen, by the way, is in a similar pickle, to use a
grocery-store term. Kragen markets its oil filters, coolant,
batteries, etc. to the western United States, and currently enjoys
no benefit with our theoretical race-car lover in Utica. The
Winston Cup circuit, including the Save Mart/Kragen 350, used to be
a local phenomenon. But now it's national, and local sponsors like
Save Mart are caught in the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Piccinini has not locked himself in his room and turned off the
lights, wallowing in grief because of the changes in NASCAR. He
hasn't become the Hamlet of Winston Cup. He's a happy guy who loves
the event, and a lot of that has to do with his pedigree in racing.
</P>
<P>
   His dad used to own a Ford dealership. In the 1957 model year,
the Piccininis ran a stock car in NASCAR and U.S. Auto Club events,
about 20 in all on the West Coast. Piccinini, who was a teen-ager,
was seduced by the excitement of seeing the family car out there.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 1989. Winston Cup was coming to Sears Point, and Banquet
Frozen Foods was the sponsor. The race was the Banquet 300 in those
days. It so happened that Piccinini sold Banquet foods in his
stores. And one of his perks as a Banquet vendor was a free seat at
the race and, one presumes, all the Banquet foods he could eat.
Piccinini liked the whole package, especially the race which
brought him back to his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   He would go to Sears Point every year and party at the Banquet
hospitality tent. Banquet once let him be the official race
starter. Another time he was the grand marshal.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was the winter of 1991, and Steve Page, current
president of Sears Point, had just signed on. The morning after he
took the job, Banquet dropped out. Page immediately got on the horn
to Piccinini, and he also called Lucky Stores. He talked and he
negotiated, and he made a deal with Save Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Lucky phoned. They wanted to be the sponsor.
Sorry. Too late.
</P>
<P>
   You get the point, right? The race was two days away from being
called The Lucky 350. Are we talking supermarket wars here, or
what?
</P>
<P>
   Save Mart sponsored the race for one year. Piccinini liked it,
so much that he picked up an option for an additional two years.
After that, he negotiated a series of three-year contracts and the
current deal expires after the race in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoys hosting his own hospitality tent at Turn 11. And he
enjoys zooming around the grounds on his golf cart greeting people
and feeling like the host of the event. And, let's face it, he
enjoys meeting the drivers. But he doesn't push that part of it.
``If I walk through the pits? I have my own pass and I see a driver
and he's just standing there, and if I catch his eye, I might go
over and talk. I try not to be intrusive. It's their work time.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Piccinini. He's still a working man, and he understands
other working men, and he's reluctant to bother them. He also
understands business. He and Sears Point are currently in
negotiations for another three-year deal, to begin 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Will he continue sponsoring the race?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's yet to be determined,'' Piccinini says.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
