<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 25, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Sluggish winds from the northwest at 20,000 feet will direct a
soggy disturbance from Kentucky toward the Carolinas. The envelope
of clouds associated with low pressure on the west slopes of the
central Appalachians will extend from central New York to the
Carolina coast and westward along the Ohio River.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt on the southern flank of the low
along a warm front in the central Carolinas. A few sections may
receive over 2 inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   A few thunderstorms will form ahead of a weakening cold front in
the St. Lawrence Valley. Very warm and humid conditions over New
England will lead to several potent storms in the higher
elevations. The Northeast Coast will notice hazy sunshine and sea
breezes, most sections will stay dry.
</P>
<P>
   The merging of a couple of clusters of thunderstorms over
eastern Oklahoma, Texas and Arkansas will lead to a dull, damp day
in the western Gulf region. The most potent storms should occur
Friday morning near the eastern part of the Red River Valley. The
western and central Plains will turn hotter.
</P>
<P>
   A push of sultry air into the Dakotas and Minnesota ahead of a
jet stream disturbance will trigger several large thunderstorms.
The storms will weaken as they move toward the Middle West.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, moist onshore winds will promote showers west of the
Cascades. The interior Northwest will be bright, but not as warm.
Except for a few thunderstorms in New Mexico, the Southwest will be
sunny and hotter. The California coast will notice some fog. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Maine Storms
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of strong thunderstorms descended on Aroostook County,
Maine, late Wednesday. Oddly, the storms were moving from north to
south. Potent thunderstorms are associated with very warm and humid
air, which can reach Maine in the early summer.
</P>
<P>
   The sultry weather is usually transported into New England on
balmy breezes from the south. Indeed, surface winds were light
southerly, but thunderstorms are tall clouds that are directed by
winds above 10,000 feet. The clockwise flow around a stationary
high at 20,000 feet over Quebec sent the Maine storms southward. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
