<HEADER>
A8399 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     06-24 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEXUS AND OLIVE TREE SYMBOLIC OF TODAY'S STRUGGLE TO LIVE IN TWO
WORLDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember how easy it was for business during the Cold War?
</P>
<P>
   Not that it was pleasant living with a nuclear arsenal pointed
at us all the time, but, back then, the American and the Soviet
governments were more or less in charge of most everything.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was divided, compartmentalized, homogeneous and except
for a handful of creative engineers in a space race, the business
world was relatively static, bureaucratic, heavy, slow.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Berlin wall came down in 1989. And everything changed.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to globalization.
</P>
<P>
   A new book, artfully written by New York Times foreign affairs
columnist Thomas Friedman, provides an insightful look at the
chaotic world in which we now live, a world in which global
business is the dominant mover and shaker.
</P>
<P>
   His observations on topics from Japanese factories to the
Wailing Wall in Jerusalem are skillfully chronicled in ``The Lexus
and the Olive Tree,'' (Farrar, Straus, Giroux, 394 pages, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   ``The slow, stable, chopped-up Cold War system that had
dominated international affairs since 1945 has been firmly replaced
by a new, very greased, interconnected system called
globalization,'' Friedman writes. ``We are all one river.''
</P>
<P>
   And that river was created from cheaper telecommunications
because of microchips, satellites, fiber optics and the Internet,
Friedman asserts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what also makes this era of globalization unique is not
just the fact that these technologies are making it possible for
traditional nation-states and corporations to reach farther,
faster, cheaper and deeper around the world than ever before,'' he
writes. ``It is the fact that it is allowing individuals to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman aptly describes this new era of business with words
like integration and speed. Its symbol is the World Wide Web, as
opposed to the Cold War's Wall. Its defining economist is Intel's
Andy Grove. Instead of Einstein's theory of relativity, the new era
is based on Moore's law that the computing power of silicon chips
will double every 18 to 24 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Cold War, the most frequently asked question was: `How
big is your missile?' In globalization, the most frequently asked
question is: `How fast is your modem?'''
</P>
<P>
   Along with this modern world, however, are powerful ties to the
past, hence the title of the book.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman tells us of one trip he made to Japan where he visited
a Lexus car factory at which 310 robots and 66 people were making
cars. The people were there there primarily for quality control.
</P>
<P>
   On his way back, speeding along in Japan's bullet train, he
noticed a newspaper item about further unrest among the
Palestinians in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck me then that the Lexus and the olive tree were
actually pretty good symbols of this post-Cold War era: half the
world seemed to be emerging from the Cold War intent on building a
better Lexus, dedicated to modernizing, streamlining and
privatizing their economies in order to thrive in the system of
globalization,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And half of the world _ sometimes half the same country,
sometimes half the same person _ was still caught up in the fight
over who owns which olive tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Olive trees are symbolic not just of property rights, but of
religion, community, nationalism and home, Friedman writes. The
Lexus, meanwhile, represents the human drive for improvement,
prosperity and modernization.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman sees globalization also as Americanization of the world
and devotes many chapters to the influence of American culture on
the rest of the world. He also has a section on the backlash
developing against this new economic/political system.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the book is full of fascinating pictures of how once
far-reaching parts of the world are being woven together, as well
as insightful commentary on what it all means.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther King Jr. On Leadership: Inspiration &AMP; Wisdom For
Challenging Times''
</P>
<P>
   By Donald T. Phillips
</P>
<P>
   Warner Books, $22
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being an interesting history of African-Americans
in this country from pre-Revolutionary times on, plus a biography
of Martin Luther King Jr., this book also provides insight into
King's ability to rally much of the country around him. Guiding the
movement, winning over people and ensuring the future are
leadership ideas that emerged in King's speeches and writings from
which any leader could learn.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Human Resources Kit for Dummies''
</P>
<P>
   By Max Messmer
</P>
<P>
   IDG Books, $24.99
</P>
<P>
   Author Max Messmer is also chief executive of one of the world's
largest specialized staffing companies. In this easy-to-absorb
book, he explores the complex world of corporate human relations,
covering such topics as creating an employee-friendly work
environment, creating benefits packages, measuring employee
performance and setting up wage structures. The book also lists
numerous resources, such as the top 10 Web sites and books with
which human resource personnel should be familiar. A CD-ROM
includes more than 30 documents, such as policies, forms, contracts
and laws, as well as Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``How to be a Star at Work''
</P>
<P>
   By Robert E. Kelley
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $12
</P>
<P>
   Author and Carnegie Mellon University teacher Robert Kelley
estimates that between 10 percent and 15 percent of all workers
outperform their peers by a wide margin. This qualifies them as
``stars.'' Kelley outlines nine strategies on how to become a
member of the star club, with a separate chapter providing
additional hints for women and minorities. Now out in paperback,
this book was originally published in 1998 and became a bestseller.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
