   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING _ A look at who Mindspring might be discussing
partnerships with and why. The candidates include
telecommunications companies like BellSouth who would provide the
DSL connections Mindsprings needs, computer hardware companies like
Dell who need to expand their revenue streams and content providers
like Microsoft who would give Mindspring a portal on the Internet.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   w/MINDSPRING-NEXT _ MindSpring Enterprises Inc., the No. 4 U.S.
Internet service provider, said it's in discussions about possible
``business combinations.'' Analysts speculate the potential
partners range from BellSouth.net to Dell Computers. In the
Internet climate today, Wall Street rewards risk takers so it's not
enough for Mindspring to be merely profitable. It has to
demonstrate what its next move is going to be. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-FINANCIAL _ A look at the companies financials since
its IPO a year and half ago. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-PROFILE _ A profile of Mindspring and how it grew up
from a funky local internet service provider to one of the largest
ISPs in the nation. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BELGIUM _ BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Checking on the latest
developments of the Coca-Cola crisis in Belgium. Talking with
retailers who are anticipating the return of Coke products within
days. Also checking the status of the beverage ban in Luxembourg
and the Netherlands. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   w/COKE-FRANCE _ PARIS _ Now that the French government has
lifted its ban on Coca-Cola products from a plant in Dunkirk,
Coca-Cola Enterprises is making preparations to get that plant,
along with plants in Belgium, up and running again. The decision
comes after a food-safety investigation concluded that beverages
from the plant were safe. Still unanswered is the status of a probe
into the suggestion that rat poison could be the source of
contamination on drink containers produced at the plant. Also
checking to see whether Coca-Cola is planning the same media blitz
as the one in Brussels. Also checking the status of the EU
investigation. (Holmes, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-CCE _ ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc. expects to take
a $60 million charge in the second-quarter because of its soft
drink recall in Europe. The Atlanta-based bottler, the Coke
system's largest, said it expects the recall will hurt sales, cash
operating profit and earnings per share in the countries where its
products were pulled after becoming contaminated. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Package will move in (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   UTLITIES-DEREG _ WASHINGTON _ Walter Higgins, chairman and CEO
of AGL Resources, is meeting with utility executives from around
the country who may be interested in adopting the Atlanta Gas Light
model for their own deregulation plan. The group may also include
merger and acquisition candidates for the gas company's parect.
(Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ELCTRICITY-TRADING _ Southern Co. is off to a smooth start with
its electricity trading business this summer and executives do not
forsee a repeat of last year, when a sudden heat wave sent
wholesale prices soaring to crisis levels. (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   CEOS-MEETING _ ATLANTA _ More than 400 CEOs and other top
executives from small and large companies are in Atlanta for a
couple of days to talk business and discuss the innovations that
affect the way they do business. What they heard is that survival
of the fittest rules today's competitive business world, and a
company without a ``digital business plan'' may be in peril.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CHECKFREE _ CheckFree Thursday withdrew its secondary public
offering of 3.8 million shares to remove any question that there
might have been anything more than coincidence behind the timing of
the offering Wednesday and the rival bank annoucement Thursday.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   KIDDIE-SUITES _ ATLANTA _Next month, Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts will
unveil its new Holiday Inn Family Suites Resort in Orlando. The
800-room hotel offers a variety of unsual suite arrangments
including one for kids with a playroom , bunkbeds etc.; one for the
exercise buff with a recumbent bike, weights and incline bench; and
a cinema suites that comes with a 60-inch tv screen and
surround-sound speakers. We take a look at the project, others
planned and the market potential. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
