<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW IN HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Demise of Divx clears the field &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However the collapse last week of Divx, the alternative digital
video disk, affects the spread of DVD, it at least relieves
confusion for consumers and perhaps increases the inclination of
studios and other distributors to commit more films to a new medium
that several months ago seemed to be getting tangled in a format
war.
</P>
<P>
   Divx, developed by Circuit City, the consumer-electronics chain,
was predicated on a marketing concept that made it incompatible
with standard DVD and required a different player. (Basically, the
Divx disk was designed to play once, whereupon, among other
options, the user could throw it away rather than return it to the
video store.)
</P>
<P>
   By late winter Divx was accounting for about 10 percent of the
overall DVD market. Nevertheless, Circuit City, citing high costs,
difficulty in getting movies for the format and distribution
problems, announced on June 16 that it was discontinuing the line.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of standard DVD stopped short of performing back flips,
but the Divx withdrawal disarms a situation that in its first
stages had disquieting intimations of video's VHS-Beta conflict of
the early 80s. Now the consumer no longer has to choose one form of
DVD over another, and that pleases the movie makers and
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be more aggressive in changing all our VHS titles into
the DVD format,'' said Amir Malin, president of Artisan
Entertainment, an independent film and video company with a library
of 6,600 films, among them titles like ``Dirty Dancing,''
``Reservoir Dogs'' and ``Terminator 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Malin, a strong supporter of the standard disk, said the removal
of Divx positions DVD to replace videotape and the VCR eventually.
That remains to be seen, of course, but with DVD now in more than
two million households, one can at least agree with his observation
that it has overcome another format that had the misfortune of
competing against the VCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now,'' Malin said, ``there was always the issue of
whether DVD was going to be the technology of the future or another
format like laser disk: high-end use and limited availability.'' &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &UR;  &LR; Truffaut for the Home  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday a two-month Francois Truffaut retrospective ended at
Film Forum in Manhattan, but videophiles should be aware that six
of the films are available in restored editions, on both tape and
DVD, from Fox Lorber, the distributor that provided the movies for
the Film Forum series. They are ``The 400 Blows,'' ``Shoot the
Piano Player,'' ``The Last Metro,'' ``Confidentially Yours,''
``Love on the Run'' and ``Two English Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 24 seven more Truffauts will appear on tape and disk:
``Jules and Jim,'' ``The Soft Skin,'' ``The Woman Next Door,''
``Bed and Board,'' ``Stolen Kisses'' and two short films on one
cassette, ``Les Mistons'' and ``Antoine and Colette.''
</P>
<P>
   All the videos have been made from new prints and have newly
translated subtitles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
