<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUSTICE-LEWIS25-COX     06-24 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTICE-LEWIS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKERS PROPOSE RENAMING JUSTICE HEADQUARTERS FOR RFK
 &HT;    180&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Legislation to rename the main headquarters of the
Justice Department building for Robert F. Kennedy was proposed
Thursday by Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., and other House members.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Kennedy his ``shining inspiration,'' Lewis said he was
delighted to co-sponsor the bill with Reps. Joe Scarborough,
R-Fla., Tim Roemer, D-Ind., and Jack Quinn, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of no more fitting and appropriate way to honor
this great man's legacy'' than by renaming the building where he
served as attorney general, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bill has a very good chance of passing. My
colleagues have talked with (House Speaker Dennis Hastert) and he
is very supportive,'' Lewis said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he initiated the bill several years ago, but it
failed in committee. He said he thinks it will pass this time
because of its bipartisan sponsorship and because of a different
climate in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have had the opportunity to name several buildings
after Republican leaders,'' he said, pointing to those named after
former presidents Ronald Reagan and George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I had known Robert F. Kennedy for many years'' and worked with
him on his 1968 presidential campaign, Lewis said. ``I was with him
when he informed us of the death of Martin Luther King and had
spoken to him before he was killed in Los Angeles'' the night
Kennedy won California's Democratic primary that year.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said Kennedy epitomized the very best the country had to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a champion of the poor, the voiceless and the
forgotten. He possessed a passion for justice and fought hard for
what is right,'' he said. Lewis, a noted civil rights activist,
said Kennedy was ``at home'' with people of color, helping to give
a ``sense of hope in a time of hopefulness.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
