<HEADER>
A8415 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV01-     06-24 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV01-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARIJUANA EASES THEIR PAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, July 1)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, it would have been more efficient to grow his own,
but that didn't work, and so the young man's sister went out on the
street and bought marijuana for him.
</P>
<P>
   His mother said, ``Any one of us would have done it for him,''
but it was his pregnant sister who insisted on helping him out,
``putting herself, her husband and her baby at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man lived with AIDS for four years before he died.
Without question his family believes that marijuana prolonged his
life.
</P>
<P>
   His mother explains, ``They use the term wasting because that's
exactly what happens to a body. The person with AIDS can literally
starve to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Marijuana made the life-giving difference. ``If he smoked, he
could eat. If he didn't smoke, he couldn't eat.'' I became a
believer after watching the relief it brought to a friend with
cancer. One moment she was lying in a fetal position, huddled
against the pain and the fear, so weak she asked me to light her
marijuana pipe and hold it her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   She inhaled and lay back against the pillows, whispering ``thank
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later she was sitting up and waiting to tell another
story. She was clearheaded. Her face had relaxed into a smile. She
said the thing she had to fight the most was fear and anxiety and
marijuana put them to rest for a while.
</P>
<P>
   If you're the mother of a child with AIDS or a friend of someone
with terminal cancer there's no question about sick people having
access to something that brings them such relief.
</P>
<P>
   It's so simple. It's relatively cheap. And it works. To withhold
it is inhumane. To make it difficult to get is cruel.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in California two and a half years ago made it legal for
people to grow and use the otherwise illegal drug for medicinal
purposes with a doctor's permission.
</P>
<P>
   The ``growing'' part has been a problem. Not everyone can grow
their own and when others grow it for them, or worse, for several
people, law enforcement steps in. The problem is attaching money to
marijuana. Police rip out plants, arrest growers, arrest users,
close down clubs that provide marijuana for many sick people.
</P>
<P>
   There's a provision in the law that allows a person' caregiver
to grow for a patient but that person is far less protected than
the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes small groups of patients will get together and share
the expense of a garden, growing it together in a cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Last week AIDS patients in Sonona County, Calif., went before
the Board of Supervisors asking them to stop police raids on
medicinal marijuana gardens. A recent raid in Petaluma had dried up
supplies in San Francisco, said one man who begged the board not
only to stop police from raiding marijuana patches but to open up
the county to growing marijuana in a big way for people anywhere
with a medicinal need.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney said he doesn't want to see Sonoma County
become the marijuana garden for San Francisco or anywhere else.
That's understandable. Being known as Wine Country is one thing;
Dope Country is another.
</P>
<P>
   But being known as compassionate and doing whatever it takes to
ease people's pain would seem to be a worthy goal of any entity.
</P>
<P>
   The title of the 1996 law was the Compassionate Use Act but
compassion has had to wait on the details of how medicinal
marijuana is grown and distributed. In the meantime people often go
without. They don't eat; they stay coiled in a ball of pain.
</P>
<P>
   There are stories of people who grow their own, thereby
complying with the current law, but are hassled because their
doctor's note _ required under the law _ is considered too vague.
There are stories of doctors who freak when a police officer calls
to verify if they really recommended marijuana for a person's
condition. There are still people who think that a young man
smoking marijuana so he can keep his dinner down mocks efforts to
dissuade young people from imbibing.
</P>
<P>
   I loved seeing the smile return on my friend's face when the hot
pain subsided, but I don't think that picture would tempt any
teen-ager to get stoned.
</P>
<P>
   Things could be improving. California's attorney general is
expected to soon put his blessing on a task force's recommendations
to involve public health departments instead of police departments
in enforcing who gets medicinal marijuana and how.
</P>
<P>
   The mother took her son on a trip out of the country before he
died as one of her last gifts to him and they took along plenty of
his special medicine. ``You wouldn't believe what was in that
suitcase,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And was she worried the whole time that they'd all be busted?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course. But this was my son. I said I'd worry about that
another day.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
