u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAYER-LION-BOS &LR;      06-24 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYER-LION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYER TO SET UP US BIOINFORMATICS FACILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bayer AG, one of the world's largest pharmaceutical companies,
confirmed Thursday that it agreed to invest up to $100 million in a
Cambridge, Mass. facility to develop a state-of-the-art technology
known as bioinformatics.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer, based in Leverkusen, Germany, said it would make the
investment over a five-year period through a research collaborative
with a German biotechnology company, Lion Bioscience AG.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Bayer and Lion will set up a facility in
Cambridge, to be called Lion Bioscience Research Inc. About 20
researchers will develop computer hardware and software in an
effort to aid Bayer in its race to identify genes and gene
sequences that can be used to develop targets for new drugs. The
technology known as bioinformatics.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion of the facility would depend on its success, Bayer
said. But Bayer said the agreement gives the company the right to
take over the facility when the agreement ends.
</P>
<P>
   Lion Bioscience Research will be Bayer's second project in
Cambridge involving drug development tied to an ongoing global
effort among scientists to identify the 100,000 or so genes in
human beings. At the center of this effort is the Whitehead-MIT
Center for Genome Research.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Bayer committed $465 million to Cambridge-based
Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. to develop targets for drugs to
treat cancer, liver fibrosis and cardiovascular disease and other
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cambridge is the birthplace of genomics and bioinformatics,''
Wolfgang Hartwig, head of international pharmaceutical research,
said Thursday. With Millennium nearby, ``it makes sense'' to locate
Lion Bioscience Research in Cambridge so that researchers can share
information, Hartwig said.
</P>
<P>
   In a newly emrging field of drug development, pharmaceutical
and biotech companies hope to use these newly identified genes as
the basis for identifying genes linked to diseases and deriving
drugs based on those genes. Bioinformatics involves using computers
to sort through mounds and mounds of data to find targets. In
addition to bioinformatics technology, Bayer and Lion agreed to
develop diagnostics for diseases identification through information
about genes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
