<HEADLINE>
WANT TO GET OUT OF TOWN TO RING IN THE NEW YEAR? IT'S NOT TOO LATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're like me, you made a New Year's resolution last year
not to put off making plans for New Year's this year. And if you're
like me, you probably still haven't even thought about making those
plans.
</P>
<P>
   But don't panic. You're not alone. A lot of folks have yet to
make plans to party like it's 1999. And despite all the dire
predictions made by compulsive types who booked their tickets to
the Y2K bash two years ago, there are still plenty of options
available for the New Year's procrastinator.
</P>
<P>
   Not that those options are cheap. There's a reason your
more-organized acquaintances plan well in advance _ to save a
little cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're probably going to pay 30 to 40 percent more than normal
for a New Year's package this year,'' said Christie Crawford, a
travel agent with Carlson Wagonlit Travel in Fort Worth. ``There
are no discounts on millennium travel. All the cruise lines are
taking nonrefundable deposits. Even if you're deceased by the time
your vacation comes up, you're not getting your money back.''
</P>
<P>
   The new millennium, of course, begins with the arrival of 2001.
But try telling travel agents, resort managers or big-city
officials around the world planning their megacelebrations for when
the clock strikes midnight on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a once-in-a-lifetime thing, and it should be worth the
extra money,'' said Barbara Ford, president of Country Day Travel.
``If you don't see it that way, you better start planning your
party at home.''
</P>
<P>
   So what should we definitely rule out as a New Year's
destination?
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents agree that Paris, London and New York are going to
be suffering from millennium madness, with rooms almost impossible
to find. Don't plan a Disney vacation, either. It has been reported
that all 25,000 rooms at the 27 Disney hotels are booked. Even if
you find a room on the outskirts, theme parks have a maximum
occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hawaii is going to be astronomical for New Year's, and Vegas
could sell out,'' Crawford added.
</P>
<P>
   But although she agreed that a good portion of the planet is
booked for the holiday, there are still plenty of packages
available to make it a memorable New Year's. Some travelers have
canceled early plans, so spaces are becoming available.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens if you go some place really cool and Y2K
strikes, wiping out the world's computer network and causing mass
hysteria? Crawford sounded unperturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows exactly how it will affect things,'' she said.
``But a lot of travelers aren't that concerned. I think the
airlines are taking so many precautions and gearing up, and most
people are booking to Europe well into the new year.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are feeling adventurous, here are some suggestions for
places to celebrate New Year's with a few hundred thousand close
friends.
</P>
<P>
   I WANNA BE A PART OF IT ...: You have never done New Year's in
New York, but you've virtually been there watching ``Dick Clark's
New Year's Rockin' Eve'' TV show for the past 15 years. Well, don't
get your hopes up about actually seeing the former ``American
Bandstand'' host up close if you venture to Times Square this year,
not without the aid of telescope, at least. You'll be lucky to spot
the specially built Waterford crystal ball drop at 11:59 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 500,000 is expected, which is how many people
officials say they believe they can cram into Times Square. People
will begin arriving the morning of Dec. 31, 1999, and party well
past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're willing to camp out for a good space, you would
probably be better off watching it the old-fashioned way ... on TV.
But if your heart's set on the Big Apple, don't miss the
spectacular fireworks display over the Hudson River, with good
viewing spots along the Hudson shoreline or across the river in
Hoboken, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said you can still get a good air fare (about $240), if
you book now and are ``very'' flexible with travel times. But
expect to pay no less than $300 a night for a hotel room unless you
can score a good hotel package.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the popular hotels are booked, a few venues
opened their reservation books only this month.
</P>
<P>
   A few semiaffordable options we found: the Broadway Bed &AMP;
Breakfast ( (212) 997-9200) at 264 W. 46th St., a short walk from
Times Square. It has a six-night package, starting on Dec. 26, with
double rooms from $250-$410 a night. The Roger Williams (31st and
Madison ( (212) 448-7000), a boutique-style hotel, is offering
double rooms at $499.95 after Dec. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Among New York-area hotels you wouldn't normally consider, a few
options remain. The Parsippany, N.J., Days Inn (3159 U.S. Route 46
( (800) 329-7466) is less than 45 minutes from the Big Apple by
bus. The train station is a short drive away. A regular room rate
of $135 for Dec. 31., $89 for Jan. 1, gets you a double, including
continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
