<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON'S ROLLER COASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is doing just
fine with New York voters at the moment, thank you. It may not mean
the moon in the long run but it's better than her two buddies are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton gets no respect for his role in NATO's
military victory in Kosovo and Vice President Al Gore suffers from
reviews panning the uninspired launch of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Hillary Clinton's pending run for the Senate is
looking good.
</P>
<P>
   Her chief Republican nemesis, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
has been having a bad time lately. He looked petty when he withdrew
permission to let the new magazine Talk use a Brooklyn Navy Yard
site after discovering that the first lady might be on the cover of
its first issue. And he hasn't overcome guilt by association with
scandals about failing public schools and cop brutality.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide New York Daily News poll published Sunday showed
Hillary Clinton would beat Giuliani by 8 points were the Senate
election held now. It isn't being held now, of course, but being
ahead at any time is more promising than being behind.
</P>
<P>
   The new survey also reported that 73 percent of those questioned
did not see any conflict between simultaneously running for the
Senate and carrying out White House duties. In addition, 69 percent
said the fact she does not yet have a home in the state was no big
deal and would not keep them from voting for her.
</P>
<P>
   If those majority views hold, there's no great momentum in the
two main issues Republicans have raised against her thus far.
</P>
<P>
   The real political blockbuster, however, is that only 17 percent
of those surveyed said her legal troubles stemming from Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's manic pursuit make them less likely to vote
for her. A whopping 68 percent said Starr's attacks would have no
effect on their vote.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that if Starr calls her to testify again before a
jury about the stale Whitewater scandal and trashes her in his
final report, his actions may well backfire. They are simply too
blatantly political to be taken at face value.
</P>
<P>
   Starr threw every bit of personal nastiness he could document,
exaggerate or imply at the president but could not bring him down.
To try the same stunt on the president's wife in the middle of her
Senate campaign would make reasonable people puke.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgeable former prosecutors are convinced that if Starr had
any hope of convicting Hillary Clinton of a single one of the
charges he has investigated, he would indict her. He has not done
so because he does not have sufficient evidence to prove what his
partisan bias drives him to suspect. Another high-profile loss in
court would bury his professional reputation, which is already
lower than an underground parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr is widely believed to be so bitter and frustrated he
will issue a final report that paints the first lady not simply as
evasive but downright evil. He can say anything he wants in that
report, even though he acknowledged in a June 13 Fox television
interview that he had been politically ``unwise'' in the first
place to probe the White House travel office firings, the mystery
of Hillary Clinton's missing legal files or the president's
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has a perfect opportunity to leave his post when the
independent counsel law expires June 30, but he insists he will not
give up until his job is done. He is reportedly hanging on in order
to be sure the first lady is called as a witness in the Aug. 9
trial of her former Arkansas law partner, Webster Hubbell, who is
accused of concealing work they both did in a land deal that went
sour.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton has already testified before a grand jury that
she does not recall the key details of their legal work 14 years
ago. She is unlikely to have anything more to say. But the first
lady's foes hope the drama of another court appearance will remind
everyone of the scandals that have trailed the Clintons throughout
their White House years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it may not have the political impact they anticipate. The
New York Daily News poll suggests she could emerge reinforced as a
sympathetic figure, not only the Wronged Wife but the Valiant
Victim standing up to a wicked persecutor. There's certainly a good
chance of that.
</P>
<P>
   It seems most likely, however, that all that ugly legal business
will have very little impact.
</P>
<P>
   All politics is local, even in sophisticated New York state and
even with the first lady as a central figure. As she moves about
the state, she will connect on a personal basis that will
overshadow whatever ancient baggage she carries from Washington or
Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Most voters already know a great deal about Hillary Clinton, her
strengths and weaknesses. They have heard the stories and accepted
or rejected them.
</P>
<P>
   This is a public woman. Not even her inner thoughts are much of
a mystery. And I suspect that more voters have made up their minds
about whether they like her than are currently willing to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   It is her job now to appeal to the mushy middle less likely to
be concerned about her past than her plans for helping New York
state.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
