<HEADER>
A8425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE'S-SANFRAN-ART-5     06-24 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE'S-SANFRAN-ART-5TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE ROAD: EVEN IN FOG, THAT CITY ON A HILL DAZZLES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (Eds: Last two takes contain information about visiting San
Francisco.) 
 (nk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ More than any other, this is the city that
Americans fantasize about. No one leaves his heart in Salt Lake
City. No one calls Baltimore Baghdad by the Bay, as Herb Caen, the
city's six-day-a-week poet laureate for more than 50 years, called
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   For me San Francisco has always been a paradox: a thoroughly
worldly place, yet remote and somehow detached from world capitals
like New York and London; a little indifferent to the mundane
business of trading shares and casting votes; in other words, a bit
smug. (The good Mr. Caen, who before his death in 1997 did for San
Francisco what Samuel Pepys did for London, once quoted a local
citizen who, upon reaching heaven, reported back to friends here
that ``it's nice, but it isn't San Francisco.'')
</P>
<P>
   Yet San Francisco looms large in the imagination of everyone who
knows it, myself most decidedly included. Like Paris, Venice and
Hong Kong, it is a city without peer, a city of myth and magic.
</P>
<P>
   I can't think of the place without thinking about sourdough
bread and Alice Waters, who revolutionized American cooking; Joe
DiMaggio, the fisherman's son, and A.P. Giannini, another
Italian-American, who built the world's largest bank; Turk Murphy
and San Francisco jazz; Alcatraz and San Quentin; the hairpin bends
on Lombard Street and the sudden watery vistas.
</P>
<P>
   The weather I could do without. Fog veils the city so often that
a local radio station has adopted the call letters KFOG. Fog
bleaches the color from the perky paint jobs on the Victorian frame
houses that march up and down the city's distinctive hills. When
the fog finally lifts, when everything sparkles in the sun, it is
an occasion for celebration. Yes! A five-bridge day, with all the
spans from the Golden Gate almost down to Palo Alto clearly
visible.
</P>
<P>
   But fog has its uses. Several years ago, crossing the Bay Bridge
from Oakland to San Francisco at dawn, my wife, Betsey, and I
watched bug-eyed as the Transamerica pyramid and the city's other
towers rose bronzed and beautiful from their cloudy bed. Nothing,
in truth, not fog or rain or fire or quake, ever quite masks San
Francisco's beauty or quenches its exuberance. Its setting rivals
Rio's. Its charm compares with Boston's. Its joie de vivre nearly
matches that of New Orleans; it lacks only the last Latin measure
of heedlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Characters from Nob Hill and Telegraph Hill, Chinatown and the
Tenderloin have walked straight into the pages of Bret Harte, Jack
London, Frank Norris, Dashiell Hammett, Tom Wolfe (who found the
essential San Francisco experience in ``roaring up hills or down
hills, sliding on and off the cable-car tracks'') and John
Steinbeck, who loved San Francisco, as he wrote, when ``the
afternoon sun painted her white and gold, rising on her hills like
a noble city in a happy dream.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is on something of a cultural tear lately,
cementing its position as the West Coast's cultural capital,
although Los Angeles is by no means the pothole full of philistines
many San Franciscans see when (if) they take the plane south.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Opera is the nation's second largest, after
the Met, and it has the largest budget of any West Coast arts
organization.
</P>
<P>
   An old autocrat named Kurt Herbert Adler built the opera's
reputation, bringing singers of the caliber of Tebaldi, Schwarzkopf
and Fassbaender to the United States for the first time. Lotfi
Mansouri, the current general director, has gradually lengthened
the season, and during the 10 months from next September through
July 2000, 11 different operas will be performed.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the opera is in the midst of four cycles of
Wagner's immense ``Ring of the Nibelung'' at the War Memorial Opera
House (the place where the United Nations Charter was signed on
June 26, 1945, by representatives of 50 nations). The 15-year-old
production was reshaped by Andrei Serban, the Romanian-born stage
director, who had never seen a complete ``Ring'' until his own.
Jane Eaglen, Deborah Voigt and James Morris are among the gods,
demigods and giants onstage. The final cycle ends on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, the city's orchestra is just concluding an
ambitious Stravinsky festival, exploring the master's work in
Russia, Paris and Los Angeles, where its music director, Michael
Tilson Thomas, then in his 20s, knew him at the end of his long,
hugely productive career. Successor to luminaries like Monteux and
Krips, the lithe, lean Maestro Thomas is one of only three
American-born music directors of major American orchestras, along
with Leonard Slatkin in Washington and Andrew Litton in Dallas.
M.T.T., as the local papers call him, is one of San Francisco's
genuine celebrities these days, a Pied Piper leading the young back
into the concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   If the critics grumble once in a while, the public has responded
warmly to his programs in his nearly four years here, and even a
Vienna audience would have been impressed, I think, by his powerful
but never bombastic Bruckner Ninth in Davies Symphony Hall early
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   As ever under Thomas, there will be a lot of American and modern
music next season, plus a tasty rarity, Elgar's ``Dream of
Gerontius.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Ballet is in the hands of an old New York
favorite, Helgi Tomasson, who has transformed a regional troupe
into a fine classical company since taking over as artistic
director in 1985. I won't prattle on here; it's enough to quote
Anna Kisselgoff of The New York Times, no easy mark, who proclaimed
the company ``world class'' after watching it last year.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies perform in San Francisco's Civic Center,
whose most prominent building is the newly, grandly restored City
Hall, with an enormous, echoing rotunda. (Don't miss it, even if
this stuff usually leaves you cold as a musher's nose in
midwinter.) Nearby stands the new public library, and by 2002, now
that a knot of litigation has seemingly been untied, the Asian Art
Museum is scheduled to open in the old library building, adapted by
Gae Aulenti, the Italian wizard who turned a Paris train station
into the Musee d'Orsay.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons are odious, if entertaining, but I would argue that
the Asian museum is San Francisco's best. Built around the
collection of Avery Brundage, it contains Japanese, Korean and
Indian works, but the Chinese material is supreme. When the Chinese
leader Jiang Zemin visited the museum, he was dazzled by a gilded
image of the Buddha from A.D. 338. I'll bet you will be, too.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the Asian museum shares a quake-weakened,
obtrusively buttressed building in Golden Gate Park with the M.H.
de Young Museum, which has raised $65 million for a new home, to be
designed by Herzog &AMP; de Meuron, architects of the new Bankside
building for the Tate Gallery in London. The strength of its
collection lies in American painting, from George Caleb Bingham's
``Boatmen on the Missouri'' through Frederic E. Church's ``Rainy
Season in the Tropics'' to Grant Wood's ``Dinner for Threshers,'' a
plain-faced group portrait that outshines the over-familiar
``American Gothic.'' Many of the choicest pictures came in a 1978
gift of 175 items from Mr. and Mrs. John D. Rockefeller III.
</P>
<P>
   The de Young's sister museum, the California Palace of the
Legion of Honor _ together they are known as the Fine Arts Museums
of San Francisco _ was rebuilt and reinvented several years ago,
reopening in November 1995. It occupies a picturesque site in
Lincoln Park, overlooking the great rust-red pylons of the Golden
Gate Bridge, an iconic structure that embodies this city's spirit
the way the Statue of Liberty embodies New York's.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by the flamboyant Alma de Bretteville Spreckels, whose
rich, indulgent husband, Adolph, inherited a sugar fortune, the
museum's collection centers on European art, especially French art.
The ``Old Woman'' by Georges de la Tour, a Monet ``Waterlilies,'' a
powerful off-center portrait by Degas, ``The Impresario,'' and some
70 Rodins are in the collection.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another arts district has sprung into being in recent years
in the redeveloped area south of Market Street, known as SoMa. At
its core is the Yerba Buena Center, designed for the many
small-scale arts organizations in the Bay Area. It includes
galleries by the Japanese architect Fumihiko Maki, sheathed in
corrugated aluminum siding but still somehow delicate, and a
theater designed by James Stewart Polshek, dark and angular on the
inside but more like a jaunty piece of de Stijl sculpture outside.
</P>
<P>
   Around the perimeter are a children's entertainment and
education center, complete with carousel; the brand-new $85 million
Metreon, Sony's urban version of a Disney theme park, with an
``environment'' by Maurice Sendak, which is expected to attract
five million visitors a year; the Ansel Adams Center for
Photography, and the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art. Still to
come are a new Jewish Museum designed by Daniel Libeskind, who did
a similar project in Berlin, and a new building for the Mexican
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The big cheese, of course, is the San Francisco Museum of Modern
Art, which is housed in Mario Botta's four-year-old landmark
building, whose truncated cylindrical tower lets the light flood
in. A bequest from Elise S. Haas, of the Levi Strauss family,
brought it several pictures once owned by Sarah Stein, the
sister-in-law of Gertrude, including a breathtaking Fauve Matisse,
``Femme au Chapeau.'' Phyllis C. Wattis, the San Francisco cultural
world's Brooke Astor, gave $20 million in 1998 to buy 13
Rauschenbergs and other works.
</P>
<P>
   Donald G. Fisher, the founder of the Gap clothing chain, paid
$1.9 million in May for an Alexander Calder wood-and-wire sculpture
called ``Constellation.'' It appears to be headed for the modern
art museum, too. But because of the need to rotate pictures, Bay
Area artists like Richard Diebenkorn and Sam Francis are sometimes
underrepresented on the museum's walls.
</P>
<P>
   The Yerba Buena area is the epicenter of modern architecture in
the city. Elsewhere, the pickings are slimmer, despite Frank Lloyd
Wright's building on Maiden Lane, now the Circle Gallery, which was
a precursor of the Guggenheim in its use of a spiral ramp, and his
Buck Rogers-style civic center in Marin County.
</P>
<P>
   Architecture buffs will want to see something of Bernard
Maybeck, the individualist who foreshadowed the California Arts and
Crafts movement. (The templelike Palace of Fine Arts, left over
from the 1915 Panama-Pacific Exposition, and the First Church of
Christ, Scientist, in Berkeley are his masterworks.) A
glacier-white Richard Neutra house, cantilevered over a cliff with
a picture-postcard view of the Bay Bridge, is at 56 Calhoun
Terrace. And the excess of San Francisco's Gilded Age is
wonderfully displayed in Alma Spreckels' Beaux-Arts mansion on
Pacific Heights, with 26 bathrooms. It now belongs to Danielle
Steel, the romance novelist.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hemmed in by bay and ocean at the tip of a narrow peninsula, San
Francisco is relatively small. It ranks only 13th on the list of
American cities, with a population estimated at 735,000 in 1996;
Los Angeles, San Diego and San Jose are all bigger. But the
metropolitan area surrounding the bay, with 6.6 million people, is
the nation's fifth largest.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco was built on three stout economic legs: silver
from the Comstock Lode, the transcontinental railroads and the
port, once dominated by Harry Bridges, the militant leader of the
longshoremen.
</P>
<P>
   George Hearst struck it rich in the mines; his son, William
Randolph Hearst, struck it richer in yellow journalism, which he
helped to invent; the younger Hearst's granddaughter Patty was
kidnapped in 1974 by the Symbionese Liberation Army, but survived.
The circulation of Hearst's flagship, The San Francisco Examiner,
whose logo proclaims it ``Monarch of the Dailies,'' has shriveled,
but it may yet swallow its larger rival, The San Francisco
Chronicle, whose owning families could give lessons to the
Hatfields and the McCoys.
</P>
<P>
   W.R. Hearst may have been satirized by Orson Welles in ``Citizen
Kane,'' but the men who built the Central Pacific were reviled in
their own time as profiteers. They were called the Big Four: Leland
Stanford, Collis P. Huntington, Charles Crocker and Mark Hopkins.
According to one contemporary account, they made a $63 million
profit on a $121 million investment.
</P>
<P>
   It once seemed that San Francisco got by on beauty, charm and
the spending of strangers. But that has changed, and radically.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley, just to the south, is the land of memory chips,
software and freshly coined millionaires, which attracts a third of
all the venture capital invested in the country. Five of the best
20 places to earn a living in the United States, a survey by Forbes
magazine recently found, are within an hour and a half's drive of
downtown San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder people want to live here. No wonder the median price
for a single-family house in the Bay Area has risen 14.2 percent in
the last year to $334,590. (In Atherton, a tony suburb, it hit $2.5
million.)
</P>
<P>
   But off in a corner, with no share in this orgasm of prosperity,
are the city's omnipresent homeless, begging for money at freeway
off-ramps by day, rolling out their sleeping bags by night in the
doorways of expensive stores and other buildings, hoping the police
won't notice.
</P>
<P>
   If the police do move in, some of the homeless people whip out
their cellular phones and call television stations to come film the
action.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1883, Robert Louis Stevenson remarked on the city's
cosmopolitan character, detecting ``the airs of Marseilles and
Peking'' in its streets. Writing in the same vein 50 years later,
another traveler, John Gunther, called San Francisco ``brilliant,
polyglot and sophisticated,'' and said it ``will tolerate
everything, including the intolerable.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has an established social order and lots of Old
Money, even a mini-Wall Street. It has a fondness for clubs _ the
Olympic; the Bohemian, with its encampments on the Russian River
north of town, and the Pacific Union, whose brown sandstone
clubhouse atop Nob Hill once belonged to the silver millionaire
James Flood. It is bracketed by two universities of world stature _
the University of California at Berkeley, east of the bay, and
Stanford University at Palo Alto, an hour south of the city.
</P>
<P>
   But this has always been a city that embraces rule-breakers.
From its beginnings as an R &AMP; R stop for Gold Rush pioneers through
the wide-open era of Barbary Coast saloons to the heyday of North
Beach topless bars, featuring the silicone-boosted charms of Carol
Doda, San Francisco has been a good-time town, ready to live and
let live.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of its tolerance, the city has always had more than
its share of characters, notably Joshua Norton, who proclaimed
himself Emperor of the United States in 1859 (and advanced the
obviously loony idea of a bridge connecting San Francisco and
Oakland). I saw one of his spiritual descendants this spring, a
portly fellow with full beard and flowing hair, dressed in overalls
and railroad engineer's cap, ambling along, blowing soap bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   Countercultures have flourished here since World War II. In the
1950s, Columbus Avenue gave birth to the Beat Generation and its
bards Jack Kerouac and Allen Ginsberg. In the 1960s came the
hippies of Haight-Ashbury, preaching Flower Power, dreaming
multicolored dreams and packing Bill Graham's rock concerts, and
the student rebels of Berkeley, led by Mario Savio. In the 1970s,
Huey Newton, from Oakland, made the Black Panthers a militant voice
for the dispossessed of the nation's ghettos.
</P>
<P>
   Gay men and lesbians were given an honored place in San
Francisco when they were still swept under the carpet elsewhere. It
was perhaps inevitable that the American AIDS epidemic hit first
and hardest here, but horrifyingly unexpected when the gay activist
Harvey Milk, whose election as a supervisor in 1977 had thrilled
gay San Franciscans, was assassinated in 1978 along with the city's
mayor, George R. Moscone.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mayor is Willie Brown, a black boulevardier who started
life as a sharecropper's son, a man with the charm of Cary Grant,
the audacity of a high-wire artist and lots of political smarts.
Willie, as they say here, never bothering to specify his last name,
``is a piece of work.'' Some people bridle at his Italian suits,
flashy cars and pretty girlfriends, but few will bet against him
when he stands for re-election this fall. Many nights, he attends a
half-dozen political functions before meeting a friend for a late
dinner, and then at midnight he stands on the street outside the
restaurant, greeting and teasing a few of the tourists who throng
to his city.
</P>
<P>
   His most reliable supporters are San Francisco's Chinese.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting San Francisco:
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   CAMPTON PLACE, 340 Stockton Street, (415) 781-5555. A polished
little gem of a hotel, ideally situated just off Union Square,
marred only by a few overly snug bedrooms. The multinational,
multilingual staff will jump through hoops to make you comfortable.
A half-dozen of San Francisco's best chefs have presided in the
dining room over the last quarter-century. Double room: $260 to
$400.
</P>
<P>
   MANDARIN ORIENTAL, 222 Sansome Street, (415) 885-0999. In the
heart of the Financial District yet close enough to Union Square,
Chinatown and SoMa, this is a spectacular sibling of one of Hong
Kong's finest hotels. It occupies floors 38 to 48 of a skyscraper,
guaranteeing great views. Double room: $415 to $570 weekdays; $255
to $550 weekends.
</P>
<P>
   REX, 562 Sutter Street, (415) 433-4434. Like Paris, San
Francisco is blessed with affordable hotels, and the Rex is among
the most charming. A vaguely clubby lobby with a bar and rooms with
luxury-hotel amenities _ voice mail, dataports, movies _ dispel any
hint of slumming. Double room: $165 to $245.
</P>
<P>
   RITZ-CARLTON, 600 Stockton Street, (415) 296-7465. As ritzy as
they come, this is the city's premier hotel, a worthy successor to
the grandes dames of the past like the St. Francis, the Clift and
the Fairmont. Perched on the side of Nob Hill, it is fairly stuffed
with marble, crystal and brocade, and the bedrooms are luxurious in
size as well as decor. We ate an impeccable Thanksgiving dinner one
year in the pretty restaurant. Double room: $309 to $3,500 for a
suite.
</P>
<P>
   W, 181 Third Street, (415) 777-5300, is a sassy new spot in the
Yerba Buena arts district. An octagonal three-story lobby adjoins a
``living room'' with smart modern furniture. Royal blue and
chocolate brown are the colors of choice upstairs and down. The
restaurant is called XYZ, natch. Double room: $239 to $319.
 &UR;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHEZ PANISSE, 1517 Shattuck Avenue, Berkeley, (510) 548-5525.
What to say? Alice Waters only gets better, buying superlative
ingredients from small farmers and handling them with reverence.
Every night, a six-course set menu, balanced and seasonal, is
served in an old Craftsman house half hidden by trees. In the final
week of May this year, the menus emphasized fava beans, morels,
king salmon and asparagus. The atmosphere is a little worshipful
for me, but who cares when everything looks and tastes so
beautiful?
</P>
<P>
   MASA, 648 Bush Street, (415) 989-7154. For decades now, Masa has
been the town's top French restaurant, a subdued, formal place with
subtle, complex cooking. Julian Serrano, who made it what it is,
has followed the yellow brick road to Las Vegas, but Michael Bauer,
The San Francisco Chronicle's exigent food critic, detects no
decline in standards.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETO, 5655 College Avenue, Oakland, (510) 547-5356. Close
your eyes, and Paul Bertolli will whisk you to the Umbrian
countryside. He marries peasant heartiness with city-slicker
lightness: homemade noodles with delicate sand dabs, gossamer
gnocchi with sage and brown butter, moist roast pork bathed in rich
pan juices, with fleshy white beans on the side. One of our
companions called the dense chocolate tartuffo ``heroin on a
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   POSTRIO, 545 Post Street, (415) 776-7825. This is Wolfgang
Puck's Northern California outpost, a trilevel showplace designed
by the celebrated Pat Kuleto. Puckish pizzas at the bar; more
substantial fare downstairs, notably roasted leg of lamb with
garlic mashed potatoes (aaah) and nicoise olives. Or try the fine
grilled quail. They serve breakfast, too.
</P>
<P>
   RUBICON, 558 Sacramento Street, (415) 434-4100. The room is
airy, the food solidly Californian, the management by Drew
Nieporent watchful. But it is Larry Stone, California's best
sommelier, who pulls in the winos, myself included. Can't find
Grace Family cabernets? He has them (at a price, to be sure), as
well as small-grower Burgundies and many other goodies.
</P>
<P>
   SLANTED DOOR, 584 Valencia Street, (415) 861-8032. You will find
no better Vietnamese food anywhere in the United States (or, I dare
say, in Vietnam). The neighborhood is proletarian (no parking), but
classic dishes like spring rolls and caramelized shrimp are
executed with all the finesse of Alain Ducasse. The spicy squid and
chili green beans aren't bad, either.
</P>
<P>
   TADICH GRILL, 240 California Street, (415) 391-1849. Born with
the Gold Rush, Tadich's turns 150 this year. Fabulously fresh fish,
simply prepared, is the house specialty: sand dabs and petrale
sole, grilled or pan-fried; the tomato-based seafood stew called
cioppino, and peerless Dungeness crab in the shell, in a cocktail
or in a salad. Go for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   TON KIANG, 5821 Geary Boulevard, (415) 387-8273. Think you know
dim sum? Ton Kiang will teach you a thing or two about greaseless
frying, translucent dumpling skins and the use of chives, spring
onions and ginger to point up flavors. This is a favorite of the
chef Barbara Tropp, which speaks volumes, and it earns a tip of my
hat for its smiling, efficient service.
</P>
<P>
   ZUNI CAFE, 1658 Market Street, (415) 552-2522. A friend of mine
calls Judy Rogers' Spartan cafe, with copper bar and roaring
wood-burning oven, ``the soul of San Francisco.'' So it is, in its
delicious simplicity, whether you order a pristine martini and a
plate of oysters at the bar, or a Caesar salad fit for a Caesar or,
if you go late, an unlisted treat: a princely hamburger made from
brined beef ground when you order and served on focaccia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO OPERA, War Memorial Opera House, Van Ness Avenue
and Grove Streets, (415) 864-3330. Wagner's ``Ring of the
Nibelung,'' through July 3. Box office: Mondays through Saturdays,
10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Tickets: $30 to $190. Last production until
September.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO SYMPHONY, Civic Center Complex, Davies Symphony
Hall, 201 Van Ness Avenue, (415) 864-6000. Through tomorrow, ``A
Stravinsky Festival''; sold out. Thursday through Aug. 1, the San
Franciso Symphony presents its Summer in the City pops concert
series, with special guests. The first concert is on Thursday and
next Friday, with Patti LuPone. Tickets: $10-$48. Fall season
begins on Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO BALLET, Civic Center Complex, War Memorial Opera
House, 301 Van Ness Avenue, (415) 865-2000. The ballet tours in the
summer. Fall season begins in December with ``The Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN ART MUSEUM, Tea Garden Drive, off John F. Kennedy Drive,
Golden Gate Park, adjacent to the M.H de Young Memorial Museum,
(415) 379-8801. About 200 pieces of Chinese jade from the Avery
Brundage collection are on view through next summer; ``The Unending
Path: Paintings by Harold Wong From 1957-1997,'' through Oct. 17;
``From the Rainbow's Varied Hue: Textiles of the Southern
Philippines,'' through Aug. 15. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays,
9:30 a.m. to 4:45 p.m. Admission (includes the M.H. de Young
Museum): $7; $5, the elderly; $4, children 12 to 17; free, children
under 12 and members.
</P>
<P>
   M.H. DE YOUNG MUSEUM, 75 Tea Garden Drive, Golden Gate Park,
next to the Asian Art Museum, (415) 863-3330. ``The Art of Craft:
Contemporary Works From the Faxe Collection,'' tomorrow through
Oct. 17. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Admission: See Asian Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA PALACE OF THE LEGION OF HONOR, 34th Avenue and
Clement Street, Lincoln Park, (415) 863-3330. ``Francis Bacon: A
Retrospective Exhibition,'' through Aug. 2; ``The Treasury of Saint
Francis of Assisi,'' July 24 through Nov. 14. Hours: Tuesdays
through Sundays, 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.. Admission: $8; $6, the
elderly, $5, children 12 to 17; under 12 is free.
</P>
<P>
   YERBA BUENA CENTER, 701 Mission Street, at Third Street, (415)
978-2787. Through tomorrow night, ``Sleazoid Express Film
Festival.'' Admission to films and exhibitions: $6; $3, students
and the elderly. Summer highlights include the Summerstage free
lunchtime series in the Gardens, featuring a weeklong dance
festival (July 19-23); San Francisco Butoh Festival (July 31); San
Francisco Mime Troupe (Aug. 1) and noontime concerts.
</P>
<P>
   METREON, Fourth and Mission Streets, (415) 369-6000 or (800)
638-7366. A four-story complex of theaters, shops and restaurants
in the Yerba Buena Gardens area. Hours: Daily, 10 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Admission: $7; $5, children. Web site: www.metreon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ANSEL ADAMS CENTER FOR PHOTOGRAPHY, 250 Fourth Street, (415)
495-7000. ``Innovation/Imagination: 50 Years of Polaroid
Photography,'' through July 18; ``Ansel Adams: Selections From the
Permanent Collection,'' through July 10. Hours: Daily, 11 a.m. to 5
p.m.; to 8 p.m. the first Thursday of each month. Admission: $5;
$3, students; $2, the elderly and children 12 to 17; free for
members and children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM OF MODERN ART, 151 Third Street, (415) 357-4000.
``Carleton Watkins: The Art of Perception,'' through Sept. 7;
``Bill Viola,'' through Sept. 12; ``Robert Rauschenberg,'' through
Sept. 6; ``Daido Moriyama: Stray Dogs,'' through Aug. 3. Hours:
Thursdays through Tuesdays, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.; to 9 p.m. on
Thursdays. Admission: $8; $5, the elderly; $4, students; children
under 12, free. After July 1, $1 more.
</P>
<P>
   PALACE OF FINE ARTS, 3601 Lyon Street, in the Marina District
near the Golden Gate Bridge. Constructed in 1915 for the
Panama-Pacific Exposition. Inside is the Exploratorium, a science
museum where ``Frogs'' is on view through Sept. 12. Hours: Daily,
10 a.m. to 6 p.m.; to 9 p.m. Wednesdays. Museum admission: $9; $7,
students and the elderly; $5, children 6 to 17; $2.50, children 3
to 5; under 3, free. Museum information: (415) 561-0360.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   BY AIR: Continental, (800) 525-0280, has six daily nonstop
flights from Newark to San Francisco Airport, with fares ranging
from a special Fourth of July weekend rate of $262 (reserved seven
days in advance) to the regular seven-day advance round-trip fare
of $1,354 (Saturday stay-over). The 14-day advance reservation fare
is $420 round trip. The last-minute fare is $950 each way. TWA,
(800) 221-2000, has two daily direct flights from Kennedy
International Airport; United Airlines, (800) 538-2929, six from
Newark and eight from Kennedy, and Delta, (800) 221-1212, two from
Kennedy.
</P>
