<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-RANCH _ AUSTIN _ Is McGregor the next Kennebunkport? And is
Gov. George W. Bush taking steps toward creating the next Texas
White House? That's the talk in Central Texas as sources confirm
that Bush is looking to buy a ranch west of Waco. (Reagan, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BEACHES _ WASHINGTON _ Taxpayer-financed efforts to protect
beaches from erosion are costly and ineffective, the author of a
new book claims, leading activists to increasingly turn to
development curbs as a more effective solution. (Dart, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   JUSTICE-LEWIS _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., talks about
a bill he is co-sponsoring to designate the main Justice Department
building the ``Robert F. Kennedy Department of Justice Building.''
(Hill Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   COX-VETERANS _ WASHINGTON _ A Senate panel agreed Thursday to
allow veterans to receive Medicare coverage at eight VA facilities
beginning next year. (Lipman, Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-WWIISOLDIER _ Marteller Pollack, one of a handful of
African-Americans allowed to fight with white soldiers in World War
II, will receive a Bronze Star for heroism Friday - 55 years late -
at a ceremony at Fort McPherson. With photos to be taken Wednesday
at his home and hopefully a shot of him in WWII uniform. The Army
was segregated in World War II, but during the Battle of the Bulge
some black volunteers were assigned to white infantry outfits.
Interview with Mr. Pollack, who lives in East Point. (Hendrick,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   SHIPS-ATLANTA _ ATLANTA _ Relics from the last of five warships
named after the city of Atlanta will be permanently loaned Friday
to the Atlanta History Center in a ceremony one ex-sailor calls
``long overdue.'' 11 inches. Should get color photo of one guy
mentioned in story. (Hendrick, Atlanta Jounal-Constitution). 11.
</P>
<P>
   BIRDS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ On Wednesday morning eight osprey chicks
woke up in their nests in the Maryland wild. Now the chicks are
living in nesting boxes 25 feet off the ground in the Spring Valley
Wildlife Area as part of an effort to bring the bird species back
to the state of Ohio. (Kipp, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CUTS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ In the last year and a half,
cuts in what Medicare pays have squeezed health care providers
across Texas and across the country, causing hospitals to scale
back services. What effect does this have on the elderly? (Park,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TENSIONS _ ZEGRA, Yugoslavia _ The day after after a
shootout that left one Serb civilian dead, U.S. Marines stationed
here as part of the NATO peacekeeping mission face a microcosm the
daily tension and returibution all over war-torn Kosovo in this
little farming village. As Gunnery Sgt. William Post, the Marine
who killed the Serb, said Thursday, ``Better him than me. That's
the way I look at it.'' The Marines here find themselves sandwiched
between grateful ethnic Albanian youth who bring them cherries and
magazines while on duty, and angry ethnic Serbs who despise them
nearly as much as they do the Kosovar Albanians. Developing.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 7 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BELGIUM _ BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Checking on the latest
developments of the Coca-Cola crisis in Belgium. Talking with
retailers who are anticipating the return of Coke products within
days. Also checking the status of the beverage ban in Luxembourg
and the Netherlands. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   w/COKE-FRANCE _ PARIS _ Now that the French government has
lifted its ban on Coca-Cola products from a plant in Dunkirk,
Coca-Cola Enterprises is making preparations to get that plant,
along with plants in Belgium, up and running again. The decision
comes after a food-safety investigation concluded that beverages
from the plant were safe. Still unanswered is the status of a probe
into the suggestion that rat poison could be the source of
contamination on drink containers produced at the plant. Also
checking to see whether Coca-Cola is planning the same media blitz
as the one in Brussels. Also checking the status of the EU
investigation. (Holmes, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-CCE _ ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc. expects to take
a $60 million charge in the second-quarter because of its soft
drink recall in Europe. The Atlanta-based bottler, the Coke
system's largest, said it expects the recall will hurt sales, cash
operating profit and earnings per share in the countries where its
products were pulled after becoming contaminated. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
