<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8436 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-LOLA-SPI &LR;      06-24 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOLA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUN LOLA RUN' POWERS ALONG LIKE A TRUCK ON THE AUTOBAHN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When German director Tom Tykwer was picked for an in-person
tribute in the ``Emerging Masters'' series of the recently
concluded 25th Seattle International Film Festival, few local
moviegoers had ever heard of him, much less seen one of his three
obscure previous films.
</P>
<P>
   But the choice seemed prescient indeed when his fourth film,
``Run Lola Run,'' debuted in the festival and took the audience
(and critics) by storm. It won the Golden Space Needle Award for
best picture, and was also voted the ``most favorite'' film in a
poll of full-series pass holders.
</P>
<P>
   It's about Lola (Franka Potente), a punkish young woman with
fluorescent orange hair, who discovers her low-level gangster
boyfriend (Moritz Bleibtreu) has just left a bag containing 100,000
marks of a big-time gangster's money on the subway.
</P>
<P>
   He calls Lola and asks her to somehow try to come up with that
sum before he's scheduled to meet his gangster boss in 20 minutes.
She's his only hope, and if she can't come through, the gangster
will surely rub him out.
</P>
<P>
   So Lola tears out of her apartment, races through the streets of
the city like a marathon runner _ nearly missing a succession of
cars, baby carriages and bicycles _ and goes to her wealthy banker
father, begging for the money and praying she can get it to the
designated meeting spot in time.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't make it and the worst happens, but, by some curious
twist of fate or whim of the gods, Lola finds herself transported
back to her apartment and given the opportunity to try again _ not
once, but twice, with startingly different results in each stage of
the two re-
</P>
<P>
   races.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you've seen something like this before. It's even becoming
a bit of an overdone idea: the movie (``Blind Chance,'' ``Sliding
Doors,'' ``Twice Upon a Yesterday'') that follows the same
character in a succession of alternate plot lines, and demonstrates
how a minor incident
</P>
<P>
   can have a major ripple effect on a
</P>
<P>
   life.
</P>
<P>
   But the formula has rarely been done as well as it is in this
goofy, audacious, visually stylized omnibus of what-ifs that
operates on its own peculiar logic, and powers along with the force
of a truck on the Autobahn. On a purely visceral level, it's a kind
of unbridled celebration of the exhilaration of speed.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, ``Lola'' incorporates animation, a rock-video
editing style (with some scenes apparently even shot on video), and
flashes of various passing characters' pasts, futures and present
interior monologues. It's a jumble of techniques, but somehow it
all comes together to be a unique storytelling style.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, for a film that is almost all action, it also
showcases a highly charismatic, movie-star performance from
newcomer Potente as the indomitable title character. Beneath that
orange fright wig, there's the cool, haughty, distinctly Teutonic
sexuality of a Marlene Dietrich, and it provides this clever little
movie with an irresistible focus.
</P>
<P>
   Run Lola Run. Directed and written by Tom Tykwer. Cast: Franka
Potente, Moritz Bleibtreu, Herbert Knaup, Armin Rohde. Sony
Pictures Classics. 81 minutes. In German with English subtitles.
Rated R for no obvious reason.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
