</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-BAR-HONORED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GOVERNMENT HONORS GAY SITE AS A HISTORIC PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: RECASTS lede, adds reaction, edits throughout.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   WASHINGTON _ For the first time, the
federal government has recognized a gay and lesbian site, New York
City's Stonewall Inn, as worthy of inclusion in the National
Register of Historic Places.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bar on Christopher Street in Greenwich Village was the scene
of several nights of strident protests and fighting after police
raided it in the early hours of June 28, 1969. After the arrest of
patrons and employees, protesters assembled in the street and, by
throwing pennies, beer cans and other objects, forced police to
retreat temporarily back into the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Widely viewed as the birthplace of the gay civil rights
movement, the Stonewall has become a focal point for homosexual
activists. New York's annual Pride Parade for gays and lesbians
routinely passes in front of the Stonewall.
</P>
<P>
   In March the New York State Board for Historic Places voted
unanimously to recommend the Stonewall's listing in the national
register. The Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation
and the Organization of Lesbian Architects and Designers jointly
nominated the site.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Interior Department Assistant Secretary John Berry
officially announced the designation in a ceremony near the
Stonewall site. He compared the uprising there with other American
historical events such as the Boston Tea Party, the battle of
Gettysburg and the signing of the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the heat of a summer's night here at Stonewall that led
to the creation of a new civil rights movement for America,'' Berry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who is openly gay, added, ``Laws that would call our love
perverse, that hold our sacrifice of life in the service of our
country any less dear, and that conclude that by our very existence
we are somehow inferior are not laws founded in truth. They are
repugnant and must be repudiated.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, President Clinton cited the Stonewall in a
proclamation declaring June to be Gay and Lesbian Pride Month. He
called the original Stonewall protesters ``a courageous group of
citizens (who) resisted harassment and mistreatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations set ``in motion a chain of events'' that led
to ``the birth of the modern gay and lesbian civil rights
movement,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Department spokesman Tim Ahern said that of the 68,000
listings on the national register, no others were for gay and
lesbian sites. ``The Stonewall is the first and most significant,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of gay rights denounced the historic place
designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it has now been listed in the National Register of
Historic Places, there is no way the hearts of Americans will ever
believe homosexuality is normal or viable, or should have a
significant place in American history,'' said the Rev. Lou Sheldon,
chairman of the Traditional Values Coalition, composed of 43,000
mostly conservative evangelical churches nationwide. ``Are we going
to honor prostitution and pedophilia next? Those are `behaviors'
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Chantale Wong, senior adviser to Berry, said that to avoid
protests from anti-gay organizations, there was little effort to
publicize the designation although a press release was issued.
</P>
<P>
   Wong said Interior Department officials are considering the
listing of the Stonewall as a National Historic Landmark, the
A-list of officially designated historic places. Only 2,200 of the
nation's most famous historical sites have been named landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Stonewall protests, police harassment of gay bars was
routine in New York and other cities, according to David Smith,
communications director of the Human Rights Campaign, the nation's
largest gay and lesbian civil rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Police often raided such establishments on the pretext of
enforcing liquor licensing or morals laws, he said. Putting the
Stonewall on the historic-place register ``is a very important
symbolic gesture for our movement,'' Smith said. ``The Stonewall
has enormous cultural significance for our community.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
