<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8439 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWYEAR-DESTINATIONS-     06-24 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR-DESTINATIONS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: continental breakfast. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near Newark Airport, the Days Inn ( (800) 329-7466) and the
Travelodge ( (800) 578-7878) are quoting a rate of $150-$175 for a
double. At least you won't have to fight traffic leaving town.
</P>
<P>
   2000 BY SEA: There are plenty of cruises with space available on
their New Year's voyages. At the top of the line, Seaborne ( (800)
929-9595) is sailing from New York to Miami, then on to the
Caribbean. Its flagship, the QE2, has midrange rooms starting
around $11,139 per person.
</P>
<P>
   A little pricey, perhaps? Laurie Monroe, an agent with It's Your
World Travel, said there are several more-affordable cruises
available. Commodore offers a seven-day cruise starting in New
Orleans and sailing through Playa Del Carmen, Cozumel, the Caymans
and Ocho Rios for about $1,148.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Cruises offers a 10-day trip along the Mexican Pacific
coast, starting in Los Angeles and traveling to Cabo San Lucas,
Mazatlan, Puerto Vallarta, Ixtapa, Acapulco and Puerto Caldera for
only $1,533 a person.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe confirmed that deposits have been as much as $750 and are
nonrefundable, so make sure you're going before you make
reservations. But she also advised contacting a cruise specialist
or travel agent for more options and reservations.
</P>
<P>
   2000 BY SKI: If you've just got your heart set on spending New
Year's in front of a fireplace, drinking a hot toddy, a ski holiday
might be the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford says Carlson Wagonlit hasn't had a demand for ski
bookings yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look for that pretty soon _ people wanting to be in the
mountains and have a snowy Christmas and New Year,'' she said,
adding that many of the end-of-the-year ski packages are just
becoming available.
</P>
<P>
   One option is the Broadmoor Hotel ( (800) 634-7711) in Colorado
Springs. Its three-night, all-inclusive New Year's weekend includes
a room, all meals and a New Year's Eve gala featuring fireworks and
a concert with the Temptations. It's $2,500 per person, with a
mandatory double booking.
</P>
<P>
   What better way to ring in 2000 than blitzed on peppermint
Schnapps, with your leg in a cast, singing along to ``My Girl?''
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY NEWTON YEAR!: Can you believe a city with more hotel rooms
than almost anywhere in the world can be sold out? Well, yes, if
that city is Las Vegas, gaming capital of the world and home of
Wayne Newton. Although Vegas is still organizing 2000 programs,
count on The Strip being wall-to-wall bedlam. There are still lots
of hotels with rooms available, although most are expensive. You
can order a list from the Las Vegas Convention and Visitors
Authority ( (800) 524-3152), or check them out online at
www.lasvegas24hours.com.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the cheap rooms are about $200 a night during New
Year's, but this year, the least expensive room we found was $500 a
night for a Fairfield Inn (3850 Paradise Road, (702) 791-0899).
There is also a four-night minimum. Don't bother with the Motel 6s
and Super 8s in town. All of them are sold out.
</P>
<P>
   OVER THERE: Before crossing the Atlantic for your New Year's
celebration, take the advice of travel agent Ford, who said to
choose a less conventional destination.
</P>
<P>
   Paris and London might have a few rooms lurking in the outer
regions, but why bother when you can visit countries such as
Israel, Egypt, Morocco or Turkey? They all offer ``millennial''
celebrations, and like just about every overseas offering, their
availability wavers hourly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constantly shifting thing,'' Ford said. ``The one thing
people need to have for any kind of travel is flexibility of mind
and imagination. If they don't have that, then this should have
been booked and paid in full two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford suggested meeting your travel agent with an open mind. Her
suggestion, especially for the more mature traveler, is
Maupintour's selection of New Year's Eve packages to sites like
India, Nepal, the Galapagos Islands, Egypt and even the Vienna
Imperial Ball (with tickets starting around $4,500, including air
fare from New York).
</P>
<P>
   You can watch the clock that's the official keeper of Greenwich
Mean Time in Greenwich, a suburb outside London. It's said to be
the first clock that will tick midnight in the Western world on
Dec. 31. Rooms are still available, but with London in the grips of
millennium fever, rooms aren't expected to last.
</P>
<P>
   A huge concert and fireworks display are planned with tickets on
sale this month. For details, contact the Greenwich Tourism Office
( (011) (44) (181) 858-6376, www.info.greenwich2000.com) for
details.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand claims it will be one of the first places to be
touched by the new century's first sunrise. Festivities include a
beach party in Gisborne and a concert featuring David Bowie. Say
hello to 2000 with Ziggy Stardust. Contact the New Zealand Tourism
Board at (800) 388-5494.
</P>
<P>
   With options still available, how is an intrepid travel agent
going to celebrate the new century?
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually will be staying at home,'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
