<HEADER>
A8451 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-IDEAL-HUSBAND-SP     06-24 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-IDEAL-HUSBAND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRAMAX'S `AN IDEAL HUSBAND' COULD BE SUMMER HEIR TO `SHAKESPEARE
IN LOVE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Say what you will about Miramax's alleged underhanded
business practices and big-bucks campaigns to buy itself Academy
Awards, the studio definitely knows how to package a satisfying
movie adaptation of a classic of English Literature.
</P>
<P>
   Its latest foray into the field _ a film version of Oscar
Wilde's 1895 play ``An Imperfect Husband'' _ makes the translation
with all its wit, incisive dialogue and eccentric characters
intact, and then some. It could be the summer heir to the studio's
art-house megahit, ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1890s London, it's the story of Sir Robert Chiltern
(Jeremy Northam), a much-respected politician who seems to have it
all: health, wealth, a wife (Cate Blanchett) who adores him and a
brilliant future that seems aimed straight at 10 Downing Street.
</P>
<P>
   But not very far into the film, the MP's good life is suddenly
threatened by a certain blackmail-minded adventuress named Mrs.
Cheveley (Julianne Moore), who has popped into town from Vienna
with evidence that Chiltern's current prosperity is, in fact, based
on a highly unethical act in his past.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for her destruction of this evidence, Mrs. Cheveley
wants him to vote for a pork-barrel South American canal project.
The rest of the film is about the moral dilemma this situation
creates for him, his wife and his playboy best friend (Rupert
Everett).
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, the plays of Wilde are so stagebound and steeped in
the conventions of the late-Victorian theater that they don't tend
to translate well to film _ problems that certainly plagued
Alexander Korda's 1948 British version of ``An Ideal Husband''
starring Paulette Goddard and Michael Wilding.
</P>
<P>
   But writer-director Oliver Parker (the 1995 ``Othello'') finds
just the right middle ground between movie and play, opening it up
in the first half to present an epic visual slice of Mayfair
society life while, in the second half, maintaining such obvious
stage devices as the shuffling of characters in and out of
adjoining rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The film is genuinely witty, its web of interpersonal
relationships seem more profound and less trivial than they usually
do in Wilde, and the more contemporary aspect of its plot _ a good
politician threatened by destruction because of an indiscretion in
his past _ is slyly beefed up but never exploited to be an obvious
Clinton parallel.
</P>
<P>
   The cast doesn't have a sour note in it.
</P>
<P>
   Northam's Chiltern is believably stalwart but never a
stuffed-shirt hero; Moore's seductive blackmailer is splendidly
venomous and, finally, surprisingly sympathetic; and Blanchett _
who clearly has no limitations as an actress _ is more regal here
than she was in ``Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's Rupert Everett _ whose performance as the best friend
won him the best actor honors at the 25th Seattle International
Film Festival, where the film debuted late last month _ who steals
the movie. His dry wit, and his casual-but-perfect delivery of the
Wildean epigrams from the corner of his mouth, make him the movies'
ultimate surrogate Wilde, and put him right on track for an Oscar
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   An Ideal Husband. Directed and written by Oliver Parker, from
the play by Oscar Wilde. Cast: Cate Blanchett, Minnie Driver,
Rupert Everett, Julianne Moore, Jeremy Northam, John Wood. Miramax.
98 minutes. Rated PG-13 for no obvious reason.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1816EDT &QL; 
