<SLUG> BC-CARS-TRUNK-RELEASES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
G.M. DEVELOPS SENSOR TO MAKE TRUNKS SAFER 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Wash., Va., N.J., Conn.)   By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After 11 children died last summer in separate
incidents in which they became trapped in car trunks, General
Motors and other companies set out to design a release inside the
trunk. They did, and GM, which developed a big yellow handle that
is illuminated when the trunk is closed, made a $50 kit including
the handle available at its dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   But GM said immediately that the handle was not perfect: In
tests, some children did not figure out that pulling it would let
them escape. So the company developed an infrared sensor that
detects a person or a pet by recognizing motion or body heat. It
automatically pops the trunk, using the existing mechanism that
opens the lid from a switch near the driver or from a key fob.
</P>
<P>
   The company will include the new sensor on all of its family
cars with trunks within two and a half years. William J. Kemp, a
spokesman, said that the device would be standard equipment. These
same family cars will also have the illuminated handles.
</P>
<P>
   The company made its announcement a few days after a government
panel, made up of representatives of medical and consumer groups
and the auto industry, recommended that by 2001, all new cars
should have a release handle in the trunk. The panel said that
since 1970, 1,175 people had been caught in trunks in 992
incidents, and at least 260 of them died. Most of the deaths came
in abductions, the report said.  &QL; 
BUSES GET A BREAK  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many car-bus collisions occur when buses pull away from curbside
stops into the travel lanes in heavy traffic. A British Columbia
law that took effect in May gives buses the right of way when they
are pulling out, and a similar law will take effect this year in
Oregon. Quebec and Washington State already have such laws.
</P>
<P>
   The law in British Columbia covers roads with a speed limit of
60 kilometers an hour (37 mph) or lower. Some transit officials in
the Eastern United States are envious.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a law like this in New Jersey it would definitely
speed up traffic,'' said Steven Coleman, a spokesman for New Jersey
Transit. ``One of the biggest problems our operators face is
getting away from the curb. This would definitely improve safety.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hartford, Michael A. Saunders, the Transit and Ride Sharing
administrator for Connecticut, said the specifications for new
buses usually called for acceleration times of 0 to 40 mph in 20
seconds. A typical new car takes half that long to reach 60 mp.h.
</P>
<P>
   A law giving buses the right of way would be useful, he said,
but is not something that he would expend a lot of political
capital on. Instead, his department recently received a grant from
the Transportation Department in Washington to plan a dedicated
busway. It would consist of two paved lanes on an abandoned
railroad right-of-way, complete with 12 stations, on a nine-mile
route from Hartford to New Britain.
</P>
<P>
   On some of New York City's most congested streets, like Fifth
Avenue in midtown Manhattan, buses run on lanes set aside for their
exclusive use. When they stop to discharge passengers, they do not
pull out of the traffic lanes to do so. Thus, they do not have to
pull back into traffic to start again.
</P>
<P>
   In British Columbia, new signs are being added to the backs of
buses, showing the familiar triangular shape, the pointed end down,
with the word ``yield'' inside and a drawing of a bus with its left
directional signal flashing, as it would if it were pulling away
from the curb into a traffic lane. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOUGH LOOK, FRAGILE BUMPERS
</P>
<P>
   Sport utility vehicles may look rugged, but many of them have a
glass jaw, according to the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety,
which runs them into flat barriers, an angled barrier and a pole at
5 miles an hour to measure the damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitsubishi Montero Sport suffered combined damage that the
institute said would cost more than $6,000 to repair, making it the
worst of the six midsized sport utilities that the institute
tested. Even the sturdiest vehicle tested _ the Mercedes ML320 _
sustained about $3,000 in damage.
</P>
<P>
   An inherent problem for sport utility vehicles is that what
causes damage is not speed but force, which is speed multiplied by
mass _ and, generally, these vehicles are massive.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Lund, senior vice president of the institute, which is
financed by the insurance industry and based in Arlington, Va.,
said the real problem was much simpler. ``It's basically that the
bumpers aren't very good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Montero Sport, for example, the bumper contains no
energy-absorbing material and the bumper `reinforcement bar' that
would have to handle something like a pole hit or a corner hit is
just a thin strip of steel plate. This would provide poor low-speed
crash damage protection even for lighter vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   The bumpers may be weak because there is no Federal crash
requirement for sport-utilities as there is for cars, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no requirement for vans, either, but they are built
better, he said, perhaps in response to the safety concerns of
typical minivan buyers. In tests this spring, the Honda Odyssey
showed damage of $1,063, the Nissan Quest, $1,110, and the Ford
Windstar, $1,714, he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SEAT BELT USE IS UP  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is as effective at encouraging adherence to safety laws
as the threat of a ticket, experts say. And they are crowing about
the results of an enforcement blitz over Memorial Day Weekend. The
New York State Police, one of the first agencies to report back
with the results, said 300 police agencies in the state
participated in a May 22-31 crackdown and issued 45,084 tickets for
violations of the state's seat belt laws. Of those, 5,024 were for
violations of child restraint laws, the police superintendent,
James W. McMahon, said.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys conducted after the blitz showed that seat-belt
compliance had risen to 81 percent from 76, The high-visibility
enforcement program, which was operated nationally by thousands of
police agencies, was the fourth; the first was at Thanksgiving
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The state's goal is to have a rate of seat belt usage of more
than 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Hurley, a traffic safety expert at the National Safety
Council, said that if New York followed the national pattern, and
that if the increase in compliance continued, the state would
probably have about 100 fewer highway deaths over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is now a national model for belt use,'' he said.
Unlike most states, it allows the police to stop a car if an adult
is unbuckled. (Most states allow an officer to issue a ticket for
not wearing a belt, but only if the car is pulled over for some
other reason.) New York, Hurley said, has ``a strong law, being
superbly enforced.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
