<HEADLINE>
CAST OF `BID DADDY' IS TALENTED BUT THE SCRIPT IS A MESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are we ready for a soulful Adam Sandler?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he tried to stay love-struck in ``The Wedding Singer'' and
the film fell flat after the first 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same happens in ``Big Daddy,'' an initially silly and
darkly funny movie that follows the usual pattern for all Sandler
ventures: he's a schlub who gets dumped by his girlfriend, has no
ambition, but discovers something about his own character in the
process and finally winds up an unorthodox winner.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Big Daddy,'' Sandler plays Sonny Koufax, a goof-off who has
unloaded his promising law career for a one-day-a-week job in a
Manhattan toll booth. His longtime girlfriend, Vanessa (Kristy
Swanson), has just taken off with a guy ``with a five-year plan''
and his roommate, Kevin (Jon Stewart), just announced his
engagement to the sharp-tongued Corinne (Leslie Mann), a doctor who
used to work at the local Hooters.
</P>
<P>
   In short, everyone's life is on the upswing _ save Sonny's. But
things are about to change. Julian, a 5-year-old with a sweet lisp
and a mind that works like a serial killer's, enters his life. It
seems the tyke is the result of one of Kevin's one-night stands in
Toronto and Julian's mother has recently died. Sonny hatches a
plan. He'll tell social services that he's Kevin and, by
shouldering the responsibility of fatherhood, prove to Vanessa that
he's not a loser.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nothing is as simple as it seems, except the
predictable outcome to this subterfuge.
</P>
<P>
   Sandler employs his usual abrasive charm and Joey Lauren Adams
(``Chasing Amy'') is a good choice as a potential new love interest
(though she has little to do) for Sonny. But the real star of the
show is Julian, played by twins Cole and Dylan Sprouse. The
character is one of the most disarming kids to hit the screen since
Jonathan Lipnicki stole hearts as Ray Boyd in ``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   But though the cast is talented, the script is a mess. It's
essentially a collision of missed opportunities and Sandler
introduces one idea, only to drop it and take on another.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, ``Big Daddy'' feels like an afterthought of a
film. It shifts from comedy to pathos and winds up sliding through
whatever point it wants to make. I'd rather watch the grotesquely
fascinating and funny ``The Waterboy'' again any day over this
sentimental mishmash of a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Big Daddy. Directed by Dennis Dugan. Written by Steve Franks,
Tim Herlihy, Adam Sandler. Cast: Adam Sandler, Joey Lauren Adams,
Jon Stewart, Leslie Mann. Columbia Pictures. 95 minutes. Rated
PG-13 for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
