<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBELDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BECKER HOLDS OFF TIME AND FORMER PROTEGE TO MAKE THIRD ROUND AT
WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ If tennis years unfurl like dog years _ and
Boris Becker, Wimbledon's head watchdog, claims that's always been
the case with him _ it means he has been torching the turf of his
favorite lawn for 105 years.
</P>
<P>
   First came Becker's historic championship as an unseeded,
carrot-topped 17 year old in 1985; then came his third and last
Wimbledon triumph 10 years ago, and finally, after a 1997
quarterfinal loss to Pete Sampras, Becker confessed that he would
play here no more.
</P>
<P>
   But retiring at Wimbledon was so nice that Becker decided to do
it twice. And Thursday, after saving three match points in his
shaky Tuesday opener on Court Two, the Graveyard Court, Becker was
restored to glory on Center Court, his preferred backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old German used the sentimental homecoming to
annihilate 15th-seeded Nicolas Kiefer, 21, his German heir
apparent, 6-4, 6-2, 6-4. The faithful in the front rows had their
hero's initials painted on their faces, and the faithful in the
upper rows held banners that advised the world that Boris Is A
Tennis God. With a build-up like that, he almost had to play like
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come back after my first-round thriller to play perfect
grass-court tennis was very pleasing; to be back on Center Court,
it brought out the best in me,'' said Becker, who blasted 17 aces,
charged the net 52 times, saved three break points, and won 85
percent of his first service points. ``I can't say that this is my
place anymore: I used to own it, but Pete Sampras has taken over
the keys, so we obviously have new ownership of that court, but I
still feel obviously very much at home on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Kiefer tuned up for this Grand Slam event by winning the
Halle title and was, as the seeded contestant, the statistical
favorite to prevail, the 77th-ranked Becker believed that he still
belongs in this arena and that he deserved to reprise his 1997 swan
song.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure was pretty much on me more, because he has
another 10 years to go and will eventually do very well in
Wimbledon, but this is my last hurrah,'' Becker promised. ``So
there was an enormous amount of pressure on my shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   But Becker handled the pressure like the warrior he is. In
danger of being broken in the fourth game of the final set, Becker
corrected the break point his double fault had created by firing an
ace, one of four he produced in the game. And after holding for
2-2, he pointedly broke Kiefer for a 3-2 edge.
</P>
<P>
   A second-serve ace delivered Becker his third match point in the
10th game, and he ended things by looming up at the net and forcing
Kiefer to rush a backhand pass into the net, a faux pas that
generated a roar of approval from the partisan audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like I won the tournament, but unfortunately it
was only the second round,'' Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   Becker told Sampras in 1997 that he was glad that his last match
had been played against him. Thursday, the cursory handshake he
exchanged with the loser made it clear that he would not have felt
gratified to have Kiefer go down as the player who ended his
Wimbledon career.
</P>
<P>
   Kiefer's relationship with Becker, his former
mentor-turned-Davis Cup manager, has been frosty of late due to
Becker's displeasure with the acolyte's indifferent performance in
Germany's opening-round Davis Cup loss to Russia. Kiefer complained
that Becker ignored him when they met in the locker room here, but
Thursday Becker said whatever hard feelings there are between them
would soon dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably a couple weeks down the road we are going to drink a
beer together, and I'm retired, and he's top 10 in the world,''
said Becker, ``so what's the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Kiefer, the only seeds to make a second-round exit
Thursday were 16th-seeded Natasha Zvereva, ambushed 6-4, 7-5 by
100th-ranked Tatiana Panova, and seventh-seeded Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario, a two-time Wimbledon finalist.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez-Vicario, the versatile Spaniard, couldn't keep up with
the pace set by 37th-ranked Lisa Raymond of Wayne, Pa. The underdog
entered the match with an 0-4 record against Sanchez-Vicario and
left the court with a 7-6 (7-4), 6-1 upset. Two Wimbledon ingenues,
129th-ranked Jelena Dokic, the Australian qualifier who trounced
top-seeded Martina Hingis in the first round on Tuesday, and
86th-ranked Alexandra Stevenson of San Diego, who has decided to
spurn a scholarship offer from UCLA and turn professional here,
already feel the same fondness for Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Dokic, the 16-year-old Slovak-born prodigy that Hingis'
mother/coach, Melanie Molitor, wanted to add to her coaching stable
even before she beat her daughter, advanced to the third round by
outlasting Katarina Studenikova, 6-0, 4-6, 8-6. Stevenson,
currently working with Martina Navratilova's former coach, Craig
Kardon, upset 57th-ranked Olga Barabanschikova, 6-2, 6-7 (3-7),
6-3. In the fourth round, Stevenson, 18, plays 11th-seeded Julie
Halard-Decugis..
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking I can win the whole thing,'' said Stevenson, who
said that winning a Wimbledon title by the time she is 19 has been
her raison d'etre since she was 3. ``That would be really cool, to
beat my goal.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
