<SLUG> BC-PENN-STATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODEL FOR PENN STATION ON VIEW AT THE MODERN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A model of the proposed design for the new
Pennsylvania Station has been placed on view at the Museum of
Modern Art. The display will remain on the fourth-floor landing
outside the museum's architecture and design galleries until Aug.
1.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation revives the Preview series, an exhibition
program initiated in 1993 by Terence Riley, chief curator of the
Modern's department of architecture and design, as a showcase for
individual buildings before construction. Projects previously
featured in the series include the Tokyo International Forum,
designed by Rafael Vinoly; the Austrian Cultural Institute in
Manhattan, by Raimund Abraham, and the Nara Convention Hall, by
Arata Isozaki.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by David Childs of the New York office of Skidmore
Owings &AMP; Merrill, the new Penn Station is to be housed in the James
A. Farley Building, the Beaux-Arts post office on Eighth Avenue
between West 31st and 33rd Streets. The design includes a new
ticketing hall, two blocks long, housed beneath a dramatic, curving
space frame of metal and glass. The framework, 150 feet high, also
contains the main entrances to the train station, which will be on
31st and 33rd Streets between Eighth and Ninth Avenues. Waiting
areas and shops will occupy a series of platforms, or trays, that
step down from street level to the train platforms four stories
below ground.
</P>
<P>
   The $486 million project, the most important public work
undertaken in New York in more than a generation, will include the
Manhattan terminal of a rail link to Kennedy Airport, in addition
to hubs for Amtrak, New Jersey Transit and the Long Island Rail
Road. A rail link to Newark Airport is also planned.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the U.S. Postal Service will continue to operate in the
1935 annex to the Farley Building, which was designed in 1913 by
McKim, Mead &AMP; White, the architects of the original Penn Station.
The postal service will also maintain its existing retail
operations in the lobby on the Eighth Avenue side of the building.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Riley said, ``The Preview series will resume at
a steady beat, focusing on newsworthy projects as they break.'' He
said he expected New York building projects to be a regular feature
of the museum series. ``For the last three decades, New Yorkers
with an interest in architecture have had to settle for mediocre
developer work as the homegrown product,'' Riley said. ``The
Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill design for the new Penn Station is
mercifully an exception, and hopefully is the beginning of renewed
interest in the city and in architectural excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penn Station project faces economic and political obstacles
before construction can proceed. About $80 million of the projected
cost has yet to be secured. Supporters of the project were dismayed
when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani declined to attend an unveiling
ceremony last month. Though the city has committed only $25 million
_ roughly 5 percent of the total cost _ Giuliani has the power to
veto the spending of funds already obtained from federal and state
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has also expressed reservations about Childs' design.
At a news conference, he likened the new ticketing hall to a side
alley. For the next few weeks, visitors to the Modern will have the
opportunity to see for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
