<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS CHAMPIONSHIP WOULD BE FIRST RATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Consider all the Firsts we will see if, as expected,
the San Antonio Spurs win the 1999 NBA championship:
</P>
<P>
   --First graduate of the Naval Academy to win a title.
</P>
<P>
   --First AIC man to win a third title.
</P>
<P>
   --First Southern University man to win a title.
</P>
<P>
   --First Drexel man to win a title.
</P>
<P>
   --First Longwood College man to win a title.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs a big-school pedigree?
</P>
<P>
   And there's more . . .
</P>
<P>
   --First resident of the Virgin Islands to win a title.
</P>
<P>
   --First Georgetown man to win a title, at least in the John
Thompson era.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, they have Steve Kerr and Sean Elliott, Arizona guys
with a Final Four background. But they are a minority factor on a
team that mainly comprises people who have known rejection and
dismissal, or who have come to the ultimate world basketball
showcase from a very strange starting point.
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson is a basketball star of the first magnitude, but
that wasn't his goal when he left home as a 6-foot-7-inch high
school kid from Osbourn Park High School in Manassas, Va. in order
to become a naval officer. He didn't plan on growing an additional
seven inches, without which none of this would be happening.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan was going to be a swimmer. (If you've heard this
1,000 times, this is just going to have to be 1,001.) Then came
Hurricane Hugo, and there went the only decent Olympic-type pool on
St. Croix. When he arrived at Wake Forest as a 6-10 blank canvas of
hoop, no one realized we'd be looking at a player who now is
threatening to own the NBA for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Then we get to our friends from such non-mainstream basketball
outposts as AIC (Mario Elie), Southern (Avery Johnson), Drexel
(Malik Rose) and Longwood (Jerome Kersey). All but the soon-to-be
37-year-old Kersey (it happens Saturday) are rotation players on
the Spurs, and Kersey is still capable of making a contribution, as
a first quarter 3-pointer demonstrated in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Kersey, Johnson, and Elie are all foxy old pros. Rose is a
third-year player. The old guys have already answered all the
questions about their uphill climbs to the NBA penthouse. Kersey
will tell you that this is a long way from the days when the big
rival was Randolph-Macon. The undrafted Johnson can tell you about
being bounced from Seattle to Denver to San Antonio to Houston to
San Antonio to Golden State and then, finally, back to San Antonio
in 1994. Elie, who once thought Springfield was a big game, was a
1985 seventh-round draft pick (Milwaukee), who played in Portugal,
Argentina, and Ireland, as well as the CBA, the USBL, and the WBL.
Not to mention Philadelphia, Golden State, Portland, and Houston,
where he picked up a pair of championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   So if young Mr. Rose, who spent the first two years of his NBA
career in Charlotte, is looking for advice on how to handle any
hard times in either his personal or professional life, he has
certainly come to the right team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we all just believe in ourselves,'' says the
affable young man who recalls regarding Delaware, BU, and Maine as
prime rivals when he was carving out a reputation as the ``Shaq Of
The NAC'' a few years back.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in one more vagabond, albeit one with a more upscale
collegiate background. That would be 31-year-old Jaren Jackson,
who, in his ninth NBA season, is playing for his eighth team to go
along with his four stops in the CBA and one stint in the WBL.
Jackson is on the verge of becoming the first John
Thompson-developed Georgetown man to play on an NBA champonship
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought much about all that,'' says Kersey, who made
two previous trips to the Finals (1990, '92) as an 11-year member
of the Portland Trail Blazers. ``We're just a team of basic
fundamentalists. We don't have a lot of high-flyers pulling off
reverse dunks.''
</P>
<P>
   And for more emphasis, Elie even says that coach Gregg Popovich
is ``one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true enough. There is no great NBA pedigree attached to
him, either. He played at the Air Force Academy. During his five
years in the military he played on various service and AAU teams
and was even invited to the 1972 Olympic Trials. He later coached
at Division 3 Pomona-Pitzer. His entree into the NBA was Larry
Brown, who hired him as an assistant in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   He likes the idea of having so many guys from the wrong side of
the basketball tracks on his team. These are guys who haven't had
it just given to them,'' he declares. ``They've come up the hard
way. When you show confidence in guys like that you get it back
tenfold. They are happy to be here, and they are willing to accept
roles. This all makes sense, at least in my mind, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Popovich's team of ``basic fundamentalists'' _ and it really is
his team since he is also the general manager _ has been a purist's
delight during their steady march to the title. For this is a team
that has brought back the hook shot (Robinson and little Avery, who
made three first-half Lenny Wilkens-style running hooks in Game 4),
the bank shot (Duncan), and, most amazingly of all, the flat-footed
one-hand set shot (Elie).
</P>
<P>
   That may not be the way they play basketball at UCLA (since Bill
Walton left, anyway), Michigan or UNLV. But that's apparently the
way they learned how to play it at Navy, Southern, St. Croix/Wake
Forest, and AIC. Perhaps players at the glamour schools should be
taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
