<HEADER>
A8466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-JARRETT-NY     06-24 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-JARRETT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT IS A MAN ON A MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is, if he can keep it up, an unbeatable pace. Since the
Daytona 500, when he lost control of his car trying to get back in
line and wrecked, Dale Jarrett has been a man on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   And that mission is to win his first Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Sunday's Save Mart/Kragen 350k at Sonoma, Calif.,
Jarrett boasts an 89-point lead over another rapidly rising
contender, Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   But Labonte and everybody else is going to have a difficult time
dealing with him unless Jarrett and his team start fouling up.
</P>
<P>
   Since that wreck in the season's first event, Jarrett has
finished in the top 10 in 13 of the 14 races run, and the one time
he missed, at Las Vegas, he was 11th.
</P>
<P>
   In 12 of the last 14 races, he has been fifth or better.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, in fact, has run so well that he has overshadowed an
outstanding stretch by defending Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon.
Going into this weekend, Gordon has finished second three straight
times. Despite that, he has lost 10 points to Jarrett in his effort
to catch the leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sat down last year, we talked about the way we were
going to have to perform and what we were going to have to do to
win championships,'' Jarrett said. The answer was consistency that
produces a high finish average throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know somebody will do that, so it might as well be us to
set that standard,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   At 42, Jarrett appears to be peaking as a driver in Robert
Yates' second car prepared by crew chief Todd Parrott.
</P>
<P>
   With their Ford's performance in 1999, it is fair to say that
Jarrett and Parrott have shown, beyond doubt, that they now form
one of NASCAR's elite teams.
</P>
<P>
   Originally signed as a fill-in until injured Ernie Irvan was
able to return, Jarrett and Parrott were teamed in 1996 by Yates
when he decided to add a second car. Since then, Jarrett has won 16
races and finished the last three years third, second and third,
respectively, in the point standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have good equipment everywhere I go now,'' Jarrett said.
``What's benefited us a lot is that when you win, you know the kind
of feel you're looking for in a race car. Until you get to that
point, you're not exactly sure what it takes to win and to make
that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that as I go to these race tracks we've performed well
at, I know a certain feel that I'm looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett said he is making no assumptions about a championship.
While he has established himself as the man to beat, he knows he's
just a couple blown engines or blown tires or wrecks away from
losing the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do everything you can,'' Jarrett said. ``You make your
calls throughout the year and you drive your races and, if they
come out like you want them, that's great. If they don't, you start
to get ready for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we get caught up a little bit too much in what we do
and it's not quite as important as we think when you look around,''
Jarrett said. ``You've always got your family to go home to, no
matter what happens, they're behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   And if he keeps running the way he has, so are a lot of other
people.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
