A8472 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DESERT-SPI &LR;      06-24 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DESERT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS, REVELATIONS OF `DESERT BLUE' TOWN EASY TO FIGURE OUT EARLY
ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Morgan J. Freeman's second film after his critically acclaimed
``Hurricane Streets'' is a slice of small-town life that mirrors
the deserted desert existence it depicts _ nothing happens.
</P>
<P>
   Baxter Beach boasts a population of 89 and is located in a
wasteland in central California. It's a place that holds one
tourist attraction: the world's largest ice cream cone.
</P>
<P>
   Yet life is about to alter radically for the residents. When
teenage TV star Skye (Kate Hudson) and her scientist dad (John
Heard) are waylaid and quarantined in town by the FBI after a truck
carrying a mysterious substance results in the death of the driver,
everyone's eyes are opened to new, potential worlds beyond Baxter's
claustrophobic borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desert Blue'' visually captures the idle existence. But this
turf has been trod in dozens of other films, and Freeman's movie
resembles virtually every screen depiction of a sleepy, shuffling,
nowhere town. Ultimately, it has to rely upon eccentricity to
separate it from the competition. It winds up paralleling its tired
subject matter with an equally lumbering pace, and the secrets and
revelations are transparently easy to figure out early on.
</P>
<P>
   Though it boasts a cast of up-and-coming Hollywood talent _
Hudson, Christina Ricci, Casey Affleck and Brendan Sexton II _ its
strength lies with its older actors. Lucinda Jenney gives the film
its true emotional range. The relationship that buds between her
character and Heard's has a degree of depth that comes from the
despair of being alone with no hope.
</P>
<P>
   The film strains to find a parallel between its middle-aged and
youthful ennui, broken dreams and the prospect of nowhere to go,
but the idea doesn't gel, especially in the way these kids pin
their notions of leaving on a single incident.
</P>
<P>
   That dramatic impetus _ a celebrity in town _ is contrived, and
the result is a movie that sparks to life about as often as a
breeze blows through this hot, still desert town.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Blue. Directed and written by Morgan J. Freeman. Cast:
Brendan Sexton III, Kate Hudson, Christina Ricci, Casey Affleck,
John Heard. Samuel Goldwyn. 89 minutes. Rated R for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
