A8475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-NEWCAR-NYT     06-24 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NEWCAR-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MONTE CARLO IS COMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hendrick Motorsports and RAD, the aerodynamics arm of three
Chevy teams, are going full speed ahead on the new Monte Carlo,
2000 model.
</P>
<P>
   The car, which was expected to debut this year, was put on hold
until 2000 after Chevy and NASCAR got into a prolonged debate over
its characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy wanted a version superior to its present Monte Carlo,
while NASCAR wanted to make sure any new design was not inherently
superior to the competition.
</P>
<P>
   That delayed NASCAR approval of the 2000 model until the end of
May. Now, Hendrick Motorsports, which is building a superspeedway
car for Talladega and Daytona, and RAD, which is building the
so-called downforce car that will run every place else, are working
to get test cars ready for the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the process of taking the NASCAR templates and
building a test car for RAD,'' said Steve Hmiel, technical director
for Dale Earnhardt's team. In Hmiel, formerly Mark Martin's crew
chief, and aero engineer Louis Duncan, who played a major role in
designing the Taurus, RAD has two of stock car racing's top chassis
experts.
</P>
<P>
   RAD was put together by three Chevy owners _ Richard Childress,
Andy Petree and Earnhardt _ with the goal of improving performance.
Duncan was hired to assist the teams in building more aerodynamic
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The templates have now been released and all three RAD
organizations have a complete set, which means we can start
building cars,'' Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a race team call, but I think we could have a car on the
track, probably sometime in the next few months, once NASCAR gives
us a test date,'' Duncan said. A car should be ready for wind
tunnel testing within weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the new Monte Carlo evolved, NASCAR ran a series of tests
before giving its approval, trying to be certain Chevy wasn't
trying to build a rocket ship.
</P>
<P>
   But despite wind tunnel tests and design calculations, there is
no way to predict how a new car will perform until it actually gets
out and runs.
</P>
<P>
   And NASCAR still has to be a little nervous about this because
most expect the new Monte Carlo to have more downforce, which means
it should be better than the present model except at Daytona and
Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   And that means Jeff Gordon, who drives for Hendrick, should be
even better.
</P>
<P>
   So this story is just getting started and the ending is not yet
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-REFLECT-ART     06-24 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REFLECT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL WITNESS LEAVES STAND IN MICROSOFT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The heated accusations of monopoly, the lively
e-mail flavored with capitalist aggression and the spirited
testimony alleging and denying misconduct came to a close Thursday
as the last witness stepped off the stand in the Microsoft
antitrust trial, eight months after proceedings began.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft trial is by no means over, but it sharply shifts
gears as the daily theater in the courtroom gives way to a more
sober weighing of facts and law. ``Now the showmanship ends and the
legal maneuvering really begins,'' observed Andrew Gavil, a
professor at the Howard University law school.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the points in the daily courtroom drama went to the
Justice Department and the 19 states suing Microsoft Corp. Led by
trial lawyer David Boies, the government team caught Microsoft's
witnesses off guard again and again, presenting them with
embarrassing e-mails or previous statements that appeared to
undermine their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Even William Neukom, Microsoft's general counsel, found it
impressive, if not convincing. Since the start of the trial, Neukom
notes that he has fielded expressions of concern that things are
going badly for the company from many of his colleagues, even his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has put on a great performance,'' he said,
``but it does not add up to a solid antitrust case. It's all fluff
legally.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Klein, assistant attorney general in charge of the Justice
Department's antitrust division, counters that the evidence and
testimony presented in court has been occasionally entertaining but
consistently incriminating. It adds up to a detailed and convincing
portrait, Klein said, of ``Microsoft's ability and willingness to
do whatever is necessary in using its market power to protect its
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal reckoning that matters, however, will be made by Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson, who will rule in this trial without a
jury. Both Microsoft and the government will make further written
and oral arguments over the summer and fall.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson must then comb through the mountains of evidence to try
to answer one essential question: What are the appropriate legal
restraints on the behavior of a powerful company in a dynamic
high-technology industry?
</P>
<P>
   The issue extends well beyond the Microsoft case, and the stakes
are high. The ruling could set ground rules for competition in the
modern economy, affecting companies and consumers alike for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The legal guideposts to help Jackson reach his decision,
antitrust experts say, are not clear-cut. The major antitrust
rulings over the last two decades are few, and they mostly involve
mundane businesses including ski resorts in Colorado, a rural Ohio
newspaper, a bowling alley in New Jersey and an egg processor in
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the plaintiffs brought a very traditional
antitrust suit. The government says Microsoft repeatedly and
illegally used its market power to thwart new competition
represented by the rise of the Internet, especially software for
browsing the World Wide Web. With exclusionary contracts and
threats, Microsoft, according to the government, used its market
power to defend its monopoly product _ the Windows operating
system, the software that serves as the central nervous system of
90 percent of the personal computers sold today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is mainly an old-fashioned contract case,'' said Herbert
Hovenkamp, a professor at the University of Iowa law school and
leading antitrust scholar, who is advising the government. ``There
is nothing novel about the practices. The one thing that is novel
is that the case is in the software industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the industry context is a crucial consideration. The
software business is regarded as the forerunner of what has been
called ``the new economy'' _ a fast-moving, fluid environment in
which market leadership can be fleeting, but technology can also
hasten the concentration of market power and the creation of
monopolies. In short, new-economy theories can cut both ways in
antitrust cases. There has been plenty of talk of ``network
effects'' and ``winner-take-all markets'' from both sides in the
Microsoft trial.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Microsoft case focuses on a fast-moving,
technically complex industry complicates the legal judgment the
court must make. ``It makes the toughest issues that courts have to
deal with in antitrust cases _ determining market power, evaluating
the significance of conduct and designing remedies _ far more
difficult,'' said William Kovacic, a professor at the George
Washington University law school.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many antitrust experts who have followed the trial expect
that Jackson will side with the government on some of its many
charges against Microsoft. They base that view partly on a reading
of Jackson's behavior _openly questioning the testimony of some
Microsoft witnesses, and showing impatience with Microsoft's
lawyers _ and partly on a reading of the law, that some Microsoft
contracts with online services and personal computer manufacturers
did inhibit competition from software rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is by no means conceding defeat in Jackson's federal
district court. But Neukom suggests that its legal strategy is to
prevail on appeal. ``The thing to remember is that we're engaged in
a legal decathlon, and we're still at an early stage,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the two sides reach a settlement, Jackson's ruling,
expected by the end of the year, will certainly be reviewed by a
federal appeals court and possibly by the Supreme Court as well. If
it goes to the Supreme Court, the Microsoft case may well not be
finally determined until 2002, legal experts say.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
