<SLUG> BC-GAYS-DISCRIMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIPARTISAN GROUP REINTRODUCES BILL TO PROTECT HOMOSEXUALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan coalition of lawmakers on Thursday
introduced legislation to ban job discrimination against gays and
lesbians and expressed hope that it would win approval despite the
failure of two similar measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Employment Non-Discrimination Act of 1999 (ENDA) would bar
employers from discriminating against homosexuals in hiring,
firing, promotion or compensation. If it becomes law, ENDA would
extend to gays and lesbians that same federal protections already
guaranteed for race, religion, gender, national origin, age and
disability.
</P>
<P>
   The ENDA bill does not require domestic partnership benefits and
doesn't apply to the armed services. It also contains an exemption
for religious organizations and prohibits employers from giving
special treatment or adopting quotas for gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters insist this version will be more popular than earlier
bills because the new legislation would prohibit affirmative action
or preferential treatment based on sexual orientation. In the past,
opponents have argued that the legislation would lead to special
treatment for homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The bill ``will achieve equal rights _ not `special rights'''
for gays and lesbians, Sen. James M. Jeffords, R-Vt., a key sponsor
of the bill, told a Thursday news conference. ``Success at work
should be directly related to one's ability to do the job,
period.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., another key sponsor, called it
``the next important step for civil rights in America.'' Kennedy
said Congress must take steps to achieve fairness for gay men and
lesbians who ``encounter blatant discrimination in the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn., another sponsor, said the
case of James Hormel, a San Francisco businessman whose nomination
to be ambassador to Luxembourg was blocked in the Senate for 18
months because he is gay, ``underscores the vulnerability of the
average worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel will be sworn in next week as ambassador to Luxembourg
because President Clinton intervened and used his constitutional
authority to make a recess appointment and install him directly
during the Memorial Day congressional recess. But, Lieberman said,
there is a need for the legislation because ``there is not such
thing as a recess appointment in the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., the main sponsor in the House,
said he is optimistic that Congress will approve the measure this
year, especially after the House last August voted overwhelming to
uphold Clinton's executive order banning discrimination based on
sexual orientation for federal employees.
</P>
<P>
   The new ENDA has a record number of 163 co-sponsors in the
House, including 15 Republicans, and 35 co-sponsors in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill came within one vote of passage in the Senate in
1996. The measure was reintroduced again in 1997 but failed to win
passage.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has never come up for a vote in the House.
</P>
<P>
   A leading Christian conservative has vowed to block the new
ENDA.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Lou Sheldon, chairman of the Traditional Values
Coalition, a conservative group that draws support from evangelical
churches, said homosexuals are not being unfairly discriminated
against in the workplace. He also said gays and lesbians are not a
true minority because they can ``disengage'' from a homosexual
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not in bread lines or unemployment lines or living
under bridges as homeless people,'' Sheldon said. ``Why then are we
elevating a behavior-based lifestyle to minority status?''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven states have passed laws to protect homosexuals from
discrimination in the workplace. They are Nevada, New Hampshire,
California, Connecticut, Hawaii, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New
Jersey, Rhode Island, Vermont, Wisconsin and the District of
Columbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
