<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8480 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CENTURY-SPI &LR;      06-24 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CENTURY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN-HANDED TREATMENT CARRIES `GUERRILLA WARS' INSTALLMENT OF
`CENTURY' SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any card-carrying revolutionary will say winning hearts and
minds is the key to winning the bigger prize, be it a new
government, a new way of life or the same old way of life with some
new guy eating bon-bons in the imperial palace. In the next-to-last
airing of PBS's Peabody Award-winning ``People's Century,'' two
different methods of gaining popular support are placed in stark
counterpoint and examined with the cool dispassion that has made
``People's Century'' a history teacher's dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guerrilla Wars,'' the first hour of Monday's two-part entry,
covers a lot of familiar ground. But because of its non-American
provenance _ ``People's Century'' is a BBC production in
cooperation with WGBH-Boston _ there's a refreshing balance that we
may not have realized was missing from U.S. reportage when the
events were taking place.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in ``People's Cen tury'' the accounts of
guerrilla-war tactics that stymied the United States in Southeast
Asia are neither
</P>
<P>
   pro-American nor pro-North Vietnamese. The facts are presented
not with an eye toward ideology, but more as a means of
illuminating a chapter of history that will forever be obscured by
philosophical posturing in many U.S. precincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guerrilla Wars'' producer Bill Treharne Jones is careful not
to gloat in the victory of a people's army over a superpower. He is
even more careful in showing the repetitious nature of history:
Though ``Guerrilla Wars'' is ostensibly about the withdrawal of
American troops from Vietnam in 1973, it begins with a brief
summary of the surprisingly swift and effective guerrilla campaign
that brought socialism to Cuba in the 1950s, and it ends with the
Soviet Union repeating the mistake of arrogant conceit in
Afghanistan in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of Monday's program looks at revolutions rooted
in the deployment of religion, not rifles. ``God Fights Back''
centers on the backlash that began in the second half of the
century after ``modern technology and Western thought had swept
religion to the margins of public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the documentary renders no judgment. Producer Ben
Loeterman is scrupulously evenhanded, whether he's dealing with the
rise of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran or the explosion of
fundamentalist fervor in the United States. The issue isn't the
ayatollah's anti-Americanism or Jimmy Swaggart's personal
peccadilloes; it is the fusing of faith and politics into a
lightning rod that has galvanized millions of disaffected,
disenfranchised people around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Kerley, a follower of Swaggart's brand of televangelism,
succinctly summarizes the rhetoric that keeps a revolution rolling.
``What I liked about Jimmy Swaggart,'' Kerley says, ``was the fact
that when you watched him on TV, he had the ability to keep you on
fire. It was what you wanted to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``People's Century'' has a flaw, it is the dryness of its
delivery. Both John Forsythe and Alfre Woodard, who alternated as
narrators for all 26 PBS installments _ 13 last year, 13 this year
_ don't exactly make the subject matter come alive. Instead, they
give it the measured, understated approach that lets the topics
speak for themselves, underscoring the promise of executive
producer Zvi Dor-Ner, who allowed ``no pundits, no academics'' to
appear on camera.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the people who lived the history, such as Fidel
Castro in a rare glimpse of him speaking English, are what will
keep ``People's Century'' alive for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   People's Century. The 11th and 12th installments in the second
season of PBS's retrospective on the 20th century look at different
yet oddly similar ways of fomenting revolution. Monday at 9 p.m.
Repeats July 2, 1 a.m. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
