<SLUG> BC-ULSTER-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE INFORMANT CHARGED IN BELFAST LAWYER'S KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ A former British soldier who worked as an undercover
agent for the police in Northern Ireland was charged Thursday with
killing a Belfast lawyer who represented IRA suspects in one of the
most contentious murders here in the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   William Stobie, 48, stunned a courtroom here when he declared
his innocence, saying he had worked from 1987 to 1990 as an
informant for the Royal Ulster Constabulary, during which the
lawyer, Patrick Finucane, was shot dead in his West Belfast home as
he ate dinner with his wife and children in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   A group of English police detectives called in this year to
investigate Finucane's murder and this year's killing of another
lawyer who represented IRA suspects say Stobie supplied the gun
that was used in Finucane's murder and say he knows more than he is
telling about who did it. They say Stobie was in charge of
supplying weapons to the assassins of the Ulster Freedom Fighters,
a loyalist paramilitary group of Protestant extremists.
</P>
<P>
   Stobie is arrested at a sensitive time in Northern Ireland, when
the peace process is stalled over the fate of IRA weaponry. The
Ulster Unionists, who represent middle-class Protestants, refuse to
form a local government with Sinn Fein, whose voters support the
IRA, unless the IRA begins to disarm. Sinn Fein says there is
nothing in the Good Friday Agreement of 1998 that links IRA
disarming to their participation.
</P>
<P>
   A British government commission headed by Chris Patten, the last
British governor of Hong Kong, is about to recommend how to reform
the Royal Ulster Constabulary, or RUC. The allegations will aid the
argument by Irish Catholic nationalists that the police force,
which is 93 percent Protestant, must be fundamentally reformed.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mageean, a legal officer for the Committee for the
Administration of Justice, Northern Ireland's leading civil
liberties group, said Thursday's revelations were the most damning
in years of claims that the RUC colluded with loyalist paramilitary
groups in targeting suspected IRA members and sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   Mageean said the arrest of Stobie called into question the RUC's
earlier contention that it had nothing to do with Finucane's murder
after the Ulster Freedom Fighters chief intelligence officer, Brian
Nelson, admitted that he had set Finucane up to be killed.
</P>
<P>
   The RUC had claimed that Nelson was working as an informant for
the British Army, and that it had not been aware of a plan to kill
Finucane.
</P>
<P>
   But Stobie's claims contradict the RUC, suggesting that the
police were complicit in the plan to murder Finucane, a claim the
Finucane family has made for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Mageean said it was now a matter of public record that the
British government had on its payroll Nelson, the Ulster Freedom
Fighters chief intelligence officer, who targeted Catholic
nationalists for murder, and Stobie, the man who supplied hitmen
with weapons to carry out all such assassinations in the part of
Belfast where Finucance was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state controlled the man who targeted people for
assassination in the whole of Northern Ireland, and the man who
supplied guns in West Belfast, how was the (Ulster Freedom
Fighters) allowed to kill anyone during that period?'' Mageean
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Stobie's attorney, Joe Rice, told Judge John Cleary that Stobie
had been charged with firearms offenses in 1991, but that the
police had provided no evidence and he was found not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Mageean said those circumstances were highly unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a public explanation of what happened in
this case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stobie said he wanted ``to tell the truth'' about what happened
during his employment as an agent of the British government. He was
taken into custody without bail after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest raises new questions about the murder this year of
Rosemary Nelson, who like Finucane was a lawyer who represented IRA
suspects and who was killed by loyalist assassins in similar
circumstances. The RUC's chief constable, Ronnie Flanagan, allowed
the investigation into Nelson's murder to be transferred from his
detectives to a team headed by London's Metropolitan Police deputy
chief John Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who took Finucane's murder as well as Nelson's into his
responsibility, has made progress quickly where the RUC had not.
Within two months of his appointment, Stevens found evidence that
the RUC was not able or willing to bring forth, showing a RUC
informant had been involved in Finucane's murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
