<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-RETRAINING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSES PUT OLDER WORKERS IN TOUCH WITH COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATHAM, N.Y. _ Jane Willey tried to negotiate 54-year-old
fingers around an ovoid plastic lump and to learn the function of
the mouse and other foreign-sounding items on the first day of
computer training class.
</P>
<P>
   During Introduction to Windows '98 at IKON Office Solutions, the
trainer, Mary Carrier, 33, helped guide Willey's right hand to
double-click on an icon to change the computer's screen saver.
</P>
<P>
   Before the midmorning coffee break, Carrier tried to break the
ice with tentative, fearful older students by teaching them how to
play solitaire on their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Willey, of Schenectady, who was laid off in April after 14 years
as an administrative assistant at an insurance company, never
expected to have to learn new technology in middle age. Or to be a
student taking instructions from a teacher two decades her junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm old enough to be her mother,'' Willey said of Carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Around New York's Capital Region, in antiseptic, air-conditioned
computer training classrooms, humming with the white noise of
pentium processors, a quiet revolution is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   The generational tables have been turned across this retraining
landscape. People in their 40s and 50s have become the students
(``career changers'') and technological whiz kids in their 20s and
30s are their teachers (``trainers'').
</P>
<P>
   The trend has been fueled by the fallout of downsizing and plant
closings as well as a workplace increasingly reliant on workers
with computer expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients talk about the age factor all the time,'' said
Marilyn Itovitch, executive director of The Northeast New York
Alliance for Business, a nonprofit organization in Albany that
coordinates computer training and other services for people over 50
who have been laid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of fear, apprehension and self-esteem issues
hooked into this,'' Itovitch said. ``We try to address the age
factor right away and to reassure them that they're taking classes
because they need a new skill. Being older shouldn't be an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Itovitch's clients have quadrupled in the past five years and
now number more than 100. Although precise statistics are not
available for the trend, anecdotal evidence from companies that
provide computer retraining for career changers suggest that the
numbers are surging.
</P>
<P>
   The generational shift has been accompanied by a struggle on
both sides of the teacher's desk to examine and adapt attitudes
surrounding age, knowledge and authority.
</P>
<P>
   Carrier, a trainer at IKON for the past three years, said she
draws upon her master's degree in adult education as much as her
computer knowledge in working with older students who are out of
work and realize they need to upgrade their technology skills to be
competitive in today's job market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a unique learning style no matter what their age
is,'' Carrier said. ``The older students often feel intimidated,
and I try to recognize their fears and make sure I go slowly and
explain everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge is finding a common language,'' said
another IKON trainer, Eric Halse, 27.
</P>
<P>
   Halse said his students invariably stumble over what he at first
thought were simple instructions. When he says, ``Press any key,''
Halse often gets blank looks as his middle-aged career changers
search in vain for an ``NE'' key.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer technology is full of lingo and it's a young
terminology, so I try to find analogies and examples that my older
students can relate to,'' Halse said. ``If you can get an older
student over their fear, they'll do fine.''
</P>
<P>
   At Computer Visions, a Colonie computer training firm, general
manager Pamela Smith searches for trainers in their 30s and 40s
with empathy to go with the technical side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older students respond better to mature trainers with more
life experience,'' Smith said. ``Trainers need to realize that
these older students are going through a very difficult life
transition and they're not thrilled to have to retrain to begin
with.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of clients at such training centers is surging. At
IKON, 15 classrooms are filled weekdays, nights and Saturdays with
more than 700 students. In 1992, IKON had just two classrooms and
20 students. It's already outgrown a new 25,000-square-foot
building near Albany International Airport, with an addition built
last fall and another anticipated, Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer technology training isn't cheap. Cynthia Gilchrist,
director of employment training with the Albany-Colonie Regional
Chamber of Commerce, estimated it typically costs between $5,000
and $12,000 for six months to one year of training, followed by a
certification test. Dislocated workers or those unemployed for more
than 15 weeks qualify for federal retraining funds, Gilchrist said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
