<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-SINGING-PRIEST     06-24 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-SINGING-PRIEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGING PRIEST ATTRACTS FOLLOWERS AND CRITICS IN BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Rossi is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ His debut CD has sold more than 3 million
copies, and when he takes the stage here, supported by a four-piece
electric band and two backup singers, thousands of his admirers
greet him with roars and applause. But Marcelo Rossi is not a pop
music idol: He is a Roman Catholic priest.
</P>
<P>
   At 32, Padre Marcelo, as the faithful here call him, has emerged
as the driving force and main symbol of the Charismatic Renovation
movement that is transforming the face of Catholicism in the
world's most populous Roman Catholic nation.
</P>
<P>
   Barely five years removed from the seminary, he has gone from
simple parish priest to Brazil's king of all media by ``adapting
the eternal message of the church to new methods of
communication,'' as he put it.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the five Masses he celebrates each week here at the
Sanctuary of the Byzantine Rosary, a warehouse rented from a glass
factory, Rossi has a daily hourlong radio program that is broadcast
by 95 stations to every corner of this nation of 165 million
people. He also has his own daily TV program and is one of the most
sought-after guests on Sunday television variety programs because
his appearance automatically drives ratings up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel such an inner peace whenever I listen to him talk, so I
never miss a chance to see him or hear him,'' said Sebastiana
Pereira de Souza, 46, a fruit vendor, who says she has also bought
several copies of Rossi's record to give to friends. ``He transmits
the word of God with such tenderness, like an angel who has
descended among us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more than other Latin American countries, Brazil
has a long tradition of popular religiosity focused on charismatic
figures. The novelist Mario Vargas Llosa wrote about one such
leader, the 19th-century prophet Antonio Conselheiro, in ``The War
of the End of the World,'' and folk cults have grown up more
recently around Padre Cicero Romao and Frei Damiao, priests who
served in the same arid and impoverished northeastern part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Rossi may be another expression of that tendency, but he
``speaks to a very different audience in a very different way,''
said Ralph della Cava, an expert on religion in Brazil who teaches
at Queens College in New York. ``He addresses a largely urban
audience of young people in a world permeated by secular values,
proposing a set of alternative values through the medium that has
always been the most important in Brazil, the popular music of the
day.''
</P>
<P>
   His emergence is also notable because of where it occurs. Under
Cardinal Paulo Evaristo Arns in the 1970s and '80s, the Catholic
Church here in Brazil's largest city was a stronghold of liberation
theology, a blend of Catholic and Marxist doctrine that Pope John
Paul II has sought to discourage.
</P>
<P>
   During those stormy times, Rossi was ``a typical teen-ager, who
dated, played guitar and was not all that interested in church,''
his mother, Vilma, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   After serving a year in the Brazilian army, he became an
instructor at an exercise academy here, spending much of his
income, he said, on body-building supplements and equipment
intended to bulk up his 6-foot-4 athlete's frame.
</P>
<P>
   But after a favorite cousin died in a car accident and an aunt
was told she had cancer, both on the same day, he was plunged into
a spiritual crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that pain that led me back to the church,'' he said,
``and once I came back I fell in love with Catholicism and my faith
grew and grew,'' fed by his admiration for Pope John Paul II, ``who
had been an actor and athlete as a young man, full of strength and
vigor.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, traces of Rossi's days in the gym can be detected in
the way he celebrates Mass. As he sings rock-flavored tunes like
``Angels of God'' and ``I Breathe,'' he waves his arms and and
kneels and jumps about with an energy and fervor that recall James
Brown in his prime, inviting the faithful to do the same, and
afterward, he often leads the congregation in a session of what he
calls ``the Lord's aerobics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, the music you heard in church was enough to put you to
sleep,'' said Antonio Carlos de Oliveira, 57, an automobile worker
who attends three of Rossi's services each week. ``But not now. The
prayers are songs, so you feel better and you are also
participating. It's good for your health and good for your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   As his popularity and influence have grown, though, Rossi has
also drawn detractors. Fundamentalist Protestant ministers, who
have made significant inroads in Brazil in recent years, complain
vociferously that he has copied their preaching style and even
their musical repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Liberation theology advocates within the Roman Catholic Church
here have criticized him, too, though mostly indirectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eucharist is not a show,'' Monsignor Pedro Casaldaliga,
the combatively progressive bishop of Sao Felix do Araguaia in the
Amazon, said when asked about Rossi's approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``What frightens me is to see a pop star priest,'' Frei Betto,
one of the leading theoreticians of liberation theology, wrote in a
recent essay addressed to Rossi. He added that, rather than
appearing on television, ``I prefer to appear among the excluded,
on the periphery, among the landless and homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossi said that though ``I had an initial prejudice against
liberation theology that was very strong,'' that is no longer the
case. ``Now I understand how important a role Dom Paulo played in
resisting censorship and how many people's lives he saved'' with
his human rights work during the military dictatorship that ruled
Brazil from 1964 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rossi maintained, over the years liberation theology has
led to ``a certain exaggeration of the social pastoral at the
expense of the Mass.'' And while ``the church has to give
preference to the poor, that must be done without excluding
others,'' he added. ``We need to seek an equilibrium.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a more traditionalist faction within the church
that, as Della Cava put it, sees Rossi's approach as ``not
intellectual enough, as fun-and-games, short-cut Christianity that
panders to popular opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   When a ``surfing priest,'' clearly emulating Rossi, started to
become popular in Rio de Janeiro and also recorded a CD, the
conservative hierarchy there quickly squelched his activities.
</P>
<P>
   To those conservative critics, Rossi replies that what he is
doing is merely using music to glorify the word of God, just as his
predecessors did centuries ago with Gregorian chants. And with a
grin, he buttresses his position with a citation from St.
Augustine: ``He who sings prays twice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
