u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     06-24 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOAST TO BUD COLLINS AT AWARD TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Today we pause to toast one of our own. The great Bud
Collins Thursday was presented the Red Smith Award at the annual
Associated Press Sports Editors convention and yours truly has the
delightful task of writing about Bud.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us who get into this business do it because it's fun and
nobody has more fun on the job than Bud Collins. I only wish all of
you could spend just one evening in his joyous presence.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great things about the Globe sports department is its
roster of writers who've become synonymous with the sport they
cover. Peter Gammons reinvented the way baseball was covered over
the last three decades, Fran Rosa wrote his way into the Hockey
Hall of Fame, Will McDonough is the top football expert in the
country, and Bob Ryan is rightfully known as ``Commissioner'' in
basketball circles.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there's Bud Collins _ the last word on
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Bud wrote the tennis encyclopdedia. Literally. He knows all the
players and they know him. I shall never forget the sight of Chris
Evert, walking off center court after losing a Wimbledon final to
Martina Navratilova, and greeting a microphone-wielding Collins, on
live television, with, ``Nice pants, Bud.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning moment. Here was one of the game's greatest
players, moments after an extremely difficult and celebrated
defeat, and the first thing out of her mouth is . . . ``Nice pants,
Bud.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud always had a way with the players. Only Bud could salute
each player in his or her native tongue, and finish the interview
with ``well done,'' in English, Spanish, Czech, or Romanian.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Globe sports editors Jerry Nason, Ernie Roberts,
Dave Smith, Vince Doria, and Don Skwar have sent Bud around the
world to cover the racquet circuit. Many a Globe rookie assigned to
Longwood has leaned on Bud to meet the people and learn the game.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Globe newcomer, Shira Springer, wrote of Bud's
``colorful prose and pants to match.'' Nice line. Shira can only
hope someday Bud shows her around Wimbledon or the US Open. Going
to a tennis event with Bud Collins is like going to the Academy
Awards with Jack Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud knows everybody,'' says television sportscaster Lesley
Visser, who covered a dozen Wimbledons with Bud. ``When I started
covering tennis, I'd just tell players, `I work for the Globe. I
know Bud Collins.' That was my credential. And then the player
would always say, `What do you need?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to make tennis fun for the masses with crisp and
inventive writing. He is so much more than a sportswriter. He's a
historian, an ambassador, the book of knowledge for the game. I
remember so many times on deadline, there would be a line of
reporters from different countries and everyone had a question for
Bud _ `Who's the first Romanian woman to get to the semifinals?' _
and he would know.''
</P>
<P>
   Even non-tennis people know and love his work. Speaking
informally at his Florida kitchen last summer, Ted Williams
launched into a passionate pledge of allegiance to Bud:
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, that Bud Collins knows tennis. He used to write some
(expletive) about me when I played and I wasn't so sure about him,
but now I like watching the tennis on television and I've learned
so much from listening to him. You tell him, he's the best!''
</P>
<P>
   Bud wasn't always strictly a tennis guy. He covered the Red Sox
during the Impossible Dream season of 1967 and hung out with
Muhammad Ali when the champ was still Cassius Clay. He covered the
Olympics, the British Open, and went on a patrol with the US
Marines as part of an assignment during the Vietnam War. He's even
well versed in Groton-St. Mark's. And who else can say they coached
Abbie Hoffman in tennis at Brandeis? (Bud liked to say that Hoffman
played a conservative game, never rushing the net.)
</P>
<P>
   Bud wrote for the Boston Herald before joining the Globe in
1963. He became a Globe part-timer when he went to work for TV for
keeps in 1974. He gave us colorful nicknames like the Belleville
Basher (Jimmy Connors), the Bucharest Buffoon (Ilie Nastase), The
Great Whomping Crane (Pam Shriver), and most recently, Sisters
Sledgemhammer (Venus and Serena Williams). I can't wait to see what
he does with Belarus's Anna Smashnova.
</P>
<P>
   He's already in the tennis Hall of Fame. Now he joins a lofty
circle of past Smith Award winners including Jim Murray, Shirley
Povich, Edwin Pope, Dave Kindred, Dave Anderson, Jerome Holtzman,
and Red Smith himself.
</P>
<P>
   What I remember most is his willingness to help young people and
his generosity. Never a media ``star'' Bud's always happy to answer
random office phone calls with his favorite salutation, ``Globe
sporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud accepted his award via satellite from Wimbledon Thursday. He
said, ``I've always felt I was a newspaper guy,'' then added,
``Let's have fun. Let's make the deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   He always has fun. He always makes the deadline. And as always,
I can't wait to read his column from Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
