<HEADER>
A8485 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KUBRICK-RETRO25-COX     06-24 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUBRICK-RETRO25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kubrick still an enigma
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Stanley Kubrick died March 7, cinephiles
moaned, Hollywood shuddered and Harry Knowles' Web site, perhaps
the best grief index of all, turned into an impromptu counseling
center, a congested Wailing Wall of shock and disbelief expressed
in ALL CAPS and thickets of exclamation points. Knowles told
readers he felt physically sick.
</P>
<P>
   The world, meanwhile, kept spinning.
</P>
<P>
   What was there to say? By all accounts, the hermitic Kubrick was
finished with his last film, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' about which little
is known. The sexually frank drama, starring Tom Cruise and Nicole
Kidman, will be released July 16. The rest is innuendo and wishful
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is the great director's first film in 12
years. He made five films in the past three decades, and they,
along with four of his earlier works, will enjoy a special,
``Kubrick-approved'' release Tuesday on video and DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the Bronx in 1928, Kubrick moved to the English
countryside in 1961, where he led an impressively reclusive
existence away from Hollywood, the press and the public. As with
Austinite Terrence Malick, to find a recent photograph of the
director is an otherworldly feat.
</P>
<P>
   Yet we mourn the passing of the nonpareil creator of ``Dr.
Strangelove,'' ``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' ``A Clockwork Orange''
and ``The Shining.'' And now, nearly four months since his
un-Kubrickian death (quietly in his rural England home; nothing
less than a mushroom cloud of fiery egress would've been proper),
he haunts us with the video package and the wildly anticipated
``Eyes Wide Shut,'' and this gives us pause.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick will be missed in death.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but ... he was missed in life.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick, like Malick, Salinger and Bigfoot, was a confounding
celebrity, an enigma wrapped in a pain in the behind. He was
obstinate in his obstinacy, secretive in his secrecy,
uncompromising in his uncompromising-ness. It was like he was
already dead.
</P>
<P>
   He was, they said, brilliant and cerebral, which isn't always an
asset for an artist, who's supposed to run on impulse and emotional
surprise. His films frequently feel mechanical and overcalculated.
Cold technique reins; emotion is muzzled. He was a perfectionist
toiling in an imperfect field.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, his films could be brittle things that didn't
always fare so well outside of the Kubrick hot house. Hitchcock's
work springs to mind, but rarely did Hitch sacrifice narrative flow
for his pretty pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Around the time of 1962's ``Lolita,'' Kubrick lost interest in
the simple story and, some argue, people. It was as if he found a
higher calling and shifted from moviemaker to Artist. He lavished
energy on making every frame a masterwork, with fanatical attention
to costume, art direction and lighting, and little to actors. Each
image served a purpose, and nothing was arbitrary. His epic
shooting schedules are legendary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very tenacious, independent filmmaker who followed
his own muse; there's no question about it,'' director Robert
Altman, another Hollywood outsider, recently told me. (Like most
people, Altman ``never saw him face to face. I knew him on the
telephone.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``We approached film in quite a different manner,'' Altman said.
``He was very, very precise and control-oriented, and I don't do
films that way. I can't do that kind of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Few filmmakers can.
</P>
<P>
   Even fewer can boast an oeuvre as ranging and extraordinary as
Kubrick's. He made three war movies, two noirs, two grand-scale
historical epics, two biting social-political satires, a horror
film and two kinky ones. In them, he explored themes of violence,
anomie, obsession, the macabre, hypocrisy and the tragic limits of
human intelligence. There's not a routine movie in the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   When he died, at age 70, he was hailed as a genius, a giant and,
inevitably, a god. Kubrick would savor the paradox: It took death
to make him mortal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
