<HEADER>
A8486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATRE-PHILLY25-COX     06-24 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATRE-PHILLY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finding theatre in Philadelphia, P(erforming) A(rts)
 &HT;    By Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It's no joke. The next American theatrical hub _
outside New York City _ may not be Chicago, Seattle, Washington,
D.C., San Francisco or another artistic center. Instead, new plays,
new acting careers and new energy are emanating from a city that
might surprise you _ Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A recent gathering of the American Theatre Critics Association
in the City of Brotherly Love proved that it is no longer a
theatrical stepchild of Manhattan. For more than a century, it
hosted Broadway try-outs without creating its own distinct theater
culture. Now, seething with activity, the nation's fifth-largest
entertainment market is home to more than 50 substantial theater
companies, several of them quite innovative.
</P>
<P>
   The largest group occupies one of the nation's oldest theater
buildings. Built in 1809, the Walnut Street Theatre was rescued
from destruction in the 1960s. It underwent some disastrous
renovations this century, ruining some of its former intimacy, but
the Walnut Street remains drenched in history. Now its nonprofit
company presents popular seasons of mainstream plays and musicals,
attracting tens of thousands of subscribers a year. The critics saw
a finely crafted, though less than scintillating version of the
musical ``Grand Hotel,'' directed by former Houstonian Bruce
Lumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Far more noteworthy was ``Violet,'' a new musical by Jeanine
Tesori and Brian Crawley, produced by Arden Theatre Company. With
two new stages located in the touristy Old City neighborhood, this
group offers heartier material than the Walnut's. ``Violet''
certainly qualifies in this category. The story of a severely
scarred young woman crossing America on a bus, it previously
received a short off-Broadway run, but Arden reanimated it with a
mobile set and a winning cast who liberated its tuneful score.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia is committed to the musical format, as home to the
American Music Theater Festival, which has created some 70 new
musicals since 1984. Its latest, presented at the handsome Prince
Music Theater, is ``Somewhere Over the Rainbow, Yip Harburg's
America.'' This revue, construed from Tin Pan Alley lyricist
Harburg's 550 songs, including standards from ``The Wizard of Oz,''
was still previewing when critics saw it. It needs some work. (It
was startling to see Marsh Hanson as one of the show's five
singers. Hanson played Tony in Austin Musical Theatre's ``West Side
Story'' last season.)
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think Philadelphia is only about musicals _ it also
anchors two musical touring houses, the fabulous Academy of Music
opera house and another, under-construction regional performing
arts center _ there are substantial companies that excel at dramas
and comedies. The Philadelphia Theatre Company has been winning
laurels for its contemporary plays, many of them premieres, for
years. Performing in the dusty, but delightful old Plays and
Players Theatre, the company produced a well-synchronized version
of the Martin McDonaugh hit ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane.'' An
unforgiving comedy/drama about an Irish mother and daughter waging
domestic war, it fell just short of being quite nasty enough, but
nonetheless swept us into its psychological vortex.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilma Theater performs in a new, no-nonsense space on Broad
Street, downtown's central axis that has been dubbed Avenue of the
Arts by the current municipal administration. ($450 million is
pouring into new arts spaces under way, on or near this spruced-up
avenue.) Its version of Tennessee Williams' ``Orpheus Descending''
vaguely recalled the Peter Hall production seen on Broadway almost
a decade ago, but it was still impressive in its acting firepower.
I'm confident we'll hear more from this company, which finds
inspiration in cross-cultural dramatic literature.
</P>
<P>
   Located in suburban Malvern, the People's Light &AMP; Theatre
Company splits its season between two stages, both enclosed in a
gorgeous garden setting. While some critics saw a revival of a
Feydeau farce, I was more interested in Russell Davis' strange
drama, ``Sally's Gone, She Left Her Name.'' A muffled,
psychological journey into a middle-class family's breakdown, it
turned into several hours of quiet tedium. Nonetheless, it was
gratifying to see such artistic ambition far from the city's core.
</P>
<P>
   The play most favored by critics was Israel Horovitz's
``Lebensraum,'' a fantasy about the return of Jews to a future
Germany. Superbly acted by a three-actor cast playing dozens of
characters, this comedy is a bold act of imagination, staged by the
small but well-regarded InterAct Theatre Company. Part of the
National New Play Network, it is clearly in the league with
parallel Austin groups, such as Frontera (at) Hyde Park Theatre,
Salvage Vanguard Theater and Rude Mechanicals.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's critics, who have visited some theatrically vibrant
cities over the past few years, could not stop commenting on the
quality and quantity of theater available in Philadelphia. Clearly,
the city's conscious effort to push the arts in order to reactivate
a dreary downtown has also pushed its artists into new territory.
In the back of my mind, I kept thinking, ``If it could happen in
Philadelphia, it could happen anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
