u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GORI-BOS &LR;      06-24 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GORI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE A SURPRISE, GORI SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUPEN FOFARIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It's not that he's unhappy with the deal. Mario Gori
just doesn't understand it.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Argentine defender who was traded to the Miami
Fusion six months ago after three years with D.C. United was traded
again. This time, Gori was dealt to the Revolution for midfielder
Edwin Gorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' said Gori, who learned about the deal
from Miami coach Ivo Wortmann. ``I said to him, `You're kidding,
right?' I mean, I was starting there and everything was great. I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Gori has nothing in particular against coming to New England, he
just isn't thrilled about moving again. He had no clue how he would
explain it to his family, which includes his wife, 1-year-old son,
and his parents (who flew to Miami nine days ago from Argentina to
visit for a month).
</P>
<P>
   When he played in Argentina's First Division, he didn't have to
deal with trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``(D.C. United) told me a month before,'' Gori said. ``They said
this is a good move for you _ new experience with a new team, a
young team. So I said, `OK, no problem.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was starting in Miami, and now this happened. So now I
will play 100 percent for New England. Against D.C., against Miami,
against everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The best gift Gori ever received was his first pair of soccer
cleats, which his parents gave him when he was growing up in
Rosario, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   He used to play soccer all day on any open field he could find.
And it was on those fields that Gori learned to kick the ball, get
past a defender and score a goal, check an opponent and clear the
ball. It was on those fields that he learned to play _ and love _
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   One thing he didn't learn about on those fields was trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MLS is different than other leagues (because they) trade
in the middle of the season,'' said Gori. ``I think it's bad for
the player. But we work for the MLS.''
</P>
<P>
   Gori said he won't let the fact that he has been traded twice
this year get to him. He doesn't play so any one team will like
him. He plays because he loves to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play hard,'' said Gori, who is known for his aggressive
style. ``I don't like to play dirty, I like to play hard. I play a
very intense 90 minutes, and I love to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we can play great, sometimes we can play a bad game.
But the more important thing is play with the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Swapping the 36-year-old Gorter for 26-year-old Gori adds youth
to the Revolution, and it also adds some championship experience.
Gori was a starter on the 1996 United team that won the inaugural
MLS title. He was hampered by injuries the last two seasons _ a
torn ACL in his right knee in 1997 and knee and shoulder troubles
in '98.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
