<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8488 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRIMINAL-ASSETS-HNS &LR;      06-24 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIMINAL-ASSETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL TO CURB GOVERNMENT SEIZURES OF PRIVATE PROPERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an unusual show of bipartisan cooperation, the
House voted 375-48 Thursday to make it harder for the federal
government to seize private property from people without filing
criminal charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's chief sponsor, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said the
legislation is needed to remedy what he saw as an ``oppressive
instrument'' used to abuse the rights of innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill puts civil liberties and due process back into our
judicial system,'' Hyde said during a floor debate on the measure.
</P>
<P>
   It would dramatically overhaul the nation's civil forfeiture
laws, which allow federal agents to seize the assets of suspects
without a hearing, a trial or even an arrest _ and often allow the
government to keep the assets after suspects are acquitted or their
cases are dropped without an arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, civil forfeiture laws require defendants to prove
at their own expense that their property was never linked to any
criminal activity if they want to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming majority of seized properties are associated
with drug cases.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the laws contend that hundreds of innocent people
have been victimized by overzealous federal and state law
enforcers, who view seizing money and property as a way to stop
drug dealers _ and to fortify their budgets. Hyde pointed out that
in most cases, the assets seized go directly to the state or local
agency that made the bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be like traffic cops got half of every ticket they wrote
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Justice Department officials, in the past
decade the federal government has averaged $500 million a year in
seizures, mostly in cash, but also in property such as cars, boats
and planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can take your home, your farm, your car, most anything
you own without even proving that you have broken the law,'' said
Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., who said 80 percent of those whose
property is seized are never charged.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's fate in the Senate remained unclear. No similar
measure has been offered there, but a spokeswoman for Judiciary
Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said he is looking at introducing a
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Among the incidents cited as reasons to change the law were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Apfelbaum, a salesman from Sunshine, Fla., flying to
Las Vegas in 1992 with $9,640 in cash to use for gambling, was
stopped during a layover at the Dallas-Fort Worth Airport by Drug
Enforcement Agency officials who were suspicious of his one-way
ticket. They asked to search his bag, and he agreed. They seized
his money, concluding that such a large sum of cash must be related
to illegal drug activity. But Apfelbaum was not detained or charged
with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, he tried to retrieve his money, posting the
required 10 percent bond and spending $2,000 in attorney's fees. In
the end, Apfelbaum gave up, saying, ``I'm not in a position to
spend $10,000 in legal fees trying to get $9,000 back.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A Los Angeles man, Hosep Bajakajian, traveling to Syria in
1994 had to go to the Supreme Court to get back $357,144 seized by
customs officials. The cash was not tied to any crime and it would
have been legal to take it out of the country if Bajakajian had
alerted authorities that he was carrying more than $10,000. Noting
the maximum criminal penalty for the offense was $5,000, the high
court overturned the seizure in 1998 for being ``grossly
disproportionate'' to Bajakajian's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's bill has drawn support from unusual array of ideological
opposites. In the House Judiciary Committee, it was sponsored by
many of the main combatants in the impeachment fight including the
ranking Democrat, John Conyers Jr. of Michigan, staunch
conservative Bob Barr Jr., R-Ga., and outspoken liberal Barney
Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill has been backed by such disparate
organizations as the American Civil Liberties Union and the
National Rifle Association, as well as groups of bankers, lawyers,
realtors, developers, boat owners and anti-tax activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you only see this kind of coalition about every 10
years,'' Conyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's bill would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Require the government to prove that the property seized was
part of a criminal act. Under the existing procedure, the property
owners must prove that it was not used in a crime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Raise the standard of proof to one of ``clear and convincing
evidence'' that the property was linked to a crime. Now the
government needs to show only ``probable cause'' to seize suspect
property.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow federal judges to order disputed property released to
the owner pending final disposition of the case in instances where
the owner can show that loss of the property would create a
``substantial hardship.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Remove a current requirement that an owner post a bond equal
to 10 percent of the property's value in order to get a hearing to
challenge the government's claim.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enable judges to appoint an attorney for property owners who
cannot afford the cost of pressing claims for return of their
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow a property owner to sue the government for any damage or
destruction of the seized property while in its possession.
</P>
<P>
   _ Award interest to a property owner who succeeds in getting any
seized money back.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and many national law enforcement groups
have fought hard to kill or weaken the Hyde bill.
</P>
<P>
   Department spokesman Myron Marlin said Thursday that civil
forfeiture laws are an ``incredibly effective tool'' for
authorities to deprive criminals of the assets they need. But he
added that the department is open to working with Congress on a
bill.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
