u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     06-24 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: `NO WONDER HE'S NO. 1' 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harrison, N.Y. _ On the 565-yard par-5 fifth hole at the
Westchester Country Club, David Duval's drive seemed to be soaring
toward a landing strip somewhere in New Rochelle before it hopped
to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you look where Duval is!'' a voice in the gallery sighed.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval's little white ball, about a clublength short of the
tangled rough that crosses the fairway, was 325 downhill yards from
the tee and 240 downhill yards to the green. He took a 3-iron, then
switched to a 2-iron that he drilled into the middle of the green,
about 20 feet from the cup. Two-putt birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``No wonder he's No. 1,'' another voice said.
</P>
<P>
   Through eight holes in Thursday's opening round of the Buick
Classic, Duval had not played like the No. 1 golfer in the world
rankings. After starting on the 10th hole, wandering drives had
cost him a double-bogey at the 15th and a bogey at the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied the long 18th and the third, then flubbed a chip shot
from behind the fourth green the way a duffer would, but holed a
12-foot putt from the fringe to save par. With another birdie at
the uphill 505-yard ninth, he finished at one-under-par 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not where you wanted to be?'' somebody suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I am,'' Duval, his wraparound sunglasses now atop
his blue cap, was saying outside the scorer's trailer. ``I can't be
concerned with where I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And as much as anything else, maybe that's why he's No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval is concerned with reality, not with the translucent
title of being No. 1 in the world ranking. He doesn't wave his
right index finger. No golfer ever has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being No. 1 is not the biggest deal,'' he said. ``Winning golf
tournaments is more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially major golf tournaments, none of which Duval has yet
won. His next opportunity will be the British Open, starting July
15 at Carnoustie where he played in the 1995 Scottish Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to remember it was pretty tranquil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnoustie might not be tranquil this time. With wind and rain,
it could be more difficult than Pinehurst No. 2 was at last week's
U.S. Open when Duval, only a shot off Payne Stewart's lead after
the third hole in Sunday's final round, finished with a 5-over-par
75 and 287, tied for seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Pinehurst,'' he said, ``the difference between playing
really good and good was eight shots.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the exact difference between his 3-under-par 67 that
shared the first round lead and his last two rounds of 75-75 on
Pinehurst No. 2's turtleback greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I told the Mets,'' he said, ``it was like trying to
hit a 6-iron onto the pitcher's mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval threw out the first ball at Shea Stadium on Tuesday night
after taking batting practice with three other touring pros _ Bob
Tway, Mike Hulbert and Doug Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``No homers,'' he said, ``but I one-hopped one into the Bud Lite
sign in left field.''
</P>
<P>
   He batted righthanded, the way he plays golf, but sometimes he's
lefthanded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amphibious,'' he said, smiling. ``I shoot a rifle
lefthanded. I shoot pool lefthanded. I play ping-pong with either
hand. If I played hockey, I'd probably shoot righthanded. Sometimes
I fool around hitting golf balls lefthanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for next week's Canadian Skins Game, the Buick Classic
will be Duval's last tournament until the British Open. In other
years here he tied for eighth in 1995, missed the cut in 1996, and
tied for 27th in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful up here,'' the 27-year-old Floridian said.
``When you think of New York, you don't think of it being this
beautiful this close to the city. I just love it here and I love
the fans here.''
</P>
<P>
   And they love him. Standing on the edge of the practice putting
green after his round, he signed hats, golf balls and pairing
sheets for at least 10 minutes until more than 40 of those fans had
the autograph of the world's No. 1 golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider that part of our responsibility on the tour,'' he
said. ``We get paid well, and I represent Titleist and Tommy
Hilfiger. And there weren't that many people. If there's a big
crowd, you can't always sign for everybody, but today I could.''
</P>
<P>
   After he shot a record-tying 59 in winning the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic earlier this year, David Duval joked that ``I have some
things to work on'' at the practice range, but after Thursday's 70
he smiled and said, ``I'm just going to work on some lunch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
