<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITOR-BAZAAR-NYT &LR;      06-24 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITOR-BAZAAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 THE NEXT EDITOR OF HARPER'S BAZAAR COMES FROM RIVAL VOGUE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After months of white hot speculation in the
notoriously gossipy magazine world, Cathleen P. Black, the
president of Hearst Magazines, has plucked the next editor in chief
of Harper's Bazaar from the ranks of an archrival.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Betts, the fashion news director at Conde Nast's Vogue
and considered the heir apparent to Anna Wintour, resigned her post
Friday and will take over as editor in chief of Harper's Bazaar on
Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Betts, who is nine months pregnant _ she was due to deliver
her baby Friday _ will take a two-month leave before officially
assuming her new responsibilities as the replacement for the late
Elizabath Tilberis, who remade the magazine into a sleek, modern
magazine with an emphasis on dramatic design and fashion
photography. Ms. Betts' first full issue will be the December
issue, and will appear on newsstands in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Betts, who has worked with Ms. Wintour for the last eight
years, was previously an editor for the Fairchild Publications unit
of the Walt Disney Co., writing about fashion from Paris for W and
Women's Wear Daily.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Betts, who is 35, takes over as Harper's Bazaar has
struggled a bit in the face of flat fashion advertising and the
rise of lifestyle magazines that focus less on fashion. While Ms.
Betts has directed most of her energies toward covering the fashion
industry, her vision for the magazine, she said, includes a set of
plans to focus on features and life-style articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal will be to extend the focus of the magazine by
establishing it as the style source for readers,'' she said,
``adding fashionable people and writers with engaging voices to the
very modern mix of fashion, design and photography that Bazaar has
come to represent in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``American women are definitely interested in fashion. But
fashion is happening in places not necessarily on the runway. I
hope to bring that mix of fashion and features to Bazaar, exploring
the lifestyle connection to fashion, and the Hollywood connection,
which is where a lot of exciting thigns are happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Black said that the selection of Ms. Betts was ``not just
about clothes. Kate is a very contemporary woman, and can relate to
women between the ages of 30 to 45 and how they are thinking about
their lives.'' She said: ``Her view extends into the home, into
arts and entertainment, and every other aspect of our 21st century
life styles.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogue leads the four major fashion magazines, with an average
circulation of 1.2 million and in 1998, a total of 2,681 ad pages.
according to the Publishers Information Bureau. Harper's Bazaar's
circulation is 732,572 _ third behind Elle, which is published by
Hachette-Filipacchi Magazines, a unit of Lagardere Group _ and the
fourth, behind W, in advertising. Last year it carried a total of
1,542 ad pages.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Hearst has raided the Conde Nast
cabinet _ or tapped a protegee of Ms. Wintour's _ for the position
of Harper's Bazaar editor. Ms. Tilberis was editor in chief of the
British edition of Vogue when she took over Harper's Bazaar, and
had previously worked for Ms. Wintour at British Vogue as fashion
director. Ms. Black at Hearst said she did not choose Ms. Betts to
weaken Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our industry, we go for talent,'' Ms. Black said. ``It
didn't matter if Kate had worked at Women's Wear Daily. This was
about finding an incredibly talented and creative editor to take
Harper's Bazaar to new heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Betts has long been considered a rising editor at Conde
Nast, a unit of Advance Publications. A graduate of Princeton, she
has written extensively for Vogue, often about popular culture, and
directed much of the magazine's fashion coverage.
</P>
<P>
   About losing her second in command to the competition, Ms.
Wintour said: ``Kate is a good friend of mine. She's a terrific
girl and I could not be more pleased for her. Competition is a good
thing. It's a healthy thing. It's good for the magazine. It keeps
you on your toes. So I look at that as a very positive thing.''
</P>
<P>
   One concern of advertisers had been that Ms. Betts would not be
able to take the reins early enough to woo advertisers for the
September issue. Ms. Black said that Ms. Tilberis, the magazine's
editor in chief who died of ovarian cancer in April, had planned
issues far in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liz had really done a lot of work on the early fall issues,''
she said. ``September is basically done. We will involve Kate in
top editorial decisions, but she obviously can't be involved in
every page that goes into the October issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Betts is married to Chip Brown, a magazine writer and author
who has written for many magazines, including Vanity Fair, Conde
Nast Traveler, the New Yorker, Esquire and Harper's Bazaar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
