<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-ALTAVISTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ, CMGI SAY THEY'RE TALKING ALTAVISTA DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. and Internet firm CMGI Inc. made it
official Thursday, saying they are discussing a deal that would
give CMGI partial or total control of Compaq's AltaVista Internet
search engine.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement confirmed rumors that have circulated in
financial markets throughout the week. Both companies refused to
provide details of the negotiations and stressed that a deal may
not be consummated.
</P>
<P>
   An acquisition of AltaVista would make CMGI a major investor in
two top Internet search sites. The Andover, Mass. company also owns
about 20 percent of Lycos Inc. and is rumored to be interested in
acquiring a controlling stake.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI may have a rival bidder in Atlanta-based Mindspring
Enterprises Inc. Mindspring, a major Internet service provider,
announced Thursday it is actively seeking to combine with other
Internet businesses to strengthen its competitive position.
Mindspring founder Charles Brewer has said Lycos is one of several
firms that might make a good partner.
</P>
<P>
   But if CMGI takes control of both Lycos and AltaVista, it's not
clear how well these assets would fit together. Both Lycos and
AltaVista are well-established brand names on the Internet,
attracting millions of visitors every month. And each uses its own
sophisticated technology for performing Internet searches. Lycos is
based on research done at Pittsburgh's Carnegie Mellon University,
while AltaVista was created by engineers at Digital Equipment
Corp., which Compaq purchased last year.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Bane, an Internet analyst for the Yankee Group in
Boston, thinks CMGI may be interested in buying AltaVista mainly to
get at its valuable brand name, as well as its recently acquired
on-line shopping service, Shopping.com. ``AltaVista could easily be
broken up for its better parts,'' Bane said.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI and Compaq say their proposed deal would include some kind
of ``strategic partnership.'' This makes sense to analyst Ullas
Naik of First Albany Corp. in Boston. ``I think it would be
essential for Compaq,'' said Naik, noting that other major computer
makers such as Dell Computer Corp. and Gateway 2000 Inc. are
setting up their own Internet services as a way to build long-term
relationships with their customers. Naik thinks any deal to spin
off AltaVista will include an arrangement to make the site the
primary Internet destination for purchasers of Compaq computers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, engineers and marketers at Lycos revealed their
roadmap for offering Internet services especially tailored to home
users with high-speed Internet connections. An initiative called
Lycos Lightning will result in the gradual rollout of new features
that take advantage of the ability to download Internet data at
millions of bits per second.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos chief content officer Mark Simmer says that for years to
come, most Internet users will rely on slow telephone modems,
rather than high-speed cable modems and the new DSL telephone
services. Therefore, Lycos won't launch a unified suite of
high-speed services. Instead, said Simmer, ``we're identifying
things that people will do today that we think will be compelling
high-speed applications.''
</P>
<P>
   Lycos has already begun to offer some of these services, such as
a special search engine designed to seek out music files recorded
in the popular MP3 format. MP3 files reproduce music with very high
fidelity, but the files are millions of bytes long and are best
downloaded over a high-speed Internet connection. Still, even
people with slow modems can use the Lycos service to locate and
download music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
