<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONG-KONG-NYT &LR;      06-24 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MOVE HAS HONG KONGWORRIED IT WILL LOSE TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mo.)  (rk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Fears about Hong Kong's future as an Asian trading
post have grown here in recent days after the U.S. Senate moved to
tighten export controls to this former British colony in response
to a congressional report on military espionage and China.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday approved legislation that would impose
more-stringent controls on the export of equipment and technology
with military uses to Hong Kong and Macao _ a Portuguese colony
that will be returned to China in December _ unless both
territories allow the United States to verify that sensitive
shipments end up in the right hands.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., grows out of
accusations in the recent congressional committee report that Hong
Kong is a staging ground for the acquisition of military technology
by China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prudence demands that if China diverts sensitive U.S.
technology, we impose on Hong Kong and Macao the same export
controls that govern sales to China itself,'' Ashcroft said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   It may be prudent for Washington. But for Hong Kong, which has
$56 billion a year in trade with the United States, it could mean
deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely serious issue,'' said Victor Fung,
chairman of the Hong Kong Trade Development Council. ``It would
affect a major area of development for us, which is moving up the
food chain into high technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many people here, Fung disputes the accusations in the
congressional report from a committee led by Rep. Christopher Cox,
R-Calif. And he is angry that some in Congress want to strip Hong
Kong of its status as an autonomous trading entity within China.
Though it reverted to Chinese sovereignty nearly two years ago,
Hong Kong polices its own borders and is a member of the World
Trade Organization. ``It is manifestly unjust not to honor Hong
Kong's status,'' Fung said. ``You don't do that to a member of the
WTO.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong plays only a minor role in the Cox report, which
asserts sweeping theft of American military technology by China.
But it does come in for criticism as a teeming bazaar in which
sensitive technology imports can be diverted to the mainland. The
report asserts that a ``sizable number of Hong Kong enterprises''
are fronts for the People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The army maintains a garrison here and regularly moves equipment
to and from mainland China. The report says Hong Kong is not
allowed to inspect army vehicles crossing the border _ making them
a perfect way to smuggle goods.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Hong Kong said they had the right to inspect
Chinese army vehicles. But the procedure is cumbersome: Customs
authorities must call the garrison if they suspect an illegal
shipment. The garrison then sends soldiers to conduct the
inspection under the scrutiny of customs officers. Hong Kong
concedes it has not inspected a single army vehicle since the
handover.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, we've had no grounds to suspect a breach of Hong Kong
laws,'' said Yvonne Choi, Hong Kong's acting secretary for Trade
and Industry. ``But that doesn't mean it won't happen in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's Security Bureau is investigating a report published
in a Chinese-language newspaper here that an army truck recently
entered the enclave without making a full declaration of its cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Choi declined to comment on the incident. But she said Hong
Kong had an exemplary record of policing exports and imports. She
argued that the examples cited in the Cox report _ including one in
which parts for an air-to-air missile were found on a commercial
flight arriving in Hong Kong _ illustrated the vigilance, not the
laxity, of local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider it unfair to treat our successful enforcement
actions as a cause for concern,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's government plans a lobbying campaign to try to
persuade lawmakers in the United States that its customs standards
are adequate, and that Congress should not change Hong Kong's
trading status. Officials recently invited Cox to visit Hong Kong
to judge its controls for himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill must go before the House of Representatives
before it becomes law. But with feelings against China running high
on Capitol Hill, officials here said they were taking no chances.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong may find an ally in the Clinton administration.
Richard A. Boucher, the U.S. consul general, praised the
territory's security in a speech here on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
