<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8499 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWYORKCHEAP25-COX     06-24 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYORKCHEAP25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    See the Big Apple with little dough
 &HT;    By Ray Marcano
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Start spreading the news _ you can travel to New
York City and not break the bank.
</P>
<P>
   How can that be, in a city in which $300-a-night room rates,
$50-per-person dinners and $65 theater tickets aren't uncommon?
Easy. Hunt for bargains and get to know Manhattan before you go,
and your trip will be a lot of fun without sending you deep in
debt.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to go and have been scared off by price, here
are a few tips.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lodging: A hotel doesn't have to cost several hundred dollars
a night. If you don't have to stay in Midtown, check out some of
the hotels just over the river in New Jersey. Secaucus, for
example, has several hotels and motels that range from $89 and up
per night (plus a 6 percent room tax). Some even offer free
continental breakfasts. Secaucus is just a few miles from midtown
Manhattan, and you can catch a bus to Midtown for $2.35 per person
each way (it's the No. 320). From there you catch the subway to any
destination in the city.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to stay in Midtown, get a hotel through
www.priceline.com on the Internet. On Priceline, you tell the
service how much you want to spend per night and the service
selects a hotel for you. Some warning: You have to give a credit
card number (although you can do that over the phone); the service
picks the hotel for you and you don't have a say in the matter;
once Priceline picks the hotel your credit card is automatically
charged and you can't get a refund _ so if the trip gets canceled,
you're stuck.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the service, for some users, is terrific. I'll be in New
York this fall, and by using Priceline I'm staying at a first-class
hotel on 51st Street and Seventh Avenue for $113 a night _ tax
included. In all, that's just $15 more than the Secaucus option
(when including bus fare, train fare), and well worth the
convenience.
</P>
<P>
   You can also use Priceline to set your own airfare, but that's
even more of a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   You have to consent to making at least one stop along the way,
and that could be anywhere. So be careful.
</P>
<P>
   _ Meals: You shouldn't spend a lot of money on food in New York.
First, avoid the hotel restaurants. You'll spend $20 on two eggs
and some toast. Instead, go to one of the many delis or grab a bite
from a street vendor. You'll get a real bagel with butter and
coffee for as little as $1. If you want something larger, eggs, a
bagel and coffee can be had for less than $3 at most delis.
</P>
<P>
   For lunch, get New York hot dogs _ again from street vendors _
for $1.50 each, loaded up with onions, relish, sauerkraut and more.
</P>
<P>
   For dinner, get a large New York pizza. There is nothing like a
fresh-made New York slice, and you can get a whole pie _ enough to
feed three easily _ for less than $12. If you want something
fancier, find a midtown deli or dinner that serves all kinds of
food for less than $10 per person. Get incredible hero sandwiches
with roast or corned beef, pastrami or other staples that are meals
in themselves, and are far superior to any chain sandwich stuff.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a sweet tooth, you're in a lot of trouble. Get a
black and white cookie _ very large, half with chocolate, half with
vanilla frosting _ for $1 to $1.25. How about an Italian ice
(cherry, lemon, other flavors) scraped out of the case for about
$1? Then there are the incredible array of danishes and pastries as
well as East Coast staples found in any deli _ Devil Dogs and Ring
Dings. At these prices, you won't have to watch your expenses, but
you will have to watch your waistline.
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting around: Seeing the sights won't cost an arm and a leg,
either. You can simply walk through any of Manhattan's incredible
areas _ Central Park, Midtown, Greenwich Village, Soho _ and admire
the shops, landmark stores and incredible architecture. For
example: You can start at 96th Street and Broadway, walk a few
blocks over to Central Park, then walk all the way down Central
Park West to 59th Street and Columbus Circle. From there, head down
Broadway to Times Square. If you're not used to walking you'll be
exhausted; if you can't make it all the way, hop on a bus for
$1.50. If walking doesn't bother you, you'll see several terrific
sights.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy a pass to see six great New York attractions,
including the Empire State Building, for $28 _ about half of what
it would normally cost. Those passes are available in Madison
Square Garden and other tourist spots.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clubbing: Entertainment can be free or nearly so, especially
during the week. Pick up a copy of The Village Voice _ it's free _
and look for clubs that charge no cover or admission. There are
several in the Village that are within walking distance of each
other. You'll have to buy drinks, so expect to pay $5 to $6 for a
beer and $6 and up for a mixed drink. But if a couple has two
drinks each, you can still have a night out for about $20, with
music, and that's not bad anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   _ Souvenirs: When on your New York walking tour you'll find
shops that have New York T-shirts, three for $10; I even found a
few that had four for $10. You can get all kinds of hats _ New York
Yankees, New York emblems, anything you'd like, two for $10.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
