<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF NEW UTILITY COMPANY CASTS EYE ON BOSTON GAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The future president of the holding company that is
taking over Boston Edison and Commonwealth Electric said Thursday
his company likes the idea of adding Boston Gas to its corporate
stable, a consolidation that could create an eastern Massachusetts
utility giant serving 2 million gas and electric customers.
</P>
<P>
   Russell D. Wright, who will be president of the new entity
NStar, approved by both utilities' owners Thursday, said of Boston
Gas parent company Eastern Enterprises: ``The Eastern system is a
very good physical fit with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the right terms and conditions, sure, we'd be
interested'' in acquiring or merging with Eastern, Wright said in
an interview, adding that ``we'd like to grow the gas business to
be equal to the electric side.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Wright, president of Commonwealth Energy System, nor
officials with Edison or Eastern would say whether any talks were
under way.
</P>
<P>
   At separate meetings Thursday, shareholders of Boston Edison
parent BEC Energy and those of Commonwealth Energy System each
voted overwhelmingly in favor of the merger to create NStar, which
would have just over 1 million electric customers and 240,000 gas
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both companies said the only possible hangup they
see for the receiving the necessary regulatory approvals is if they
have trouble meeting a July 13 deadline to sell Edison's Pilgrim
nuclear plant to a Louisiana firm, which could delay Nuclear
Regulatory Commission approval. They hope to complete the NStar
merger by mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, they face strong opposition from business and
consumer groups to a rate plan being reviewed by state regulators
that would freeze Edison and ComEnergy bills for four years and
allow the companies to recoup more than $600 million in
merger-related costs.
</P>
<P>
   NStar officials say that amount will be far exceeded by savings
on customers' bills. But critics want firmer guarantees those
savings will be passed on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Edison chairman and chief executive Thomas J.
May, who will hold the same positions at NStar, said he wanted
Edison to grow to 2 million customers by the end of 2000. That goal
has been complicated, as possible New England merger partners have
been snapped up by out-of-region utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being an obvious geographical fit with NStar, Eastern
Enterprises would be mathematically perfect. Its 750,000 gas
customers in 115 eastern Massachusetts communities _ once its
takeover of Colonial Gas is approved next month _ would bring NStar
to just over May's 2 million goal in one fell swoop. It would also
create a company, as Wright described, evenly balanced between gas
and electric.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the BEC vote, May would not comment on
whether he would like to combine with Boston Gas. ``I'm comfortable
that we have enough size and scale to achieve our customer service
goals over the next two years,'' May said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we're in a panic and looking over our shoulder
and saying, `If we don't execute that (goal of reaching 2 million
customers), we have to sell the business.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing growing speculation that NStar may be an attractive
takeover candidate, May said, ``I think probably everyone would
prefer to be independent, but you also realize you work for the
shareholders,'' whose best interest may lie in selling the company
or merging for a premium. ``We're attractive to 10 utilities,'' May
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright told ComEnergy shareholders: ``This is not the last deal.
There is likely to be further consolidation in the business,'' a
comment he later said applied to NStar as well as other New England
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   In New York Stock Exchange trading Thursday, BEC closed at 42
7/8, down 1/16. ComEnergy was up 1/4 at 43, and Eastern Enterprises
was down 1/2 at 38 3/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
