A8501 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FBI-NYT &LR;      06-24 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FBI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI BEGINS SEARCH FOR EVIDENCE TO BE USED AGAINST MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia _ FBI forensic teams began sifting through
evidence Thursday morning at two houses that are believed to be
massacre sites in hopes of helping the prosecution of Slobodan
Milosevic and other Serbian leaders charged with war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Laying out piles of shiny new equipment _ shovels, big screens
for sifting dirt and ashes and two huge electric generators _ the
FBI team went to scenes cited in the indictment brought in May by
the International Tribunal for War Crimes in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   One was the house where a survivor, Hani Hoxha, has told of the
mass killing of about 20 people, including his wife, three
daughters and grandchildren. The dead belonged to three related
families who had tried to hide in the house of one family, the
Vesas.
</P>
<P>
   The second site was a nearby house on Ymer Grezda Street, where
the indictment says six men were executed.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow police tape reading, ``Crime scene _ Do not enter,'' was
stretched on both sides of the street in front of the Vesa house.
Italian soldiers and tanks of the NATO security force kept away
journalists, who had been summoned for a news conference by the FBI
and David J. Scheffer, the State Department's ambassador at large
for war crimes issues.
</P>
<P>
   The crime scene was hardly pristine. Journalists have been going
through it for almost two weeks, and the site had been unattended
for more than two months.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the yellow tape, the FBI agents, most in standard
American camouflage uniforms with American flags on the left
sleeves, wore a variety of hats _ baseball or floppy wide-brims _
and moved in and out of the house with their gear. Most were also
equipped with dark sunglasses that they put on when they entered
their vehicles, even though it was a dank overcast day. Several
agents cradled stubby black rifles with large telescopic sights.
</P>
<P>
   Under its director, Louis Freeh, the bureau has been expanding
its overseas role. But this is the first major deployment of agents
to investigate war crimes. The contingent numbers about 60 agents
from six field offices and 95,000 pounds of equipment, including
Humvees, trucks, tents, communications gear and laboratory
equipment. Its commander is Roger Kniesly, head of the Critical
Incident Response Group in Quantico, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The team includes explosives experts, specialists in evidence
collection and forensic photographers. There are also forensic
anthropologists on loan from the Armed Forces Institute of
Pathology. Their tasks are to photograph and map crime scenes; to
analyze blood, bones, cartridges, clothing and to try to identify
bodies through DNA samples.
</P>
<P>
   But the bodies in the houses that they searched Thursday had
already been buried, according to Faton Pollushka, the municipal
official in charge of disposing bodies here, who added that there
were barely enough remains to fill one grave. There were a few
bones in the ruins of one burned structure, including a jawbone
that appeared to be that of a child.
</P>
<P>
   In April in an interview in the Albanian capital, Tirana, Hoxha
described the night when his family and friends were killed and
took this reporter's notebook to diagram the family compound, how
the killings had been carried out and where people had died. His
sketch precisely matched the layout, including a pool hall facing
the street with a charred basement in which he said people had been
killed and burned, and the now rusted-out car that they had pulled
in front of the gate in a futile hope of blocking entry.
</P>
<P>
   Believing that the Serbs were only looking for men, Hoxha
recounted, he and two other men had slipped out of a second-story
window, onto a wall, and escaped. He told how, wedged in hiding
between two buildings, he heard gunshots and cries in the night,
and how he found his family dead in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, Gani Kadriv, said in a recent interview that he,
too, had heard gunshots and the cries of women and children that
night.
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer, the war crimes specialist, said at a news conference
that the two sites that the FBI was investigating were ``only
representative'' of the Serbian massacres of Albanian civilians and
that new ``atrocity sites are popping up every day,'' found by
journalists or NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   He said the bureau's experts were conducting ``detailed forensic
work'' to ``support the indictment of the war crimes tribunal.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and other senior officials were charged with crimes
against humanity in Kosovo, including the murder, forced
deportation and persecution of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The other officials charged were Milan Milutinovic, the Serbian
president and a longtime close aide to Milosevic; Dragoljub
Ojdanic, the chief of staff of the Yugoslav armed forces and a
former commander of an army corps in eastern Bosnia; Nikola
Sainovic, the deputy prime minister of Yugoslavia, and Vlajko
Stojilkovic, the minister of internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accuses Milosevic of the persecution of Albanians
on racial, religious and political grounds and traces what it
describes as the mass execution of hundreds of them in several
towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serb army and police violated so many laws, they were a
perfect example of how not to conduct a war,'' Scheffer said. ``And
they were a perfect example of how not to withdraw. They
systematically burned, looted and destroyed evidence on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is continuing, he said, adding, ``One would
not expect the indictments issued by the tribunal to be the end of
the story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
