<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8505 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TENSIONS-0625-     06-24 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TENSIONS-0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MARINE FIREFIGHT MARKS TENSION, VIOLENCE IN KOSOVO
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZEGRA, Yugoslavia _ U.S. Marines saw the tension in their little
corner of Kosovo building. It culminated in a deadly shoot out
Wednesday, and an exodus of defeated and frightened Serbs from this
village Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The little law that governs Kosovo right now could be summed up
by Marine Gunnery Sgt. William Post, of the 3rd Marine Battalion
from Camp Lejeune, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about killing a Serb gunman, he said: ``They
shot at my people unprovoked. He shot at me. So, it's better him
than me. That's the way I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Around war-shattered Kosovo, violence continued Thursday,
despite NATO forces vowing to make the province secure and the
KLA's promises to demilitarize.
</P>
<P>
   Three Serbs were found shot to death in the Serb-run economics
department at Pristina University. NATO soldiers sealed off the
basement and were investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Going to the cause of the bitterness, NATO troops arrested a
Serb man identified by residents of the village of Solvinije as one
of the perpetrators of the massacre of 43 Kosovar Albanians there
in the horrific ethnic cleansing campaign during the 78-day NATO
air war against Yugoslavia. Witnesses also said two women were
raped before being killed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties confronting his troops trying to keep a
lid on ethnic tensions, Clark, the NATO commander, said he was
pleased so far with the alliance's operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going extremely well,'' he said. ``We're meeting
all of our objectives and milestones.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the previous 24 hours, Zegra, a southeastern Kosovo farming
village of about 4,000 with a 10 percent minority of Serbs to
ethnic Albanians, had become a microcosm of troubled Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines, behind their sandbags and M-16s, have grown used to
receiving cherries to eat and magazines to read from ethnic
Albanian children grateful that NATO has chased the Serb police and
paramilitary forces from their town. Meanwhile, they have gotten
suspicious glares from Serbs now afraid for their safety.
</P>
<P>
   With growing frequency, ethnic Albanians, who had seen their
homes burned and neighbors shot by Serbs during the NATO bombing
campaign, stepped up their revenge. On Wednesday, for instance,
Marines saw two Albanians beating a Serb paramilitary commander and
there were threats made against others.
</P>
<P>
   These smaller incidents, however, were only precursors to the
gunfight later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling something was going to happen,'' said John
Holmstrom, a Marine Corps medic from Michigan, who had treated a
Serb for a broken nose suffered in a beating.
</P>
<P>
   Around 5:20 (local time) Wednesday, a few Serbs took to the
streets with guns. They appear to have fired toward the homes of
their Albanian neighbors and then, one of them, toward the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines were in a sandbag post and the gunman was across a
bridge less than 100 yards away. According to Marine accounts, they
returned the fire and hit the man in the arm.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, about 10 other Marines made a flanking run from their
schoolhouse headquarters here, through a creek bed and around the
side of the Serbs. One group answered automatic fire coming from a
grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Gunnery Sgt. Post and a Marine translator focused on the injured
gunman, now taking refuge in a white Yugo. They ordered him to get
out and give up his weapon. Instead, he ran bleeding to a niche in
a wall and fired at them. Post shot him in the head and the Serb
died a couple hours later at the Marine base.
</P>
<P>
   The other Serbs escaped to surrounding houses. In house-to-house
searches aided by ethnic Albanians, the Marines arrested two
wounded men and a third who had not been shot.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Marines were sizing up their tenuous role as
peacekeepers against a bleak backdrop. More than 45 cars and
tractors formed a convoy carrying almost all the last Serbs out of
Zegra.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some complained that the Marines could not protect them. Others
said they were being threatened and beaten by members of the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Two Serb houses were burning. Marine Col. Kenneth Glueck
speculated that the Serbs set their own homes on fire, but that
could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is new. This is something we haven't seen before,'' said
Capt. Robert Riggle, as he watched the Serbs pull out of town as
they have in so many other areas of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus is a small defeat for NATO, which has encouraged
Serbs to remain under the protection of the Kosovo peacekeeping
force, called KFOR.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite the smiles of the ethnic Albanians, the Marines
know they must be ready to exert the only real authority in Kosovo
now, that of weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Cpl. Matthew Simmons of Missouri, one of the Marines who
shot at the Serb gunmen, said the tension didn't get to him until
after the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I thought about it a while, I was a bit shaky,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
