<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8508 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TEDESCHI-SPI &LR;      06-24 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TEDESCHI-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISING STAR TEDESCHI GETS A LITTLE HELP FROM STEVIE'S FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Susan Tedeschi's gonna be in Double Trouble when she
gets to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts-bred singer and guitarist with the red-hot
blues album ``Just Can't Burn'' is on the road with the late Stevie
Ray Vaughan's rhythm section, Double Trouble, featuring drummer
Chris Layton and bassist Tommy Shannon. Completing the band is
Tedeschi's longtime keyboardist, Tom West.
</P>
<P>
   The four musicians played in front of a live audience for the
first time last week on ``Late Night with David Letterman.''
Tedeschi, West and Double Trouble are now on the road, opening for
Keb' Mo' Saturday night in Seattle. It's only the third gig on the
foursome's current cross-country tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be fun because how many times do you get to play
with guys like that?'' Tedeschi said in a phone interview from Los
Gatos, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwell, Mass., native discovered the joys of performing in
front of a live audience before she started grade school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to be an entertainer. I love being
onstage,'' she said in a girlish voice quite unlike the big-mama
howl of her live shows.
</P>
<P>
   Tedeschi, whose mother was active in musical theater, made her
stage debut at age 4 in a local production of ``Oliver!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of being in day care, my mom would put us in shows
that she was either directing or producing or whatever,'' Tedeschi
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great because I wanted to do it anyway. I got to hang
out with other kids and it was actually better than day care
because you're accomplishing something and working toward a common
goal instead of just hanging out and not doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Tedeschi is convinced her early theatrical training helped
motivate her later in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been really motivated. I've always had ridiculous
career goals. And I've always achieved them. So I feel very lucky
to have had that experience at a young age,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old musician has sold more than 300,000 copies of
``Just Can't Burn,'' her explosive debut album. The album includes
five Tedeschi originals, as well as such tunes as John Prine's
``Angel From Montgomery,'' Junior Wells' ``Little by Little'' and
the Ruth Brown classic ``Mama, He Treats Your Daughter Mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Tedeschi won four Boston Music Awards in April and two W.C.
Handy blues awards in May. Her largest followings are in Boston,
Seattle, San Francisco, Minneapolis, Dallas/Fort Worth, Austin,
Denver, Chicago and Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Tedeschi has now jumped onto the rock charts. Last week, the
rambunctious single ``Rock Me Right'' made its debut on Billboard's
Mainstream Rock Tracks chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reaching a whole new audience of men between 25 and 45,
which is kinda cool,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tedeschi, whose parents owned many LPs while she was growing up,
recalled liking the blues when she was a small child. Her dad's
collection included music by Lightnin' Hopkins and Mississippi John
Hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably more into blues when I was 5, 6 or 7 than I was
in my teens,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up Catholic, she sang in church. Later she was drawn to
gospel music and sang at predominantly African-American Baptist and
Methodist churches.
</P>
<P>
   In her late teens, Tedeschi moved to Boston to attend the
Berklee School of Music. It was while living there that she began
discovering, through friends, some of the greatest blues albums
ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden one day when I was 22, I said, `Damn, what the
hell have I been missing out on? I've been looking for this kind of
music my whole life and it's been right there.'''
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, Tedeschi began jamming at local clubs and
polishing her singing and guitar playing.
</P>
<P>
   People often compare her to singers such as Janis Joplin, Etta
James and Bonnie Raitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't get too upset when they compare me to people
like that because I just do what I do. I don't really try to sound
like anyone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Tedeschi's fans come from many different age groups, they
seem to be getting younger and younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting the really young kids _ 3, 4, 5 and 6 years old,''
she said. ``They come with their parents. The parents are playing
the record at home and their kids are hearing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really funny because the kids know all the words.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
