<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT27-COX     06-24 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT TRIAL ENDS AS IT BEGAN, WITH GATES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Microsoft antitrust trial ended Thursday on the
same note on which it began last October _ with explosive evidence
from Microsoft chairman Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, a constant if distant presence in the courtroom
throughout the 21-week trial, was quoted in handwritten notes from
Microsoft's still-secret files as having dismissed the threat posed
to the software giant by the recent $10 billion merger between
America Online Inc. and Netscape Communications Corp., a deal in
which Sun Microsystems Inc. also plays a key role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Platform threat _ AOL doesn't have it in their genes to attack
us in the platform space,'' said Gates. ``If you want to lose sleep
tonight, worry about Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates' comments at a Dec. 14, 1998, Microsoft strategy meeting _
the rest of the document remained sealed _ seemed to contradict the
line that his lawyers had taken in the courtroom during 78 days of
often rancorous testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft was clearly engaged in a broad pattern of illegal
behavior,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney General Joel Klein told
reporters on the courthouse steps when the trial ended. ``They used
every trick in the monopolist's book. ... You name it, they did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In its defense, the software giant, which stands at the apex of
booming high-tech industry, argued that its dominant Windows
operating system could fall prey at any time to dynamic industry
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing minutes of the trial. Microsoft lawyer Michael
Lacovara dramatically produced what was to become the final item of
more than 2,000 defense exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   It was an MSNBC news story, broadcast within the hour, reporting
that AOL, the nation's leading Internet access provider, is in
talks with Microworkz(cq) Inc., a maker of low-cost computers, to
produce an AOL-branded PC dedicated to running a Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who has presided
over the landmark case without a jury, thereupon called it a day.
``It has been almost a pleasure,'' Jackson said. ``Let's keep it
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unexpected settlement, Jackson is unlikely to issue
his verdict before the end of the year. A lengthy appeals process
could keep the case winding through the federal courts for several
more years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Jackson gave Microsoft and the Justice
Department, which joined with 19 states in suing the company, until
Aug. 10 present competing ``findings of fact.'' A month later, on
Sept. 10, the two sides must submit their revised findings after
having assessed each other's submissions.
</P>
<P>
   Once those two voluminous rounds of paperwork are out of the
way, Jackson said he will hear closing arguments in his courtroom
on Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The trial's final witness, economist Richard Schmalensee of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, argued forcefully Thursday
that Microsoft has been unfairly portrayed by the government as a
hard-core monopolist that illegally wields unchecked power in the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Schmalensee, an $800-an-hour expert appearing on
Microsoft's behalf, exploded in a rage when David Boies, the
government's lead lawyer, accused him of presenting ``selective
testimony'' to shore up Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that a blanket challenge to my ethics?'' Schmalensee
declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you at least grant that you are here in part as an advocate
for a particular position?'' Boies responded.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Schmalensee had dismissed Gates's assessment of the AOL
threat to Microsoft. ``This is a judgment from someone who hasn't
seen those documents,'' the economist said.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening phase of the trial, Boies played in the courtroom
a videotaped Gates deposition in which the world's richest man
seemed so evasive that even Jackson felt bound to tell his lawyers
privately: ``I think it's evident to every spectator that, for
whatever reasons, in many respects Mr. Gates has not been
particularly responsive.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates came to Washington at least twice during the trial, but
never visited the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
