<HEADER>
A8518 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOOTHIES-AZR &LR;      06-24 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOOTHIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOOTHIES: HEALTHFUL QUALITIES DEBATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Arizona Republic &QL; 
(at)6 They fly the flag of health, sometimes right in the face of
McDonald's and Burger King, these ubiquitous juice bars that have
popped up in every strip mall from Malibu to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Their franchise player is a 24-ounce milkshake called a
smoothie, a quotidian beverage actually, consisting primarily of
fresh or freshly frozen fruits, non-fat yogurt and ice. Also on
board are the juices, both fruit and vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the heart of this business, the part that keeps the hard
core coming back for more, is the wide array of dietary
supplements, ginkgo biloba to bee pollen, that can be added to
these drinks for an additional charge.
</P>
<P>
   Are these health-food-stores-in-a-blender really as good for us
as their bright brochures proclaim?
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic visited four juice bars in the Valley,
three chains (Smoothie King, Jamba Juice, Juice Works) and one
independent (Sun Valley Smoothies), and faxed their menus to local
nutritionists for professional opinions on the true health benefits
of the juice-bar scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking at these as a healthy snack, they're fine,''
said Debra Laundau-West, a Scottsdale consulting dietitian. ``Most
of them are a good source of vitamin C. The fresh fruits are an
excellent source of fiber and antioxidants.''
</P>
<P>
   Laundau-West also praises the vegetable juices because of their
use of fresh carrots as a base.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful source of beta carotene, another
antioxidant that also provides fiber,'' she said. ``Natural beta
carotene can reduce your risk of cancer and heart disease.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Laundau-West takes issue with juice-bar brochures
stating that smoothies are a multicourse meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're a substitute for consuming a wide
variety of fruits and vegetables,'' Laundau-West said. ``It's not
like having a meal with bread that has complex carbohydrates, or
tuna fish or chicken or turkey that's a high-quality source of
protein.''
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Baker, Phoenix dietitian and spokeswoman for the American
Dietetic Association, believes that a smoothie can be a meal in
some situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every meal doesn't have to include 100 percent of your RDAs
(recommended daily amounts) of everything,'' Baker said. ``You are
getting protein, a number of nutrients and far less fat from a
smoothie than a hamburger and fries. I think a smoothie can be
considered a healthy treat but also used occasionally as a lunch
meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who is a long-distance runner, says she averages a
smoothie a week, usually after working out.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Stremble, community nutrition program manager in the
Maricopa County Office of Nutrition, said that if you're on the run
and have a choice between a smoothie and another fast-food
alternative, she'd recommend the smoothie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a more healthful choice,'' Stremble said.
``But it's not something you want to do on a day-to-day basis.
Fruits and vegetables are great, but they're primarily
carbohydrates. You need a blend of carbohydrates, protein and
fat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you don't want to do is eat a regular meal and then drink
a smoothie also, unless you can burn it off,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because of the calories. It's no secret that smoothies
are loaded with them, 300 to 550 calories for a 24-ounce serving,
or about the same as a McDonald's Quarter Pounder hamburger. Adding
peanut butter and chocolate, as some smoothie recipes call for, can
bring the calorie count to 700, a hefty total for a drink perceived
to be healthful.
</P>
<P>
   ``These smoothies are high in simple sugars because of the
frozen yogurt or sherbet and all the fruit juices that go into
them,'' Laundau-West said. ``Unless you're a really active person,
you're going to gain weight if you have a 550-calorie snack over
and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Doreen Mahar, manager of Sun Valley Smoothies at the Arizona
Center in downtown Phoenix, said you can buy smoothies that contain
fewer calories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on what you put in it,'' Mahar said. ``But
there are a lot of calories in 24 ounces of any food. Managing your
calories is the important thing. People tell me they've replaced
their breakfast and lunch with a smoothie and lost a pound a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Our nutrition specialists agree that a healthy dose of
skepticism may be in order when choosing nutritional supplements
offered as optional extras, allowing customers to customize their
smoothies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, juice bars claim that adding lecithin nutrients to
your drink will help prevent arteriosclerosis, protect against
cardiovascular disease and improve brain function. Quite a bargain
for 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything really happens with these supplements
if you just have them put in your drink one time,'' Landau-West
said. ``If you take an herb one time, nothing really happens,
either. Herbs take approximately 30 days of consistent use to have
an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I really like smoothies, I don't have (additional)
supplements,'' Baker said. ``I think that's throwing your money
away. Supplements for therapeutic effects really need to be taken
over the course of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many physicians, Dr. Karla Birkholz, a family practitioner
with Your Family Physician in Glendale, questions the value of
synthetic supplements anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take creatin,'' Birkholz said. ``No one knows if that's OK or
whether it provides any value. I think the true value in juice bars
is the natural nutrients from the real vegetables and fruits.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahar, who said she has studied nutrition for 30 years,
acknowledges that vitamins and certain herbs do need time and
repetition to perform optimally in the body. But she also believes
that certain combinations of nutrients can have an immediate
effect.
</P>
<P>
   She points to Sun Valley Smoothies' 93-cent ``energy boost''
nutrient package, which contains bee pollen, ginseng root and
ginkgo biloba root.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have one, and you'll be zooming for the rest of the day,''
Mahar said. ``You really will be more alert and energetic. People
who try it for the very first time come back the next day and tell
us how great they felt, then buy it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Moss, a general practitioner in Fountain Hills, said
he's not even familiar with some of the supplements, such as
citrimax, being offered at local juice bars, but what concerns him
most is the lack of warnings on juice-bar brochures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thermogenic herbs, for example, can cause problems for
individuals with hypertension or cardiac problems,'' Moss said.
``Echinacea, the so-called cold buster, might cause problems if you
have autoimmune problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Francis, a staff pharmacist for CIGNA Healthplan of
Arizona Inc., agrees with Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful what they do throw in there,'' Francis
said. ``Some of these supplements are stimulants. Not good if you
have high blood pressure. People with health conditions shouldn't
go nuts on these supplements without consulting their physicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue is the amount of nutrient supplements used in
juice-bar drinks. Some critics claim that no one knows whether
enough is used to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a problem with supplements in general,'' Baker said.
``They simply aren't regulated close enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Stremble said it's important that consumers realize that herbs
and dietary supplements aren't magic bullets, even though people
selling them often present them that way. She said the Dietary
Supplement and Health Education Act, passed by Congress in 1994,
``opened the floodgates'' for this kind of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 act allows manufacturers to make any claim they want as
long as they avoid assertions that products can cure or prevent a
specific disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herbal products and supplements don't have to be proven safe
or effective to be sold,'' Stremble said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheri Roberts, owner of Juice Works at Camelback Road and 32nd
Street in Phoenix, has been in the business a little more than a
month, but she said one thing in particular has impressed her in
the brief time she's managed Juice Works.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a core of loyal customers,'' Roberts said. ``I'm not
a nutritionist, so I'm not going to go out on the limb and say a
smoothie takes care of your meal for the day. I will say we watch
people in the parking lot. And we can tell just by looking at them
who is coming to visit us and who is going next door to A Taste of
Philly.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
