<HEADLINE>
PAINTING THE NATION RED: CELEBRATING AN ICON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In honor of the 130th anniversary of Heinz, the company proudly
cites University of Pennsylvania psychologist  &UR; Paul &LR; 
 &UR; Rozin &LR; , who calls ketchup ``one of the few constants in our
culture. ... It's surprising how strongly people feel about this
condiment.''
</P>
<P>
   To wit, the top per capita ketchup consumers in the nation live
in Salt Lake City. Women prefer to dunk foods in ketchup; men pour
it on. And one thing more: Ketchup comes out of the bottle at a
rate of 25 miles per year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW WOODY ALLEN LIKES TO WATCH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fervent Knick fan  &UR; Woody Allen &LR;  was so excited leaving Monday's
game at Madison Square Garden that he and his wife,
 &UR; Soon-Yi &LR; , got into the wrong Rolls Royce afterward, reported the
New York Post. When they realized their mistake, they got out and
searched for their own limo.
</P>
<P>
   Allen explained to the New York Daily News why he doesn't gab
with the other celebrities at games, and always appears unexcited:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been teased about this many times. I'm not interested in
all the promotions on the floor, or the propaganda that comes over
the TV screen. I just watch the guys play basketball, and as I do,
I quietly make lists in my mind, remembering the great moments and
the players who made the great plays....''
</P>
<P>
   Allen called  &UR; Latrell Sprewell &LR;  ``the magic ingredient.'' Even
when he misses, he said, ``he finds a way to score. He does
something to the chemistry, to the psychology, and it looks
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROSEANNE'S PILGRIMAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roseanne  &LR; was in Jerusalem this week for the grand opening of a
kabbalah school run by the institution at which she studies in Los
Angeles. When Mayor  &UR; Ehud Olmert &LR;  took her to the roof of City Hall
to point out Jerusalem's historic sites, she cried and they held
each other close.
</P>
<P>
   She said she wanted to study kabbalah right there, and that she
had brought many scholarly tomes with her for that reason. She also
said she likes the Bible, which she called ``very funny. ... It's
like one great sitcom.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESTING IN PEACE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Alice Adams &LR; ' memorial service in San Francisco Sunday at the
Presidio's Golden Gate Club, will be a significant literary
gathering. Among the speakers scheduled:  &UR; Annie Lamott &LR; ,  &UR; Orville &LR; 
 &UR; Schell &LR;  and  &UR; Mary Gaitskill &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bob Geary &LR; , the police officer who had a horse named after
him a few weeks ago, says that Bob's first duty was Monday, when
the horse and his mount,  &UR; Phil Downs &LR; , were assigned to stand guard
at St. Gabriel's church in the Sunset District, during the funeral
of  &UR; Joseph Geary &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Geary, Bob Geary's father, was 96 years old, and his son
said he had a special fondness for horses, having learned to ride
bareback by American Indians in his native Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Arriving at a party after a premiere showing of ``Rogue
Trader'' in London on Monday night,  &UR; Jerry Hall  &LR; gave  &UR; Mick Jagger &LR; 
a peck on the cheek. As the couple are said to be getting divorced
_ although Jagger claims they were never married _ this kiss was
viewed as significant, but no one could say exactly how.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bob Harrington &LR;  is seeking a translation of this sentence,
which appeared on the back of his DMV Registration Renewal Notice,
form number DMV83VR: ``An annual $4 smog abatement fee is due for
vehicles registered in a biennial smog area, which are four model
years old or newer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Nichols set the whole thing up on this hydraulic platform
so that the platform would descend hundreds of feet with the
wallpaper moving in the background. We had to do 40 takes ... over
several weeks to get the descent just right. Then when he was doing
the final edit he called us back and we had to do it again another
40 times because the air bubbles in the machine made all these
jerks and jiggles. ... At the time, (it) seemed so shocking and
discomforting, but now I just see it as bold and brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Rita Moreno telling Baird Jones at an HBO party for ``Oz''
about her most embarrassing movie task, performing what would later
be known as a Monica in ``Carnal Knowledge.'' The camera focused on
her face, which seemed to be moving downward in the film.
</P>
