<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8530 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XGAMES-IMPACT-SFCHRON     06-24 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XGAMES-IMPACT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X GAMES' MAIN EVENT: RAISING REVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: For use with XGAMES-SFCHRON)  
 By YUMI WILSON  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As skateboarders, dirt bikers and other
``extreme'' daredevils gear up to take over some of the city's most
scenic spots this weekend, civic and business leaders are preparing
for crowded streets, parking madness _ and a big boost in the
city's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN, which produces the X Games, expects about 200,000 people
to come to San Francisco over the next 10 days. The games are being
held in San Francisco for the first time and may return next year.
</P>
<P>
   Like the events themselves, the parking and traffic could get
extreme. Events will run from noon until 9 p.m., and some roads
will be closed or severely restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Pristash, a 52-year-old city librarian, said he learned only
recently that ``the street luge, or something like that,'' would
result in road closures near his home in the Outer Richmond, on the
west end of town near the Pacific Ocean. Even so, he's looking
forward to watching contestants lying on sled-like boards zoom down
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have cable,'' Pristash said. ``So it'll be fun to see
in my neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Parking and traffic figure to be congested at Piers 30 and 32,
where skateboarders, snowboarders, dirt bikers and the majority of
X Games contestants will compete. Big crowds are also expected on
Treasure Island in San Francisco Bay for wakeboarding, described as
water skiing with a surfboard. The event will be held at Clipper
Cove on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's the crowds, not the closures, that city and business
leaders are looking forward to. Mayor Willie Brown sees the games
as ``a good opportunity to showcase San Francisco and bring in more
revenue,'' said spokeswoman Kandace Bender.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the games generated $32 million for San Diego,
according to a study commissioned by the San Diego International
Sports Council. The event drew 230,000 people, more than half
younger than 24.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN spokesman Chris Stiepock said it is hard to know exactly
how many people or how much money San Francisco will get. But with
the Bay Area as the draw, he said, these games should attract at
least as many as found their way to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important than the money, supporters say, is the
exposure San Francisco will get during 28 1/2 hours of TV coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really aimed at the youth market,'' said G. Rhea
Serpan, president of the Chamber of Commerce. ``They are an
important and fast-growing market segment, particularly for our
retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   Serpan plans to check out some of the events himself. ``I don't
understand the board-shredding stuff, so I gotta go find out what
it's about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the events are free to the public, ESPN officials loaded
up on sponsors such as Walt Disney Pictures, the Marines and the
Office of National Drug Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsorship for San Francisco, however, did not come as easily.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN gave its national corporate sponsors exclusive rights to
hang their logos and banners at the games. As a result, few local
businesses were interested in fronting cash for an event at which
they will get little or no on-air exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials feared that the city would have to tap taxpayer
funds to pay for police, traffic control and maintenance crews. But
Brown and Supervisor Gavin Newsom finally persuaded several local
businesses and individual donors to come forward with a total of
nearly $700,000. Providian Financial Corp., Pacific Bell, Rite Aid,
KMEL and Pacific Gas and Electric Co. are among the city's
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any fund-raising effort, it was challenging,'' Newsom
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
