<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8533 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-24 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BANK ON IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They give you this target, a huge glass board, and
they paint thick white lines in the middle, right above the
cylinder in which you'd like the ball to drop. They do everything
but write in the words: Aim here, win valuable prizes.
</P>
<P>
   There is money in the bank shot, so why is it that almost no one
in professional basketball besides Tim Duncan seems to have figured
this out?
</P>
<P>
   The best offensive basketball minds in the country have been
asked to develop new and improved ways to increase scoring in the
game before it requires shoot-outs, like soccer, to determine a
winner. After watching Duncan dominate the Knicks in three of the
four games of the NBA finals and lead the Spurs to the brink of
their first championship, sources tell me that David Stern's crack
committee has begun its report with the following recommendation:
</P>
<P>
   To all shooters:  &UR; Duh! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm surprised that more guys don't use the
backboard,'' Duncan said. ``It's just that it's a bit easier, a bit
easier for me, to throw it off the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I wouldn't exactly say throw, and nor would Duncan's
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows where his soft touch comes from?'' said Gregg
Popovich, after the Spurs finished Thursday's workout in
preparation for Game 5, Clinch Night I, Friday night at Madison
Square Garden. ``If we knew, all our guys would have it.''
</P>
<P>
   That still didn't answer the question of why the bank shot has
generally become more loathsome in basketball than the 1-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich, leaving the court for the interview room, pointed to a
San Antonio television person and said, laughing, ``Because of
people like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he was standing behind a blue curtain, waiting for David
Robinson to finish talking, and saying: ``Seriously, I think it is
the whole television thing, the kind of shots that kids see on the
highlights every night. They just don't practice bank shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pressey, Popovich's assistant, was Don Nelson's ``point
forward'' in Milwaukee in the 1980s, when already the memories of
Sam Jones pulling up for a banker on the break at Boston Garden
were as dated a Sixties' staple as Jimi Hendrix's rendition of the
Star Spangled Banner. He said he often used the backboard from
``8-to-10 feet and in.'' In the mind of the modern player, Pressey
said, the bank shot came to look too much like a lucky ricochet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most players like to see the ball go through the net because
they think it looks better,'' said Pressey. ``But I always felt it
gave you not only a target but more of a gray area to shoot at.''
</P>
<P>
   In this era of falling field goal percentages, forgotten are
those _ Julius Erving then, Scottie Pippen now _ who weren't
naturally gifted shooters but helped themselves by using the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Popovich dispatched Pressey to Wake Forest
to run Duncan through a series of drills prior to the draft,
Pressey could barely believe what he was watching. A gifted giant
moving side-to-side, banking in one 15 footer after another. At
dinner, Pressey asked Duncan why he had developed the angled
banker, when the majority of players can't make the mid-range
jumper but still can't be talked out of aiming for the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan _ no child of the Nike summer camps _ compared it to
playing the angles in his beloved video games. Pressey called
Popovich, sitting pretty back home with the No. 1 pick. Pressey
said, ``This is the next coming, the player who's going to have the
huge impact on the league. I don't know how soon, but soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan retired in this, Duncan's second season. He is
shooting 52 percent in the finals, to the Knicks' 38. In the
probable event this concludes with the Spurs as champions, only the
sympathy vote for Robinson could prevent Duncan from winning most
valuable player. Is this soon enough?
</P>
<P>
   We'll never know how much of a difference even a sub-par Patrick
Ewing would have made, but Larry Johnson on Duncan has to be one of
the most unfair matchups in the history of the league. Chris Dudley
and Marcus Camby have only been marginally better. When he isn't
ripping L.J., Bill Walton _ who, when healthy, was the most
diversely skilled big man I ever saw _ must love watching Duncan
catch, turn and score off glass. Walton wore opponents out with
that shot.
</P>
<P>
   But there I go again, getting all nostalgic about old-school
fundamentals, when everyone knows that the rim is hip and the
backboard is square. Here is what Tim Duncan knows: one more
victory and he will stand tall, at the pinnacle of his sport. Bank
on that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0305 </DOCNO>
