<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYZE THIS, SAY WALTON AND COLLINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Doug Collins strode rapidly across the Madison Square
Garden hardwood Wednesday night before Game 4 of the National
Basketball Association finals. When he stopped, Collins, an NBC
Sports analyst and former Detroit Pistons coach, sounded overly
caffeinated, overly excited. Only his brush cut lacked conspicuous
animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's mellow compared to when he coached,'' said Bob Costas,
his partner on the air. ``He sweats through his shirt and jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking slowly on the Garden floor on painful feet was Bill
Walton, who is with NBC's pre- and post-game programs. The night
before, on Charlie Rose's PBS talk show, Walton unloaded a dump
truck's worth of outrageousness, from saying, ``I'm for anything
that gets Charlie Ward off the court'' to failing to name the five
smartest NBA players. He managed four _ slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The question, he said, flummoxed him, having never been asked
such a stumper before. Now, he could name more than five (he
regretted forgetting Chris Mullin) but would rather list brainy
old-timers and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   And so, our tale of two analysts, both former players: Collins,
the X's and O's overlord, and Walton, the full-time loose cannon
with zero tolerance for players who fail to follow the tao of
teamwork as taught by his personal Yoda, John Wooden, who coached
him at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Collins talks faster than Walton and is kinder when players err,
which isn't difficult; he avoids personal attacks (a bad shot is
not a license to excoriate) and offers focused commentary. Costas'
whimsy leavens Collins' single-minded resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Collins quickly saw that San Antonio was calling numerous
screen-and-rolls, rather than post-ups, to promote team movement;
he cautioned that Marcus Camby, starting as the Knicks' center, had
to be a little too tired from expending his nervous energy to be
effective; he suggested that the key to handling the Knicks'
Latrell Sprewell was to let him shoot from the field and keep him
off the foul line, and he linked Knicks point guard Charlie Ward to
the word ``great'' for scoring 10 points in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The praise for Ward put him on a collision course with Walton,
whose halftime demeanor _ he was on a set with Hannah Storm, Isiah
Thomas and Pete Vecsey _ is that of a serene assassin, ready for a
portentous pounce. Having no air time for over an hour had him
bubbling to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about my man, Charlie Ward!'' said Walton. Was this his
newest flip-flop (like his sudden, recent playoff embrace of ``my
Knicks'') from wishing exile for Ward to exulting over him? ``But
please _ here's a guy _ $30 million _ and all he gets is a couple
of baskets in a half of a half? Please!''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Knicks hung around gamely before losing, 96-89,
they fell prey to what Collins expected just as the second half
began: the tightening of the Spurs' defensive noose led by Tim
Duncan and David Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The harshest nugget from Collins was: ``It's been a nightmare
for Larry Johnson in the paint.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a retirement party tribute compared with Walton's
post-game censure on CNBC. Walton stirred Johnson's bad
performance, obscene tirades and remarks about the Knicks being
``rebellious slaves'' into a withering broadside: ``What a sad
human being. This is a disgrace to the game of basketball, to the
NBA _ he played like a disgrace tonight. He deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton first scorched Johnson on Tuesday on ``MSG SportsDesk''
(which nearly overlapped with his taped ``Charlie Rose'' gig),
saying his actions and comments are a ``disgrace to anyone who's
ever worn the NBA jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed not only for the league, but for the human
race,'' Walton added.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Johnson said, ``Isn't that the same Bill Walton that
was at UCLA and smoked pot, a hippie?''
</P>
<P>
   While Walton was protecting those of genteel constitutions from
L.J.'s oratory, Collins was revisiting the game after the final
buzzer. Inside NBC's production truck outside the Garden, Collins
stood opposite producer David Neal, planning video packages and
statistical tales for Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should lead with San Antonio,'' said Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Collins said, easing into his fast-talking mode.
``We've talked about the Twin Towers, but in games they've won,
it's the supporting cast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What if we do bar graphs on all four games?'' said Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supporting cast,'' said Collins, riffling though his
scoresheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One bar has Robinson and Duncan's combined points,'' said
Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty to 50 each night,'' said Collins. ``For Game 4, it'll be
higher for the supporting cast. They had 46.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the Knicks?'' Neal asked. ``Let's do Spree and
Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the stars,'' Collins said. ``But offense wasn't their
problem tonight. It was San Antonio's defense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do a package of San Antonio defensive stops,'' said
Neal. ``There was that terrific block Duncan didn't get credit
for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had nine blocks,'' said Collins. ``Robinson and Duncan
were always there.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Collins's post-game relaxation. He did not seem tired,
yet talking about the game he had just talked about somehow calmed
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, it's a way to unwind,'' Collins said. ``It's fresh
in our minds, so why not talk about it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
