<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY-N     06-24 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDY, ASSURED HIS JOB IS NOT IN JEOPARDY, SET TO RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying he had been assured by Madison Square Garden
president Dave Checketts between two and three weeks ago that his
job is not in jeopardy, Jeff Van Gundy gave the clearest indication
yet Thursday that he will return to coach the Knicks next season.
</P>
<P>
   The day before his team faced elimination in Game 5 of the
National Basketball Association finals, the once-embattled coach
reluctantly ended any looming speculation that he and the franchise
would part ways after a 10-year association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really up in the air,'' Van Gundy said Thursday
before the Knicks practiced at Madison Square Garden. ``Dave made
it clear to me that he wants me back. That's not the question. It
hasn't really been a question for two or three weeks. We just said
we're not going to talk about it until after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it clear that's what he wants. We just have to make
sure that it's the right thing. I'm sure it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as the Knicks, down by 3-1 in the
four-of-seven-games series against San Antonio, prepared for Friday
night's game. It has been nearly a month since Van Gundy's job was
thought to be in jeopardy if the Knicks did not get out of the
first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts has been mum about Van Gundy's situation, saying only
that he planned to meet with the coach after the season. Thursday,
he declined comment through a spokesman, who added that Checketts
was sticking to his original plan of discussing the team's future
with Van Gundy after the finals.
</P>
<P>
   But the feeling among most observers inside and outside the
Garden hierarchy is that if Van Gundy was in any danger of losing
his job, the Knicks' implausible run to the finals after a mediocre
regular season helped secure his future in New York.
</P>
<P>
   After the disclosure before Game 3 against Atlanta in the second
round of the playoffs that Checketts had secretly met with Phil
Jackson in April about taking over the team, Van Gundy went from
another beleaguered coach on the firing line to instant martyrdom,
the persecuted underdog trying to save his job with each victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made it clear to me that he wants me back; I don't think
that's a revelation,'' Van Gundy said of his informal discussion
with Checketts. Told that the news of his probable return as coach
was a revelation, Van Gundy added: ``Well, I didn't mean it to be.
That's not even what I'm thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just saying, he's made that clear to me. In the process,
he's also said we're going to wait until after the season to talk
about it. Which is exactly what I wanted, too. Because why would we
want to talk about next year when this year is still happening?''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was unclear about when Checketts relayed the message,
but it appears to have taken place between the Hawks series and the
Eastern Conference championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about whether Checketts' clandestine meeting with Jackson
would prevent him from again trusting the Garden president, Van
Gundy said: ``That was never a huge issue. Some other things _ not
with Dave _ were more of an issue to me.''
</P>
<P>
   After a tumultuous season that included a covert and often
bitter feud with the deposed general manager, Ernie Grunfeld, over
personnel decisions _ Grunfeld reportedly was on the verge of
firing Van Gundy twice during the regular season _ Van Gundy
appears headed toward a long-term extension after the season.
</P>
<P>
   By making the finals, Van Gundy insured himself $6 million _ $2
million to be paid next season, a club option that automatically
kicked in for the following year at $3.5 million and a $500,000
bonus for guiding the team to the championship round.
</P>
<P>
   Given that most of the game's premier coaches have signed
five-year deals in the last two seasons _ including Jackson's $30
million, five-year contract with the Los Angeles Lakers last week _
Van Gundy's agent, Rob Ades, will most likely try to work out an
extension on his client's current deal, which expires in 2001. The
spiraling salaries of his peers could put Van Gundy in line for a
package worth about $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen who will take over the Knicks' general
manager duties. Checketts, who has returned to the role on an
interim basis since re-assigning Grunfeld in April when the team
was 21-21, will not remain in that role.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant general manager Ed Tapscott has ties to Grunfeld, but
has worked closely with Checketts and Van Gundy on a multitude of
personnel matters for much of the last decade. Van Gundy has
intimated he wants a more defined role in personnel decisions, but
it is unlikely he would be offered the general manager position, or
accept it, if it involved day-to-day duties at the team's midtown
corporate offices.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the coach, who has been on and off the firing line
since March 8, 1996, the day he replaced Don Nelson, seems
committed to the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only thinking about coaching here,'' Van Gundy said.
``I've been fortunate to be here a long time and I've really never
wanted to be someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he believed he had done a good job this
season, he refused to comment on his own performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, our team has done a great, great job of finding
itself in a shortened season with a lot of change and hanging in
there and playing its best basketball when it counts,'' Van Gundy
said. ``I've said it before: this is not a magical run. This is not
Cinderella.''
</P>
</TEXT>
