u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKJACK ON THE WEST BANK, SURREAL IN ISRAEL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ Israeli-Palestinian relations have
entered into a bizarre twilight. Quite simply, thanks to the Oslo
peace process, Israelis and Palestinians have become
psychologically disconnected enough in their daily lives to be more
concerned with their respective internal politics than each other.
Yet, in reality, they are physically more connected than ever.
</P>
<P>
   When you are with secular Israelis today, they spend all their
time complaining about the ultra-Orthodox; when you are with
Palestinians today they spend all their time complaining about
Yasser Arafat, corruption and their lack of democracy. But
Palestinians and Israelis talk very little about each other
anymore. They remind you of a couple who have decided to get
divorced, but still can't agree on how to divide up their property
_ and may never agree _ so they live separate existences under the
same roof. They try to ignore each other, but can't help bumping
into each other.
</P>
<P>
   You can really see this when it comes to the issue of democracy.
Palestinians will tell you that what impressed them most about the
latest Israeli election was not Ehud Barak's victory, but the swift
way Benjamin Netanyahu conceded defeat and disappeared. That just
would not happen in any Arab state.
</P>
<P>
   More and more Palestinians will now tell you frankly that they
would like a Palestinian state like Israel _ with a strong supreme
court, a civil liberties union and real freedom of speech. More and
more Israelis will now tell you that they would like a Palestinian
state like Syria _ with no real supreme court and no civil
liberties union, so that Arafat will have no inhibitions about
kicking in Palestinian doors at 3 a.m. to find Hamas terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   More and more Palestinians are starting to realize that they
cannot make peace with Israel without Yasser Arafat, and that they
will never have democracy with Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Nablus-based Center for Palestine Research found
that 71 percent of Palestinians feel there is corruption in the
Palestinian Authority, and 57 percent feel they cannot criticize
their leaders. When asked if they had a ``positive'' assessment of
Palestinian democracy, 27 percent of Palestinians said yes. When
asked if they had a ``positive'' evaluation of Israeli democracy,
70 percent of Palestinians said yes.
</P>
<P>
   But while Israelis and Palestinians have never seemed more
separated psychologically, they have never seemed more integrated
physically. The web of roads, tunnels and settlements that connects
Israel and the West Bank is increasingly seamless. This is creating
some weird interactions. Ahmed Tibi, an Israeli Arab and former
adviser to Arafat, was just elected to the Knesset, and he has
asked for a place on the Knesset's most important committee _ The
Defense and Foreign Affairs Committee, which oversees the Mossad _
where no Israeli Arab has ever been allowed to serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house is the symbol of Israeli democracy,'' Tibi told me
in an interview in his Knesset office. ``This democracy has to be
absolute, not relative. I cannot accept that there are secrets I
can't hear because I did not serve in the army. We have many
members of this Knesset from the Orthodox Jewish parties who did
not serve in the army. I was elected by the people to express my
opinion on every issue. There is no government post that I would
restrict myself from, except chief rabbi.''
</P>
<P>
   Another blurring of lines happened this week when Israeli police
opened fire with rubber bullets on Arab protesters _ in the Israeli
Arab town of Lod _ and wounded an Israeli Arab Knesset member in
the process. The Arabs pointed out that Israeli police had fired on
the Israeli Arab demonstrators as if they were no different from
Palestinian refugees in Nablus.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Palestinian casino in Jericho, which is now
raking in roughly $1 million a day from Israeli visitors.
(Palestinians are not allowed to gamble.) Whatever peace deal is
achieved, Israeli gamblers will insist on their legitimate rights
to be able to go to Jericho for blackjack.
</P>
<P>
   It is often said that the Israeli doves won the debate about
peace _ a majority of Israelis now favor the creation of a
demilitarized Palestinian state _ but that the Israeli hawks won
the land, because the amount of territory they have claimed in the
West Bank will make a separate, contiguous Palestinian state
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The hawks may be sorry. If the psychological separation between
Israelis and Palestinians cannot be turned into physical
separation, you may end up with Israeli Arabs and West Bank
Palestinians one day merging, and declaring: ``Maybe the Israeli
hawks are right. Maybe we should just have one state between Jordan
and the sea. Rather than having a corrupt little Palestinian
dictatorship, maybe we should focus instead on fighting for equal
rights in Israel. After all, under a Palestinian state, my standard
of living will go down, my civil liberties will go down, my press
freedom will go down. The only thing that will go up is my flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't rule it out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
