<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8545 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-24 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO CHIEF CALLS FOR SPEEDUP IN TROOP DEPLOYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT AND KURT PRITZER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark called
for an accelerated deployment of peacekeeping troops Thursday as
the cycle of violence between ethnic Albanians and Serbs continued
to escalate here.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and NATO Secretary General Javier Solana basked in the
cheers of ethnic Albanians who came out by the hundreds to greet
them in the Kosovo capital chanting, ``NATO, NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   But only blocks away the death toll from brutal revenge attacks
was mounting.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of three men, including a Serb professor, were found
at the Serb-run economics department at Pristina University. Two
were bound and gagged and a third lay on the floor. They were
apparently beaten with a hammer, which lay next to the bodies, and
then shot to death, said the dean of the department, Milos Simovic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops sealed off the basement and were investigating.
</P>
<P>
   In another neighborhood, a Serb was killed and an ethnic
Albanian wounded in a gunbattle Thursday when a family of Albanian
refugees returned to their Pristina apartment and found it occupied
by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were taken to the capital's main hospital, where
relatives of the dead Serb again opened fire in a hallway, wounding
a guard and a nurse. British officers intervened and told them to
lay down their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the homes of Serb families who had fled Kosovo
continued to burn throughout the province, especially in the
northern city of Pec, where scores of homes smoldered as ethnic
Albanians looted Serb homes block by block. They filled tractors
and trucks full of sofas, televisions, and refrigerators as the
smoke rose from fires.
</P>
<P>
   With only half of the requested 55,000 international
peacekeeping team deployed in Kosovo, Clark said, ``We've asked
member governments and contributing partner governments to speed
the deployment of those troops to the maximum extent possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain and France have agreed to put thousands of soldiers on
standby for rapid reaction service, officials said Thursday.
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Britain would put the
equivalent of a brigade -- usually from six to eight thousand
soldiers -- at U.N. disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Serbs held a demonstration here to highlight
their fears over the looting and killing by ethnic Albanians. The
demonstration turned violent as Serbs gathered in the street began
pelting with rocks several ethnic Albanian families who were
returning on tractors from refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the rising tension, Clark said, ``KFOR will look after you.
Stay and give peace a chance. This is the message I delivered to
the Serb political and religious leaders when I met them a few
minutes ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need for anyone to leave Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Solana also met with KLA leaders and the Serbian Orthodox
Church's Bishop of Pristina who he said shook hands and agreed to
hold further meetings. Church officials say that at least 20 Serbs
have been victims of vengeance killings in the week since the
withdrawl of Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Solana and Clark said that they believe the horrors being
uncovered in Kosovo provide clear justification for the alliance's
punishing bombing campaign of Serb forces that began on March 24
and lasted 11 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Solana and Clark arrived a day after US Marines came under fire
by Serb attackers armed with AK-47s in the southeastern Kosovo town
of Zegra. The Marines, who called in attack helicopters, killed one
of the assailants and wounded two others, a NATO spokesman in
Pristina said.
</P>
<P>
   No Marines were injured, but the shooting underscored the risks
facing NATO troops trying to restore security after 17 months of
ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO leaders toured the burned sections of Pristina,
Yugoslavia's parliament voted to end the state of war declared when
NATO began its bombing campaign on March 24. The measure, which
takes effect Saturday, lifts media restrictions, a ban on
military-age men leaving the country and a ban on public
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   But the parliament is to vote Friday on measures to give the
Milosevic government power to crack down on dissent and keep its
wartime controls over banking and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressure, disgruntled Yugoslav army reservists
blocked roads in central Serbia for the second straight day
Thursday, demanding back pay for service during the bombing
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But in Pristina, the celebrations of NATO were thunderous.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds swarmed central Pristina for a look at the men they see
as liberators -- Solana, Clark, and Lt. General Mike Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   It was the largest demonstration in Pristina since ethnic
Albanians took to the streets to plea for NATO intervention shortly
before the bombing campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   Several men dressed in traditional white conical hats worn by
ethnic Albanians broke through the crowd to kiss the smiling Solana
before he disappeared into the former Yugoslavia headquarters now
home to the UN mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KFOR forces are now working hard to end the violence that
for many dark months was part of everyday life in Kosovo,'' Solana
said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the KFOR troops would continue to fight to make
Kosovo a place ``where justice can prevail and all the refugees can
return home.''
</P>
<P>
   But for that justice to prevail ethnic Albanians say the Serb
leaders who ordered and executed the murderous campaign of ethnic
cleansing throughout Kosovo must be brought to trial in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   FBI forensic experts began gathering evidence at two sites in
the western Kosovo town of Djakovica to build the case for the
indictment of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. The US
ambassador-at-large for war crimes issues, David Scheffer, said
their work would be vital to uncovering evidence Serbs tried to
hide or destroy.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops were holding a man who residents of the northern
village of Slovinia identified as taking part in the April massacre
of 43 men and of two women who were raped before being killed.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the State Department announced a $5 million
reward for information leading to the arrest and conviction of
people sought by the UN tribunal trying war crimes cases from the
conflicts in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
