<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8548 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      06-24 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JURORS, NO CLEAR-CUT VILLAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The verdict was a metaphor for the case itself.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors in the Reggie Lewis medical malpractice case, peppered
for weeks with duelling experts, contradictory evidence, and one
witness who testified both ways on the crucial question of drug
use, gave back what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   They saw shades of gray, not black and white.
</P>
<P>
   They saw nuance and complexity, not clear-cut villains or
victors.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day you've got one of the city's leading
cardiologist's reputation dragged through the mud,'' said Boston
attorney Robert A. Sherman. ``At the end of the day, you've got the
former Celtic captain's reputation tarnished by allegations of
cocaine use.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no winners. Reggie Lewis is dead and nothing can be
done to alter that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Just after he declared a mistrial in the case against Dr.
Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., who Lewis's family claimed was negligent in
his diagnosis and treatment of Lewis, Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith
searched fruitlessly for a champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense nobody's a winner or a loser here,'' he said before
dismissing the jury. ``Everybody is a loser. We've all lost Mr.
Lewis. Everybody's reputation has been attacked on both sides of
the case. I think it's a sad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, Donna Harris-Lewis, Lewis's widow, abruptly
canceled plans to speak to reporters at a news conference at the
Reggie Lewis Track and Athletic Center at Roxbury Community
College. She issued a brief statement, saying that her husband's
reputation ``has emerged from this stronger than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   But some observers struggled to see how anyone could reach that
conclusion in a case where only the ancillary players -- two
consulting physicians cleared of wrongdoing -- walked away with a
clear-cut verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mudge can't feel good tonight, but he's got to feel better
than Donna Harris-Lewis,'' said Michael E. Mone, a Boston
plaintiff's attorney. ``This is not the worst-case scenario from a
plaintiff's point of view but, boy, it's right up there. If you're
going to try the same evidence again, who's to say another jury is
going to come out any differently?''
</P>
<P>
   That legal calculation had many courtroom observers predicting
that the case against Mudge would ultimately end in settlement, not
a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine having to try this case again?'' asked David
White-Lief, chairman of the Massachusetts Bar Association's civil
litigation section.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to show that the Reggie Lewis case is just like
every other medical malpractice case in Massachusetts: tough, tough
cases to win,'' said White-Lief. ``With all the demystification of
many professions in the last 20 years, the profession of medicine
retains a lot of mystery and honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances H. Miller, a professor of law and public health at
Boston University said that while Harris-Lewis did not win, she
accomplished two things by putting her case before a jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to be heard on something that she thought was not
right and she got that forum,'' said Miller, referring to
allegations -- vehemently disputed by her Harris-Lewis -- that her
husband had used cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``She might not be happy with what came out of it, but she got
her forum,'' Miller said. ``And she sent a deterrent signal that
was heard loud and clear in the medical profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Mudge's testimony that he had misled the public
about Lewis's condition, and his comments regarding Lewis's alleged
admission of cocaine use, Miller said, ``You play with fire when
what you say to the media is not what you fully believe, and you
play with fire when you talk about your patients after the fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Harris-Lewis, who grew up in public housing in
Bridgeport, Conn., worked her way through Northeastern University
and married her college sweetheart, began the journey to Thursday's
verdict with a newspaper story, a 1995 Wall Street Journal story
suggesting that cocaine use was a factor in Lewis's death.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball star's widow said the allegations of drug use
sparked the civil suit that she hoped would redeem her late
husband's reputation as a man of easy smiles and charitable works _
a man whose body now lies in Forest Hills Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Harris-Lewis was criticized for exposing her
husband's memory to further assault even after she collected more
than $10 million in insurance money paid through policies the
Celtics had taken out on Lewis and his basketball contract.
</P>
<P>
   But Harris-Lewis steadfastly maintained that it was the search
for truth _ not money _ that propelled her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't physically bring him back, but his character is
something that never dies, and this lawsuit was my way of not only
understanding the circumstances surrounding his death, but
restoring his name and good character,'' Harris-Lewis said on the
eve of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, when it was over, Harris-Lewis, who has called her
late husband her soulmate, claimed through a terse statement that
somehow she had accomplished just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no telling how much good he could have done if he had
been treated properly and lived,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But where Harris-Lewis saw vindication, others saw a verdict as
divided as the evidence itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, as it stands right now, the only thing
that's been accomplished is the tarnishing of the memory of her
husband and the jury's verdict shows it wasn't clear cut in the
mind of those jurors _ as often in real life things are not clear
cut,'' Sherman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 1944EDT &QL; 
