<HEADER>
A8551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGWAY-ADVISORY-NY     06-24 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (lmp) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MANAGING EDITORS, WEEKEND EDITORS, FEATURE AND BOOK EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls to your attention the
package of articles on Ernest Hemingway produced by The Kansas City
Star in connection with the 100th anniversary of his birth, July
21.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway's first writing job was as a police reporter for The
Star in 1917 and '18, and he returned to Kansas City periodically
over the years, including stays there for the births of two sons.
</P>
<P>
   During one of those visits, in 1928, he was writing the
difficult final passages of ``A Farewell to Arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the articles The Star has moved are too tightly
localized to be of use by most NYT News Service clients. But
several are of broader interest and could provide centerpieces or
sidebars in presentations that clients may be planning around the
publication in July of the last book from Hemingway's unfinished
manuscripts, ``True at First Light.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories in The Star's package that may be of wider
appeal. All are for use Sunday, June 27, and thereafter. (All have
moved in the ``l'' and ``e'' categories.) Questions or reruns:
Melanie Gray, 816-234-4778 (e-mail: mgray(at)kcstar.com).
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-DEFINE-KAN _ He was born on July 21, 1899, and died by
his own hand on another July day 62 years later. In the intervening
years, his life not only paralleled the rise of the American
century,'' he also helped define it. He was an American abroad. He
was all brawn and swagger. And in one of the surest ways to extend
one's life beyond its natural boundaries he wrote it all down, and
much of what he wrote down was very good. This year marks the
centennial of Ernest Hemingway's birth, and unlike the 100th
anniversary of, say, James Gould Cozzens or Robert McAlmon, two of
his contemporaries, the event is drawing considerable attention. By
Steve Paul. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-BIOGRAPHY-KAN _ That Ernest Hemingway could be
exasperating has been established. Happily, that's not the entire
agenda of Michael Reynolds, the Hemingway scholar who now has
completed his cycle of Hemingway biographies with ``Hemingway: The
Final Years.'' This is the fifth and final volume of the series
Reynolds began back in 1986, and through which Reynolds has
established himself a scholar who, while possessing a vast store of
sympathy for the Hemingway the artist, has never hesitated to
identify troglodyte conduct when he encounters it. By Brian Burnes.
800 words.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-BIRTHS-KAN _ During a poignant period in 1928,
Hemingway and his wife Pauline spent a few weeks in Kansas City
awaiting the birth of their second son, Patrick. It was a
complicated pregnancy and resulted in a birth by Caesarean section.
During that period when Hemingway is writing the final section of
``A Farewell to Arms,'' in which the emotional end involves a
difficult pregnancy and stillbirth. By Brian Brian Burnes. 1,800
words.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-HANNEMAN-KAN _ Audre Hanneman toiled in modest
obscurity for many years to produce one of the most important
resources ever created for Hemingway students, researchers and
collectors: A two-volume descriptive bibliography of works by and
about him, which scholars still today find indispensable. And they
also lament that she or no one else has filled in the blanks since
her last volume appeared in 1975. Hanneman, who spent 30 years in
New York, how lives in Kansas City in semi-retirement. By Steve
Paul. 2,000 words. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-TIMELINE-KAN _ A chronology, suitable as the copy for
a sizeable graphic, tracing the highlights of Hemingway's life and
career. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-BIBLIOGRAPHY-KAN _ A selected bibliography. 250 words.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-WRITERS-KAN _ Contemporary writers on Hemingway. 550
words.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-RESOURCES-KAN _ Listing new books and web sites for
Hemingway info and study. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-HISWORDS-KAN _ Selected quotes from Hemingway and his
writings. 600 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
