<HEADLINE>
FAA, AMERICAN AIRLINES REVIEW SAFETY PROCEDURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal aviation officials and American Airlines are closely
examining safety procedures, pilot training, and flight operations
in the wake of this month's accident at Little Rock, Ark., that
killed 11 people. That crash was the most recent in a series of
accidents and close calls involving American going back to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its investigation into the June 1 accident, the
National Transportation Safety Board will look at several past
accidents to see if there is a connection, although the board,
issued a press release saying there was no separate investigation
into the practices of the airline. The Wall Street Journal Thursday
reported that there was such an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA and American are also conducting reviews of the nation's
second largest airline, a spokesman for the airline said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   American has had a series of incidents _ one at Bradley
International Airport in Connecticut where the plane sliced through
trees on a ridgetop before landing _ and two fatal accidents: one
in December 1995 in Cali, Columbia, that killed 157 when the flight
crew put wrong information into a computer, became lost, and hit a
mountain while trying to land, and the one this month in Little
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be some similarities in the history of
accidents and incidents over the past six years and our commitment
to safety requires our vigilance in maintaining industry-leading
training and operating procedures,'' Robert W. Baker, American's
vice president for operations, said Thursday. ``For that reason, I
have ordered a thorough top-to-bottom review of our flight
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   American said it will focus on six incidents _ Hartford, Cali,
Little Rock, a 1993 accident when a DC-10 went off the runway at
Dallas-Fort Worth; a 1997 incident in Cleveland where a DC-9 was
heavily damaged when it slid off a runway during landing; and a
Feb. 9, 1998, incident at Chicago's O'Hare Airport where an
American Boeing 727 with 121 people on board landed in heavy fog
some 200 feet short of the runway, struck light poles, and skidded
some 2,000 feet before landing coming to rest in a muddy field.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a high-ranking NTSB source said the review by the
agency _ which has no power to regulate and can only recommend
changes _ may include other incidents and crashes involving
American Eagle planes, whose pilots receive the same training
program as American Airline pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not unusual when there is a series of incidents, as few
as two, involving one carrier that calls into question the actions
and thoughts of a flight crew that we will go down the road a
little ways,'' said the NTSB source. ``We will look at training, at
corporate culture. We have gone down this path before with other
airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, there were two fatal American Eagle crashes. In
October, an ATR-72 crashed in Roselawn, Ind., killing all 68 on
board. Icing and the French manufacturer's failure to disclose
information concerning icing during operation were blamed for the
crash. In December, an American Eagle plane crashed while landing
at Raleigh-Durham, N.C., killing 15.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB found the pilot failed to follow procedures for engine
failure identification and AMR Eagle training was lax. AMR is the
corporate parent of American Airlines and American Eagle. AMR stock
closed Thursday at 64, down 2 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the NTSB investigated two hard landings by American
planes in 1997 and 1998 which resulted in substantial damage to the
tails of the airplanes. One incident occrred in St. Johns, Antigua,
the other in La Paz, Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   Several aviation sources also expressed concern that relations
between American's management and the pilots union for the carrier,
Allied Pilots Association, have reached a nadir with the costly
sickout earlier this year by the pilots group, protesting two-tier
wages and that should be a part of any investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bradley incident, which occurred in November 1995, the
NTSB found that crew members failed to ask for an updated altimeter
pressure reading even though they knew that weather was changing,
which would necessitate an updated reading.
</P>
<P>
   In the DC-10 case, the pilot overruled his first officer and
decided to land in a wind-whipped rainstorm. The plane skidded off
the runway and caught fire. More than 30 passengers were injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
