<SLUG> BC-FEDERAL-JUDGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION FOE SOLE DISSENTING VOTE IN SENATE JUDICIAL
RECOMMENDATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Judiciary Committee, over the objection
of an ardent abortion opponent, recommended Thursday that the full
Senate confirm Houston attorney Keith P. Ellison to be a federal
trial judge.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote within the next few weeks to
confirm Ellison, a sole practitioner, to be a judge on the U.S.
District Court for southern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H. and a GOP presidential candidate, was the
sole senator on the 18-member committee to oppose sending Ellison's
name for full Senate consideration. Smith, who opposes any judicial
nominee who indicates support for abortion rights, said he objected
to Ellison's unacceptable answer to his question of whether an
``unborn child'' is a human being.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to Smith's inquiry, Ellison wrote,
``Current law does not appear to conclude whether an unborn child
is a human being per se.'' Ellison cited the Supreme Court's 1992
decision in Planned Parenthood of Southeastern Pennsylvania vs.
Casey, which reiterated the justices' landmark 1973 Roe vs. Wade
ruling legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who has urged the high court to overturn Roe vs. Wade,
also objected to four other judicial nominees Thursday who, like
Ellison, did not echo the senator's view that life begins at
conception. The committee, despite Smith's misgivings, also
recommended Senate confirmation of these other nominees from
Mississippi, California, South Dakota and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Following his likely confirmation, Ellison, 49, would give up a
law practice that grossed $1 million for him last year in return
for life tenure and an annual salary of $136,700. Ellison listed
his net worth at nearly $3.59 million in a financial-disclosure
statement he provided to the Senate committee in January.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison's smooth sailing in committee was in contrast to the
controversy that preceded President Clinton's nomination of the
attorney in January.
</P>
<P>
   Local Democratic members of Congress had favored state District
Judge Ruben L. Guerrero, and his and Ellison's names were sent to
the White House for presidential consideration. When Ellison
emerged as the Clinton administration's preferred candidate, local
Hispanic leaders threatened to stage a protest rally at the
president's April 1998 forum on race in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was called off after the White House agreed to
consider Houston Hispanics for high-profile federal jobs. Houston's
Democratic members of Congress then supported Ellison's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, a New Orleans native, has been practicing law in
Houston for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
