A8558 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTORS-UNION-BOS &LR;      06-24 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-UNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS LAUD, HMOS CRITICIZE AMA UNION VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The historic vote by the American Medical Association to form a
union for doctors as a way of fighting back against powerful
managed-care interests drew criticism Thursday from some HMO and
hospital officials, but energized an already-growing physician
labor movement across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The endorsement of a doctors' union by the AMA is an enormous
boost to the doctors' unionization movement,'' said Dr. Barry
Liebowitz, president of the National Doctors Alliance, a newly
formed 15,000-member group that just affiliated with an AFL-CIO
union, the Service Employees International Union. ``This movement
is not based on economics. This movement is based on patient care
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that the AMA finally realized that this was
a good model,'' said Sandy Shea of the House Officers' Association,
which represents interns, residents, and fellows at Boston Medical
Center, and is part of the National Doctors Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Medical Center association has a two-year-old case
pending before the National Labor Relations Board, to get formal
government acknowledgment of the right of house officers across the
country to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   But national organizations representing health plans, hospitals,
and even manufacturers Thursday objected to the AMA's vote to
create a separate labor union, saying it will threaten patient
care, lead to anti-trust violations by some physicians and drive up
health care costs as unions demand higher wages for physicians,
among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``In conjunction with proposed legislation...(the) AMA vote
could, in fact, increase health insurance premiums by up to 11
percent and add at least two million Americans to the rolls of the
uninsured,'' said Chip Kahn, president of the Health Insurance
Association of America, in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignani, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, said in an interview Thursday that one of her greatest
objections is that the AMA vote will lead to the formation of
``cartels'' on the part of the nation's 350,000 self-employed
physicians, particularly if pending legislation to give doctors
anti-trust exemptions gets passed. ``It's anti-competitive,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allowing doctors to unionize will be utterly disastrous for
our health care system because it will completely undermine efforts
to monitor quality and control costs,'' said Neil Trautwein, the
health care lobbyist for the National Association of Manufacturers,
in a statement. The Washington-based group was founded more than
100 years ago to promote a pro-growth, pro-manufacturing policy
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA vote on Wednesday came on the heels of a similar one by
the American Nurses Association, to create a separate national
labor union, United American Nurses, to strengthen existing
collective bargaining, according to an association spokeswoman. The
same pressures of managed care and hospital cutbacks were cited
during the debate over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where they stand on the issue, nearly all involved
_ doctors, HMO administrators and hospital officials _ agree that
the AMA vote to unionize its doctors is an indication of a health
care system in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harry Greene, executive vice president of the Massachusetts
Medical Society, said, ``I think it's bringing this to a head. I
think we have to have a major dialogue about how to bring people
the care they need for the next millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17,000-member professional society last year created a
committee to study the issue of unionization, but that committee
has not yet reported back, according to Greene. With the AMA's
vote, he said he is sure the society will also tackle the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Philip Boulter, senior vice president and chief medical
officer for Tufts Health Plan, said while he does not expect to see
physician unionization sweeping across Massachusetts, he
acknowledged it is a response to cost pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managed care has been put in the unenviable position of being
in the middle,'' Boulter said. ``We are in a tough position from
that standpoint.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
