<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENEM-MARADONA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE POLITICS-SOCCER DRUG CASE REVERSES FIELD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ The boundary between politics and
soccer can be extremely fine in Argentina, especially when it comes
to the travails of Diego Maradona, the former World Cup sensation
and on-again, off-again political ally of President Carlos Saul
Menem.
</P>
<P>
   When Maradona's manager was arrested three years ago by the
police, who said they found a vial of 500 grams of cocaine in his
luxury apartment, the political opposition and the media gleefully
linked the scandal to the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   The manager, Guillermo Coppola, was widely known to be a close
friend of Menem's personal secretary, and the president's two adult
children were often photographed partying at Coppola's nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   But the twists and turns of the case came to an astonishing
climax on Wednesday night, when a judge threw out the case against
Coppola for lack of evidence. The judge took the action a day after
a federal prosecutor called for an investigation into the federal
judge who had initiated the case, asserting that the judge had
forged documents as part of an effort to ``target Guillermo Coppola
and Diego Maradona's inner circle without any justification.''
</P>
<P>
   It should have been a resounding victory for Maradona, and
indirectly for Menem, even though some in the media and legal
sector suggested that the often politicized judicial system was
again working to protect the political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   But Maradona, who admitted years ago that he was addicted to
cocaine, looked far from ebullient most of this week as he appeared
in court. Television news programs showed the former star athlete,
who has gained a lot of weight, speaking incoherently and nodding
out on his wife's shoulder while seated in the Buenos Aires
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The political shock waves of the case only grew when Maradona
testified on Wednesday that Menem had made contact with him after
his manager's arrest and ``offered me whatever I wanted, all that
he could possibly do.''
</P>
<P>
   Maradona said he responded to Menem by saying, ``Look president,
if I accept anything from you, I'll be one more corrupt guy.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed by a judge to explain what type of help Menem
offered, Maradona said the offer was vague. The president's press
office did not respond to questions about the supposed
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Maradona had long accused the Buenos Aires governor, Eduardo
Duhalde, a political foe of Menem, of being behind the arrest of
his manager although he never offered proof. This week in court he
said Duhalde, who is gradually making peace with Menem as he runs
for president, had dropped his pursuit of the case and left the
prosecuting judge in the lurch.
</P>
<P>
   Menem administration officials have studiously avoided comments
on the case, hoping to steer clear of its fallout. But few
Argentines have forgotten that when Menem was far behind in the
polls in 1995, Maradona helped save his re-election bid by
appearing in his television advertisements and beside him at his
campaign rallies.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship went into hibernation after Coppola's
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola had long been held responsible for Maradona's drug
problems even after charges that he had dealt cocaine to Maradona's
teammates in the Italian league were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration's office at
the time of Coppola's arrest in 1996 took the unusual step of
announcing to local news agencies that the manager was on a DEA
list of suspected traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Coppola said the cocaine found in his
apartment had been planted. His charge has now been supported by
Raul Perotti, the federal prosecutor, who originally intended to
prosecute the case against the manager but is now turning his fire
on the federal judge who initiated the case, Hernan Bernasconi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernasconi knew that he was ordering raids on the basis of
fake accusations,'' Perotti said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bernasconi faces a probable impeachment trial in the
Argentine Senate, making him the latest in a string of judges over
the last two years who have been impeached or forced to resign
because of scandals. Bernasconi's secretary has been placed under
arrest, along with three police officers involved in the
investigation that lead to Coppola's arrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
