<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SANTULLI-     06-24 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SANTULLI-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE JETS FOR (MORE OF) THE PEOPLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Eds: Please note correct slug above for BIZ-PROFILE-HAFT)  
 (af)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On paper, Richard T. Santulli seemed an unlikely candidate to
revolutionize the elite business of owning private jets. Raised in
Brooklyn, N.Y., where his family lived with one set of grandparents
and across the street from the other, he did not take his first
plane flight until his honeymoon in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 54, he travels worldwide, is worth hundreds of millions
of dollars, raises expensive thoroughbreds and talks almost daily
with Warren E. Buffett, whose company, Berkshire Hathaway, bought
his, Executive Jet, for $730 million last year. Santulli, however,
remains the chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Santulli came up with a concept for joint ownership of
private jets, thus broadening their market. Under the plan, a jet
that costs $6.7 million, for example, can be split among 16 people
for $417,500 each _ plus $4,850 a month for maintenance and $1,242
per hour flown. A number of jets are pooled to insure availability
to owners.
</P>
<P>
   At those prices, Santulli's invention still has not touched as
many lives as Henry Ford's Model T. But it has put private jets
within the reach of many more individuals and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   When Santulli, who is not a pilot, first approached makers of
private planes about his idea, many dismissed him. Now, Executive
Jet, in Woodbridge, N.J., is their biggest customer, helping to
produce record sales in an industry that has suffered violent booms
and busts.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at the Paris Air Show, he announced an order for as
many as 100 new Hawker jets from Raytheon, a deal worth $2 billion.
In the last four years, Executive Jet has ordered 587 new aircraft
worth $9.75 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that we are grateful would be an understatement,'' said
Russell W. Meyer, chairman of Cessna Aircraft, the first
manufacturer to back his concept.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Santulli had the fractional-ownership market to
himself _ and with 1,300 owners and 165 planes, he remains the
market leader. But success spawns imitators. Two manufacturers _
Bombardier of Canada and Raytheon _ have started their own
joint-ownership plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bombardier, which makes Lear jets and other models, says its
program, Flexjet, offers superior service and support. It says that
Flexjet will have 90 planes by year-end and that it will eventually
overtake Executive Jet. But some analysts wonder how well any of
the players will do if the economy turns down and demand cools.
</P>
<P>
   Santulli is not worried. He sold to Berkshire Hathaway, he said,
so he could manage for the long term. ``Warren says when things go
bad, we will buy more planes,'' Santulli said.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett first learned about Executive Jet in 1995, when he
bought a quarter share in a Hawker 1000 for his family. He was so
pleased that he later did a rare testimonial advertisement. Last
year, when Goldman Sachs, which held a 20 percent stake in
Executive Jet, was pressing Santulli to take his company public, he
approached Buffett, who offered to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked him and I liked the business,'' Buffett said in a
recent interview. The two men are now planning Executive Jet's
overseas expansion. ``I talk to him more than almost anybody
else,'' Buffett said.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to Santulli's success, and one of his bonds with
Buffett, is his head for numbers. ``If you understand math, you
don't have to study it,'' Santulli said. ``All my friends would
spend hours on history and philosophy. To me, I hate to say it,
math was the easy way out.''
</P>
<P>
   After attending the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, Santulli
taught mathematics. He went to Shell Oil in 1967, helping the
company crunch numbers. Two years later, he received a call from a
Goldman executive who wanted to start a group to do computer
analysis of companies and deals. Santulli was soon heading the
firm's new quantitative analysis group and, later, a unit that used
computers to structure leases for real estate and equipment. But in
1979, on the verge of a partnership _ he decided to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you are a partner at Goldman, the money is too large for
you ever to leave,'' he explained. ``I didn't like that. I always
wanted the freedom to do what I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Santulli started his own leasing company and soon became one of
the world's biggest lessors of helicopters. In 1984, he bought
Executive Jet, a perennially unprofitable charterer of private
jets.
</P>
<P>
   He knew that owning a jet made no financial sense for most
people unless they flew at least 400 hours a year. But joint
ownership of such a high-priced toy posed problems, too, because
each co-owner wants to use the plane at his leisure.
</P>
<P>
   Using his math skills, he worked out the problem. ``I knew that
if we could come up with a way to share the cost and at the same
time guarantee service, we would hit a home run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Jet's fleet has nine types of planes, including
Cessnas, Hawkers, Gulfstreams and the new Boeing Business Jet, a
modified 737. Owners buy stakes in a specific airplane but don't
necessarily fly in it. Executive Jet promises to have whatever
model they share available on four hours' notice.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, Santulli has also applied his math skills to
breeding race horses. He estimates that his stable is now worth
about $60 million. In November, he paid $3.5 million to buy out his
partner's share of a prize mare.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Santulli married Peggy Casey, his longtime assistant
in the horse business. They now have a 5-month old daughter, Mary
Ann. He also has an adult son, Richard Jr., from his previous
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Santulli spends much of his free time figuring the odds of
breeding champion horses and valuing the thoroughbreds he sells.
``It's very mathematical, in my opinion,'' he said. ``There is a
logic to it and I like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
