<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULSTER-POLICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER POLICE `ORDINARY PEOPLE,' UNION CHIEF SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Les Rodgers is a plumpish, pink-cheeked man who spends
his spare time tending roses and reading Tom Clancy novels. He also
is the hard-line head of a union that represents the membership of
one of the world's most reviled police forces _ the Royal Ulster
Constabulary of Northern Ireland. Catholics curse his men as
``black bastards,'' a reference to uniforms they once wore, and
``SS RUC.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks we're devils with horns,'' said Rodgers.
``What we're trying to say is that we're ordinary people _ ordinary
police officers _ upholding the law and order.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers, the chairman of the Police Federation in Northern
Ireland, was in Boston, this week where he met Wednesday with
Boston Police Commissioner Paul Evans.
</P>
<P>
   With a report on the RUC's future looming, Rodgers has traveled
to the United States on a two-prong mission: To burnish his 13,000
member organization's tarnished image and to pick up some tips
about community policing, Boston style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we've had to deal with the scourge of
terrorism,'' Rodgers said. ``We've had to live in a mode we want to
get out of. We'd like to go back to being a community police force
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Though its presence is more muted than it was before the 1996
cease-fire, the RUC still seems more like an occupying army than a
police force. Its Kevlar-clad riot police roam the streets in
armor-plated Land Rovers or hunker down in their heavily fortified
headquarters buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But the terms of the Good Friday Agreement of 1998 specify that
the RUC must be reformed. Sometime in the next several months a
commission headed by Chris Patten, the former Hong Kong governor,
will issue a report specifying what changes exactly are to be made
by the RUC.
</P>
<P>
   With pressure mounting, the RUC has already announced some
internal reforms. The organization, which is 92 percent Protestant
in a region that is 40 percent Catholic, has been struggling to
recruit more Catholics. In five years, the RUC hopes to have a
70-30 Protestant-Catholic ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers said the organization now puts its members through
``community sensitivity'' training that includes visits by a
Catholic priest. A course in human rights is in the works. Rodgers
said there have even been visits from gay and lesbian community
members to teach police not to persecute homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers and the Police Federation secretary, David McClurg, said
the lessons of Boston's effort to improve relations between its
police department and minority communities had been instructive.
While both men firmly eschewed the use of hiring quotas (``It
hasn't worked here,'' Rodgers said), they talked excitedly about
implementing a program in Northern Ireland similar to the 10 Point
Coalition initiated by black ministers in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That struck such a chord with me,'' McClurg said.
</P>
<P>
   But many in Northern Ireland wonder if the 13,000 member
organization will ever be a truly non-sectarian police force.
Skeptics point to a speech Rodgers delivered earlier this month at
the RUC's annual convention. Rodgers said he believed the
nationalist party Sein Fein was organizing an ``evil conspiracy''
against the RUC, assisted by human rights groups and academics. He
was also insistent the name of the RUC must never be changed.
``Attacks on the name, in particular, are really attacks on the
very existence of the RUC.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the RUC find such rhetoric unnerving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very disturbing,'' said Maggie Beirne, the research and
policy officer at the Belfast-based Committee on the Administration
on Justice. ``The problem with remarks like Les Rodgers' is they
highlight that there still is a strong antipathy toward change in
the RUC.''
</P>
<P>
   And congressional staff members familiar with Rodgers' visit to
Congress earlier in the week said they were disappointed by his
uncompromising approach. ``He still seemed to be in a state of
denial about the need for serious reform,'' one senior Capitol Hill
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers vociferously rejected that assertion. ``Serious reform
means we've done something wrong,'' he said. He said many parties
in the peace process, including Sein Fein, won't be satisfied until
the RUC is disbanded completely. ``That's something I'd be
completely against,'' Rodgers said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Rodgers said he looked forward to the day when the
RUC could tear down its fortified buildings and get rid of its
guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could take a generation for things to be forgiven, though
I'd like to think it would be sooner,'' Rodgers said. ``I'm an
eternal optimist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
