<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-WWIISOLDIER25-C     06-24 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-WWIISOLDIER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black veteran to be awarded Bronze Star _ 55 years late
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When a desperate call went out for black support
troops to join all-white combat units during the Battle of the
Bulge in December 1944, Marteller Pollack Jr. didn't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately signed up, along with 4,500 other
African-Americans who were performing secondary roles in the
service. Pollack was one of 2,221 quickly accepted, given M-1
rifles and assigned to one of 41 white infantry units that were
being desegregated by necessity. There weren't enough white troops
to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack, now 79, will be rewarded for heroism with a Bronze
Star, one of the nation's highest awards for combat valor. The
medal _ delayed for reasons the Army can't specify _ will be
presented today in a military ceremony at Fort McPherson, complete
with an honor guard, a military band and several hundred troops
standing stiffly at attention.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack, a native Atlantan and a carpenter by trade, says he and
the other black men felt it was their ``duty as patriotic people''
to do all they could to beat back the Germans, who at the time had
overrun Allied positions in Belgium in what turned out to be the
bloodiest battle of World War II. The fact that the U.S. armed
forces were almost completely segregated, and blacks were mostly
relegated to supporting roles, didn't stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I opened the way for more colored to get in, even though I
knew it might kill me,'' Pollack said.
</P>
<P>
   To volunteer, black soldiers with rank had to agree to give up
their stripes and become privates again. Pollack, already serving
behind the lines in Europe, was a private at the time, but within a
few months had risen to sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   The African-Americans were called on because they were badly
needed, says Army Lt. Col. Guy Shields at the Pentagon. As combat
support troops, they had already been through some infantry
training.
</P>
<P>
   Allied headquarters issued a statement at the time conceding
``every available weapon at our disposal must be brought to bear
upon the enemy. To this end, the commanding general is happy to
offer a limited number of colored troops who have had infantry
training the privilege of joining our veteran units at the front to
deliver the knockout blow.''
</P>
<P>
   They wound up fighting shoulder-to-shoulder with white soldiers
more than three years before President Harry S. Truman ordered the
military desegregated, Shields says.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack is one of only five of the black volunteers to be
awarded the Bronze Star _ the others got theirs last year _ but he
doesn't recall ``doing nothing special. I just fought on into
Germany and then got an honorable discharge as an infantry sergeant
and came on home.''
</P>
<P>
   Shields speculates that it might have taken this long to bestow
the Bronze Star because the Army had lost track of Pollack, or
because of a fire at an Army archives center in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these men left the service before everything they
were authorized could be given to them,'' Shields says. ``They
cared more about getting home than getting another medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Pentagon spokesman, Shari Lawrence, says delayed rewards
like Pollack's are given fairly often. Usually, old veterans, their
wives or children petition the military seeking recognition.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't happen in Pollack's case.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to Atlanta to become a carpenter again, he says
he gave his war experiences little thought. He ``just went back to
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence says it's possible his unit commander or a fellow
soldier petitioned the Pentagon on Pollack's behalf at some point,
but no one knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember it too much,'' Pollack says of the fighting.
``I do remember men falling all around me, some of my friends got
shot and got killed, but I knew it was going to happen. It had to.
And I just did what I had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack adds: ``We were all supposed to be fighting for our
country. That was the job. I know a lot of us died, a lot of
colored guys. And a lot more died in there after I went through.''
</P>
<P>
   He also remembers some battle successes. ``Me and my platoon
captured a few,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel real good about it all,'' he says. ``I went because I
was an American. For the most part, there wasn't no colored in the
infantry, but I was in combat until the end of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   The military relaxed its strict segregation rules only until the
Germans were defeated in the Battle of the Bulge, Adolf Hitler's
desperate gamble to push back the Allies that almost succeeded, and
which would have certainly prolonged the war. When the war in
Europe ended, segregation became the rule again, and Pollack was
reassigned to a support unit.
</P>
<P>
   Records don't indicate how many of the black volunteers died or
were wounded in battle.
</P>
<P>
   But, says Army spokesman Shield: ``We're proud of what these
soldiers did. They made great sacrifices to do what's right, and
we're proud to give the recognition, although it's late.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack's wife, Rosa, 67, is proud, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how all this got started. One time a man came
here and talked to him, but we didn't hear any more about it,'' she
says. ``We're just shocked, and happy, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``And very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
