<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USS Atlanta relics to be presented in ceremony
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Relics from the last of five American warships named
after the city of Atlanta will be permanently loaned to the Atlanta
History Center in a ceremony today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great way to honor all men who served on the
Atlanta,'' says Robert Shaw, 75, of Hiawassee, who survived the
sinking of an earlier USS Atlanta by a Japanese torpedo near
Guadalcanal in November 1942. ``We hope this will make people
remember those who were not as fortunate as I was.''
</P>
<P>
   That ship, the third Atlanta, went down with 300 of its 700-man
crew on Nov. 13, 1942. ``It never seemed to get publicized much,''
Shaw says. ``I went through a lot of Novembers and nobody ever said
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The relics in today's ceremony will come from the submarine USS
Atlanta, which was decommissioned this year. Artifacts will include
the ship's silver bell, an enlisted man's bunk, a duffel bag and
the vessel's periscope.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 a.m. event at the history center is being sponsored by
the Atlanta Metropolitan Council of the Navy League of the United
States. The former commander of the submarine, Maurice Montana,
will be among the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Several other men who served on the ship that sank near
Guadalcanal are expected to be on hand, but Shaw said ``there's
only a few of us left.'' He joined the Navy shortly after Pearl
Harbor with 12 other Georgians who were guaranteed that they'd be
allowed to serve on the USS Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has no plans for a sixth ship named Atlanta. But Shaw
said, ``Those of us at Guadalcanal would like to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the relics ``are a good way to honor all the young men
who died, and I'm thrilled to death.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
