<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Salinger bio: His literature, life and loves
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   J.D. Salinger's troubles apparently are not over. Yes, a
collector who bought 14 letters that Salinger wrote to teenage
admirer Joyce Maynard plans to return the correspondence to the
reclusive writer, but a new book published this week not only
delves into Salinger's private life, it gives detailed directions
to his Cornish, N.H., home.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in ``J.D. Salinger: A Biography'' (Renaissance Books,
$24.95), author Paul Alexander traces Salinger's literary career,
his success after ``Catcher in the Rye,'' and his mysterious
withdrawal from the public eye. Alexander also describes Salinger's
various romances with younger women, including the teenage Oona
O'Neill before she married Charlie Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   As for Salinger's letters to Maynard, software entrepreneur
Peter Norton bought them for $156,500 at a Sotheby's auction
Tuesday. ``My intention is to do whatever he indicates to me he
wants done with them,'' Norton told The New York Times. ``He may
want them returned. He may want me to destroy them. He may not care
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Salinger had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Giants of the century: A collection of profiles about the most
influential people of the past 100 years could have been dull, but
Time magazine wisely decided to commission distinguished authors
and leaders to write about the heroes and icons of the 20th
century. Now Time, CBS and Simon &AMP; Schuster have announced they
will publish an illustrated book this fall. CBS anchorman Dan
Rather will write the foreword and Time's managing editor Walter
Isaacson will write the afterword.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the essays include Lee Iacocca on Henry Ford, Budd
Schulberg on Louis B. Mayer, Colin Powell on the American GI, Rita
Dove on Rosa Parks, Arthur M. Schlesinger on Franklin D. Roosevelt
and Salman Rushdie on Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 100 figures profiled in the book will be selected as
``Person of the Century'' and will be featured in the year-end
issue of Time and be the subject of a CBS News television special.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eye-opener: Book tie-ins to movies are nothing new, but the
edition of ``Eyes Wide Shut'' by Warner Books is unique. The book,
which won't be released until nearly a month after the film opens
July 16, includes the screenplay for the much-anticipated Stanley
Kubrick film as well as a new translation of the book on which the
movie is based: Arthur Schnitzler's 1926 novel, ``Dream Story.''
Meanwhile, Frederic Raphael, the screenwriter for the film, has
written ``Eyes Wide Open: A Memoir of Stanley Kubrick''
(Ballantine, $12 paperback), which arrives in stores this week. The
book is Raphael's account of his turbulent relationship with the
director while adapting Schnitzler's novel for the screen.
According to Raphael, Kubrick talked extensively about everything
from Julius Caesar to the Holocaust, and reminisced about Kirk
Douglas, Audrey Hepburn and other actors he directed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literary deals: The adventure books continue. Scott Cookman
has signed a six-figure deal with John Wiley for ``Ice Blink: The
Mysterious Fate of Sir John Franklin's Lost Polar Expedition.''
Cookman examines the theory that the explorers died from eating
tainted canned meat. ... Knopf has paid six figures for ``The
Northern Lights'' by Lucy Jago, the story of Norwegian scientist
Kristian Birkeland, who solved the mystery of the aurora borealis.
... British journalist Howard Sounes (``Charles Bukowski: Locked in
the Arms of a Crazy Life'') has signed a six-figure deal with
Grove/Atlantic for a major biography of folk legend Bob Dylan.
Publication is scheduled in 2001, in time for the singer's 60th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
