<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8575 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS27-COX     06-24 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Penguin bio gets to heart of Mozart's gift
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 27
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is something satisfying about the sorry spectacle of the
genius neglected,'' Peter Gay writes of the most revered name in
classical music, ``something romantic about the contrast between
the lonely artist and the philistine world in which he is forced to
live, and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a genius _ or so we imagine _ was Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart,
buried in a pauper's grave, unappreciated in his own time. It makes
for a real tear-jerker, and the Mozart that Peter Shaffer conceived
for stage and screen 15 years ago brought forth buckets.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth, as usual, is less romantic, and, as Gay deftly
shows, closer to the grain of ordinary life. ``Mozart'' is another
in Viking's Penguin Lives series, brief biographies of major
figures by contemporary writers, and it is by all odds a signal
achievement. Gay, whose first volume of his study ``The
Enlightenment'' won a National Book Award, might be the most
elegant stylist among contemporary academic historians. Here, as in
his previous works, he is gracefully in command of a vast sweep of
our cultural past.
</P>
<P>
   In fewer than 180 pages he introduces us to the Wunderkind who
was composing at age 5 and dead by age 35, traces Mozart's lifelong
emotional burdens to the expectations of a father who held himself
beyond arm's reach, and gives us an understanding of the time as
well as the man.
</P>
<P>
   The human being behind the genius
</P>
<P>
   The man was no more admirable than most of us. He was given to
crude, scatological humor, he was self-indulgent and unable to
support his family even though playing for royalty, and he never
overcame the infantile dependency his father helped create. He grew
musically, but not in other ways. It is doubtful he could have and
still have been Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   ``A child prodigy,'' Gay writes, ``is, by its nature, a
self-destroying artifact: what seems literally marvelous in a boy
will seem merely talented and perfectly natural in a young man. But
by 1772, at sixteen, Mozart no longer needed to display himself as
a little wizard; he had matured in the sonata and the symphony, the
first kind of music he composed, and now showed his gifts in new
domains: operas, the oratorio, and the earliest in a string of
superb piano concerts.''
</P>
<P>
   From childhood on, he lived on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Goethe, more than 60 years after seeing Mozart as a child
performer in Frankfurt, recalled ``the little man in his coiffure
and sword.'' Yet the age of rapt attention, as Gay writes, had not
yet dawned for classical musicians, even Mozart: ``There is a
much-reproduced painting of 1766 by Michel Barthelmy Ollivier which
shows the 10-year-old Mozart bravely at the keyboard while a
select, elegantly garbed assembly help themselves at a lavish
buffet table.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at a tender age Mozart knew he was a commodity. Leopold
Mozart had made it clear, happily raking in what the son's
performances brought in the cultural capitals of Europe. From
Salzburg to Munich to Paris to Prague to London, some combination
of the Mozarts traveled, much like the family of a modern teenage
tennis pro. ``Even though he was with his parents and sister and
the subject of flattering attentions,'' Gay tells us, ``he seems to
have felt unanchored and needy.''
</P>
<P>
   Plumbing psychological depths
</P>
<P>
   Gay is not only a historian but a psychoanalyst, wearing a
second hat that does not always fit writers or scholars well. In
his most recent books he has not hesitated to poke around in the
dark attic of a subject's mind, but he is restrained and even
common-sensical in suggesting how one particular child prodigy
became Mozart. His understanding of the period and his intuitive
grasp of his subject's inner life allow him to portray a man whose
genius was more than a gift of Providence. In particular, he sees
in the relationship between Leopold Mozart and his son an age-old
story: the father who can never be fully pleased, and the son who
cannot do enough to win the approval of the central figure in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must,'' Gay writes, ``have taken offense at his father's
scattershot and undeserved recriminations, swallowed the replies
they deserved, and then, as people with a strong conscience will,
turned his anger against himself.'' It is not a prescription for a
long life, and Mozart's ended as he was in the midst of composing
his Requiem. The tug of irony should be resisted. It was just
another piece written to order, Gay argues, and not a summation of
his lifework. He needed money. And the cause of death was certainly
not poison, as legend has had it, but probably rheumatic fever.
</P>
<P>
   As Gay writes, ``There was less pathos in his end, sad as it
was, than many have liked to think.'' But if the truth lacks the
romance of the legend, there is the consolation of knowing it has
taken 200 years to realize the full measure of Mozart's greatness.
Some, but not many, knew it in his own time. Goethe ranked him with
Shakespeare and Raphael, a judgment that would have struck many as
rash but seems obvious today. In the ups and downs of reputation,
Gay writes, the place our own time has assigned Mozart ``remains
one of the achievements of which the dismal 20th century can
rightfully boast.'' There is Mozart, and then there is everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mozart by Peter Gay. Viking Press. $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
