<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELF-PROMOTION, MADE EASIER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Calif.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Some years ago, I left the corporate world to start my own
public relations firm. Most of my work involves writing and media
relations. I love what I do, but since my divorce two years ago,
I've had trouble making ends meet. My clients seem happy, but I
obviously need to do a better job of attracting new business. Any
advice?
</P>
<P>
   A. You have been using all kinds of public relations skills to
promote your clients' message. Now it's time to put that knowledge
to work for yourself. Break out that Rolodex and start dialing for
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Your first target should be all those clients who are already
familiar _ and satisfied _ with your work. ``The idea isn't to
immediately start networking broadly, but to become more focused on
existing clients,'' said John Chuang, chief executive of Aquent, a
Boston-based networking and placement firm for independent
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cross-sell,'' Chuang advised. ``If you're doing work for a big
company, find out if another division could use your services.''
</P>
<P>
   William Shear, president of Guerrilla Marketing International, a
consulting and training firm in Mill Valley, Calif., agrees that
talking to existing clients is also the best way to start expanding
your network. ``Use them as a base, Shear said. ``Get testimonials
from them and send those out to people you want to become clients.
Get clients to call the people they know and recommend you.''
</P>
<P>
   If you aren't comfortable asking others to call for you, ask for
their suggestions on potential clients, get clearance to use their
names and work the phones yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Current clients, of course, shouldn't be your only sources,
Chuang said. Check in with everyone you know _ friends, past
clients, former colleagues from your corporate days.
</P>
<P>
   And be persistent. The biggest obstacle for most people trying
to succeed as independent contractors is not that they lack talent,
he added, but that they are not dogged enough in their
self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people become discouraged if they don't see an
immediate payoff from networking. ``They keep changing tactics,
because they think what they're doing is not working,'' Shear said.
Prepare yourself for a certain amount of rejection and just keep
going, he added.
</P>
<P>
   You also should recognize that marketing your business is just
as important as your basic work _ and perhaps more difficult.
``Starting out, you may need to spend half your time on this,''
Shear said.
</P>
<P>
   Because financial security is an immediate concern, you might
tap your network for part-time opportunities with a company. You
could accept a slightly lower hourly rate for a guaranteed, steady
amount of work.
</P>
<P>
   Companies, of course, like assigning part-time work,
particularly if they don't have to provide employee benefits, Shear
said. But such an arrangement has an advantage for you, too: It can
provide you with a financial cushion while still giving you freedom
to build your outside client base. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
