<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-GLORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO PROHIBIT FLAG DESECRATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted overwhelmingly Thursday to amend
the Constitution to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the measure said it would cover burning, but there
seemed to be some disagreement over what other assaults on the
nation's symbol of freedom would also be banned.
</P>
<P>
   The argument over whether the symbol or the freedom it
represents is more important was at the heart of a two-day debate
that began Wednesday and ended with a vote of 305-124. That was
more than enough to garner the two-thirds support required to pass
a measure aimed at amending the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the amendment, including Rep. Kevin Brady, R-The
Woodlands, suggested that the flag ought to be treated more like a
government institution, noting for example that while it may be
acceptable to criticize city council actions, it's against the law
to vandalize city hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly protect the right of every American to criticize
the government, but not to desecrate the American flag. Too many
lives have been lost defending it,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   But another Texan, Rep. Ron Paul, R-Surfside, said that lives
were lost defending the ideals of freedom and democracy envisioned
by the Constitution, not the Red, White and Blue itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I served our country to protect our freedom and our
Constitution. ... To change it because some misfits burn flags, is
a dangerous step,'' said Paul, who suggested that flag burning
ought to be protected like free speech or expression under the
First Amendment ``just like most of our rights.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paul was one of only five Texans _ and the only Republican
member of the 30-member House delegation _ to vote against the
amendment. He was joined by Democrats Lloyd Doggett of Austin,
Sheila Jackson Lee of Houston, Eddie Bernice Johnson of Dallas and
Charles Gonzalez of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
END OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vote marked the third time the House has approved
legislation calling for a flag protection amendment to be added to
the Constitution, which also would require a two-thirds vote of the
Senate and then ratification by three-fourths of the states.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved a similar amendment in 1995, but it fell
three votes short of passage in the Senate. The House also easily
passed it in 1997, but it was never taken up by the Senate that
year because there was no chance of approval.
</P>
<P>
   This year, House supporters are hopeful the outcome in the
Senate will be favorable. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., has said he hopes to have a vote on it this summer. But
the measure still appears at least two votes short of the 67 needed
in the Senate to send it on to the states for ratification, and
some Senate aides say it might not be brought up at all.
</P>
<P>
   In his argument on behalf of the amendment, Rep. Duke
Cunningham, R-Calif., noted that legislatures in 49 states _ with
the exception of Vermont _ have already passed resolutions backing
it. Cunningham, the chief sponsor of the amendment, said his
purpose was not to limit free speech, but to ban the physical
desecration of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   He said an amendment would help restore the 48 state laws
protecting the flag that were struck down by Supreme Court rulings
in 1989 and 1990. The court said flag burning was labeled a form of
free speech and expression protected under the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Although attempts to prohibit flag burning by amending the
Constitution have been primarily a Republican-driven effort, it has
cut across party lines, with some Democrats joining the move and
some Republicans deserting it.
</P>
<P>
   Even opponents say they understand the frustrations expressed by
supporters. Still, they argue that the freedoms represented by the
flag are far more important than the symbol itself. They also argue
that the number of flag desecration incidents are greatly
exaggerated and not significant enough to warrant a change in the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the threat?'' Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., asked
supporters of the amendment during the House debate. ``The real
threat to our society is not the occasional burning of the flag,
but the permanent banning of the burners. Even a despicable,
low-life malcontent has a right to disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed by the House would, if accepted by the Senate
and ratified by the states, call for the addition of a 17-word
amendment to the Constitution, which has been altered 27 times
since it was ratified in 1788.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment would read, ``The Congress shall have power to
prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Most lawmakers believe that the amendment would have no impact
at all on free-speech rights. Basic rights would still be
protected, said Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston, in offering his support
for the measure. But he added that a protection amendment would at
least ``put burning or desecrating the flag ... on the same level''
as ``yelling fire in a crowded theater,'' for which people can be
arrested and prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's too much to ask ... for protecting the
flag,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents fear that one step toward making an exception for flag
burning could spawn a movement to criminalize other forms of speech
or expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we open the doors to criminalizing constitutionally
protected expression related to the flag,'' said Rep. John Conyers,
D-Mich., ``I am afraid that there will be further efforts to limit
and censor speech or conduct that we do not like.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
