<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LED BY BIG TRADING GAINS, MORGAN STANLEY POSTS 35% INCREASE IN
EARNINGS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SHOLNN FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., demonstrating
strength in its securities trading and credit card businesses,
posted second-quarter results Thursday that beat analysts'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported that its net income in the quarter ended
May 31 rose 35 percent, to $1.15 billion, or $1.95 a diluted share,
compared with $852 million, or $1.37 a share, in the period a year
earlier. Analysts had expected profit of $1.56 a share, according
to the First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength was across the board,'' said Michael J.
Freudenstein, a managing director of J.P. Morgan. ``In particular
what stood out was that trading revenue was significantly higher
than expected, and on the securities side we saw a marked
improvement in credit quality. It was hard to identify a weak
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenue increased 23 percent, to $5.65 billion from $4.6
billion. Morgan's return on equity, one way to judge its
profitability, rose to 31 percent in the second quarter from 25
percent a year ago. It was the company's third record quarter in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's strong results come after similar reports from
Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. this
week. On Wednesday, Goldman, in its first quarterly report as a
public company, reported a 30 percent increase in profit. The day
before, Lehman also reported earnings well above analysts'
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had proof this week that prognosticating even short-term
results for securities firms has become a very difficult art,''
said Samuel G. Liss, a managing director of Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Five analysts told First Call Thursday that they were raising
their 1999 earnings estimates for Morgan Stanley to an average
$6.96 a share from a previous estimate of $6.25 a share
</P>
<P>
   Despite the solid results, shares of Morgan Stanley fell
$1.9375, to $91.3125, on a day when the rest of the market was
down. Brokerage and other financial stocks have been hurt recently
because of concern over rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Robert G. Scott, the company's chief financial officer,
expressed frustration that the company's excellent results were
overshadowed by the stock's decline. ``It's a little disappointing,
frankly, to watch a stock trade down,'' he said, adding that
investors might have driven the stock up last week on expectations
of the good profit report.
</P>
<P>
   In Morgan Stanley's securities business, net income jumped 54
percent, to $829 million. Scott pointed to record growth in
investment banking and trading for big investors as well as growth
in the retail consumer business.
</P>
<P>
   Like other firms, Morgan reported big gains from trading.
Trading revenue increased by 77 percent, to $1.9 billion. The firm
also reported a 29 percent increase in commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from underwriting new stock issues and advising
companies on mergers and acquisitions gained 3 percent, to $1
billion. The dollar volume of announced mergers and acquisitions
rose to $308 billion, compared with $196 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Net income at the company's Discover card unit increased by 23
percent, to $211 million, compared with $171 million in the period
a year earlier. Scott said that gain came from the improved credit
quality of Discover card customers and credit card holders in
general. The company reported big drops in the number of card
holders who walk away from their credit card debt and those with
balances delinquent more than 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Profit in the last leg of Morgan's business, money management,
fell 23 percent, to $111 million, even though assets managed by
Morgan Stanley rose 7 percent, to $402 billion. Scott attributed
the decline to the volatility of the merchant banking business.
</P>
</TEXT>
