<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8589 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-BELGIUM25-COX     06-24 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BELGIUM25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shelves still bare as Belgian bottlers gear up
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Berrasaa Mohammed rounded the corner of the
beverage aisle at a Delhaize supermarket here Thursday, only to
again find disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, no Coke again?'' Mohammed asked no one in particular. He
discovered the bright red shelves that usually hold his favorite
soft drink nearly empty _ nearly, except for a few 2-litre bottles
of Pepsi-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   After glancing at a store management's note asking for
customers' patience while Coca-Cola prepares for its return,
Mohammed took solace in a big bottle from the brand's archrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Coke, but how long can I wait for it?'' he asked as he
tossed the Pepsi bottle into his cart with a thud and rolled on.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the Belgian government set out the path Coca-Cola
must take to return its full line of products to stores, both
Coca-Cola Co. and Coca-Cola Enterprises are desperately trying to
get ready for Mohammed's next visit to the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   CCE, which owns the bottling plant in Antwerp that was the
target of a health safety investigation, said Thursday it had
planned to resume production at either Antwerp or its other plant
at Ghent before the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But it still will be two weeks or more before production returns
to full form, said Coca-Cola Co. spokesman Randal Donaldson.
Coca-Cola Co. provides CCE and other bottlers with the concentrate
used to produce Coke brands.
</P>
<P>
   Before CCE can get into full swing with production, it must
first complete the grim task of destroying cases upon cases of its
beverages as a safety precaution demanded by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the challenge has been that the employees have to
destroy the product before they can get to producing new product,''
Donaldson said. ``It will be next week before we can get any
product out of one of the plants.''
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian government lifted restrictions on the sale of Coke
products Wednesday, a move followed quickly by Luxembourg and the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring France lifted its restrictions Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be safe to say that we're up and running in Europe,''
Donaldson said. Coca-Cola has offered refunds to Belgians made ill
by its products and intends to pay the medical expenses of those
who became sick after drinking its products.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester also offered to buy everyone in the country of 10
million a Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a prominent toxicologist went on Belgian television
to say he accepted Coke's explanation for the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Nemery de Bellevaux, professor in toxicology at Leuven
University, told VTM television that the illnesses were probably
psychosomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying they weren't ill,'' Nemery de Bellevaux said.
``They were ill; that was obvious. But they were not poisoned.''
</P>
<P>
   The scientist said Belgians were ripe for such a response
because of recent food scares, particularly the fresh one over the
discovery of cancer-causing dioxin in animal feed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have the feeling that our food is poisoned, and so it
was, partly, with the dioxin case,'' Nemery de Bellevaux said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
