<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-CCE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recall to cost CCE about $60 million
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Enterprises estimates the massive recall of
its products because of the European health scare will cost $60
million.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest soft drink bottler also said there will be a
``negative impact on sales, cash operating profit and earnings per
share in the second quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company said the extent of the lost sales and
profits ``is difficult to determine until the company can assess
the effect of product reintroduction campaigns in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Marc Cohen of Goldman Sachs estimated Thursday that
the company's cash operating profit will be cut by $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very significant hit for the quarter,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Cohen reduced his second-quarter earnings estimate
to 21 cents a share, from 27 cents. That does not include the
nonrecurring $60 million charge for the recall, which would reduce
earnings per share by another 8 cents, CCE said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen was more pessimistic than some other analysts. A First
Call survey of analysts Thursday came up with a consensus of 23
cents a share for the quarter. That was down from 28 cents before
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it may recoup some of the $60 million cost of
the recall through insurance. About 14 million cases were affected
by the recall, which amounts to less than 1 percent of CCE's annual
volume.
</P>
<P>
   Two CCE plants, one in Antwerp, Belgium, and the other in
Dunkirk, France, were blamed for causing illnesses in nearly 250
people who drank the bottler's beverages.
</P>
<P>
   To try to win back consumers, both CCE and Coca-Cola Co. will
share in the costs of an increased marketing and advertising
campaign that will extend into the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies hope that consumers regain confidence in a
relatively short time, so that the problem does not carry over into
next year's financial results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that we can minimize the short-term impact on
sales, and we are confident that this situation will not materially
affect financial results in the year 2000 and beyond,'' Henry
Schimberg, CCE's president and chief executive officer, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Wilkins, an analyst for Deutsche Bank, generally agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the consumer reacceptance of Coke will occur in a
relatively short period of time,'' Wilkins said. ``For the most
part, I think people are rational.''
</P>
<P>
   For fiscal 1999, Cohen predicts CCE will earn 23 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The First Call consensus is now 25 cents, down from 30 cents
before the incident. Last year, the company earned 28 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the seasonal nature of its business, CCE generally
makes money in the second and third quarters and loses money in the
first and fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Cohen reduced by a penny a share his second-quarter
estimate for Coca-Cola earnings because of the crisis. He now
expects the company to make 40 cents a share, instead of 41 cents.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, CCE fell 68 3/4 cents Thursday to close at
$31.68 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Coca-Cola Co., which owns 40 percent of CCE, rose 87
1/2 cents to close at $62.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
