<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8591 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      06-24 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTER DEFEATS DOUBLES PARTNER BJORKMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ They've seen more of each other in the last two days
than some celebrity couples do in the course of an entire marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But such is the ambivalent nature of tennis unions that they
were partners one afternoon, adversaries the next _ which, come to
think of it, does describe some celebrity marriages. At any rate,
Patrick Rafter proved the better half Thursday as he barely beat
darkness and his doubles accomplice of 24 hours earlier, Jonas
Bjorkman, 6-2, 7-6, 6-7, 6-2. It was a 2-hour 57-minute endurance
test that concluded the Wimbledon festivities on a day when a
record 40,312 zealots stampeded through the All England Club gates.
</P>
<P>
   This duel in the gloaming on Court 1 came in the wake of a
2-hour 40-minute exercise in cooperation Wednesday when Rafter and
Bjorkman, the third-seeded doubles duo here, won a five-set
first-round struggle against Brent Haygarth and Marius Barnard. And
they'll be reunited Friday for another go at doubles, unless
they're sick of one another by then.
</P>
<P>
   Small chance of that, since both understand the dictates of
their profession, though facing one's regular ally is hardly a
match made in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's going to happen when you go into a
tournament,'' said Bjorkman, ``so you just go out and let the best
man win, and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   This time that was Rafter, though that hasn't always been the
case. The two-time defending US Open champion and No. 2 singles
seed at Wimbledon evened his career record against Bjorkman at 4-4.
But his old buddy, with whom he won this year's Australian Open
doubles crown, still gave him fits. After a first-set breeze,
Rafter was forced to a second-set tiebreaker, which he captured
handily, 7-3. He wasn't as fortunate in the third set, when
Bjorkman survived match point at 5-6, then prolonged the ordeal
with a 9-7 tiebreaker decision.
</P>
<P>
   By then, both the combatants and the conditions were entering
the twilight zone, and Rafter petitioned umpire Kim Craven to
suspend the match. Craven informed him that tournament referee Alan
Mills wanted the proceedings to continue _ to the roaring crowd's
delight and Rafter's displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Alan Mills isn't playing, so how's he going to judge
that?' '' recalled Rafter. ``I don't see much point in playing
four, five more games and walking off.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter was able to take care of business before sundown, but
neither man was in much shape to walk off. In the final set, both
soaked their towels and chewed ravenously on bananas during
changeovers, and Bjorkman, laying flat out at courtside, required
treatment for a pulled leg muscle he believes was a souvenir from a
slippery surface Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorkman vows that it won't force his withdrawal from doubles,
but Rafter will understand if it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the attitude for doubles that if we're not ready to
play or it's going to interfere with our singles, then we'll give
it a miss,'' he said. ``We've always had that arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why their union can withstand the occasional
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, notorious Court 2 _ which didn't earn its
nickname, ``The Graveyard of Champions,'' because of its curative
powers _ claimed another notable victim, No. 7 women's seed Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario, who bowed to Lisa Raymond, 7-6, 6-1. The former
French and US Open winner joined a notable memorial list that
includes Ilie Nastase, John McEnroe, Jimmy Connors, Arthur Ashe,
Boris Becker, Pat Cash, and Andre Agassi _ all winners of major
tournaments who were interred in the emerald tomb across from
Centre Court.
</P>
<P>
   Even one who avoided regicide, 1996 Wimbledon king Richard
Krajicek, is duly daunted by the court's reputation and his
experiences on it. After easily handling Todd Woodbridge, 7-5, 6-4,
6-4, in the day's first match on Court 2, the No. 5 seed said, ``I
don't have my best memories on 2. I have lost to (Arnaud) Boetsch
one year. I've lost in the first round one year to (Darren) Cahill.
And the year I won, I played my toughest match, my worst match _
however you want to say it _ against Brett Steven. So somehow maybe
it does play with your mind a little bit, especially in the
beginning. When you come out there, you almost want to ask the
referee to measure from the baseline to the back fence, it's so
small.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Agassi found Court 1 more comfortable as he dominated
Guillermo Canas, 6-3, 6-4, 6-3. The No. 4 seed, still cresting from
his surprise French Open win that made him the fifth man ever to
capture the career Grand Slam, now has another quest: becoming the
first since Bjorn Borg (1978-80) to hold the French and Wimbledon
titles in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Ivanisevic would be happy with one major title, especially
after three runner-up finishes here, including last year. The No.
10 seed stayed in the hunt, but with some difficulty, shaking off
Sandon Stolle, 7-6, 6-4, 4-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Defending women's champion Jana Novotna, seeded fifth and
virtually unnoticed amid the furor over top seed Martina Hingis's
first-round ouster and No. 2 Steffi Graf's second-round scare,
quietly removed a difficult obstacle from her path. With a 6-3, 6-1
decision, she got even with Sylvia Plischke, who had beaten her at
the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis slayer Jelena Dokic _ the qualifier who is so new to
these surroundings that she still isn't sure whether the cream goes
on the strawberries or the strawberries go in the cream _ had a
considerably tougher time against a considerably lesser opponent.
Unseeded Katarina Studenikova pushed her to the limit, 6-0, 4-6,
8-6, as Dokic rallied from a 4-2 deficit in the deciding game.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't play as well as Martina did,'' said Dokic, ``and
Martina forced me to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Studenikova merely forced her to escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
