<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-FRANCE25-COX     06-24 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-FRANCE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    France lifts partial ban, says problem wasn't at factory
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The French government Thursday lifted its partial ban on
the sale of Coca-Cola soft drinks after declaring them safe.
</P>
<P>
   But company officials acknowledged that their work has only
begun to restore their brand's good name in Western Europe after a
health scare erupted two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   French food safety officials determined there was no evidence
that Coca-Cola's beverages were contaminated at a factory in the
northern city of Dunkirk. The decision in France came a day after
officials in neighboring Belgium completely lifted a ban there.
</P>
<P>
   The Dunkirk plant, which employs 240 and produced 1.5 million
cans last year, could resume production as soon as today.
</P>
<P>
   Some supermarkets in Paris were restocking their shelves with
cans of Coca-Cola just hours after the morning announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The top executive at Coca-Cola Enterprises, which owns the plant
in Dunkirk, said the French decision should remove any doubts about
the quality of Coca-Cola beverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any allegation or insinuation that beverages produced at the
Dunkirk plant are unsafe is factually, medically and scientifically
unfounded,'' Henry Schimberg, president and chief executive officer
of CCE, said in a statement after the lifting of the French ban.
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola and CCE are left to counter lingering, unanswered
questions over why nearly 250 people became ill after drinking the
companies' brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we don't know what caused those
illnesses,'' said Stephane Muracciole, a representative of France's
consumer affairs ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola had maintained that the problems in France were caused
by a foul odor that came from the bottom of cans transported in
treated wooden pallets.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, CCE executives said an internal
investigation determined that 800 out of 150,000 wooden pallets
used to transport beverages were contaminated with the chemical
phenol, which is used as a disinfectant.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical, which ``polluted the bottom of the cans,'' created
a foul smell that caused consumers in France and Belgium to feel
ill, said Dominique Reiniche, president of Coca-Cola Enterprises
France.
</P>
<P>
   Reiniche said the problem resulted from a ``malfunction in the
distribution chain'' that has been corrected.
</P>
<P>
   She said the company ``profoundly regretted'' the distress and
inconvenience caused by the bad odors.
</P>
<P>
   But in the public mind, uncertainty is likely to persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been holding on to this one to get a refund,'' said Jean
Luc Gassean, a Paris hotel clerk, producing a can from his lunch
sack. He said it had been there since the government banned sales
on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think it is safe to drink it?'' he asked a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola executives recognize they must rebuild public
confidence after the biggest product recall in the company's
113-year history.
</P>
<P>
   With the reappearance of Coca-Cola, Coca-Cola Light (the
European version of Diet Coke), Sprite and Fanta on store shelves,
the company will launch a massive advertising and promotional blitz
beginning this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be the familiar theme ``Always Coca-Cola,'' but only in
French: ``Toujours Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's Web site for French consumers and print ads in
newspapers this week have declared that the quality of its brands
is ``beyond reproach.'' A toll-free number also has been set up to
invite consumers to call with questions or complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The first reports of illnesses emerged in Belgium two weeks ago,
and the crisis quickly spread to other European countries,
including France, the Netherlands and Luxembourg. These are all
countries served by CCE.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lifting of the sales ban, a separate judicial
inquiry into the health scare is ongoing. A French prosecutor
opened the case Monday after traces of rat poison were discovered
on the outside of one can.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Muguet, the state prosecutor in Dunkirk, said his probe
would proceed in an effort to determine the cause of the illnesses.
He told reporters Thursday that his investigation is not meant to
suggest wrongdoing by Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not accusing them of misleading anyone or of hiding
anything,'' Muguet said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, by the evening Thursday, an anchorman on French
television TF2 was declaring, ``The crisis for Coke is ended in
France.''
</P>
<P>
   France trails most other Western European countries in its
per-capita consumption of Coca-Cola products.
</P>
<P>
   But for those with a taste for Coca-Cola, they never really had
to do without. Fountain sales were never interrupted. Neither were
sales of Coca-Cola soft drinks in bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
