<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLD-BANK-NYT &LR;      06-24 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TO GET WORLD BANK LOAN DESPITE U.S. OBJECTIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)   By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The World Bank overruled the United States Thursday
and approved a $160 million antipoverty loan for China. It agreed,
however, to delay financing for the resettlement of 58,000 farmers
in a traditionally ethnic Tibetan area until an independent review
board determines whether the program meets the bank's environmental
and resettlement standards.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to postpone payment for that portion of the loan
was in part a last-minute effort by the president of the World
Bank, James Wolfensohn, to keep the United States from opposing the
loan.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone call Wednesday evening, however, Wolfensohn
apparently failed to convince the Treasury Secretary-designate,
Lawrence Summers, that American objections to the resettlement
program had been fully addressed. The United States, in an unusual
breach between the Bank and its largest shareholder, still voted
against the project, as did Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has such a small World Bank program, especially one aimed
at helping some of the world's poorest farmers, attracted such
controversy. In this case, the plan to move farmers who earn
roughly $40 a year to more fertile land ran afoul of objections
from pro-Tibetan groups, whose cause _ autonomy or independence for
Tibet _ has become a rallying call for opponents of China's
Communist government.
</P>
<P>
   The groups said that the voluntary resettlement of the farmers
would dilute the population of ethnic Tibetans in western Qinghai
province, which lies on the Tibetan Plateau north of the Tibet
Autonomous Region. The farmers, about 40 percent of whom are ethnic
Chinese and the remainder Hui Muslim and other minority groups,
would be moved from the northeastern part of Qinghai.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics compiled by the World Bank and the State Department
suggest that, in fact, the ethnic composition of the area would not
change radically. But the issue quickly caught the attention of
Congress, came up during Summers' confirmation hearings, and became
enmeshed in the tensions between Washington and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   World Bank officials said Thursday that they expected the
program would ultimately go ahead, but only after substantial
modifications to assure that several environmental objections have
been addressed _ and to ensure that China does not use the program
to dilute the presence of Tibetans in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the harshest critics of China should prefer this solution
to having the entire project canceled,'' Wolfensohn said in an
interview Thursday afternoon, after he had flown back from a trip
to Europe to quell the dispute over the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``China didn't need our $40 million to resettle these farmers,''
he said, referring to the portion of the loan that would go to this
move. ``But now they have agreed to a further study, and to allow
foreign visitors into the area, unattended by Chinese officials, to
assess what is happening. That is a big breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfensohn's proposal for an independent inspection of the
project by a three-member fact-finding body, appointed by the
bank's board, was supported by the Chinese government. But only
hours earlier, Beijing had accused Washington of interfering in
Chinese domestic affairs by seeking to block the project.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Chinese Foreign Ministry, Zhang Qiyue,
said that the American concerns were politically motivated ``on the
pretext that this will undermine the status of Tibetans.''
</P>
<P>
   The compromise, however, apparently did not convince either
pro-Tibetan groups or the United States. They said that the project
had been rushed through the Bank's review process, largely because
later this month China will lose its eligibility for the
40-year-long, no-interest loans provided to the world's poorest
nations. Now classified as a richer country, China will have to
compete for loans at interest rates closer to what commercial banks
charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration insists that, in its haste, the Bank
never conducted satisfactory environmental studies of the effects
of moving the farmers. But the real objections centered on the
concern that the Tibetan influence in the region would be watered
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this project never should have gone to the board,''
said John L. Ackerley, the president of the International Campaign
for Tibet. ``We don't think the bank has any business diluting
ethnic populations.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank argues that its poverty reduction program would benefit
1.7 million of China's poorest people. It was designed, the bank
said, to help farmers escape eroded lands where malnourishment is
common. It would also improve health, education and employment
opportunities for people in some of the country's most inaccessible
villages, bank officials said, by providing farmers with seeds and
fertilizers, basic roads and clean drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Though the bank never says so, it also provides Western aid
workers and observers with an outpost in a remote and politically
sensitive corner of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are some of the best projects in the bank,'' said
Wolfensohn, an Australian-born former investment banker who was
appointed to his post by the Clinton administration. ``I've seen
barren areas transformed to look like they are as lush as
Switzerland.''
</P>
<P>
   After the independent board reports its findings, the bank's
board of directors will determine whether to release the $40
million portion of the loan that was frozen Thursday. The United
States has about 18 percent of the voting power on the board. But
apart from Germany, it had no allies Thursday in its effort to stop
the China loan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
