<SLUG> BC-DELAYED-FLIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS FLIGHT DELAYED 24 HOURS, PASSENGERS IRATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RYAN DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A 24-hour delay in their flight to Paris left
passengers on American Airlines Flight 146 in a state of revolt
Thursday at a time when the airline industry and Congress are
talking of the need for a passenger Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The American flight was supposed to leave Logan Airport at 6:10
p.m. Wednesday. But after numerous delays, punctuated by airline
excuses and angry passenger reaction, it finally took off at 5:45
p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we were hostages,'' said passenger Rosemarie
Beskind of Hanover, N.H., describing the hour-by-hour announcements
of delays due to mechanical problems Wednesday night before the
flight was cancelled at 10:30 p.m..
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one more instance of an airline being arrogant and
totally disorganized,'' passenger Theo Melas-Kyriazi of Brookline,
said after American failed to deliver on the promise it made
Wednesday night to get Paris-bound passengers off by 10:30 a.m.
Thursday. The crew that was supposed to fly the plane couldn't
because they didn't have the federally required hours of downtime
from the night before.
</P>
<P>
   An American spokeswoman in Chicago said mechanics ran into
trouble Wednesday night trying to find a bolt to fix the engine
cooling system. But the airline should have known that the crew
would not have been able to take off this morning, spokeswoman Mary
Frances Fagan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dropped the ball,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan defended the actions of American's people against
passenger complaints, however. ``To the passengers it may have
appeared (employees) were not very organized,'' said Fagan, ``but
appearances are sometimes deceiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the snafus on Flight 146 come at a time when passenger
complaints have caused the airlines to plan the implementation of
the Bill of Rights. Moreover, people stranded in a snowstorm on a
Northwest Airlines flight in Detroit in January are contemplating a
class action suit.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before the alleged lunacy at Logan began, the Senate
Commerce Committee passed the passenger Bill of Rights, a measure
aimed at helping people like those stranded at Logan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll find a lot of people supporting that here,''
said passenger Michael McElroy of Groton.
</P>
<P>
   The Bill of Rights includes a clause that requires airlines to
provide passengers with honest information about delays,
cancellations and diversions, David Fuscus, a spokesman for the Air
Transport Association, said.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers said truthful information was hard to come by at
Logan on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had us wait for hours, continuously telling us that the
flight would leave in an hour,'' said Jean Matheson of Newton.
</P>
<P>
   Just before leaving Logan Thursday, passengers angrily recounted
the frustrating events of Wednesday night and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wenesday, the daily flight to Orly International Airport in
Paris was supposed to take off at 6:10 p.m..
</P>
<P>
   At 6:10, they were told it would leave at 7.
</P>
<P>
   At 7, they were told it would leave at 8.
</P>
<P>
   At 8, the pilot told them the plane was fixed and they would
``definitely'' leave that night.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 they were told it would leave at 10.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:30 the flight was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers said they didn't receive dinner vouchers until
almost midnight. They said confusion erupted when American
employees could not find taxi and hotel vouchers, but eventually
American paid for hotel rooms and taxis.
</P>
<P>
   American told passengers to return for a 10:30 a.m. flight
Thursday, but that too was canceled. The flight finally left at
5:45 p.m. because if it left earlier a curfew at Orly would have
prevented the Boeing 767-300 from landing.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, the passengers each received a $1,000 voucher
for future travel, a letter of apology and a promise from the
airline to pay for all unused Paris hotel rooms from Thursday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
