<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-PROFILE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From one-man start up to major Internet player
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The MindSpring story is the stuff legends are made of.
</P>
<P>
   In countless speeches and interviews, Chairman and founder
Charles Brewer has honed the tale of how a bright young man looking
for a business to start wound up running the fourth-largest
Internet service provider in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer founded MindSpring in his appartment in the Ansley Park
section of Atlanta where he employed himself as founder, chairman,
product manager and customer service representative. In his spare
time, he also tried desperately to spread the word about his
service via Usenet newsgroups and word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Later as the company grew, Brewer moved into modest office space
on West Peachtree Street. Subscribers, analysts and consumers were
charmed by Brewer's low-key self deprecating style, the lawn
furniture decorating his office and his three-legged dog Louie.
When Brewer founded the company in 1994, the Internet was a hippie
wonderland of mavericks, entrepreneurs and hip Web geeks looking to
break even doing work they loved. Brewer's now-legendary core
values and beliefs, which guide the company, also helped the
company's reputation as the type of ISP the Internet's earliest
adopters would want to use.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1994, MindSpring had a few hundred customers
and had attracted the attention of ITC Holding and it decided to
invest in the company. ITC Chairman Cam Lanier had a long record of
building successful and profitable telecommunications companies.
The ITC influence would be one of the major drivers in MindSpring's
overall philosphy of keeping an eye on the bottom line and working
toward profitability. That, combined with Brewer's commitment to
providing service and support to MindSpring users, separated them
from the pack of companies in the ISP industry.
</P>
<P>
   ITC's funding helped MindSpring expand to eventually become the
largest ISP in the Southeast. In 1996 the company went public,
trading under the NASDAQ symbol MSPG.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, MindSpring was the largest ISP in the Southeast with
about 350,000 subscribers. In March, the stock took its first huge
leap as Internet stocks began to take off. Takeover rumors were
rampant, but MindSpring insisted it had no plans to sell the
company. Instead as the stock prices soared, MindSpring began a
string of acquisitions culminating with the SpryNet acquistion in
1998. The acquisition of Netcom for $245 million in 1999 doubled
MindSpring's subscriber base and made it a major industry player.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with 1.2 million subscribers, MindSpring has progressed
from a funky start-up, to one of the top Internet companies in the
United States. In January, Brewer talked about the problems of
becoming a major corporation while trying to hold on to the core
values he founded the company with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Net is going from being a relatively minor and kind or
quirky branch of the telecommunications business to being the main
thing,'' he said. ``It's certainly something I never anticipated
when I started the company and its very exciting for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer also talked about the conflicts facing a company that had
grown from a one-man operation into a million-dollar corporation.
``As we got bigger, some things have gotten harder and in other
ways things have gotten easier,'' he said. ``I compare it to
gravity. The bigger we get it seems like there's a force trying to
suck us back to being like any other company.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
