u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COCA-COLA-EUROPE-965&AMP;     06-24 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCA-COLA-EUROPE-965&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA FACES TASK OF REGAINING CONSUMER CONFIDENCE IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BORNEM, Belgium _ Sixteen days ago, Sasha Cockx bought his
midday Coke at the School of St. Mary and flipped back the
bottlecap to collect the token underneath. Collecting 500 points _
one from each small bottle, three from a large one _ could produce
a cellular telephone for only about $75, the 14-year-old scholar
said. It is a prize he is not likely to collect.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after he drank the Coke, his head began to ache and his
stomach hurt. His friend Timothy Alen, who drank two Cokes, even
though both he and Cockx said they thought the soda had smelled
strange, said his knees started to tremble and he felt nauseated.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, both boys were on their way to the St. Joseph's
Clinic in this neat, prosperous town of 20,000 people to be told
that they were suffering from what a physician there called
``probable intoxication.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never drink Coke again,'' Cockx said Thursday. That is
exactly the sentiment Coca-Cola Co. fears most in Belgium and many
other parts of Europe after the biggest recall in its 113-year
history, caused by the experiences of people like Alen and Cockx
who blame Coke for their sickness. Since then, Coca-Cola products
have been under suspicion in European countries ranging from
Portugal to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The routine lunchtime drink was the beginning of a nightmare for
the Atlanta-based company, which has now discovered that the
venerable Coke brand is vulnerable, not just to lapses in quality
control that may have led to the contamination of its products, but
to the shifting perceptions and political sensitivities of its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   First, Coca-Cola recalled 2.5 million bottles around this area
of Belgium, 25 miles northwest of Brussels. Then, Coca-Cola plants
in Antwerp and Ghent were ordered closed. ``Quite honestly, we let
the people of Belgium down,'' said M. Douglas Ivester, the
Coca-Cola chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Only on Wednesday, when the government lifted a 10-day ban, was
the giant American company permitted to restart production in
Belgium. (France followed suit Thursday, permitting a bottling
plant at Dunkirk, which had supplied the Belgian market, to
reopen.) And whatever the financial cost to the company, the
challenges in regenerating faith in its brand may only be
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coca-Cola has said they'll pay the medical expenses, but
there's a moral responsibility, too,'' said Odilon Hermans, the
director of the School of St. Mary, whose 280 students are 13 and
14 years old and which was unusual among the six schools here
because in addition to other beverages, it sold Coke to its pupils
to augment their lunch-packs from home. ``For two weeks now the
children have not been so good. The parents are distressed. Four
pupils are still off school.''
</P>
<P>
   The school, he said, has instructed a lawyer to write to
Coca-Cola saying it holds the company legally as well as morally
responsible. Altogether, he said, 39 children at his school were
taken ill, 33 on the first day of the crisis and six more the
following day. All underwent throat X-rays and urine and blood
tests. Some needed to use respirators. Fifteen were hospitalized
overnight. Two days later, some were still complaining of sickness
and were sent home again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not psychological or mass hysteria,'' Hermans said,
referring to suggestions by the Belgian government that some of the
scores of Coke drinkers who subsequently reported becoming ill
might have overreacted _ a view shared by some sociologists and
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, in this town, as elsewhere in Belgium, there is a
questioning not so much of consumers' reactions but of the
company's and the government's.
</P>
<P>
   The Coke crisis erupted at a particularly fraught moment. Across
Europe, supermarket shoppers have begun to question the provenance
of products on store shelves. And in Belgium the government was
reeling from a scandal over the contamination of meat and poultry
traced to the discovery of the cancer-causing chemical dioxin in
animal feed grains.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government faced elections on June 13, so anything
that smacked of negligence in the food chain carried heavy
political freight. Then came the Coca-Cola recall _ just days
before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Spiessens, an administrator in a local mental health clinic,
said: ``There had been the dioxin business. Elections were coming.
This was the last straw.''
</P>
<P>
   As he shopped Thursday at an outlet of Colruyt, a discount
Belgian supermarket, where the soda section offered mineral water,
Pepsi and a local brand of cola called Eldorado, Spiessens
commented: ``Most people still have doubts. They fear that they
haven't been told the whole truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the government in Brussels said on Wednesday that it did
not accept Coca-Cola's explanation, which attributed the illnesses
to traces of sulfur used to produce carbon dioxide bubbles in the
soda, and to creosote, an oily liquid distilled from tar that is
used on wooden storage pallets as a preservative and disinfectant.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hugo Bontinck, medical director of the St. Joseph's Clinic,
said he was one of the first physicians to treat the sick children
here. ``Mainly they had headaches, dizziness, nausea and muscular
vibration,'' he said in an interview Thursday. ``Some of them were
vomiting, but there was no fever.''
</P>
<P>
   He, like the government, has doubts about Coca-Cola's version of
events. ``The mechanism that created the symptoms is not very
clear,'' he said, arguing that the contaminants identified by
Coca-Cola were found in such small amounts that ``it is not so
likely that these low concentrations can explain the symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he said, the cause of the sickness may never be
determined because the contaminants may have dispersed rapidly
enough so that they did not show up in the blood and urine samples.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Belgian toxicologists, he said, are examining the plant extracts
and sulfide gases used in the recalled Coke, trying to establish
whether it had higher-than-normal levels of substances that are
usually found in Coke. But that seemed to be problematic as well,
because the formula for Coke is secret _ so secret, in fact, that
it resides in a locked bank vault in Atlanta and even top
executives are said to be unable to see it without a formal vote by
the company's directors.
</P>
<P>
   A senior government official in Brussels said investigators were
examining whether any of a staggering 15,000 substances could have
caused the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a marketing drive to reclaim the public trust,
Ivester, the Coca-Cola chief, said on Wednesday that he would buy
everyone in Belgium a Coke. That might not be too enticing for
people who were sickened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't accept it,'' Alen, one of the stricken
14-year-olds, said shortly before his year-end English exam
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola might have better fortune with people like Diane
Heymans, a worker in one of the light industrial plants fringing
this town. She stopped buying Coke only when it was recalled, she
said at the Colruyt store Thursday after buying a bottle of
Eldorado cola, whose label proclaims ``The Original Taste.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll buy Coke again as soon as it comes back onto the
shelves,'' she said. ``I'm not afraid. I'm sure it's safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe or not, it will disappear from the School of St. Mary. ``We
had decided even before this to stop selling Coke at school,'' said
the director. ``We thought there was too much sugar in it for the
children's health.''
</P>
</TEXT>
