<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-PREMIUMS-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS BACKING AWAY FROM CLINTON'S PLANS FOR MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Ill., Wash.)  (rk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Medicare officials said Thursday that they had told
the White House that its initial hopes of offering coverage of
prescription drugs for a premium of no more than $25 a month were
unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, House Democrats said they had become nervous
about the plan being drafted by President Clinton to revamp
Medicare, because they feared that the prospect of higher premiums
could alarm elderly voters.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare generally does not cover prescription drugs for people
outside the hospital, even though elderly people fill an average of
18 prescriptions a year.
</P>
<P>
   Federal health officials and actuaries who work for the Medicare
program said the premium for new drug benefits would have to be at
least as high as the existing premium for coverage of doctors'
services, $45.50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats said they worried about being drawn into an
election-year battle over details of the Medicare plan that Clinton
intends to unveil next week.
</P>
<P>
   Senior House Democrats conveyed their concerns to John D.
Podesta, the White House chief of staff, at a meeting on Wednesday
night in the office of Dick Gephardt, the House Democratic leader.
And they elaborated on their concerns in interviews Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers said they were frustrated at their inability to
confirm details of the president's plan, even though they would be
expected to defend it.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of the Democrats' message, as described by one
lawmaker, was: ``Don't make us walk a plank that will blow up on
us.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, White House officials have refused to rule out the idea
of charging higher Medicare premiums to high-income beneficiaries.
House Democrats said they had told Podesta that the president would
be courting political disaster if he proposed ``income-related
premiums.'' They said that such a proposal reminded them, and could
remind many elderly voters, of the surtax that Congress adopted in
1988, as part of a bill to provide catastrophic health insurance
coverage under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The law provoked such an outcry from the elderly that it was
repealed a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., said the House Democrats had told the
White House that Clinton's proposal, if not carefully designed,
could create a ripe political target for Republicans and could do
political damage to the presidential hopes of Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Our message to the White House was, `Don't sell us out,''' Stark
said. ``I have heard from people inside the administration,
including high-level health policy-makers, who worry that the
president will cut a deal with the Republicans on Medicare in
October.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark said the secrecy of the White House process and the
administration's last-minute rush to meet self-imposed deadlines
reminded him of the way in which Clinton's proposal for universal
health insurance was developed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., said: ``If the president provides
too many specifics, he will simply give the Republicans ammunition
for an endless battle over the future of Medicare. That would be
wasteful and stupid. The issue of Medicare can't be dealt with on
the back of a galloping horse for public relations purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the president returned to the United States from Europe
around 1 a.m. on Wednesday, White House aides have been scrambling
to get his approval for details of his Medicare plan.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, said Thursday
that the president would announce his proposals next week, although
there are still several unresolved questions about the financing
and the scope of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the president's plan would be ``comprehensive,''
Lockhart declined to characterize it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn., said, ``I was delighted that Podesta
came up to solicit our views, and I expressed my opinion that
Medicare should not be means-tested in any way.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Likewise, Rep. Jan Schakowsky, D-Ill., said: ``The president's
Medicare plan must not include premiums based on income, and must
not increase out-of-pocket costs for seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schakowsky, a former director of the Illinois State Council
of Senior Citizens, said she told Podesta: ``Don't do it. It's bad
policy, and it's very bad politics.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, elderly people from Ms. Schakowsky's group jeered Dan
Rostenkowksi, then chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee,
because they held him responsible for the surtax, or ``supplemental
premium,'' that was to have financed prescription drug coverage for
about one-sixth of Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, William Roth, R-Del., who is chairman of the
finance committee, said Thursday that he intended to move Medicare
legislation through his committee this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to put together a bipartisan Medicare bill,'' said
Ginny Flynn, a spokeswoman for Roth. ``He wants to include a drug
benefit for the sickest elderly and for low-income elderly
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
