<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-FINANCIAL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thriving Mindspring stock splits 2-for-1
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since its initial public offering in March 1996,
shares of MindSpring Enterprises have shot up along with the
company's national presence.
</P>
<P>
   Had you invested $1,000 in MindSpring stock March 14, 1996, and
kept it there, you would have $29,758, based on Thursday's closing
price of $82.12 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Atlanta-based MindSpring originally sold for a
split-adjusted $2.67. Shares of the fourth-largest Internet access
provider are due to split 2-for-1 today. This year, while
MindSpring's share price has grown more slowly than in the past, it
has bucked the trend set by the rest of the Internet stocks. The
company's shares are up 34.5 percent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Russ, an analyst with Atlanta-based Robinson-Humphrey,
said MindSpring's stock suffered initially because of a perception
by investors that ISPs are a commodity. In 1996 and 1997, there was
a lot of competition and very little to differentiate the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring had its first positive cash flow in mid-to-late 1997,
which is what started the stock moving, Russ said. In August 1997,
MindSpring traded for about $5 a share. By the end of that year,
shares had more than doubled. By the end of 1998, the first year
MindSpring turned a profit, shares were selling for $70.
</P>
<P>
   ``MindSpring management recognized that building a brand name
and offering quality customer service can make an ISP stand out,''
Russ said. ``It earned its first profit in 1998 and showed you can
really make money. The stock price snowballed from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING25-COX     06-24 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring seeks to join industry joinings
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring's Thursday announcement that it was ``in
discussions'' with businesses about ``possible business
combinations'' added more grist to the rapidly spinning rumor mill
that the computer hardware industry is looking to add Internet
properties to its holdings.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring's shares rose $3.50 to $82.12 1/2 and are up 45
percent in the past eight days, giving it a market value of about
$2.52 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of California-based competitor Earthlink, another
Internet service provider, soared Thursday on news South
Dakota-based Gateway Inc. was considering buying the company.
MSNBC.com, which seems to be computer-rumor central, also reported
Thursday that America Online was in talks to produce AOL-brand PCs
in conjunction with Microworkz.com, a manufacturer of inexpensive
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Microworkz.com Chief Executive Rick Latman was later reported by
Bloomberg News as saying his company was talking with several
''major ISPs'' to provide service on its new $199 iToaster
Internet-ready computer, which has no Microsoft Corp. software or
floppy disk drive. The iToaster is expected to begin shipping in
mid-July. ''We are talking to AOL about the potential of AOL
getting new subscribers from Microworkz machines,'' Latman said.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from any hardware merger discussions is
Midtown-based MindSpring. Spokesman Ed Hansen said Thursday's
cryptic release was in response to rampant speculation that the ISP
was also considering an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   However, as the Internet/hardware speculation continues, Jupiter
Communications broadband and telecommunications strategies director
Abhi Chaki says it would be wrong to count MindSpring out of the
derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all boils down to the concept of who distributes Internet
access,'' he says. Earlier this year, Jupiter issued a report
predicting that companies not currently in the business of
providing Internet access will begin offering Internet access. That
someday looks like today, as more and more partnerships and
alliances are announced in an increasingly consolidated
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more and more difficult to survive going solo,'' he says.
``That's what this is all about, partnering and partnering
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaki says the notion of MindSpring or Earthlink teaming with a
PC maker could be a good move for both parties. ``What Gateway is
doing with Gateway.com is promoting their goods and services all
the time,'' he says. ``They still have a relationship with the
customer after they buy a PC. They don't want to make it a one-time
sale as PC margins are eroding. On top of that, the computer
companies get a nice recurring revenue stream from partnering with
an ISP.''
</P>
<P>
   Still there might be other suitors for MindSpring, including
telecommunications and cable companies. There's also an outside
chance that MindSpring's stated desire to see its service delivered
via the broadband cable TV wires has caught the interest of a cable
company looking to expand its subscriber base. Chaki says that the
Excite/AtHome cable modem service could be considering acquiring a
dial-up ISP like MindSpring with the eventual goal of converting
them to cable modem subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Chaki says a potential alliance between MindSpring and a PC
maker or telecommunications company would definitely give
MindSpring the financial ammunition it needs to continue building
its subscriber base to eventually reach its stated goal of becoming
the No. 2 ISP in the country behind America Online, which has 17
million subscribers, compared with MindSpring's 1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would give them more financial reach,'' Chaki said.
``MindSpring is a very frugal company. For once they could take
their eyes off the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin, Texas-based Dell Computer Corp. already offers ISP
service with its computers in Europe, and Michael Dell confirmed
this week that Dell was going to announce an ISP relationship later
this summer. He wouldn't say when or with whom the company would
team. ``Stay tuned'' is all he told reporters meeting with him in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent flurry of initial public stock offerings for
Internet-related companies such as Media Metrix, TheGlobe.com and
Salon, stock prices have soared even though their filings with the
Securities and Exchange Commission state quite clearly that they
don't even expect to turn a profit in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not terribly important for Internet companies to show a
profit right now,'' Chaki says. ``The market is rewarding people
who are taking risks and show the potential to build very large
businesses.'' MindSpring is ... justifiably proud of its recent
string of profitable quarters. However, when it comes to the
Internet, Wall Street seems more impressed by flashy mergers and
gutsy deals than solid companies making money.
</P>
<P>
   Strategic relationships are becoming more and more important to
companies like MindSpring as high-speed Internet access via cable
modems and DSL telephone lines threaten the ISP industry.
MindSpring has a deal with sibling cable company Knology to provide
cable modem service to several markets in the Southeast and also
has a deal with BellSouth to offer high-speed Internet telephone
access beginning this fall. However, industry pundits believe that
an alliance with a major PC manufacturer could attract greater
numbers of new users to MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   Dark horses in the MindSpring sweepstakes include the Microsoft
Network, the Redmond, Wash., software maker's dial-up Internet
service that MindSpring Chairman Charles Brewer recently said he
would like to acquire. Analysts are divided on whether Microsoft
wants to hold on to the dial-up venture or divest it and focus on
its Web offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
