<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JUNE 25
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June
23, about the United Nations' decision to delay a vote on the
future of East Timor misidentified the independence campaigner who
said he supported the decision. It was Jose Ramos-Horta, not Jose
Alexandre Gusmao. The report also referred incorrectly to Mr.
Gusmao. He is not a winner of the Nobel Peace Prize. Mr.
Ramos-Horta shared the 1996 prize with Bishop Carlos Ximenes Belo,
another East Timorese advocate.
</P>
<P>
   BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Friday, June 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, June 18,
about Pope John Paul II's appointment of three new bishops in
Vietnam misspelled the name of the city in central Vietnam for
which Pierre Nguyen Soan was named bishop. It is Qui Nhon, not Quy
Nhon.
</P>
<P>
   BC-JAPAN-SUMO-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 26,
about the sumo wrestler known as Musashimaru, the second American
to achieve the sport's top ranking in Japan, misstated the record
of another American, known as Konishiki. He did not win two
consecutive tournaments in 1992 or at any time. The article also
misspelled the name of a retired grand champion. He is Chiyonofuji,
not Chiyonafuji.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BERLIN-PHILHARMONIC-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June
23, about conductors vying for music directorships of some eight
major orchestras misstated the day Sir Simon Rattle was elected to
lead the Berlin Philharmonic. The announcement was made on
Wednesday, not Tuesday.
</P>
