<HEADER>
A8613 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-TEXTILES-950(2T     06-24 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-TEXTILES-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HUGE WIN FOR LABOR IN SOUTH, TEXTILE WORKERS APPEAR TO APPROVE
UNIONIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANNAPOLIS, N.C. _ Workers at the nation's largest textile plant
_ a huge brick fortress of resistance to labor organizing in the
South _ apparently ended a 93-year epoch on Wednesday night and
voted to allow a textile workers union inside the walls to
represent them.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned officials of the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and
Textile Employees, known as UNITE, declared victory Thursday in the
long-running battle to organize the Fieldcrest Cannon plant, not
quite believing they had won after so many years of defeat. With
more than 5,200 workers at the complex of six plants, Fieldcrest
Cannon would represent the largest victory ever for labor in the
South, particularly given the company's history of intense
hostility to labor, which repeatedly drew angry citations from the
National Labor Relations Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like we just organized GM,'' said Bruce Raynor, the
union's organizing director. ``Suddenly, we've got a beacon to show
other textile workers that they can do it. And it sends a message
to other owners that they're going to have to take into account the
needs of workers as they modernize.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor experts said the turnabout, after four previous
unsuccessful elections at the plant, which makes sheets and towels,
was apparently due to fear caused by shifting ownership in the
textile industry, the increased demands of modern production lines
and a growing number of immigrants in the workforce, who tend to be
more likely to support unionization.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's social climate _ with the kneejerk anti-union
attitude of most major manufacturers and the use of every tool
available to fight off unionization _ it's a stunning victory for
the union,'' said Leon Fink, a labor historian at the University of
North Carolina. ``It's the biggest breakthrough in a traditional
Southern industry for probably the past quarter century.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials were not conceding the outcome of Wednesday
night's vote, and the NLRB said the outcome remained too close to
call. At the moment, the vote stands at 2,270 in favor of the union
and 2,102 against it, with challenges to about 285 votes. Charles
Hansen, the chief executive of Pillowtex Corp., which owns the
complex of six mills, said that the company has not challenged any
of the votes, and would await an official announcement by the labor
board.
</P>
<P>
   The board challenged 53 of the votes; the rest of the challenges
came from the union, which said some of those who participated may
have been in supervisory positions, making them ineligible to vote.
Union leaders said it was virtually a mathematical impossibility
that the labor board would not eventually award the election to the
union, in a matter of weeks or months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we've won,'' said Mike Zucker, the union's
chief organizer at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen Thursday said he was not conceding.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, the percentage of the workforce that belongs to
unions is lower than in the rest of the country. While 13.5 percent
of the workforce belongs to unions nationwide, two professors at
Florida State University, Barry T. Hirsch and David A. Macpherson,
found that just 4.2 percent of workers belong to unions in North
Carolina and 4.5 percent in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   And unions in the South have had many of the same problems as
unions elsewhere in the country. They have lost members as
companies have closed factories and moved operations overseas. In
the South, perhaps more than elsewhere, employers have bitterly
fought unionization efforts. Employers have been helped by a lack
of union tradition in the South and by right-to-work laws that
permit workers at unionized workplaces not to pay union dues.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, unions have mounted organizing efforts, with
various success rates, in the South, with the Cannon Fieldcrest
effort being labor's biggest victory in the private sector. Unions
have recently organized nursing home workers in Miami, and more
than 600 food workers at a New Orleans convention center. But
organizing drives have also fallen flat at many poultry plants and
nursing homes across the South.
</P>
<P>
   The first Cannon mills were built here in 1906 by James Cannon,
who also created the village of Kannapolis out of the surrounding
cotton fields as a white-clapboard company town for his employees.
The first effort at organizing came in 1921, when workers grew
angry about their $5 weekly paychecks and walked out. Most came
back 10 weeks later, broken by hard times and the refusal of the
management to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   The first real election at the plant came in 1974, the same year
as labor's famous triumph at the J.P. Stevens mill in Roanoke
Rapids, N.C., depicted in the movie ``Norma Rae.'' But the Cannon
company actually worked harder to fight off the union, firing some
employees and threatening others, and the vote failed that year and
again in 1985. Similar tactics in an unsuccessful 1991 election
infuriated the labor board, which accused Fieldcrest Cannon of
engaging in ``numerous, pervasive and outrageous'' unfair labor
practices. That election was thrown out by the board and by the
court, and was run again in 1997, when again the board threw out
the results and ordered a new vote.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote was in effect a rerun of the one in 1991. The
company had been purchased by Pillowtex, a Dallas-based bedding
manufacturer which has several unionized plants. Raynor, who has
spent the better part of a career trying to organize Kannapolis,
said that for the first time this year, the company did not engage
in any illegal tactics, and simply tried to state the case to
workers why they should not vote for the union.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the various buyouts and shifting ownerships in the industry
left many workers uncertain of the future. Mitchell High, a
dye-range operator in the plant who controls the color of finished
goods, said he voted against the union because he is satisfied with
his working conditions. But his colleagues who voted for it told
him they're worried about their job security, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what's coming, so they're hoping the union can
protect them,'' he said. ``I guess we'll find out if they're
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemberly Shoaf Taylor, who hems sheets at the plant, said she
voted for the union because management is using technology to prod
employees into working much too hard. When she started 19 years
ago, she said, she was part of a crew of seven people who turned
out 300 sheets a day. Now three people have to do much more work on
each sheet, she said, but are being paid little more. Other workers
said they hoped the company's low pension benefits would be a major
issue once negotiations between the union and the company begin.
</P>
<P>
   The vote comes at a time when the percentage of unionized
private-sector employees in the South continues to fall faster than
in the country as a whole, 7.1 percent in 1985 to 4.1 percent in
1998, according to the Bureau of National Affairs, a private
research organization in Washington. But several Southern states _
notably the textile belt of North Carolina, South Carolina and
Virginia _ have actually seen increases in unionization during the
last three years. UNITE, a successor to the old Amalgamated
Clothing and Textile Workers Union, has recently won several
victories at smaller textile plants in the South.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, black workers have been more amenable to the
appeal of unions than the old all-white work force, said Thomas E.
Terrill, a history professor at the University of South Carolina.
Hispanic and Asian workers, who are gaining a foothold in the labor
market of the South, have also voted in increasing numbers for
unions, although they make up only about 5 percent of Fieldcrest
Cannon's workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Raynor said he hoped the outcome would convince workers at other
plants they too can support a union.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote puts the lie to the notion that manufacturing
workers in the South can't be organized, that they're anti-union,''
he said. ``If companies conduct themselves fairly, southern workers
will vote for a union in very large percentages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
