A8615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTLITIES-DEREG25-COX     06-24 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTLITIES-DEREG25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AGL won't become a `stealth company,' top executive says
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Atlanta Gas Light Co. will not become a ``stealth
company'' when Georgia's natural gas deregulation is completed this
fall, and its marketing affiliate may even sell gas and electricity
in other Southeastern states that deregulate, Chief Executive
Walter M. Higgins said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Natural Gas Roundtable, an industry group,
Higgins said that once SouthStar Energy Services, the partnership
that operates Georgia Natural Gas Services, gets Georgia under its
belt, the company intends to enter Southeastern markets as they
open up to competition.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins is chief executive of both Atlanta Gas Light and its
parent company, AGL Resources, which is the lead partner in
Atlanta-based SouthStar, technically the parent of Georgia Natural
Gas. He found a receptive audience of industry insiders as he
outlined the company's experience with deregulation during a
luncheon address.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins recapped what he called the utility's bumpy road to
deregulation, which will be completed in October when Atlanta Gas
Light terminates gas sales and becomes a distribution company with
a regulated rate of return.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the ``bumps in the road'' the utility has experienced,
Atlanta Gas Light plans today to file papers with the Georgia
Public Service Commission seeking to pass on to consumers millions
of dollars in unexpected costs incurred in the transition to
deregulation. Included are the costs of operating call centers to
handle customer inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exact value of the potential stranded costs is not known
at this time,'' a draft filing says.
</P>
<P>
   Roger B. Cooper, executive vice president of the American Gas
Association, one of about 50 people who heard Higgins' speech, said
Georgia's 1997 deregulation law is closely watched in the $100
billion-a-year natural gas industry. It is the only law so far that
mandates that the monopoly supplier withdraw entirely from gas
sales, although the law did permit the parent AGL Resources to set
up a separate marketing affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins noted that Virginia recently enacted a gas deregulation
law, and other states won't be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Higgins said that Atlanta Gas Light will
``continue to play an important but different role'' after
deregulation is completed. He said distribution will remain the
most profitable part of the business for some time.
</P>
<P>
   AGL Resources has begun looking for new marketing opportunities
as other states deregulate. Higgins noted that marketers will offer
``every imaginable service that can be provided,'' such as
electricity, telephone and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins has named Mark D. Caudill, vice president for energy
competition at AGL Resources, to keep track of deregulation
programs and urge enactment of the Georgia model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly it's an advantage if it's a system we're familiar
with,'' said Caudill. ``There are great opportunities for us in
those markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
