<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-MEDICAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INEXACTNESS OF MEDICINE ON TRIAL IN LEWIS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When all was said and done, the laypeople of the jury
came to the same conclusion about Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. that the
experts did: no conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's inability to blame or acquit Mudge in the 1993 death
of Celtics star Reggie Lewis, after the most exhaustively argued
Massachusetts malpractice trial in memory, represents ``exactly
what the medical community'' thinks, said Dr. Deeb Salem, chairman
of medicine at New England Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although at first blush, things may have seemed clear, when a
lot of data came out, it was not obvious what to do,'' said Salem,
a heart specialist who consulted for Mudge's defense. Another heart
specialist called it a coin toss.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Isner, chief of vascular medicine and cardiovascular
research at St. Elizabeth's Hospital, was also unsurprised by the
mistrial in Mudge's case. ``It was a very tough call,'' said Isner,
who had been prepared to testify for Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's decision to acquit Drs. Mark Creager and Peter
Friedman, who consulted on Lewis' case, underscores the uncertainty
that at least 13 of the 15 jurors felt about blaming the
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one lesson for patients, several doctors said Thursday,
is that for all its technological trappings, medicine is a far less
certain enterprise than many imagine. ``Much of what we deal with
is not an exact science,'' Salem said. ``Much of what we deal with
is uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty, in fact, is the accused physician's best ally.
</P>
<P>
   Malpractice lawyers said that if defense attorneys can
underscore this element of medical uncertainty, as Mudge's defense
team did with its parade of experts, it can undermine a lay jury's
willingness to find a doctor negligent, no matter how much they
struggle to reach a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, 94 percent of all medical malpractice cases
are won by the defense. ``The benefit of the doubt always goes to
the doctor,'' said Andrew Meyer, a prominent plaintiff's attorney.
``When a case was as well tried as this one was on both sides, it's
not surprising at all to see it arrive at a dead heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy O'Neill, who defends many Harvard-affiliated doctors in
malpractice cases, agreed. ``These cases are difficult,'' he said.
``It's difficult to convince people in an emotional case like this
on a particular point of view. Often the evidence doesn't make a
lot of difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Another moral of the tragic Reggie Lewis story, said several
physicians and malpractice attorneys, is the importance of clear,
direct, one-on-one communication _ a difficult goal to attain in
ordinary cases but one that can be especially elusive with
celebrity patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notoriety of this case contributed to all the complex
20-20 hindsight,'' said Dr. Thomas Graboys, director of the Lown
Cardiovascular Center at Brigham and Women's Hospital and a member
of the so-called ``dream team'' originally assembled to advise on
Lewis's care, before Reggie and Donna Harris-Lewis transferred his
care to Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had been an ordinary patient who had had one primary
care physician and one cardiologist. . .it might have been a
different situation,'' said Graboys, who strongly supported Mudge's
position.
</P>
<P>
   Isner agreed that Lewis's care was complicated by his
celebrity-athlete status. Mudge ``was trying to make a decision not
just to prevent death but to preserve a career, and that is
probably too tricky a proposition,'' Isner said. ``It probably
exceeds the diagnostic acumen of any mortal cardiologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson of the case, many said, is that physicians tread
on dangerous ground when they call press conferences to discuss
patients' cases _ and then are forced to acknowledge, as Mudge did,
that they were less than truthful about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not going to be forthcoming, you ought not to come
forward at all,'' Meyer said. ``Public relations is a field that
doctors ought to leave to public relations professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   The malpractice attorneys said they expected Mudge's insurer
eventually to reach a financial settlement with Donna Harris-Lewis
to avoid a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff has every incentive to press for a retrial as
leverage for a settlement, attorneys said. Most of the plaintiff's
costs of retrial _ investigating, deposing witnesses, and other
preparation _ have already been borne, they said. A good part of
the lawyers' expenses have already been financed from the
settlement Harris-Lewis won from Dr. John D. Rutherford, a Dallas
cardiologist who consulted on the case.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the hung jury undoubtedly lowers the
settlement stakes, lawyers said. ``Dr. Mudge's insurer will say
`We're not going to pay full value because we almost won this
case,' '' Meyer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
