<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEOS-MEETING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Update your business plan, experts tell chief execs
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just when businesses are flying high and operating
profitably may be the time to start work on a radically new
business plan for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   That was the gist of the message conveyed Thursday to more than
400 chief executives and other managers attending a two-day forum
in Atlanta on ``corporate Darwinism,'' or survival of the fittest.
</P>
<P>
   What they heard from academic experts and other business leaders
is that new business approaches, including a ``digital business
plan,'' are links to survival in today's globally competitive
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Digital business plans are strategies for doing more work,
trade, distribution, sales and other activities on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The forum at the Ritz-Carlton Buckhead, fifth in an annual
series sponsored by Forbes magazine, is viewed by the executives as
an opportunity to renew acquaintances, learn what others are doing
and listen to the latest studies by business consultants
specializing in strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's session, dealing with ominous subjects such as
``Adapt or Die'' and ``Disruptive Technologies,'' reminded them
that some of the most secure companies in business history, like
Sears, IBM, Digital Equipment and Wang, became stagnant and were
overtaken by change.
</P>
<P>
   James Kelly, chairman of Sandy Springs-based United Parcel
Service, told how his package carrier, alert to new demands, is
going electronic to stay ahead of the curve and be of greater use
to the its loyal customers.
</P>
<P>
   George M.C. Fisher, chairman of Eastman Kodak, related how his
company decided that digital photography needed to be embraced _
even if it was at odds with the core business in chemical
processes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that the one unvarying fact for us was that
customers love pictures,'' said Fisher. ``Customers don't care
about chemicals or electrons, just pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the company now has a solid niche in digital
photography, which is expected to drive the industry for the
foreseeable future, it also still has solid business in the
traditional lines of film, chemicals, papers and other products
that are the main sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   G. Richard Thoman, president and chief executive of Xerox, told
how his company had rebounded, partly by providing more seamless
services for handling documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now spend 70 percent of our research and development
dollars on the 30 percent of new business.'' Asked why he comes to
meetings like the Forbes forum, David S. Pottruck, president and
co-CEO of Charles Schwab Corp., said there are several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to talk to people and get our name around, and look for
talent,'' he said. ``My company will hire between 3,000 and 4,000
people this year, most in the technology area. ... We're in this
battle for intellectual capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
