<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECKFREE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CheckFree pulls offering of stock
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stung by speculation about the timing of a $148.2
million stock sale, CheckFree on Thursday withdrew the offering.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic payment processor said it stopped the sale of 3.8
million shares to quiet speculation that its timing _ two days
before three major banks formed a rival company _ was anything more
than coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the shares were priced at $39. On Wednesday, three
CheckFree customers, Chase Manhattan Bank, Wells Fargo and First
Union, said they would form a company, called the Exchange, to
deliver bills electronically. That company eventually would compete
with CheckFree, one of a handful of companies trying to make the
Internet the place people get and pay their bills. That news took a
24 percent chunk out of CheckFree's stock, leading to speculation
it planned the sale to occur before the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree closed Wednesday at $28.75, down $8.93 3/4. Its shares
sold as high as $34.50 Thursday but closed at $28.12 1/2, down 62
1/2 cents. CheckFree shares are down 26.7 percent over the last
five trading sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The 3.8 million shares _ 2.4 million owned by the company and
1.4 million by existing shareholders, including Pete Kight,
chairman and chief executive _ were priced Monday but were not to
be delivered to the underwriters in New York until today.
</P>
<P>
   Kight, whose 658,122 shares would have earned him $25.7 million,
said the company was reacting to speculation that the stock sale
was timed to beat the Exchange announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, CheckFree executives sat across the table from more
than 50 institutional investors, many of whom requested an
allocation of stock,'' Kight said in a statement. ``I don't ever
want to walk back into the offices of these analysts and portfolio
managers and have to think that they might be wondering whether we
had been honest with them. Our credibility with shareholders is
more important than any offering.''
</P>
<P>
   Pricing a stock for a public offering is a step toward
completing a sale. But the deal does not close until the shares are
delivered to the underwriters, who act are intermediaries between
the company and investors. CheckFree's stock sale was to have been
underwritten by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown and
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Group.
</P>
<P>
   James Marks, an analyst with Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown, upped
his recommendation on CheckFree to a ``strong buy'' from a ``buy''
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree spokeswoman Laurinda Wilson said the company still
might sell the shares.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
