<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8631 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      06-24 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE AGAINST REGGIE LEWIS DOCTOR ENDS IN MISTRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a torturous, inconclusive end to a
highly-controversial trial, a judge Thursday declared a mistrial in
the Reggie Lewis medical malpractice case after jurors twice said
they could not agree on whether Lewis's chief cardiologist, Dr.
Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., was negligent in treating the heart condition
that killed the 27-year-old Celtics star six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While the jury could not reach a verdict on Mudge, it did clear
two consulting physicians, Peter L. Friedman and Mark. A. Creager,
of malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly seven weeks of a trial that saw the clash of
institutions and cultures that define Boston -- professional sports
and preeminent medicine -- the indefinite conclusion means that it
is not over, at least for Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be back to do it again,'' vowed attorney Robert G.
Harley, who represented Lewis's widow, Donna Harris-Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in the front row of the courtroom's spectator gallery,
where he sat each day since the trial began in early May, Mudge
showed no reaction as the jury announced for the second time that
it was deadlocked on the claims against him and Suffolk Superior
Court Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith declared a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   But after the jury was dismissed, Mudge smiled broadly and was
quickly surrounded by family members and friends, including several
of his patients, who offered congratulatory hugs and handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   Commended by one well-wisher, a beaming Mudge replied that, ``I
don't know what we've won, but . . .'' his voice trailing off as he
continued shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly absent from the courtroom was Harris-Lewis, who was
in the courtroom earlier but left before the verdict to return home
to her two children. Friends and relatives, including her brother
and Lewis's mother, Inez Ritch, were emotionless during the judge's
announcement, and then left the courtroom rapidly and silently.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis, who canceled plans to hold a post-trial press
conference, was said to be ``devastated'' by the outcome. In a
written statement, she said, ``No lies, no rumors, and no gossip
about my Reggie can ever change the good and kind and caring person
he was.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15 jurors, who deliberated for 38 hours over six days,
looked strained and weary as they filed into the courtroom shortly
after 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdicts were read, jurors were thanked personally by
Fremont-Smith, quickly dismissed, and ushered to a service
elevator. Once outside the courthouse, they immediately scattered,
leaving in groups of two and three. On the sidewalk, two white
female jurors who exited the building together remained
tight-lipped.
</P>
<P>
   Driving a green Saab convertible with the top down and radio
playing, Fremont-Smith -- who called the case ``a sad situation''
with ``good people on both sides'' -- also left quickly, ignoring
reporters' questions as he drove away.
</P>
<P>
   Lingering inside the courtroom, Tom Fall, whose wife, Linda, had
a heart transplant under Mudge's care seven years ago, said he
wished Mudge had been cleared, but expressed relief that the trial
had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big tragedy,'' said Fall, who attended several days
of the trial with his wife, ``and I just hope Donna Lewis thinks
long and hard and doesn't come back for another trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Testimony during the lengthy trial ranged from the technical to
the farcical, with the introduction of a convicted felon who
claimed he saw Lewis sniffing cocaine in a public bathroom, and an
elderly former Northeastern University doctor who contradicted
himself on the stand, saying that Lewis both had and had not tested
positive for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict comes one month shy of the sixth anniversary of
Lewis's death and three years after Harris-Lewis filed a medical
malpractice lawsuit accusing four cardiologists of failing to
diagnose her husband with a life-threatening heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   One of the cardiolgists, Dr. John D. Rutherford, now in practice
in Texas, settled out of court with Harris-Lewis in April, on the
day that jury selection began. Details of the settlement have not
been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Filed in May 1996, the lawsuit spurred furious debate over
Harris-Lewis's motives and timing. The suit came just months before
the state's three-year statute of limitations would have barred the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters hailed Harris-Lewis as a grieving spouse determined
to clear her husband's name, which she said had been smeared
posthumously in media reports linking his medical troubles with
cocaine use, which can cause lasting heart damage.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, meanwhile, saw her as a greedy widow, willing to
sacrifice her husband's legacy and reputation for financial gain;
during the trial, a sports agent testified that Lewis could have
earned more than $117 million if he had continued playing
professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Harris-Lewis, who denied that her husband used
drugs, said the suit was motivated by a 1995 Wall Street Journal
story suggesting that cocaine played a role in her husband's death,
and by Mudge's subsequent claim that Lewis confessed to him two
weeks before his death that he had used cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge, now director of cardiac transplantation at Brigham and
Women's Hospital, has said Lewis's belated confession impeded him
from accurately diagnosing the player's condition.
</P>
<P>
   The first public sign that Lewis, nicknamed ``His Regginess'' by
local sportscasters, had a medical ailment came on April 29, 1993,
when the National Basketball Association All-Star collapsed on the
Boston Garden's parquet floor during a playoff game against the
Charlotte Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of that collapse was shown numerous times to jurors,
who watched raptly as the 6-foot 7-inch player stumbled and fell on
the court, his legs appearing to become heavy and sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, Lewis was admitted for tests to New England
Baptist Hospital, where a team of 12 prominent doctors from across
the city -- quickly dubbed the ``Dream Team'' -- concluded he had a
serious heart problem that could end his basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a bizarre turn of events three days later, Lewis left
the Baptist against medical advice in the middle of the night,
pulling off his heart monitor. He was transported to the nearby
Brigham and into Mudge's care.
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt transfer sparked speculation that Lewis and his wife
were shopping for a rosier diagnosis, one that would allow him to
continue his lucrative playing career.
</P>
<P>
   Seven days after being admitted to the Brigham, Mudge announced
confidently at a press conference that Lewis had a ``poorly
understood,'' but benign, fainting condition, not a serious heart
condition. With medical supervision and unspecified treatment, he
would be able to play basketball again, Mudge proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven weeks later, Lewis collapsed and died of heart failure
while shooting baskets at a Brandeis University gym on July 27,
1993, leaving behind a pregnant wife and year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   His death prompted an outpouring of grief by fans in Boston and
beyond, who were charmed by Lewis's soft-spoken manner, gentle
demeanor and philanthropic nature, qualities that made him the
antithesis of the trash-talking, bad-boy athletes of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge, whose diagnosis had been publicly criticized by some
members of Boston's medical community, received death threats after
Lewis died and was given temporary police protection at his home.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy of Lewis's body found no evidence of drugs in his
system, and his death certificate listed adenovirus, a relatively
minor virus spread by coughing and sneezing, as the cause of
scarring found in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   But that finding came under intense public scrutiny when the
Wall Street Journal story was published nearly two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, lawyers for Harris-Lewis argued that
allegations of drug use were false, as well as irrelevant. Lewis's
doctors, they argued, were responsible for providing him with
top-quality care regardless of the cause of his heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors' lawyers, meanwhile, suggested that Lewis's death
was caused by his own failure to follow doctor's orders and avoid
strenuous exercise, noting that two witnesses testified they saw
Lewis sweating while working out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
