<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANFORD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT CLEANUP AT HANFORD `NOT WHAT IT SHOULD BE,' REPORT
FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite evidence that soil and ground-water
contamination at the Hanford Nuclear Reservation may be threatening
juvenile salmon and causing rashes on Native Americans fishing in
the area, the government still isn't doing enough to clean up the
contamination, according to a new report.
</P>
<P>
   Solutions to the problem are elusive, and the Department of
Energy is so wedded to conventional methods that it is failing to
take advantage of recent technological advances, according to the
report released Thursday on ground water and soil cleanup in the
nation's nuclear weapons complex.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the National Research Council warns that even
after spending billions of dollars trying to clean up the nation's
nuclear weapons facilities, the government is not making enough
progress. The National Research Council is an arm of the National
Academy of Sciences chartered by Congress to provide advice on
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked in depth at their progress, and found that it's not
what it should be,'' said Herb Ward, a Rice University engineering
professor and chairman of the committee that wrote the report.
``They find a great deal of comfort in doing cleanup the standard
way, which is not very effective and is very expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the Department of Energy continues to rely
on the general philosophy that when ground water or soil is
contaminated, water or soil should be pumped or excavated. But
increasingly, scientists have concluded that those methods are
often ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they stress new technologies that treat contaminants
without removing them. For example, electrical fields can be used
to extract metal and radionuclide contaminants from soil, while
steam can be used to move contaminants into recovery wells.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those technologies have been developed in the private
sector, others at the Department of Energy. But the government
bureaucracy has made it difficult to take new methods from the
laboratory and into the field, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no downside for contractors to keep doing the same
thing, and it's dangerous for them to try something innovative,
because it hasn't gone through all the appropriate hoops,'' said
Richard Johnson, another committee member and a ground-water expert
at the Oregon Graduate Institute of Science and Technology. ``The
status quo is kind of institutionalized because of the way the
system is run, and it inhibits people from trying things that might
potentially be better.''
</P>
<P>
   One positive exception may be at Hanford, where scientists have
developed a method for treating chromium-contaminated water with
chemical agents. Chromium is one of many harmful chemicals of
concern at Hanford. Hanford officials hope soon to use the
methodology on a broad scale.
</P>
<P>
   The report cites a 1995 study by Tulane and Xavier universities
that asserted that ``Native Americans have reportedly developed
rashes consistent with exposure to chromium after being in the
vicinity of contaminated seeps'' at Hanford.
</P>
<P>
   The report also warns that contamination heading for the
Columbia River from Hanford has concentrations of chromium at
levels 25 times higher than that known to damage juvenile salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some significant improvements in identifying
research and technology needs for cleanup at Hanford, but the
deployment by the contractors and the Department of Energy is way
behind the promises,'' said Gerald Pollett, executive director of
Heart of America Northwest, a watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   The National Research Council recommended that the Department of
Energy place a higher priority on developing and using new methods
of treating contaminated soil and ground water.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy, which commissioned the report, said it
agreed with the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view the report as part of our ongoing process to improve
our cleanup efforts, particularly with respect to protecting water
resources,'' said James Owendoff, acting assistant secretary for
environmental management at the Department of Energy. ``The
department has already begun taking steps to address the
committee's concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Owendoff said the department is increasing coordination with
other government agencies and private companies to develop new
cleanup technologies, and is pushing project managers at
contaminated sites to increase their use of new technologies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
