<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MARINES-2TAKES     06-24 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MARINES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS ABANDON VILLAGE WHERE FIREFIGHT WITH MARINES OCCURRED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZEGRA, Yugoslavia _ If the U.S. Marines who have taken over this
remote part of southeastern Kosovo came to forge peace between
Kosovo's Serbs and Albanians, the result was anything but.
</P>
<P>
   After a firefight with Marines that killed one Serb and wounded
two others on Wednesday night, Zegra, like so many other villages
across Kosovo, was gripped by a new contortion of fear, violence
and retribution on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every Serb in this small village left at noon, most of
them in a single, bedraggled column of cars, trucks and trailers,
some pulled by tractors, others by oxen or horses. As they left,
ignoring the entreaties of their Orthodox priest to stay, smoke and
flames poured from at least a dozen houses in the village.
</P>
<P>
   Slavka Ristic sat in the back seat of a beaten-up car crammed
with all her belongings that would fit. She was crying, at times
uncontrollably. The night before, her son, Mikajovic Jugoslav, had
been seriously wounded in the firefight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not safe here,'' she sobbed, as she joined at least 100
Serbs who hurriedly packed their clothes, furnishings and whatever
else they could Thursday morning and left.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the flight of Serbs from Kosovo are reports of
violence against Serb civilians. A Serb professor and two Serb
workers at the University of Pristina were found shot to death
Thursday in a classroom building. Later a Serb and an Albanian were
wounded in a gun battle when a family of Albanians returned to
Pristina to find Serbs living in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs in Zegra blamed the Albanians and even NATO for the
fires, but the timing pointed to the Serbs, whose homes began to
burn just as their owners left.
</P>
<P>
   After the Serbs left, the Albanians, some of whom had returned
to the village only Thursday morning, went from house to house,
taking whatever they could. Some said they were simply retrieving
what Serbs had stolen from them after Yugoslav forces drove them
from their homes in March. But others sought only revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Feti Ajvazi, 19, and his brother, Ali, 17, carried a dining
table down a narrow back street littered with the wreckage of the
Yugoslav crackdown and now filled once again with smoke. ``They
took all our things,'' the older brother said. ``Now it is our turn
to take all of their things.''
</P>
<P>
   Platoons from the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit were out in
force Thursday, rumbling around atop armored vehicles and manning a
checkpoint on the main road into town. But they did nothing to stop
the Serbs from leaving or the Albanians from looting. One captain
said the troops would intervene if they saw wrongdoing, but it was
clear that they were not looking very hard.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Marines arrived in the sector, Zegra, a
once-pretty village split by a river, has been one of the
flashpoints their commanders expected would erupt. Before
Yugoslavia's crackdown last fall, Zegra's population was
predominantly Albanian, but there were many Serbs, too. After
NATO's bombing stopped, the Serbs here remained, even though
thousands had fled from other parts of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours after the shooting on Wednesday night, the Marines'
commander, Col. Kenneth Glueck, said NATO peacekeepers were
determined to be evenhanded in their dealings with Serbs and
Albanians alike. Now only Albanians remain.
</P>
<P>
   American and NATO officials defended the Marines' action in the
firefight, saying they fired only after a crowd of Serbs who had
gathered in a small plaza separating a grocery store and a house
had fired at a Marine checkpoint roughly 100 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Gunnery Sgt. William Post, who was there, said that after the
initial bursts of fire, he and three other Marines, one of them a
translator able to speak Serb and Albanian, approached the plaza
from a river gully and spent five minutes trying to persuade the
Serbs to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, bloodied, climbed into a car, but refused to come
out. ``We told him to lay down his weapon,'' Post said. ``He told
us, in Albanian, to lay down ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The wounded Serb then went from the car to a stoop on the house
and, the sergeant said, opened fire on the translator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He leaned forward,'' he said. ``And that's when I shot him in
the head.''
</P>
<P>
   The firefight created a panic among Zegra's Serbs, all that was
needed to persuade them to flee. Mrs. Ristic was sure that her son,
Mikajovic Jugoslav, had died because the Serbs here believed that
all three Serbs struck in the battle had been killed. The truth was
that Marines ferried two by helicopter to the Army's field hospital
near Urosevac.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO spokesman, Lt. Comdr. Louis Garneau of Canada, said
Jugoslav had been struck by a bullet in the neck, but not killed.
He identified the dead man as Momcilo Zivokovic and the other man
wounded as Sasha Stojanivic.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth man was arrested, and an AK-47 rifle, a shotgun, a
grenade and several clips of ammunition were seized. Garneau said
that the Serbs' motives for attacking the heavily armed Marines
remained murky and that it was not clear whether those involved had
any affiliation with Yugoslav army or paramilitary units that the
Albanians said had terrorized the village throughout NATO's war
with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Marine officials said, however, that the checkpoint had been set
up specifically to keep a watch on the store and house, which were
suspected of being gathering places for armed Serbs. On Thursday,
as departing Serbs formed their column on a side road at the site
of the firefight, they angrily denounced the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   They accused them of siding with the Albanians and the Kosovo
Liberation Army, even though the same Marines had disarmed a
company of rebel fighters after they marched through the village a
week ago. Several said the rebels, whose presence has grown in the
town, had become increasingly provocative and intimidating. They
said it was the Kosovo Liberation Army, not the Serbs, who had
fired first on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not only running from the KLA,'' one Serb yelled,
standing near the spot where the Serb had died, his blood smeared
on a doorway and pooled in the street. ``We are running from the
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   An Orthodox priest, a young man who would give his name only as
Father Zijar, said he wanted the Serbs to stay, to try to live with
their Albanian neighbors. Zegra is one of four villages in his
parish, he said, two of them now empty of Serb parishioners. ``I'm
trying,'' he said, ``but I can't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bearded and dressed in a black frock, he nervously fingered a
keychain. ``It's terrible,'' he said, as the column began to wind
slowly through the Marine checkpoint the Serbs had fired on only
hours before.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single Albanian on Zegra's worn streets was sorry to see
the Serbs go. Aslan Zeneli, 64, returned to Zegra Thursday from
Macedonia. After the Albanians fled in late March, he said, the
Serbs burned the Albanians' houses, stole their belongings and even
took over their farmland, raising the crops for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Zeneli returned to his home to find it destroyed. All he could
find to save was a mattress and two blankets. ``You see what they
did to me,'' he said, standing in his ravaged courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Several Albanians, like Zeneli, insisted on giving tours of the
destruction that had taken place. The health clinic had been
sacked, along with a barber shop, a cafe and several shops. Dozens
of homes were little but ashes, charred beams and broken red tiles;
the walls of one were smeared with feces. The beautiful
silver-domed mosque in Zegra's center had been desecrated, its
windows broken and its carpets piled inside and torched.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians said that at least 10 Albanians, and possibly as
many as 20, had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, the Serbs can't stay here, because of all the things they
did in the village,'' said Sabri Idrizi, 49, who said two of his
uncles and an aunt were killed the day Serb paramilitary forces
arrived on March 29. ``They were thinking the Albanians would not
come back, but we came back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8635 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-EXPANSION-BOS &LR;      06-24 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-EXPANSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL ENJOYING SHOT OF REVENE FROM EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The National Hockey League is growing, again, and it
is all about business. Even Ted Turner wants a piece of the action
this time.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Sports Inc. owns the latest addition to the NHL, the
Atlanta Thrashers, which will select some of its players in the
league's expansion draft Friday, beginning at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   For a league that not long ago was largely a regional
enterprise, desperate for more of the national exposure and money
that accrues to the NFL, the NBA, and Major League Baseball, the
current robust period of expansion should help grow important
sources of revenue, especially the value of crucial television
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sport whose footprint wasn't as strong as the other
sports leagues from a competitive standpoint, both for television
and from advertising,'' NHL commissioner Gary B. Bettman said in an
interview this week. ``In the early 1990s, we were only in 11 US
markets. It's not the millennium yet, and we got to 20 markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial implications are clear. The NFL's television
contract is worth $17.6 billion. The NHL's new agreement with ABC
and ESPN is worth $600 million. And even that marks significant
improvement in the 1990s. Expansion also has increased the
involvement of content-starved media companies in the ownership of
franchises, including Turner and Disney Sports Enterprises Inc.,
the owner of the Anaheim Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   By 2000, the NHL will have grown by nearly half in the 1990s,
from 21 to 30 teams _ 24 in the US and six in Canada. The Nashville
Predators began play last year, the Thrashers will open in the new
Philips Arena in October, and the Minnesota Wild and Columbus Blue
Jackets will begin play in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This expansion, we believe, will make the league stronger, a
more vibrant factor in the entertainment sports marketplace,''
Bettman said.
</P>
<P>
   But expansion has inherent risks, observers say. While Bettman,
who was once the deputy to NBA commissioner David Stern, continues
to receive high marks from observers for increasing the value of
the franchises and the league, the NHL is contending with some
major management and financial issues.
</P>
<P>
   Will more franchises mean a decline in the quality of play as
the talent pool is diluted? Will the increased demand for
top-of-the-line players exacerbate the salary inflation that some
owners feel has already reached crisis proportions?
</P>
<P>
   Why is the league trying to reestablish itself in Atlanta and
Minneapolis-St. Paul, where franchises have failed before? And how
successful can the NHL be if economic issues continue to block any
expansion in Canada, the sport's homeland, where the game is
revered?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's no doubt that it is key that the NHL expands
to potential major markets like Atlanta,'' said Bob Williams, who
compares the market for different sports as he links athletes with
advertisers for the Burns Sports Celebrity Service in Chicago.
``But I think you have to walk a fine line, in some areas,
especially on the issue of diluting talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bettman needs to avoid that, because the NHL is not nearly as
stable financially as, say, the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman says that adding three teams in four years is not too
much, too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the expansion franchises is very strong in terms of
the three most important criteria, namely ownership, market, and
arena,'' he said. ``Each of the three franchises starts with in
excess of 12,000 season tickets sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bettman asserts that European players will continue
to reinforce the talent pool. And the National Hockey League
Players Association has agreed to reduce rosters by one player,
from 24 to 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a league of our size, (the additional) jobs isn't that
significant,'' Bettman said. ``Now, 20 percent of our players come
from outside of North America, and they are some of the most highly
skilled and talented players in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But expansion means an increased demand for prime talent in the
NHL, which is bound to drive salaries higher. Salaries already have
increased markedly in the 1990s, from an annual average of about
$470,000 per player in 1992-93 to $1.3 million in the past season,
according to league and union sources.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins president Harry Sinden revealed last December that,
leaguewide, the NHL is paying 72 percent of its revenue to players.
When the NBA owners asserted that the players were gobbling up 57
percent of the league's revenue, they locked them out and canceled
much of the current season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is the expansion teams traditionally have the lowest
payrolls,'' Bettman said.
</P>
<P>
   But that logic seems easy to refute, when it comes to the demand
for star players. Harvey Schiller, president of the Thrashers, said
the emphasis in Atlanta will be on winning, and when he was asked
recently about the team's marketing strategy, Schiller told
reporters, ``Sign Pavel Bure.'' It was an obvious reference to the
Florida Panthers signing the flashy, Russian-born winger last
season, and experiencing an immediate spike in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   As for concerns about returning to two towns where the NHL has
previously failed, Bettman and others assert that the previous
failures had much more to do with the circumstances of the owners
than the acceptance of hockey in either town. Both the Atlanta
Flames, who left the South after seven seasons for Calgary in 1980,
and the Minnesota North Stars, who left Minneapolis for Dallas
after 26 seasons in 1993, developed a strong fan base. And while
the corporate community in Atlanta never quite poured money into
supporting the team, the city is a much different town now, almost
doubled in population, with a substantial influx of northerners who
will look forward to watching a little hockey in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta has now emerged as one of the truly dynamic cities in
terms of population growth, the economy, and it's a great sports
town,'' Bettman said. ``In addition to which, the Flames did very
well actually. They were regularly outdrawing the basketball team
the last time around. The move really had more to do with ownership
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing can be said with respect to the Stars,'' he
said. ``Norm Green had a number of issues, and the team wound up
moving to Dallas I think in part because of building problems, in
part because of ownership problems. But Minnesota is probably one
of the greatest hockey markets in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman and others say that Columbus has been an overlooked
market for major sports franchises, too, and it is ripe for a team,
with a population of 1.4 million and a substantial number of
corporate headquarters. Still, Columbus is the slowest of the three
new teams to reach the NHL minimum of 12,000 season tickets sold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, none of the expansion teams is destined for Canada,
where higher tax rates leave owners paying 300 to 400 percent more
than their counterparts in the United States. And the national and
provincial governments, as well as taxpayers, are far less
interested in financing new arenas.
</P>
<P>
   Some Canadian politicians and observers predict that as many as
three of the six Canadian franchises may soon move to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not a competitive bid for an expansion team from any
of the Canadian markets,'' Bettman said. ``Hamilton had put in an
application, but it did not have an ownership group.''
</P>
<P>
   But overall many observers think that Bettman's expansion plans
make sense _ as long as the talent holds out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
