<SLUG> BC-BKN-GAME5-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS' HOPES SEVEN FEET HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over there. Yes. That's Tim Duncan. He's the young
7-footer who has brought an old shot back to the NBA. He's the king
of subtle technique, too. He'll use it when he's taking the bank
shot, a shot no one has seen consistently since Elvin Hayes used it
in the 1970s. He'll also use that technique _ as he showed Thursday
_ when he wants to crack on that ugly hat you're wearing.
</P>
<P>
   And over there. Yes. That's David Robinson. He's the veteran
7-footer who went to Hawaii in May 1997 and quickly got a vision.
The vision was simple. It was of a college kid named Tim joining
the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long you want help,'' David said Thursday. ``Help!
Help! Send somebody down here to help me . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He began to laugh when he said that. His '97 vision was correct.
Help has arrived. Because of that, an NBA championship in '99 is
only 48 minutes away. Tim wouldn't be in this position without
David; David wouldn't be here without Tim. It is so obvious that a
few people at Madison Square Garden couldn't separate the two
7-footers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim,'' someone said to David. They caught themselves. ``Oh,
I'm sorry. David.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look like Tim at all,'' David replied. He smiled.
Later, as he answered questions about the Spurs' 3-1 series lead
over the Knicks in the NBA Finals, there was a questioner who
called him ``Tim'' again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim?'' he said. ``I'm David.''
</P>
<P>
   ``David,'' the questioner replied, ``I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a name, that's OK,'' David said.
</P>
<P>
   More laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. That's 23-year-old Tim. That's 33-year-old David. And David
is right: sometimes it's just a name. The Knicks know that after
Wednesday night, when David had 14 points, 17 rebounds, and 4
blocked shots. Tim contributed 28 points, 18 rebounds, and 3
blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Missed shot? Tim or David has the rebound. Blocked shot? David
or Tim. A Knick wants to drive the lane? Watch out for Tim; watch
out for David; watch out . . .
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Tim, will be the MVP of the Finals if the Spurs win
Game 5  &UR; tonight &LR; . He'll also be officially annointed as the best
player in the league. The other, David, will finally silence the
people who have called him soft throughout his career. He will
silence those who have said his interests are too diverse to be a
basketball champion. No one will have anything silly to say as long
as these two are together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get this done,'' said the man named Tim, wearing
his Wake Forest hat backward. ``We don't want to give them any
life. We're really focused on what we have to do. And that's a
horrible hat.''
</P>
<P>
   Pow. No one was expecting that. The man Tim was talking to was
wearing a Duke hat. Duke is Wake's rival. Many people have called
Tim boring, but he notices everything, even a hat with the tiniest
Duke logo on it.
</P>
<P>
   That's Tim. He overwhelms you with observation and fundamentals.
He is a great rebounder not because he jumps better than everyone
else; he simply has better extension of his arms and gets better
position than everyone. He was on his way to being an Olympic
swimmer, a 400-meter freestyle champion, because his technique was
so good. His best shot is rooted more in mathematics than
acrobatics. He loves using the backboard because it's easier. He
likes the angles.
</P>
<P>
   David likes talking about Tim:
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got Tim, I knew Tim was a great player, but I didn't
know how good his basic skills were. I knew a little about his
attitude; he seemed to have a great attitude. I was very excited
(when the Spurs got him). I remember where I was. I was in Hawaii,
actually, and I remember the day of the draft lottery, when we
found out we got the first pick. And, I don't know, just something
about it, I knew it was going to happen. I told my wife and a bunch
of people. I didn't watch the lottery, but a bunch of people came
to me and said, ``Hey, you guys got the No. 1 pick.' I just felt
like I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   That's David. When you ask him a question, he embraces it. You
can ask him a four-word question and he'll respond with a 45-word
answer. He smiles a lot. He's got a musical voice, something that
doesn't surprise you when you know that he's a musical man (he
plays the piano). He and Tim both know about the water. Tim because
of his swimming; David because he attended Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Tim likes talking about David:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's been given enough credit by anyone for what
he's done for us. He's been the glue that kept our team together,
the person that really stepped up and made things happen both
defensively and offensively. Although his numbers aren't _ just
because they're not what they were a couple years back, he's doing
so much more for this team . . . He's just been everything to us.''
</P>
<P>
   You want stories? They could tell you stories. Both were No. 1
draft picks, 10 years apart. No one is saying test scores indicate
intelligence, but David aced his SATs. No one is saying being alert
in the classroom indicates intelligence, but Tim skipped the third
grade. David can be musical; Tim can be whimsical (one day he
decided to collect knives; he also owns a few Samurai swords).
</P>
<P>
   While in college, critics said Tim was soft. During an interview
once with the San Antonio Express-News, he was asked about that.
This is what he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want me to be mean? I can be mean. I'm leaving (the
interview) . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't leave. But he made his point. Some rough guys off the
court can't play. Some nice guys off the court can be ferocious on
it. There's nothing complicated about that.
</P>
<P>
   Over there. Yes. The Larry O'Brien Trophy. They give that to NBA
champions. If two 7-footers do their normal work, they could be
holding that trophy  &UR; tonight &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8638 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-EXPANSION-BOS &LR;      06-24 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-EXPANSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL ENJOYING SHOT OF REVENE FROM EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The National Hockey League is growing, again, and it
is all about business. Even Ted Turner wants a piece of the action
this time.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Sports Inc. owns the latest addition to the NHL, the
Atlanta Thrashers, which will select some of its players in the
