<SLUG> BC-AIDS-ANONYMOUS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anonymous testing for HIV decreasing, CDC report says
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Over just two years, the number of anonymous tests
taken to determine HIV infection has dropped sharply, the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the option of anonymous testing must continue to be offered,
the agency added, because it is the only type of testing that some
groups at risk will use, and because new AIDS treatments make early
testing critical to successful treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In its weekly report on disease in the United States, the CDC
said the number of anonymous HIV tests taken from 1995 to 1997
declined 26.6 percent, from 636,069 to 466,560. In contrast, the
number of tests in which the patient's name was known to the
health-care provider but kept confidential rose 2.9 percent, from
1,394,921 to 1,434,709. The data comes from the CDC's National
Center for HIV, STD and TB Prevention and covers the more than 2
million federally funded tests administered annually. Those tests,
which do not include tests given during blood donation, represent
about 15 percent of the HIV tests given in the U.S. each year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, white and Asian men who have sex with other men were
more likely to use anonymous testing, which is available in 39
states including Georgia. Women, black men and men who inject drugs
were more likely to use confidential testing, which might be
offered in a community clinic, drug treatment center or prison, as
well as in a center devoted to HIV testing.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy might indicate that those receiving confidential
services were tested in the course of other health care, or were
not tested until they showed symptoms. But because the groups using
the two types of tests are so disparate, all types of testing
should continue to be offered, the CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
