<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8654 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BALTIMORE-REVIVAL     06-24 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BALTIMORE-REVIVAL-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RETAILERS IN SOME CITY CENTERS, GENTRIFICATION IS A FOUR-LETTER
WORD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Calif., N.Y., Md.)   (ART ADV: Photo map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JOEL KOTKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ For 70 years, Hippodrome Hatters has sold handmade
hats to fashion-conscious shoppers from a small store on North
Eutaw Street on this city's West Side. Lou Boulmetis, who took over
the business from his grandfather, has seen this area, once the
center of Baltimore's retail trade, suffer through a long decline:
the departure of old-line department stores, a rise in crime and
the erosion of once-glorious retail facades.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the so-called revival that has Boulmetis worried. His
shop is in a building built in 1810 that is now scheduled for
demolition in a sweeping city program to remake the shopworn
18-block retail district, whose patrons are now mostly
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The project could displace more than 100 small businesses, many
of them owned by African- or Korean-Americans, as roughly 100
properties are condemned and leveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty is in the eye of the beholder,'' said Boulmetis, 47, a
scrappy, bantamweight hat maker with no patience for
``yuppification,'' as many opponents derisively refer to the
sprucing-up of urban neighborhoods to appeal to wealthy, young,
mainly white professionals. ``We've been here through everything,
and now they want to remake the place for the educated class on the
backs of the people who are already here.''
</P>
<P>
   The planned $350 million redevelopment of the West Side includes
2,000 new housing units, splashy retail stores, renovation of a
theater and new parking structures, reflecting the growing
confidence among investors in the economic health of city centers.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood revival plans are usually catnip to local business
people, and in cities across the country merchants have organized
business improvement districts to improve neighborhoods and attract
new shoppers and investment.
</P>
<P>
   But for many people, projects like Baltimore's that call for
sweeping demolition harken frighteningly back to the huge
redevelopment projects of the 1950s and '60s, and threaten to
destroy everything they are meant to revive: the unique fabric and
traditions of neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, including Baltimore's West Side, redevelopment
also threatens to obliterate a historic part of the city's
architectural heritage: as many as 100 retail and office buildings,
some dating to World War I or earlier.
</P>
<P>
   This has made the planned demolition a cause celebre with
preservationist groups like Baltimore Heritage and the National
Trust for Historic Preservation, which earlier this month named the
West Side one of the nation's 11 most endangered places. (Baltimore
has also drawn criticism recently for its sweeping demolition of
row houses, a staple of the city's working-class neighborhoods.)
</P>
<P>
   In some city neighborhoods, preserving architecture has mattered
less than fighting off the numbing sameness that increasingly
characterizes urban retail districts. Storied places like Old Town
in Pasadena, Calif., Harvard Square in Cambridge, Mass., and
Chelsea _ among others _ in New York City are in some ways becoming
victims of their own success as they attract wealthier urbanites
and the national specialty chains that cater to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to be a place no one heard of, and if they did, they
never would want to move to,'' said Robert Trentlyon, a longtime
Chelsea resident and the former publisher of a neighborhood
newspaper, The Chelsea Clinton News. ``Then we got discovered about
10 years ago'' and rents and land values soared, he said, with
federal-era town houses that sold for $10,000 in the 1950's now
fetching $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, one of New York's more eclectic shopping
districts, with antique shops, thrift stores and local restaurants,
is being transformed into yet another homogenized urban
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Old Town Pasadena has already arrived where Chelsea seems to be
headed, and where many on the West Side of Baltimore fear to go.
When Old Town was first redeveloped in the early 1980s, it
attracted adventurous independent merchants while the larger chains
stayed on the sidelines. But as the area caught on, attracting an
increasingly prosperous customer base, the national chains poured
in.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rising rents and landlords' preference for financially secure
corporate tenants have all but driven out the small and unique
shops, according to one of Old Town's original redevelopers, Joseph
Paggi. ``The guys who came in originally, the independents, end up
losing economically,'' said Paggi, now chief operating officer of
Center Trust, a real estate investment firm in Manhattan Beach,
Calif. ``The change to the Crate and Barrels and Barnes &AMP; Nobles
puts everything into the stratosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Paggi says Old Town's evolution leads him to think that
successful urban shopping districts are destined to be
``pasteurized'' sooner or later. ``We'll have a Banana Republic on
every corner and a Starbucks right next to them,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   To officials leading the redevelopment of Baltimore's West Side,
that's no bad thing, and may even be indispensable. M.J. Brodie,
president of the quasi-public Baltimore Development Corp., says new
investment is needed in areas like the West Side to attract
middle-income shoppers and residents back into the urban core. To
save some old buildings, he said, there may be a need to replace
others with new structures like parking garages.
</P>
<P>
   Brodie's efforts are strongly backed by Baltimore's political
elite, many of whom are African-American, including the outgoing
mayor, Kurt L. Schmoke, and a majority on the city council. (Peter
Angelos, a powerful real estate developer who owns the Baltimore
Orioles, is also on board, as are Nationsbank and the Weinberg
Foundation, which owns large chunks of West Side real estate.)
</P>
<P>
   Brodie chafes at claims by Boulmetis and other local merchants
that the project's real goal is to replace the area's mainly black
shoppers with a more ``upscale'' population drawn from young
professionals and the University of Maryland campus nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you try to improve something, there's a trade-off,''
Brodie said. ``We want to create a success story that includes all
kind of people, working class, African-American, WASPs.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodie, who led the recent redevelopment of Pennsylvania Avenue
in Washington, says that demolishing old buildings and relocating
tenants is a price worth paying to revive the area.
</P>
<P>
   But many West Side merchants say the price he is willing to pay
is their destruction. To fight the project, they have enlisted
William Donald Schaefer, who was mayor of Baltimore from 1971 to
1987 and remains one of the city's most respected political
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer has said he favored improving the West Side using more
imagination and less of a ``bulldozer mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   With his support, and a threatened lawsuit, Boulmetis and other
West Side merchants still hope to stave off the wrecker's ball.
``This area evolved because it serves the market,'' Boulmetis said.
``Let it evolve. Not everything has to be the same, like any
suburban mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a matter of pretty buildings,'' he continued.
``It's our livelihood.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Kotkin is a senior fellow at the Pepperdine Institute for
Public Policy. His column on the Main Street economy appears the
fourth Sunday of each month. E-mail: grassrts(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
