</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-AIR-ACCIDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL OFFICIALS INVESTIGATING CLUSTER OF ACCIDENTS BY AMERICAN
AIRLINES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Honduras, Colombia)   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal safety officials said Thursday that they planned to
investigate why American Airlines, the country's second-largest
airline, has had more accidents in the last six years than any
other major domestic carrier. The announcement comes in the
aftermath of the crash of an American jet in Little Rock, Ark.,
earlier this month that killed 10 passengers and a pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said Thursday that it would
join with American over the next few weeks to examine all aspects
of its flight operations to determine what, if anything, the
incidents have in common and whether some action is necessary to
improve safety.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, American jets have been involved in six accidents,
two of them accounting for 171 deaths. The other accidents damaged
airplanes but did not seriously injure anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The latest accident occurred last week when a Boeing 757 jet hit
an airport fence while landing in Tegucigalpa, Honduras. The fence
shredded a tire and punched holes in the airplane's fuselage, but
none of the 190 passengers were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to determine whether there are some patterns
between the Little Rock accident and other recent accidents in the
American system to see if there is something we need to do,'' said
Paul Turk, a spokesman for the aviation agency.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board said Thursday that it
might also review American's accidents as part of its investigation
of the crash in Arkansas of Flight 1420, a McDonnell Douglas Super
80 jet, which skidded off the runway while trying to land in a
severe thunderstorm at Little Rock's airport on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Baker, American's executive vice president in charge
of operations, defended the airline's safety record, saying that
American went 15 years, from 1980 to 1995, without a fatal
accident. The 1995 crash, which is American's most serious so far,
occurred when a Boeing 757 crashed into a mountain near Cali,
Colombia, killing 160.
</P>
<P>
   Baker acknowledged that the recent accidents may form a pattern
and said that American was beginning its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appear to be some similarities in the history of
accidents and incidents over the past six years,'' he said, ``and
our commitment to safety requires our vigilance in maintaining
industry-leading training and operating procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   American has long been known for having one of the most
aggressive management teams in the airline industry. Like many
other airlines, it has had its share of difficulties with the labor
unions representing its workers. In recent years, its relations
with its pilots have been particularly strained, leading to a
``sick-out'' by pilots in February that forced American to cancel
more than half its flights.
</P>
<P>
   Some American pilots point to a corporate culture at the airline
that they say values profits over safety as perhaps one reason for
the recent crashes. They say that American managers intimidate
pilots who force the cancellation of flights for safety reasons and
have skimped on pilot training to save money.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots are particularly critical of American's failure to
comply with federal rules requiring that pilots have at least eight
hours of rest in the 24 hours before they complete their flight
duty.
</P>
<P>
   The two pilots in the cockpit of Flight 1420 had been working
more than 13 hours when they tried to land in Little Rock.
Investigators are looking at whether fatigue may have clouded their
judgment or pushed them to try the landing rather than divert to
another airport merely to bring a quick end to a long day.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chiames, an American spokesman, said that American did not
compromise on safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day we go out and sell our product, which is safe
transportation,'' Chiames said. ``There is nothing in our interest
to call into question our commitment to safety.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
