<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top form for Smoltz until eighth
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Smoltz continued to distance himself from a 22-1
loss to Baltimore on June 13 and prove his elbow is well enough by
blowing past the Expos for seven innings Thursday. A couple
mistakes in the eighth cost him a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on top of his game,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``He was
that good today.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz continued to use a more over-the-top fastball, mixed in
an occasional slider and felt comfortable, he said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back RBI triples cost Smoltz a 1-0 lead in the eighth
inning. Vladimir Guerrero, the Expos' leading run producer (51
RBIs), didn't start because of a strained groin, but he looked fine
rounding the bases on a pinch-hit triple off Smoltz. Another triple
by Manny Martinez and the Expos had a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made one bad pitch, a hanging slider to (Chris) Widger,''
said Smoltz, who allowed Widger a double to lead off the inning.
``Guerrero is just Guerrero. ... This is an aggressive hitting
team, a lot of young guys who want to hit the ball. I mixed in some
good pitches and went right after them.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon to have MRI on knee
</P>
<P>
   Randall Simon will have an MRI today on his left knee, which he
injured last week sliding into home plate at the Astrodome. Simon
has been playing on it, but hasn't seen much improvement. ``The
doctor said there may be some stretched ligaments,'' he said. ``I'm
still feeling some pain for almost a week already. They want to
know what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher's box
</P>
<P>
   Umpire Bob Davidson confronted the Braves on the size of their
catcher's box following Wednesday's game and had head groundskeeper
Ed Mangan draw up a new, smaller one for the game Thursday. The box
is supposed to be 43 inches wide. But catcher Eddie Perez said
Thursday's plate umpire, Mark Wegner, didn't make any special
effort to enforce it. ``He didn't really care,'' Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   The catcher's box has been a source of debate this season as
some umpires have enforced the rule that a catcher must stay within
the box, to help them call a more narrow strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
