<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ITEMS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thumbs up to Jimmy Spencer
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jimmy Spencer put the disappointment of a mediocre
season behind his struggling No. 23 Ford team at Pocono Raceway in
Long Pond, Pa., where he briefly led last week's Pocono 500 with
less than 20 laps remaining. Spencer, of Berwick, Pa., charged up
the hometown crowd when he passed Jeff Gordon on lap 172. ``My
spotter said, `You ought to see this crowd. They're going crazy,'''
Spencer said. ``I couldn't believe it. I said to myself, `There are
only 15 laps to go, and we're leading this race.''' It must have
been too good to be true, however, as Spencer's Ford hit some oil
on the track a few laps later and he slipped to finish 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down
</P>
<P>
   To NASCAR's wacky points system. Two-time defending Winston Cup
champion Gordon has put together an impressive run with three
runner-up finishes in a row. Yet, he made up only five points on
leader Dale Jarrett, who still holds a 349-point advantage over
Gordon. Jarrett's finishes in the last three events were sixth,
first and third. Last week at Pocono, both Gordon and Jarrett
scored 175 points. How's that for suspense?
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot?
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people expected Jeremy Mayfield to be a championship
contender this season after getting his first career victory and
finishing seventh in points last year. However, seven finishes of
17th or worse kept Mayfield out of the top 10 in points during the
first four months of this season. Mayfield, 30, of Owensboro, Ky.,
finally showed some consistency with three top-10s in the last four
races. His ninth-place effort in last week's Pocono 500, which he
led late, moved Mayfield to ninth in points, 560 behind leader
Jarrett. Since replacing fired crew chief Paul Andrews before The
Winston all-star race in Concord, N.C., on May 22, Peter Sospenzo
has an average finish of 10th with Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not?
</P>
<P>
   Less than three months ago, Rusty Wallace was coming off a
victory at Bristol and was eighth in points, trailing then-leader
Jeff Burton by only 173. Since then, however, Wallace has only
three top-10 finishes in eight events. Now he's 11th in points, 591
behind Jarrett. Wallace has three finishes of 12th or worse in the
last four races, including a 43rd at Pocono last week. In that
race, a blown tire sent Wallace into the wall after only seven
laps. It was his worst finish in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
