</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-SPENCER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A season up in smoke
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jimmy Spencer has watched his NASCAR season literally
go up in smoke.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Spencer, 42, of Berwick, Pa., was ninth in the
points standings heading into Sears Point Raceway, the first of two
road-course events on the Winston Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   When the Winston Cup series makes its annual stop in the San
Francisco area on Sunday, however, Spencer will find himself 29th
in points, trailing leader Dale Jarrett by a whopping 1,056.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, who had eight top-10 efforts last year, is still
looking for his first top-10 with 15 of 34 races completed this
season. He didn't finish five races this season and finished 25th
or worse in eight events.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's main problem has been blown engines and his sponsor,
Winston cigarettes, says it won't be back next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we've just been getting down on ourselves,'' said
Spencer, one of the series' most popular drivers because of his
outspoken personality and aggressive driving style. ``We're really
pounding harder on each other than we really need to. And we're
wanting to do the best we can. Maybe we're putting too much
pressure on ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed Spencer was ready to turn the corner last year, his
10th season in NASCAR's highest series. He had four top-seven
finishes in the first nine races of the year and stayed in the top
10 in points for three months.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's season came unraveled on Aug. 1, however, when he
wrecked at the Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis Motor Speedway. He
suffered a concussion in the wreck and missed races at Michigan and
Bristol, Tenn. He returned for the final 11 events and finished
14th in points.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer seemed poised for even greater success this year after
owner Travis Carter added a second team and veteran driver Darrell
Waltrip. But this season was a nightmare from the start, as Spencer
finished 20th or worse in four of the first five races.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it only got worse:
</P>
<P>
   _ A week after his car caught on fire in practice at Darlington,
S.C., Spencer wrecked his No. 23 Ford late in the Primestar 500 at
Texas Motor Speedway on March 28 and finished 28th. Spencer
suffered bruised ribs and used a relief driver, Steve Grissom, the
next week at Bristol. Spencer was pulled from the car midway
through the race after complaining of breathing problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ After finishing 36th at California and 29th at Richmond,
Spencer suffered perhaps his worst embarrassment May 22. He failed
to qualify for The Winston, NASCAR's annual all-star race, which is
sponsored by his primary sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   _ A week after The Winston, Spencer was the first driver behind
the wall for repairs during the Coca-Cola 600 at Lowe's Motor
Speedway in Concord, N.C. His crew needed five laps to repair a
broken radiator and he finished 38th.
</P>
<P>
   _ At Michigan Speedway two weeks ago, Spencer was the only
driver not to finish the race. His engine blew up after 159 laps in
the 200-lap event.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. announced that its Winston
brand would not renew its contract with Travis Carter Enterprises
after this season, ending a six-year partnership.
</P>
<P>
   While Carter searches for another sponsor for his primary car,
Spencer, who is in the final year of his contract, remains quiet
about his future with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that a lot of people will feed the press some rumors
just to see how far it will go, for no apparent reason,'' said
Spencer, who finished a season-best 14th at Pocono last week.
``I've not talked to any car owners about next year, including
Travis. I don't think it would be unfair to say I want to be with
Travis next year. But next year is a long ways away, in my mind,
and we can wait down the road to think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter also seems uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not spoken about next year,'' Carter said. ``I don't
know if he's ready to say he wants to stay. I don't know if I'm
ready to ask him to stay. We want to see if the team can get up and
run good with him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
