<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8663 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LPGA-BOS &LR;      06-24 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY CHECK FOR JONES, DAVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ As Rosie Jones made the turn in Thursday's
opening round of the LPGA Championship at DuPont CC at 6-under-par
30, then went to 7 under on her 10th hole, thoughts of 59 danced
through her head. ``Sure,'' she said, ``and then everything stops.
I don't care who you are, you cannot stop thinking about it. I
don't think it stopped me, I just didn't have a good visual on a
couple of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   As Laura Davies, who along with Jones started on the back nine,
also made the turn to the front side at 30, she, too, had thoughts
of 59. ``People talk about the Hall of Fame,'' said Davies, ``but
my ultimate goal is to shoot a 59. It'll happen some day. No
question about it. Players have gotten too good and the courses are
not that long.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones and Davies both returned to reality. Jones, who nearly
won the US Women's Open at Salem CC in 1984 and still is searching
for her first major title, had a bogey on No. 5 and finished
34-30_64. Davies played it out with nine straight pars and ended up
one shot astern at 35-30_65 on a hard, firm course.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions were ideal for scoring and 48 of the field of 144
broke par 71. The grouping at 67 included Allison Finney, Jenny
Lidback, Liselotte Neumann, Alison Nicholas, Trish Johnson, and
Vicki Fergon. Se Ri Pak, who was the wire-to-wire leader last year
as she won the first of two major championships, was in a group of
nine at 68.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who has nine career tour wins, made a regulation par on
her first hole, then went on a birdie rampage. She birdied her
second (wedge, 20 feet), third (9-iron, 12 feet), fourth (wedge, 4
feet), fifth (wedge, 6 feet), eighth (6-iron, 15 feet), and 10th
(7-iron, 15 feet).
</P>
<P>
   She bogeyed her 14th hole when she drifted into the left bunker.
After picking up a final birdie on her 17th (6-iron, 25 feet), she
thought she had made the putt on her closing hole for a 63, but a
12-foot try rimmed out.
</P>
<P>
   Is this her best round over the course? ``I don't think it
counts because we've been here in May and that's not fair for me,''
Jones said. ``It's a whole different tournament. I knew coming into
the week we were going to be wearing shorts and not pants and rain
gear and mittens. It's always so wet. The greens were hard in the
afternoon. I'm not a bad mudder. It just needs to be warm for me
and I'm playing real well right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies, who has always had great length but has struggled with
her putter over the past few years, has regained the touch that
made her one of the top players in the LPGA. ``I'm really
disappointed,'' she said after missing six birdie putts of 15 feet
or less over her last nine holes. ``I'm disappointed I didn't do
better. Having said that, 65 is my best round in an LPGA
Championship. I admit I was a bit frustrated, but it's good because
that means you're playing very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting on the 10th tee, she registered birdies on 10
(8-iron, 4 feet), the par-5 11th (two putts, 25 feet), and 14
(wedge, 25 feet). She eagled the par-5 17th (4-iron, 30 feet, two
putts) and just missed a 20-foot putt for a 29 on 18. ``I honestly
thought I was going to hole the putt,'' she said. ``Just at the end
it caught the lip. As it turned out, it pretty much stopped the
round.''
</P>
<P>
   Neumann, who was paired with Davies and ageless JoAnne Carner,
thought she might see a 59. ``She played so well,'' said Neumann.
``She could have had a 59. I couldn't believe how many putts just
didn't drop for her. It was very, very impressive. She was so
solid. She hit some great shots off the tee and great shots on the
green. It's tough to play with her when she's bombing them out
there so far. You have to stick to your game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak put together a round of five birdies and two bogeys. ``The
course was actually playing longer than it was last year.'' she
said. ``I had a very good driver today, and that's why it didn't
play hard. It's a very good golf course, conditions are perfect,
and I'm set.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
