<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-CLOSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NABISCO BAKERY CRUMBLES AFTER 50 YEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NELSON ANTOSH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Nabisco plans to close its 50-year-old cookie and
cracker bakery in Houston later this year, putting 425 hourly and
salaried employees out of work.
</P>
<P>
   The last day for the sprawling plant near downtown will be Nov.
20, company officials from the headquarters in Parsippany, N.J.,
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a phased shutdown, the first group of 140 employees will be
laid off Aug. 27, according to John L. Butler, senior vice
president of human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1949, when the plant was built, the smells of baking have
perfumed the area just south of downtown Houston. The combination
bakery and distribution center is in a 63,000-square-foot building
sitting on 20 acres. The area of the bakery where dough is mixed is
four stories tall.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the plant makes Ritz crackers, Air Crisps Cheese
Nips, Nabisco Graham crackers and Chewy Chips Ahoy chocolate chip
cookies. In the past, it also made Saltines.
</P>
<P>
   The bakery is being closed because the company's baking capacity
exceeds its needs, said spokesman Henry Sandbach. Industrywide, the
growth in demand for cookies and crackers is very slow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is one of the oldest bakeries in the system, the
Houston plant has been under-used, Nabisco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to close our Houston bakery was very difficult,''
said Thomas G. McBrady, Nabisco's vice president for operations.
</P>
<P>
   The bakery's current output will be handled by the company's
remaining nine bakeries in the United States, said Butler. The
plants nearest to Houston are in Atlanta and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Employees were concerned that the work might go to Mexico or to
a nonunionized plant, but that will not be the case, Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   After the plant is closed, Nabisco will have about 1,000
employees in Texas at sales offices and warehouse locations. The
number to remain in Houston was not available.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco is restructuring to try to cut costs, said Sandbach.
Last November, it closed a plant in Pittsburgh, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook appeared good in the spring of 1998, when Nabisco
announced plans to add an Oreo line to the Houston plant and
upgrade the facility, spending $40 million to $45 million while
getting a tax abatement.
</P>
<P>
   The Oreo line was never built, however, and the tax abatement
was never applied for, said Sandbach. Another plant handled the
Oreos that were to have been baked here.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston bakery survived a major scaling back in the summer
of 1996, said an official with the local Bakery, Confectionery,
Tobacco Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   The closing makes no sense because the bakery is profitable,
said the union official, who preferred not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's recent profits have declined, with
first-quarter earnings off 18 percent as Nabisco spent heavily on
promotions to boost sales.
</P>
<P>
   In April, it reported profits from operations totaling $45
million, compared with $55 million a year earlier. Last year, Chief
Executive Officer James Kilts said he would increase advertising
and promotion on major products to regain sales lost to Keebler
Foods.
</P>
<P>
   An analyst said the tactic was working because Nabisco's market
share went up for nine consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco is the nation's largest maker of cookies and crackers,
with more than twice the market share of any other company, Butler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco will negotiate severance benefits with the four unions
represented at the plant, Butler said. It will offer salaried
employees a package of severance pay, benefits and career-planning
services.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing the plant-closing Thursday morning, Nabisco
sent the employees home. The facility won't start baking again
until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, real estate professionals from the company will meet
with the Partnership to discuss possibilities for the site, which
Nabisco wants to sell. It could be used for manufacturing, for
warehousing or cleared for the land, Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
