<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-WRIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SENATOR HAS THE WRIGHT STUFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cathie Wright hands her legislative assistant a
piece of paper that has the words green beans and milk written on
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Why are you giving me a shopping list?' '' Lee Angela
Reid remembers asking her boss, the Republican state senator from
Simi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Wright responds, ``No, the other side'' and proceeds to tell
Reid how a woman approached her in the supermarket with a problem.
Wright wrote it down on the back of her shopping list.
</P>
<P>
   It was this kind of personal approach that caused Wright to help
save four Cal State Northridge men's sports two years ago. Cynics
might say Wright swooped into the CSUN debate for political reasons
_ she convinced a Legislative conference committee to approve a
one-time bailout of $586,000 from a system-wide general support
fund _ but she has steadfastly stayed on the case, working to
promote Senate Bill 338, which would require institutions to give
public notice if they plan to cut sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't jump on any issue when it makes headlines,'' Wright
said from her Sacramento office. ``I go with legislation that I
feel is important.''
</P>
<P>
   A sports fan, Wright believes in this cause and expects the bill
to pass. And this is what makes her a good legislator, said Sen.
Teresa Hughes, D-Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   ``She cares about her district,'' Hughes said. ``That's what
makes a good legislator: She passes a law because it's the right
thing to do. It crosses party lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright, 70 and a grandmother, developed her stance after having
been on the other side of what's fair.
</P>
<P>
   _Upon graduation from Old Forge High in Scranton, Pa., Wright
was selected valedictorian yet didn't receive the $500 scholarship
that often went with the honor because a classmate's mother was the
organization's president.
</P>
<P>
   _As a 20-year-old junior college graduate, Wright earned a
purple seal on her diploma for her 95 percent average. That also
entitled her to be placed in a high-paying job that the school
helped her find, but the department in the accounting firm she was
to head said she was too young.
</P>
<P>
   _She went to workfor an air conditioning and heating company in
Lacrosse, Wis., and regularly worked 14-hour days in the hopes of
earning promotions. One day, the company told her she would train
the next manager.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 19 years in the Legislature, Wright's been standing
up for that elusive ideal of fairness. That's why she won't talk to
someone who is rude to a member of her staff. That's why she reads
all the mail first.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the hallway say, `Look, there goes Team Wright,'''
Reid said. ``When she has an issue, she won't let go.''
</P>
<P>
   When Northridge decided to cut baseball, soccer, volleyball and
swimming after the 1997 season, Wright found herself inundated with
calls and letters from her constituents.
</P>
<P>
   So she dove in, investigating university documents and finding
the money to keep the programs afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Wright also frequently checked on the Task Force on
Intercollegiate Athletics to make sure it was finding answers. When
she wasn't satisfied, Wright threatened an audit of Northridge, and
opposition toward the $586,000 stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Cathie Wright, I'm not sure how this would've played
out,'' said activist Duke Russell, who helped draft Senate Bill
338. ``Without that money, there might not be baseball now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright's sport of choice is basketball (she played the sport in
high school and attended various levels of games six nights a
week), but she shares with Russell a longstanding recognition of
the importance of athletics to a person's development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do anything when it affects people's lives without
knowing I can do it,'' she said. ``The point is fairness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
