<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 06/24/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WASHINGTON -- June 24, 1999 -- CONGRESS-FLAG, 6-24 --
Former Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon of New York, right, with two
students from San Diego, helps celebrate passage by the House on
Thursday of an constitutional amendment to prohibit desecration of
the flag. The vote, 305 to 124, was well in excess of the
two-thirds majority needed to approve a constitutional amendment.
(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) WASHINGTON -- June 24, 1999 -- INTEREST-RATES-3, 6-24 --
Laurence H. Meyer, governor of the Federal Reserve Board. ``Even
with generous allowances for structural change, labor utilization
would seem to be at a level that might eventually begin to put
persistent and growing pressure on labor costs and prices,'' he
says. (Amy Thompson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) DALLAS -- June 24, 1999 -- INTEREST-RATES-2, 6-24 --
Robert D. McTeer Jr., president of the Federal Reserve Bank of
Dallas. ``The thing is that productivity increases have been so
strong lately that even though wages have been going up nicely,
labor costs have not,'' he says. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) VUCITURN, Yugoslavia -- June 24, 1999 --
KOSOVO-VIOLENCE-3, 6-24 -- Ethnic Albanians remove items from a
house which belonged to a Serb in the northern Kosovar village on
Thursday. Looting by Albanians intensified in the region on
Thursday resulting in more anxious Serbs streaming out. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) WASHINGTON -- June 24, 1999 -- FORFEITURE, 6-24 --
Members of the House Judiciary Committee in the Rayburn Room of the
U.S. Capitol after successful passage of a bill governing federal
forfeiture of property on Thursday. From left are Reps. Bob Barr,
R-Ga., John Conyers, D-Mich., Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the
committee, and Barney Frank, D-Mass. An unusual coalition of
liberals and conservatives persuaded the House to approve
legislation making it significantly harder for Federal and state
law enforcement authorities to confiscate property before they
actually bring criminal charges in narcotics and other cases. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) ZACATECAS, Mexico -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 27 -- MEXICO-DROUGHT-3-COX, 6-24 -- Dried cactus in a field in
Zacetecas. This is just one aspect of the drought conditions that
are currently affecting parts of Mexico. (Stephen Levine/Cox
Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) ZACATECAS, Mexico -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 27 -- MEXICO-DROUGHT-2-COX, 6-24 -- With a face as parched and
wrinkled as the land he has been trying to farm, Apolonio
Hernandez, 76, sits in a field dried and cracked by the current
drought. (Stephen Levine/Cox Newspapers Photo)
