<P>
   (NYT29) IZBICA, Yugoslavia -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 27 --KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-2-COX, 6-24 -- Sadik Gjemajli, 42,
right, and Afrim Gjemajli, 35, are officers of the Kosovo
Liberation Army who have kept the list of names and chronology of
events to give to investigators from The Hague tribunal. Local
farmers say Serb troops uncovered and removed the bodies of Kosovar
Albanians buried in a mass grave here - evidence of a massacre that
was listed as one count in the war crimes indictment against
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. (Marcia Kunstel/Cox
Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 27 -- KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-1-COX, 6-24 -- At least 20 Kosovar
Albanians were said to be burned alive in this house in Djakovica
in early April. Gani Kadriu, 50, says he watched from his
neighboring garden as Serbian forces assaulted the home and then
set it on fire. The act has been listed as one count in the war
crimes indictment against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
(Marcia Kunstel/Cox Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) SAO PAULO, Brazil -- June 24, 1999 --
BRAZIL-SINGING-PRIEST, 6-24 -- Father Marcelo Rossi during a Mass
at the Sanctuary of the Byzantine Rosary, a former warehouse Rossi
converted into his home church. At 32, Padre Marcelo, as the
faithful here call him, has emerged as the driving force and main
symbol of the Charismatic Renovation movement that is transforming
the face of Catholicism in the world's most populous Roman Catholic
nation. (Larry Rohter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- June 24, 1999 -- INSURANCE-FRAUD, 6-24 --
Martin Frankel in a recent but undated photo. Federal authorities
have issued an arrest warrant for Frankel, though he has not been
charged with any crime. They suspect that his firm, Liberty
National Securities, was the foundation of a pyramid scheme. (/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) VUCITURN, Yugoslavia -- June 24, 1999 --
KOSOVO-VIOLENCE-2, 6-24 -- Enthnic Albanians laugh while a house
which belonged to a Serb is consumed in flames on Thursday in the
northern Kosovar village. Looting by Albanians intensified in the
region resulting in more anxious Serbs streaming out. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UROSEVAC, Yugoslavia -- June 24, 1999 --
KOSOVO-VIOLENCE-1, 6-24 -- An enthnic Albanian boy covers his face
as he climbs out of a stationary store after breaking the window
and looting notebooks and other items on Thursday in the northern
Kosovar village. Looting by Albanians intensified in the region on
Thursday resulting in more anxious Serbs streaming out. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK-- June 24, 1999 -- GORILLA-EXHIBIT-FLOATER,
6-24 -- John Frawley looks at a Western Lowland Gorilla on Thursday
at the ``Congo Gorilla Forest'' exhibit at the Bronx Zoo. The
exhibit opened to the public on Wednesday and consists of a
6.5-acre habitat with 300 animals that sets a new world standard
for conservation. (Billy R. Smith 2d/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-B&AMP;W, 6-24 -- Ray Goldberg, the Moffett Professor of
Agriculture and Business at the Harvard Business School and head of
the agribusiness program there. ``Traceability is becoming much
more important in our food system,'' he says. ``In the not too
distant future, we are going to be able to bar-code every product,
from a grain of cereal to a loaf of bread.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BALTIMORE -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
BIZ-EARNER-FAMILY, 6-24 -- Mark and Anastasia Edmonston of
Baltimore returning from a shopping trip with their daughter,
Hannah, in their five-year-old Volvo. Mrs. Edmonston is leaving her
job to pursue a master's degree. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BALTIMORE -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
BIZ-BALTIMORE-REVIVAL, 6-24 -- Lou Boulmetis, right, reminiscing
with William Blount, 81, about streetcar traffic that used to pass
in front of his hat store in Baltimore. The business is among
approximately 100 that could be displaced by a redevelopment plan.
(Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) DALLAS -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
BIZ-MED-CENTER, 6-24 -- Dr. Kern Wildenthal, president of the
Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas, talking with a researcher,
Jenny Michalopulos, at the Harmon Cancer Center. Wildenthal has
helped build three medical research towers here over the last five
years, and can describe plans for three more. The buildings and
programs they house reflect his talent for separating Texans from
their millions. (Mark Graham/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- June 24, 1999 -- INTEREST-RATES, 6-24 --
Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., gestures towards supporters of his
position against the Federal Reserve raising interest rates outside
Capitol Hill on Thursday. Looking on from left are: John Sweeney,
of the AFL-CIO, Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., Rep. Maurice Hinchey,
D-N.Y., Judith Lichtman with the National Partnership for Women &AMP;
Families, Kweisi Mfume, head of the NAACP, and Rep. Bruce Vento,
D-Minn. Economists and investors are all but certain that the Fed
will push its benchmark lending rate up by a modest quarter of a
percentage point next week in a preemptive strike against the
possibility of resurgent inflation. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-2, 6-24 --
New York Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy during a Thursday press
conference at Madison Square Garden. ``Size does matter in this
league,'' Van Gundy says of his team's 96-89 loss to the San
Antonio Spurs on Wednesday night in Game 4 of the Finals. ``Their
size beat our speed and quickness because not only did they affect
us on the boards and in the post scoring, but every penetration was
a difficult, difficult shot because of their shot blocking.''
(Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-1, 6-24 --
New York Knicks forward Larry Johnson looks as though he would
rather be elsewhere than at this Thursday press conference at
Madison Square Garden. Johnson, limited to five points and six
rebounds during the San Antonio Spurs' 96-89 victory Wednesday
night in Game 4 of the Finals, recalls New York's frustration down
the stretch. ``We didn't get ours to fall, and those guys ran just
like a practice,'' he says. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 6-24 -- For
the last month, Linda Hart has been donning a fat suit and
astounding audiences with her portrayal of the coarsely hysterical
Bunny Weinberger in Second Stage's revival of Albert Innaurato's
``Gemini.'' She says she had to think twice before taking on
Bunny's bad self, but that it was a lesson from the pulpit that
keyed her into the character. ``You don't go up there without
knowing you're going to go for it,'' she says. ``It's a real leap
of faith.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOSTON -- June 24, 1999 -- WORKING-LESS-BOS, 6-24 --
Katy Abel having ice cream with her son Rubin Brenner and his
brother in Boston. Six months ago, faced with a hectic workload
that kept her from spending enough time at home, Abel left her
part-time job as features reporter for a Boston television station.
But Ms. Abel, 40, has discovered what a growing number of parents
are realizing: Working part time is no panacea for people
struggling to juggle the demands of career and family. (Janet
Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEEDHAM, Mass. -- June 24, 1999 -- LAW-FAMILY-BOS, 6-24
-- Andy Epstein plays with his son Matthew, 3. Epstein, a Harvard
Law School graduate who joined a prestigious New York firm before
practicing at a big firm in Boston, quit big firm life and took a
job as an in-house attorney for Lotus Development Corp. in
Cambridge, Mass. Now he works out of his house as a solo
practioner. ``You realize your life doesn't have to be your work
and your work doesn't have to be your life,'' he says. (Janet
Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- BARGE-MUSIC, 6-24 -- Olga
Bloom, the founder and director of Bargemusic, with, from
background left, Toby Hoffman, Peter Nagy and Ronald Thomas. Since
1977, a 102-foot solid steel barge docked on the East River in
Brooklyn has been the home of Bargemusic. The barge serves as a
platform where music lovers can experience the intimacy of chamber
music as it was in the days of Mozart and Mendelssohn. (Michelle V.
Agins/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- BASH-THEATER-REVIEW, 6-24
-- Calista Flockhart in the one-act play ``A Gaggle of Saints,''
which is one of several short plays comprising Neil LaBute's
``Bash: Latter-Day Plays,'' which opened Thursday night at the
Douglas Fairbanks Theater. The characters in this transfixing
evening of monologues have an idealized sheen that Labute uses to
disarm the audience. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SAN FRANCISCO -- June 24, 1999 -- APPLE-SANFRAN-2, 6-24
-- Victorian homes on Waller street in the Haight Ashbury district
of San Francisco. San Francisco has always been a paradox: A
thoroughly worldly place, yet remote and somehow detached from
world capitals like New York and London, a little indifferent to
the mundane business of trading shares and casting votes, in other
words a bit smug. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SAN FRANCISCO -- June 24, 1999 -- APPLE-SANFRAN-1, 6-24
-- The Palace of Fine Arts, a 1915 architectural gem overlooking
San Francisco Bay. San Francisco has always been a paradox: A
thoroughly worldly place, yet remote and somehow detached from
world capitals like New York and London, a little indifferent to
the mundane business of trading shares and casting votes, in other
words a bit smug. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- June 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-HOLBROOKE, 6-24 --
Richard Holbrooke, nominated by President Clinton as U.S.
ambassador to the U.N., during his confirmation hearings before the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee on Thursday. Holbrooke was
questioned Thursday on his views on the current situation in
Kosovo. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WALLULA, Wash. -- June 24, 1999 -- LABOR-IMMIGRANTS, 6-24
-- Workers at the IBP, Inc. beef processing plant march to call
attention to their strike. In a sign of the increasing voice of new
immigrants in the labor movement, a group of workers at the meat
processing plant that includes Laotians, Mexicans, Vietnamese and
Bosnians has organized a wildcat strike because as one worker put
it: ``Enough is enough.'' (Jackie Johnston/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
NY-STARCK-ARCHITECTURE, 6-24 -- The LVMH Tower's folds of glass
burst out from the curtain walls along the north side of East 57th
Street. Designed by Christian de Portzamparc, the youngest
architect to be awarded a Pritzker Architecture Prize, in
association with the Hillier Group, the 23-story office tower does
the skyline a great service. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
JENNIFER-LOPEZ-ALBUM-2, 6-24 -- Elvis Crespo, a New York-born
singer who melds Dominican merengue with modern dance beats. The
American news media has declared a Latino explosion that heralds
not just a new level of commercial success for Latino-American
singers but the long-awaited acceptance of Latin music into the pop
mainstream. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
JENNIFER-LOPEZ-ALBUM-1, 6-24 -- ``The music on the record is
directly linked to the person I am,'' says Jennifer Lopez, whose
debut album, ``On the Six,'' draws on her Bronx upbringing. The
record presents a polished urban mix of Latin, rhythm-and-blues and
soul-tinged ballads and dance numbers, with most of the songs in
English but a few in Spanish, like a salsa-flavored duet with her
fellow Nuyorican singer Marc Anthony. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NICASIO, Calif. -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
27 -- HAUNTING-FILM, 6-24 -- Gary Rydstrom at Skywalker Ranch in
Northern California, where he is working on scary sounds for ``The
Haunting,'' set to open July 23. The film, directed by Jan De Bont,
is layered with the sounds of inhuman conversations - between wood
and air, between stone and glass, and between an evil entity and
its tormented victims. ``To me, a scary sound is one that you can't
pin down, or one that is behind you,'' says Rydstrom. (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
SEX-THEATER-2, 6-24 -- Sigourney Weaver and Guy Boyd in Christopher
Durang's ``Sex and Longing.'' One of the few American sex comedies
offered this season, its main character is a nymphomaniac who needs
sex every 15 minutes. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
SEX-THEATER-1, 6-24 -- Ciaran Hinds and Anna Friel in Patrick
Marber's ``Closer.'' In a culture in which sex looms as a major
presence in everything from music videos to painting, from novels
to advertising, Marber's production is one of the few offering
explorations of sex in what has been widely hailed as Broadway's
season of the play. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
