<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANNETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANNETT OFFERS $1.5 BILLION FOR NEWSQUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After more than a decade in which foreign investors, from Robert
Maxwell to Conrad Black, bought newspapers in the United States,
the Gannett Co. reversed the trend Thursday, offering about $1.5
billion in cash plus assumed debt for Newsquest PLC, a regional
newspaper publisher in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Newsquest is the company that emerged after the investment firm
of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. put up the first portion of what
would eventually be an investment of 100 million pounds, or $168
million in British publishing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the company hired Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. to examine its
financial options, and has entertained a variety of bids. According
to Scott Stuart, a partner in Kohlberg Kravis, Gannett's offer was
the highest.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement issued by Gannett said that, because the
company's management and its two largest shareholders had accepted
its offer, 51.7 percent of the outstanding stock is pledged to
Gannett _ a majority stake that makes the success of their bid
highly probable.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett's other foreign venture is the overseas edition of USA
Today, which is printed in London, Frankfurt and Hong Kong and
distributed in 60 countries. In a prepared statement Thursday,
Douglas H. McCorkindale, vice chairman and president of Gannett,
said, ``This acquisition is the right opportunity to expand our
international operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven N. Barlow, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston,
said Thursday that Gannett's investment in overseas newspapers ``is
unusual, but if anyone could do it, it would be'' Gannett. With a
market capitalization of $19.75 billion, ``they have the financial
wherewithal to make a large acquisition,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   With 74 newspapers and 21 television stations in the United
States, ``they cover a lot of geography in the United States,'' and
it is more likely that a large acquisition could run afoul of
regulatory requirements, like the Federal Communications Commission
rule against owning both a newspaper and a television station in
the same market.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Barlow said, U.S. newspaper companies have had
little inclination to invest abroad because ``there have been
enough opportunities in the United States.'' When it comes to
foreign newspaper investments, Barlow added, American companies
have often shied away because ``there has been trepidation about
trying to manage a far-flung empire.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Broadwater, a managing director of Veronis Suhler &AMP;
Associates Inc., a company that has handled several newspaper
acquisitions, said the Gannett-Newsquest deal made sense in part
because the two companies' businesses are similar. He also pointed
out that ``The way the British media marketplace as developed over
the years,'' regional newspapers ``are very attractive businesses,
particularly for financial investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Since about two-thirds of the slightly less than 1,500 dailies
in the United States are owned by chains, Gannett's options for
large investment in this country are becoming rare, Broadwater
added. But given its size, he said, Gannett could well afford to
make the Newsquest purchase and, should it choose to, also invest
in a property like The San Francisco Chronicle, which is currently
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkindale told a meeting of investors and financial analysts
earlier this week that Gannett's 1998 cash flow was $1.75 billion,
and that it anticipated a cash flow of $1.89 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gannett's offer, Newsquest shareholders would receive 460
pence ($7.31) in cash for each of 200.4 million fully diluted
shares.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, coupled with earlier sales of parts of its Newsquest
holdings, would give Kohlberg Kravis a cumulative return of 400
million pounds on their initial investment for a profit of 300
million pounds (or $504 million), Stuart said.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett stock closed at $70.6875 Thursday, down $2.75, or 3.7
percent. Newsquest's stock, trading on the London Stock Exchange,
closed at 455 pence, up 32 pence, or 7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart of Kohlberg Kravis said that the current management team
at Newsquest would mesh well with Gannett's managers. He added that
``The regional newspaper industry in the U.K. is a terrific
business. It is the dominant form of local news and advertising for
the local communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the 11 dailies that would come under Gannett's ownership
are The Evening Argus, based in Brighton, on Britain's southern
coast, and The Northern Echo, which covers northeastern Britain
from the town of Darlington. The Northern Echo was also the first
newspaper edited by Harry Evans, now the editorial director of The
Daily News in New York, U.S. News &AMP; World Report and The Atlantic
Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who in the late 1970s sought American investors when he
was trying to prevent Rupert Murdoch from taking over the
London-based Sunday Times, said that back then ``American newspaper
owners had a terror of the British newspaper unions.'' But since
Murdoch's battles with the unions sapped the unions' power, Evans
said, this fear has evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are a good group of papers,'' Evans added. ``It's good
for them to stay in a newspaper family, instead of being in some
international conglomerate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
