<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8691 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-ENDS-HNS &LR;      06-24 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ENDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT ENDS TERM SHARPLY DIVIDED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, in its just-completed term,
reflected a sharp ideological split among the justices, including
conservative rulings that expanded state authority and liberal
decisions that broadened federal rights to protect schoolgirls.
</P>
<P>
   The court's slim five-member conservative majority asserted
itself in many other opinions, such as those that protected
employers in discrimination suits. It also rejected the appeals of
death-row inmates and gave police greater authority to search
passengers during traffic stops. But the high court's four-member
liberal minority also enjoyed significant victories, picking up
needed conservative support to limit the power that cities can give
their police officers in the fight against gang violence.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the enigmatic term, Steven Shapiro of the American
Civil Liberties Union said the justices have created confusion as
to the future of individual rights, citing the court's apparently
contradictory rulings in favor of states' rights and against
expansive police powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their long-term impact on civil rights and civil liberties is
uncertain but troubling,'' said Shapiro, ACLU's national legal
director, referring to the states' rights decisions. But ``the
court's record on more traditional civil rights cases was probably
better than expected,'' he said. Shapiro is a frequent critic of
the conservative-led judicial body.
</P>
<P>
   During the term, 5-4 decisions proved plentiful, with the same
justices often forming the majority or being relegated to the
minority.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative majority consisted of Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, Sandra Day
O'Connor and Anthony M. Kennedy. Forming the minority were liberal
Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of the ideological divide became apparent this
year as justices on both sides often took the deeply symbolic step
of reading their dissenting opinions from the bench. Justices
reserve this public gesture for themselves only when they have the
deepest philosophical differences with the majority.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on Wednesday, the court's final public day this
term, three liberal justices _ Souter, Breyer and Stevens _ read in
somber tones their vehement objections to the majority's decision
that the Constitution gives states immunity from most civil suits
in federal and state courts. The dissenters said the court's
position will deny citizens the chance to vindicate their rights
against states that have abused governmental authority.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case, Kennedy last month voiced his objection to
the court's decision that the federal law banning sex
discrimination at schools also prohibits sexual harassment by a boy
against a female classmate. Kennedy assailed the court's broad
reading of Title IX of the 1972 Education Amendments, adding that
it will prompt a flood of litigation in cases of mere playground
teasing.
</P>
<P>
   The just-completed term mirrored past years, with Kennedy or
O'Connor often being the deciding vote in close cases, said
University of Houston law professor David Crump.
</P>
<P>
   These two justices remain ``relatively unpredictable swing
votes'' on a generally conservative court, Crump said. ``It looks
to me as though the coalitions on the court haven't changed much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy and O'Connor factor proved critical in three major
cases this term.
</P>
<P>
   In one, Kennedy and O'Connor joined their more liberal
colleagues in ruling unconstitutional a Chicago ordinance that
allowed police to disperse people congregating on street corners
with a suspected gang member. The court called the local law vague,
saying it gave police unbridled authority to order loiterers to
separate while providing city residents with no warning of what
behavior would constitute an illegal act.
</P>
<P>
   The second case was the one involving Title IX in which O'Connor
not only joined the liberal wing but signed the majority opinion
that said school districts can be held liable for ignoring severe
sexual harassment of one student by another.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy joined the liberals and wrote the majority opinion in
the third case, in which the court held 5-4 that a judge cannot
hand down a harsher sentence against a convict simply because the
criminal remained silent during a trial's sentencing phase. The
court, over the objections of its conservatives, said the
constitutional privilege against self incrimination extends to the
post-conviction part of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   In another 5-4 decision, the court's solid, though slim,
conservative majority said doctors, lawyers, accountants and other
professionals who make house calls enjoy no constitutional
protection against unreasonable police searches while conducting
business in someone else's home. The court's decision upheld the
conviction of two Minnesota men whom a police officer saw packaging
cocaine in a colleague's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The court, on another 5-4 vote along ideological lines, rejected
the pleas of two death-row inmates _ including one from Texas _ who
argued in vain that judges had violated their rights to a fair
trial by giving confusing sentencing instructions to the juries
that called for their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas case, the majority held that the judge was under no
constitutional obligation to tell jurors that Louis Jones Jr. would
spend the rest of his life in prison even if they did not vote to
sentence him to death for the brutal murder of Air Force Pvt.
Tracie Joy McBride. In the other case, the justices told a federal
appeals court that it should not have set aside a California death
sentence ``without first determining that the (judge's) error had a
substantial and injurious effect on the jury's verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives also held sway in ruling 5-4 that employers
can avoid being assessed punitive damages in discrimination cases
if they made a good-faith effort to comply with Title VII of the
1964 Civil Rights Act, which prohibits job bias.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also took a hit at the hands of the
conservatives, as the court on a 5-4 vote struck down as a
violation of the federal Census Act his proposal to use a
statistical formula to complement the traditional head count of the
U.S. population in the 2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in another case, ruled against automobile passengers.
Breyer joined the conservatives in a 6-3 decision that the
Constitution's prohibition on unreasonable searches does not
protect passengers from having their belongings examined by police
who suspect the driver has committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, Souter and Ginsburg joined the conservatives in
reading the Americans with Disabilities Act narrowly to hold that
job applicants making discrimination claims under the law must
first prove their physical or mental afflictions cannot be easily
alleviated.
</P>
<P>
   The court, despite its sharp ideological split, found unanimity
in ruling that the Constitution forbids police officers from
automatically searching the cars of motorists they have pulled over
for traffic violations. The justices were also in agreement that
courts should defer to the attorney general's decisions in
political-asylum cases on whether an immigrant is justifiably
trying to escape political persecution at home or merely seeking to
avoid legitimate prosecution for having committed serious
nonpolitical crimes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
