<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marcis out, mad at Brett Bodine
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Driver Dave Marcis, injured in a nasty crash in
Sunday's Pocono 500, will sit out this week's race at Sears Point
Raceway. Marcis, 58, still is complaining of a sore collarbone,
ribs and ankle and headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Marcis' No. 71 Chevrolet made contact with Brett Bodine's No. 11
Ford in the ``Tunnel Turn'' on the 2.5-mile triangle-shaped
speedway at Pocono. Marcis' car was turned into the outside wall
where it hit, first on the nose and then on the tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body's still sore, and I'm still a little upset with Brett
Bodine,'' Marcis said. ``He did the same thing to his brother
(Todd) a couple of years ago at Indy. He just flat spun me out.
Robert Pressley was right behind us. I haven't spoken to Robert,
but he told guys on my team that it was a cheap shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ended up being a pretty bad accident, and my car is just
about busted in half. The car is junk, thanks to Brett Bodine. I'm
sure he's going to send me a check for it, but I don't suppose I
should hold my breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcis, who owns his car, hired road-course specialist R.K.
Smith to drive in this week's race. Smith, 61, of Rancho Sante Fe,
Calif., drove in the 24 Hours of Daytona earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hood tethers a success
</P>
<P>
   The new hood restraint NASCAR tried on selected cars last week
at Pocono got an early test when Rusty Wallace's No. 2 Ford slammed
into the wall on lap seven. The device seemed to work.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's car blew its right front tire before going into the
wall on the first turn, smashing the right side of the car. Wallace
was not hurt, but he called it ``one of the hardest hits I've ever
had in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hood, tethered to the chassis by a support cable, didn't
appear to move or be damaged. Also using the cable were Jeff Gordon
and Pocono 500 winner Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials rushed testing of the restraints after a May 1
accident during an Indy Racing League event at Lowe's Motor
Speedway in Concord, N.C. Three spectators were killed and another
eight were injured when a wheel and other debris flew into the
grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is basically for fan safety, if these things happen to
get off the car,'' Wallace's crew chief, Robin Pemberton said. ``It
shouldn't be a big hassle, not for what you get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Third team for Petree?
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet owner Andy Petree couldn't wait for U.S. Tobacco Co.
to re-sign with his No. 33 Winston Cup car before seeking out
another sponsor. So Petree, who owns the cars of drivers Ken
Schrader and Kenny Wallace, went out and landed another sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Petree said Schrader, his top driver, won't be driving the No.
33 Skoal car next season. Instead, he will drive a car with the new
sponsor, which could be Oakwood Homes, a mobile home manufacturer,
which sponsors Schrader's Busch car this year.
</P>
<P>
   Petree said he will add a third team if U.S. Tobacco Co. returns
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Praying for rain
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear shipped 2,600 rain tires to Sonoma, Calif., and Watkins
Glen, N.Y., hoping finally to test them in one of the NASCAR races
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup drivers were allotted 1,200 tires, while Busch and
Craftsman Truck drivers have 800 and 600, respectively. The tires
can be used only on road courses.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
