<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-EXPOS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A weird victory in 11
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Go figure the Braves' 3-2 win over Montreal on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   How can John Smoltz dominate for seven innings, get a
season-high nine strikeouts and be trailing 2-1? And how does
Ugueth Urbina, one of the game's best closers, give up flares to
Otis Nixon and Keith Lockhart and blow his first save in a month?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who've been stranding runners with regularity, left
another 10 in scoring position. But with two out in the ninth,
catcher Chris Widger let an Urbina pitch pass under his glove and
Nixon scored from third to tie it 2-2 and force extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan, who didn't expect to play because of a sore wrist,
drove in the game-winning run with a single in the 11th. But the
Braves aren't going to try to explain it, prefering to ride it into
a weekend series with the Mets, who won again Thursday to remain
three games back in the NL East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just happy to get out of here with a win,'' manager Bobby Cox
said. ``A good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz took a no-decision after allowing five hits in eight
innings, three of them in the eighth. He gave up two runs on
back-to-back two-out triples by a pinch-hitting Vladimir Guerrero
and Martinez. That set up more late-inning drama by the Braves, now
7-3 in extra inning games this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Guillen led off the 11th with his third hit of the game,
then stole second as Chipper Jones swung and missed on a
hit-and-run try and Chris Widger's throw to second sailed wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get on base,'' Guillen said. ``Luckily I got
to second base. Then when they walked Chipper, we had a chance to
bring up best RBI man on the team, maybe baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was just glad to get through the game, and through the
Expos, who left with one win in three tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate playing against teams like this,'' said Jordan, who was
2-for-5 and got his 58th RBI. ``Those guys have nothing to lose.
They go out there and they fight and scrap and they give everybody
trouble. I don't think any team in the league likes to see the
Expos come to town.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
