<SLUG> BC-BKN-GAME5-ADVANCE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robinson on verge of a title
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Robinson has been most valuable player of the
NBA, the league's best rookie, the defensive player of the year and
a scoring champion. He has made the All-NBA team and the
all-defensive team.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years in the league, though, and Robinson has not won a
title. When he went down with a bad back after six games in
1996-97, it appeared he could be one of those players who had
always missed the ring, who always would have a hole in his resume.
</P>
<P>
   His teams had a history of stumbling in the West, failing
against Utah, losing a conference final to Houston. The window was
closing, and the Admiral was standing on the outside. No matter
what happened to the Spurs, the perception was that Robinson lacked
something, not because there was a deficiency at shooting guard or
small forward or because the bench was thin or the coach
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before Michael Jordan started winning regularly, the
fault seemed to lie with the other Bulls players. The same was true
with Oscar Robertson in Cincinnati and Jerry West in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for Robinson. Yet, he accepted his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of that has been because I take that
responsibility on,'' Robinson said Thursday. ``And justified or
not, I think, as a leader, the results do lie in your lap. It's how
it is in this business, how it is in every aspect of your life. You
dictate the character of the team. You dictate the personality of
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   His wait probably will end tonight in Madison Square Garden, or
Sunday or Wednesday in San Antonio, when the Spurs get rid of the
pesky New York Knicks and crown themselves champions of this
bizarre season.
</P>
<P>
   And Robinson, leaning heavily on his young pal Tim Duncan, will
have reached the pinnacle a dozen years after the Spurs picked him,
knowing that they would have to wait two seasons for the Annapolis
graduate to finish his Navy tour.
</P>
<P>
   Among the perceptions of Robinson is that he's too nice a guy to
steer a title team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice when people see that I can have the personality that
I have and still be a champion,'' he said. ``That's a nice feeling
(because) it hurts when they question your ability to get things
done, say some things about me that I knew weren't true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the most competitive people I know. And when people
question your desire to be out there on the floor, that bothers
you. So, it just gave me a little bit more fuel to keep coming at
it, keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and Duncan have dominated the under-sized Knicks.
Combined, they are averaging 43.5 points, 27.1 rebounds and 5.5
blocks a game in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wear you down,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   And with no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to see them doing what they're doing,'' said Avery
Johnson, their point guard. ``To see Tim, a young guy, playing at
this level, and David finally getting his due really makes me feel
good. But that's what playoff basketball is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, waived twice by the Spurs in the early days of his
career, says this postseason world is a mix of ``pain and pleasure
_ pain when you lose, pleasure when you win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember sitting in the visitors locker room in Houston
(after losing Game Six of the West final 1995), and they announced
that tickets for the NBA Finals will go on sale tomorrow. That's
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs figure they've had enough pain. They are 14-2 in the
playoffs, and they don't want this thing to linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really going to be focused in,'' Robinson said. ``That's
what we talked about today. Getting better. Do better stuff than
you did in the last game. Get better. Win.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
