<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DRAFT-EUROPE25-CO     06-24 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-EUROPE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Europeans not foreign to the NHL
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Wayne Gretzky played his final game two months
ago, it seemed appropriate that the game's deciding goal was not
scored by Brantford, Ontario's famous son, nor anybody else from
the northern provinces. Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr, a native of
Kladno, in the Czech Republic, sent Gretzky into retirement with a
loss. And with his winning goal, Jagr might have punctuated the
European overthrow of the ``National'' Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Gretzky implied that Jagr was the man to take
over as hockey's premier ambassador. If the Penguins' star needs
support, he can always turn to other NHL transplants. The game's
best goalie, Dominik Hasek, also is from the Czech Republic and the
best all-around forward, Colorado's Peter Forsberg, is from Sweden,
as is the best defenseman, Detroit's Nicklas Lidstrom. The three
MVP candidates this year are Czech, Czech and Russian _ Hasek, Jagr
and Alexei Yashin.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for the trend to end any time soon. Although North
Americans will continue to dominate in numbers, Saturday's NHL
entry draft is further evidence that foreign ingredients make up
the league's upper crust. The projected first four picks are
forwards Patrik Stefan and Pavel Brendl of the Czech Republic and
twins Daniel and Henrik Sedin of Sweden. It follows the Czechs'
defeat of Russia in the final of last year's winter OIympics, not
the U.S.-Canada showdown the NHL had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the apocalypse,'' said Brian Burke, Vancouver general
manager and former NHL vice president. ``This is still a strong
North American draft after the first few players. But I do think we
need to look at ways of changing how we develop our players. They
develop more elite players in Europe. If you look at all of our
finalists (for 1998-99 awards), it's dominated by Europeans.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's Central Scouting Service would have you believe the
power shift is not that extreme, but its rankings of players in
this draft are misleading. The scouting service issues two sets of
quarterly rankings: North American players and European players.
But the ``North American'' designation pertains to the player's
team in the amateurs _ not where he was born, lived for most of his
life and learned the game.
</P>
<P>
   The two best examples are the players who are listed 1-2 in the
North American rankings. Stefan is a native of Prague and Brendl of
Olomouc. But Stefan played this year with the IHL's Long Beach Ice
Dogs and Brendl with Calgary of the Western Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the top 10 ``North Americans'' in those rankings are
from Europe: Stefan; Brendl; No. 5 Denis Shvidki (Ukraine), who
played for Barrie of the Ontario Hockey League; No. 9 Branislav
Mezei (Slovakia), who played for Belleville of the OHL; and No. 10
Oleg Saprykin (Russia), who played for Seattle in the Western
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Hockey News' projected first round in
Saturday's draft, the first four players, six of the top nine and
14 of the first 28 are Europeans. But in total numbers, the actual
country breakdown still favored Canadians: Canada 11, Russia 5,
Czech Republic 4, United States 3, Sweden 2, Ukraine 1, Finland 1,
Slovakia 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question the more skilled players are coming out of
Europe,'' Los Angeles general manager Dave Taylor said. ``Players
there spend more time practicing and play fewer games, so they have
more of a chance to develop their skills. Over here, our focus is
on winning. When you look at teams with character and players with
the will to win, you see North Americans. But the top skill-level
players are coming from over there. We're producing some, but
they're producing more.'' Taylor said the Kings recently bought
into a team in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   Moose Jaw forward Jamie Lundmark, the draft's top-rated player
who really is from North America, said he thinks that this year is
an aberration. ``I don't think it's anything to worry about,''
Lundmark said. ``We've dominated them for a long time. Maybe it's
their time for a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan said he thinks the influx of such Czech stars as Hasek
and Jagr might have helped the NHL become more of a focus for
youths in his country. ``The Olympic games maybe helped a little,''
he said. ``The Czech team won the gold medal, and people around the
world see that Czech players are not so bad. But I think it's just
a good year for European players.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell probably will take several
Europeans in the draft, including some older players in the later
rounds who never have signed with NHL teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe these things go in cycles, with all the top
players this year being from Europe,'' Waddell said. ``But if you
look around the league, with guys like (Anaheim's Teemu) Selanne
(of Finland) and Jagr, you can see where the highly skilled guys
are coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   And where they are going.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
