<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-THRASHERS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers set to make trades, history
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If the rumpled clothes, the half-eaten room-service
lunch, the player rosters spread over desks and the several mock
drafts taped to walls on the 33rd floor of a Boston hotel suite
don't indicate a certain lack of stability going into the
Thrashers' expansion draft today, maybe this will:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got 17 trades on the table,'' general manager Don Waddell
said.
</P>
<P>
   They might as well be 17 dominoes, because any trades Waddell
cements before the draft will affect his selections. He doubts that
he will top the eight trades announced by Nashville general manager
David Poile after the Predators' expansion draft last year, but
Waddell said, ``We could make four or five for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this frenzied pace of trade talks and meetings with
other GMs has been about what he expected, Waddell said,
``Crazier.''
</P>
<P>
   The only certainty about the Thrashers' 26 picks today, starting
at 3 p.m., is that they will be largely devoid of goal-scorers. The
NHL mandates that Atlanta selects at least three goalies, eight
defensemen and 13 forwards, plus two free picks to use as they
like. Further complicating the selection process is that the
Thrashers can select only six restricted and/or unrestricted free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Finding 13 forwards hasn't been easy, but the allotment of
talented unprotected defensemen ``is a lot stronger than we
expected,'' Waddell said. ``There's not only good defensemen, but
they're young.''
</P>
<P>
   Two examples are Anaheim's Jamie Pushor and Dallas prospect Petr
Buzek. Conversely, the number of competent forwards is so low that
the Thrashers could be persuaded to claim some unprotected players
who are earning high salaries, such as Vancouver's Trent Klatt
($1.1 million) and Tampa Bay's Alexandre Daigle, the well-traveled
former first-round pick of Ottawa's ($900,000 plus incentives).
</P>
<P>
   Waddell had projected that the Thrashers' overall payroll would
be among the lowest in the league next season. But this week he
said, ``If we have to go to the well, the well's pretty deep. ...We
have enough money to buy any player on that list, and then some.
What we don't want to do is mortgage the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential deals have clouded what seemed to be certain Thrashers
selections.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit goalie Norm Maracle remains the team's most likely
backup to Damian Rhodes. But the Red Wings have stirred interest by
leaving center Igor Larionov unprotected. Atlanta doesn't have much
interest in Larionov, but several other teams do, and they might be
willing to offer enough to persuade Waddell to take him. Drafting
and trading Maracle would affect other potential draft-and-trade
deals involving Boston goalie Robbie Tallas, Carolina's Trevor Kidd
and possibly St. Louis's Jamie McLennan.
</P>
<P>
   A similar situation has developed on the Los Angeles pick. The
Thrashers long have focused on left wing Vladimir Tsyplakov. But
the Kings' exposure of tough winger Matt Johnson has caught the
attention of some general managers.
</P>
<P>
   How late will Waddell go with trade talks? ``The league allows
me to go until 3,'' he said. ``But I think I'll give myself a
self-imposed deadline of 12. For one thing, I have to spend some
time (preparing for Saturday's) amateur draft. But there are some
deals I'd really like to do. So if they don't happen by 12, I might
just wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainty, Waddell is comforted by the job he and
his scouts did this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be intimidating if we hadn't done our homework,''
he said. ``But as we went down the (protected) lists, there were
only about 10 guys we missed on. The most important thing is we had
our depth charts in place so we knew the players we were looking
at.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
