<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Special Olympics fanfare beginning
 &HT;    By Knight Chamberlain
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ In what is being billed as the largest peacetime
airlift, 2,000 athletes representing the United States were to
begin arriving today aboard 275 corporate jets at Raleigh-Durham
International Airport for the 10th Special Olympics World Summer
Games, being held in North Carolina beginning Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The business jets, which will be landing or taking off every
three minutes for 12 hours, were donated for the occasion by 260
corporations from 40 states.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 7,000 athletes and 2,000 coaches from 150 countries
and territories have spent the week training and being entertained
in 150 communities across North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, they will begin competing at venues in Raleigh,
Durham and Chapel Hill. The Games will end July 4.
</P>
<P>
   The only hitch so far has been the mysterious disappearance of
two men associated with the Special Olympics delegation from the
Dominican Republic. A cab driver told police that he took two
Spanish-speaking men wearing purple Special Olympics T-shirts from
a Greensboro shopping mall to the Charlotte bus station. He said
they asked how to get to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainer Billy Crystal will host the opening ceremony
Saturday at Carter-Finley Stadium in Raleigh. Guests will include
actor Arnold Schwarzenegger, singer Stevie Wonder, rock band Sugar
Ray, North Carolina evangelist Billy Graham and Detroit Piston
basketball star Grant Hill, vice chairman of the '99 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five thousand volunteers are helping stage the Games, and
various organizations are providing special assistance to mentally
retarded athletes. Through the Special Olympics Healthy Athletes
Initiative, each athlete is being offered vision and dental
screenings.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Flame of Hope will arrive in Raleigh today in a
ceremony at the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning last Monday, 84 law enforcement officers from 26
countries escorted relays of the Special Olympic torch across North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors hope the Games will draw 400,000 spectators to watch
the athletes compete in 19 sports.
</P>
<P>
   The officers will escort the flame to Carter-Finley Stadium on
Saturday to light the cauldron during Opening Ceremonies to
officially start the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, a founding sponsor of the Special Olympics, plans to
distribute 1.6 million cans of Coca-Cola Classic in the
Raleigh-Durham-Chapel Hill area promoting the motto of the '99
Games: ``It's All About Attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
