<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars get exposure in nude calendar
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ So, all that ails track and field in this country
is a lack of exposure.
</P>
<P>
   That's been the party line for decades. Just get the sport some
regular TV coverage. Put some faces on the sport's marquee
performers. Create a buzz that extends beyond the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the latest gimmick is just that _ exposure. A year 2000
calendar featuring nude and nearly nude photos of a dozen of the
sport's leading ladies. Something every young track fan should
have, right?
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the TrackGirls 2000 calendar to go on sale here
Saturday and Sunday at the USA Track and Field Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, people have been really supportive,'' said high jumper
Amy Acuff, project coordinator and one of the calendar girls.
``It's very tasteful nudes. Very artistic and creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the models are sprinter Inger Miller, high jumper and
former Atlanta-area school teacher Tisha Waller and American pole
vault record-holder Stacy Dragila. The only defection from the
original dozen was triple jump champion Sheila Hudson, who Acuff
said ``got cold feet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a sport that gets recognition every four years (at the
Olympics), so to be able to create something like this is very
important in terms of the awareness of the athletes involved in the
sport,'' said high jumper Gwen Wentland, another calendar girl.
``It shows a lot of diversity _ ethnic diversity, event diversity.
We have throwers, sprinters, jumpers.''
</P>
<P>
   The calendar has the whatever-it-takes endorsement of the track
federation, though it has no role in its publication.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15,000 calendars have been printed. They're priced at $16,
and half of the profits are to go to the athletes and the remainder
to a community foundation founded by the late Florence Griffith
Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for liftoff
</P>
<P>
   After hyper-extending her knee almost two weeks ago, Marion
Jones returns to the long jump tonight. The 23-year-old is the
event's overwhelming favorite, though Jones relies largely on her
speed and is working to refine her jumping technique.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing she needs is a serious knee injury, eyeing five
gold medals at next summer's Olympics. Jones acknowledged Thursday
that the incident was scary enough that she can't watch a tape of
the jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the knee is not 100 percent, but it's well enough
that I can come out and win,'' she said. ``I hope I can win on the
first jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the track
</P>
<P>
   Florida freshman sensation John Capel sat out the 100 meters to
concentrate on the 200 this weekend, where the field is led by
world record-holder Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene. Capel, a
wide receiver/kick returner, had this year's world-leading time of
19.87 seconds in winning the NCAA title. ... A trio of Atlanta
residents _ Angelo Taylor, defending Olympic champion Derrick
Adkins and world record-holder Kevin Young _ advanced to the
semifinals tonight in the 400-meter hurdles. ... Other locals
advancing were: Milton Campbell, Derek Mills and Jonas Motiejunas
in the 400; and Derrick Peterson in the 800.
</P>
</TEXT>
