A8702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING-NEXT25-COX     06-24 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-NEXT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring announcement stirs speculation
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises on Thursday set off a storm of
speculation about a possible merger or acquisition, with a terse
announcement that it is holding talks aimed at forging some kind of
``business relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   After that brief statement, the company declined further
comment. But the notion that Atlanta-based MindSpring, the nation's
fourth-largest Internet service provider, might be edging close to
a high-stakes deal _ perhaps even being sold _ boosted company
stock and added to a spate of rumors already rife in Net circles.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation of a big-ticket agreement involving MindSpring
comes at a time of consolidation among Internet companies _ with
rumors of still more to come.
</P>
<P>
   Chatboards on the Net were filled with guesses: MindSpring will
be bought by BellSouth or Prodigy; it will snap up Microsoft's ISP
or merge with California-based Earthlink Networks. Meanwhile,
Earthlink was busy denying that it is about to be purchased by
Gateway Inc. A number of computer-makers are also being mentioned
as possible partners for MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   Pascal Aguirre, a principal in the Renaissance Group consulting
firm, said the rush to partner is inevitable. ``The players need to
gain scale so they can enjoy good revenue growth and reduce their
operating costs per customer. That applies to MindSpring.''
</P>
<P>
   It happens in every industry, just not as fast as it has
happened among ISPs, he said. ``The difference is less in the
nature of the expectation but (more) in the timing. You've had a
grace period. Now it's time to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring has about 1.2 million subscribers to its service. The
company last year had sales of $115 million and a $10.5 million
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Founder and Chairman Charles Brewer has set his sights on
becoming the nation's No. 2 ISP, behind 17 million-strong America
Online. Talk about a pending deal centered on the assumption that
rapid growth for MindSpring _ as well as renewed popularity among
fickle investors _ depends on a dramatic move, an agreement that
extends its marketing reach and delivers thousands of new
customers.
</P>
<P>
   That can happen in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could buy someone, get bought or buy part of a company,
the way they did with Netcom,'' said analyst Jeff Sadler of FAC
Equities. ``There are all sorts of ways to structure a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, MindSpring could buy the Net business from a
company whose specialty is something else, Sadler said. ``That is
probably what they are looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   That would mean a deal with a company whose specialty is
elsewhere _ say, AT&AMP;T or BellSouth, both of which declined comment
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring may be responding in part to the atmosphere on Wall
Street. A swarm of Net companies _ many, like eBay, Amazon.com and
Priceline, that are reporting nothing but large losses _ have
launched public offerings of stock whose value has soared hundreds
of percent.
</P>
<P>
   Prices have defied the old _ pre-Internet _ rules that linked
profitability to stock performance. While this week's dip in the
market has perhaps softened the impact some, many prices have not
returned to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Risk, not reticence, is rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, MindSpring is one of the few Net companies with a
record of profitability. But company stock slipped from a high of
$124.93 1/4 in April to below $60 earlier this month, though it has
of late rebounded with talk about a deal: It closed Thursday at
$82.12 1/2, up $3.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, MindSpring must try to maintain its
trajectory, the zoom from obscurity to national status within three
years. Previously, most of its expansion has come either on its
home turf in the Southeast or through acquisitions, like those of
Netcom's and PSI's consumer subscribers. But industry consolidation
has eliminated most easy purchase targets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, MindSpring's business is becoming more challenging,
even as those changes lure a number of companies toward the ISP
business _ and perhaps a marriage with MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is sluggishly but steadily shifting away from the
telephone dial-up Internet access on which MindSpring's business
was built. Increasingly, users will be routed to the Net via
broadband connections, high-speed wires. Those links are provided
mostly by telephone and cable companies, which will be _ or already
are _ Net providers.
</P>
<P>
   Many free services have popped up, offering Net access in trade
for consumer willingness to endure endless advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   A leveling off in sales of personal computers has spurred
manufacturers to consider providing their own Internet access. Dell
Computer's top executive Michael Dell recently confirmed his
company plans to partner with an ISP.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday came confirmation that AOL is talking to tiny,
Seattle-based Microworkz.com about putting AOL service in that
company's discount PCs. The specter of AOL as a rival for the
nation's computer business adds still more weight to the notion
that another worried computer-maker is seeking a union with
MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
