<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-1STLD-     06-24 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETALIATORY ATTACKS INTENSIFY IN SOUTHERN LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE figures of killed and wounded;
CORRECTS in 5th graf, The conflict ..., that Barak is Israeli prime
minister-elect.)  (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli fighter planes bombarded Lebanon on Thursday
night while Shiite Muslim guerrillas fired rockets into northern
Israel, with the exchanges reportedly leaving two Israelis and six
Lebanese dead and dozens wounded. The action was a severe step-up
in the conflict in southern Lebanon at a moment of political
transition in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   It was a back and forth of retaliatory attacks, which began on
Thursday afternoon when Shiite Muslim guerrillas from the
Hezbollah, or Party of God, showered northern Israel with Katyusha
rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Israel then let loose a furious aerial assault, with nine
airstrikes on power stations, guerrilla strongholds and bridges in
Lebanon, causing a blackout in Beirut, killing six and wounding 45
people, according to The Associated Press in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   And, just after 11 p.m., Party of God guerrillas resumed fire on
northern Israel, where most residents were huddled in shelters. Two
Israeli civilians died. A third was severely wounded, with at least
12 others also reported hurt. The deaths were the first of
civilians in northern Israel related to the Lebanon conflict since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is stepping up at an intensely delicate moment,
days after Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak and Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad, who controls much of Lebanon, made public
declarations of their mutual intentions to reopen peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters, the decision to bomb was made by the
departing prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu. He continues to run
the country one month after his election defeat on May 17 while
Barak assembles a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the bombing began, television reporters asserted
that while Netanyahu had authorized the attack, Barak had been
informed. But the prime minister-elect's office was quick to
respond that he was not involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not a part of the decision-making process in this
matter,'' Barak's office said in a statement broadcast on Channel
One television.
</P>
<P>
   Barak promised during the campaign to end Israel's longstanding
military presence in southern Lebanon. Toward that end, he is eager
to kick-start the negotiations with Syria, and public compliments
he exchanged with Assad this week, through the press, signaled the
beginning of the thaw.
</P>
<P>
   But the sudden intensification of the conflict is a reminder of
just how volatile the border remains, and how difficult it will be
to extricate Israeli troops from what has become a chronic
low-level war zone.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli troops have occupied a 9-mile-deep border zone in
southern Lebanon since 1985 to protect its northern towns from
attack by the Iran-backed Hezbollah. But the steady loss of from 25
to 30 Israeli soldiers a year has made its engagement there very
unpopular here.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening attack on northern Israel on Thursday afternoon,
four Israeli civilians and one soldier were lightly wounded by
Katyusha rockets and mortar bombs, which struck the border town of
Qiryat Shemona and the western Galilee town of Shlomi.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah said it was avenging a recent spate of civilian deaths
in southern Lebanon. According to a Web site of a
Hezbollah-affiliated television station, the initial attack was
provoked on Thursday by what it said had been the death of Saada
Mansour, a 45-year-old woman, in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah said Mrs. Mansour was killed by shrapnel when mortar
rounds struck her house, which was apparently caught in the
crossfire between guerrilla fighters and the Israeli-backed South
Lebanese army troops.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``In reprisal for the targeting of peaceful southern villages,
the Islamic resistance today shelled the Israeli settlements in
occupied northern Palestine with appropriate weapons,'' the
guerrillas' statement on their Web site said. ``In defense of our
civilians, our artillery reinforcement unit (ARU) bombarded with
Katyushas the settlements of Qiryat Shemona and Shlomi at 16:20 and
17:40 this afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli army statement on Thursday said that Israel had
``displayed much restraint'' after recent attacks by Hezbollah, but
that ``today's grave incident'' could not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The strongly worded statement went on to threaten not only the
Hezbollah, ``but those backing them and standing behind them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Speaking on Israeli radio on Thursday evening, Shaul Mofaz, the
army chief of staff, said political leaders had denied two recent
army requests to retaliate in Lebanon. Radio reports said the chief
of staff had shuttled back and forth between the departing and new
prime ministers, neither of whom wanted to make the decision to
take action.
</P>
<P>
   In Beirut on Thursday night, high-rise apartment buildings, many
of which are stocked with generators, gleamed in the darkened city.
At first, the Lebanese capital barely stopped in its busy Thursday
night routines. Cars clogged the streets; loudspeakers called
Muslims to prayer; and the restaurants were hopping as the weekend
began.
</P>
<P>
   By late night, though, the effects of the bombing began to be
felt _ and broadcast on television. Israelis struck a power station
on the outskirts of Beirut, three bridges south of Beirut, what
they called ``terrorist targets'' south of the Litani River, in an
area of Lebanon firmly under Syrian control, and a power substation
in the Bekaa.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, in northern Israel, reports of the two
civilians killed _ and one severely wounded _ began making their
way through the bomb shelters that have become like second home to
the residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
