<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-FEDERALISM-NYT     06-24 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FEDERALISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FEDERALISM AWAITS '00 WITH THE HIGH COURT NARROWLY
DIVIDED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The angry language from the Supreme Court about
this week's federalism cases almost suggested the issue had the
vitality it enjoyed in the first 50 years of the Republic.
</P>
<P>
   It does not. Expect no duels, nor even billboards. But in fact
the reach of power from Washington is a vibrant issue to many
conservatives. They fear the advantages they have recently enjoyed
may be jeopardized by the presidential election next year.
</P>
<P>
   This week's narrowly decided federalism cases involved issues
like whether states had to obey federal wage and hour laws. But the
next Supreme Court battlegrounds are sure to be more explosive,
testing whether and how states can be compelled to follow federal
antidiscrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   With a slim 5-4 majority in place, the federalism decisions
underscored the political reality that the election could tip the
court's balance on the issue. One change on the court could change
policy on federalism, just as a different outcome in a court
appointment (the rejected Robert H. Bork instead of the approved
Anthony M. Kennedy) could have led to a reversal of Roe vs. Wade
and severe curbs on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The federalism issue may fly below the radar of next year's
presidential election. It has little of the voting or fund-raising
potential of abortion, an issue that probably helped Bill Clinton
when he promised to nominate justices who would uphold Roe vs. Wade
in 1992, or of crime, which Richard M. Nixon used effectively in
1968 when he promised to appoint tough judges.
</P>
<P>
   But the election will almost certainly have a more profound
effect on the issue than the issue will have on the election.
</P>
<P>
   The court's two oldest members, Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist, 74, and Justice John Paul Stevens, 79, are on opposite
sides of the question. A Rehnquist retirement would give a
Democratic president the opportunity to turn the court around. But
a Stevens departure would give a Republican president a chance to
solidify the majority.
</P>
<P>
   That is because even if no attorney general poses federalism as
a litmus test, and even if nobody bothers to ask about it in a
confirmation hearing (it was all but absent in the most recent
exhaustive hearings, those on Bork and Clarence Thomas), Democratic
and Republican judges see the question differently. Democrats side
with the federal government, Republicans with the states.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the justices appointed in the 1980s or 1990s only David
H. Souter, a New Hampshire Republican whose career has only
confirmed the worries of conservatives who were reluctant to
support him, deviated from that rule this week. The other
Republican appointee to dissent, Stevens, came from President
Gerald Ford's time, when Republican justices were not chosen
primarily to satisfy the right.
</P>
<P>
   By Supreme Court standards, the opinions were unusually blunt.
When Justice Stephen G. Breyer, dissenting, said the majority
opinion owed more ``to the thought of James I than of James
Madison,'' he was comparing five of his colleagues to a British
monarch with more concern for his prerogatives than skill in
getting along with Parliament, which he rarely summoned.
</P>
<P>
   Souter did not reach back to the 17th century, but to the time
of the founders. He compared the majority view to the now
discredited idea of industrial life as free and even democratic, a
concept he said was false to begin with and ``grew insistently
fictional over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority, Souter argued, ``has chosen to close the century
by conferring like status on a conception or state sovereign
immunity that is true neither to history nor to the structure of
the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the majority opinions had no need for similar
denunciations (after all, they had five votes), but Justice Antonin
Scalia dismissed the Breyer dissenting opinion:
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice Breyer reiterates (but only in outline form,
thankfully) the now-fashionable revisionist accounts of the 11th
Amendment set forth in other opinions in a degree of repetitive
detail that has despoiled our northern woods.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are comparable passions on the anti-federalist side
outside the court. Michael Greve of the Center for Individual
Rights, fears that ``one more Democratic replacement would wipe out
all the advances the Supreme Court has made'' on federalism issues.
For Democrats, Greve said, resisting any challenge to federal
authority ``is so deeply rooted, it's instinctive.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other conservatives fear that the dissenters are just
itching for a chance to reverse the decisions, as Rehnquist
admitted he was ready to do on the other side of the issue in 1985,
in a case whose ruling was reversed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Souter validated their concern in his dissent to the ruling that
employees of the State of Maine cannot sue to get time and a half
for overtime. He predicted that the majority's ``unrealistic'' and
``indefensible'' concept of state immunity would prove
``fleeting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
