u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-FBI-HNS     06-24 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-FBI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI COMMAND CENTER WEEDING THROUGH THOUSANDS OF SIGHTINGS OF
SUSPECTED KILLER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JANETTE RODRIGUES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few days ago, the command center that the FBI set up in
Houston to find suspected serial killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez had
all the excitement of a telephone answering service.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 people sat at their desks, phones glued to their
ears, asking questions and taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   It was quiet, except for the hum of fax machines, printers and
desktop computers. Occasionally, an investigator called out
information to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are slow days and busy days,'' Houston FBI spokesman
Rolando Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was a busy day. After a noon news conference, the
command center, a clearinghouse for the multiagency task force
working on ``Operation Train Stop,'' began to look like a telethon.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the team had fielded 1,100 tips. Within a couple
hours, that number shot up to 1,800.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours a day, seven days a week, men and women sit in
the converted conference room and methodically sift through the
often mundane minutia of an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   They are looking for leads, associates and family members as
they try to figure out how to catch Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Color and black-and-white mug shots of him are everywhere, on
the walls, on the tables, in the fax machine being sent to
law-enforcement agencies that can't download them from the FBI's
Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of his fingerprints are spread across a table near a wall
covered with maps of train routes and rail yards in Greater
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteboards list information that includes more than a dozen
agencies involved in the case and the suspect's 30-plus aliases.
Televisions hang from the ceiling like in a sports bar, except
they're tuned to CNN's Headline News instead of ESPN. There's a map
of the U.S.-Mexico border and another of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, two investigators confer about reinterviewing some
Resendez-Ramirez family members. Another investigator talks on the
phone to a caller with a possible sighting in Oklahoma City.
Another investigator shows a co-worker how to access information on
a laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the phones continue to ring.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Loader, FBI assistant special agent in charge, said one of
those calls might lead to the man suspected of killing at least
eight people since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well over 90 percent of the tips are possible sightings of him
in a store, a car or a train,'' Loader said. ``Hopefully, we are
getting some solid sightings. We would like to catch him before
another murder event.''
</P>
<P>
   Each tip is handled by the task-force members sitting in the
``switchboard area.'' A high-tech tape recorder registers sound
levels; lights blink on multiline phones.
</P>
<P>
   The people on the phones try to determine whether the tip has
any merit. If it does, it's passed on to a special agent or a
detective, who interviews the caller in depth.
</P>
<P>
   When a tip becomes a lead, it's sent electronically, via the FBI
Rapid Start system, to field officials in that area, and
investigators are sent out to interview callers and show them mug
shots of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, most tips are called in after a story has appeared
on local or national news broadcasts. While Loader said that all
the possible sightings are helpful, many turn out to be
look-alikes.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes bad tips can be weeded out easily, as when callers in
different cities believe they saw the suspect on the same day and
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them can't be true,'' Loader said. ``But 250 million
eyes are better than one or two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
