<SLUG> BC-DEPORT-ASYLUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 IRAQIS FREED FROM U.S. DETENTION CENTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ After being held for two years in a detention
center in Los Angeles, five Iraqis were freed Thursday and were
reunited with their families here, where they will be allowed to
find jobs and stay until another country agrees to give them
permanent political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The five were among 7,000 Iraqi dissidents brought to the United
States after the unsuccessful effort to overthrow President Saddam
Hussein after the Persian Gulf War, but fell under suspicion of
being double agents working for Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998 an immigration judge found that the men were a
national security risk and signed an order for their deportation to
Iraq, after a hearing in which the information against them was
classified.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, a former director of the Central Intelligence
Agency, James Woolsey, became involved in their fight to avoid
deportation, which he said could have meant their ``being sent to
their deaths based on classified information.''
</P>
<P>
   Their freedom came as a result of an agreement reached on June
11 with the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   A leader of the Iraqi National Congress, Dr. Ahmad Chalabi, said
he new three of the men and could vouch for their integrity,
calling them ``fighters for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the immigration service in Washington, Russ
Bergeron, said the agency had acted properly. ``There was a broad
range of evidence collected that indicated that these men were a
threat to national security,'' Bergeron said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the five, Adil Hadi Awadh, said because of the aid of
Woolsey and others, he felt no bitterness. ``We're grateful for the
support from the American people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NET-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      06-24 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: DEALS REAL, DEALS IMAGINED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the Internet almost anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the bad news, for both companies and investors, who
must confront a menagerie of potential products and deals to find a
few that someday just might pay off.
</P>
<P>
   The painful confusion can be seen in several of the rumored
deals in the market this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Dan Dorfman, writing on the Jagnotes.com Web site,
said that Compaq Computer Corp. was interested in trading its Alta
Vista Internet service for stock in CMGI, an Internet investment
concern. The companies confirmed those talks Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, someone using the name of Andy Nguyen posted a rumor
on a Yahoo message board that Gateway Inc., the computer maker,
would offer to buy Earthlink, a big Internet service provider, for
$75 a share. The companies decline to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Through subsequent and circuitous events, the Earthlink rumors
forced Mindspring, another Internet service provider, to publish a
cryptic statement that it was in talks about possible ``business
combinations.'' It declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   What all these possible deals have in common is that neither the
personal computer companies nor the Internet firms are really
comfortable in their own businesses, and they are wondering if the
grass is greener on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Selling computers these days has all the security of cliff
diving, as prices are falling as fast as an Acapulco diver.
Compaq's inability to keep from very painful belly flops, quarter
after quarter, was largely the reason that the board dismissed its
chief executive, Eckhard Pfeiffer, two months ago. Seeking profits,
both Compaq and Gateway, which is doing somewhat better as it uses
the increasingly popular direct sales approach, have decided to try
to funnel their customers to Internet services they control. That
way they can earn monthly fees or at least advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway, in fact, has been able to attract 400,000 customers to
its Gateway.net Internet service, although by offering one full
year free, it's hardly a big money maker yet. Compaq's Internet
activities revolved around Alta Vista, a popular search service
that it acquired with Digital Equipment Corp. last year. Compaq at
first ignored Alta Vista. But earlier this year it decided to plump
it up in preparation to sell a piece to the public. And it began
its own Internet service that directs users to Alta Vista.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet companies, meanwhile, have been struggling with
their own businesses. None of the Internet service providers has
found a way to break out of the pack to compete with America
Online, which continues to snare half the new online users.
Providing Internet access is largely a commodity telecommunication
service, much like long distance. As for the Internet portal
businesses, the biggest, like Yahoo, may well attract a big enough
audience to profit from advertising, but it's still unclear how
Alta Vista will survive.
</P>
<P>
   But it is certainly far from clear that computer makers and
Internet companies should jump into each other's arms. Potential
buyers for Internet service providers include telecommunications
companies that want to offer all-in-one packages, or a host of
other technology businesses. Microsoft, for example, has been
sniffing around looking to buy Internet service providers, a sharp
reversal from its stance a year ago, when it was considering
selling its MSN Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Internet portals, like Alta Vista, because they can attract
large amounts of traffic, could well be attractive for companies
including media companies and online retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, according to people close to its executives' plans,
appears to be intrigued by owning a smaller piece of a larger
Internet effort. CMGI is a combination of a venture capital
investment fund and an incubator that has started a number of
successful Internet companies, including Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   A potential purchase of Alta Vista by CMGI has the financial
advantage of being an exchange of one Internet stock for another.
CMGI's stock, which closed at $96.50 Thursday, is trading at nearly
two and a half times the value of its underlying holdings,
according to Keith Benjamin, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson
Stephens. That premium reflects the buoyant Internet market and
investor confidence in the company's management team. The value
also allows it to pay a reported $2 billion to $3 billion for Alta
Vista, which no traditional media company could afford.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the same sort of analysis shows that a
Gateway-Earthlink deal would be difficult, as Gateway suffers from
a real world valuation of 27 times earnings. Earthlink, like most
Internet companies, loses money. Walter Winnitzki, an analyst with
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, figures that buying Earthlink would cause
substantial dilution to Gateway's earnings, something its
management is loath to do.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway and Earthlink declined to comment on whether they have
had any talks. But Garry Betty, Earthlink's chief executive, said
in a telephone interview that the company did not want its main
method of finding new customers to be through buyers of computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that is all you had to rely on, it would be very risky,''
he said. Nor, Betty added, is the company focused on acquisitions.
The intention, he said, is to grow through aggressive marketing for
new subscribers, largely those who want to graduate from America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yahoo posting about an Earthlink Gateway deal may have
been nothing more than someone trying to hype a stock, it did have
the unintended effect of prodding the cryptic admission of deal
making by Mindspring. In response to the reports about Earthlink,
one Mindspring executive told a reporter that the company was not
in any merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't exactly true,'' Charles Brewer, the company's
chief executive, said Thursday. ``And the misinformation needed to
be corrected.'' Brewer did say, without elaborating, that Internet
service providers have the potential to become more profitable as
they grow larger. Analysts say that Mindspring could well be trying
to buy another Internet service provider, like Prodigy
Communications. Or it could be considering bids from a
telecommunications company, Microsoft or perhaps even a computer
maker.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet anything is possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
