<HEADLINE>
A SECOND GUN CHARGE FILED IN LITTLETON CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A man already charged with selling the handgun used in
the killings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., was
charged on Wednesday with another firearms violation, possession of
a shotgun with a sawed-off barrel and stock.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor said Thursday that on March 6, friends videotaped
the man, Mark Manes, 22, shooting the shotgun in the foothills
south of Littleton with two Columbine seniors, Dylan Klebold and
Eric Harris. Six weeks later, the two students used the shotgun in
the school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   It is illegal to use a shotgun with a barrel shorter than 18
inches. Last month, Manes was charged with providing Klebold and
Harris with the semiautomatic handgun used in the shootings, a
Tec-DC9. Providing a handgun to a minor and the possession charge
are felonies. If convicted on both counts, he could be sentenced to
nine years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
