<HEADER>
A8727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-FLAG-ART-NYT     06-24 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-FLAG-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RECURRING DEBATE, HOUSE VOTES TO BAN FLAG-BURNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Eds: This story was eliminated earlier and has now been
restored)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Continuing the culture war that dominated the
debate on gun control and youth violence last week, the House of
Representatives this week fought its perennial battle over
flag-burning.
</P>
<P>
   In five hours of speeches over two days, one lawmaker after
another sharply criticized flag-burners, and the Supreme Court that
gave them license. Then, just as it did in 1995 and again in 1997,
the House voted Thursday to approve a constitutional amendment that
would overturn the Supreme Court's 5-4 ruling in 1989 that laws
prohibiting desecration of the American flag are unconstitutional
infringements on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The supporters of the amendment, mostly Republicans, clearly
relished the discomfort that the opponents, mostly Democrats, felt
in voting against a measure that polls show 80 percent of Americans
favor.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, 305-124, was well in excess of the two-thirds majority
needed to approve a constitutional amendment. But as everyone in
the House knew, the debate was for political exercise and the vote
was for naught.
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional amendment also requires a two-thirds vote of
the Senate. All 100 senators have declared their position, and only
65 are in favor of the amendment, two shy of two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   No end is in sight to debates and votes in the House on matters
grounded in conservative principles. A week ago, the House voted to
enourage the display of the Ten Commandments in public schools.
Next week, the House will consider legislation that would make it a
federal crime to take a minor across state lines for an abortion
without notifying her parents. There may also be a vote later in
the year on a constitutional amendment that would permit organized
prayer in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the gun-control debate, when the House floor was
often crowded, few people were present for the debate on
flag-burning, and the arguments were the familiar ones given year
after year.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed amendment states: ``The Congress shall have power
to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the supporters were emotional. ``I ask members to give
themselves a vision, Iwo Jima, and the men that put up that
American flag,'' declared Rep. Randy ``Duke'' Cunningham, R-Calif.,
one of the chief sponsors of the amendment. ``Now allow some hippie
to go up there and burn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were more legalistic. Rep. Charles T. Canady, R-Fla.,
argued that the Supreme Court had ruled that obscene and physically
threatening speech was not protected by the First Amendment and
that flag-burning could also be outlawed without damaging the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argued that flag-burning was not a problem _ only 72
cases have been reported in this decade, said Rep. John Conyers,
D-Mich. _ and that the First Amendment should not be tampered with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I abhor flag-burners,'' said Rep. Melvin L. Watt, D-N.C.,
adding: ``I am here to defend the First Amendment. I am here to
defend the freedom of expression. I am here to defend the right of
people who have views that are contrary to mine to express those
views.''
</P>
<P>
   On the final vote, 210 Republicans and 95 Democrats voted to
amend the Constitution. Voting ``no'' were 10 Republicans, 113
Democrats and one Independent.
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional amendment must be approved by three-quarters of
the state legislatures, but 49 states _ all but Vermont _ have
passed measures expressing support for a flag amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Senate voted on the amendment was in 1995. The
vote in favor was 63-36, or three votes short of two-thirds. (There
was a vacancy.) Last year, a count showed that the amendment was
three votes shy, and no vote was taken.
</P>
<P>
   In November, three senators who favor the amendment were elected
to replace senators who had voted against it. But two opponents,
Charles Schumer of New York and John Edwards of North Carolina,
both Democrats, defeated senators who had voted for it. So the
proponents needed two more votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
