<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS25-COX     06-24 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oft-maligned Spurs just a step from the summit
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For so long, they have been targets for ridicule,
absorbing enough verbal jabs from fans, media and opponents to
leave scars far beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson and Sean Elliott are too soft. Avery Johnson is
marginally talented. The San Antonio Spurs will never transcend
those flaws to win an NBA championship, even with superstar Tim
Duncan in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Then a strange thing happened. The Spurs kept winning games this
season, advancing farther than ever before. Now they lead New York
3-1 in the best-of-seven NBA Finals, and they can secure the
franchise's first championship with a victory tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' said Robinson, a 10-year veteran who has
earned everything _ scoring title, MVP, defensive player of the
year _ except a championship. ``I try not to think about it too
much because we still have a lot of work to do. But each game, I
was thinking, `We're four games away, we're three games away, we're
two games away, we're one game away.' You get a little bit more
excited and more excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about wiping out the past, individually and collectively. A
victory tonight, Sunday or Tuesday will validate the careers of
several Spurs players as well as the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said Mario Elie, a former journeyman who won two
championships with the Houston Rockets. ``I told Dave yesterday,
`You can shut a lot of people up Friday night.'''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone has the right to aim counterpunches at their critics,
it is the Spurs. But don't expect much of that from them _ it's not
in their nature. R.C. Buford, the Spurs' director of scouting, said
he does not foresee gloating by players or from Gregg Popovich, the
no-nonsense, often gruff coach whom many fans and some reporters
have never liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not how we built this team,'' Buford said. ``And it's
mostly through his Popovich's direction.''
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, fans and reporters seem to have fallen
for the Spurs, particularly Robinson and Johnson, citing them as
the antithesis of everything Americans find distasteful about rich,
spoiled, egotistical athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Fans watching the NBC telecast of game four on Wednesday heard
announcer Bob Costas say that he witnessed Robinson receiving an
ovation from Knicks fans in a New York restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich said Robinson never talks about what a championship
would mean to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we all know,'' Popovich said, ``if we are fortunate enough
to get this done, it would provide me with the greatest
satisfaction personally to see Sean and Avery and David in a room
celebrating. To be around when they finally do it will be an
amazing experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his own vindication as a coach who might have been
fired if the Spurs had struggled beyond their 6-8 start, Popovich
said, ``I'm not trying to be humble. Everyone likes credit to some
degree, but they took me to the NBA Finals. I didn't take them.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie said he joined a ``special group'' of players this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys that get along,'' Elie said. ``We care about each other,
cheer each other on, share the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that can be attributed to a lack of pedigree. Most of
the Spurs emerged from relatively modest basketball backgrounds,
even Duncan and Robinson. Elliott is the only former McDonald's
All-American in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Elie played in smaller leagues around the world before gaining
entrance to the NBA at age 27. Johnson has been with five teams in
11 seasons. The Spurs let him go twice. Jaren Jackson bounced
around the NBA and minor leagues more than a game ball. When he
joined the Spurs last season, it was his eighth NBA team in as many
years.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has played only for the Spurs, but no one has been
slammed harder. Criticism is an occupational hazard for great
athletes who fail to win championships. Even Michael Jordan and
John Elway were targets during the years before they won. Robinson
has the added burden of his demeanor, said the Spurs' Will Perdue,
a former teammate of Jordan's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone questioned David's heart and desire because he's not
an emotional guy,'' Perdue said. ``I think that was wrong. When we
were in Chicago, Michael took some hits because people said he was
too much of an individual player. No one questioned his heart and
desire, but they said he'd never win a championship because he
wouldn't play team basketball. So it seems that no matter who you
are, they find something wrong with you.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Bulls lost, Jordan sometimes blamed his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``David never blamed anyone,'' Perdue said. ``Whether his
teammates were inadequate, or they weren't good enough to help him
win a championship, he never pointed a finger at anybody. He
pointed it at himself. That just increased the criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Robinson and the Spurs have a chance to celebrate their
first championship, although they expect another difficult game
with New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to see them popping champagne bottles on our
court,'' the Knicks' Kurt Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Nice guys that the Spurs are, they would probably clean up after
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
