<HEADER>
A8732 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMIT-SUMMITT_SFCHRO     06-24 1607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT-SUMMITT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 East Bay Hospital Merger Nearing Federal Approval  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal antitrust regulators are leaning toward approval of a
hotly contested hospital merger in the East Bay, leaving it up to
state officials to decide whether to oppose the deal on the grounds
that it could diminish competition and raise hospital prices.
</P>
<P>
   Informed sources told The Chronicle that, after a three-month
investigation, the Federal Trade Commission seems poised to allow
Oakland's Summit Medical Center to merge with Berkeley's Alta Bates
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Summit is the East Bay's largest hospital. Alta Bates, which is
part of the Sacramento-based Sutter Health chain, is the
second-largest hospital in Alameda and Contra Costa counties.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would make Sutter the East Bay's most powerful
hospital chain. A Chronicle computer analysis shows that it would
control 28 percent of hospital patients in the two-county area, and
44 percent of patients in the triangle of East Bay cities from
Hercules to San Leandro to Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   If the FTC does approve the merger, it will put heat on state
Attorney General Bill Lockyer to block the deal under state law.
Lockyer is under pressure from East Bay elected officials, who fear
a Sutter stranglehold on hospital care if Sutter swallows Summit
and Kaiser follows through on its announced plan to close its
Oakland hospital and divert thousands of patients to Summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be concerned when you have an organization such as
Sutter controlling 50 percent of patient days in Alameda County, 60
percent in Oakland and 70 percent in Berkeley,'' said Supervisor
Keith Carson, whose district includes the heart of the Summit-Alta
Bates territory.
</P>
<P>
   An FTC spokeswoman said the agency never comments on
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   But a source at Sutter Health said an announcement of the FTC
decision could come as early as today or sometime during the &LR;   &LR; next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter Executive Vice President Pat Fry and Summit Chief
Executive Irwin Hansen have been in Washington, D.C., this week,
trying to persuade FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky and his three
fellow commissioners to approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really feel bringing together Summit and Alta Bates in the
Sutter Health system is the best decision for this community,''
said Summit spokeswoman Nancy Happel.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is still quite fluid and there remains a chance
the FTC could still raise some objection to the deal. ``After all
the effort they've put into this, it's not easy for regulators to
walk away,'' said Glenn Melnick, a health care finance professor at
the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust attorneys have been watching the Summit-Alta Bates
investigation for clues as to how the federal regulators feds &LR; 
 &LR; will assess future hospital mergers _ at a time when industry
critics say such consolidations will lead to spark  &LR; higher medical
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision will have national echoes,'' said Karen
Silverman Johnson, an antitrust attorney in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the federal government the feds have  &LR; has had
little luck stopping hospital mergers in the past. Although the
U.S. hospital industry has averaged 200 mergers a year for several
years running, government attorneys have taken only 11 deals to
federal court since 1984 _ and lost six of them.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government racked up this dismal record even
though its past challenges mainly involved mergers in rural areas _
where hospitals are few and far between, Johnson said. To challenge
a deal in the East Bay, where 22 hospitals dot the Alameda and
Contra Costa landscape, would force the government feds  &LR; _ which
hasn't who haven't  &LR; won many in the countryside _ to fight in a one
of the country's largest metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the key variable affecting antitrust decisions is
how government attorneys define the size of East Bay hospital
market. If they decide the market is the ``inner'' East Bay, the
merger would raise greater fears of a monopoly than if all of
Alameda and Contra Costa counties were considered a single hospital
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   A Chronicle computer analysis illustrates the tough calls
federal and state officials have had to make in determining whether
a Summit-Alta Bates merger would give Sutter the market power to
stifle competition, raise hospital prices or decrease services.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis reviewed a state database of all 210,499 patients
who were treated in the 22 acute care hospitals in Alameda and
Contra Costa counties in 1997, the most recent year for which data
are available.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle's computations &UR;  &LR; grouped the 22 hospitals into four
chains, plus a fifth category made up of hospitals that are either
independent or have no other affiliates in the target area. An
assumption was made that the merger had gone through and that
Summit and Alta Bates were part of Sutter.
</P>
<P>
   But calculating patient totals for each chain isn't enough.
Antitrust regulators must decide the boundaries of the competitive
market. If, for instance, they decide to include all 22 hospitals
in the two-county area, Sutter would control 28 percent of hospital
patients, probably not enough to warrant a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But if regulators define the market as the string of cities from
Hercules to San Leandro, and east to the Lamorinda hills, Sutter's
market share would be 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Should regulators adopt this smaller market and add Kaiser's
13,042 Oakland patients to Summit's total, Chronicle research shows
Sutter's share would grow to 58 percent _ a more worrisome total
from antitrust regulator's view.
</P>
<P>
   The most dogged critic of the Summit-Alta Bates merger has been
the Oakland-based Service Employees International Union Local 250,
which represents 1,065 workers at the two hospitals. SEIU has waged
a labor war against Sutter throughout Northern California and fears
job cuts in the event of a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of threatening strikes, SEIU has attacked Sutter's
merger plan with spreadsheets. SEIU President Sal Rosselli and
research director John Marshall have spent the past few months
immersed in the arcane formulas government antitrust lawyers use to
determine market boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The SEIU analysis, which shows a slightly smaller market than
the Chronicle analysis, eliminates two non-Sutter hospitals in San
Leandro, thus increasing Sutter's market share to more than
two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Oakland it's a particular threat because of the monopoly
they'll have created'' if Kaiser sends its patients to Summit,
Rosselli said. ``People won't have the ability to go to Sutter's
competitors because there aren't any.''
</P>
<P>
   But merger supporters ridicule such an analysis. Wanda Jones, an
industry analyst with New Century Health Care in San Francisco,
said the Bay Area is becoming one big hospital market, as East Bay
patients routinely travel to San Francisco or the Peninsula to see
specialists at UCSF Stanford Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is very fluid and can't be demarcated by some
artificial government boundary,'' Jones said. ``People moan and
groan about mergers, but they don't step back to see the larger
picture. There are still too many hospitals with too many empty
beds, and more than enough competition to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutter spokesman Bill Gleeson said that no matter how the
government calculates market share, ``numbers don't tell the whole
story.'' He said government attorneys will also look at the
financial state of Summit and Alta Bates. The two hospitals get 70
percent of their patients from Medicare and Medi-Cal. Their overall
revenues declined last year, partly because of in part &LR;  due to
 &LR; federally imposed budget cuts. Both lost money in 1998 and project
even larger losses in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Merging Summit and Alta Bates, and eliminating administrative
overlap, is the best way to ensure the survival of both hospitals,
Gleeson said. Sutter will also argue that the government has
allowed two other recent mergers _ the UCSF Stanford Health Care
complex and the John Muir-Mount Diablo combine in eastern Contra
Costa County.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCSF Stanford is pulling patients away from us, so is
Muir-Diablo,'' Gleeson said, adding that competition is
particularly fierce for lucrative operations, like heart surgery.
``Right now, Summit and Alta Bates are at a huge disadvantage
because their competitors were allowed to merge.''
</P>
<P>
   If the FTC has accepted Sutter's arguments in favor of the
merger, it doesn't mean the deal has the final green light. State
antitrust officials must also approve the merger, and California
has shown some willingness to amend the terms of mergers federal
regulators the feds  &LR; have approved.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Columbia/HCA sought to acquire the Alexian
Brothers Hospital in San Jose, the state stopped the deal, after
the federal government feds  &LR; gave their  &LR; its blessing, until
Columbia promised to invest millions in hospital upgrades and local
charity care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other reason people are watching this is to see what the
state does,'' said Johnson. ``Alexian was the state's first effort
to take a more active and public role in hospital mergers,'' and if
it tries to stop or alter the Summit-Alta Bates deal, it would
signal California's intent to subject mergers to greater scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Lockyer's office declined to comment. But one
antitrust expert said it would be tough for the state to go into
court alone in an attempt to block a merger that has won federal
approval.
</P>
