<HEADER>
A8733 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      06-24 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES SAYS BUSH BROKE `NO TAX INCREASE' PROMISE TO TEXANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes
challenged George W. Bush's anti-tax credentials Thursday, accusing
the Texas governor of proposing 75 tax increases during the 1997
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The tax increases that Forbes cited were part of a proposed $4
billion tax swap, which Bush supported, that also would have
sharply cut school property taxes in Texas. Forbes did not point
out the trade-off.
</P>
<P>
   Bush lobbied Republican legislators for the controversial plan,
drafted by a House committee, that expanded sales and business
taxes to dozens of new items. It was approved by the full House but
died in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning across the country in the last few weeks, Bush has
touted the nearly $2.9 billion in tax cuts approved by Texas
lawmakers while he has been governor. They include $1 billion in
school-tax relief, eventually approved in 1997, and $1.85 billion
in tax cuts enacted this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says they amount to the largest tax cuts in Texas history.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has promised that, if elected president, he would veto
any increase in federal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes, a magazine publisher badly trailing front-runner
Bush in the polls for the 2000 Republican presidential nomination,
said the Texas governor broke an anti-tax promise he made during
his first gubernatorial campaign in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for people to know that in his 1994 campaign,
Mr. Bush took a pledge not to raise taxes. Then, in 1997, Gov. Bush
broke his pledge by proposing 75 tax increases,'' Forbes said in a
written statement issued in Indianapolis by his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 campaign, Bush signed a pledge offered by a group
called Taxpayers for Accountability promising to oppose the
creation of a personal income tax or an increase in the sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, after speaking to Hispanic community leaders in the
Mexican Town section of Detroit, dismissed Forbes' criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just trying to get in the news,'' Bush said. ``I've
signed the two largest tax cuts in the state's history, and, as you
know, I proposed a plan that would have reduced taxes by $6 billion
at a cost of $5 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   About 200 Hispanic community leaders filled a small park to hear
Bush speak Wednesday. They turned out, they said, at the request of
Michigan Gov. John Engler, who has targeted the Mexican Town area
for economic redevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   Engler's wife, Michelle, a native of San Antonio, introduced
Bush to the crowd in Spanish, and Bush opened his speech in
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the crowd that he wants to make sure everyone in
America has access to a good education and economic opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush later said he plans to court traditionally Democratic
Hispanic voters as a basic part of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won between 40 percent and 49 percent of the Hispanic vote
in Texas in his 1998 re-election campaign, a record for a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message has got to be the American dream is meant for
(Hispanics) as well,'' Bush said. ``My first stop in Michigan, an
important battleground state, is right here.''
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Varela, a local plant manager, said, ``I know he has
helped the Hispanic people who live in Texas. I don't see why he
won't help the Hispanic people in the rest of the United States,''
said Varela, who added that he usually votes Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 session, Bush made property-tax relief and a more
equitable tax system his key goals. He proposed a plan that would
have cut school property taxes by $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the cuts would have come through $1 billion in state
budgetary savings. But the governor also proposed a one-half cent
per dollar increase in the state sales tax and a new
business-activity tax to raise enough money to help make the school
tax cuts possible.
</P>
<P>
   His business-activity tax would have replaced the
corporate-franchise tax and would have applied to all forms of
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Bush argued that his proposal would have created a fairer state
tax system, but it was too controversial for the Legislature. So a
House committee drafted a substitute, which the governor supported.
</P>
<P>
   The House plan would have used $1 billion in budgetary savings,
plus state-tax increases of about $4 billion, to cut school
property taxes on Texans' homes by about $5 billion. Many
homeowners would have seen their school taxes cut almost in half.
</P>
<P>
   The House rejected the governor's proposals for a new
business-activity tax and an increase in the sales-tax rate.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the school-tax relief for homeowners, the House
plan would have expanded the corporate-franchise tax to
partnerships, would have added numerous untaxed items and services
to the sales tax, and would have imposed or increased a number of
other business-related taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the ``75 tax increases'' that Forbes accused Bush of
proposing. Legislative researchers could not immediately confirm
that all the individual taxes listed by Forbes were actually in the
House bill. At least one was not. But most were _ items as varied
as expansion of the corporate-franchise tax to partnerships, higher
cigarette and alcohol taxes, higher taxes on aviation fuel, and new
taxes on massages and solar-energy businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature then simply increased the homestead exemption
for school-property taxes by $10,000, which saved the average Texas
homeowner about $140 a year on school taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, that amounted to $1 billion for the 1998-99 budget
period, the amount that Bush now claims as property-tax relief from
the 1997 legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
