<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8734 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XGAMES-XGAMES_SFCHRON     06-24 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XGAMES-XGAMES </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 `Extreme' Athletes to Show S.F. Their Stuff  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
America's suits will rub shoulders with America's youth at the X
Games this weekend _ and the suits are shelling out millions of
dollars for the opportunity.
<P>
   The fifth annual summer X Games, which showcase unconventional
sports such as skysurfing, aggressive in-line skating and street
luge, begin today on San Francisco's Piers 30 and 32.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen sponsors, including AT&AMP;T and Mountain Dew, paid the
event's creator, cable sports network ESPN, $22 million for the
right to hang stadium signs, operate booths at the event, and show
commercials during television broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   The package, for which six ``gold'' sponsors paid $2 million
each and 10 associate sponsors forked over $1 million, includes
related events such as the winter X Games and add-ons like links on
the ESPN Web site. Marketers pay extra to actually produce the ads
and freebies.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will award close to $1 million to winning athletes during
the nine-day event, which ends July 3. But the real prize is an
estimated $100 billion spent by U.S. teens each year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Blue chip marketers invest in the X Games because they attract
an unusually concentrated youth audience and provide a coolness
factor that sponsors hope will rub off on their brands.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of game attendees, who totaled 233,000 at last year's
San Diego event, are 21 or younger, according to Performance
Research of Newport, R.I. Seventy percent of the crowd is male.
</P>
<P>
   The home audience for the event is also youth- and male-heavy.
For every 100 households watching the games in prime time, there
are 50 males ages 12 to 34, according to ESPN. That compares to 38
young males watching NFL football.
</P>
<P>
   Even though X Games viewership is small _ fewer than 1 percent
of cable-watching  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; c,14p10 lwrap  &LR;  households tune in _ the event is important to
marketers because young people are hard to reach. Despite their
slacker reputations, teenagers actually watch less television than
older people and children, according to Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, youth marketing is laden with potential pitfalls.
Companies that wind up looking corporate instead of cool can easily
tarnish their brands among notoriously cynical young people.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers need to be actively involved in the event, rather than
simply hanging signs and running ads, ``so kids don't smell a rat
and say, `Oh, they're just trying to sell me something,''' advised
Sarah Haynes, chief executive of Onboard Entertainment in
Sausalito.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes warned marketers to avoid ``any campaign with a loud,
obnoxious, wacky vibe, which is kind of old.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the term ``extreme'' sports, ``which sounds crazy or
dangerous or stupid,'' is being replaced with the term ``action''
sports, she said. ``These athletes take these sports very
seriously. They look at them as core sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Brands such as Mountain Dew that have successfully aligned
themselves with youth and sports over the years seem to have a
natural advantage at the X Games.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 Performance Research survey, for example, 92 percent
of game attendees remembered that Mountain Dew was a sponsor and 80
percent named Nike, but only 62 percent mentioned AT&AMP;T and 55
percent recalled Chevy Trucks.
</P>
<P>
   (Nike dropped its sponsorship two years ago and Adidas is now
the sole footwear sponsor.)
</P>
<P>
   X Games sponsors have developed a variety of strategies to
appeal to youth without looking like exploitive capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  Visa, which is based in Foster City, is hawking credit
cards with X Games images on the front and giving away water
bottles to all college-age youths who apply for the card. Visa will
also promote its Rankit.com Web site, which provides financial
advice to young people, through a sweepstakes offering scooters as
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of XGAMES25 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``We're making a connection between the X Games and Rankit, and
that translates to brand loyalty,'' said Visa spokesman Lorne
Fisher. By being an X Games sponsor, ``You tie it in with this
cool, hip event, which is growing in popularity, and you get a
captive audience.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is using the X Games to promote its collect-call number,
800-CALL-ATT, which is used largely by young people. Market
research shows that AT&AMP;T's previous X Games sponsorships increased
awareness of the number _ and collect callers ``use the last number
they see,'' said Howard McNally, president of transaction services
for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  The primary benefit for AT&AMP;T, though, ``is to get our
brand in with the teenage crowd that will be (paying the phone
bills) when they grow up,'' said McNally.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T was forced to rethink its traditionally conservative
approach to advertising when it became an X Games sponsor three
years ago, McNally said. It now uses spokespeople like actor David
Arquette and features a rap jingle in a radio ad _ strategies that
would hardly be considered revolutionary for many marketers but
were a big change for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing things now that we never would have done three
years ago, and that makes some people inside AT&AMP;T nervous,'' said
McNally.
</P>
<P>
   Adidas, another X Games sponsor, risks being seen as a
``poser,'' since it only recently began selling shoes for
extreme-sports athletes.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid appearing too commercial, the company is limiting its
signage to about half of what it is entitled to, said Aaron Leeb,
events project manager.
</P>
<P>
   In partnership with the X Games, Adidas hosts field trips for
low-income youth to talk with professional athletes and coaches,
Leeb said. Such activities are designed to demonstrate that the
company cares about athletes and isn't just out to make a buck.
</P>
<P>
   Even the stodgy U.S. Postal Service is getting into the act with
an X Games commemorative stamp. ``Stamp collecting has become the
focus mostly of older folks, especially white, older men,'' said
USPS spokesman Don Smeraldi. ``We're trying to attract kids and a
more general audience with more contemporary subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of XGAMES25 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  USPS benefits from stamp collectors because every stamp that is
not used is pure profit for the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN, which created the games back in 1995, also faces a
marketing challenge. MTV recently launched an annual music and
extreme games festival, and this fall, NBC will host a similar
event, the Gravity Games.
</P>
<P>
   To stay on the cutting edge, ESPN this year is emphasizing the
Internet, adding an hour's worth of live video footage each day
from its Web site and letting site visitors judge one of the
events. Chat room conversations will scroll live at the bottom of
some telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The sports network also is adding more live music at this year's
games, with bands such as Protein, Sprung Monkey and Let's Go
Bowling.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN risks losing both viewers and sponsors if NBC's event takes
off, since NBC's audience is much larger, said Haynes. However,
fans will probably remember that ``long before NBC ever cared about
these events, ESPN was airing it and probably losing some money.
There is a loyalty factor there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
