<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8737 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUC-PUC_SFCHRON &LR;      06-24 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC- </SLUG>
 PUC _ SF CHRON  
 PUC Says Net Calls Are Local  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Consumers got a break yesterday when state regulators voted to
continue treating phone calls to Internet service providers as
local, staving off a potential increase in the cost of surfing the
Web.
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  The state Public Utilities Commission also agreed to
temporarily suspend a new area code overlay plan _ that requires
11-digit dialing on every call _ in West Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of the overlay plan for the 424 area code has no
immediate affect on the Bay Area, but eventually could lead to a
cancellation of four overlays scheduled for this region.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling on Internet calls quells a frenzy that had erupted in
California over what consumers pay to get online.
</P>
<P>
   By law, local phone companies are obligated to pay one another
for completing each other's local calls. The term for this fee is
``reciprocal compensation.'' The fee does not apply to
long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's ruling stems from a dispute between Pacific Bell and
Pac-West Telecomm, a competing local phone company that provides
phone service to many Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Every time a Pac Bell customer calls an ISP that uses Pac-West
as its phone company, Pac Bell has to pay Pac-West a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell had argued that it shouldn't have to pay Pac-West a
fee because calls made to the Internet are long-distance since they
could wind up anywhere on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC sided with Pac-West yesterday, concluding that Internet
calls are local. That means that phone companies who serve ISPs
will continue to get fees on every Internet call.
</P>
<P>
   If the PUC had decided to end reciprocal compensation, phone
companies said they might have had to raise rates to ISPs, and
those higher rates could have been passed on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Josiah Neeper was the only one of five commissioners who voted
against the decision. He had crafted an alternate proposal that
would have postponed a decision and opened a hearing on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Commission President Richard Bilas said yesterday's ruling ``may
have been one of the most difficult telecommunications decisions
I've had to make.''
</P>
<P>
   The PUC had been deluged with 3,000 to 4,000 letters and e-mails
from consumers and state legislators, many demanding that Internet
calls continue to be classified as local.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling has far-reaching implications because other competing
local phone companies can now demand that Pac Bell pay them for
handling Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell may appeal the ruling, which officials said is damaging
to their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where would Pac Bell or any other originating carrier come up
with the money to pay for this?'' said Bill Mashek, a spokesman for
Pac Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Blase, vice president of regulatory &UR; cq  &LR; for Pac Bell, said
the company may have to pass the cost on to customers through
higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups and competing carriers hailed the PUC's
action, saying it will keep rates for Internet calls affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will allow us to provide economical service to millions
of Californians,'' said David Simpson, president of the California
Internet Service Provider Association.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is far from settled, however. The PUC is expected to
consider hearing an appeal of an earlier order on reciprocal
compensation and the Federal Communications Commission also plans
to explore the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Another contentious issue that promises to keep rearing its head
is the issue of area code changes.
</P>
<P>
   Moved by public discontent and a pending bill in the state
Legislature, the PUC voted 4 to 1 yesterday to temporarily halt the
state's first area code overlay in West Los Angeles while it
debates the merits of 11-digit dialing.
</P>
<P>
   Overlays are one way to deal with the growing shortage of area
codes. Instead of dividing a region geographically and giving all
the customers in one half a new area code, an overlay plan lets
existing customers keep their area code and assigns the new area
codes to new phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that customers in the same neighborhood or even
the same house can have different area codes, and everyone in the
overlay region has to dial 1 plus the area code plus the number on
every call _ even if they're calling someone in the same area code.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven-digit dialing went into effect in the 310 region on April
17. After July 17, new phone customers in the 310 region were
scheduled to get 424 as their area code.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's vote will suspend implementation of the 424 area
code and prevent phone companies from giving out 424 phone numbers.
Eleven-digit dialing will continue during the temporary suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Henry Duque said the PUC should take another look
at the 310 overlay because there have been technical problems and
customer confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The delay gives the PUC more time to look at the overlay plan,
which has drawn the ire of consumers and state Assemblyman Wally
Knox.
</P>
<P>
   Knox has been pressuring the PUC to rescind the overlay, saying
there is no area code shortage. Knox said there are more than 145
million telephone numbers in the state that have been assigned to
phone companies but are not being used.
</P>
<P>
   He has a bill pending in the Assembly that would force phone
companies to disclose how many phone numbers they have and how many
are in use before consumers are inconvenienced with an overlay.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is important to the Bay Area, which is slated to
get overlays in the 408, 415, 510 and 650 regions during the next
two years. At public hearings on overlays, more people in the Bay
Area have complained than in the Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC also wants to change how numbers are assigned, something
that would help preserve existing area codes.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, phone numbers are assigned in blocks of 10,000,
regardless of how many customers a company has. Even if a phone
company only has 300 customers, it still must request 10,000
numbers. With more than 150 phone companies operating in
California, the supply of available numbers has quickly dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC has asked the Federal Communications Commission for the
right to assign numbers in blocks of 1,000 instead of 10,000. The
FCC recently opened a proceeding to look into how numbers are
assigned and could issue new rules within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates supported the PUC's ruling and said the
commission should vote to rescind all the state's overlays.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need for overlays or splits in California,'' said
Regina Costa, telecommunications analyst with The Utility Reform
Network. ``Why are customers being put in a vice? The reality is we
don't have to be in that vice because the area code crunch is an
artificial problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell officials disagreed, saying the 310 region is running
out of numbers and is in need of immediate relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are running out of numbers down there and customers are
going to be harmed if we can't do an overlay,'' said John Britton,
a Pac Bell spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
