<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8740 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS_SFC     06-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 WORKWAYS/ILANA DEBARE  &HT;     Part-Time Help Is Out There 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: As district manager for a major pharmaceutical company, I'm
having a very hard time filling sales positions. These jobs _ which
involve talking to doctors, pharmacists, et al. about new products
_ would be ideal for someone who wants to work in a part-time,
flexible-hours or job-sharing arrangement. I know there are people
out there who want such schedules as a way to balance their
personal and professional lives. But I don't seem to be finding
them through our regular help-wanted ads or recruiters. Any
suggestions?
<P>
   A: You're right that there are many skilled professionals _
especially working moms _ who would like part-time jobs. And you're
smart to use flexible schedules as a selling point for your firm in
today's tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   But a part-time schedule alone isn't enough to attract top-notch
candidates. Make sure pay and benefits are competitive. And make
sure that the job is doable: Don't ask people to do 40 hours of
work in a 20-hour week.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, here are a few ideas for ways to recruit the
kind of people you want:
</P>
<P>
   _Check out Working Options, a San Francisco recruitment firm
that specializes in placing professionals who want part-time or
flexible schedules. It can be reached at (415) 835-9466.
</P>
<P>
   _Post your job listing with career counseling centers such as
Alumnae Resources and Jewish Vocational Services in San Francisco,
or the Career Action Center in Cupertino. These centers often have
workshops on finding professional part-time work: Their attendees
would be prime candidates for your openings.
</P>
<P>
   _Try advertising in local newspapers or magazines that are
geared to parents, such as Parents' Press in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   _Contact local organizations of saleswomen or businesswomen.
Part-time work is still more popular among women than men. These
groups might mention your openings in a newsletter; or you could
spread the word in person by attending some of their events.
</P>
<P>
   Do you want more information on how to manage or recruit
employees with flexible schedules? Contact New Ways to Work, a San
Francisco nonprofit that has been helping companies with
alternative work arrangements for years. You can find them at (415)
995-9860 or  &LR; www.nww.org &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Unfulfilled promises
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there any laws that would keep an employer from
repeatedly hiring temporary secretaries, promising them permanent
employment in numerous verbal and written ways, but having no
intention to really hire them permanently? I've seen this happen
and it's pretty cruel. The temp ends up working under false
expectations and loses out on other career opportunities while
waiting for a permanent job that never arrives.
</P>
<P>
   A: There's a word for what this employer seems to be doing _
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's classic fraud _ saying something you know to be a lie, in
order to get someone to do something,'' said San Francisco attorney
Mark Thierman, who has represented temporary and contract workers
in several high-profile lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean these secretaries could take the boss to
court, though.
</P>
<P>
   Most lawyers won't take a case unless the victim can show some
economic damages _ such as lost salary, out-of-pocket moving
expenses to take a new job, etc.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, what have the secretaries lost?
</P>
<P>
   Thierman says they haven't lost much, economically. That's
because they probably would have been at-will employees if they
were hired permanently. And like all at-will workers, they could
have been dismissed at any time for any reason _ even on their
second day of work.
</P>
<P>
   So it would be hard to make an argument in court that the
secretaries lost out on 10 years' worth _ or even two weeks' worth
_ of guaranteed paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're at-will, you're about as permanent as a temp,''
Thierman said.
</P>
<P>
   There is one legal argument these secretaries might be able to
pursue: If they've been working for this employer for more than
five or six months, they might argue that they should receive the
same benefits as permanent employees.
</P>
<P>
   That's an evolving area of law. Some courts have said that
long-term temps should receive the same benefits as permanent
employees, but other courts have disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the most effective strategy may be for a
respected permanent employee to ask the boss to deal honestly with
the company's temps. If he won't listen, perhaps some permanent
staffer should take the newly hired temps aside and advise them to
take the boss' promises with a grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MORE ON NANNY TAXES &QL; 
Several weeks ago, I wrote about how to fill out tax documents for
an in-home baby sitter. Reader Jo Ellen Kaiser called with a
suggestion for people who want to follow the law but can't stomach
the paperwork _ use a payroll/tax service.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser uses an Austin, Texas, firm called Breedlove &AMP; Associates
Ltd. that handles payroll and tax paperwork for household
employers. Breedlove charges a set-up fee of $75 and then a flat
fee of $350 a year to handle all your payroll taxes and filings.
Want more information? Call (888) 273-3356 or see  &LR; www. &LR; 
 &LR; breedloveinc.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
