<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COURTROOM TESTIMONY ENDS IN MICROSOFT ANTITRUST CASE
</P>
<P>
   The heated accusations of monopoly, the lively e-mail flavored
with capitalist aggression and the spirited testimony alleging and
denying misconduct came to a close as the last witness stepped off
the stand in Microsoft's antitrust trial, eight months after
proceedings began.
</P>
<P>
   The government argues that it has more than proved its case, but
Microsoft, while conceding that the Justice Department put on an
impressive performance, says the facts do not add up to a violation
of antitrust rules. The legal reckoning that matters, however, will
be made by Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who will rule without a
jury.
</P>
<P>
   UNRAVELING MYSTERY IN FRAUD CASE
</P>
<P>
   The authorities are sorting through many questions concerning
Martin R. Frankel, who is suspected of looting seven insurance
companies of $335 million, wiring the money to foreign bank
accounts, incinerating documents and leaving behind notes that show
he was researching which foreign countries have no extradition
treaties with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   RUMORS SWIRLING ON INTERNET DEALS
</P>
<P>
   A recent spate of rumored Internet combinations shows the
menagerie of potential products and deals that companies and
investors must face to find a few that might pay off someday.
Compaq Computer confirmed that it was interested in trading its
Alta Vista Internet service for stock in CMGI. The computer maker
Gateway declined to comment on speculation that it would buy
Earthlink, an Internet service. And those rumors forced Mindspring,
another Internet service, to publish a cryptic statement that it
was in talks about possible combinations. Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN STANLEY BEATS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, demonstrating strength in its
securities trading and credit card businesses, posted
second-quarter results that beat analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   INTEREST RATES PUSH STOCKS LOWER
</P>
<P>
   Stocks tumbled as long-term interest rates jumped. The Dow Jones
industrial average dropped 132.03 points, or 1.24 percent, to
10,534.83. The Nasdaq composite index fell 44.13 points, or 1.7
percent, to 2,553.99, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
lost 17.28 points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,315.78.
</P>
<P>
   PEARSON TO SELL LAZARD HOLDINGS
</P>
<P>
   The British media company Pearson said that it was selling its
holdings in three Lazard investment houses in a deal that analysts
said would enable both Pearson and Lazard to become more
competitive by focusing more closely on their primary businesses.
</P>
<P>
   NEW EDITOR AT HARPER'S BAZAAR
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Betts, the fashion news director at Conde Nast's
Vogue, who was the heir apparent to Anna Wintour, resigned and will
take over as editor in chief of Harper's Bazaar on Sept. 1. The
announcement ends months of speculation in the notoriously gossipy
magazine world about whom Cathleen P. Black, the president of
Hearst Magazines, would choose as editor.
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND TV WORK MOVING OVERSEAS
</P>
<P>
   About 27 percent of American movies and TV series made last year
were filmed outside of the United States to save money, costing the
nation the equivalent of 23,500 full-time jobs and more than $10
billion, according to a study by two Hollywood unions.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN AIRLINES UNDER SCRUTINY
</P>
<P>
   Federal safety officials plan to investigate why American
Airlines has had more accidents in the last six years than any
other major domestic carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ORDERS FOR DURABLE GOODS UP 1.4 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Orders placed with factories for durable goods increased 1.4
percent in May, the second rise in three months, further evidence
that manufacturing is pulling out of last year's slump, government
figures showed.
</P>
</TEXT>
