<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: SHAKE-UP BOLSTERS TEACHERS' POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps the biggest winner in the shake-up of the
school system announced by Chancellor Rudy Crew on Wednesday was a
player whose role was largely behind the scenes: the teachers'
union.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the president of the United Federation of Teachers,
Randi Weingarten, proposed that the union assume responsibility for
a failing Bronx school and operate it under a set of new rules,
including a longer school day, incentive pay for teachers to work
that extended day, a reduction in class sizes and increased
training time for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the chancellor politely declined the offer, partly out
of unwillingness to relinquish substantial direction of the school
to the union.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan that the chancellor announced on Wednesday for
seizing direct control of 40 low-performing elementary and middle
schools was strikingly similar to what the union had proposed.
Aides to Crew said that his plan was not the union's alone, but an
amalgam of several ideas, from many sources.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the chancellor's plan includes a generous package
of benefits for teachers who choose to work in those low-performing
schools: a 15 percent raise, an annual $2,500 tuition reimbursement
for those pursuing master's degrees, a paring of class sizes to 20
students (from as high as 30) in the youngest grades, and daily
time set aside for teacher education.
</P>
<P>
   And while the chancellor stopped well short of turning the keys
of those schools over to the union, he enlisted it as an unusually
strong partner in making any number of decisions, ranging from
choosing the curriculums in each school to determining how teachers
will be retrained and who will be hired.
</P>
<P>
   By closely aligning itself with the chancellor's plan, the union
takes on some risks. The pay increase for teachers in
low-performing schools could not have been adopted without the
union's blessing, and unions seldom endorse paying some members
more than others. Moreover, if the schools continue to fail, the
union would bear some blame.
</P>
<P>
   Harold O. Levy, the chairman of the state aid committee of the
State Board of Regents, characterized Ms. Weingarten's
participation as ``extraordinarily brave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has demonstrated she's prepared to be flexible in the very
place where a union is most vulnerable: treating all its members
with pristine equality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the potential payoff for Ms. Weingarten seems worth the
risk: a little more than a year before its contract is set to
expire, the union has won recognition from the school system and
the city that the worst schools, at least, need to pay more to
attract good teachers.
</P>
<P>
   That rationale could eventually serve as the foundation for
across-the-board raises and, if the investment appears to be paying
off, could turn Mayor Rudolph Giuliani into an ally just as the
next contract is being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between the union and Crew, which the mayor's
aides approved in advance, would benefit more than 1,000 teachers
at 40 schools. (Three high schools taken over by the chancellor
were not part of the negotiations.)
</P>
<P>
   Given that the average teacher's salary in the city is $44,000,
the average raise would be $6,600. And the $2,500 in tuition money
represents, in effect, an additional 6 percent raise on top of
that.
</P>
<P>
   Under the chancellor's plan, which was swiftly approved by the
board of education on Wednesday, the teachers would collect the
additional benefits in exchange for transferring to these schools
and working an extra 40-minute period a day. The benefits would
expire in three years.
</P>
<P>
   While teachers who remain at the schools would also be entitled
to the new benefits, board officials hope to replace all of the
temporary, uncertified teachers on their staffs.
</P>
<P>
   While the union and the central board would decide together
which teachers should be hired at the schools this fall, the union
agreed to a concession: seniority would not be a driving factor in
ranking candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Weingarten has her eye on a bigger prize: using the
goodwill engendered by her participation in the chancellor's
experiment to raise all teacher salaries next year to within
striking distance of the city's nearest suburbs, which routinely
pay their educators tens of thousands of dollars more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that through all of the clack, we were able to
reach a meeting of the minds,'' Ms. Weingarten said. ``Hopefully,
this will open up an opportunity to talk about other things that
are educationally important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
