<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON GROUP SUES POET FOR NOT APPEARING AT FUNCTION IN HER HONOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Houston group that honored noted African-American
poet and writer Maya Angelou with its ``Order of Kilimanjaro'' last
year has sued her for not showing up at the award ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``She (Angelou) refused to return our phone calls and letters
and generally snubbed us,'' said Clay Crawford, attorney for
African Overseas Union, the nonprofit group that presented the
award.
</P>
<P>
   He said the cash-strapped organization lost $50,000 to $75,000
to prepare for Angelou's scheduled ceremony Dec. 5, only to be told
the days before _ without explanation _ that Angelou would not make
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Harris County state district court suit, filed Wednesday,
wants Angelou to pay for the losses because she allegedly breached
a contract that stated she would attend.
</P>
<P>
   Angelou's representative in Winston-Salem, N.C., did not return
a phone call from the Houston Chronicle. Angelou, 71, a professor
at Wake Forest University, is perhaps best known for her 1969
autobiographical account ``I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings,'' but
she also has dabbled in popular culture, helping write and produce
the movie, ``Sister, Sister'' and other films.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says Angelou sent a letter to the Houston organization
in July 1998 saying she would accept the award, and enclosed
biographical information and photographs to be used in a program
book. She asked that the ceremony be held in December because she
was already planning to be in Houston at that time, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preparations of the elaborate event began,'' the suit said.
``Angelou gave specific measurements in order that ceremonial
attire could be hand-tailored to her exact size and proportions.
Angelou was to be presented with a hand-carved staff of office from
Benin City, Nigeria. A traditional dance troupe from Nigeria was to
be flown to Houston for the event. Angelou gave specific
instructions as to the type of food not to be served in her
presence due to severe allergic reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the suit said, ``Angelou was informed that African
Overseas Union had arranged for His Royal Highness, the Alafin of
Oyo, Nigeria, to be in attendance as a guest of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit said that board members of the group suffered the
embarrassment of having to go to the site of the ceremony to tell
the public the event was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Angelou postponed a scheduled performance at Jones Hall in April
because of lingering effects from a recent bout with pneumonia, but
Crawford said he has no idea if Angelou was sick for the December
event because ``she's refused to talk to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Order of Kilimanjaro, named after Africa's highest
mountain &UR; ,  &LR; is bestowed to ``African-Americans who have
distinguished themselves by their contributions to the community,''
the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   Previous recipients are noted artist Dr. John Biggers in 1995
and African writer Chinua Achebe in 1996. Crawford said there were
no past problems with honorees not showing up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
