<SLUG> BC-GEPHARDT-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT SAYS FASTER CHECK COULD SHORTEN GUN-CONTROL TIME FRAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Less than a week after House Democrats voted
against a gun-control package rather than accept what they said
were soft terms in a measure to regulate gun shows, Rep. Dick
Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority leader, seemed to open the
door at least a crack Thursday to some sort of compromise on that
point.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday morning, Gephardt suggested that
while he and many other Democrats had insisted on three business
days for gun-show vendors to complete background checks on
customers, a shorter time frame might be acceptable if the check
system worked faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's a way to find common ground there, where we're
increasing the ability to get the checks done and we don't need _
over time, maybe not right away _ but we can quicken the time when
the instant check can be done,'' Gephardt said. ``I'm willing to
look at that, as I think a lot of us are, to see if we can find our
way through this.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview late Thursday afternoon, Gephardt
sought to clarify his remarks, saying he did not intend to imply
that he or other Democratic proponents of gun control were willing
to cede ground on a matter they felt was critical.
</P>
<P>
   What he was proposing, the congressman said, was that supporters
and opponents of gun control work to make the background-check
system so fast that disagreements about time limits would become
moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, it seems to me, is the place where you get consensus,''
Gephardt said. But until that day, he added, ``I think you've got
to have three business days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
