u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PENGUINS-NYT &LR;      06-24 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMIEUX CAN KEEP PENGUINS IN PITTSBURGH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ore.)   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A U.S. Bankruptcy Court judge granted approval Thursday to Mario
Lemieux's plan to keep the Penguins from either leaving Pittsburgh
or having their players dispersed to other teams in a special
National Hockey League draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in it to make money, but I'm not in it to lose
money,'' Lemieux said after the 6 1/2 hour court hearing. ``We want
to make sure the Penguins stay here. They've been a big part of my
life and my success.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux's victory ended a tense financial drama that found his
former team, which owed him and other creditors more than $100
million, playing deep into the playoffs this season under the
shadow of a bankruptcy filing dating to last October.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Judge Bernard Markovitz in a Pittsburgh courtroom
made Lemieux the general partner of the team for which he scored
1,494 points in a 12-year career, with an ownership stake of at
least 20 percent. As part of his reorganization plan, Lemieux
converted $20 million of the $32.5 million he was owed in deferred
salary by the team into equity in the revived franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Although some former players have owned small team stakes _ such
as Magic Johnson's minority share of the Los Angeles Lakers _
Lemieux's controlling role is unique.
</P>
<P>
   The immensely popular Lemieux, 33, who led the Penguins to two
Stanley Cup championships before retiring as a player in 1997, is
expected to let existing management, including General Manager
Craig Patrick, run the team. The Penguins finished this season
37-30-14 and lost in the conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   William Daly, the NHL's senior vice president of legal affairs,
said: ``We're very happy; we're very gratified. We think it's
important to keep hockey in Pittsburgh.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux's group is committed to investing at least $60 million
in the team. Thursday morning, the group said it had $11 million in
escrow, with $30 million on the way, but by afternoon, the figure
was up to $38 million. ``That's pretty good, on short notice,''
Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   Daly said Team Lemieux has until mid-July to show it has
collected more of the $60 million investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great for our clients,'' said Joel Walker, the lawyer
for the Penguins' unsecured creditors.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle for Lemieux is the Penguins' lease situation at the
Civic Center. Lawyers for Lemieux and SMG, which has leased the
arena from a local agency and rented it to the team for $6 million
a year, could not agree on a new lease before Thursday's hearing.
Last week, Markovitz ruled that the existing lease was invalid
because it was really a loan to Howard Baldwin to help buy the team
in 1991. SMG is appealing the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were up to Mario, he'd probably like a one-time buyout
and be rid of SMG,'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   But SMG controls the building, and it may be best for Lemieux to
negotiate a favorable new lease while he has leverage, or risk not
having a place to play.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's hearing, an SMG lawyer threatened a lawsuit if
Markovitz lets the Penguins operate the arena themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still want to talk to them, but if not, we'll let the court
decide their fate,'' Lemieux said.
</P>
<P>
   SMG is also the Islanders' landlord at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL had also filed a reorganization plan that would have
provided for the sale of the team to an out-of-town buyer _ one
such suitor, believed to be in Portland, Ore., had placed $85
million into an escrow account _ or for the players' dispersal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
