<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN EMBASSY BOMBINGS PROCLAIMS INNOCENCE IN LETTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Texas man accused of conspiring with Osama bin
Laden in terrorist attacks against Americans said in recent letters
to his family that he was innocent and accused American officials
of not acting quickly enough to prevent the bombings of U.S.
Embassies in Africa last August.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the letters from Wadih el-Hage marks the first
time any communications from the five defendants in the terrorism
case, who have been jailed under unusually restrictive conditions
in New York, have been made public. Each of the five is in solitary
confinement and is barred from communicating with almost all
outsiders, including the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for el-Hage, who has been charged with conspiring to
murder Americans overseas and with perjury, have said he is upset
at his inability to state his case publicly.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing on Tuesday, after a federal judge refused to read
aloud a letter the defendant wrote, he bolted from his seat and
charged at the judge. He was quickly tackled by a federal marshal.
The letter has not yet been released by the judge, who cited
government concerns that it might contain coded messages to other
fugitives.
</P>
<P>
   The two letters that were made public were written by el-Hage to
relatives, and were given by a close family member to Oriana Zill,
a reporter who worked on a documentary about the case that was
jointly produced by the public television series ``Frontline'' and
The New York Times. She is also the author of a profile of el-Hage
for the Internet Web site of ``Frontline''.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter written on May 4, el-Hage sought to refute the
allegations against him, questioning the prosecutors' motives and
suggesting that their case was built around innocent associations
in his past with bin Laden, Haroun Fazil, another fugitive in the
case, and others.
</P>
<P>
   El-Hage contended that he had had ``nothing to do with their
actions.'' Mocking the prosecutors, he wrote: ``They couldn't get
Bin Laden or Haroun, let's get el-Hage,'' and continued: ``We want
to win this big case. It doesn't matter if we ruin his or his
family's life, we want to win this case, fame, position,
promotions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated Feb. 13, el-Hage wrote, ``I am confident, by
the will of Allah, that I will be acquitted, for I had nothing to
do with this whole issue of actions of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Herbert Hadad, a spokesman for U.S. Attorney Mary Jo
White, nor Sam A. Schmidt, el-Hage's lawyer, would comment Thursday
about the letters.
</P>
<P>
   The federal indictment says that el-Hage served as bin Laden's
personal secretary in Sudan, and that he tried to obtain chemical
weapons for his group. He is accused of carrying messages and money
between bin Laden and others in what prosecutors say is bin Laden's
worldwide terrorist conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. el-Hage has served as a front man for the bin Laden
organization for years,'' a prosecutor said in one court hearing,
adding that el-Hage was linked to ``both violence and violent
people.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In blaming the government for not acting quickly enough to
prevent the bombings, el-Hage refers to accounts that the
authorities, in a search of his house in Nairobi, Kenya, in August,
1997, found an incriminating letter on his computer. The government
seized the letter, which talked about bin Laden's `East Africa
network,'' during its investigation bin Laden before the bombings.
Prosecutors have said the letter was probably written by Fazil, who
they say was el-Hage's deputy.
</P>
<P>
   El-Hage said the authorities had had the letter ``for one whole
year'' before the embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were they waiting for a tragedy to start their
investigations?'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He also contended that from what he had read about the Nairobi
bombing, those who carried it out used stun grenades and shot
bullets into the air to warn and disperse people. ``I cannot
imagine a Muslim targeting innocent people,'' he wrote. ``They
maybe targeted the U.S. Embassy, but from what the indictment
explained, they couldn't be targeting other civilians in the
vicinity around.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   El-Hage, who has pleaded not guilty, has taken the position
through his lawyers that he worked for bin Laden, but only in what
he believed were legitimate businesses. He has denied any role in
terrorism or other wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The relative, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said she
was making the letters public because of her frustration at
el-Hage's inability to communicate with the outside world. She said
she believed el-Hage had become ``psychologically impaired by being
kept away from any other human contact besides his jailers for nine
months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody would have snapped,'' the relative said, referring to
el-Hage's action in court this week. ``He is frustrated beyond
words.''
</P>
</TEXT>
