<SLUG> BC-GOVERNORS-DEMOCRATS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC GOVERNORS TALK OF WAYS TO EMERGE FROM POLITICAL
WILDERNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The years of Bill Clinton's presidency have been a
dark age for Democratic governors, as one statehouse after another
fell to the Republicans and big names like Mario Cuomo and Ann
Richards were ousted by voters.
</P>
<P>
   But statehouse survivors were talking a Clinton-like agenda of
technology, international trade, education and school safety as
keys to emerging from the political wilderness as the Democratic
Governors Association gathered here Thursday for its summer policy
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is cyclical. We're on our way back,'' said Gov. Howard
Dean of Vermont, who has watched Democrats dip from control of 30
statehouses to their current total of 17.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Frank O'Bannon of Indiana added: ``If we can focus on
(issues), the politics can take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The way back is not old-time Democratic populism, free spending,
or stemwinding speeches about solidarity with organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governors huddled Thursday with corporate chief
executive officers. A top adviser to California Gov. Gray Davis
talked excitedly of an upcoming summer meeting between his boss and
Microsoft CEO Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   O'Bannon, a Democratic governor of a Republican state, spoke of
states' needs to adopt ``a more businesslike approach to quality
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were in control of 30 statehouses at the dawn of the
1990s. Nowadays, Republicans hold 31 governorships. Two statehouses
are held by independents, Govs. Jesse Ventura in Minnesota and
Angus King in Maine.;
</P>
<P>
   The party's biggest losses came in 1994, two years into the
first term of Clinton, a former chairman of the Democratic
Governors Association. Democrats lost statehouses in such populous
states as New York, Pennsylvania, Texas and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   As the decade ends, there is only one Democratic governor _
California's Davis _ in the nation's 10 largest states. Five
moderate Democrats held Mountain States governorships at the start
of the 1990s. All five statehouses are now in Republican hands.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican governor, George W. Bush of Texas, is his party's
leading presidential contender. Another GOP chief executive, Tommy
Thompson in Wisconsin, has instituted the country's most
far-reaching welfare reform program.
</P>
<P>
   An economic boom, fueled by lowering of taxes, has kept the
governorship in Massachusetts _ arguably America's most Democratic
state _ in Republican hands. In the labor stronghold of Michigan,
GOP Gov. John Engler has won three terms by cutting taxes, backing
charter schools, and instituting welfare reform requiring work.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governors Thursday tried to claim credit for
successes of their Republican counterparts. ``The ones on the
cutting edge out there are following our policies,'' said O'Bannon.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats scored a few notably gubernatorial successes last
year. Davis ended 16 years of Republican control in California,
while Tom Vilsack became the first Democrat since 1968 to occupy
the Iowa governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   They also found an issue in the Deep South, the creation of
state lotteries to fund scholarships and education improvements.
Democrats ousted GOP governors in Alabama and South Carolina, and
held onto the Georgia governor's mansion. This year, they are an
even-money bet to end eight years of Republican control in
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us never thought in our lifetimes that we would see
Democrats back in Deep South statehouses,'' Dean said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But after the anti-government uprisings of the early 1990s,
which cost their party dearly, the new generation of Democratic
governors are charting their course with care. The deliberately
low-key Davis has concentrated on a cause to which all Californians
can rally _ restoring the state's run-down school system. Gov. Roy
Barnes of Georgia has set his sights on transportation and
unsnarling Atlanta's gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   The most populist governor elected last year, Iowa's Vilsack, on
Thursday talked the centrist's language of international trade and
economic developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy percent of Iowa's crops are grown and leave the state
with no value added,'' Vilsack said. ``Our farmers are getting
prices below cost. ... If we can turn that around it will have
tremendous impacts. We have to have a strong trade presence, and it
must have a strong international component.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' host, Washington Gov. Gary Locke, chimed in with
talk about ``the importance of public-private partnerships and
``how states can open up markets abroad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
