<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-FUGITIVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE'S TRAIL LEADS TO EL PASO, KENTUCKY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By S.K. BARDWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Accused serial killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez has been
seen recently in El Paso, Texas, and Louisville, Ky., officials
confirmed Thursday, but the hard part is determining where he will
turn up next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get the information that will lead us one step
ahead of where he's going,'' said Don K. Clark, special agent in
charge of the Houston FBI office.
</P>
<P>
   That will be difficult, said Texas Ranger Drew Carter, a member
of the Houston-based task force hunting Resendez-Ramirez, because
he stays on the move and easily travels the country by rail.
</P>
<P>
   At his press conference, Clark confirmed that Resendez-Ramirez
had been sighted in El Paso about three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Louisville FBI office confirmed that
Resendez-Ramirez had been seen in town June 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Louisville Police Department said officers
were checking homeless shelters and railroad yards but had no
homicides in which Resendez-Ramirez was a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   A profiler from the Houston FBI office was in Lexington, Ky.,
Thursday to brief law-enforcement agencies on Resendez-Ramirez's
methods.
</P>
<P>
   The task force of local, state and federal officers hunting
Resendez-Ramirez gathered information indicating that he told
someone on June 10 that he planned to go to Kentucky to obtain
migrant work. Clark declined Thursday to discuss whom
Resendez-Ramirez has contacted since the nationwide manhunt began.
</P>
<P>
   Carter acknowledged that family members of the fugitive in the
El Paso-Ciudad Juarez area had been interviewed Wednesday, but he
said there were ``no real surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were supportive of him and talked of him as you or I
would of a family member,'' Carter said. ``They gave no indication
of any dark side to this individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said Resendez-Ramirez's family was cooperative, but
added, ``I think they're somewhat in a state of denial'' about the
allegations against him.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez has been charged with murdering a father and
his daughter in Gorham, Ill., earlier this month, and University of
Kentucky student Christopher Maier in August 1997. He also is
charged with raping Maier's girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez has been linked by physical evidence to five
homicides in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Hughes Springs, Texas, are still waiting to see
if a palm print left by the killer of an elderly woman matches that
of Resendez-Ramirez. Evidence in a Pontiac, Mich., murder also is
being examined for a possible connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had some other law-enforcement agencies who have asked
to compare (information), and there are some comparisons going on
as we speak,'' Clark said. He declined to give the name of any
agencies or to say how many.
</P>
<P>
   Some cases are nothing more than deaths that have occurred near
railroad tracks, Clark said. He emphasized that no cases would be
closed by attributing them to Resendez-Ramirez, as was done in the
1980s when Henry Lee Lucas confessed to dozens of murders, then
recanted when evidence surfaced that he had been lying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law-enforcement agencies are responsible,'' Clark said
Thursday. ``If there is a homicide near a railroad track, in all
likelihood, law-enforcement agencies are going to check it out and
see if there's a connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Rewards being offered for information leading to the arrest and
conviction of Resendez-Ramirez, who was placed on the FBI's Ten
Most Wanted Fugitives list Monday, are up to $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI announced a new toll-free telephone number for calls
regarding Resendez-Ramirez Thursday. Clark said 1-800-889-8161 will
be answered 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
