</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOURTH-GRADERS HELP ARCHITECTS ENVISION THE OFFICE OF TOMORROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If you want to know what the workplace of the future
should look like, why not go to the experts: the workforce of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Callison Architecture Inc., a Seattle firm, did just that when
it recruited fourth-graders from Villa Academy to brainstorm the
way the office of the future will work.
</P>
<P>
   The kids came up with a host of intriguing, sometimes
insightful, and just plain fanciful suggestions for the office of
2015.
</P>
<P>
   One kid, for example, designed a hot tub with a built-in
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``About two years ago, when we started planning for Future at
Work, it occurred to us that those people (who will be working in
the future) are alive now,'' said Kim Jennings, co-principal with
the firm, who worked with Callison Principal Andrea Vanecko on the
Future at Work project. ``And they were the ones who didn't have
any preconceived notions about the way offices were supposed to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the same people employers will be recruiting in 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigwig in the corner office is an idea handed along and
has evolved through existing office culture,'' Jennings said.
Fourth-graders wouldn't be handicapped by history.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they have pretty vivid imaginations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks, 16 9- and 10-year-olds joined a team of Callison
architects to explore the nature of work and what people will need
to get their work done well.
</P>
<P>
   For kids, whose previous career ambitions mostly centered on
non-office work (firefighter, police officer, circus clown), the
notion of working in an office initially wasn't very appealing,
Jennings said. They described the office as a place ``no one wanted
to be in and everyone wanted to get out of.''
</P>
<P>
   But that described the office of today, Jennings said. When kids
were given a list of intriguing office jobs (travel agency for
space travel) and permission to recreate the office as we know it,
their perceptions changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found kids were definitely not perceiving work in the office
of the future as a negative thing,'' she said. ``They seemed to
have a lot of energy for accomplishment and collaboration. They
didn't bring negativity to the whole environment.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the kids' key findings was that businesses should help
people work together.
</P>
<P>
   Collaboration is critical to the economy of the future, but the
traditional office doesn't facilitate good teamwork, Jennings said.
The kids thought work would be like a team ``relay'' with
hand-offs. The spirit of group achievement permeated their thinking
with an emphasis on information sharing, rather than information
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish work in that fashion, they wanted more couches and
coffee tables, rather than desks.
</P>
<P>
   And they wanted soft, thick carpets ``so that when you want to
relax, it's comfortable to rest on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how social they were,'' Jennings said. ``They
wanted to have places where people could talk to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, they turned an existing concept _ the home office _ on
its ear, inventing instead an office-home that people wouldn't want
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the kids wanted to build in room for recreation and
leisure activities, such as virtual golf, she said. Also on their
wish lists were ``resting'' rooms, juice bars, and nature areas.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort was key. Light, warmth, food and nature were considered
essential office tools. Nature, in particular, was important ``to
look at because it calms you in case you get stressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Variety was another theme of the new office as envisioned by the
fourth-graders, perhaps not surprising given their quicksilver
attention spans.
</P>
<P>
   The kids wanted to to be able to change their media and their
environment easily. That meant taking today's open-plan design one
step further by creating a free-flowing ``compound'' of functional
areas. Such a compound would allow them to move around at will and
work in a variety of spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Closed offices should exist only for ``top secret'' work, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   For children of a high-tech world, the fourth-graders also
expressed a surprising interest in low-tech tools, such as markers
and whiteboards.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether they thought anything like what they imagined
existed in the workplace today, the children turned wistful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe (it did) in the '80s,'' said one, who wasn't even born
then. ``Because offices today (are) too high-tech.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
