<HEADLINE>
THE PREVIEW IN IOWA IS DRAWING A CROWD 
AS THE WORLD TURNS, THE FORDICES FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Iowa, Miss., Texas, Tenn.)  (nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Iowa's first-in-the-nation caucuses are still seven months off,
but the frequency with which presidential candidates are showing up
in the state makes it seem as if the big event is nearly at hand.
And in a sense it is.
</P>
<P>
   With many states moving up the date of their Election 2000
caucuses and primaries in order to gain the kind of early influence
Iowa has traditionally had in the nominating process, next year's
campaign schedule is so front-loaded that a straw poll Iowa
Republicans have scheduled for Aug. 14 _ this Aug. 14 _ is
beginning to loom as the first real make-or-break test. The poll
could well take on the winnowing role of the caucuses and cut the
dozen-candidate field to three or four true contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week Texas Gov. George W. Bush began scouring the
state's cities and farm towns for organizers, apparently seeing the
August gathering as a chance to all but lock up the nomination, if
he wins big.
</P>
<P>
   Another hopeful, Pat Buchanan, asserted the other day that Bush
``clearly, basically, wants to end the race for the Republican
nomination on Aug. 14.'' Buchanan then began stepping up his own
Iowa appearances.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander,
still long on presidential hopes but lagging in the polls and as a
result beginning to run out of money, decided to concentrate almost
all his resources on Iowa. His campaign organizations elsewhere
were cut to the bone or all but shut down.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, former Vice President Dan Quayle, also squeezed
for money and lagging in the polls, announced that he was ``ramping
up'' his Iowa effort. He sent in a new chief of operations, hired a
consultant to help him latch on to the state's big Christian-right
vote, doubled the number of his field workers to 14 and committed
himself to five major campaign swings though the state between now
and the August straw vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a do-or-die event for some candidates,'' said Greg
Mueller, a consultant to another Republican contender, Steve
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   If Mueller has it right, even Forbes' huge personal fortune
might not be enough to keep him politically alive should he stumble
in Iowa in August.
</P>
<P>
   As the World Turns, The Fordices Fight
</P>
<P>
   In our last installment, Mississippi Gov. Kirk Fordice had just
returned from vacationing in France with a woman not his wife and
had demanded a divorce. His wife, Pat, had responded that she did
not want to dissolve a marriage of 44 years and intended to remain
ensconced in the Governor's Mansion. She said the other woman, Ann
Creson, an old flame of the governor, would just have to wait her
turn. Mrs. Fordice then offered ``apologies for being a partner in
a marriage that has become a source of embarrassment for
Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   The War of the Fordices has now escalated. On Tuesday, the
Republican governor summoned some members of the press corps and
tried to make a case for a speedy divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live separately in the Governor's Mansion,'' he argued,
``totally, with a closed door, no communication whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   The press cut to the Continental liaison, asking whether the
governor might be considered a hypocrite, given that a few months
back he criticized President Clinton for marital infidelity and
more recently signed on as a national co-chairman of the Quayle
presidential campaign, whose main pitch is family values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never lied before a grand jury,'' the governor replied,
``never lied to the people, wagging my finger on TV, never
conducted a scurrilous affair with a person half my age in the
White House in the middle of the day while talking on the telephone
to a senator. I'm not a womanizer of much renown.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he announced that he had just resigned his Quayle post,
telling the former vice president he wanted to do ``what's best for
you, Dan.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Mrs. Fordice fired back, saying that contrary to
what the governor had said, she had maintained ``regular contact,
companionship and communication'' with him until the recent trip to
France. The governor, she said, is turning a marital tragedy into
``some sort of romantic comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   What, she asked, is she supposed to do with her life? Where is
she supposed to go?
</P>
<P>
   One answer, sort of, comes from Mississippi Pol Online, a
political tip sheet. It says there is some talk in the state's
political circles that Pat Fordice, perhaps inspired by the Hillary
Clinton model, ``may be looking'' to run for Congress. Possible
target: Rep. Ronnie Shows, a freshman Democrat from Mississippi's
4th Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
