<HEADER>
A8766 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-ART-4     06-24 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTED CON MAN LEFT PLENTY OF WARNING SIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Repeating to fix coding ,  slug on 4th take (ART ADV: Photo NYT26 has moved to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On April 28, with the sun setting outside their elegant Hilton
Hotel conference suite in downtown Jackson, Miss., the key figures
in what was, on paper, a vast philanthropic and insurance empire
gathered together for the first and last time.
</P>
<P>
   Those present included two Tennesseans who managed the Franklin
American Corp., operator of a dozen insurance companies in five
states. Also attending, after a long flight from Rome, were two
elderly Catholic priests representing the charitiable foundation
which owned the Franklin company.
</P>
<P>
   The guest of honor, and the man who controlled the empire, was a
pasty 44-year-old who variously introduced himself as a genius bond
trader, a multi-millionaire and an amateur student of Catholic
theology. They knew him by different names _ Eric Stevens and David
Rosse _ but his real name was Martin R. Frankel. That day, he
appeared in person for the first time to many people in the room.
</P>
<P>
   They have not seen him since. Frankel did not show up the next
day when the group met Mississippi regulators in an attempt to
convince them that the companies' books were in order.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, court records show, Frankel wired as much as $334.6
million in insurance company money from Franklin American to
foreign bank accounts, incinerated documents in his $3 million
Greenwich mansion and fled. He left behind notes that show he was
researching which foreign countries have no extradition treaties
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators suspect that Frankel looted at least seven
insurance companies in several states of money they had given him
to invest. While no charges have been brought against Frankel, a
warrant has been issued for his arrest in what authorities is one
of the largest insurance frauds in history.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel also left behind a trail of questions that authorities
are still trying to answer. Why did so many people ignore what
appeared, in hindsight, to be clear signals of fraud? Were the
people who gathered at the Hilton unwitting dupes, as they or their
lawyers now maintain, or did they have some inkling of what was
going on? And, finally, where is Frankel?
</P>
<P>
   Those mysteries will not be solved soon. But what does emerge
from court documents and interviews with friends, business partners
and neighbors is a picture of Frankel as a brazen but wily con man,
a master puppeteer whose dealings spanned the globe, from Franklin,
Tenn., to the rarefied address of Lake Avenue in Greenwich, to the
British Virgin Islands to the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Athough he was investigated once, in 1991, by the Securities and
Exchange Commission and agreed not to associate himself with the
securities business again, he promptly disregarded that ban. And as
he expanded his business reach, he added characters to the plot.
</P>
<P>
   His main and most recent target appeared to be the Vatican. Born
to a middle-class family in Toledo, Ohio, he at times portrayed
himself as a Jew interested in the Catholic religion. He flattered
Catholics on both sides of the Atlantic and promised millions for
Catholic charities to get into the good graces of the church
hierarchy. He courted prominent Catholics with private jet trips or
tickets on the supersonic Concorde, even though many of them did
not repay his attentions with much support.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most spectacularly, Frankel persuaded Monsignor Emilio
Colagiovanni, who edits a Rome-based journal on canon law, to sign
a sworn statement indicating that the Holy See funded and stood
four-square behind an organization Frankel headed. Colagiovanni
acknowledged in an interview in Rome that the statement was
``misleading,'' but denied he had engaged in any wrongdoing or knew
anything about the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the affidavit helped persuade the prominent law
firm of Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld to continue representing
the foundation. The firm and its famous partner, Robert S. Strauss,
the former Democratic national chairman and former ambassador to
the Soviet Union, collected several hundred thousand dollars in
fees working on possible acquisitions of insurance companies, none
of which came to pass, according to a person who has reviewed the
billings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of people were conned by Marty Frankel, Eric Stevens,
David Rosse _ whatever his name was,'' said Aubrey Harwell, a
Nashville, Tenn., lawyer who represents the two Tennessee
businessmen who attended the April 28 meeting in a lawsuit against
Frankel. ``It's a classic ponzi scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   There were warning signs. Frankel mixed and matched his aliases
so boldly that guests at his dinner parties in Greenwich sometimes
addressed him by different names. His intermingling of charity and
commerce was befuddling to many who dealt with him. He bestowed
gifts on friends so lavishly that many said they considered him
reckless with his money, as if it did not belong to him.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel also led an eccentric, even dark, personal life. He
turned his luxury Greenwich estate into a fortress, traveled with
body guards when visiting his hometown, and trolled the Internet
for women to serve as clerical help, neighbors and associates said.
</P>
<P>
   He met and lived with several women he found through personal
ads, according to a statement he gave Greenwich police after a
woman was found hanging from a noose tied to the deck of one of his
Connecticut homes in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   EARLY LIFE IN TOLEDO
</P>
<P>
   Martin Richard Frankel was born on Nov. 21, 1954, into a
respectable middle-class family of lawyers and public servants. His
father, Leon, worked as a referee at a domestic relations court in
Toledo, and his mother, Tillie, was a clerk in the Toledo city
government.
</P>
<P>
   Marty, as he was known, was the third of four children. By all
accounts, he was a bright youngster, even brilliant, friends say.
Almost 6 feet tall, Frankel was thin, weighing 135 pounds, and,
friends say, awkward and introverted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have many friends when he was growing up,'' said
Bradford Dolgin, who attended Whitmer High School with Frankel.
``He was pretty eccentric.''
</P>
<P>
   In class, his political views were left-wing and unconventional,
one faculty member recalled.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Frankel's high intelligence, though, friends and
faculty members say he had trouble finishing what he started. He
seemed to have a phobia about taking exams, and rarely turned in
class papers, they said.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from high school in three years, near the top of
his class. He took courses at the University of Toledo in the late
1970s and early 1980s, but never earned a degree. His academic
record is under privacy seal, at his request, according to the
school's registrar.
</P>
<P>
   It was during his college years that Frankel fell in love with
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty was kind of a jack of all trades, master of none,'' said
George J. Windau, a college friend of Frankel. ``And then he became
a master of one: the stock market, commodities, currencies.''
</P>
<P>
   He became a day trader, rapidly buying and selling stocks, often
many times a day.
</P>
<P>
   He took his first professional crack at the securities business
at the Toledo branch of a New York brokerage firm, Dominick &AMP;
Dominick. Details are sketchy, but John Schulte, who headed the
branch, says that he fired Frankel in 1987 for failing ``to
produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Other tensions emerged between the two men. Schulte said his
marriage with his wife, Sonia, fell apart and she began a long
relationship with Frankel. According to police records, the three
at times tussled over allowing Schulte time to visit his two
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Those confrontations, friends say, caused Frankel to grow
increasingly fearful that Schulte would retaliate against him. It
was, some friends believe, one reason he left Toledo and turned to
aliases.
</P>
<P>
   Even before he left, friends and neighbors say he began to
install security equipment at home and hired a man named David
Rosse, who would eventually travel with him to Greenwich as his
security guard and whose name Frankel would appropriate for his own
use.
</P>
<P>
   When Frankel returned home last November for the funeral of his
father, who died at the age of 87, he came with a small army of
security guards.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY FAILURE
</P>
<P>
   By the late-1980s, Frankel had struck out on his own, setting up
a money management firm he called Frankel Fund, which he operated
from a room in his parents' home. He recruited local people and
retirees as investors.
</P>
<P>
   As the fund grew, he moved to West Palm Beach, Fla., seeking to
strengthen his business with retirees. Friends say that he moved at
the suggestion of Douglas I. Maxwell, a Tennessee man who formed a
partnership with Frankel called PDS Securities Inc. The partnership
raised at least $1 million for the Frankel Fund, according to
securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Creamer, the lawyer for two Ohio retirees who filed suit
against Frankel, said he boasted of living an extravagant life and
of having attracted a Romanian queen and the king of Yugoslavia as
investors. ``He was a kind of Woody Allen character, kind of
goofy,'' Creamer recalled. ``It's kind of disarming.''
</P>
<P>
   But the venture did not last long. At least one of Frankel's
clients raised questions, and soon Frankel was back in Toledo,
telling investors that his partner, Maxwell, had bungled their
investments.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission had another view. It
froze the accounts of the Frankel Fund. In a settlement, Frankel
agreed to stay away from the securities industry forever as
punishment for having lied about the fund's performance, his own
experience and even how the proceeds would be used.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE INTERESTS GROW
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the SEC was cracking down on the Frankel Fund,
Frankel was teaming up with John A. Hackney, a Tennessee bank
executive, to buy insurance companies. It is an industry that is
regulated by the states, not by federal agencies like the SEC.
Frankel appears to have targeted small, troubled insurance
companies that were vulnerable to embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel and Hackney did not actually meet until eight years
later, in the Mississippi hotel. But over the phone, Hackney became
fast friends with the man he came to know only as Eric Stevens, who
portrayed himself as an experienced bond trader eager to employ a
novel and lucrative trading strategy to improve the returns on
insurance company assets, according to Harwell, Hackney's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said that Hackney was paid a straight salary for
managing insurance companies that he bought on Frankel's behalf and
had no other interest in Frankel's dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Hackney did agree to steer the insurance companies' investment
business to Frankel's Liberty National Securities.
</P>
<P>
   To make their first acquisition, of Franklin American Corp., the
two partners set up Thunor Trust. Frankel's name was not associated
with the trust, but several of his acquaintances are identified in
state documents as investors who put up the $3.8 million in startup
funds.
</P>
<P>
   They were Sonia Schulte, the Toledo girlfriend, Edward Krauss, a
Frankel family friend who now lives in Columbus, Ohio, and Mark C.
Shuki, an acquaintance from Chicago. Krauss said in an interview he
had nothing to do with Thunor and did not willingly lend his name.
The others could not be reached for comment. It is unclear where
the seed capital actually came from.
</P>
<P>
   Thunor grew rapidly. In half a dozen transactions between 1993
and 1995, it acquired controlling stakes in eight insurance
companies, including some based in Mississippi, Oklahoma, Arkansas
and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   All of the companies sent their money to be invested by Frankel
through his company, Liberty National. The address sounded
impressive, 82 Wall St., Dept. 1105, but it was nothing more than a
mail drop. Harwell said Hackney was not aware of that fact.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's Liberty National appeared to be doing an outstanding
job managing Franklin's assets, according to financial statements
the securities firm sent to Hackney. When Franklin needed money
back for some reason, Liberty National readily provided it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was every appearance of legitimacy,'' Harwell said. They
thought Frankel ``was a guru,'' he said. The companies' statements
from Liberty National showed they were earning outsized returns on
simple-sounding investments in U.S. government bonds _ performance
that would have been astounding from Wall Street's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty National was operating from Frankel's mansion in
Greenwich. He moved to the wealthy New York suburb in 1991, around
the same time he plunged into the insurance business. According to
associates and neighbors, Frankel converted his home into a
full-fledged trading floor, with 80 computers, satellite dishes and
direct links to the New York Stock Exchange. He later bought two
other residences in the area.
</P>
<P>
   But the major splash Frankel made had little to do with his
reputed trading prowess.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon in August 1997, Arnold Courier, an elderly
Greenwich resident, heard a woman's screams echo through Lake
Avenue. The commotion seemed to be coming from the home of a
reclusive neighbor that he knew as Martin King, another alias for
Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Courier said, he and other neighbors learned that
something horrible had happened at 881 Lake Ave.
</P>
<P>
   A woman had hanged herself. Police arrived on the scene to find
Frances Burge, a heavy-set 22-year-old, lying dead on the ground
outside the house.
</P>
<P>
   The death was ruled a suicide. Days later, when the Couriers
read about what had happened in the local newspaper, they asked
their lawyer, Gregory Saum, to contact the police to tell the story
of the chilling screams. Saum said he later contacted the Drug
Enforcement Administration, fearing that the death may have been
related narcotics activity. DEA agents came to the neighborhood and
asked questions. The agency's inquiry does not appear to have led
to any action. A spokeswoman for the agency said it does not
confirm or deny the existence of any non-public investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is among the many bizarre events that unfolded at
the Frankel houses on Lake Avenue throughout much of the 1990s, as
Frankel used the money that the government now says was stolen to
create a lavish lifestyle. Interviews with people who knew him and
visited his homes paint a vivid picture of a reclusive and paranoid
man, obsessed with his physical safety.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel turned his properties into armed camps, posting
gun-toting guards, and erecting a 6-foot metal fence complete with
cameras and flood-lights perched on top.
</P>
<P>
   But associates also described a man who had trouble meeting
women and who scoured the Internet and placed ads in the Village
Voice in search of dates. Some of the women who befriended him were
from far-flung locations, like Switzerland, Alaska and Russia, the
associates said. Several ended up living in Greenwich homes that
Frankel rented for them, for prices ranging from $4,000 to $10,000
a month, according to local real-estate experts.
</P>
<P>
   Pornography and sexual fetishes were prominent features of the
house. According to police reports, during a search of the house
following the death of Ms. Burge, authorities discovered a leather
riding crop, ropes and sadomasochistic literature and videos.
Similar items were found by police following Frankel's
disappearance, along with a number of pornographic videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   When police interviewed him about Ms. Burge's death, he spoke
openly about how he found women in personal ads, invited them to
his home and often paid them to live with him or nearby. ``The
girls do not get paid a salary, but I give them money as they need
it,'' he told the police.
</P>
<P>
   To some who knew him, Frankel seemed odd rather than dangerous.
These people described him as a compulsive talker, who flitted from
topic to topic. They said he was a compulsively fussy eater who had
two live-in chefs who worked around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   But some neighbors said they worried about what was going on at
Frankel's Lake Avenue residences. The driveway bristled with fleets
of BMWs and Mercedes Benzes, as people traipsed in and out of the
Lake Avenue homes 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions erupted. In one case, when Frankel's fence cut off a
public riding trail, the director of the Greenwich Riding and
Trails Association, Donna Nives, said that she rang the doorbell at
881 Lake Ave., only to hear an electronic recorded voice: ``Who are
you and what do you want?'' She fled.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   COURTING CATHOLICS
</P>
<P>
   Though he was raised Jewish and expressed fervently pro-Israel
political views to friends, Frankel aggressively courted the
Catholic Church and the Vatican religious hierarchy beginning last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of his involvement with Catholic priests and the
Vatican differ, but one thing seems certain: Frankel promised
lavish financial contributions to Catholic charities in return for
support from their leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel told the priests he met with that his interests were
purely charitable. But from the moment last August when the Saint
Francis of Assisi Foundation was founded in the British Virgin
Islands with the motto ``To Serve and Help the Poor and Alleviate
Suffering,'' he used it as a vehicle for business transactions.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear why. One explanation advanced by associates of
Frankel is that a foundation backed by the Vatican might lend him
credibility in buying additional insurance companies that would
keep his scheme alive. Others suspect that he may also have seen an
advantage to creating another layer between himself and the
companies he controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his motives, he pursued his quarry with ardor. He
stacked the shelves of the library in his Greenwich home with
Catholic literature, including histories of the saints and papal
encyclicals, visitors to his home said. He familiarized himself
with the life of St. Francis of Assisi, renowned for helping the
poor. He told people he had repeatedly watched the Franco
Zefferelli movie about St. Francis.
</P>
<P>
   The books and the knowledge of the saints helped Frankel win the
trust of Thomas A. Bolan, a New York lawyer and supporter of
Catholic causes who became a foundation trustee. Frankel told
Bolan, who was the law partner of the late Roy Cohn, that he
planned to give at least $50 million to Catholic charities
immediately, and wanted Bolan's help in arranging an audience with
senior Catholic clerics to discuss the gifts, said Bolan's lawyer,
Maurice R. Nessen.
</P>
<P>
   Bolan introduced Frankel to another well-connected American
Catholic, the Rev. Peter Jacobs, who would also become a trustee of
Frankel's foundation. Jacobs, despite having had run-ins with the
Catholic church hierarchy in America, had connections in Rome,
where he lives in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jacobs who introduced Frankel to his most important
religious contact, Colagiovanni, 80, who serves as president of the
Monitor Ecclesiasticus Foundation, an educational organization that
has ties to the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Colagiovanni, now retired, had served as a judge on an important
church tribunal, the Roman Rota. As president of the Monitor
Ecclesiasticus, he served at the behest of the Vatican Curia, or
Senate. Vatican officials said there was no connection between the
Monitor organization and the Vatican but declined to answer further
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Colagionvanni recalls being impressed with Frankel's
determination to help the poor, as well as the securities trader's
knowledge of St. Francis of Assisi. ``If I cannot trust the
Catholic Church, who can I trust?'' Colagionvanni recalls Frankel
asking him.
</P>
<P>
   The Church officials say they were also dazzled by Frankel's
personal generosity. While negotiating with the Vatican, he bought
Bolan tickets on the Concorde, and flew Jacobs across the Atlantic
in first-class cabins after the priest said he declined offers to
fly on Frankel's private jet. When Frankel learned that Bolan's son
was dying of multiple sclerosis, he paid for a nurse to attend to
the son at home, Bolan's lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The courtship paid dividends. Jacobs and Colagiovanni arranged
for the St. Francis of Assisi Foundation to have access to an
account at the Instituto per le Opere di Religione, the Vatican
bank, which is jealously guarded and off-limits to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most helpful to Frankel were two affidavits, drafted
by Frankel's lawyers and signed by Colagiovanni, several people
directly involved in the process confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The first, issued last November, claimed that the St. Francis of
Assisi Foundation was an organization within the Holy See, meaning
that it carried the imprimatur of the pope.
</P>
<P>
   A second, issued three months later, backed off that assertion.
It said the Monitor Ecclesiasticus Foundation contributed $1
billion to the Saint Francis of Assisi Foundation, and further
claimed that the money emanated from ``various Roman Catholic
tribunals and Roman Catholic cultural institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Both statements are now widely doubted. Colagionvanni calls the
affidavits a ``mistake'' and ascribes his willingness to sign to
misplaced trust in Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   But though Frankel clearly expected the religious overlay he put
on his operation to help him expand his empire rapidly, the
purported link to the Vatican ties did not, apparently, do him much
good. They might even have contributed to his demise.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the St. Francis of Assisi Foundation bought control
of Thunor Trust and, by extension, Frankel's growing network of
insurance companies. Frankel, however, quickly discovered that
invoking the name of the Vatican raised red flags everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations for two new purchases of insurance companies, one
in Colorado and another in Washington State, fell through after
Frankel arranged for the St. Francis foundation to become the
purchaser instead of Thunor Trust. Foreign ownership, prohibited by
some state insurance regulators, was one stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Francis was telling us that they were ultimately
controlled by the Vatican. But if that was the case, then they
could not buy Capital Life,'' said Joseph L. Blattner, president of
the Capital Life Insurance Company of Denver, which negotiated with
Frankel's organization for nearly six months before the talks
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, by late 1998, regulators were beginning to catch up
with Frankel. Tennessee state examiners questioned why the Franklin
insurance companies that they oversaw had placed so much money in
one pot _ Frankel's Liberty _ and worried about rapid turnover of
the Liberty accounts. Liberty reported trading volume in 1998 of
about $14 billion, in exchange for earning a negligible $40,000 in
commissions. Frankel dodged a bullet when he transferred assets
back to Tennessee before a deadline.
</P>
<P>
   He had a harder time fending off Mississippi officials a few
months later. Regulators in that state questioned the same trading
patterns. But Franklin's answers made matters worse. They revealed
that the change in ownership from Thunor to St. Francis of Assisi
had not been reported, as required, to local authorities. That is
what prompted the late April gathering in Jackson, where many of
Frankel's colleagues saw him in person for the only time.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show that Frankel may have known the end was near.
Even before that meeting, Franklin subsidiaries began transferring
large sums to Liberty National or other accounts directly
controlled by Frankel, including $161 million from Mississippi
insurance companies and $117 million from affiliated companies in
Missouri. The court records suggests that most of that money was
transferred into foreign bank accounts by early May.
</P>
<P>
   On May 7, two days after firefighters responded to a fire caused
by burning documents in the Greenich mansion, Hackney, Jacobs,
Bolan, Colagiovanni, legal officers at Akin, Gump, regulators in
several states and many others were told that Frankel had
disappeared without a trace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all seemed so good, like Brooke Astor,'' Jacobs said,
referring to the New York benefactress and reflecting on his ties
to Frankel. ``Only he turned out to be the devil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
