<HEADLINE>
EX-CLAIMER BUDROYALE CLOSES IN ON $1 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ One evening last fall, as they toasted
Budroyale's California Cup Classic victory at Santa Anita, owner
Jeffrey Sengara offered trainer Ted West Jr. the sweetest deal this
side of Cal Worthington.
</P>
<P>
   West had pointed out that Budroyale was creeping up on $1
million in earnings, no mean feat for a vagabond claiming horse
with a severe Lasix dependency. West also had mentioned something
about needing to replace the beat-up truck he was driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get this horse to the $1 million mark, I'm going to
have to buy you a car,'' replied Sengara, remembering how his
Pacific Northwest neighbor Mike Pegram made a similar promise to
Bob Baffert regarding the sprinter Letthebighossroll.
</P>
<P>
   Now the only question seems to be... stick or automatic?
</P>
<P>
   Budroyale will go into Sunday's $1 million Hollywood Gold Cup
needing just $22,690 to reach seven figures. Seeing that there are
only four entrants in the race, and fourth place is worth $60,000,
all the 6-year-old gelding has to do is finish the 1\ miles and his
trainer will have all the horsepower he can handle.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, West and Sengara are hoping to do a lot better than
fourth. And since the illness of would-be favorite Old Trieste left
Budroyale and jockey Garrett Gomez the likely pacesetters, plenty
of objective analysts believe they can pull down the $600,000
winner's purse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if Old Trieste ran his race, we were all running for
second,'' West said this week, referring to Budroyale and his Gold
Cup opponents Real Quiet, Puerto Madero and Malek. ``Now, I think
we have a legitimate chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Hollywood Gold Cup is a classic race for older horses,
and its winners include Seabiscuit, Citation, Swaps, Round Table,
Native Diver, Ack Ack, Affirmed and Cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Could its 60th running be won by a son of Cee's Tizzy who has
run for claiming prices between $32,000 and $80,000 15 times, who
didn't win a stakes race until his 27th start, who has competed for
six trainers and raced under a dozen jockeys?
</P>
<P>
   Well, if ex-claimer Charismatic can win the Kentucky Derby and
Preakness, then Budroyale can win the Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sengara claimed him for $50,000 at Santa Anita in February
1998, the gelding has earned nearly $700,000, winning five stakes
in 12 tries including the Grade II Mervyn LeRoy in May and the
California-bred Super Diamond two weeks ago. This has to be the
most profitable claim of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Not many horses show improvement at the advanced ages of 5 and
6, but Budroyale has done it. Sengara credits Ted West, his trainer
of record until April, and Ted Jr., who's running the barn while
his father is suspended for a medication violation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Wests, Budroyale this year has been able to avoid the
bouts of pulmonary bleeding that held him back in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always had the fundamentals there. He's always had the
athletic ability and the heart,'' said Sengara, who first noticed
Budroyale when he beat 1996 Kentucky Derby winner Grindstone in an
allowance race that February, and didn't need to be talked into
claiming him when West suggested it two years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a tremendous amount of credit has to be given to the
Wests for isolating the things that needed to be taken care of to
get him to this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Budroyale ran in the Gold Cup last year and finished fifth
behind Skip Away. He won't finish fifth this year _ and not only
because it's a four-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a much better horse this year,'' the younger West
said.
</P>
<P>
   This would be the biggest win in the careers of jockey Gomez,
27, trainer Ted Jr., 26, and owner Sengara, 29.
</P>
<P>
   The effervescent Sengara inherited his Vancouver lumber business
and his love of horse racing from his late father, who had horses
with the elder West. Now Sengara is passing his enthusiasm on to
his two children. Budroyale is helping.
</P>
<P>
   Sengara said his 2-year-old son Kevin shows no interest in
watching Barney, the purple dinosaur. He'd rather watch videotapes
of Budroyale, the bay horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of fathers have baseball or some other passion they
share,'' Sengara said. ``It looks like we have horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever a day that stands out in my life, other than
the day I married my wife and the days my two wonderful kids were
born, February 15 (1998) is the day that changed my life,'' Sengara
said. ``Bud has just put a lot of confidence into everyone that's
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   But can little Kevin afford his share of the car payments?
</P>
<P>
   Sengara laughs about his promise to West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much to my relief, he went out and bought a new car earlier
this year, so maybe I can get away with giving him a little rust
bucket,'' Sengara said. ``I didn't tell him what year the car would
be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's hedging,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. The last rust bucket Sengara bought turned into a
Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   That's Budroyale. &UR; !dlim! &LR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
