u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-US-CHAMPIONSHIP25     06-24 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-US-CHAMPIONSHIP25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Krummenacker eyes top-miler role
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ On any weekday afternoon, the track at Georgia
Tech resembles the warmup field at the Olympic Games. Gold medalist
Derrick Adkins and his quick understudy, Angelo Taylor, are honing
their stride pattern over the 400-meter hurdles, while gold
medalist Derek Mills is running repeat 400s. NCAA runner-up Andria
King works to improve her standing in the 100-meter hurdles, while
defending U.S. champ Tisha Waller is practicing the high jump.
</P>
<P>
   They all dream of Sydney, and competing in next summer's Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, does David Krummenacker, an unassuming, yet confident
young man. Only Krummenacker also aspires to fill the void _ if not
this year, then by the summer of 2000 _ as the next great American
miler.
</P>
<P>
   Krummenacker is a somewhat unexpected candidate for such a lofty
role, having fancied himself an 800-meter runner before graduating
from Tech last spring. His speed has held up nicely over the longer
distance, though. Last season, he was ranked No. 5 in the U.S. at
1500 meters and figures to contend for a title here at the USA
Outdooor Track and Field Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Even though bothered by a strained calf muscle the past week,
the 24-year-old advanced from the semifinal round Thursday night,
finishing fourth in his qualifying heat in 3 minutes, 45.85
seconds. His top competition in Saturday's final is likely to come
from Steve Holman _ generally regarded as the top American miler,
but a runner who has a mental block when it comes to the national
championships and Olympic trials _ and defending national champion
Seneca Lassiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. is really looking for an up-and-coming miler,'' said
Krummenacker, three-time ACC champ in both the 800 and 1500 meters.
``For a long time, people thought Steve Holman would be the guy. I
think I'm capable of being the guy. I'm well built (6-2, 170) for
the 1500. I have the proper speed to hang with all of the top
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The best part is he's grudgingly come to accept that his future
rests in the 1500, not the 800.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's been an on-going conversion. The 800 has always been
his signature race. That's what he ran at the 1996 Olympics Trials,
advancing to the semis. And it wasn't until he showed up here
Tuesday that it became official, he would give in to the preachings
of his coach, Alan Drosky, and bypass the 800 for the 1500.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely arrived on the national scene, and I'd say
he's very close on the international scene,'' Drosky said. ``I can
see him running world-class times this summer in Europe, in the
3:33 range (for the 1500). My guess is he's about a year away from
being truly on the world-class level. I think he can be ready for
the Olympics, I really do. What transpires this summer will factor
into his Sydney chances. Krummenacker needs the experience of
running in national and world championships at 1500 meters, along
with landing invitations to top European races this summer _ which
is why a strong showing here is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about experience,'' Krummenacker said. ``The 800 is
over so quick. You're down to 200 meters and everybody is gunning
(for the finish). The 1500 is a lot more tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   The 800 has evolved into almost an all-out sprint, led by world
record-holder Wilson Kipketer (1:41.11). Krummenacker has speed to
match the top American 800-meter athletes, but on the international
scene his best hope to make an impact is in the longer distance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
