u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT &LR;      06-24 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS FOCUS ON MARLINS, NOT SCOREBOARD, AND EARN A SWEEP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Fla., Canada)   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mets agreed beforehand not to watch the scoreboard, not to
worry about what the National League East-leading Atlanta Braves
were up to in their afternoon game against Montreal. For most of
the afternoon Livan Hernandez and the Florida Marlins made sure the
Mets paid attention to what was unfolding Thursday on the dirt and
grass of Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Until the eighth inning, Hernandez, the Cuban right-hander,
looked a lot better than his numbers. He blew fastballs by Mets
hitters for four strikeouts, used nasty breaking stuff to pitch out
of jams and even led off the seventh inning with a double and
scored to tie the game at 2-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But much to the delight of a sun-soaked crowd of 29,567, the
Mets once more came up with counterpunch hitting, this time from
the bats of John Olerud and Robin Ventura in the eighth, to hand
the Marlins their ninth consecutive loss, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Mets' 14th victory in 17 games. They have won six
consecutive series and are 10 games over .500 (41-31) for the first
time this season.
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves' 3-2 victory in 11 innings over Montreal, the
Mets remained three games behind the Braves in second place as they
headed to Atlanta for the first of six games tonight against the
Braves (44-28) in the next 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the team in front of us, and those games are very
important to win,'' Ventura, who was 3 for 4 with two runs batted
in, said.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who has hit .358 in the last 20 games, drove in the
game-winning run _ it was his eighth r.b.i in the last 10 games _
after Olerud floated a one-out double down the left-field line
against Hernandez, who was tiring in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   While manager Bobby Valentine of the Mets replaced Olerud with
the pinch-runner Luis Lopez, Manager John Boles of the Marlins left
Hernandez in to face Ventura. It was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Ventura had singled down the right-field line to
drive in Edgardo Alfonzo and tie the score at 1-1. Brian McRae then
hit a sacrifice fly to left field to score Olerud, who had reached
first on an error by the third baseman Mike Lowell, and the Mets
led, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But the Marlins tied the score in the seventh inning when the
Mets' starter, Orel Hershiser, was replaced by Greg McMichael. If
Hershiser was erratic _ he allowed six hits and one run with five
strikeouts and three walks _ then McMichael was plain ineffective.
He gave up two hits and a run in a third of an inning before being
replaced by the left-hander Dennis Cook.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the eighth, with Lopez on second, Ventura sliced a
fastball that Hernandez was trying keep away from him just beyond
the reach of the shortstop Alex Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking for something to put the barrel of the bat
on,'' said Ventura, who chased Hernandez from the game and dropped
his record to 3-7 despite allowing just two earned runs in seven
and a third innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' late-inning dramatics came as the Shea scoreboard
showed the Expos beating the Braves, 2-1, in the ninth inning.
Before the game, the Mets' ace, Al Leiter, said his teammates knew
it was too early to begin watching the scoreboard. He said it was
appropriate only after the second week of August.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think they know we're going to be there all year,'' he
said of the Braves. ``We were last year and we're a better team
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has a case, especially from the pitcher's mound. Cook
threw an inning and two-thirds, gave up one hit and struck out
three to improve his record to 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   John Franco took over the National League lead in saves, with
his 19th, by pitching a scoreless ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting the pitching and real clutch hitting,'' Cook
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are peeking ahead at the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he had not heard much talk in the clubhouse about
their rivals and confessed to only glancing at the scoreboard at
the end of the game to discover the Braves had tied the Expos, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   In the clubhouse, however, the players were searching for
television sets and providing one other updates of the Atlanta
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chipper Jones knocked one with two outs,'' reported Turk
Wendell to a couple players shaking their heads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But beginning Friday night the Mets have a chance to alter the
standing themselves, even if, according to Leiter, it is too early
to matter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
