<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      06-24 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY GIVE UP? KNICKS SHOOTING TO MAKE HISTORY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two months ago, the Knicks were a cautionary tale,
not characters for a storybook. They were caught in the political
Garden games between Ernie Grunfeld and coach Jeff Van Gundy, mired
in discord and performing selfishly on the floor. They were an
embarrassment, a collection of misfits assembled for a league-high
$68 million, a team of stars on the verge of a humiliating
collapse. They became an allegory on how money corrupts.
</P>
<P>
   But something as priceless as pride kicked in, and the Knicks
turned doom into destiny and paid back their debt. They won for the
ticket-holders who came to see them and for the fans who wanted to
love them. They filled the ownership coffers by stretching out a
profitable playoff run and gave the league a big-market draw for
the National Basketball Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   There is certainly nothing to be embarrassed about, even though
the Knicks face elimination Friday night in Game 5 at Madison
Square Garden. No one has ever come back to win the finals after
being down, 3-1, so no honor would be lost in a defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But after all the games the Knicks have played in pain, played
short-handed and played in defiance of logic, why give in now? Why
not live for one victory and give good karma a chance? That's all
Van Gundy asked of his players when he met them before practice
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they're only bound by what they believe can still
be accomplished,'' Van Gundy said. ``If they believe that since no
one else has ever done this, that it can't be done, then that will
be reflected in our play. As I told them, no eighth seed has ever
made it here, either. So history doesn't have to hamper us. All we
have to do is win one home game. Can we win one home game? Then can
we go to San Antonio and get one road game? And then you're playing
the ultimate game. I just made that sound a heck of a lot easier
than it is, obviously. But that's the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as I said to them, you don't ever want this, but who's to
say that sometime soon we may not be the team that suffers an
injury that hurts you? It could happen. And the longer you play it
out, the more chances you give yourself to be the beneficiary of
good fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan and David Robinson had a healthy glow Thursday after
combining for 42 points, 35 rebounds and 7 blocked shots to give
the Spurs a 96-89 victory in Game 4 on Wednesday. The Knicks pulled
to within a point in the last six minutes but were too fatigued,
emotionally drained and undermanned. The Knicks could have lived
with the dominance of the Twin Towers, but not with what Avery
Johnson did. Every time he penetrated past Charlie Ward or a big
man on a mismatch, he broke down the Knicks' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pick-and-roll coverage was an abomination,'' Van Gundy
said. ``It was more communication and breakdowns rather than
getting picked apart on great plays. Avery Johnson was in the lane
all night off pick and rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't our offense. It was our defense and rebounding. You
can't get outrebounded by 15 and win.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the answer?
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have the right spirit, but their bodies are on the
last-call round at the bar. They are down to five players at full
strength. With one day of rest on his sprained right knee, Larry
Johnson may be helpless to slow Duncan or give much more than his
5-point, 6-rebound effort of Game 4. With a sprained left knee that
felt only moderately better Thursday, Chris Childs will be hard
pressed to run around with Avery Johnson when Ward gets tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very complementary to each other,'' Ward said of Childs,
who played just seven minutes in Game 4. ``It's like taking your
wife away. Sometimes, you feel a little loss. I fought through it
Wednesday night, but hopefully Chris will be able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   There is hope. But there has to be a plan, too. The Knicks will
have to show more discipline in their defensive rotations or watch
Robinson and Duncan out rebound them as a team again. Allan Houston
and Latrell Sprewell have to make better decisions when
double-teamed and have their teammates knock down their open shots.
Bad knee and all, Larry Johnson has to be one of those offensive
threats to complement the points Marcus Camby can give.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my Spurs got a little something on me with those 3s,''
said Larry Johnson who was 0 for 3 from 3-point range Wednesday
night. ``They're rotating on me. It's one thing for a 6-8 guy to be
rotating to you, it's another for a 7-footer to do it. They're
doing a heck of a job of bothering that shot, but I'm doing a heck
of a job of missing it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have been missing up close, as well. Layups have
never been so hard for the Knicks with the looming presence of
Robinson and Duncan in the paint. The Spurs, after being beaten by
Houston's midrange jumpers in Game 3, were able to funnel the
Knicks inside where Robinson and Duncan lurked in Game 4. The
repetition of blocked shots seemed to frustrate the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are averse to major change, if things get
desperate, the Knicks might try the big backcourt combination of
Houston and Sprewell, using a lineup that Van Gundy sarcastically
refers to as the ``panacea'' for their problems.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the only cure for their dire predicament is a
victory at the Garden. All the motivation they need is the fear of
the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see them jumping around and cutting down our
nets in the Garden,'' said Camby, whose 20-point, 13-rebound effort
made an impact in Game 4. ``Our fans don't want to see it, and we
definitely don't want to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks want to see San Antonio. To make that trip, the they
will have to scrape the residue from a bone-dry tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think fatigue is a factor,'' Van Gundy said. ``I can't sit
here and say we are not tired and not tired within the game and not
less than what we'd like to be health-wise. I think all of those
factors can hurt your mental state. And that's what I addressed
with our team, is that we owe it to ourselves to win tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   They have paid their debt to everyone else after a season that
even the Spurs had to admit seemed ripped from the pages of a
motivational manual.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about perseverance,'' Avery Johnson said.
``Those guys can persevere. They've been weathering storms all year
long. They need to write a book.''
</P>
<P>
   A storybook rather than a cautionary tale. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
