<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-COCA-COLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE BOTTLING SITE IN FRANCE GIVEN CLEAN BILL OF HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.) (Eds: See also COCA-COLA-EUROPE) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNKIRK, France _ French authorities lifted a ban Thursday on
canned Coca-Cola soft drinks produced at a bottling plant here,
saying they had found no evidence of contamination to explain an
outbreak of nausea by people who drank them in Belgium early this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Coca-Cola Enterprises, the bottling company that is
about 40 percent owned by Coca-Cola Co., said the ensuing health
scare, and bans on Coke products in France and Belgium, would
reduce the bottling company's earnings by $60 million in the second
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The bottling company officials, saying they hoped the crisis was
now over, attributed the problems to a Dutch pallet supplier they
would not identify. They said it had supplied them with the wooden
pallets on which stacks of cans were shipped to Belgium. But
between February and April this year, they said, the Dutch company
treated 800 of the pallets with a type of disinfectant compound
banned in food production that could have rubbed off on some cans
and made them smell bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain customers in Belgium were made queasy by this bad
odor,'' said Dominique Reiniche, president of Coca-Cola Enterprises
SA, the company's French bottler.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Schimberg, president and chief executive of Coca-Cola
Enterprises Inc., the parent bottling company in Atlanta, said,
``All the affected pallets have been removed from the plant and
from the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite assurances by the French health authorities and
government officials in Paris Thursday that all the cans they had
tested were free of impurities, outside or inside, and had caused
nobody in France to become sick, the chief prosecutor in Dunkirk,
Francois Muguet, was continuing an investigation into whether rat
poison on soft-drink cans could explain why some drinkers fell ill.
</P>
<P>
   Marylise Lebranchu, the French consumer minister, said earlier
Thursday that no traces of rat poison had been found on any cans
produced here. ``We have not been able to establish a correlation
between illnesses in France and the beverage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Reiniche commented: ``There is no rat-poison problem. I
would say we'll let justice take its course.''
</P>
<P>
   The French government lifted its ban Thursday morning on sales
of Coke, Sprite and Fanta produced at the sprawling, squeaky-clean
plant on the outskirts of Dunkirk. On Wednesday, the Belgian
authorities ended a 10-day ban on the same beverages there.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the conveyor belts here were rattling with trains of
red cans that were about to be double-stacked, 16 feet high, on
wooden pallets that make it easier for forklifts to distribute
them.
</P>
<P>
   The French food safety agency certified Coca-Cola products as
safe Thursday morning, citing the transitory symptoms reported by
consumers in France and the few people affected.
</P>
<P>
   But privately, French officials said they were not impressed
with attempts by Coca-Cola to explain what might have gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A Dutch toxicologist hired by Coca-Cola reported earlier this
week that the pallets had been treated with a compound similar in
some respects to creosote, a wood preservative that can contain the
strong petroleum distillates phenol or cresol and is used to keep
fungi and insects from attacking railroad ties or fence posts.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vincent Garry, director of environmental medicine and
pathology at the University of Minnesota, said that phenol- or
cresol-based preservative compounds could produce headaches or
nausea in people who came in contact with them, particularly in a
closed or hot space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the dose that makes the difference,'' he said, and large
doses or chronic exposure could produce nerve inflammation, skin
allergies or even cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The tightly guarded gray plant, behind barbed wire fences on the
southern edge of Dunkirk, has produced 11 billion cans of
carbonated soft drinks since it started operations in 1989, as many
as 8 million a day. Schimberg said Coca-Cola Enterprises had
invested more than $100 million in it and said it had 240 full-time
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them, like Eric van den Put, a Dutch truck driver who
was waiting Thursday to pick up a load of soft-drink cans to take
them to the Netherlands, were hoping that the trouble with the
company's products would just blow over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't found a thing wrong with Coke anywhere, have
they?'' van den Put said as he backed his trailer up to the
warehouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
