<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-RIVER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED LEGISLATION AIMS TO IMPROVE RECREATION, RESTORE HABITAT
ALONG MISSOURI RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Let's restore the original, wild Big Muddy
-- at least a bit, says one U.S. senator. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The dams, the levees, the channeling of the Missouri River have
all served a purpose, says U.S. Sen. Bob Kerrey, a Nebraska
Democrat. But wouldn't it be nice, Kerrey asked Thursday, to have a
river to fish in, to canoe in, to picnic by. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey on Thursday introduced a legislative package of river
reforms -- the Missouri River Valley Improvement Act -- that, if
approved, would allocate $320 million over the next 10 years to
improve recreation and restore fish and wildlife habitat along the
length of the Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Missouri River Valley Improvement Act of 1999 will help to
restore and improve our access and enjoyment of the river, and will
provide vital economic, recreational and educational opportunities
for everyone who lives along and visits this great river, the crown
jewel of the Midwest,'' Kerrey said Thursday on the Senate floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation is also timed to prepare for, and take
advantage of, increased interest in the Missouri that is expected
to come with the 200th anniversary of Lewis and Clark's 1804
exploration of the river. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the proposed new programs: channel enhancements that would
create more habitat for fish and wildlife; a federal study of ways
to restore 25 percent of the lost flood plain habitat in Missouri,
Iowa, Kansas and Nebraska; promotion of riverfront developments;
and a study of replenishing the once-vast cottonwood stands along
the upper Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest-ticket item is $188.8 million for long-term
scientific monitoring of the river. That would be overseen by the
U.S. Geological Survey's center in Columbia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kit Bond, a Missouri Republican, may be key to the proposed
legislation's fate. Last year, Bond proposed his own legislation to
improve fish and wildlife habitat on the lower Missouri. And Bond
is among the Republican leaders on environmental issues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bond's staff said Thursday that the senator had yet to review
the Kerrey bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such river issues are so controversial that Bond would prefer to
receive feedback from river interests before deciding whether to
support the proposed legislation, said Dan Hubbard, Bond's
spokesman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey's bill also would amend the Flood Control Act of 1944 to
give the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers new authority to protect,
enhance and restore fish and wildlife on the Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The construction of dams and levees may have aided flood control
and navigation, Kerrey said, but that work also has reduced habitat
and squandered opportunities for recreation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bill also proposed the construction of Lewis and Clark
interpretive centers along the river, although Kerrey didn't
specify their locations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups have railed for years about the way man has
changed the Missouri in the last half-century -- channeling,
cinching, dredging, shortening and damming it. As a result, they
contend, most of the river's natural life -- its fish, flora and
animals -- has been lost, not to mention an opportunity to attract
more tourists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Rivers, a national environmental group that has long
advocated changes in the Missouri's operation to benefit fish and
wildlife, supports the Kerrey bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to put fish and wildlife on equal footing with other
river issues,'' said Chad Smith of American Rivers. ``This bill
helps strike a good balance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the bill should have a good chance of success because
it doesn't tackle the most controversial issue on the Missouri --
the control of its flow. The flow issue pits downstream barge
interests, which want high flows for as long as possible, against
upstream states that want to hold the water in recreation lakes
during the summer, and environmental advocates that want the Corps
of Engineers' controls to mimic nature -- allowing the river to
rise in the spring and shrink in the summer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The corps in October is expected to issue its latest proposal
for controlling the river's flow. The corps has delayed issuing its
plan, hoping that the Missouri River Basin Association, which
includes representatives of the Indian tribes and states in the
Missouri River valley, will reach a consensus on the flow issue,
said Richard Opper, the association's executive director. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The association last year assembled its members and other
interested parties and reached consensus on a number of new
programs to improve fish and wildlife habitat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation includes a lot of things that the Missouri
River Basin Association has already agreed to,'' Opper said.
``There's a lot in it that we would support.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the proposed legislation may help the corps because
it will have a legal responsibility to take steps to recover
endangered species that remain in the Missouri, Opper said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a growing awareness of these issues,'' Opper said,
``and I think Congress will be supportive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
