<DOCNO> NYT19990624.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPREWELL-HOUSTON-     06-24 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPREWELL-HOUSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNICKS' OPTIONS DWINDLE TO SPREWELL AND HOUSTON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks have tweaked the lineup and shifted the
load with each bit of attrition. They needed more scoring, so
Latrell Sprewell became a starter again. The team's stamina
flagged, so Marcus Camby got his first start.
</P>
<P>
   They found new offensive patterns without Patrick Ewing and
unearthed a different vein of scoring with each new casualty.
</P>
<P>
   But now as they cradle desperation _ with Larry Johnson's knee
wearing down to a nub and Chris Childs the latest to be slowed by
injury _ just how much more can the Knicks hope to wring from their
exhausted offense Friday night in Game 5 of the National Basketball
Association finals?
</P>
<P>
   Even if Camby can match his effort in Game 4 on Wednesday night
_ when his 20 points made up for Johnson's lack of production _ and
even if coach Jeff Van Gundy decides to put Sprewell and Allan
Houston in the backcourt together, can the Knicks find enough
points to overcome the dominance of Tim Duncan and David Robinson?
Especially if the rest of the Spurs' starters perform as they did
in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spree and I are both prepared for it,'' Houston said of the
possibility of their being backcourt mates, with Sprewell playing
point guard, as the Knicks try to stay alive in a series they trail
three games to one. ``We're comfortable with it. We feel we can be
effective if called upon.''
</P>
<P>
   What has become obvious during the post-season is that even when
the Knicks get significant scoring from a third source _ as they
did from Johnson in Game 3 and Camby in Game 4 _ Sprewell and
Houston are the only reliable offensive options Van Gundy has.
</P>
<P>
   When the Knicks' defense failed in Game 4 _ as the Spurs plucked
every rebound off the rim like blooms from the vine _ the Knicks
had to go shot for shot with San Antonio. With double-teams on
Houston and Sprewell forcing the Knicks to penetrate, they played
into the Spurs' strength.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks drew fouls and shot 28 free throws, but they were
also hurt by the Spurs' 9 blocked shots. At the end of the Spurs'
96-89 victory, with Sprewell and Houston reluctant to drive to the
basket and settling for jumpers, there were simply not enough good
shots left in their weary bodies to snatch a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our aggression going to the basket was good,'' Van Gundy said
Thursday. ``We went to the basket and I thought we went hard. We
got to the free throw line some. They got some blocks. That's just
part of it. If you're not going to go there, you're not going to
get to the free throw line and we need to get to the line. Duncan
and Robinson did a great job protecting the paint, but offense
wasn't really our problem last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense was. But the Knicks' offense could not make up for it.
Certainly, Sprewell and Houston, who played 46 minutes each, were
fatigued late in the fourth quarter when the Knicks trailed by only
a few points. In the last five minutes of the game, Sprewell and
Houston missed seven jumpers, one a 3-point attempt that Sprewell
rushed to take in anticipation of a double team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't attack them down the stretch,'' Sprewell said. ``We
have to mix it up. All of the shots weren't bad shots. We've got to
take some of those jump shots and take it to the basket. When
they're doubling us, somebody is open. We have to consistently find
that open guy. And it's up to that guy to make those shots. We have
to stop these guys. We're in low 40s and they're in high 40s. We
have to find a way to bring that down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell had 26 points on 9-of-22 shooting, 40.9 percent from
the field. That may sound low, but Sprewell shot 41.5 percent from
the field in the regular season. Houston had 20 points on 7-of-18
shooting, 38.9 percent, just below his 41.8 percent regular season
average.
</P>
<P>
   They can have breakout games, as Houston did in Game 3 with 34
points, but Sprewell and Houston are doing about all that can be
expected from them. With so many of their teammates withering, they
will have to do more of it if the Knicks hope to survive for
another game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are going to back off, I'm going to shoot the
jumper,'' Houston said. ``We have to be aggressive offensively. We
can get into the penalty early. Sometimes we can get our shot off
before the double-team comes. The key for us is to make the correct
pass out of the double-teams and get our guys good looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope to mine another lode of offensive production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
