<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMPLETE ROBINSON LOOKING FOR VALIDATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everyone, besides the Knicks and their faithful fans,
seems to be gearing up for the validation of David Robinson. It is
as if all his individual achievements _ his placement in 1996 among
the 50 best players in National Basketball Association history, his
Most Valuable Player award in 1994-95 and his eight All-Star Game
appearances _ will finally be legitimized if the San Antonio Spurs
win the championship this season.
</P>
<P>
   The questions and correlations have begun to border on the
humorous. For instance, Robinson was asked Thursday if he had seen
the movie ``Jerry Maguire.'' After answering yes, he was asked if
the film's climactic moment, in which the sports agent portrayed by
Tom Cruise tells his wife: ``You complete me,'' summed up his
feelings about winning an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not quite,'' Robinson responded with laughter. ``It feels
good, but it doesn't feel that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, one of the most respected and well-rounded players in
the league, said he already feels complete, thank you. An NBA title
will not change his opinion of himself, he said. But that does not
mean he lacks an intense desire to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident Wednesday night, when he displayed a
seldom seen aggression on the offensive backboards, nearly
outrebounding the Knicks by himself in that category. Robinson's
nine offensive rebounds in Game 4, one fewer than the Knicks'
total, helped give the Spurs a 14-10 advantage on the offensive
glass and a 49-34 rebounding advantage over all.
</P>
<P>
   When the close final score (96-89), the Spurs' 17 turnovers and
the basic effectiveness of the Knicks' offense are taken into
account, it is obvious that the Spurs' dominance on the backboards
was the difference in the outcome. That is a credit to Robinson,
who had 17 rebounds, and Tim Duncan, who had 18. Despite San
Antonio's overwhelming height advantage, its sudden supremacy in
rebounding was a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs were outrebounded in each of the first two games and
tied the Knicks with 36 rebounds in Game 3. The Knicks' dominance
had been on the offensive end. They entered Game 4 with a 35-19
advantage on the offensive glass. Robinson had been incredibly
ineffective, grabbing just one offensive rebound through the first
three games.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, when the title the Spurs seemed to be taking for
granted was suddenly in jeopardy, Robinson, 33, went after missed
shots with a ferocity that many have said he does not possess.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was just a monster,'' Spurs Coach Gregg Popovich said.
``I'm so happy for him because he showed a lot of people what he
could do. A lot of people counted him out this year for reasons
that I'm still trying to figure out. But he was absolutely
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all good big men, including the Knicks' Patrick Ewing,
Robinson is judged by more than his statistics and moderate
post-season success. Though his place among the league's best
players is secure, in the eyes of many, he must win a title to join
the elite players.
</P>
<P>
   That criterion has dogged Robinson perhaps more than any of his
contemporaries because of the long-standing view that he is a soft
player, one who might have already won a championship if he had
played with more fire. That notion reached its peak when, after
winning the mvp award in 1995, Robinson was outplayed by Hakeem
Olajuwon when the Houston Rockets eliminated the Spurs in the
Western Conference finals. Robinson is not too proud to admit that
living with that perception has been painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would say something about me that I knew was not
true,'' he said. ``I mean, I'm one of the most competitive people I
know. When people question your desire to be out there on the
floor, that bothers you. It bothered me. So it just gave me a
little bit more fuel to kind of keep coming at it, keep working. So
now it's nice to kind of come to a point where people see that I
can have the personality that I have and still be a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's teammates understand that one more victory will go a
long way in lifting his stature.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Elie recalled a recent conversation with Robinson. ``I
said, `Hey, you can shut a lot of people up, big dog.' He was
excited. He knows he has one more game to win and he knows what's
at stake. This is the only thing that he hasn't accomplished in his
career, and this would be a nice final chapter to a terrific career
he's had.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson understands what a title would mean. ``It gives
justification to all the work, the time that you put in,'' said
Robinson, who has career averages of 25.1 points and 11.5 rebounds.
``You spend all those times in the summer doing your sprints,
running up and down the hill, trying to get your body together, and
it's kind of a closure in that sense. That's where it would really
be a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no. I'm pretty complete before the championship. I didn't
feel incomplete last year, and I don't think I would feel
incomplete without it. It just makes me feel like all that
individual working came to everything. Big deal if you won stuff _
scoring champ, defensive champ _ if it doesn't amount to anything.
Now it's amounting to something good.''
</P>
<P>
   That being, however unfairly, the validation of a great player. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
