<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON RESPONDS TO WALTON 
TELEVISION RATINGS DOWN
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ The horn to signal the end of the interview session
sounded twice, but Larry Johnson kept talking even as his Knicks
teammates were stretching before Thursday's practice. What subjects
so engrossed him? Slaves and Bill Walton.
</P>
<P>
   One actually related to the other. On Sunday, Johnson picked up
a $25,000 fine for his obscene tirade after two National Basketball
Association officials asked him to take part in a mandatory
interview session. Two days later, Johnson compared his Knicks
teammates to ``rebellious slaves.'' In the aftermath of those
comments, Walton, the NBC analyst, called Johnson a disgrace to the
NBA and a sad human being.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was amused at Walton's insights, and delivered a
response as part of a lengthy interview in which he explained his
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that the same Bill Walton that was at UCLA and smoked
pot, a hippie?'' Johnson said. ``If that's the way Bill feels,
that's the way Bill feels. You know what? I respect that. That way
me and Bill know where each other stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like for as long as Bill has been killing me on TV from
what my family and everyone tells me.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson then did his Walton impersonation. He smiled wide while
tilting his head up and down to depict how disingenuous he thought
Walton was when they occasionally pass in the hallways. Then the
smile left his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't come at me like that,'' Johnson said. ``If I'm on fire,
don't spit on me. I won't spit on you. That's respect. You go your
way, and I'll go mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was asked to explain how he could compare himself to a
slave when he has an $84 million contract in his chosen profession.
At that moment, the horn blew and coach Jeff Van Gundy and the team
were waiting for him on the practice floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a minute, Jeffrey,'' Johnson said. ``I ain't getting
fined no more. I might get put out of the league. But let's say
this: No one man can rise above the masses or the condition of his
people. I am privileged and honored by the situation I'm in. No
question, I have an excellent opportunity. And this is a beautiful
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we've made beautiful strides, but what percentage of
black people has made that stride when I go back to my neighborhood
and see the same thing? I'm the only one who came out of my
neighborhood. All of them dead, on drugs, selling drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I supposed to be honored and happy just by my success? Yes,
I am. But I can't deny the fact of what's happened to us over years
and years, and we're still at the bottom of the totem pole. I can't
turn my head to that. That's my point.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson made his point. But some wonder if his controversial
ramblings this week are associated with his frustration over
playing with an injury and struggling to guard Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's guarding a guy who is a lot taller than him,'' Don
Chaney, the Knicks assistant coach, said. ``He's half hurt, and
he's not handling it very well. I think it's getting to him
mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Selena Roberts
</P>
<P>
   Television Ratings Down
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ratings for the National Basketball Association finals
continued to falter during Game 4 of the Knicks-Spurs series, which
produced a 12 Nielsen rating, down by 37 percent from the
comparable game last year, when Chicago played Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Through four games, the 11.3 average rating is down by 35
percent from 17.5 a year ago. The San Antonio market posted a 53.6
rating, New York a 22.6.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the last time the Knicks played in the finals,
against Houston in 1994, this year's rating is down 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Richard Sandomir &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
