<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Less than a week after House Democrats voted
against a gun-control package rather than accept what they said
were soft terms in a measure to regulate gun shows, Rep. Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority leader, seemed to open the door
at least a crack Thursday to some sort of compromise on that point.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday morning, Gephardt suggested that
while he and many other Democrats had insisted on three business
days for gun-show vendors to complete background checks on
customers, a shorter time frame might be acceptable if the checks
were faster.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview late Thursday afternoon, Gephardt said
he did not intend to imply that he or other Democratic proponents
of gun control were willing to cede ground on a matter they felt
was critical. What he was proposing, he said, was to make the
background-check system so fast that disagreements about time
limits would become moot.
</P>
<P>
   White House Seeks to Expand Drug Offender Programs
</P>
<P>
   In a fresh effort to break the cycle between drug abuse and
crime, the Clinton administration is pushing to expand the testing
and treatment of drug offenders whose addiction led them to collide
with the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's director of national drug control policy, Gen.
Barry McCaffrey, is scheduled to announce details of the
initiatives Friday at a forum on substance abuse and the criminal
justice system in the White House Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
   The main proposals include making more federal money available
for drug courts, which offer nonviolent lawbreakers treatment as an
alternative to prison; helping states and cities expand drug
testing and treatment of their inmates, and compelling offenders on
probation and parole to abstain from drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
