<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-BUICK-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMES FINDS WESTCHESTER TO BE EASYGOING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ It has been a difficult year for Stephen Ames,
who has encountered more problems off the golf course than on it.
</P>
<P>
   A resident of Canada and a native of Trinidad &AMP; Tobago, Ames
missed almost five months of the PGA Tour season while waiting for
complications with his visa to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long story,'' said Ames, who spent the first 21 weeks
of the year at home in Calgary, Alberta, his golf career on hold.
``I couldn't get into the states. I thought all the hiccups had
been resolved, but another hiccup occurred at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even watch golf. Knowing what I was capable of
doing, I couldn't watch. It was eating me up inside. I didn't look
at the papers at all. It was frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Ames made up for lost time Thursday. Playing with confidence in
his debut at Westchester Country Club, he shot a six-under-par 65
in the first round of the Buick Classic and led by one stroke over
Frank Nobilo and by two strokes over Jim Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Byrum, Greg Chalmers, Jay Haas and Steve Pate were in a
four-way tie for fourth place at 68. But they were all chasing
Ames, who has returned to golf with the ease of a fish returning to
water.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in only his third tournament this year, Ames had seven
birdies and one bogey, using accurate driving and strong iron play
to leave himself consistently close to the hole. The longest birdie
putt that Ames made was a 12-footer. He saved par on his final two
holes by getting up and down from bunkers, making a 15-foot putt at
No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   At age 35, Ames wants to make a name for himself in the United
States after spending five successful years on the European Tour.
Winning the Buick Classic would be an excellent way to start, and
he believes that Westchester suits his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great golf course; I enjoyed it very much,'' Ames said. ``I
very much like the old style kind of golf course, the fact you can
play a variety of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his visa problems, Ames did not make his 1999 debut
until last month in the Kemper Open, where he finished tied for
44th. Considering how he felt on the first tee that week, Ames was
pleased to finish that high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heart palpitations,'' he said. ``I had forgotten what
that felt like. I started off bogey, bogey, double bogey. I
completely forgot how to play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ames regrouped quickly, and now his No. 1 goal is to retain
his tour card for next year, either by winning a tournament or by
finishing among the top 125 on this year's money list.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, Ames will remember 1999 not only for the
hassles, but also for the high points. His wife, Jodi, gave birth
to the couple's second child, Ryan, last month, and both Jodi and
Ryan were waiting for Ames when he finished Thursday's round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with my performance, but there's a lot of golf to
go,'' Ames said. ``I'd like to keep the same thoughts I had today,
the same feelings in my golf swing. If I can retain that, I'll be
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nobilo, Thursday's round was further evidence that he is
coming back from numerous health problems. Nobilo was diagnosed
with a form of arthritis in his wrists two years ago, and the
medication to treat that condition weakened his tendons and
ligaments.
</P>
<P>
   Nobilo fell from 23rd on the tour money list in 1997 to 108th
last year. In addition, an errant tee shot at a golf course in
Florida last summer struck Nobilo above the left eye and he
required 30 stitches.
</P>
<P>
   But Nobilo's luck and his golf game have changed for the better
recently. He has stopped taking medication for his wrists, and they
have been free of pain for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Nobilo looked like his old self Thursday, making 30-foot putts
for birdies at No. 10 and No. 16 and a 20-footer for birdie at No.
15. After his recent struggles, Nobilo was thrilled to see his name
on the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the hardest thing in my life,'' Nobilo, a native of
New Zealand, said of his health problems. ``I made a lot of
sacrifices to come over here and play. I wasn't a great player but
I was a good player, contesting in all the majors. My attitude
suffered. As positive as I tried to be, I couldn't be. I wanted to
do well, but for a period of time, I wasn't competitive. For
awhile, I thought it was the end of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Carter, he turned 38 Thursday and celebrated by shooting
one of his best rounds of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot it was my birthday until my college golf coach
reminded me,'' said Carter, whose best 1999 finish is a tie for
11th at the MasterCard Colonial. ``Not too bad of a birthday
present.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
