<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME LOSE, SOME GAIN AS ACCOUNTS SHIFT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Mo., Ill., Kan.)   (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with hundreds of Madison Avenue executives away in Cannes,
France, for the 46th International Advertising Festival, accounts
have been moving around at a hectic pace.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines eliminated the New York office of Foote, Cone
&AMP; Belding Worldwide, from its agency roster after seven years by
moving its international account, with billings estimated at $40
million, to Ogilvy &AMP; Mather New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy New York, part of the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of
WPP Group PLC, will handle advertising and direct marketing for the
important Northwest Asian-Pacific routes, creating campaigns to run
both domestically and in Asian-Pacific markets like Hong Kong,
Korea, Japan and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Dow, vice president for marketing programs and worldwide
advertising at Northwest in St. Paul, Minn., attributed the
selection of Ogilvy New York to factors including the agency's
``extensive travel expertise.'' Current and former travel clients
include American Express, Eastern Airlines and Trans World
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest roster includes agencies like Carmichael Lynch in
Minneapolis, owned by the Interpublic Group of Companies, and Hunt
Adkins in Minneapolis. As it happens, Hunt Adkins is one of seven
small shops that joined with Ogilvy Worldwide in February to form
the Syndicate, a creative consortium.
</P>
<P>
   At Foote, Cone, a unit of True North Communications, Vonda
LePage, a spokeswoman, said: ``We of course regret losing the
Northwest business. But we have been on a good new-business streak
this year.'' Gains include assignments from Clairol, Sunbeam and
Vlasic.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago office of DDB Worldwide Communications Group, a unit
of Omnicom Group in New York, figured in three account shifts.
</P>
<P>
   The Ameritrade Holding Corporation in Omaha named DDB Chicago as
the first agency to handle the account of Onmoney.com, a
financial-planning Web site to be introduced next month. Billings
were estimated at $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a three-month review that Kim Shepherd,
a spokeswoman for Ameritrade, said had been narrowed to DDB Chicago
and two other finalists: Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi in New York, part of
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC, and Ogilvy One in Chicago, part of Ogilvy
Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   DDB Chicago is also losing an account, the Salon Selectives line
of hair care products sold by a unit of Unilever Home and Personal
Care U.S.A. in New York. Salon Selectives is being shifted to
another Unilever agency, J. Walter Thompson New York, part of the
J. Walter Thompson Co. unit of WPP. Billings were estimated at $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Andress, a spokeswoman for Unilever, confirmed reports
about the shift, which came without a review, in the trade
publication Advertising Age and the Frohlinger's Marketing Report
newsletter. A sibling brand, Thermasilk, is handled by Thompson
Chicago; DDB Chicago continues to handle two others, Finesse and
Degree.
</P>
<P>
   And Webstreet Securities, an online stockbroker, awarded its
account, with billings estimated at $50 million, to TBWA/Chiat/Day
in New York, part of the TBWA Worldwide unit of Omnicom. Webstreet
parted ways with DDB Chicago in June 1998; advertising had been
handled in-house in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   Avi Fox, co-chairman at Webstreet in Deerfield, Ill., confirmed
a report in the trade publication Adweek about the decision, which
came, he said, after an eight-month review narrowed to
TBWA/Chiat/Day and Lord Group in New York, a joint venture of
Dentsu Inc. and Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, a client formalized a relationship with an
agency. Monster.com in Maynard, Mass., a career management Web site
owned by TMP Worldwide, formally named Mullen Advertising in
Wenham, Mass., as the first agency to handle its account. Billings
were estimated at $15 million to $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen, part of the Lowe Group unit of Interpublic, had
previously handled Monster.com on a project basis, most notably the
creation of a popular commercial that ran during Super Bowl XXXIII
in January.
</P>
<P>
   Two other units of Lowe based in New York _ Lowe Fox Pavlika and
Lowe Interactive _ were named to handle assignments for Beenz.com
in New York, a company introducing a currency called ``beenz'' that
consumers can spend on electronic commerce. Billings were estimated
at more than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowe units will work on tasks that include direct marketing,
interactive marketing and a fall campaign for Beenz.com aimed at
consumers. The units will collaborate with Twelve Stars
Communications in London, a brand strategy consultant that
developed the Beenz brand.
</P>
<P>
   In another change, J.Crew Group placed its account in review
after the resignation of Angotti, Thomas, Hedge in New York, which
had been agency of record for only two months. Billings were
estimated at $10 million to $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Terrie M. Paladino, chief operating officer at Angotti, Thomas,
a unit of Interpublic, confirmed an Adweek report about the
resignation. Because ``the scope of the assignment changed
dramatically,'' she said, ``we did not want to continue to work
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Karina Sokolovsky, a spokeswoman for J.Crew in New York,
confirmed the review but would provide no further information.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Yellow Freight in Overland Park, Kan., the
transportation company owned by the Yellow Corporation, began a
review for a national branding account, with billings estimated at
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Bension, managing partner at Select Resources
International in Los Angeles, which is managing the review, said
the Yellow Freight agency of 12 years, NKH&AMP;W in Kansas City, Mo.,
had resigned in tandem with the decision to review. The review will
be narrowed to six or seven agencies, she said, with a decision
expected by mid-August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
