u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS-MADE-ABROAD-NYT     06-24 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-MADE-ABROAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISING COSTS PUSHING FILM PRODUCTION ABROAD, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.Y., Wash., Texas, Ill., N.C.)   (af)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ About 27 percent of American movies and television
series made last year were filmed outside the United States to save
money, costing the nation the equivalent of 23,500 full-time jobs
and more than $10 billion, according to a study being released on
Friday by two Hollywood unions.
</P>
<P>
   The report, commissioned by the Directors Guild of America and
the Screen Actors Guild, is apparently the first to try to quantify
the extent of ``runaway production,'' the movement of film making
to lower-cost countries that many film industry workers say has
cost them their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Both unions have hired Washington lobbyists and are expected to
use the study's results to push for federal tax breaks to keep film
production in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that 34 percent of television productions last
year were made outside the United States for cost reasons, as
opposed to script requirements, up from 14 percent in 1990. Most of
that increase came from movies made for television.
</P>
<P>
   About 139 films, or 45 percent of television films, were made
outside the United States in 1998, virtually all of them in Canada.
The number of television series and miniseries _ each of which was
counted as one production _made abroad for cost reasons was 46 in
1998, or about 35 percent of the total number of series.
</P>
<P>
   About 19 percent of theatrical films last year were made abroad
for cost reasons, mostly low-budget movies. Still, that was up from
14 percent in 1990. And 24 movies with budgets of more than $25
million were made outside the United States in 1998, compared with
none in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to witness an accelerating trend here,'' said
Mark Lubkeman, the project leader at the Monitor Co. in Cambridge,
Mass., which conducted the study. ``We're starting to see some
larger productions start to run away.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic effect, however, is considerably smaller than the
percentage of productions would suggest because television movies
have lower budgets than series or feature films. About $2.8 billion
was spent abroad on such productions in 1998 out of a total
production budget of $17.6 billion for the films and television
series surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Including indirect effects of the lost spending, the study
estimated a loss to the nation's economy of $10.3 billion out of a
total economic impact of $74.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that producing in Canada was about 25 percent
less expensive than in the United States because of tax incentives
and the weak Canadian dollar. Some studio executives say that union
contracts are partly responsible for the high costs in the United
States, but Lubkeman said that even if wages were cut significantly
it would not erase the cost gap with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Getting tax breaks in Washington could be difficult because of
the controversy over violent movies. Moreover, the report itself
notes that movie and television production has continued to grow in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   To gain support in Washington, the unions are trying to show
that runaway production is a problem for the whole nation. The
report said that Los Angeles and New York had experienced growth in
film making over the last few years while North Carolina,
Washington, Texas and Illinois, which rely on low-budget
productions, had seen significant cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, which represents the large studios, said Thursday that he
had not seen the report. But he said that some productions had
always gone abroad and that the movement to Canada could reverse if
the Canadian dollar strengthened. Also, some of the job pressures
being felt by film workers came from cutbacks in the number of
films being made.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti said he would favor investment tax credits for
production in the United States but cautioned that Hollywood could
not be too nationalistic because 42 percent of its revenue now
comes from foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say, `We want to enter your market but we won't let
our people produce in your country,''' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
