<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-MECHANICS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA MECHANICS EXPRESS DISPLEASURE WITH TENTATIVE AGREEMENT,
NEGOTIATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Area mechanics of Trans World Airlines
vented their anger and frustration Thursday as they gathered to
vote on a tentative agreement with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Machinists Local 1650, after a morning meeting
downtown, made it clear they weren't happy with the 18-month
contract proposal, which has the union leadership's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going down,'' said one man as he walked away from the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 16,000 TWA employees in three separate work groups have
the chance to vote on the proposal, including about 2,300 mechanics
who work at TWA's overhaul base at Kansas City International
Airport. The results of the voting by all three groups are not
expected to be released until July 10.
</P>
<P>
   As they usually do when voting on a contract proposal, union
members are also taking a strike authorization vote.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Nelson, president of Machinists Local 1650, said the union
members' frustration did not necessarily mean the proposal would be
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're angry about it and expressing their complaints about
different parts of it,'' he said. ``It doesn't mean they'll reject
the entire contract. You just can't tell until the voting is
completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Several TWA mechanics at the meeting Thursday expressed similar
complaints about the proposal: wages that remain below the industry
standard and an inadequate pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't happy with it,'' said John Partridge, a mechanic
who has worked at TWA for 25 years. ``We'll still be at the bottom
of the pay scale for any of the major airlines. We have families to
take care of, and the older guys are way short on their retirement
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Heilig, a 33-year TWA veteran, said past concessionary
contracts and employee sacrifices had not amounted to a financially
stronger airline. Meanwhile, Heilig said, the company has made
payments to departing TWA chief executive officers through the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much contingency and too much `blue sky' in this
thing,'' said Heilig, also a mechanic. ``The company has reneged on
their word before, so why won't they do it again? TWA has to
convince me they want to run an airline and not run with the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   About 400 people attended the meeting Thursday, Nelson said.
Those who work the early shift at the overhaul base were scheduled
to meet Thursday evening to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Speer, another longtime TWA employee, said the anger among
TWA's Kansas City work force was significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have some very unhappy campers going to vote,'' Speer said
before attending the evening meeting. ``I think they feel they have
been sold out by the union and the company. You've got people here
ready for retirement, and this contract does not help them one
iota.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he expected many union members to express their
frustration at the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we didn't get everything we wanted with this
tentative agreement,'' he said. ``It's not easy to take the hit our
members have taken through the years. But our chief negotiators
felt they got everything there is to get. We represent so many
different work groups that it's hard to resolve all of their
problems at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Several TWA mechanics Thursday expressed their distrust of both
the company and union leaders as a result of the tentative
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said, ``It's unfortunate they feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the mechanics should be upset if union negotiators
``fail to extract money from the company if it's there to get. But
there's simply nothing else left to get.''
</P>
<P>
   The tentative contract for mechanics and related workers would
raise senior mechanics' top hourly pay to $20.04 by August 2000
from the current $17.93. Ramp workers' top hourly pay would
increase to $16.59 in August 2000 from the current $14.85.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has agreed to pay $10 million to settle various
grievances and issue 3 million shares of common stock over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
   The contract also calls for TWA to begin contributing to the
Machinists' national pension fund in March 2000. TWA stopped
contributing in 1992, when the airline filed its first bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Another complaint about the contract is that pay raises are not
retroactive. Under federal labor law, TWA's contract with the
Machinists union remained in effect even though it was supposed to
expire in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics and related groups have most of their employees in
St. Louis and Kansas City, with smaller numbers in New York and Los
Angeles. Ramp workers at various TWA destinations also are voting.
Voting in St. Louis took place Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the mechanics, the Machinists represent the
flight attendants and passenger-service workers. If any of the
three groups votes down the tentative agreement, the contract is
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty to 40 area passenger-service employees will have a chance
to vote on their contract proposal at Local 1650's union hall in
Riverside today. The flight attendants, who are voting by mail,
will have presentations on their proposal Saturday and Sunday at
Local 1650.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, Jim Martin, TWA's senior vice
president of human resources, resigned Thursday. Martin, who was
hired in October 1997, was vilified by union leaders and employees
during the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders had contended that Martin's previous record,
including a stint with the Coors Brewing Co., showed a hostility
toward unions.
</P>
<P>
   TWA declined to comment on the circumstances of Martin's
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Brown, a TWA spokesman, said the company was determining
whether to fill Martin's position. In the meantime, Martin's duties
of employee relations, labor relations and corporate security will
be handled by Kate Soled, senior vice president and general
counsel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
