<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING ON DISABLED TEACHER   IS ANNULLED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court followed up its new, restrictive views
limiting protections for disabled Americans Thursday by setting
aside a lower court ruling in New York that said state officials
had discriminated against a law school graduate with a reading
disorder who failed the state's bar examination five times.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, without ruling on the merits of the case, told a
federal appeals court in Manhattan to restudy its ruling last year
in the light of the justices' decisions on Tuesday sharply limiting
the definition of who should be considered disabled under the
Americans With Disabilities Act of 1990, which prohibited
discrimination against the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court held in three cases that people with physical
impairments are not protected by the law if they can function
normally by wearing glasses, taking medication or otherwise
compensating for their disabilities. The rulings were applauded by
employers, but denounced by advocates for the disabled who
contended that millions would be deprived of needed protections.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York case, Marilyn Bartlett, a Vermont Law School
graduate who is a college instructor, had argued in a 1993 lawsuit
that she was entitled, because of a reading and learning
disability, to extra time in taking the bar exams, along with the
opportunity to circle multiple-choice answers in a test booklet
rather than a computerized test sheet and other accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   The accommodations had been refused by bar examiners after an
expert said Bartlett's reading test scores did not confirm a
disorder. Many licensing organizations charged with maintaining
professional standards contend that some claims of disability are
made as a cover for academic shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal trial judge, Sonia Sotomayor, and the Second
Circuit Court of Appeals in New York agreed with Bartlett, 50, who
earned a doctoral degree from New York University and even worked
in medical malpractice law for two years before being forced to
leave her firm because of her repeated bar exam failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Bartlett, who has fought an uphill battle with a reading
disorder throughout her education, is among those for whom Congress
provided protection under the Americans With Disabilities Act,'' a
three-judge panel of the Second Circuit Court of Appeals held.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Bartlett's cognitive impairment _ her difficulties in
automatically decoding and processing the printed word _ limits her
major life activities of learning and reading to a substantial
degree,'' the court added. It said the accommodations would let her
compete fairly ``so that it will be her mastery of legal skills
that the exam is designed to test _ and not her disability _ that
determines whether or not she achieves a passing score.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge had ordered the state board of examiners to pay
Bartlett $12,500 in damages for four tests she was forced to take
without the extra time _ she failed the fifth despite being given
the accommodations _ but the appeals court ordered a recalculation
that would award her no more than $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The New York attorney general's office argued in an appeal to
the Supreme Court that, even if Ms. Bartlett was suffering from a
reading impairment, she had ``developed self-accommodating
techniques which allow her to read at a speed and in a manner
comparable to that of an average person'' and should thus not be
covered by the Americans With Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at her homelast night, Bartlett said she was
disappointed by the high court's decision to set aside the ruling
in her suit, one of about half a dozen cases the justices sent back
for lower-court review in light of this week's rulings. But she
voiced confidence that the circuit court judges would reaffirm
their decision. ``They have recognized that I do have a
disability,'' she said. ``A learning disability is not a
correctable impairment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett's lawyer, Joanne Simon, said there were ``light years
of difference'' between her client's disorder and the disabilities
the Supreme Court said were correctable and excludable from the
law's protections. She said the court had taken a ``seductively
simplistic path'' in saying, for example, that a disability could
be corrected with eyeglasses. ``It's too easy,'' she said. ``You
can't analyze most disability issues the way you analyze myopia.''
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dopp, a spokesman for the New York attorney general,
Eliot L. Spitzer, said he could not comment on the ruling until
officials had a chance to study it. But he said it appeared to be
``the first demonstration of just how far-reaching the court's
Americans With Disabilities Act decisions will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
