<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-NIGERIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMM DELIVERS AS U.S. RUNS OVER NIGERIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., North Korea, Nigeria)  By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Sixteen minutes into Thursday night's jittery
beginning against Nigeria, Mia Hamm had been knocked down at least
three times. When a Nigerian player tried to help her up, Hamm
turned her back, clearly furious with the hard tackling. Soccer's
greatest female player was about to begin a little hammering of her
own.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, Hamm played a free kick hard and low to the
right foot of a charging Michelle Akers for a game-tying goal.
Seconds after that, she blasted a shot into the upper right corner
of the net. Before the half was over, Hamm had played another
perfect free kick for a goal by Kristine Lilly. What had been a
dangerous beginning quickly became a 7-1 rout for the United States
before 65,080 fans at Soldier Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans tied a Women's World Cup record with six goals in
the first half, collecting their second victory of the first round
and all but guaranteeing advancement to the quarterfinals on July
1. Akers finished with two goals (one of which was being reviewed),
and so did Tiffeny Milbrett. Hamm had a goal and two assists as
Nigeria's early assertiveness was sabotaged by a disorganized and
indifferent defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had counted on the belief that Nigeria would send
so many players forward, relying on speed and athleticism, that its
defense would lose its shape, and perhaps, its will. That is
exactly what happened as the first half unfurled. It was sometimes
difficult to tell whether this was Soldier Field or Coors Field,
the way the score kept rolling up. Some cattle drives don't require
as much open space as the Nigerian defense left for the relentless
American attack.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of a few minutes, a match that had opened in
Nigeria's favor turned completely against the Super Falcons. But it
was the Americans who appeared fidgety and confused in the first
few minutes, and it took Nigeria all of 62 seconds to score.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Foudy tried to clear a pass from the penalty area, but
headed the ball dangerously toward the middle instead. (Marvelous)
Mercy Akide pounced on the loose ball for Nigeria and played it to
Mkiru Okosieme, whose sliding punch put the Super Falcons ahead by
1-0 on the stunned Americans.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, Brandi Chastain and Carla Overbeck collided in
front of the American goal. As goalkeeper Briana Scurry strayed
from her line, a retreating Chastain had to stick out her leg near
the left post to deflect a threatening shot.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the American defense settled down. Kate Sobrero, who
sprained an ankle on Wednesday and was an uncertain starter
Thursday night, had recovered enough to make a beautiful
backpedaling maneuver, changing directions several times, to
smother a Nigerian foray. After missing four scoring chances, the
Americans finally connected in the 19th minute as Hamm, soccer's
career-leading scorer in international matches, channeled her anger
into points.
</P>
<P>
   Akers charged to her left across the goal mouth, took a perfect
corner kick from Hamm and appeared to flick the ball back to her
right, tying the game at 1-1. Officials later said that they would
review the goal, leaving open the possibility that the ball had
actually scored inadvertently off the foot of Nigeria's 16-year-old
defender, Ifeanyichukwu Chiejene.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum switched quickly and inexorably into the Americans'
favor. Hamm took a through pass from Lilly and blasted the ball
past the flat-footed Nigerian goalie, Anne Chiejine. Milbrett then
slammed a shot off Chiejine's right hand into the net. Nigeria was
so deficient in the rudiments of defense that it stood around
without marking the Americans on set pieces. In the 32d minute,
Hamm lasered another free kick to Lilly, who headed the ball for a
4-1 American lead.
</P>
<P>
   Foudy redeemed herself with a cross from the right flank that
Akers headed in for a 5-1 lead. In the 42d minute, Chastain headed
a pass to Cindy Parlow, who also punched the ball with her head and
punched out the lights for Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   The six American goals in the first half tied a record that
Sweden set in an 8-0 victory over Japan in the 1991 Women's World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Sobrero and Akers, who suffers from chronic fatigue syndrome,
were substituted for in the second half, and, as the game
degenerated into cheap fouls, Hamm soon followed after being kicked
in the stomach. By then, she had delivered many more blows than she
had received.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
