u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEARSON-LAZARD-NYT &LR;      06-24 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARSON-LAZARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEARSON WILL SELL ITS STAKES IN 3 HOUSES OF LAZARD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British media company Pearson PLC said Thursday that it was
selling its holdings in three Lazard investment houses in a deal
that analysts said would enable both Pearson and Lazard to become
more competitive by focusing more closely on their primary
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson has agreed to sell to the French investment group Gaz et
Eaux SA its 50 percent stake in Lazard Brothers &AMP; Co. in London, a
7.6 percent interest in Lazard Freres &AMP; Co. in New York and an 8
percent share of Lazard Freres &AMP; Compagnie in Paris. Gaz et Eaux,
which has close ties to Lazard, said it would pay $649 million for
the three related firms. Pearson intends to use the proceeds of the
sale to repay debt.
</P>
<P>
   The company _ which owns The Financial Times newspaper, 60
percent of The Economist, the Penguin book-publishing company and
television programming like ``Baywatch'' _ has been seeking to shed
assets that are not directly related to its core publishing and
media businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``From their perspective, this means they will become a pure
media group,'' said Jonathan Helliwell, an analyst with Goldman,
Sachs. ``Historically, when they are in a lot of different areas,
their overall valuation has suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal will help Lazard, an investment banking partnership,
reach its goal of unifying its European and American operations.
Though profitable, the closely held firm has struggled to keep up
with other global powerhouses in the lucrative business of advising
top executives on financial and merger strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Lazard is now trying to create a more cohesive corporate
structure to compete with the fluid global networks of rivals like
the Goldman Sachs Group and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. Earlier
this month, Lazard announced that it would integrate its London,
Paris and New York operations and reshuffle its executive ranks in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The deal requires the approval of Pearson's shareholders, as
well as the approval of the directors of the three Lazard houses.
It is also contingent upon the completion of Lazard's planned
integration of the divisions into a single global partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lazard just wants to tidy everything up and make sure they
have total control of the combined company so they can then decide
how they want to go into the 21st century,'' said Tom Burnett,
director of Merger Insight, an institutional-research firm in New
York. ``Right now, their ownership is fragmented.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Michel David-Weill, chairman of Lazard Freres &AMP; Co.,
characterized the Pearson deal only in terms of the publisher's
desire to tidy up its own house. Despite Lazard's 80-year
association with Pearson, he said, ``We fully understand their
desire to refocus their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pearson has been looking for the right opportunity to
shed its peripheral role in investment banking since 1997, when
Marjorie M. Scardino, its American chief executive, stepped in with
a mandate to refocus the conglomerate's far-flung businesses into a
sharper media operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``By consolidating, she is really telling Wall Street and her
stockholders that they are making a major commitment to the media
and entertainment world, both in North America and elsewhere,''
said Albert Greco, an associate professor of business at Fordham
University, who studies media management.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scardino said that the sale of Pearson's Lazard holdings
``allows us to invest all our resources in the businesses we manage
and that are forming the future of Pearson.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bruno Roger, chairman of Gaz et Eaux, said, ``We are very
pleased at the prospect of becoming a significant partner in the
Lazard Group.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Pearson announced that it would strengthen its
alliance with Telefonica, the Spanish telecommunications company.
The companies already have a joint interest in Recoletos, a Spanish
media business. With the new arrangement, in which Telefonica will
acquire 5 percent of Pearson, the companies will jointly develop
Internet and multi-media services in Spanish- and
Portuguese-speaking countries.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Villalonga, chairman of Telefonica, said that the deal
would link Pearson with a partner with the ability to ``use our
infrastructure to extend the range of media services we provide in
Spanish and Latin American markets we know well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
