<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-NYT &LR;      06-24 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER CONVICTED IN TORTURE OF LOUIMA SEEKS NEW TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeking to win a new trial for Charles Schwarz, one
of the police officers convicted in the Abner Louima case, defense
lawyers asserted Thursday that prosecutors failed to turn over
evidence the defense said showed that Schwarz had played no role in
the torture.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz was convicted earlier this month of violating Louima's
civil rights following testimony that he was the officer who had
restrained Louima in the bathroom of a Brooklyn precinct house as
another officer, Justin Volpe, had thrust a broomstick into
Louima's rectum.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, however, has said through his attorney that another
officer, not Schwarz, was present during the attack _ a claim that
two jurors now say would have caused them to acquit Schwarz had
they known about it during deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Schwarz's lawyer, Stephen Worth, submitted sworn
statements from the two jurors _ who identified themselves only as
No. 2 and No. 6 _ as part of a request to Judge Eugene Nickerson of
U.S. District Court in Brooklyn to grant a new trial. In their
statements, first reported Thursday by The Daily News, the jurors
said Volpe's new claims about the assault ``would have created a
reasonable doubt'' about the guilt of Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   According to Worth, prosecutors learned during the trial that
Volpe was prepared to take the witness stand and clear Schwarz.
``The fact that Volpe was prepared to waive his Fifth Amendment
right and exonerate Schwarz was unknown to the defense and was not
disclosed by the prosecution,'' Worth said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors declined to comment Thursday, but in a letter to
Worth they denied any impropriety and they suggested that Worth,
despite his claims of having been in the dark, had been well
informed of Volpe's offer.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, dated June 17, Alan Vinegrad, an assistant U.S.
attorney, acknowledged that Marvyn Kornberg, Volpe's lawyer, had
``informed the government that, if called as a witness, his client,
Justin Volpe, would testify in substance that an individual other
than Charles Schwarz was the `other officer' who was present in the
bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad said Kornberg shared this information on May 20, five
days before Volpe dropped his claims of innocence and made a
dramatic courtroom confession that he had tortured Louima after
arresting him in August 1997. Vinegrad disputed Worth's contention
that court rules obligated prosecutors to share their new knowledge
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Vinegrad wrote to Worth, ``this information was
either known by you or could easily have been ascertained by you.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Kornberg said he ``fully informed''
Worth of Volpe's willingness to exonerate Schwarz, and he
criticized Worth for failing to call Volpe as a defense witness.
Worth has said that Volpe would have been worthless as a witness
because jurors would have rejected any version of events offered by
``an admitted sex torturer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that Steve Worth made a colossal blunder,''
Kornberg said, ``in not calling Justin Volpe to the stand to
exculpate his client when he knew at the time what Volpe's
testimony would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth said Kornberg told him during the trial that Volpe's
account of the bathroom assault exonerated Schwarz. But Worth said
he did not trust Kornberg to tell him the truth and that mistrust
played into his decision not to call Volpe as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Had the government told me, `This is what Volpe
intends to say,' that would be one thing. But a fellow defense
counsel representing his own client's interests has no obligation
to tell me the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
