<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OK-CORRAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARP, HOLLIDAY CLEARED OF CHARGES IN O.K. GUNFIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For three hours Thursday the jurors listened to dramatic
testimony about an eruption of deadly vio lence, watched men fling
around old nickel-plated pistols, then sat to gether to ponder the
gunfight at the O.K. Corral.
</P>
<P>
   When they were done, about 10 seconds later, the eight-person
panel concluded that this famous tale ended the way the folklore of
the Wild West always told us it did.
</P>
<P>
   The guys we've always been told were good really were.
</P>
<P>
   Or, at least, the other guys were worse.
</P>
<P>
   More than a century after the gun smoke disappeared into the af
ternoon sky in Tombstone, a jury vindicated Wyatt Earp and Doc
Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   During a mock trial at the Phoenician Resort, a group of
prominent Arizona attorneys dis sected the 27-second gunbattle and
with it, a story that in many ways defines Arizona and the West.
</P>
<P>
   The story, nine men shooting it out on a mining town back
street, still intrigues people so much that theories about who did
what and why remain topics of hot debate. Earlier this year, a man
paid $220,000 for Holliday's shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's production was part history lesson and part entertain
ment. It used real transcripts from an official inquest after the
shoot ing, for example, and featured a law school dean in a billowy
prairie dress displaying a remarkable ability to cry on cue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's thrilling to bring it to life,'' said Wyatt Earp, the
great grand nephew of his namesake, who portrayed his famous
ancestor in the trial. ``It's another frontier effort, and I hope
folks will have more of a concern of what happened there that
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Earp and Holliday were cleared in the 1881 gunbattle,
the trial depicted a fictional civil suit filed by the mother of
Tom McLaury, one of the three men killed in the battle in that
rowdy southern Arizona mining town. The other two men killed were
Billy Clanton and Tom's brother, Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Johns played one of
the plaintiff's attorneys, while Michael Daly Hawkins, a 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals judge, oversaw the case.
</P>
<P>
   Former Phoenix Mayor Terry Goddard pasted on a fake mustache to
portray Ike Clanton, a friend of the McLaury brothers who ran away
as the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, part of the State Bar of Arizona's annual convention,
tried to challenge commonly held good-guy, bad-guy myths of the
story, passed down to generations and retold in books and movies.
</P>
<P>
   Tom McLaury's attorneys tried to portray Earp as a man so
politically ambitious that he would kill to become sheriff. They
portrayed Hol liday as a gambler and drunk, saying the two men had
pistol-whipped the McLaury and Clanton brothers before the shooting
and had fired the first shots.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Patricia White, dean of Arizona State
University's College of Law, played the grieving mother of Tom
McLaury.
</P>
<P>
   And she didn't hold back. At times White mocked &UR; the judicial
process, dabbing her eyes with a handkerchief and throwing in a
``they murdered him'' at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Boze Bell, local writer, actor and radio-show host, got the
most laughs with his ad-libbed humor, playing the sheriff who was a
friend of the Clantons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to remind me what I said, it's been 118
years,'' he joked, when asked to tell what he first said about the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   While attorneys are often infa mous for delaying trials, this
one unfolded in less than 3{ hours. And when lunch approached and
clos ings weren't in view, the judge called counsel to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume the defense rests,'' the judge said following a brief
confer ence and without hearing from Holliday, one of the
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   In closings, Flagstaff attorney Deborah Fine said Earp and Holli
day didn't act in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizonans won't tolerate the killing of innocent men in our
street,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Hendricks, defending Holliday and Earp, told the jury his
clients were deputized and acting as lawmen when they tried to get
McLaury and the Clanton brothers to put away their guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should put yourself back in time to 1881 and walk in their
boots . . . in a town out of control,'' he said. ``They were called
upon to make a split second decision.''
</P>
<P>
   A jury _ not quite of Holliday and Earp's peers as it included
mostly lawyers and the wife of their defense attorney _ issued a
unani mous not-guilty verdict. The delib eration was so quick that
when the judge asked who the foreman was, jury members looked at
each other until one man shot up, naming himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that day, if guns start flying, that's what any law officer
would do,'' juror Liz Sexson said. ``So, we cleared them.''
</P>
<P>
   Earp, in his string tie and black Western suit with velvet
collar, smiled as the verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never crossed my mind it would go any other way,'' he said.
``I think it helped clarify the reality of the time, which was
chaotic.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience, about 450 attor neys and a few history lovers,
also voted with electronic keypads; 66 percent favored Wyatt and
Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some who came to see the show Thursday wanted more.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hushion, an Old West his tory buff who says he is the
world's leading expert on the O.K. Corral, drove from Santa
Barbara, Calif., for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was entertaining,'' said Hu shion, a lawyer who said he
spent more than 1,000 hours examing forensic evidence from the
gunbat tle. ``But I'd like to see a full-blown trial, done without
the fiction. Because for 120 years, no one can agree on what
happened.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
