<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8936 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-HNS &LR;      06-24 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ The Larry O'Brien Trophy will be nearby, shined, ready.
Champagne will be on ice. Plastic sheeting will be in place to
protect the contents in the visitors' locker room.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the San Antonio Spurs insist their success has been built on
their humble concentration and an appreciation of a day's work for
its own sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we have to do,'' Spurs forward Tim Duncan said.
``We know we're not going to come in and be too happy about
anything or be too secure about anything. We want to get this done.
We don't want to give them any life. We're really focused on what
we have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he said, noticing a garish cap in a crowd of hundreds
of reporters, ``that's a horrible hat.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for focus. A reporter's cap would seem easier to ignore
than the championship trophy the Spurs will try to secure in Game 5
of the NBA Finals tonight at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs will try to forget what they believe awaits them
should they beat the New York Knicks tonight. This is not yet the
time, they have told themselves, to indulge in thoughts of the
trials that had brought them here, the criticisms along the way or
the celebration that could be just ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   And they will fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm what-iffing,'' Spurs forward Malik Rose said. ``I
know I'll be ready for Game 5. But you can't help but to think
about it. You're going to get a ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who have been there said the Spurs cannot think about
rewards they cannot get out of their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ignore it,'' said Spurs guard Steve Kerr, a winner
of three championships with the Bulls. ``As soon as you think about
celebrating and what happens if you win, then you take your mind
off the task at hand. It's going to be important to not think about
champagne and cigars.''
</P>
<P>
   But with that, Kerr could not keep up the front. Ignoring the
chance to finally break through and win a title is not realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally unrealistic,'' he said. ``But you have to know
that going in and settle into the game. A lot of times, you fall
behind quickly and that jolts you back into reality and you start
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs might be far from the Alamodome, but they remain in
familiar territory. They clinched each of their previous three
series on the road. With the Knicks needing to win three
consecutive games, the Spurs have not lost even two straight since
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're road warriors,'' guard Mario Elie said. ``Our focus is
real high. I don't remember the last time we lost two games in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have somebody down, we have to finish them off. Our
guys are focused. We're feeling good about ourselves. When they
bring that trophy in, guys will look at it and want to hold it.
We'll have one more 48-minute game to get it done. But this is the
most difficult game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have reacted to their 3-1 deficit by leaning on all
the doubts that have faced them before. The Knicks said their
troubles even reaching the playoffs, their rise from an eighth seed
and ability to overcome the loss of center and captain Patrick
Ewing prove that even their current situation is not too great to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks pledged that they would not go down easily. More than
that, they were offended at the implication that there are more
preferable ways to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean, `make it tough on them'?'' Knicks guard
Chris Childs said. ``We're going to win tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   But Childs offered few reasons to expect such a thing, other
than pointing out what the Knicks have been unable to do, as if
relying on probability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to come out and play our best ballgame,'' said Childs,
who will have trouble playing at all because of a sprained right
knee. ``We haven't played a great ballgame yet. We haven't played a
complete game. Sometimes we defend. Sometimes we score.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Spurs try to fight thoughts of postgame cigars and
champagne, the Knicks have welcomed the vision, hoping to use it to
drive them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want those guys celebrating on our floor,'' Knicks
guard Latrell Sprewell said. ``You just can't have that. We have
too much pride for that as a team. We want to take this thing back
to San Antonio. If we can start with that, then we can worry about
Game 6.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Knicks almost seemed to be trying to talk themselves
into logic to restore their faith.
</P>
<P>
   They did not offer solutions to the problem of the dominance
inside by Duncan and David Robinson. They could not come up with
ways to be more efficient offensively. They instead pointed out
what they have not done well enough, seeming to want as much burden
as possible to create the sort of against-all-odds success that has
marked their season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the character of this team, which is strong,'' Knicks
forward Larry Johnson said. ``Jeff (Van Gundy, the Knicks' coach)
made an excellent point to the team. Never in the Finals has a team
down 3-1 come back (to win the championship). Never (before New
York) has an eighth seed been to a Finals. Let's throw all that
history junk out. All we need to do is win tomorrow night and go
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has stressed that his team think only of tonight's
game to keep from being overwhelmed by the 3-1 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they're only bound by what they believe can still
be accomplished,'' Van Gundy said. ``If they believe that since no
one else has ever done this that it can't be done, then that will
be reflected in our play (tonight). History doesn't have to hamper
us. All we have to do is win one home game. That's the question:
Can we win one home game? Then can we go down there and get one
road game? And then you're playing the ultimate game. I just made
that sound a heck of a lot easier than it is, obviously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you win one home game? And the bigger question is, Do we
really in our heart of hearts want to go back to San Antonio?''
</P>
</TEXT>
