<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-TAMPA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SWEEP PAST TAMPA BAY AND ON TO BALTIMORE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Arizona Diamondbacks had the great
fortune of being placed in the same division as the dysfunctional
Los Angeles Dodgers. But the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, the other
expansion team of 1998, were trapped into sharing the American
League East with the Yankees. There is no escape, for now.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees continued their stranglehold of the Devil Rays
Thursday night, winning by 7-3. At game's end, most seats in
Tropicana Field had been captured by Yankees' fans chanting,
``Sweep!''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who have improved their record to 42-28, move on to
a three-game weekend series in Baltimore, where the Orioles have
been mounting a charge.
</P>
<P>
   The victory Thursday night was well-timed, with the principal
owner, George Steinbrenner, watching from a private box above the
third base line. Some members of the organization maintain that
Steinbrenner, who resides in this area, is more adamant about the
Yankees' beating the Devil Rays than any other team. The Yankees
have dominated the rivalry, winning 14 of their 15 meetings,
outscoring Tampa Bay in those games, 85-29.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer, who blasted a home run Tuesday and hit the ball
hard in all five at-bats Wednesday, ripped a double and single
Thursday night, and for a few moments, anyway, there is a sense of
order in left field for the Yankees. Probably not for long,
however, since Ricky Ledee was recalled from Class AAA Columbus
Thursday for what might be the determining test of his future with
the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, nine years removed from the day he was drafted by the
Yankees, has a month to show he can produce in left field, and if
neither he nor Spencer establishes a lock on the position, the
Yankees will pursue another established outfielder. Thus far, the
Yankees' left fielders have generated the worst numbers of any
position for any team in the major leagues _ worse even than some
National League pitching staffs. As play began Thursday night,
their left fielders were batting .184, with 6 home runs and 19 runs
batted in.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have asked Kansas City about Johnny Damon, and they
could pursue Detroit's Bobby Higginson. But they will try Spencer
and Ledee for a final monthlong audition before reconsidering their
options.
</P>
<P>
   When Spencer led off the seventh inning with the Yankees down,
3-2, his teammates were engaged in full battle with Joe Brinkman,
the home-plate umpire. Andy Pettitte had thrown first-pitch strikes
to 21 of the first 24 batters he faced, through five innings, but
in the sixth, he couldn't throw strikes _ or rather, in the
Yankees' view, Brinkman wasn't calling any strikes. Twenty of the
28 pitches Pettitte threw were called balls, but at least some of
them appeared to be strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi, the Yankees' normally mild-mannered catcher, began
jawing with Brinkman; Pettitte glared in. At one point, Girardi
went so far as to look at the Yankees' bench and motion with a hand
at Brinkman: What's up with this guy?
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Manager Joe Torre had moved forward from the dugout to
yell at the umpire, his cap tipped back and his face dark and
serious, with bench coach Don Zimmer chiming in. The nastiness
continued between innings, with Torre yelling at Brinkman, and
after Spencer took a strike to start the seventh, he and Brinkman
exchanged words.
</P>
<P>
   But Spencer settled in and laced a single to center. Tampa Bay
anticipated a bunt from Scott Brosius, but Brosius slammed a line
drive over shortstop, the ball skipping and rolling on the
artificial surface, all the way to the wall in left-center field.
Spencer scored, Brosius had a double, and after Brosius advanced to
third on a bunt, he scored on Chuck Knoblauch's sacrifice fly. The
Yankees led, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, 15-for-26 since moving from cleanup to the No.
2 spot in the batting order, had the first of his two singles in
the first inning, and he scored on a two-out single from Paul
O'Neill. Chili Davis accounted for the Yankees' second run,
pounding his 11th home run in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees gave away two of the three runs Pettitte allowed in
his six and two-thirds innings. Derek Jeter made an error at
shortstop to set up one run, which Pettitte sent home with a balk,
and the second scored after Brosius threw a ball away and Jeter
flubbed a relay homeward. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
