<HEADLINE>
DEAD OR ALIVE, RATTLERS CAN STRIKE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if bites from live snakes weren't bad enough, sink your teeth
into this:
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's proof dead snakes bite, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bites from dead snakes are more common than you might think,
said Dr. Jeffrey R. Suchard, a medical toxicolo gist at Good
Samaritan Regional Medi cal Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 15 percent, five of 34 snake bite victims admitted to
Good Samaritan from June 1997 to April 1998, were bitten by dead
snakes, Suchard and his colleague, Dr. Frank LoVecchio, also a
toxicologist at Good Samaritan, wrote in a letter published
recently in the New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study turned up several sur prises,'' Suchard said. ``We
were sur prised the percentage was that high. We were also
surprised most people didn't know dead snakes still bite.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Cluff isn't surprised. The 21-year-old Queen Creek man
could have died after picking up the decapi tated head of a Mojave
rattler a friend had shot with a .22-caliber rifle.
</P>
<P>
   The snake head rallied and sank a fang into Cluff's knuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been around snakes so much I felt comfortable with
them,'' Cluff said. ``I guess I loosened up on my grip. That's when
it bit me. The pain was terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Cluff ended up losing part of his right index finger.
</P>
<P>
   Suchard said he and LoVec chio began to take a closer look at
the dead snakebite phe nomenon after admitting a pa tient a couple
years ago who had been bitten while gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man used a shovel to cut off the head of the rattle
snake,'' Suchard said. ``When he bent down to pick up the snake's
head, it bit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Suchard said documented cases of dead snakes delivering fatal
bites can be traced back several hundred years to Spanish
explorers. In 1972, rattlesnake researcher L.M. Klauber published a
study showing that rattlesnake heads are dangerous for 20 minutes
to an hour after decapi tation.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sloan of the Arizona Herpe tological Association said that
al though he doesn't know anyone who has ever been bitten by a dead
rattlesnake, he understands how it might happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you go down the evolution ary scale, the functions of the
brain and functions of the body become a little more separated,''
Sloan said. ``There's a reflex action involved when you touch a
snake's mouth. The fang is like a hypodermic needle. It's going to
continue to work if you put your hand near it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Taylor said he knows of people who have even been pricked
and poisoned by discarded fangs. Taylor, like Sloan, is a member of
the Arizona Herpetological Associ ation, which is dedicated to the
conservation, study and understand ing of reptiles and amphibians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snakes shed fangs as well as their skins,'' Taylor said. ``The
dried venom on the fangs can also cause a bad reaction if you prick
yourself with an old fang.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said this happened to him while cleaning out an aquarium
where he kept blacktail rattlesnakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shedded fangs are little and transparent,'' Taylor said.
``Five minutes after pricking myself with one, my finger began
throbbing and I had to sit down for an hour or two before the pain
dissipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's two poison control cen ters _ Samaritan Poison Center
and the Arizona Poison and Drug Infor mation Center in Tucson _
receive 200 to 300 snakebite calls a year. It's not known how many
of those calls involve bites delivered by dead snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Suchard said Good Samaritan's toxicology referral center
averages 35 to 60 snakebite admissions a year.
</P>
<P>
   An average 10 to 12 people die of snakebites in the United
States each year. Arizona recorded its last snakebite fatality
earlier this year when a Phoenix rattlesnake hobbiest was bitten by
his own snake. It was the first state snakebite fatality since
1986.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Stocker, spokesman for Ru ral/Metro Fire Department, said
snakes are most active during the hottest months. He said
Rural/Metro currently receives 10 to 30 calls a day from people who
ask the company to remove snakes, usually from their properties. He
said in the eight years he's been with Ru ral/Metro, he is not
aware of anyone being bitten by a dead snake.
</P>
<P>
   Stocker recommends calling for a free retrieval service rather
than handling snake situations by your self. The Arizona
Herpetological Association and Rural/Metro Fire Department perform
this service. He said he'd also like the public, especially
newcomers to the state, to be more sensitive to the intricate
interactions of a desert ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've moved into the snake's habitat; they're not moving into
ours,'' Stocker said. ``We get calls from people with cell phones
who are horseback riding or on a hiking trail. They come across
snakes and want us to come out and remove them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, Stocker said, is people think all large snakes
are dangerous, so they're often killed indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some snakes, like king snakes, are natural enemies of
rattlesnakes and not dangerous to humans,'' Stocker said. ``People
should also understand that snakes do a lot of good. If we didn't
have them, we'd be overrun by rodents.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan agrees and recommends just leaving wildlife alone whether
it's alive or dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically,'' Sloan said, ``we've found that the average
snakebite victim is a White male between 15 and 35 with lots of
alcohol in him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Good Samaritan's study, all patients were 20 to 48 years old.
Only one, however, was intoxicated when bitten. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
